<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE BRACES FOR N. ARIZONA PASSING ATTACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHRIDGE, Calif. _ The talk at Cal State Northridge for nearly
two weeks has been about whether the Matadors' patchwork offensive
line will be able to block No. 13 Northern Arizona's quick front
four. But CSUN defensive tackle Levi Line sees something else when
he looks at the Lumberjacks.
</P>
<P>
   `They think they can pass on us all day. They think they can
gain big yards on us all day,'' said Line, a transfer from Nevada.
``They have a fairly good offensive line. Big and touted.We looked
into it and, yeah, they think they can pass on us all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Line isn't just talking about Lumberjacks quarterback Travis
Brown (27 of 55, 356 yards) throwing deep but also the quick
hitters on three-step drops that he was so effective doing in last
week's 38-16 demolition of Southwest Texas State.
</P>
<P>
   And even though Brown's status remains uncertain because of a
bruised elbow, NAU's approach should be the same if Clay Brown (5
of 7, 115 yards) gets the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think they have a good passing attack anywhere on the
field,'' Line said. ``They'll mix it up and that's what we have to
be prepared for as a defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Bussin' it, baby: Typically, CSUN would fly to Saturday's game
at NAU, but coach Ron Ponciano elected to bus it so he can bring 58
players instead of 48. So after practice today, the Matadors will
bus to Laughlin, Nev., spend the night and then head to Flagstaff,
Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we used to travel 48, we used to take three or four guys
just because they were good scout kids and they deserved to go on a
trip,'' Ponciano said. ``We're struggling at 58 now. It's really a
tough part of this job, but it's a good sign for our program
development.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those not making the trip is freshman free safety Hassan
Abdul-Malik, who is nursing a shoulder injury he suffered in
practice, and senior cornerback Tayari Ferrell.
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano said Ferrell is sore after being involved in a one-car
accident Monday and needs more time to heal.
</P>
<P>
   Among those making the trip is converted wide receiver James
Maldonado, now a safety. He's impressed the coaching staff in
practice, Ponciano said.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping up with Jones: Sitting on the bench absorbing
Wednesday's practice was Terrence Jones, a transfer from Fresno
State. Jones, a speedy wide receiver, isn't eligible this season
because of grades, but he was a regular with Fresno State and
should get a good look from the coaching staff in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Jones caught 17 passes for the Bulldogs last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen a little bit of film on him, but I haven't been able
to evaluate him yet,'' CSUN offensive coordinator and wide
receivers coach Rob Phenicie said. ``I know he has a lot of speed,
but I don't know how he'll adapt to our system. He'll get a
considerable look in the spring as long as he's eligible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
