<P>
   &UR; HOME (Moved in ``l'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SEXY-HIGH-TECH (New York) _ A moire pattern of shimmering light
bounces off a grid of copper mesh _ not the usual sight one would
expect in the stair hall of a grand old Brooklyn townhouse. The
florid sworls of carved plaster moldings, maybe; the ample curve of
a stolid wooden banister, of course. But a two-story wall of metal
mesh layered on linen? And that's but one of many experimental
metal applications appearing throughout the pristine
late-19th-century house. What would Edith Wharton think? Or, coming
at it from our end of the century: Since when did High Tech get so
sexy? By Julie Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   DESIGN-DECORATION (Undated) _ Design is serious. Decoration is
superficial. In the 20th century, modern design and interior
decoration have never had much use for each other. Design was a
science _ a hard body of facts. It was technology, like engineering
and architecture. It had purpose. Interior decoration was fashion _
an art when it prayed hard. It knows how to stop a room when it
walks in. Since the 17th century, when it appeared professionally,
it was a rich man's game. But modern design and decorator taste
have been showing up together lately _ and they make a
great-looking team.
</P>
<P>
   FREY-ARCHITECTURE (Palm Springs, Calif.) _ Albert Frey hates
waste. He sees no need for water-hungry lawns or spacious homes. He
lives modestly in a 16-by-32-foot house made of low-maintenance
materials that he built for himself 34 years ago. His principle in
life and architecture, he explains, is to ``do the most with the
least.'' So why are the young and the affluent drawn to a
94-year-old man living in a space they'd normally consider too
small to swing a cat in? Because Albert Frey is the living
embodiment of a minimalist philosophy of life and design that is
enjoying a revival by a generation fattened on the go-go 1980s and
'90s. By Frances Anderton.
</P>
<P>
   LOTTERY-TICKETS (Undated) _ One night, while buying a quart of
milk at a convenience store deep in the Catskills, I found myself
standing in front of a glass display case holding perhaps 20 neat
stacks of instant lottery tickets. Maybe it was the mountain air,
or maybe it was the magnitude of the display, but suddenly I found
these butterfly-bright slips of cardboard exotic and intriguing. By
Karrie Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   REPLICA-FURNISHINGS (Wilmington, N.C.) _ Electric cables,
television monitors, lighting and sound paraphernalia crowded the
front hallway of the two-story saltbox house. Gingerly stepping
over the wires, I crossed the foyer _ and the family home of my
imagination came alive. I spotted the dining room through an
archway: a faux-Tiffany lamp hung above an antique table of dark
luminous wood, surrounded by six red-velvet Louis XIII chairs. Made
to order in Paris by James Ivory and Ismail Merchant for their film
``A Soldier's Daughter Never Cries,'' these were replicas of the
originals I grew up with. Real ones would have been too expensive
to buy and then ship all the way to the United States. By Kaylie
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   FOXGLOVE (Undated) _ Don't take any happy homemaker tips from
the film ``One True Thing,'' which opens tomorrow _ unless you want
to poison your guests. By Anne Raver.
</P>
