u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-FOLEY-NYT &LR;      09-17 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-FOLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIB INJURY COULD SIDELINE JETS' FOLEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ Glenn Foley, whose durability was an issue
when coach Bill Parcells anointed him the New York Jets' starting
quarterback, is suffering a painful rib injury and has only a 50-50
chance to play Sunday against the Colts.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that Foley hid the seriousness of the injury (torn
rib cartilage) from Parcells, who was concerned with Foley's
passing during last Sunday's 24-10 loss to the Ravens at Giants
Stadium. Now, the Colts game has taken on an urgency for the 0-2
Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not certain he can play,'' Parcells said Wednesday. ``My
best guess is that Vinny Testaverde will get most of the snaps
today.'' Foley, however, wound up taking the majority of snaps, a
Jets spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said he had asked Foley ``four, five times during the
course of the game and he indicated he was OK''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if the injury had restricted his passing during the
game, Foley replied, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Then asked if he would have admitted to Parcells if it had.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   Foley also said, ``I wouldn't want to do anything to affect the
team.'' The implication is that he would take himself out of the
Colts game if he feels he is ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to go out there 40 or 30 percent if Vinny is
100,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde is a 6-foot-5-inch, 238-pound weight-room obsessed
34-year-old who has had 132 career starts.
</P>
<P>
   Foley was wearing a flak jacket to prevent just the sort of
injury he suffered against the Ravens. He was sandwiched between
the Colts' 280-pound defensive ends, Michael McCrary and Rob
Burnett, in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, said Foley, rammed him helmet-first in the ribs.
``You could see he was getting up slowly,'' said right guard Matt
O'Dwyer. ``He was hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He took some hit,'' said tight end Kyle Brady. ``When two guys
that size hit you, it's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the injury, Foley continued in the drive and helped
position the Jets to a field goal that cut the Ravens' lead to
17-10. But from the time he was hit until the end of the game _ he
played every down _ he suffered two interceptions and was sacked
three times, while completing seven of his last 10 passes. The
passes gained only 49 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said that he did not know the seriousness of Foley's
injury until Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Foley had spent most of his free time on Monday in the trainer's
room, having his bumps and bruises taken care of. Testaverde
suggested then that Foley would find it different being a starter,
taking most of the snaps, and having to haul a battered body to the
line every play.
</P>
<P>
   Foley is attempting to start his third straight National
Football League game, something he has been able to achieve only
once.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to play, as far as I know,'' he said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Foley saw his first extensive action in 1995 in Week 10 against
the Patriots but suffered a serious shoulder injury that ended his
season. Last year, he replaced Neil O'Donnell, started twice, but
then injured a knee and missed the last five games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells has admitted he was uncertain about Foley's staying
power and commanded him to put on 15 pounds and take a rigorous
weight-room program in the off season. Foley now weighs about 220
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   As for Testaverde's preparation, he contended it would be no
different this week, that he learned long ago he must think of
himself as starting _ even if he doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``The few times I wasn't a starter,'' he said, ``I didn't let
the details get away.''
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde has been listed as the third quarterback, while Ray
Lucas was listed as the backup. That technicality allowed Lucas to
play on kick-coverage and kick returns.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde has an almost-storied history against the Colts. In
1988, he produced a 469-yard passing performance against them for
Tampa Bay. It was the second-highest total ever achieved against
the Colts, exceeded only by Joe Namath's famous 496-yard shootout
against Johnny Unitas in 1972. Testaverde also set a rookie passing
record against the Jim Mora-coached Saints in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   For much of training camp, Testaverde outshone Foley, who became
more confident and stronger as the summer progressed. Foley has
played every down the first two games, but his won-lost record as a
starter has fallen to 1-6. He remains without a complete-game
victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
