A9703 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOXING-HOLYFIELD-NYT &LR;      09-17 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOXING-HOLYFIELD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLYFIELD A BIG DRAW IN HOMETOWN BOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (smw) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Evander Holyfield vaguely remembers when Muhammad Ali
fought Jerry Quarry here at the Municipal Auditorium in 1970. It
was Ali's first bout after he had been banned from boxing for
refusing to join the military. Holyfield was 8 and had not yet
become immersed in boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a kid I didn't like boxing,'' Holyfield said Wednesday. ``I
only liked the things that I did. If I wasn't boxing, I wasn't
watching it.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, speaking at a news conference for his title fight
against Vaughn Bean at the Georgia Dome on Saturday night, did not
have exciting memories of Ali-Quarry. ``It was just a lot of
talking,'' he said. ``It was kind of boring. I used to like to see
the little guys fight, because they were always scrapping. The
heavyweights would hold, and blow their nose and pull up their
trunks and fight for about 30 or 45 minutes and then leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield (38-3) is promising to do more than that when he
defends his International Boxing Federation and World Boxing
Association heavyweight titles against Bean, whose record of 31-1
is inflated by opponents of questionable skill.
</P>
<P>
   The promoter Don King said that as of Wednesday afternoon,
24,000 tickets had been sold, and he was projecting that 40,000
would be sold, which would make Holyfield-Bean one of the
best-selling bouts ever. Muhammad Ali- Leon Spinks II in 1978 and
Sugar Ray Leonard-Roberto Duran in 1980 (the ``No mas'' fight) both
drew 70,000 at the Super Dome in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's fight will also be broadcast on the Showtime cable
network during a preview weekend, meaning that 60 million homes
will get the fight free.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, who is distributing blocks of tickets through the
Boys and Girls Clubs of Atlanta, took a substantial pay cut to have
the fight staged here in his hometown. He will earn $3.5 million
for the fight, with a chance to make up to $5 million depending on
ticket sales. Typically, Holyfield earns $8 million for a
pedestrian fight like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an opportunity to do something for the people, and I
can't let money be the reason why I don't do it,'' Holyfield said.
``But now, I've got more people coming out than anyone expected.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time Holyfield fought in Atlanta he stopped Bert Cooper
in the seventh round on Nov. 23, 1991, before 12,996 at the Omni.
But Holyfield was a newly crowned champion, with just one defense
under his belt and no established credentials in the heavyweight
division. The fight was poorly organized and promoted, Holyfield
said, because the opponent kept changing. He was supposed to meet
Mike Tyson for the first time, but Tyson had a rib injury and was
under indictment on a rape charge. Another opponent, the Italian
heavyweight Francesco Damiani, pulled out with an ankle injury.
Cooper took the fight on one week's notice.
</P>
<P>
   So for Holyfield, this weekend's fight was the perfect
opportunity to validate himself in his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evander is the greatest fighter in the world, and he deserves
a different type of image,'' King said. ``This is an image
builder.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Holyfield steps into the ring against Bean, Tyson will go
before the Nevada State Athletic Commission to try to have his
license re-instated. Tyson's license was revoked after he bit
Holyfield on both ears during their title bout on June 29, 1997.
Holyfield said Tyson should get his license back, despite the fact
that he has been charged with assaulting two men in suburban
Maryland after a minor traffic accident.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield has made peace with the fact that he and Tyson will be
inextricably linked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure with everything he does, my name comes up too,''
Holyfield said. ``It's not like Tyson is not a good fighter. Iron
sharpens iron. This guy was good. If you mention Ali, you have to
mention Joe Frazier. No one stands alone, because they were that
great and didn't fight anybody. That's life. People are always
going to link you with what you've been through.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
