<SLUG> BC-OBIT-LIPSON-GRUZEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERENICE LIPSON-GRUZEN, CONCERT PIANIST, 73 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Berenice Lipson-Gruzen, a pianist with a long international
career, died Sept. 3 in Bad Wiessee, Germany. She was 73 and lived
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, her family said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lipson-Gruzen won notice with her visit to China in 1981,
recording the Chopin Second Piano Concerto with the Beijing Central
Philharmonic. In New York, she performed at Alice Tully Hall, the
92nd Street Y, Merkin Concert Hall and Weill Recital Hall. She
taught at Cooper Union, the New School for Social Research, New
York University and the City College of New York and gave private
lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lipson-Gruzen was born in Brighton Beach, Brooklyn. She
studied music, anthropology and psychology at Hunter College and
made her piano debut at Carnegie Recital Hall in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   She is survived by her son, Dimitri DeHarak of Montpelier, Vt.,
and her companion, James Keeler, who produced her recordings.
</P>
</TEXT>
