<HEADER>
A9708 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     09-17 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOWDOWN TIME TOOK EARLY TWIST FOR ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Local indifference was on display at the
ballyard last night. And for once in their dysfunctional season,
the indifference couldn't be blamed on the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   First place at stake. Divisional title on the September cooker.
And The Ballpark in Arlington was 9,000 seats short of a sellout.
</P>
<P>
   Blame it maybe on the team's promotional staff. Why didn't
somebody think of a fan giveaway involving X-ray prints of Troy
Aikman's collarbone?
</P>
<P>
   Be it the Angels coming in for the American League West
showdown, or the current management push involving postseason
ticket sales, there's no stampede at the Arlington windows.
</P>
<P>
   Why should there be? The Rangers have been a model of
inconsistency _ or worse _ since June. They can't be trusted to
outlast the Angels in these final days of September. Anaheim, after
all, has had plenty of gumption on its injury-riddled side, while
the Rangers seem to have an on-and-off problem with caring enough
to care.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, by most other divisional standards in baseball,
showdown time in the AL West is a battle of gnat-weights. But with
the Rangers' postseason history _ one time in 27 years _ they don't
have to be Ali or the Yankees. Just winning anything by any means
is rare enough.
</P>
<P>
   But first, the Angels have to be removed from first place. With
five games between the two teams in eight days, the outcome in the
AL West will basically be decided head-up.
</P>
<P>
   Last night's outcome, however, may have been decided in late
July. Or who knows, maybe it was decided 24 hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The trading deadline deal the Rangers made for Todd Stottlemyre
finally showed a sizable profit. Stottlemyre took on the Angels in
the pivotal first game of the fivesome, and he dominated for eight
innings in an eventual 5-3 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers now share first place with the Angels. Of interest,
however, is that on Tuesday night at Tampa Bay, Anaheim may have
sprung a crack in its Team Together image.
</P>
<P>
   A silly dispute occurred an hour before game time at Tampa Bay,
but silly disputes for a contending team this time of year drive
managers up clubhouse walls. Terry Collins, the leading candidate
for AL manager of the year, was no exception.
</P>
<P>
   A pregame memo was received from the home office in Anaheim
regarding playoff tickets. Copies were passed out to the players,
who became hot and hostile became they thought management was
telling them they had to pay for their tickets. Yes, guys making
millions have a personal budget, too. Not to mention most players
are cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Disney drone who typed up the memo had failed to
mention that these tickets were in addition to the two freebies
each player receives. Let it also be noted the Angels aren't
pleased anyway with their Disney bosses, who they think did some
dime-squeezing instead of providing enough trade help.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the dispute was finally cleared up, then the Angels took
the field and lost, 8-1. This came on the heels of the Rangers
staging a Tuesday night ninth-inning rally in Baltimore to pull
within a game of the divisional lead.
</P>
<P>
   Media covering the Angels reported Collins was on a season-high
mad after the Tuesday night game. Yes, he blamed his team for
``distractions.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins had cooled it before the game last night, saying his
reaction was ``frustration more than anything else. I know the
players weren't looking past Tampa Bay. But all the questions (from
the media) for the last week were about Texas and we had other
games to play.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was mentioned Johnny Oates had placed an embargo on the
Rangers speaking about the upcoming Anaheim games, Collins replied,
``I should have done the same thing.'' He said the memo was
``terrible timing. We are fighting for our lives here. All of a
sudden there are all these other things to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming off a disruptive Tuesday night, the Angels immediately
had ace Chuck Finley ripped for a 4-spot in the second inning last
night. Plus, they couldn't solve Stottlemyre.
</P>
<P>
   Some locker-room bulletin-board motivation also didn't work for
the Angels. A newspaper story on this series was tacked up in the
visitors' clubhouse, and ``Rangers'' in the headline was scratched
out. Written in was ``Dirtballs.'' A tad cheesy, don't you think?
</P>
<P>
   But with three games next week in Anaheim, all the Angels need
now is a split of the two here, as a calm Collins pointed out in
his postgame remarks last night. With that, they could leave town
with their one-game lead intact.
</P>
<P>
   Before tonight's finale, maybe Rangers GM Doug Melvin should
have bogus memos passed out in the Angels' locker room. Something
about this-just-in-from Disney:
</P>
<P>
   No free playoff tickets, plus meal money for all players has
hereby been discontinued.
</P>
<P>
   Under some dire circumstances, the Angels have had a good
season. But if a weakness has been found, exploit it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
