<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9710 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVILRAYS-N     09-17 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVILRAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVIL RAYS SHUT OUT YANKEES, 7-0 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Manager Joe Torre usually contains his
angry thoughts and waits a day before unleashing them in a more
digestible form. But he did not bother waiting on Wednesday night,
after fuming through the New York Yankees' 7-0 loss to the Tampa
Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   Torre planted himself in a corner of the clubhouse and chastised
the Yankees for their play and their effort, warning that they
better improve quickly, with under two weeks left before the
American League playoffs begin.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have lost 16 of their last 28 games. You cannot just
turn it on and off, Torre barked, according to one player. ``Kick
it in gear,'' he added, sternly.
</P>
<P>
   But Torre's speech was hardly educational; before he stalked
into the clubhouse, they shared the same thoughts, felt the same
way.
</P>
<P>
   During a pitching change in the eighth inning, with the Yankees
in full retreat, Derek Jeter turned to teammates Scott Brosius and
Homer Bush at the mound and said, in so many words, ``We better
start playing better.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Jeter said: ``It's like we're out there just going
through the motions. We haven't been playing well for a long time.
We just mixed in a couple of good games.''
</P>
<P>
   A Yankees meltdown seemed impossible a month ago, as remote as
snowflakes in August. The Yankees were 92-30 and on pace to shatter
Major League Baseball's single-season record for victories, the 116
games won by the Chicago Cubs in 1906.
</P>
<P>
   The best the Yankees (104-46) can do now is tie the Cubs' mark,
only if they win their final 12 games. But Torre does not care
about that. He is more concerned _ and judging by the timing of his
explosion, growing more concerned by the day _ that the Yankees
start playing better, and soon.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, they were not even prepared to play Tampa
Bay, an expansion team with the league's second-worst record.
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining his usual erect posture on the bench, Torre watched
the struggling Andy Pettitte make a series of terrible pitches and
mistakes and allow six runs in six innings. He watched the Yankees'
hitters overswing constantly with runners on base.
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, the Yankees stranded 11 base runners; Chili Davis
failed to produce an rbi in his first three at-bats despite coming
to the plate with six runners on base.
</P>
<P>
   And the left fielder Chad Curtis made a brutal throw homeward
when he had no shot at the runner there, allowing a trailing Devil
Ray base runner to move from first to second. Fundamental mistakes
on fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stunk tonight, top to bottom,'' Torre said. ``Nobody can
just turn it on. Nobody can, when you beat yourself, pitching or
outfield play or at-bats. We didn't have good at-bats tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've accomplished so many good things. Maybe my club has
spoiled me, and you set your standards a little high.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees maintained during the first two weeks of this slump
that it was no big deal, that they were just tired. But they
changed their testimony on Wednesday night; there were no more
pleadings about an innocent, harmless little slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to turn it up a notch,'' Pettitte said. ``We're
flat. We need to get motivated. Obviously, we aren't playing like
we did in the first five months.''
</P>
<P>
   There is great irony in those words from Pettitte, whose
motivation and effort seem to overwhelm his ability. A radar gun
perched high above the stands here showed that Pettitte's fastball
was consistently clocked in the range of 90 to 93 miles an hour _
strong evidence to Torre that Pettitte is perfectly healthy.
</P>
<P>
   But the left-hander has had a knack of making mistakes, trying
to make pitches too fine and then getting hammered as a result.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte sometimes pitched into trouble and almost never got
himself out. Bush's error gave Tampa Bay a runner at second and two
out, before Pettitte made a poor pitch to Fred McGriff _ whack, a
run-scoring double. Then he choked a changeup so badly that it
bounced some 5 or 6 feet in front of home plate and off catcher Joe
Girardi.
</P>
<P>
   Girardi could not see that the ball had bounced all the way to
the Yankee dugout and, incredibly, the slow-footed and conservative
McGriff scored all the way from second.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte walked Mike Kelly leading off the fifth. Kelly is such
a free swinger, 18 walks and 77 strikeouts in 95 games, that he
virtually requires a visa to take first base this way. Catcher Mike
DiFelice singled, Kelly taking third; then Kelly scored on a
squeeze play. Two outs and a runner at second, the damage still not
beyond repair.
</P>
<P>
   But Pettitte then allowed a run-scoring single to Quinton
McCracken, allowing DiFelice to chug home with Tampa Bay's fourth
run.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte's intensity _ and intense frustration _ showed its face
in the sixth inning, when the Devil Rays' hit him hard.
</P>
<P>
   The hits came courtesy of guys like Bubba Trammell and Aaron
Ledesma and Kelly, not Tim Salmon or Darin Erstad or Juan Gonzalez,
hitters Pettitte may have to face in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte has lost to Minnesota, Chicago and Tampa Bay during his
last eight starts, in which he has accumulated a 6.66 earned run
average. He was pleased with the way he felt, with his stuff. But
Pettitte did not pretend a solution is imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even know what to say anymore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Joe Torre did.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 0018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
