<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9713 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CARDS-PIRATES-NYT     09-17 0353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CARDS-PIRATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS WIN BUT MCGUIRE GOES HOMERLESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ If height were distance, Mark McGwire, the
Cardinals' power hitter, would have had two more home runs on
Wednesday night in Busch Stadium to add to his record-setting total
of 63 for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, his sky-high flyout to center field in the sixth inning
and his space shot that seemed to have aged by about three weeks
the Pittsburgh left-fielder, Turner Ward, as he waited for the ball
to descend in the seventh inning, were simply outs.
</P>
<P>
   True, they excited the 40,928 fans, who rose almost in unison as
McGwire struck the ball and uttered ``Ooohhh!'' in anticipation.
But that was all the theater they could muster out of McGwire on
Wednesday night. He went 0 for 4, with one base on balls, in the
Cardinals' 4-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
   On the scoreboard in deep center field, the season homer totals
of McGwire and Sammy Sosa of the Cubs remained unchanged at game's
end for the Cardinals. McGwire remained at 63 and Sosa, playing in
San Diego, was still at 62.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire walked in the first inning off the left-hander Chris
Peters, who was roundly booed for depriving the fans of possibly
another McGwire clout. The slugger struck out in the third on a
called third strike, and stood at the plate staring down in the
batter's box, clearly unhappy with the plate umpire Randy Marsh.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire had hit his 63d homer the night before, in a pinch-hit
role in the ninth inning of the first game of a doubleheader. He
failed to connect for a homer in the second game.
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday, he had gone six games without a homer. The
longest he had gone previously was 10 games. There had been some
question about the status of his back, since he left last Sunday's
game in the fifth inning with spasms. But he said the back is ``not
an issue'' and he seemed to be swinging hard on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   He understands the disappointment of the fans when he doesn't
please them with a home run. ``But people don't like to give credit
to the pitchers,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
