<HEADER>
A9715 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-REFORM-     09-17 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-REFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CAMPAIGN REFORMER UNDER ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Sept. 17:
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to capitalize on the distraction in Washington,
congressional Republicans are planning a new sneak attack on clean
elections. The target, as before, is Lawrence Noble, general
counsel of the Federal Election Commission and scourge of
fund-raising violations.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have tried repeatedly to oust Noble by attaching
dismissal riders to various bills, only to back down. They are at
it again this week, spreading word that a provision forcing out
Noble will be attached to an unrelated spending bill that has
already passed both the House and Senate. Proponents of campaign
reform must speak out and block this move.
</P>
<P>
   Attacking Noble represents an arrogant assault on an important
agency's independence. Since its establishment to enforce the
election reforms of 1974, the Election Commission has had more than
its share of troubles with Congress. Lawmakers who love to complain
about each other's fund-raising abuses have limited funding for the
commission and insisted on the appointment of weak commissioners
beholden to the political parties.
</P>
<P>
   But the commission's staff has persisted in going after election
law violations by both parties. Attorney General Janet Reno cited a
commission audit as the reason for opening an investigation into
the use of unregulated ``soft money'' for television ads in
President Clinton's last campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are angry because Noble has investigated Republican
fund-raising groups and defended the commission against a
Republican lawsuit to lift all restrictions on the use of soft
money for national campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Only last week Senate Republicans retreated from a proposal
cutting short Noble's term. This week they plan to attach the
measure to a Treasury spending bill that is before a conference
committee. The Republican rider would also let one party or the
other on the commission veto any personnel appointment, a dangerous
step for a bipartisan group.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in the conference committee, if they care about
their independence, should refuse to go along. If the Noble ouster
succeeds, it would present the spectacle of the Republican Party
suing the commission and dismissing the man in charge of defending
against the suit. If the ouster of Noble is adopted, Democratic
senators should be prepared to filibuster, forcing the Republicans
to find 60 votes to close off debate.
</P>
<P>
   Filibustering a Treasury spending bill would be a serious
business. But Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott was willing to
filibuster the McCain-Feingold soft-money ban this month, forcing
supporters to get the 60 votes to end the debate.
</P>
<P>
   After all, a majority in the House and Senate favor a soft-money
ban along with other campaign fund-raising restrictions. They
should do all they can to prevent Republican leaders from using the
back door to squelch reform.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
