<SLUG> BC-BOX-KING-TYSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KING WANTS TYSON TO GET HIS BOXING LICENSE BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Boxing promoter Don King said he believes former
heavyweight champion Mike Tyson should have his license reinstated
by the Nevada State Athletic Commission, but he refused to say why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have the slightest idea whether he will get it back,''
King said. ``Yes, I'd like to see him get his license back. Should
he get his license back? Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson will go before the Nevada State Athletic Commission on
Saturday for a hearing on having his license reinstated. Tyson's
license was revoked after he bit Evander Holyfield on both ears
during their heavyweight championship bout on June 29, 1997. Tyson
has sued King for $100 million in an effort to get out of his
promotional contract with King. King would not comment on the
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   King, speaking following a news conference to promote the
Evander Holyfield-Vaughn Bean heavyweight title bout on Saturday at
the Georgia Dome here, was civil in his comments about Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish Tyson well,'' King said. ``I love the man. We never had
an argument. We never had any animosity. I'm not suffering any type
of pain. Let him live his life and let me live my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson broke from King and his co-managers, Rory Holloway and
John Horne, in February and aligned himself with new advisers,
Shelly Finkel in New York and Jeff Wald in Los Angeles. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
