u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-IRAN-AFGHAN-NYT &LR;      09-17 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-IRAN-AFGHAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: IRAN VS. AFGHANISTAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Sept. 17:
</P>
<P>
   To American eyes, the clerical dictatorships of Iran and
Afghanistan can seem variations on the same Islamic fundamentalist
theme. But relations between the two neighboring countries are now
at a flash point. Ethnic, political and religious tensions have
been exacerbated by the recent killings of at least eight Iranian
diplomats by Afghan Taliban fighters. Iran is now assembling some
250,000 troops along the Afghan border and threatens military
action unless its demands for amends are met.
</P>
<P>
   There is irony here, since 18 years ago it was Iran that held 52
American diplomats hostage for 444 days. This time, Iran has a
legitimate grievance. Carrying out its military threats, however,
would undermine the efforts of President Mohammad Khatami to
reassure the world that Iran no longer seeks to threaten its
neighbors or export revolutionary violence. Instead, Tehran should
stick to diplomacy in pressing its demands for an apology and for
prosecution of the killers by an Iranian or international court.
</P>
<P>
   A United Nations working group on Afghanistan meets in New York
next Monday, and Iran's foreign minister and Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright may attend. Such talks could help defuse the
crisis over Iran's diplomats and ease tensions between Washington
and Tehran.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban, an organization that follows Sunni Muslim precepts
and is allied with Pakistan, now rules most of Afghanistan. But the
country's ethnic and religious diversity has produced opposition to
the Taliban's totalitarian rule. Afghanistan's minority groups
include Shiite Muslims, Farsi-speakers and ethnic groups akin to
those in Iran. Many of these overlapping minorities fear
persecution by the Taliban and have supported the resistance
militias that Taliban forces are now rolling back.
</P>
<P>
   Iran also supports these militias, while Pakistan backs the
Taliban. That explains why Iranian diplomats were stationed in a
militia-held provincial town that fell to Taliban forces last
month. It also explains why Iran now includes an end to Pakistani
military support for the Taliban in its list of demands.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, both Iran and Pakistan should stop their meddling in
Afghanistan's conflict. The Taliban, for its part, should apologize
for the killings of the diplomats and promise a credible criminal
investigation of the incident.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 0026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
