<HEADER>
A9721 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-ASSISTED-SUICIDE     09-17 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ASSISTED-SUICIDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: OVERREACHING ON ASSISTED SUICIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore., Ill.)  (bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Sept. 17:
</P>
<P>
   The House is poised to consider a misguided bill against
assisted suicide that would intrude on the right of doctors to
provide appropriate care at the end of a patient's life and the
right of states to regulate the practice of medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, sponsored by Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., would allow the
federal Drug Enforcement Administration to investigate and punish
any physician who prescribes lethal doses of drugs with the intent
of assisting in a patient's suicide. Even the American Medical
Association, which opposes physician-assisted suicide, is strongly
opposed to this bill.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation is an inappropriate attempt to undo the Oregon
Death With Dignity Act, which citizens in that state approved by a
60 percent vote last November. The Oregon law allows a terminally
ill patient who is of sound mind to obtain a prescription for
lethal drugs if two doctors judge that the patient has less than
six months to live.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, DEA Administrator Thomas Constantine announced
that the agency had authority to revoke a doctor's drug license for
prescribing lethal doses even if the doctor fully complied with
Oregon's law. Attorney General Janet Reno sensibly reversed that
policy in June, ruling that federal drug laws did not give the DEA
power to ban all physician-assisted suicide in this country.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has said that states should be free to engage
in the profound debate over the right to die. Oregonians have
decided that their legislation reflects their needs and values,
while other states have chosen different approaches. But
congressional opponents of the Oregon law want to deny all states
the right to make any judgments on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of heavy-handed legislation is likely to harm patients
and could even cause more suicides. Doctors facing the possibility
of a federal investigation would be less likely to provide
aggressive but potentially lethal drug therapy for pain relief. It
is the lack of adequate pain management that drives some patients
to seek suicide in the first place. The bill, by giving federal
bureaucrats new power to second-guess difficult medical decisions,
would increase needless suffering among terminal patients.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 0027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
