<HEADER>
A9724 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NY-SCHOOL-PRINCI     09-17 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-SCHOOL-PRINCIPALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A PRINCIPAL PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Sept. 17:
</P>
<P>
   Students and teachers are back at their desks. New classrooms
are open while older ones are mostly patched and painted. Now it is
time to confront another crisis threatening New York City schools _
the one in the principal's office.
</P>
<P>
   Last year a record 113 principals gave up their jobs in the
city's public schools. Many of the most talented defected to the
suburbs, where their new posts provide more money and status for
far easier work.
</P>
<P>
   What is worse is that the pool of qualified replacements is
growing smaller by the day, as top-rated applicants become
increasingly rare for a job that some describe as hell with tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the increasing number of schools being run by ``acting
principals'' is a three-year battle between city officials and the
principals' union over a new contract. The Council of Supervisors
and Administrators, a stultifying union that covers school
principals, wants to keep tenure and raise salaries for principals
of the city's 1,100 schools. The city is willing to grant much
higher pay, but only in return for the principals' giving up tenure
and performing more work through longer days and year-round
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, the principals should not even have a union. They are
managers, like the superintendent of a school district or the
president of a college, and should be treated as managers, subject
to removal for poor performance. The principals themselves should
begin trying to extricate themselves from this union if they want
the pay, authority and responsibility they deserve.
</P>
<P>
   But since getting out of the union could take years, the city
and the union _ whose talks stalled again Tuesday night _ should
find some agreement that boosts salaries handsomely in exchange for
ending the grip of tenure. The deal should include some agreement
not to oppose legislative efforts to remove tenure protections from
state law.
</P>
<P>
   At this stage, most city principals earn $20,000 to $25,000 less
than their colleagues in the suburbs. The school system should find
some way to remedy that gap, in exchange for increased freedom to
remove principals who are mediocre at this vital job.
</P>
<P>
   As for the swarm of politicians publicly agonizing about our
children and our schools in this election season, they could do a
service by taking on the tough issue of assuring high-quality
principals. Almost every educational study makes the same point _ a
great school starts with a great principal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 0028EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
