<HEADER>
A9729 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-ASTROS-NYT &LR;      09-17 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ASTROS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE AGAIN, METS COME FROM BEHIND TO WIN GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It would be almost impossible to play four
regular-season games with more plot turns than these. Home run
followed home run as the Mets kept rallying, night after night.
</P>
<P>
   And on Wednesday night, it was Todd Hundley who delivered the
biggest home run of them all.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley, who has been Mike Piazza's backup at catcher this
season after undergoing reconstructive elbow surgery last fall,
followed Piazza's game-saving three-run ninth-inning blast with a
solo homer in the 11th as the New York Mets rallied for a 4-3
victory over the Houston Astros to keep the pressure on the Chicago
Cubs in the National League wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley's third homer of the year, and first pinch-hit blast in
three and a half years, came with two out, on a 2-1 pitch from the
Houston right-hander Sean Bergmann and landed just beyond the
center-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   It came after the Astros had rallied back from Piazza's
hard-to-believe 3-run blast in the top of the ninth, which was
off-set by Brad Ausmus' home run in the bottom of the ninth to
force extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   After both teams threatened in the 10th, Hundley came through
with defining moment of what has been the most frustrating year of
the former All-Star catcher's career. And then Turk Wendell, who
has been the Mets' most valuable right-handed reliever for the
second half of the year, pitched a perfect eleventh for his fourth
save and second in as many games, as the Mets (86-68) had somehow
pulled a season-high 18 games over .500 for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Through eight and a half innings, the situation was so familiar
it was downright scary: the Mets down two runs in the south of
Texas heading into the top of the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   And on Wednesday night, with two outs and two strikes on him in
the top of the ninth, it was now Mike Piazza's turn to do what his
teammates had done before him.
</P>
<P>
   Twice before in the last three games here at the Astrodome, the
Mets had rallied to force extra-innings on improbable home runs.
And then Piazza hit his 200th career homer to give the Mets an
actual ninth-inning lead.
</P>
<P>
   But homers have been kind to the Astros, too, over these last
three topsy-turvy days. And when Brad Ausmus drilled a full-count
homer off Dennis Cook with one out in the bottom of the ninth, the
Mets and Astros were headed for extra innings for the third time in
four raucous games.
</P>
<P>
   What a series.
</P>
<P>
   Brian McRae's ninth-inning homer on Monday night had set the
stage for a 7-4 victory in 13 innings; Carlos Baerga's on Tuesday
night had only prolonged what would become a 6-5 loss in 12 innings
in the first game of a doubleheader, one in which Jeff Bagwell
would homer in the 11th for Houston to force a 12th, in which Derek
Bell would homer to give Houston the game.
</P>
<P>
   And that was all before the Mets would salvage a split for the
evening on John Olerud's go-ahead, 3-run, eighth-inning home run,
as the Mets took the nightcap, 8-4.
</P>
<P>
   These last three days had to be scripted, the way Piazza stepped
to the plate with two on and two out in the top of the ninth
against Houston closer Billy Wagner - what with the Mets, who had
already left 11 runners on base, trailing by 2-0 and trying to stay
with the Chicago Cubs in the wild card chase.
</P>
<P>
   And then Piazza responded on Wednesday evening by doing just
what the Mets hoped he would do in the stretch run when they
acquired the All-Star catcher way back on May 22.
</P>
<P>
   The man who has been carrying the Mets on his back offensively
for more than a month now, drilled a 2-2 pitch from Wagner just
over the fence in right center field for his 32d homer of the
season and a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But, after the Mets had come up with their fourth unbelievable
comeback under the dome this series, the Astros were not through
yet. Ausmus is not known as a home-run threat. But Cook was
pitching for the sixth time in the last eight days. And, after
Ausmus somehow cleared the fence in left center field for his sixth
home runs, it was time for another extra-inning game.
</P>
<P>
   And more dramatics, of course.
</P>
<P>
   In the tenth, Jermaine Allensworth singled to left to open the
tenth against Wagner and took second when the ball skipped through
Moises Alou's legs in left. But, after Luis Lopez sacrificed
Allensworth to third, Rey Ordonez grounded to second with the
infield in and pinch-hitter Matt Franco struck out. And the Mets
had stranded their 12th runner of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Which became all the more alarming when the Astros loaded the
bases against Greg McMichael with two out in the bottom of the
tenth. McMichael had retired the first two Houston batters he had
faced. But the former Met Carl Everett _ whose third-inning homer
had given the Astros their first two runs _ walked, Everett stole
second and took third on Piazza's throwing error.
</P>
<P>
   McMichael responded by intentionally walking Bagwell and then
walking Alou to load them up. And then McMichael fell behind Ricky
Gutierrez 3 balls 0 strikes. Before he threw another pitch,
McMichael nearly picked Everett off third, which would have been
something, too. But then the beleaguered right-hander calmly fired
two called strikes past Gutierrez,, who fouled two full-count
pitches off, before McMichael struck him out on an off-speed pitch
that got away from Piazza, who stepped on home to end the tenth.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it was Hundley's turn. And his first pinch-hit home run
since May 4, 1995 (it was just the fourth of Hundley's career) put
the exclamation on a series that will be hard to forget.
</P>
<P>
   By the time it was over, Mike Hampton and Bobby Jones had been
rendered mere footnotes, even though both had pitched a splendid 8
innings apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton scattered 8 hits and 6 walks in his scoreless outing,
before being lifted just as Lenny Harris had been announced to
pinch-hit to open the ninth. On came Wagner, who had surrendered
McRae's home run on Monday night. And Todd Pratt, pinch-hitting for
Harris, responded with an 0-1 single to left.
</P>
<P>
   But Wagner struck out Tony Phillips and then retired Edgardo
Alfonzo on a long fly to right. And the Mets were down to their
final out. But Olerud drilled a single off third baseman Sean
Berry's glove _ the hit was the Met first baseman's fourth of the
evening and it was hit so hard it caused Berry to leave the game.
And then Piazza came through with one of his biggest hits of the
year, as the Mets finally were able to touch home plate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
