<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLANDERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEETING MAY DECIDE ISLES' HOME ICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE PLACID, N.Y. _ For the first time since the New York
Islanders moved out of Nassau Coliseum last week and filed a $10
million lawsuit against the company that operates the arena,
representatives of both sides will meet on Thursday in the hopes of
reaching an agreement to have the team play its home games at the
Coliseum this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders moved out of the 26-year-old Coliseum last
Thursday, citing ``uninhabitable'' conditions. The team alleged in
the lawsuit against SMG, which runs the Uniondale arena, that the
hoist that supports the scoreboard and speaker system is in danger
of falling from the ceiling. It also contended that SMG knew of the
unsafe condition of the hoist for several months without notifying
the Islanders or Nassau County.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to play someplace safe and where fans can have a good
time watching hockey,'' said Steven Gluckstern, co-owner of the
Islanders, who was here Wednesday for the fourth day of training
camp. ``As of today, in effect, we have no lease.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting will include David Seldin, the president and chief
executive officer of the Islanders; Wes Westley, the president of
SMG, and Thomas Gulotta, the Nassau County Executive. The National
Hockey League will not send a representative, but an official said
yesterday that the league plans to hire independent engineers to
inspect the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our primary objective is to get all of the safety concerns
taken care of so that the season can begin on time and the fans
will not be deprived,'' said David Vieser, a Nassau County
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders-Devils preseason game originally scheduled to be
played at Nassau Coliseum on Sept. 25 has been moved to Lake
Placid. The Islanders sent a letter to season ticket holders
Wednesday with a telephone number to call for information on free
transportation to the game.
</P>
<P>
   Another concern of the Islanders' is their lease at the
Coliseum. Under the current lease, SMG does not share with the team
any revenue generated by parking, advertisements or concessions.
Gluckstern called the contract with SMG ``one of the worst leases
in the NHL.''
</P>
<P>
   Westley of SMG had a Manhattan-based structural engineering firm
inspect the Coliseum on Wednesday, checking everything but the
hoist in question, which has been taken down and is scheduled to be
replaced. According to Westley, the building was found to be safe
for public events.
</P>
<P>
   Should nothing come of Thursday's meeting, the Islanders will
move ahead with a plan to play their first 12 home games of the
regular season at several arenas, including Hartford Civic Arena,
New Haven Veteran Memorial Coliseum, Core States Center or the
adjacent Spectrum in Philadelphia, Continental Airlines Arena in
East Rutherford, N.J., or Madison Square Garden.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 0037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
