A9735 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT &LR;      09-17 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC LIVES: PLACIDO DOMINGO, BILLY JOEL, SI NEWHOUSE, GARRISON
KEILLOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES BARRON with ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DINING NOTES
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ PLACIDO DOMINGO, the tireless tenor, conductor and
cover boy for the redesigned Opera News magazine, was the guest of
honor at an Opera News party Tuesday at his own restaurant,
Domingo's, on East 49th Street. Domingo and the magazine's new
editor and publisher, RUDOLPH RAUCH, did some catching up on things
they had discussed during their interview, including Domingo's
long-out-of-print recording of Verdi's ``I Vespri Siciliani.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said I went and borrowed a copy of that recording and it's
really terrific, and it should be reissued and why hasn't it been
reissued,'' Rauch said. ``He said, `I don't know; there's the man
who can tell us,' and waved his finger at an RCA executive, who
came over and said, `Not that many people are asking for it.' I'm
thinking we can stir up some trouble on our Web site and start a
groundswell to get that recording back in the catalog.''
</P>
<P>
   3 MUSIC SCHOOL DROPOUTS
</P>
<P>
   BILLY JOEL and PAUL SHAFFER, David Letterman's music director
for the last 16 years, went to JIMMY WEBB's performance Tuesday at
Rainbow and Stars, the nightclub in the GE Building at 30
Rockefeller Plaza. Then Joel, Shaffer and Webb went to dinner. Make
that Dr. Joel, Dr. Shaffer and Dr. Webb.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're also all kind of musical dropouts,'' Webb said, ``but
we've all got these honorary doctorates. We tease each other and
call each other `Doctor.''' Webb said that his and Shaffer's
degrees were from Five Towns College on Long Island. ``I think
Billy has a whole briefcase full of them,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   PARTY ON, SI &QL;
</P>
<P>
   S.I. NEWHOUSE JR., the chairman of Advance Publications and
overseer of all things Conde Nast, has never been a big fan of
employee parties. So it came as a surprise to regulars on the
Manhattan party circuit when this week brought invitations to not
one, not two, but three Newhouse parties.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Newhouse gave a cocktail party for 100 people at the
Four Seasons restaurant in honor of RUTH WHITNEY, who is retiring
as editor of Glamour magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Newhouse, looking almost Armani-esque in a dark suit
and black T-shirt, gave a party for 200 people at Gotham. This one
honored DAVID REMNICK, the new editor of The New Yorker. And last
night, Newhouse invited another 250 to toast ART COOPER, the editor
of GQ _ again at the Four Seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been working with Si for 15 years,'' Cooper said, ``and
I never suspected that he was this iron-man party animal.''
</P>
<P>
   WRITER'S CRAMP &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GARRISON KEILLOR, the bard of Lake Wobegon, often ends his
public-radio program, ``A Prairie Home Companion,'' by crediting
what he says is the show's writing staff: Sarah Bellum, Pete Moss,
Sandy Beach and Warren Peace, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Many longtime listeners assumed that these were made-up names
and that Keillor had written every word by himself. But now he is
looking for a real, live writer to help out.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Public Radio, which produces the show, placed a
classified advertisement in The New York Times on Sunday and said
it was taking similar ads in Variety and The Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a two-hour show every week for 34 weeks a year, that is
an awful lot of material,'' said CHRISTINE TSCHIDA, the producer.
``Garrison does write nearly the entire program. It would be nice
to have a few other submissions to take off some of the pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Nice, but not easy. Minnesota Public Radio received 50 responses
to a Web-site ad in July. ``Of those 50, I've passed along about a
dozen to Garrison,'' Ms. Tschida said. ``He looked at them, and he
thought that some definitely had some flashes of brilliance, but.
He was hoping to really be bowled over, and he hasn't been bowled
over yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
