<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS DOWN ANGELS, 5-3, MOVE INTO FIRST-PLACE TIE IN AL WEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Many observers perceived the Rangers as the
American League West's team to beat July 31.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps perception became reality last night at The Ballpark in
Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Todd Stottlemyre _ whom the organization acquired
that July afternoon _ represented the best of general manager Doug
Melvin's efforts, and great expectations became realized during the
Rangers' 5-3 victory against the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre, who recorded seven strikeouts and surrendered only
one run on six hits through eight innings, provided the Rangers his
best performance to date. The victory gave the Rangers and Angels
identical 81-70 records with 11 games remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just absolutely went out there and shut them down,'' said
Rangers first baseman Will Clark, who refused to shut down after
fracturing the big toe on his right foot Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Clark served as the catalyst for the Rangers' four-run second
inning with his leadoff home run against Angels left-hander Chuck
Finley (11-8), and shortstop Royce Clayton later delivered a
two-run double that gave Stottlemyre (4-4) the offensive support
needed to pitch aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre, who provided the rotation's 13th quality start
during the past 17 games, proved as tough as the situation
dictated. The Angels went 0-for-6 with runners in scoring position,
and the heart of their lineup _ center fielder Jim Edmonds,
designated hitter Tim Salmon and right fielder Garret Anderson _
went 0-for-11 with one walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story of the game,'' Clark said, ``was Todd.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre, who took a 5-1 lead into the seventh inning, came
through magnificently during his greatest crisis. A two-out double
by Angels shortstop Gary DiSarcina put runners at second and third
and brought left fielder Gregg Jefferies to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferies entered the at-bat with two doubles and a fifth-inning
solo home run that accounted for the Angels' lone run, and
Stottlemyre put himself at a distinct disadvantage immediately with
consecutive pitches that eluded the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I've got a base open,'' Stottlemyre said. ``I know he's
gotten three hits. I'm either going to make the perfect pitch or
miss.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre responded with two quality fastballs down and away
to work the count even, but a third consecutive fastball missed.
The wheels then began to churn in the mind of catcher Ivan
Rodriguez, who flashed the signal for a 3-2 curveball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was such a great call, a gutsy call,'' Stottlemyre said.
``I was just going to grip it and rip it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre admitted that the curveball hung in the strike zone,
but the change of speed after three consecutive fastballs
devastated Jefferies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't sit on a 3-2 curveball,'' said Jefferies, who swung
through the pitch. ``It was the first one I saw all night.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre hopped off the mound and shook his fists in triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pitched a great game,'' Jefferies said. ``He got me out
when he needed to.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels made it interesting during the ninth inning after
Rangers closer John Wetteland surrendered a one-out, two-run homer
to catcher Matt Walbeck, but an improbable rally died there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep hearing how bad we are and how we should be 10 games
ahead and that our players are underachieving,'' Rangers manager
Johnny Oates said. ``Now, the only way we can redeem ourselves is
to go out and win this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers acquired Stottlemyre in an effort to achieve that
goal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
