r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     09-17 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OATES HAD RIGHT PLAN AS STOTTLEMYRE PROVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Two-and-a-half weeks ago someone writing
under the same name you see with this column tried to tell Rangers
manager Johnny Oates that he had to juggle his rotation for
Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   No way, that idiot said then, could Oates let the Todd
Stottlemyre of August start two critical games against the
front-running Angels in the middle of a late September pennant
race.
</P>
<P>
   Thank the baseball gods, Oates didn't listen.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, that wasn't exactly the Stottlemyre of August who
stepped up with one of the biggest games of his career last night
at The Ballpark in Arlington and once again enhanced his reputation
as a big-game pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre held the American League West-leading Angels to one
run in eight commanding innings and the Rangers survived a shaky
ninth by closer John Wetteland to win, 5-3, in the opener of a
critical two-game series.
</P>
<P>
   The victory sent the Rangers surging into a first-place tie with
the Angels, who are showing signs that they may finally be running
out of gas.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Rangers' second consecutive clutch victory, coming on
the heels of Tuesday night's come-from-behind 6-5 triumph in
Baltimore, while the Angels have dropped six of their past eight.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' clubhouse was still buzzing with electricity long
after the game. Loud music poured out of the jam-box speakers.
Stottlemyre was surrounded six-deep by reporters. Will Clark, who
ignited the Rangers' four-run second with a solo home run, sipped a
beer, kept his broken toe shoved into a bag of ice and extolled the
greatness of Stottlemyre to anyone who cared to listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big-game performance by a big-game pitcher,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   A relieved and excited Wetteland charged into Oates' office in
his underwear, reliving the nail-biting ninth when a base runner
reached on a strikeout/wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The game was delayed momentarily by a fan racing from the
right-field foul line to the left-field corner, where he raised his
hands above his head and waited for security to lead him away, and
then Wetteland surrendered a two-run homer to Matt Walbeck, cutting
the Rangers' lead to two and bringing the fans to the edge of their
seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm out there telling myself to keep up the intensity, keep up
the intensity,'' Wetteland said. ``I was so mad when I gave up that
home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``That guy (the fan who ran on the field), he shouldn't go to
jail. We should just go into a room together.''
</P>
<P>
   After Wetteland left, Oates grinned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think John turned it up a notch after that home run,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   No one has raised the bar higher than Stottlemyre, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few days ago we were sitting here, trying to decide who
would pitch this ballgame,'' Oates conceded after the Rangers had
regained a share of first for the first time since they led the
Angels by half a game on Aug. 13. ``We decided on Todd, and he was
very excited that he was going to be the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates won't say how close he came to looking for another option,
but Stottlemyre helped him make up his mind with strong
performances in his past three starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not damaged goods when we got him (from St. Louis at
the trading deadline), but he was not healthy,'' Oates said. ``He
hadn't pitched in 16 or 17 days, and he just wasn't 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell the difference in his last two starts
particularly. He has really been able to snap his breaking ball off
the table on hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for Gregg Jefferies, who doubled twice and hit a solo
homer in the fifth, the Angels had few good swings against
Stottlemyre, whose pivotal moment came in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   He had the four-run lead, but Craig Shipley had dumped a two-out
single into right and Gary DiSarcina had drilled a double into the
left-field corner, bringing the dangerous Jefferies back to the
plate. Stottlemyre struck him out with a full-count curveball that
started at Jefferies' eyes and tumbled to his knees.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was as big an out as there was in the game,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   At 120 pitches, Stottlemyre might have finished it, but with
Wetteland available in the bullpen, Oates saw no reason to push it.
</P>
<P>
   Eight superb innings was enough to prove that starting
Stottlemyre against the Angels last night and again next week in
Anaheim were the most logical and sanest decisions a manager could
ever make.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a full investigation is under way in an attempt to
discover the identity of the irrational scoundrel who was able to
sneak his own opinion in under this column sig, suggesting that
Oates' forget about Stottlemyre completely.
</P>
<P>
   Shame on him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 0058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
