<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9756 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-RANGERS-HN     09-17 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-RANGERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEIL HOHLFELD  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON _ When the Texas Rangers made a trade-deadline deal to
acquire pitcher Todd Stottlemyre and shortstop Royce Clayton from
St. Louis on July 31, they undoubtedly had September in mind.
</P>
<P>
   It was Stottlemyre's pitching and Clayton's hitting, fielding
and baserunning that led the Rangers past Anaheim 5-3 Wednesday and
into a first-place tie with the Angels in the American League West
Division.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams are 81-70; they play four of their remaining 11 games
against each other.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have a chance tonight to regain first place for the
first time since Aug. 13 when they send 19-game winner Rick Helling
against Anaheim knuckleballer Steve Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers and Angels also play three games next week in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre had been a disappointment in eight previous starts
with the Rangers, going 3-4 with a 5.56 ERA. But he worked eight
strong innings Wednesday, allowing one run on six hits, three of
them to Gregg Jefferies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that when you get traded for, there are a lot of
expectations,'' said Stottlemyre. ``To this point, I'd pretty much
come up a little short. But I also know that if you have a good
September, everybody forgets what you did in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't pitched well since coming over, and all day today I
was really focused. I didn't say much to my family at home, and I
didn't say anything to my teammates at the park. I knew the task at
hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Clayton went 2-for-4 with a two-run double in a four-run second
inning against Chuck Finley, who allowed nine hits and five runs in
6 innings as he lost his eighth straight decision to the Rangers
dating to June 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Clayton stole third base in the second inning and
made a run-saving stop of a ground ball into the hole in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton and Stottlemyre were key components when St. Louis
overtook the Astros to win the National League Central title in
1996. This July 31, the Rangers traded three young players to the
Cardinals for Clayton and Stottlemyre, both of whom will be free
agents at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   For Anaheim manager Terry Collins, it must seem like a recurring
bad dream. In 1996, when Collins was the Astros' manager, they had
a 2{-game lead over St. Louis on Sept. 1 but went 8-16 the rest of
the way and finished six games behind the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Collins was fired at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Todd Stottlemyre is one of the best competitors out there,''
said Collins. ``When I saw him for the first time when St. Louis
got him, the thing that jumped out was his competitiveness. It
seems like when things are at the tightest, he steps it up a notch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Royce Clayton has hurt me many times. He's a good shortstop,
both offensively and defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   For Collins and the Angels, another September to forget looms.
</P>
<P>
   Collins has a 40-50 record in four Septembers as a major-league
manager. When he managed the Astros, they fell short to Colorado by
one game in the wild-card race in 1995 and were caught and lapped
by the Cardinals a year later.
</P>
<P>
   Last season at Anaheim, the Angels led the AL West in late
August and were one game back on Sept. 1 but went 10-15 the rest of
the way as Seattle won the division.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have a recent September history that is even more
grim.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1991, they are 53-90 in the ``S'' month. The finish to the
1995 season was the measure of how to blow a commanding lead down
the stretch. The Angels led Seattle by 7{ games on Sept. 1 before
going 10-16 and losing a one-game playoff to Randy Johnson and the
Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers manager Johnny Oates said, ``I keep hearing about how
bad we are. I hear that we should be 10 games ahead by now, about
how we're underachieving. I guess the only thing we can do now to
redeem ourselves is to win this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The AL West is the only division title in the majors not
decided. With the home-run race in full bloom and four division
winners with more than 100 wins or positioned to reach that total,
the Rangers and Angels are more or less a footnote to this baseball
season.
</P>
<P>
   Before Wednesday's game, Collins said he has tried to deflect
attention from the AL West race in order to take pressure off his
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told them that if you think for one second that the focus
of the baseball world is on us, you're crazy,'' said Collins.
``We're barely being noticed. The focus is still in St. Louis (Mark
McGwire) and in Chicago (Sammy Sosa), and it should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are saying that we shouldn't even be here, so
why should we be uptight about anything?''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have lost five of their last six games, are 5-8 in
September and have lost four games in the standings to the Rangers
since Aug. 26.
</P>
<P>
   And while Collins says he has scaled back his white-hot
intensity a bit, he pitched a fit Tuesday after his team lost 8-1
at Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Collins sensed that his players were looking past the Devil
Rays. He was incensed when a memo from the front office circulated
around the clubhouse, and players groused about having to pay for
playoff tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Collins let his players know in no uncertain terms that they
wouldn't have to worry about playoff tickets unless they started to
focus more on their task at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was mad last night because we were playing Tampa Bay and
nobody was talking about Tampa Bay,'' said Collins. ``I wasn't
nervous; I was mad.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are 3-5 against Anaheim this year, all three wins
coming against Finley.
</P>
<P>
   Will Clark's homer set the tone in the second inning, and
Clayton's two-run double put the Rangers ahead 3-0. Stottlemyre did
most of the rest, holding the Angels' big hitters _ Jim Edmonds,
Tim Salmon and Garret Anderson _ to a combined 0-for-10.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, with runners on second and third, Stottlemyre
struck out Jefferies to end the threat and pumped his fist as he
came off the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``You like those people with that look,'' said Oates. ``He has a
presence that allows his teammates to gain confidence by just
watching him walk around. When guys like that walk out there, it's
like they're saying, `This is ours. Nobody is taking it from us.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
