<HEADER>
A9758 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BILLS-SMITH-HNS &LR;      09-17 1606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BILLS-SMITH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
ORCHARD PARK, N.Y. _ Life could not be better for Buffalo Bills
running back Antowain Smith.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sure, Smith would like for the Bills to be 2-0 rather than 0-2.
He would like to have more than 88 yards rushing, but he knows they
have 14 games left after losses at San Diego and Miami. And he
plans to rush for at least 1,300 yards and lead Buffalo back to the
NFL playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In his second season, Smith has a new coach, Wade Phillips, who
believes in him. He has a new role that features Smith in a
run-oriented system. A former No. 1 pick from the University of
Houston, Smith has money in the bank and a new two-story house in
this quaint, picturesque town just outside Buffalo and not far from
the Bills' offices at Rich Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antowain's got unlimited potential,'' says Phillips, the
Bills' defensive coordinator who was elevated after last season to
replace the retired Marv Levy. ``He's just so big (6-2 and 240
pounds) and fast (4.4 in the 40), and he knows how to run, too. He
has the power and toughness to run over people, but he also makes
good cuts and can bounce outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is his year to see where he's going to be because we're
going to get him the ball more as the season progresses.''
</P>
<P>
   As a rookie last season, Smith played behind Thurman Thomas but
saw enough action to convince his coaches, teammates and people
around the league he could be something special. More important,
Smith developed the confidence to prove to himself he can be one of
the best backs in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a bigger role this season, and there's more pressure
on me,'' Smith says. ``I'm the man who has to get the job done, but
my teammates will be a big part of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can be as good as I want to be, and I want to be
what Barry Sanders is to Detroit and Terrell Davis is to Denver. I
know it's not going to come easy. I busted my butt in the
offseason, and I'm ready to shoulder the load.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bills are off to a slow start, but Smith's teammates and
coaches believe he is ready to carry that burden.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's what I call a lineman-friendly runner because he makes
our jobs easier,'' Pro Bowl guard Ruben Brown says. ``Because
Antowain's so powerful, he gets a lot of extra yards. He can push
the pile. He also can make his own holes.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds offensive line coach Carl Mauck: ``He's got a great burst,
that extra gear a lot of runners don't have.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since Thomas joined the Bills in 1988, he is
not the starting halfback. Smith, his teammate, friend and protg,
earned the job after an impressive rookie performance last season
that continued through training camp and the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   In the offseason, Thomas and Smith reside in Houston, where they
plan to move permanently when their careers end. Because Thomas,
32, will return to Houston before Smith, he is passing the torch
with grace and dignity to the player who has taken his starting
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my 11th year, and I was a starter for the first 10,''
Thomas says. ``That's a lot of football. I'm not going to stand
here and say I feel like I'm 25 years old. I feel like I'm 32 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been very easy for me to help Antowain. I recognize
talent, and he's got talent. He's also a good person. I'm still
teaching him the tricks of the trade in the NFL, but he's a Pro
Bowl-caliber player who can put the team on his shoulders and carry
them all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who grew up in Alabama and played junior-college football
in Mississippi before signing with the Cougars, believes he has
been blessed in ways most people can't comprehend. He uses Thomas'
attitude toward him as an example.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most guys wouldn't have taken me under their wing like Thurman
did,'' Smith says. ``They would have turned their back on me
because I was the new kid trying to win his job. I didn't know
Thurman before I came here. I always knew he was a great player,
but I really respect him because of what he's done for me. He's
making me a better player.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have helped me get to where I am today. I
think it was destiny that brought me to the NFL. The long, hard
road that I took, the obstacles I had to overcome, I think God was
testing my will to see if I would quit. I didn't. I never take
anything for granted. I know from personal experience that on any
given day what we've worked so hard for can be taken away. I just
thank God I got this opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   When Smith talks about overcoming obstacles, he isn't
exaggerating. Few athletes have persevered as Smith has.
</P>
<P>
   In high school, Smith played football only in his senior year,
but Auburn and Alabama wanted him. Rather than play big-time
college football, however, Smith got a job in a factory that dyed
clothes because his grandmother, Clara Smith, was severely ill.
Smith spent three years caring for his grandmother before she died
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was basically raised by my grandmother and grandfather,''
Smith says. ``My mother had me when she was 16. We've got a good
relationship. I understand that times were tough back then. My
grandmother worked in the kitchen at my high school. She suffered a
stroke and wasn't able to do things she used to do. I elected to go
to work to take care of her. I made $5.50 an hour, and I worked the
3-to-11 p.m. shift so I could drive her back and forth to the
hospital so she could undergo kidney dialysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cooked for her and cleaned for her. I basically did whatever
she needed to be done. Sure, I wanted to go out with my friends and
enjoy life at 18 and 19, but I wanted to take care of her. I'm the
oldest of seven children, and I've always believed that you should
always put your family first.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandmother did everything in her power to take care of me.
A lot of people looked at what I did as a sacrifice, but to me it
wasn't a sacrifice at all because I loved her dearly. Near the end,
it was hard for me to visit her in the hospital and see her hooked
up to all those tubes, but I'd sit there and tell her not to worry
because I was going to be all right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I know she's up there looking down on me, and she's just
tickled to death that her baby made it.''
</P>
<P>
   After his grandmother died, Smith quit his job and went to
Atlanta to spend a few weeks with his mother and his brothers and
sisters. He and a friend planned to join the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the last thing my grandmother told me before she died was,
`Son, go to school,''' Smith says. ``That's what stuck in my mind.
It was always her dream to see me go to college.''
</P>
<P>
   After three years of inactivity, Smith was out of shape, but he
got a tryout at a junior college in Scooba, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran a 40-yard dash, and they gave me a scholarship right
then,'' he says. ``Man, I wanted to go home. That town was so
small, there was only one convenience store.''
</P>
<P>
   After his first practice, Smith tried to go home to Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost quit football the first day,'' he says. ``I was so
out of shape. I almost died. I had to get help to get off the
field, I was so exhausted. I tried to quit. The reason I couldn't
is because when I called home, no one would come get me. I really
didn't have any choice, so I thought since I was going to have to
stay, I might as well make the best of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith had an excellent sophomore year and met University of
Houston coach Kim Helton.
</P>
<P>
   ``When coach Helton recruited me,'' Smith says, ``he said, `Son,
if you want to get to the National Football League, I'm the one
that can help you get there. I coached in the NFL. I've got great
contacts in the NFL, and we run a pro-style offense.'
</P>
<P>
   ``What really sold me was when I came to Houston. There was so
much to do. I loved Houston right away. I was ready for a change. I
grew up in Alabama and spent two years in Mississippi, and I wanted
to go to a big city. My first year at U of H, I was second-guessing
myself because we went 2-9, but we went to a bowl game my last
year, and everything worked out well.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's senior year at UH was bittersweet. He was an outstanding
player who impressed NFL scouts at the Senior Bowl and the scouting
combine. But his grandfather died of cancer, which also struck a
younger brother, Quintin Long. Now, his brother's cancer is in
remission, and he attends Houston Community College.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really miss my grandparents,'' Smith says. ``Not a day goes
by that I don't think about them. I have their initials on the
shirt I wear (under his jersey) to every game. I just wish they
could be here to share this with me.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I think if you can overcome tragedy in your family,
you can overcome anything. I had to grow up early. I experienced a
lot at a young age.''
</P>
<P>
   When Smith left Houston, he was 25, which repelled a lot of NFL
teams but not Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ``His age didn't scare us, because we knew he hadn't been hit a
lot,'' Bills general manager John Butler says. ``He wasn't a
beat-up 25-year-old. We knew his background and what he went
through.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so refreshing to see a guy with the type of character
Antowain has. Whether it's his age or what took place in his past,
he knows how to handle success.''
</P>
<P>
   Success didn't come easy for Smith, and unless everyone is
wrong, he should have a lot of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my age, my maturity level, has helped me deal with
this situation better,'' Smith says. ``There are a lot of things
that can distract you if you want to explore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this: I don't think anyone could appreciate what I have
any more than I do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
