<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9762 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SAINTS-SMITH-HNS &LR;      09-17 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SAINTS-SMITH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
NEW ORLEANS _ New Orleans is the ultimate party town, but running
back Lamar Smith did not come to the Big Easy to drink and carouse.
He couldn't find the French Quarter with a city map and has no
desire to.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Smith, who played at the University of Houston, is happy
sticking close to the Saints' practice facility in Metairie. He is
focusing on football, making new friends and trying to put his past
where it belongs _ behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Sidetracked by tragedy and hungry from inactivity, Smith came to
New Orleans to add punch to coach Mike Ditka's offense. He left
Seattle for New Orleans because he wanted to rejuvenate a football
career that had been derailed by an automobile accident that left
former Seahawks teammate Mike Frier partially paralyzed and caused
Smith to spend two months in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new start for me, and I'm really enjoying myself,''
says Smith, who got out of a Washington jail on a work furlough in
March to come to New Orleans to sign a four-year, $7.1 million
contract. ``It's taken me awhile to get into shape physically, but
everyone's treating me real well.''
</P>
<P>
   And they will treat him even better if he continues to make the
kind of big plays he made in victories over St. Louis and Carolina.
Against the Rams, Smith caught a 35-yard touchdown pass and threw
an option pass for a touchdown. Against the Panthers, Smith carried
12 times for 78 yards. New Orleans rushed for 207 yards against the
Panthers, which brought tears of joy to Ditka's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Considering what he has gone through, Smith's career in New
Orleans could not have gotten off to a better start. He's glad to
be out of Seattle. Things were never the same for him after that
cool, rainy night in his rookie season of 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was driving. His passengers were Frier in the back seat
and running back Chris Warren in the front. They had been drinking.
The car slid off the road and crashed into a telephone pole. When
Smith was tested, he was barely over the legal limit for public
intoxication.
</P>
<P>
   ``They treated me as if I were a career criminal,'' Smith says
of the Seattle fans. ``It was an accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith emphasizes the word ``accident.''
</P>
<P>
   It could have happened to anyone who drinks and drives. And it
happened to Smith, who spent a lot of time wondering: ``Why me? Why
was I driving?''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Smith experienced enormous guilt over Frier, a
defensive lineman, being paralyzed below the waist. The guilt might
have been too much for Smith to overcome if not for Frier and his
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike's been wonderful about the whole thing,'' Smith says.
``He knows what happened. He knows I didn't mean to do it. We have
a great relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I talked to him (after the accident) was a real
trying moment for me because I didn't know how he'd accept me. I
didn't know if he'd hate me for what I'd done to him. But he
welcomed me with open arms. We had tears in our eyes, and we
hugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``His parents have been great, too. If it weren't for them, I
just don't know how I would have been able to handle it or if I
would have.''
</P>
<P>
   Originally, police tried to say Warren, the Seahawks' star
running back, had been driving even though the players told the
truth. The general opinion was that Smith, the rookie, was trying
to protect Warren.
</P>
<P>
   When it was finally figured out and determined that Smith was
indeed driving, he was charged with vehicular assault. The judge
sentenced him to 120 days in jail. He got off 30 days for community
service and 30 days for good behavior.
</P>
<P>
   To settle a civil suit with Frier, Smith agreed to give his
former teammate 40 percent of his earnings and 50 percent of his
incentive bonuses. And his contract is full of performance bonuses
that kick in when he rushes for 700 yards. He can earn as much as
$5 million in incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's mother, who resides in their native Indiana, moved to
Seattle to be with her son and help him deal with the situation.
Now, his mother has gone back home, and her son is in New Orleans
trying to make a new start on what had been such a promising
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, it was tough,'' Smith says in a voice so soft it's almost
a whisper. ``It was a four-year nightmare for me. I'd go into a
restaurant, and I could tell people were looking at me in a certain
way, like I was some kind of criminal who'd done a lot of bad
things. That's not who I am. I just couldn't take it. It was
really, really hard on me.''
</P>
<P>
   As an organization, the Seahawks treated Smith well after the
accident. But the public never really knew who Lamar Smith was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a private person,'' he says. ``I don't reveal a lot of
myself publicly. People didn't know me. After the accident, a lot
of them thought they did, but what they thought was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a bad person. I'm a good person.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than continue his appeal, he pleaded guilty, accepted his
sentence and served 60 days this past offseason on a work-release
program. He still must perform 240 hours of community service,
which he plans to do in New Orleans. He's on probation for one
year, and he has to call his probation officer once a month. His
driver's license has been suspended for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 27, never played regularly for the Seahawks. When he
played at the University of Houston, Smith became one of the
Southwest Conference's better backs before suffering a shoulder
injury. Seattle selected him in the third round of the 1994 draft,
but it was his misfortune to play behind Warren.
</P>
<P>
   Smith received opportunities when Warren was injured. In 1996,
he rushed for 680 yards. Last season, he was limited to 392 after
suffering a broken ankle.
</P>
<P>
   When Smith reported to training camp with the Saints, he was not
in good shape because he had done the time in jail. He had to work
overtime to get into the kind of shape he wants. He is listed at
5-11 and 218 pounds, but he is playing closer to 225.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still getting into a comfort zone,'' he says. ``I'm still
not where I want to be, but I'm getting there. My conditioning has
improved week to week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just thankful to be playing football. While I was in jail,
there was one point where I felt stripped of everything. It wasn't
a good feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's position coach, Lary Kuharich, is his biggest fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether by run or catch, Lamar has a unique ability to run
with the ball,'' Kuharich says. ``He's taking advantage of his
chance. He does something every day that draws a response from his
teammates and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``At his size, to do the things he does is really extraordinary.
We think he can be a big-play, game-breaking type of back. We have
to make him some room. He's shown that even when he's trapped in
the backfield, he can make moves to get out of trouble. He's tough,
competitive and smart. We knew he was a good pass protector from
watching him on film, but we're asking him to block on the run,
too, and he's knocking people down. He's everything a lead back
should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Center Jerry Fontenot is one of the blockers who has to give
Smith some daylight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed a guy who can be a possession back, someone who can
get four or five yards a pop,'' Fontenot says. ``Lamar's got strong
legs, but he's also nifty enough to put moves on people. Once he
gets this offense down a little more, he'll definitely make a big
impact on our running game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
