<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9763 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOG-DNA-TRIAL-SPI &LR;      09-17 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOG-DNA-TRIAL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOG DNA HELPS CONVICT TWO OF MURDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELAINE PORTERFIELD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The blood of a dead dog named Chief helped convict two
Seattle men of murder Wednesday in the first trial ever in the
country to use animal DNA as evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The courtroom of King County Superior Court Judge Richard Jones
erupted into moans, sobs and profanity as soon as the verdicts were
read. Courtroom officers had to step in to separate the families of
the victims and the defendants on the orders of the judge.
</P>
<P>
   The officers then trooped into the hallway to maintain order.
</P>
<P>
   The jury convicted Kenneth John Leuluaialii, 23, of aggravated
first-degree murder and of one count of first-degree animal
cruelty. Because prosecutors did not seek the death penalty, the
only sentence is life in prison with no chance of release.
</P>
<P>
   The jury also convicted George Tuilefano, 23, of two counts of
first-degree murder. He faces a minimum of 20 years in prison on
each count, served consecutively, Senior Deputy Prosecutor Tim
Bradshaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuilefano was acquitted of animal cruelty.
</P>
<P>
   Both men stared down and ran their hands through their long hair
after hearing the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   The pair was accused of shooting to death 20-year-old Raquel
Rivera and Jay Johnson, 22, along with their dog Chief, in the
couple's South Park apartment in December 1996. Prosecutors say
Leuluaialii and Tuilefano burst into the apartment demanding drugs
and cash.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera and Johnson died at the scene. Chief died about 30 hours
later, despite efforts to save his life.
</P>
<P>
   The blood of the dead dog helped convict the two, Bradshaw said
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We owe a debt to the scientific community,'' Bradshaw said.
</P>
<P>
   The DNA tests were ``exceedingly important,'' Bradshaw added.
``We could not only identify it as dog blood, but individuate it to
a single dog.''
</P>
<P>
   One unidentified juror said the evidence was very important
because it placed the men at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   But juror Mark Madden of Mercer Island said other evidence
figured more prominently in his decision. A distinctive footprint
on the front door of the slain couple's apartment that matched
shoes worn by Leuluaialii was very convincing, Madden said.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the testimony of witnesses who saw the pair at the
apartment was convincing as well, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My assessment is that a lot of the witnesses weren't
necessarily the most reliable ... but their stories seemed to
match,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors told jurors that Johnson was tortured by being shot
in both thighs by Leuluaialii. After Johnson then said ``justkill
me,'' Leuluaialii handed the gun to Tuilefano, who shot Johnson
three more times.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera was shot in the chin and mouth as she screamed,
prosecutors said, and in the neck. Chief was shot twice.
</P>
<P>
   Leuluaialii's lawyer asked Jones to immediately sentence his
client, but the judge declined to do so, saying the families of the
victims had a right to speak at his sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   No sentencing date has been set.
</P>
<P>
   After the verdict, Leuluaialii kissed a baby held up by a young
woman over and over _ as a relative of one the victims cried out,
``No more, no more'' _ before corrections officers handcuffed and
led him away. Relatives refused to identify the baby.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his violent behavior at previous court appearances,
Leuluaialii has been strapped into a special security chair to be
wheeled between the courtroom and the jail.
</P>
<P>
   Leuluaialii also asked the judge which prison he would be sent
to. Jones told him that decision was up to the state Department of
Corrections.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the judge rebuked a female relative of Leuluaialii for
her lack of control. The woman cried out, ``He's not a killer, God
knows'' and ``I love you'' before telling Johnson's family he had
deserved to be killed.
</P>
<P>
   The victims' families slipped from the courthouse without
speaking publicly.
</P>
<P>
   The jury began deliberations Monday morning, following two
months of testimony. Jurors signaled they'd reached a verdict
Wednesday by midafternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think public safety was served today,'' Bradshaw said.
``We're indebted to the jurors.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief's DNA was central to their case, said Bradshaw, who called
the dog the third, silent victim in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Its blood was found spattered on the right arm of a jacket
belonging to Leuluaialii. A sheriff's deputy testified that he saw
Leuluaialii wearing what appeared to be the same jacket several
weeks before the killings.
</P>
<P>
   The jacket was found in a Lakewood motel room when Leuluaialii
was arrested the day after the killings. Without DNA tests on the
jacket, it might have been much tougher obtaining convictions,
Bradshaw said.
</P>
<P>
   DNA from cat hair had been used in a Canadian case, authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers put three DNA experts of their own on the stand
to dispute the conclusions of experts for the state. They also
questioned the credibility of prosecution witnesses, and tried to
cast doubt on who owned the blood-spattered clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Although the prosecution had sought an aggravated-murder
conviction against Tuilefano, as well as Leuluaialii, Bradshaw said
he respected the jury's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tuilefano's conviction was based on accomplice liability,
clearly,'' he said, not for being the primary force behind the
crime.
</P>
<P>
   This report includes information from The Associated Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
