r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-ROCKIES-L     09-17 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-ROCKIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEAT ROCKIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa both surpassed Babe
Ruth's monumental single-season home run total over the last two
weeks. Los Angeles Dodgers pitcher Brian Bohanon looks as if he
caught and passed Ruth's waistline some time ago.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it, Bohanon's chances of winning a Mr. Olympia title
are about as good as the Dodgers' hopes of making the playoffs. At
6-foot-2 and a playing weight well above his listed 219 pounds,
Bohanon could easily have the worst body in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   But the left-handed, pot-bellied pitcher looks toned and trim in
today's box score. He mixed speeds and location and established a
career high in strikeouts to beat the Colorado Rockies 2-0 in front
of an announced crowd of 27,906 at Dodger Stadium on Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon, a journeyman whom the Dodgers picked up in a July 10
trade with the New York Mets, allowed two hits to start the game
and then retired 12 of the next 13 Rockies. He threw eight shutout
innings before being relieved by Jeff Shaw, who picked up his 44th
save despite giving up three hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very confident right now,'' Bohanon said. ``I feel like I
could put the ball wherever I want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Glenn Hoffman, who has seen Hoffman go eight
innings in his last two starts, said he has been impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bohanon) threw 107 pitches (tonight) and came out with hardly
a sweat,'' Hoffman said.
</P>
<P>
   OK, this was a Colorado lineup devoid of the slumping Dante
Bichette (.336 average despite a recent 0-or-9 skid), the gimpy
Larry Walker (NL-leading .357), and Rookie of the Year candidate
Todd Helton (.321, 89 RBI).
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon was tough on the kids. Rookies Angel Echevarria, Derrick
Gibson and Edgard Clemente were a combined 2 for 8 against him, but
All-Star third baseman Vinny Castilla (1 for 2, walk) didn't do
much and neither did second baseman Mike Lansing, who went 0 for 4
and struck out twice.
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon struck out a career-high 10, including six batters in a
row at one point, in his 79th major-league start. He also was
responsible for the Dodgers taking a 1-0 lead in the third. With
runners on first and third and no outs, Bohanon grounded to
Lansing. Even though the Rockies turned a double play, the ball was
hit deep enough on the infield to allow Adrian Beltre to score from
third.
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon (7-10) was also boosted by the maddening Dodgers'
defense, which booted the game away on Tuesday and came back with a
tour de force on Wednesday. The Rockies put the potential tying run
on first in the fifth, sixth and seventh, but each time, the
Dodgers turned a rally-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Mark Grudzielanek turned in the prettiest, diving to
his left on former Montreal teammate Lansing's sharp grounder and
flipping to Juan Castro at second to start the double play in the
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek also made a diving catch to his right to rob
Echevarria of a hit and double pinch-runner Curtis Goodwin off
first.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at some of those plays that were made,'' Hoffman
said, ``and it just shows how pitching and defense win games.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman said he didn't hesitate to use Shaw, even though Bohanon
was still going strong. Lansing represented the potential go-ahead
run with two outs but he grounded into a force play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff Shaw is a closer,'' Hoffman said. ``That's his job and
his role.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado starter Jamey Wright (10-12) wasn't so lucky. The
Dodgers took a 2-0 lead in the bottom of the seventh after Kurt
Abbott misplayed Roger Cedeno's single, allowing the speedy Cedeno
to advance to second with two outs. Castro singled to drive in
Cedeno. It was only the sixth hit Wright allowed.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers played without Bobby Bonilla, who was a late scratch
with a sore wrist. The Dodgers (78-75) are off today and start a
three-game series in San Francisco on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
