<HEADER>
A9770 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CUBS-PADRES-NYT &LR;      09-17 0386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-PADRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOSA REACHES NO. 63 WITH A GRAND SLAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ED GUZMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Chicago Cubs right fielder Sammy Sosa was relaxed
enough to hit his 63d home run on Wednesday night. It was simply a
matter of when.
</P>
<P>
   After singling and doubling in his first four at-bats on
Wednesday night, Sosa stood at the on-deck circle in the top of the
eighth inning holding his personalized black Louisville Slugger
bat. He made a sign of the cross, put his fingers to his lips and
then touched his bat.
</P>
<P>
   With that bit of divine help, Sosa came to the plate with the
bases loaded and two out. With the Qualcomm Stadium crowd of 49,891
on its feet, Sosa drove a 1-0 pitch from the San Diego right-hander
Brian Boehringer high and deep into the second deck in left field,
a 434-foot blast that tied Mark McGwire for most home runs in a
season and gave the Cubs a 6-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs went on to beat the Padres, 6-3, to remain a half-game
ahead of the New York Mets in the race for the National League
wild-card playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think 62, 63 are pretty good for me,'' Sosa said. ``Now I
want to take my team to the playoffs. Right now, I feel great.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa had tied McGwire at 62 on Sunday, when he connected twice
in a stunning performance at Wrigley Field. That gave him four
homers in three days.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire went back ahead with No. 63 when he pinch-hit for the
St. Louis Cardinals in the ninth inning of the first game of a
doubleheader Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's third career grand slam _ all this season _ was his 22nd
career homer against the Padres, the most against any opponent. He
was 1 for 9 with six strikeouts in the first two games of this
four-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa will have a chance to jump ahead of McGwire on Thursday,
when he faces the Padres rookie Stan Spencer. The Cardinals are off
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa and McGwire each have nine games left.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa was so loose before the game that after a horde from the
news media finished asking questions, he sheepishly said: ``Don't
leave. Does anyone have any more questions? I've got time for
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   A reporter then asked Sosa if he had any questions for the
members of the news media. After pausing for a minute, he said:
``What did Mark McGwire do today? Did he hit 64?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
