<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9792 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI &LR;      09-17 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL FOULS UP GIVING SOSA HIS DUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The post-election party for a local candidate was well
underway Tuesday night. But when you're branded a sports guy, the
sports questions never stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you think,'' the die-hard baseball fan asked me, ``that
the way baseball is underplaying Sammy Sosa is a little racist?''
</P>
<P>
   In a word, no.
</P>
<P>
   If the word in question is indeed racism.
</P>
<P>
   If the word is insensitive, then there's a point.
</P>
<P>
   For a month, the question has drifted around the periphery of
the home run chase. The suspicion is that because Mark McGwire is a
white guy, baseball and many of its fans hope he prevails over the
Latin guy with the accent.
</P>
<P>
   While no one should underestimate the rockhead portion of
American society, a hefty majority would seem to be preoccupied in
this matter by the thing that historically has been the
preoccupation of the culture _ who's first.
</P>
<P>
   As a society that endlessly quantifies, compares, lists and
ranks, we have an overwhelming desire to learn the identity of No.
1 and a near-total obliviousness about who is No. 2. Make all the
value judgments you want; it's a fact.
</P>
<P>
   As the first guy in 37 years to top Roger Maris in home runs,
McGwire's feat was accorded almost an instant national holiday. As
the second guy who passed Maris, Sosa has been hailed vigorously in
Chicago but in a more muted fashion elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The point hit home Sunday when Sosa's two home runs tied him
again with McGwire at 62, but baseball officials didn't have the
presence of moment to mark his baseballs for historic certitude, as
they did for McGwire, nor was there special acknowledgement of his
achievement within his industry.
</P>
<P>
   But Sosa broke no record. He bested Maris and Babe Ruth, but
neither holds the record.
</P>
<P>
   Without trying, Clinton-style, to split hairs, the fact remains
that while a record has been broken, a new record has not been set.
That can't happen until the season is over, or unless both players
go down with season-ending injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Until the record is set, the degree and ultimate moment of
Sosa's achievement is unknown. McGwire's achievement is more
clearly defined because he was the first to break sports' most
glamorous record. And we love our firsts.
</P>
<P>
   If the recent situation had been reversed, wherein Sosa had hit
four home runs in two days to put him at 59 while McGwire was at
56, I would be shocked to learn that this newspaper or any other
media outlet would have been any less aggressive in covering the
story of the record's imminent fall. Nor would baseball have been
less celebratory in its salute.
</P>
<P>
   To the degree that Sosa is less familiar to the sports audience
than McGwire, it is largely a factor of their baseball profiles.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, an All-Star once, had never hit more than 40 home runs
until this season. Ever since McGwire, a 10-time All-Star, hit 49
home runs in his rookie year of 1988, he has been the object of
annual speculation as to whether each year would be his year. After
hitting 58 in 1997, McGwire's middle name became ``on a pace for.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Sosa hit his astonishing 20 homers in June, he was not a
serious contender. Even afterward, it was expected by many that the
pressure that had consumed every previous pretender over 36 years
would consume him, as well as McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   But no. Both not only withstood the grind, they eventually
flourished. McGwire simply had the good fortune to run into the
Florida Marlins' Class AAA pitching staff on Sept. 1-2, when he hit
four home runs to break away.
</P>
<P>
   (A moment's digression: Anyone who thinks the feats of McGwire
and Sosa have healed baseball is apparently not a witness to the
defending champ Marlins, whose wreckage remains a more vivid
reminder of the state of baseball than any number of home runs).
</P>
<P>
   Having said all of the above, baseball again missed another
opportunity for goodwill by its inattention to Sosa's potential
achievement. As a sport with a dubious record in advancing the case
for minority athletes, coaches and executives, the last thing
baseball needs was even the appearance of insensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a stretch to imagine that Sosa Sunday and Monday could
have tied and surpassed McGwire. Nor is it difficult to imagine
that McGwire, already bothered by back spasms and a long injury
history, could have been stopped for the season at 62.
</P>
<P>
   Then what?
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, the indistinct resolution of one of baseball's
greatest individual competitions makes party planning difficult.
But it doesn't seem a lot to ask that commissioner Bud Selig spend
a few days with the Cubs or if business is so pressing (as if,
after six years without a commissioner, things couldn't wait),
designate a former Cubs great such as Ernie Banks or Billy Williams
as his representative.
</P>
<P>
   Since at this writing any of Sosa's home runs could tie or set a
splendid record, the baseballs should be marked and the game be
prepared to acknowledge in a brief ceremony the significance of his
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Would that be overdoing it? In a nation that features Las Vegas,
the Starr report, Pamela Anderson, Dennis Rodman and Humvees, the
act of overdoing is impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
