<HEADER>
A9793 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN     09-17 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' INFIELD AUDITIONS HAVE INTRIGUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Nine games remain for the Los Angeles Dodgers and
a bunch of guys who are uncertain about their futures are
auditioning for next season.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is the intrigue as thick as the middle infield. The
Dodgers have two established shortstops _ Mark Grudzielanek and
Jose Vizcaino _ and prospect Alex Cora might not benefit from
another year as a reserve, or worse, at Triple-A.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Young, who will be in the second year of a four-year, $18
million contract, is entrenched at second, but the competition to
be his backup might include Cora and Adam Riggs.
</P>
<P>
   So where does this leave Juan Castro?
</P>
<P>
   Castro, who took over for Young as the starter at second, saw
his average dip below .200 (.199) after he struck out in his first
two at-bats Wednesday night. There is no question about his
abilities defensively, although he says he feels more comfortable
at shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't thought about (next season),'' Castro said. ``What I
want is to play every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Castro committed a throwing error after replacing Young in
Tuesday night's 5-4 loss to the Rockies. But Dodgers manager Glenn
Hoffman said he feels comfortable with Castro at second. Cora can
also play second.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done well over there,'' he said. ``Juan's probably got
the most experience.''
</P>
<P>
   After going 0 for 3 on Tuesday, Castro had only eight extra-base
hits in 79 games.
</P>
<P>
   Hurting: Raul Mondesi, who has battled a sore back, was given
the night off by Hoffman, who said he wanted Mondesi fresh for the
weekend series in San Francisco.``(Mondesi)'s been dragging a
bit,'' Hoffman said.
</P>
<P>
   Left-handed reliever Mark Guthrie pitched in the bullpen without
pain Wednesday and will also be ready to pitch Friday, Hoffman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the day after he suffered a season-ending broken foot,
Young stayed home. Hoffman said Young, who played in only 117 games
this year, would rejoin the team when the Dodgers open their
season-ending homestand against San Diego next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ready for prime time: The Dodgers called up second baseman Mike
Metcalfe from Double-A San Antonio on Tuesday. At the time of the
call-up, Metcalfe was in Phoenix, preparing for the Arizona Fall
League season. He joined the Dodgers on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Metcalfe, a 25 year-old second baseman, finished the season with
San Antonio the first week of September. He wasn't expecting to
even be playing because he broke a bone in his lower back in April
and played in only about 60 games at Double-A.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pleasant surprise,'' Metcalfe said of his call-up.
``I was supposed to be out the whole year.''
</P>
<P>
   Season-ending injuries are nothing new to Metcalfe, the Dodgers'
third-round draft choice in 1994 out of the University of Miami. He
played in only two games in '96 before undergoing major surgery on
his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Future plans: The Dodgers released next season's schedule. They
open the 1999 season at home on Monday, April 5, against the
Arizona Diamondbacks, and the Angels and Rangers will play at
Dodger Stadium June 4-9.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket information: (323) 224-1448.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
