<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9802 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-GORDON-BOS     09-17 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-GORDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON'S SAVING GRACE A HEALTHY DOSE OF NERVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Here's the unvarnished truth from Red Sox closer Tom
Gordon, minutes after he broke Jeff Reardon's club record for saves
with No. 41 in Wednesday night's 4-3 win over the Baltimore
Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm nervous every day,'' he said. ``Every day. I think that
may be one reason I come to the park so early, to get past it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Boddicker once said to me, `When you're not nervous, it's
time to quit.' There's nothing wrong with being nervous. Just don't
be scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night Gordon admitted his nervous system was on
overload. He tried hard, he said, not to think about the record.
His teammates reminded him of it, he said. So did family and
friends. There were six messages awaiting him when he arrived at
the team's hotel here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only one guy here had 40 saves,'' Gordon said, referring to
Reardon, the bearded one who saved 40 games for the Sox in 1991.
``Now there are two, and only one guy today has 41.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's a blessing. Thank God for that.''
</P>
<P>
   After watching Gordon's dress rehearsal for the role last season
_ he had 11 saves in 13 chances after taking over for the traded
Heathcliff Slocumb _ pitching coach Joe Kerrigan expected big
things from him. He's the one who had sold manager Jimy Williams
and general manager Dan Duquette on the idea and convinced Gordon
it was the best move he could make for his career.
</P>
<P>
   But 41 saves and counting in his first full season on the job?
</P>
<P>
   ``We were sitting around the hotel bar one night this spring,''
Kerrigan said. ``And I don't remember who said it, maybe (Bob)
Schaefer or Sammy (Ellis), but somebody said, `You know, if the guy
gets the opportunity, he can save 40 games.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, when you win 90 games, somebody has a chance to save 40.
So no, it doesn't surprise me. Not the way his work ethic is. Total
concentration.''
</P>
<P>
   The burden of the moment, Gordon admitted, caused him to depart
from his usual approach. He fretted too much about throwing strikes
instead of just throwing his ``nastiest'' stuff.
</P>
<P>
   That changed after he gave up a double to Cal Ripken and singles
to B.J. Surhoff and Lenny Webster, which cut the Oriole deficit to
4-3 and put the tying and winning runs on base.
</P>
<P>
   ``He turned it up to 97 on Becker,'' Kerrigan said, referring to
one of the fastballs Gordon threw pinch hitter Rich Becker, who
struck out for the second out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon then retired Robbie Alomar on a liner to Damon Buford in
center to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad it's over,'' Gordon said. ``I really don't know what
to do. I've never been in this position. Do I buy myself a bottle
of Dom Perignon?''
</P>
<P>
   What he should do, Dennis Eckersley said, is savor the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had a difficult job, especially in Boston,'' Eckersley
said. ``That ballpark is not an easy place to close games out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we wouldn't be where we are without him. He's as
much our MVP as anybody. If he blows four or five games, we're
scuffling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
