<HEADLINE>
BYU, STAR RUNNER JENKINS FIND COMMON GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Ronney Jenkins is the best football player on the
Brigham Young football team coming to play Washington Saturday, and
he's not a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Unusual as that is at BYU, it isn't the most interesting thing
about the third-year sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   Rewind back to the 1995 season on an early November evening in
Oxnard, Calif., about 50 miles up the coast from Los Angeles. Jim
Lane, the athletic director at Hueneme High School, customarily
sought out the 5-foot-11, 170-pound Jenkins to shake the hand of
the star running back and wish him well.
</P>
<P>
   Lane couldn't immediately find him. Jenkins was down in the
opposite end zone, alone with his thoughts before the final game of
his high school career against Oxnard's Rio Mesa High.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you doing down here?'' Lane asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just thinking,'' Jenkins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not cooking up something special here?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to dedicate this game to my grandmother.''
</P>
<P>
   In his office today, Lane fumbles for the USA Today story, which
he has laminated and framed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Write these numbers down,'' Lane says. ``Here they are _ 93,
84, 26, 79, 43, 87, 15.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are the distances Jenkins covered for touchdowns the night
he set a national high school rushing record. He finished with 619
yards on 30 carries, which, if you're going to dedicate a game to
somebody, is a fairly emphatic tribute.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Cobbs, the grandmother, raised Jenkins in the absence of
any significant positive parental influence. She also had a say in
his decision to attend Brigham Young, and more important, in his
choice to stay there, something that will have a major impact on
Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins, an intuitive runner with breakaway speed, just sliced
up the Arizona State defense for 171 yards on 30 carries. He is
reputed to have run a 4.3-second 40 and a wind-aided 10.29 in the
100 meters, which is within hailing distance of Ja'Warren Hooker.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to size up Jenkins earlier this week, UW coach Jim
Lambright shot a bemused look at the reporter and said, ``He's a
pretty damn good running back.''
</P>
<P>
   LaVell Edwards, the longtime BYU coach, thinks so, too. At a
school so accustomed to throwing, he is delighted with a runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he stays healthy,'' Edwards said, ``I think he's going to
be as good as anyone around.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington had an interest in Jenkins three years ago, as did a
lot of schools when they got word of a 600-yard game. But he lacked
a qualifying test score, a fact that made the local paper.
</P>
<P>
   Then one day Lane got a call from a retired college professor
named Meredith Moyers. She had read of Jenkins' plight and said she
had had success in counseling such students. She was telling Lane
she could guarantee Jenkins would conquer his test with six weeks'
preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We corraled him every day for six weeks for an hour over lunch
break,'' Lane says. ``He got an 890 (needing only 700) on the
test.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, everybody but BYU, Arizona and Arizona State had
abandoned him. He picked BYU, brushing off the adjustment it would
require.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came on my trip, I felt comfortable, I guess,'' Jenkins
said this week. ``My grandmother wanted me to come here. I felt
good about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In one season, Jenkins set the Western Athletic Conference on
its ear. He rushed for 733 yards, scored 11 touchdowns and was the
WAC's freshman of the year. BYU had never seen anything like him.
</P>
<P>
   Then the tough times hit. In the spring of 1997, BYU found
Jenkins in violation of the school's honor code, bound to the
Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints. It is believed that he
had attended a function at which alcohol was served.
</P>
<P>
   Going to BYU had already proved tough for a black athlete from
Southern California. Now it would demand everything he had.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a little bitter about it,'' Lane says.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins says he had his bags packed. Schools would call Hueneme
inquiring about Jenkins and word would get back to him about what
was available.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were probably 50 colleges calling when they ran the
story that he was going to sit out,'' says the Hueneme coach, Larry
Miller. ``No question everybody and his brother wanted him. And you
know, he was talking to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins says he spoke to Arizona State, USC and Colorado, and
``I was going to talk to Washington but I didn't get a chance to.''
</P>
<P>
   His grandmother advised him to stay put.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel good about running away from what I had done,''
Jenkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins is proud of his resilience. Still, he doesn't minimize
the difficulty of a black at BYU.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just different,'' he said. ``Coming from another
environment, you have to just change. It's hard to grow up one way
all your life and change to a whole different lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for black athletes here. You get so much attention;
everybody knows who you are. You can't do things you normally would
do at home.''
</P>
<P>
   With Jenkins, BYU is a different team. The Cougars have run the
ball 93 times this year, passed it 51. They splashed him on the
cover of their media guide this year, suspension or not. And it
might be that Jenkins is headed for the same destination of his
favorite running back, a player an hour up the coast from Oxnard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people say I have a running style similar to him,''
Jenkins says, referring to ex-Husky Napoleon Kaufman, now with the
Oakland Raiders. ``I like him a lot. I talked to a him a couple of
times, when I was being recruited by Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   So there's this tip for Husky fans: If you see Jenkins off by
himself sometime in pregame warmups Saturday, be suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   IF, ANDS, MUTTS: UW linebacker Lester Towns had his foot stepped
on late in Wednesday's practice and Lambright said he would be
reevaluated Thursday. It appears that Towns will be OK. ...
Slotback Dane Looker stayed out of practice again with a thigh
bruise but Lambright said the junior transfer felt better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
