<HEADLINE>
RED SOX PUT CLAMPS ON ORIOLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ The ninth inning may have seemed like an eternity
and the eighth inning only a little shorter, but after two straight
wins, the Red Sox are making pages fly off the calendar again, with
October dead ahead.
</P>
<P>
   With cardiac units on alert from Block Island to Old Orchard
Beach, closer Tom Gordon gave up a ninth-inning run on three
straight hits and put the tying and winning runs on base with one
out but recovered for his club-record 41st save in the Red Sox' 4-3
win over the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   The win, Bret Saberhagen's 14th of the season, preserved the
Sox' four-game lead over the Toronto Blue Jays, 2-1 winners over
Detroit Wednesday night, in the American League wild-card race. It
also reduced to eight the Red Sox' magic number for a playoff berth
with a dozen games left.
</P>
<P>
   Any combination of Sox wins or Blue Jay losses totaling eight
and Boston will be in the playoffs for the first time since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But those pleasantries meant little in the ninth inning after
Cal Ripken doubled off the center-field fence, B.J. Surhoff singled
him home, and Lenny Webster followed with another base hit, all
with one out.
</P>
<P>
   Was Jimy Williams nervous?
</P>
<P>
   ``He should have been,'' said Gordon, who had entered in the
eighth and retired Rafael Palmeiro on one pitch after the one
batter Dennis Eckersley faced, Eric Davis, bounced into a double
play with runners on first and second and nobody out.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the most I've sweated in a long time,'' Gordon added.
``I mean, it was hot out there (95 degrees at game time), but it
wasn't that hot.''
</P>
<P>
   How hot was it? It was so hot, Eckersley was sweating, too, and
he was sitting in the air-conditioned visitors' clubhouse at Oriole
Park at Camden Yards, where a crowd of 42,676 was imploring its
team not to lose here for the first time this season against the
Sons of Jimy Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was not an easy win,'' said the Eck, who is now within
three of tying Hoyt Wilhelm for most career pitching appearances
(1,070). ``It was tough to watch that last inning. I'd rather be
doing it than watch it.''
</P>
<P>
   The doing was left to Gordon, after a visit from pitching coach
Joe Kerrigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I came in with a two-run lead, this was the
biggest game I've pitched in,'' said Gordon. ``I was so nervous. It
meant something to me. It meant something to my teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a chance to win two in a row, and I had a chance to
break a record.''
</P>
<P>
   Mission accomplished on both scores. Gordon struck out pinch
hitter Rich Becker _ with one fastball clocked at 97 miles an hour,
according to Kerrigan _ then induced Robbie Alomar to line out to
center. He thus broke Jeff Reardon's 7-year-old club mark and tied
Jose Mesa's 1995 major league record for consecutive saves in a
season with his 38th.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is awesome,'' said Eckersley, one of four relievers to
pitch in the eighth after Saberhagen allowed just two runs on six
hits, including Mike Bordick's 13th home run, and one walk in 6 2/3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking how if I had stayed in St. Louis, we would have
been playing the last month of the season with not much happening
(McGwire, si; playoffs, no). It would have been a drag. It would
have been hard to say goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this makes it exciting. Last winter, it was like, `I want
to play for Boston. I hope they have a good year.' Hey, just roll
'em.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight game, the Red Sox rolled out their bats,
too. They had 14 hits, their most in 22 games and the first time in
a dozen games they've reached double figures.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra had two doubles and a single and scored two
runs; Troy O'Leary had three singles, scored one run, and drove in
another; and rookie Trot Nixon, Williams's fourth leadoff hitter in
four nights, had two singles and scored a run.
</P>
<P>
   The game was close only because the Red Sox left the bases
loaded twice and stranded 11 runners in all. But they scored enough
for Saberhagen, who has won more games than in any season since
1994 and made more starts (29) than in any season in the last 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``To do the job well is a great feeling,'' said Saberhagen, who
received highlight-reel help from rookie second baseman Donnie
Sadler, who somehow speared Webster's bad-hop ground ball while
falling backward with two on and two out in the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time since I've pitched a meaningful game in
September. I did in 1995 with the Rockies, but my arm was already
blown out.''
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing wrong with his arm _ or his heart _ now.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see why he won all those awards early in his career,
can't you?'' Williams said. ``The way he competes?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a tribute to the man _ and I mean the man _ on that
mound.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
