<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERSTAD MIGHT LIMP BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Darin Erstad's strained left hamstring has
not yet healed, but it's improved to the point where he could be in
the lineup tonight against Texas, manager Terry Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad, who hurt the hamstring for the second time this season
on Sept. 2, pinch hit in the ninth inning Wednesday and struck out
on three pitches against Rangers closer John Wetteland.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy's not going to be 100 percent,'' Collins said. ``But
90 percent of Darin Erstad is still very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad, though, probably isn't even 90 percent. He says he still
can't run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can make the plays and do what it takes to do the job at
first base,'' Erstad said, ``but when it comes to going from second
to home or first to third, I can't. It's all about being able to
run. Stealing a base is something I'm not going to be able to do
the rest of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins told Erstad he doesn't want him to do too much too soon
because he might aggravate the injury and lose the rest of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that after this series we have 10 games left,
including six at home and three more against these guys (the
Rangers),'' Collins said. ``I told him, `I have to have you for
that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   After Erstad tests the hamstring in warmups this afternoon,
Collins will consult with trainers and Erstad before making a
decision. ``I think you can figure out what my input's going to
be,'' Erstad said. ``But I'm also not going to lie to him. I'm
going to tell him what I can do. I'm not going to hurt the team in
any way.''
</P>
<P>
   Newsprint fodder: The Dallas Morning News previewed the
Angels-Rangers series with a large headline proclaiming: ``Edge:
Rangers.''
</P>
<P>
   The story, which quoted anonymous scouts and a manager saying
the Rangers were the favorites, made its way into the Angels
clubhouse and was posted. A similar story, from USA Today, was also
clipped and posted.
</P>
<P>
   Many lines from both stories were highlighted, including one
that read: ``The Angels greet September like a turkey greets
November.'' A quote from a scout said closer Troy Percival has a
tendency to get ``goofy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know he's goofy,'' shortstop Gary DiSarcina said. ``Now
the whole world knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Angels said the stories didn't bother them _ ``I
don't care what they write,'' DiSarcina said _ but Collins, when
asked if the stories made the Angels angry, said, ``I hope it does.
You've got to play the game angry.''
</P>
<P>
   Intelligence reports: To prepare for this series, the Angels
sent four scouts _ typically they send one _ to follow the Rangers
on their last road trip to Tampa Bay and Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did an outstanding job,'' Collins said, ``but the games
are played by human beings. You've still got to play the game. We
know every way there is to get Juan Gonzalez out, but if you don't
get the ball where you're supposed to, he's going to hit a home
run.''
</P>
<P>
   Emergency help: With Charlie O'Brien breaking his right index
finger Tuesday night and being lost for the season, the Angels
today will activate catcher Ben Molina to serve as their third
catcher. Molina split time this season at Double-A Midland and
Triple-A Vancouver.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
