<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-SOSA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOSA SLAMS 63D 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Put Sammy Sosa back in the record book. The Catch-Up
Kid from Chicago has done it again.
</P>
<P>
   He waited until the eighth inning Wednesday night to wave his
magic wand at Qualcomm Stadium. But when he did, it resulted in his
63d home run of the season, tying Mark McGwire of the St. Louis
Cardinals for the major league lead _ and all-time season record.
Just as important to Sosa, it came with the bases loaded off
reliever Brian Boehringer to break a 2-2 tie and give the Cubs a
6-3 victory that enabled them to retain their half-game lead over
the Mets in the race for the National League wild-card playoff
berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think 62, 63 are pretty good for me,'' Sosa said. ``Now I
want to take my team to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I feel great. The game tonight was unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Even McGwire would have been proud of this wallop. Once it left
Sosa's bat, the only question was how far out it would go. It
landed an estimated 434 feet away in the second deck, only the 22d
ball to reach that area in stadium history. The San Diego crowd of
49,891 saluted Sosa with a standing ovation that lasted two
minutes. Even then, they weren't satisfied until he took a curtain
call.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa was on fire. The homer was his third hit of the night. He
singled in the second but was stranded. In the seventh, he broke a
scoreless tie with a double to left with the bases loaded, giving
Chicago a 2-0 lead. But it lasted only until the bottom of the
inning when Cubs lefthander Terry Mulholland gave up two runs.
</P>
<P>
   The home run was preceded by two hits and a walk. Tyler Houston
led off with a single. With one out, Red Sox short-timer Orlando
Merced singled to center. The Padres brought in lefthander Mark
Langston to replace Dan Miceli, and he walked Lance Johnson,
loading the bases. Boehringer replaced Langston, and Houston was
forced at the plate on a grounder to short for the second out. That
brought up Sosa, who crushed a 1-0 pitch and boosted his RBI total
to a major league-leading 154.
</P>
<P>
   The blast was the latest installment in Sosa's bid to rewrite
recent history. Only eight days before, he seemingly was consigned
to a supporting role behind McGwire, whose 62d homer Sept. 8 _ in
St. Louis against the Cubs _ eclipsed Roger Maris's 37-year-old
mark. As the first man to cross that threshold, McGwire won
nationwide adulation. Sosa, stuck on 58 home runs, appeared to be a
footnote.
</P>
<P>
   But along came the Milwaukee Brewers, a club against whom he'd
hit six home runs previously, and Sosa started firing back at
McGwire. He hit No. 59 last Friday, his 60th Saturday, and on
Sunday, he outdid himself.
</P>
<P>
   He hit No. 61 off Bronswell Patrick, and in the ninth inning, he
tagged righthander Eric Plunk for No. 62, tying McGwire and
renewing the battle royale the two have waged for months.
</P>
<P>
   Then he took his quest to San Diego. The first night was a
disaster. The Cubs lost, 4-3, and Sosa struck out a season-high
four times. On Tuesday in a 4-2 win, he went 1 for 4, a
seventh-inning single that launched the decisive rally. But in St.
Louis, McGwire struck for No. 63, inching back in front.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no denying Sosa Wednesday night. When he took the
field, he knew that McGwire had been shut out, going 0 for 3 with a
walk. And after warming up with a couple of hits, he staged the
grand finale.
</P>
<P>
   And away they go. Again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
