<HEADLINE>
GLOVER, HABIB BRING STABILITY TO SEAHAWKS' OFFENSIVE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ The question loomed before Warren Moon like a
pair of 315-pound defensive tackles: What is his biggest concern
entering Sunday's game against the Washington Redskins?
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two guys inside. They really can clog up the middle,''
the Seahawks quarterback said after practice Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the $57 million question. That's what the Redskins doled
out in free agency this offseason to sign those two defensive
tackles _ Dana Stubblefield, NFL defensive player of the year last
season while with the 49ers; and Dan Wilkinson, the first pick
overall in the 1994 draft by the Cincinnati Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks will match these two with their own free-agent
acquisitions _ center Kevin Glover, the NFC Pro Bowl starter the
past three seasons; and guard Brian Habib, a starter on the Denver
Broncos' Super Bowl team last season.
</P>
<P>
   Glover was signed away from the Detroit Lions in February after
Kevin Mawae jumped to the New York Jets. Habib was added two weeks
later to solidify a position where three different players started
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of made that line complete,'' Stubblefield said of
Glover and Habib stepping in between left tackle Walter Jones, left
guard Pete Kendall and right tackle Howard Ballard. ``If you look
at them on film and how well they play together, you think, `Well
these guys have been together for more than one, two, three
years.'''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, they've been together since April, when the Seahawks
held the first of their four minicamps. Then came a month of
training camp and five preseason games. It was extra time well
spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went out and found the best guys we could get,'' offensive
line coach Gregg Smith said. ``The thing about Kevin and Brian is
that they're smart, they understand things very well and they blend
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Experience helps. Glover is in his 13th NFL season, but when he
first joined the team after 12 years in Detroit he had Kendall to
help him with the line calls. Habib is in his 11th season and still
leans on Ballard when one of the five offenses he learned at
Minnesota and Denver collides with terminology in the Seahawks'
offense.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to know how well Glover and Habib are playing, ask
each about the other, not themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin is the consummate pro,'' said Habib, who downplays his
own contributions. ``He's stepped in here like he's known the
offense forever. He makes all the right calls, does all the right
techniques. It's just great to play next to him.''
</P>
<P>
   The first thing anyone notices about the 6-foot-2, 282-pound
Glover is how active he is. He might be 35, but Glover displays his
quickness on almost every play, and his speed has even his
teammates shaking their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``He runs around out there like a 20-year-old kid,'' Habib said.
``I can't keep up with him, and I'm three years younger than he
is.''
</P>
<P>
   As for being a leader, Glover was elected an offensive
co-captain along with Moon.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-7, 299-pound Habib made his first big impression in the
weight room. This spring, he lifted 325 pounds a team-high 19
times.
</P>
<P>
   Told that Habib was less than complementary when asked for a
self-assessment, Glover smiled and offered, ``Ask any lineman and
we feel that way. You're always searching for the perfect game.
Brian is doing real well.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ricky Watters was finding little room to run in the first
half of Sunday's game against the Arizona Cardinals, Glover and
Habib were there between series. They told Watters not to get down.
They explained what was happening, and what would happen if they
continued to pound away. Watters finished with 105 yards, with 63
coming in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like them because they talk to me a lot during the
game. So I know what they're doing up front as well as what I want
to do back there,'' Watters said. ``They are great players. Through
the league, they have tons of respect. And they're guys who are
obviously students of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Moon also has grown to appreciate the two newest additions to a
line that has been in constant change for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little surprised at how quickly they've come together,''
Moon said. ``The offensive line is a tough position to break into
and have that cohesiveness. So that's the thing that surprises me.
Not so much that they've picked up what we're doing, but how well
they're all playing together.''
</P>
<P>
   Moon last year, and now Glover, Habib and Watters. Addition by
addition.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Ricky back there and with Warren back there, who's really
handling things,'' Stubblefield said, ``I think they completed that
offense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
