<HEADLINE>
GALAXY BEATS CLASH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE _ The Los Angeles Galaxy has no idea who it will oppose
when Major League Soccer's playoffs kick off in a few weeks, but
the team learned Wednesday night who it won't be.
</P>
<P>
   With a gritty, 1-0 shootout victory over San Jose, the Galaxy
(23-7, 65 points) eliminated the Clash (11-19, 27) from postseason
consideration for the second successive year and trimmed its list
of possible playoff foes to three: Colorado, Dallas or Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't all the Galaxy gained from an otherwise meaningless
triumph before 15,893 at Spartan Stadium. With San Jose playing for
survival, the Galaxy found itself in an intensely tight battle that
will do more for its playoff preparations than any 5-0 rout could.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clash played us very tough,'' said Paul Caligiuri, one of
four Galaxy shooters to connect in the tiebreaker. ``It was a good
game to get that playoff mentality, that playoff atmosphere. They
were playing for everything, and although we didn't need a point,
didn't need a victory, it kept us honest and prepared us for the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the primary purpose of these final regular-season games,
and there was much for the Galaxy to be pleased with in that
regard.
</P>
<P>
   Goalkeeper Kevin Hartman turned in another superb performance,
notching his sixth shutout of the season. The defense, without
suspended captain Robin Fraser, allowed the Clash few decent
chances. And a vibrant midfield passing game enabled L.A. to
dictate terms much of the match, even if the strategy led to few
true scoring opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy managed just three shots on target, with only Danny
Pena's header off a 49th-minute Cobi Jones corner kick causing any
trouble. Wade Barrett cleared it off the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Jose came to play with everything they had, but we matched
their intensity ...,'' said L.A. coach Octavio Zambrano. ``Without
anything at stake, this team wouldn't lay down and take a loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the credit for that goes to Hartman, who made two diving
stops on Ronald Cerritos -- one with little more than a minute to
play -- and the crossbar, which got in the way of a John Doyle
header in the 77th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Neither team could find the net until the shootout, which L.A.
won, 4-3. Jones, Caligiuri, Welton and Mauricio Cienfuegos
connected for the Galaxy, but Hartman took the ball off Victor
Mella's feet on San Jose's first attempt, and Cerritos fired wide
on the decisive kick.
</P>
<P>
   GALAXY NOTES: L.A. called up midfielder Eric Chaisongkram from
the A League's San Diego Flash late Tuesday to bolster a roster
missing five players from suspension (Robin Fraser, Clint Mathis),
injury (Ezra Hendrickson, Wellington Sanchez) and international
duty (Martin Machon). Chaisongkram, a former UCLA standout, started
19 of 28 games for the Flash. ... Carlos Hermosillo served as
Galaxy captain in Robin Fraser's absence. ... Lawrence Lozzano made
his Galaxy debut at right back and saw 75 minutes of action. ...
The Clash were without striker Eric Wynalda (strained right calf).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
