<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASSERO SHARP IN MARINER WIN; GRIFFEY JOINS 50/20 CLUB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ The American League West is the only four-team
division in baseball, and the best thing about that might be on
display now. Only AL West teams get to play exclusively within
their division the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim Angels and Texas Rangers are doing battle in
Arlington, tied in pursuit of a playoff spot. The Mariners and
Oakland Athletics? They got together before 12,371 at the Oakland
Coliseum Wednesday night, with the keys to the basement the booby
prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to finish in the cellar,'' said left-hander
Jeff Fassero, who pitched the M's to a 4-1 win that kept them out
of last place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think these games are important, especially against
Anaheim and Texas. We could decide one of two (contenders') fates.
It's going to be a big last 10-11 games for us.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's true for the Mariners as a team, it's also true for
Fassero personally. Fassero lost seven straight decisions before
beating the Royals with eight strong innings last Friday. He hasn't
had a losing record since his rookie season of 1991, and he evened
his mark at 12-12 Thursday by working 72/3 innings, allowing one
run on four hits and no walks.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero said he had all three of his pitches working, and made
hitters hit his pitches by staying ahead in the count. At one point
Thursday, he retired 22 of 23 A's.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always want to be above .500 and somewhere around 15
wins,'' Fassero said. ``I have two starts left so obviously I can
only get to 14, but if I pitch like I did tonight, maybe I can get
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero's thinking 14, Alex Rodriguez is thinking 40/40 and Ken
Griffey, Jr., is done thinking 50/20.
</P>
<P>
   While Rodriguez went hitless in four at-bats and still is one
homer from joining the 40 homer/40 stolen base club, Griffey stole
his 20th base to become the third player in history with 50 homers
and 20 steals.
</P>
<P>
   The M's center fielder stole second in the eighth _ putting
himself in position to score the Mariners' final run _ and joined
Willie Mays (1955) and Brady Anderson (1996) as the only players to
go 50/20.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to make a big deal, because I enjoy playing
baseball,'' said Griffey, who has 52 homers. ``If you stay healthy
and be consistent, things happen. You have to be consistent and
take what they give you.''
</P>
<P>
   For Griffey, it was the second milestone in as many days.
Tuesday in Minnesota, he became the fourth youngest player to drive
in 1,000 runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you take for granted the things he does,'' manager
Lou Piniella said. ``But I played, so I know how hard it is to do
the things he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakland right-hander Gil Heredia made things hard on everyone
for awhile yesterday, retiring the first 12 Mariners in order. But
Edgar Martinez greeted him in the fourth by ripping a homer off the
facing of the second deck. It was Martinez's 28th homer _ one off
his 1995 career high _ and gave the Mariners a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez would add two more hits and another RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Martinez has a future with the Mariners, Piniella said
yesterday, but it probably will be in a slightly different role.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have until Nov. 1 to pick up their $3.5 million
option on the 35-year-old designated hitter, and Piniella said
Martinez would be back next year. He'll need to play some first
base, however, which would free up the DH spot to give other
players days off now and then.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm open to that,'' said Martinez, who has played their
briefly this year. ``It's for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   What Martinez doesn't know is if he'll need surgery on his left
knee, which has some cartilage damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to think about surgery sometime soon, so I can get
ready for spring training,'' Martinez said. ``But we haven't
decided if it's going to be surgery or not. We're still talking
about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
