<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-CONFUSION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEX SCANDAL CREATES CAPITAL CONFUSION 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The world of Washington _ where life is scripted
and orchestrated like a Broadway play _ has become suddenly,
unpleasantly confused. No one in the cast seems to know his lines,
and the directors haven't a clue how the story might end.
</P>
<P>
   Following independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report, routine
legislative work continues, with its scuffles over spending bills
and its debates over tax cuts and health care. But everything now
occurs under a surreal cloud that is part fear, part opportunism,
part distaste and part disillusionment, all mixed up in a vapor of
genuine bafflement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here 17 years, and I've never seen anything remotely
like this,'' said a GOP House committee aide. ``No one has any idea
what's going to happen now. No one has been in this situation
before. It's unsettled and fluid, and no one can really know what
effect this is going to have on normal business around here, except
that it's going to be large.''
</P>
<P>
   Said an environmental lobbyist and former Democratic House aide:
``It's like finding a big pile of dog doo-doo in your yard and you
step in it and you've got this mess to deal with. Where the analogy
falls apart is that you just don't know what to do next.''
</P>
<P>
   Most members of Congress seem determined to go on with business,
partly because they must but also because committee rooms and floor
debates provide a haven from a political theater where neither
polls nor principles provide obvious guidance.
</P>
<P>
   The Starr report's lurid if not pornographic accusations against
President Clinton _ and low hanky-panky is not unknown in Congress'
own hallowed halls _ revolve primarily around Clinton's grand jury
testimony in a case involving not the affairs of state, but an
affair.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations hover in a bizarre netherworld, between the
Constitution's ``high crimes and misdemeanors'' that would provide
grounds for impeachment of a president and lies about an illicit
affair that by itself had little to do with the public's business.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, many House members find nothing murky about perjury.
Maverick Ohio Democrat James Traficant declared on the House floor
Tuesday: ``If Joe Q. Citizen lied to a grand jury, he'd go to jail.
Lying is perjury, perjury is a crime . . . Does America now have
two legal standards, one for you, one for me? One for he, one for
she? . . . One for presidents, one for residents? . . . An America
with two legal standards is an America with no legal standards.''
</P>
<P>
   But even some Republicans hesitate to compare Clinton's alleged
lies with former President Richard Nixon's, who resigned before an
almost certain impeachment. ``I don't think he's crossed the line
that Nixon had crossed yet, but he's getting very close,'' said
Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Most Democrats crave a quick end to the scandal, possibly
through a vote to censure Clinton. Most Republicans simply say they
will follow the ``process'' _ Washington's code word for the
seldom-tested path toward possible impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   But that process is hardly clear. There is no specific
definition of high crimes and misdemeanors, and impeachment, most
agree, is ultimately a political act.
</P>
<P>
   With congressional elections a month and a half away, and
Clinton's troubles dominating political discourse, escape is
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are trying to grapple with finding a solution when
there does not seem to be a ready solution,'' said a Senate
Democratic aide. ``It's very tough. A lot of people are very
disillusioned. There is important legislative agenda still to be
accomplished, and it's tough to figure out a way to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Hellman, lead House lobbyist for the National Federation
of Independent Business, said, ``Every time I see a member, they
want to talk about tax cuts and spending bills, not the Monica
stuff. They talk about it because other people want to talk about
it, but the rank and file and the leadership don't really want to
talk about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Moderate Democrats, who are most closely allied with Clinton,
are deeply frustrated. ``At what point is this essentially allowed
to obliterate any kind of policy discussions in the country for the
foreseeable future?'' asked Ed Kilore, political director for the
centrist Democratic Leadership Council, a group Clinton helped
form. ``At what point do we go from what some are calling a
constitutional crisis, to a real political crisis? The public would
sort of like their elected representatives to govern.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservative activist Grover Norquist, president of Americans
for Tax Reform, is gleefully sounding the death knell for new
Democrats _ who include such moderates as Ellen Tauscher of Walnut
Creek, Calif. _ now that their leader is crippled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 10 to 20 Democrats in the House and the three to five in
the Senate who are going to lose in November are the people who ran
in rural, suburban, Southern and Western districts who can no
longer survive as those districts move Republican and their party
is seen as hewing left,'' Norquist said.
</P>
<P>
   Norquist, who has close ties with GOP House leaders, also
predicts a more aggressive Republican agenda on the Hill. ``Nobody
is afraid that Bill Clinton will get up and give five speeches and
change the topic of debate,'' Norquist said. ``Before, a few
Clinton speeches could move voters. And for Republicans to get
through the Clinton message cost millions of dollars in
advertising. This time around, that just isn't an option.''
</P>
<P>
   Liberal Democrats are simply furious. Clinton's problems may
well torpedo their chances to take back the House and restore their
powerful committee chairs that help set national policy on
everything from airline regulation to the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats are angry, and they're going to wonder just how much
they want to come to bat for the president,'' said an aide to a
high-ranking House Democrat. ``They have to decide what's in
Congress' best interest and what's in the president's best
interest, and it's not necessarily the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate end of the Clinton drama, whether bodice-ripper
comedy or constitutional tragedy, will not be known for some time.
``Nature abhors a vacuum, but politics doesn't,'' said John Pitney,
a political scientist at Claremont-McKenna College in Los Angeles
County. ``We may be looking ahead to two years of nothingness.
These are strange days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
