<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-MEDIA18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Techmedia
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In print
</P>
<P>
   The number of cool gadgets for home businesses is growing. The
September issue of Small Business Computing takes a quick look at
some of the interesting ones recently released. Among them is the
Novatel Minstrel, an 8-ounce modem for the PalmPilot. The Minstrel
slips around the PalmPilot to create a new device no bigger than a
cellular phone. It enables the PalmPilot to receive e-mail and surf
the Web. A big difference between the Minstrel and a cellular phone
is the price. The Minstrel costs $400. Another product discussed is
a slender little black box called Symphony. It enables users to
wirelessly share files, printers and faxes, as well as connect to
the Internet. Made by Proxim, it retails for $299.
</P>
<P>
   No longer are affluent white males the typical Net users. Users
now are as varied as the country's population. At least that's the
conclusion of a special report in the September issue of Yahoo!
Internet Life. The magazine found that nearly 52 million people are
online. The article features interviews with a varied group of
surfers including students, comedians, park rangers and truck
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   War game simulations are becoming increasingly realistic. A new
example is ``Spearhead,'' a desert tank game just released by
Interactive Magic. You play a platoon leader in the 3rd Armored
Division. Your platoon is part of Operation Removal, a U.S.
campaign to repel Libyan invaders from Tunisia in North Africa. The
game includes 20 single-player missions and one big campaign. The
tanks and other armored vehicles look like their counterparts in
real life. You can also play the game over the Internet or a
network. The game is available only for PCs with Windows 95 or
higher operating systems and retails for $39.95.
</P>
<P>
   Broderbund Software is releasing a trio of new learning games
using Dr. Seuss characters. Designed for young children, the games
are ``Dr. Seuss Preschool,'' ``Dr. Seuss Kindergarten'' and ``Dr.
Seuss Kindergarten Deluxe.'' Each title includes 250 lessons in
math and reading. The lessons are taught through more than 50 Seuss
characters, who sing original songs and act in the various
activities and games. The first two games retail for $19.99, while
the deluxe game is $29.99.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   Now you can read Consumer Reports' exhaustive reviews online.
The venerable product rating organization has put most of its
research on the Web. Full access costs $3 a month, but there's
plenty to read for free. You can find Consumer Reports at
http://www.consumerreports.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
