A0056 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-REPORT18-COX     09-17 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-REPORT18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smaller packages pack more PC power
 &HT;    By John Ghirardini
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thin is in these days, and computer manufacturers looking to
fatten their wallets haven't let that fact go unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   IBM and Toshiba have unveiled new desktop machines, aimed at the
high-end consumer and the mid-range commercial markets, that look
almost anorexic when compared with the squat computer cases and
bulky monitors that weigh down many work spaces.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers who must have the fastest and latest, IBM has
topped its Aptiva line with the SE7, which features a 450 MHz Intel
Pentium II MMX chip, 128 megabytes of RAM expandable to 384 megs, a
16.8 gigabyte hard drive, a DVD-ROM drive, a 56K modem and a pair
of Infinity speakers.
</P>
<P>
   To save space, IBM offers a 15-inch flat-panel LCD monitor that
offers the viewable area of a 17-inch standard monitor. The SE7 is
available with either a 17- or 19-inch standard CRT, but the basic
configuration has a purposeful, futuristic look about it that
technophiles will find hard to resist.
</P>
<P>
   Retail price is $2,399 without monitor; the choice of monitor
will raise the price to around $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   For commercial users, there's the new Toshiba Equium 100, which
has a 300 MHz Pentium II chip, 64 megabytes of RAM, a 4 gigabyte
hard drive, a CD-ROM drive and a built-in networking capability.
The entire setup takes up less desk space than a single standard
17-inch monitor, Toshiba says.
</P>
<P>
   Crowning it all is a 15-inch digital LCD monitor with integrated
speakers, a built-in microphone and built-in jacks for headphones
and mike input and output.
</P>
<P>
   The screen can swivel to a 90-degree vertical or horizontal
viewing angle, allowing large documents or spreadsheets to be seen
in either portrait or landscape mode.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for the Equium 100 begin at $2,999.
</P>
<P>
   Go forth and utilize
</P>
<P>
   The popular AltaVista search site on the Internet is trying to
make it easier to find information.
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista Discovery, a free utility program, is now available
for downloading at http://altavista.digital.com. The program lets
users search in both local and public domains without changing
applications _ including the Internet, e-mail and more than 100
document and file types that may be lurking on the computer's hard
drive.
</P>
<P>
   The utility will highlight key words, summarize page content,
find similar pages, identify Web sites referring to a particular
page, offer a list of other sites with relevant information and
show a complete listing of all pages from the same site as the page
being viewed.
</P>
<P>
   Installing the program produces a customizable toolbar that
attaches itself to the browser, giving access to AltaVista Search
from anywhere on the Net. Users then can switch to look at e-mail
or documents on the hard drive that contain the same selected
search string.
</P>
<P>
   The software requires Windows 95, 98 or NT, 16 megabytes of RAM,
24 megs of disk space and Netscape Navigator 3.0 or later or
Microsoft Internet Explorer 3.0 or later.
</P>
<P>
   One-on-one instruction
</P>
<P>
   Kids 3 to 7 can combine learning and fun with a new product from
Microsoft, ``My Personal Tutor: Preschool-First Grade'' for Windows
95.
</P>
<P>
   The software features a new Tutor Assist learning technology,
which according to Microsoft recognizes when a child needs help
with a concept, then offers a multimedia tutorial to help the child
understand.
</P>
<P>
   The software comes in a suite of four CD-ROMs, all featuring
Professor P.T. Presto, who guides children through tutorials with
music, animation and humor. The CDs contain hundreds of songs,
games, activities and characters designed to foster confidence,
curiosity, exploration and learning, Microsoft says.
</P>
<P>
   The four titles are:
</P>
<P>
   ``Preschool Workshop'' (ages 3-5), in which kids learn shapes,
colors, counting and other skills while helping friendly jungle
animals build toys;
</P>
<P>
   ``Alphabet Playhouse'' (ages 3-5), which highlights letter
recognition, uppercase and lowercase letters and pre-reading skills
with Rosy Raccoon;
</P>
<P>
   ``Reader Railway'' (ages 4-6), which focuses on vocabulary and
reading comprehension during a trip to the circus with Rosy
Raccoon's cousin Rusty; and
</P>
<P>
   ``Mathopolis'' (ages 5-7), in which kids hone their thinking and
problem-solving while developing addition and subtraction skills in
five fast-paced games.
</P>
<P>
   The software will be available in late September for a retail
price of $55. A free trial version has been available since Sept.
10 at http://www.microsoft.com/kids/.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
