<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Improved Find feature important part of OS 8.5
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Apple Computer plans to release its next update to the Mac
operating system in less than a month, and it looks like a keeper.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed OS 8.5, this upgrade not only speeds up basic performance
but adds several important features. Those include a greatly
enhanced Find feature and the ability to customize the look of the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of this OS upgrade is lots of new code written
specifically for the PowerPC chip that runs all new Macs. That code
enables Power Macs to run an average of 30 percent faster. Actions
that will run faster include copying files, searching and emptying
the trash can.
</P>
<P>
   The downside is you can't use this upgrade if your computer is
not a Power Mac. That includes such models as the SE, Centris, LC,
IIsi and Classic.
</P>
<P>
   In OS 8.5, Apple Computer has totally rewritten its Find
feature. It will now be able to search for content within files.
And what's found will be sorted by relevance, with the closest
match listed first.
</P>
<P>
   The new Find feature will also let you search the Internet
without a browser. Of course, you'll still need a modem and an
Internet provider to access the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Another great new feature is the ability of the OS now to check
and repair itself. It won't catch and fix every problem but is
designed to identify the most common ones. This feature used to be
a separate program called Disk First Aid. Now it has been built
into the OS.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the changes in OS 8.5 are cosmetic tweaks that make the
Mac more fun and easier to use. For example, Apple Computer will
now allow you to customize the look of your screen. You can choose
among themes that change the look of scroll bars, arrows and title
boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Apple Computer will supply two new theme looks, called Hi-Tech
and Gizmo, with the OS 8.5.
</P>
<P>
   Another small but helpful change will be the ability for a
floating window that lets you switch applications with a click of
the mouse. This feature, offered for years by shareware, now will
become part of the OS.
</P>
<P>
   These are just a few of the many changes coming in OS 8.5. No
price has yet been released for this upgrade, expected to be
released Oct. 9.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, check out Mac Web sites such as MacNN. It
features a special page devoted to OS 8.5, called Allegro. You'll
find the site at http://www.macnn.com/reality/allegro.shtml
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
