<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Goodbye to campaign funding reform
 &HT;    (Eds: Tom Teepen will be on vacation the week of Sept. 21. His
column will resume the week of Sept. 28 with a column moving that
day.)
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   While we all vicariously joined the president of the United
States as he contemplated Monica flashing her thong undies and in
general were puzzling out who had done what and with which and to
whom, there was a murder in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans finally did in campaign-funding
reform. They used the noisy release of the Starr report to cover
the crime.
</P>
<P>
   The next presidential and congressional election cycle will
differ from the last only in further excesses of the de facto
extortion and bribery that political fund-raising has become.
</P>
<P>
   Already in this election go-round, Republican committees have
raked in $193 million in regulated money, Democrats $108 million.
That's an increase of 19 percent for the GOP, 30 percent for
Democrats over the last similar period. ``Soft money'' _ boodle
from corporations, unions and the super-rich that the parties use
to get around limits on candidate fund-raising _ has gone up 70
percent for Democrats, to $53 million _ and up 250 percent for
Republicans, to $71.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   When the House slalomed last month through the last of the
sundry barriers Speaker Newt Gingrich had thrown up against reform
and voted 252 to 179 to ban the soft-money dodge, reformers felt a
surge of hope that an earlier Senate roadblock could be revisited
and crashed.
</P>
<P>
   But the brief numerical bipartisanship of the House vote only
masked the enduring partisan split. Many Republicans wanted a
reform vote on their records this November and could cast one in
confidence that Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott would do what he
had said all along he would do _ quash any reform that came over
from the House.
</P>
<P>
   Only six Republicans joined their co-sponsor colleague, John
McCain of Arizona, to override the Lott-created filibuster. With 45
Democrats, that left the good guys eight votes short of the 60
needed. R.I.P.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two years, Republicans in both the House and
Senate have staged hearings to torture Democrats over their at best
compromising, at times illegal fund-raising hustles in the last
election.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats had it coming, but absent any reformist
follow-through, the hearings stand as little better than political
show trials. Indeed, making matters worse, Republicans used the
hearings to learn how to catch up with and surpass Democrats in
soft-money excesses. GOP leaders are now, in effect, threatening
corporations with legislative reprisal if they give to Democrats as
well as Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Expect some Republican movement on this issue next year, but
probably only toward refining its previous, failed attempts to
legislatively close off traditional Democratic funding sources
under the color of ``reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls for Public Campaign in eight core-sample states
found that majorities in each believe the current campaign funding
system is flawed and should be changed. But until those majorities
shake off their fatalism, we have an electorate, sluggish to the
point of being inanimate, that is willing to let its democracy be
subcontracted out to special-interest vendors.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
