<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-GARRETT18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Garrett can be Cowboys' hero
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Four years after leading the Dallas Cowboys to
one of their most memorable victories in team history, backup
quarterback Jason Garrett has been asked to be a leading man again.
</P>
<P>
   But when Garrett takes the snap in the nationally televised game
against the New York Giants, he will not be alone. His teammates
and coaches vow they will not let the 32-year-old Ivy Leaguer
shoulder all the responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only human that I'll want to do a little extra,'' running
back Emmitt Smith said after practice at Valley Ranch. ``I'm a
human being, and I think everyone on this team wants to do a little
extra in order for us to win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Garrett has been known for his patience during his career with
the Cowboys. Always behind Troy Aikman on the depth chart. Usually
No. 3 behind players such as Wade Wilson and Rodney Peete.
</P>
<P>
   This week, however, Garrett is the headliner. This week he has
been asked to relive an exciting Thankgiving Day game in 1994, an
improbable 42-31 victory over the Green Bay Packers. With Aikman
and Peete nursing injuries, Garrtt threw for 311 yards and two
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   That was the last time the Princeton graduate made a significant
impact for the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``That game was a long time ago, and I've certainly turned the
page on that,'' Garrett said. ``But it certainly was a great day
for me and something I'll remember the rest of my life. It'll
certainly help Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   This will be the first game in a monthlong journey for Garrett,
who has replaced Aikman as the starter. Aikman has a broken left
collarbone, an injury that will keep him inactive for at least four
games, and Garrett's first game is against one of the most imposing
defenses in football.
</P>
<P>
   Through two games, the defending NFC East-champion Giants have
an NFL-best 13 sacks.
</P>
<P>
   Any bets the Giants will add a blitz or two to their defensive
scheme, now that a relative newcomer has taken Aikman's slot?
</P>
<P>
   ``You know they're going to bring the house,'' Dallas guard Nate
Newton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the Giants can possibly do any more on defense
than they've already shown,'' Cowboys Coach Chan Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey may be new in town, but he is familiar with Garrett's
1994 heroics against the Packers. He watched that Thanksgiving Day
shootout on TV, saying that game is one reason he decided to make
Garrett the No. 2 quarterback this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I remember about that game is that he took his team to
victory,'' Gailey said. ``You can say what you want about
quarterbacks, but that's the bottom line. Did you take your team to
victory?''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said the Cowboys have not simplified the offense to ease
Garrett's role. He doesn't have Aikman's arm strength, but Garrett
knows the playbook as well as anyone on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett's promotion begs the question: Who plays if Garrett goes
down? For the record, newcomer Mike Quinn, who threw two passes for
the Pittsburgh Steelers last year, will get his first taste in a
Cowboys uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said Quinn, who has taken only a handful of snaps, will
have to learn the offense ``by osmosis.''
</P>
<P>
   After Quinn, the job would go to someone already on the roster.
Tight end Eric Bjornson played quarterback at the University of
Washington and has been designated the No. 3 quarterback this week.
Running back Sherman Williams and cornerback Deion Sanders were
given a look Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have almost zero chance of getting in, but if I do, I'll try
to get out of there alive,'' Bjornson said.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest part of Wednesday's practice was warming up,
Bjornson said: ``I had to ice my arm down after four throws.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders took a few snaps after practice, and said he's willing
to try playing quarterback. When asked if he has ever thrown a pass
in the NFL, he recalled that he threw an option pass to Andre Rison
while with the Atlanta Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   It was incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy ran a bad route,'' Sanders insisted. NOTES: Defensive
linemen Leon Lett and Chad Hennings (sprained left knees) missed
practice Wednesday and are questionable for Monday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
