<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-MARINO18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A buddy system in name only
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ Jimmy Johnson and Dan Marino aren't buddies, and
don't need to be.
</P>
<P>
   Their coach-quarterback relationship, as important as it is to
the Dolphins' success, doesn't require friendship.
</P>
<P>
   It just has to be professional enough to allow them to work
together.
</P>
<P>
   Two games into the third season of the process, they're still
smoothing out the kinks.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty is in the adjustment of one man to the other.
Johnson is, by title, the boss. He's the head coach. Marino is, by
reputation, the icon. He's the superstar.
</P>
<P>
   Both have been supremely successful _ Johnson with two Super
Bowl titles during his tenure with the Dallas Cowboys; Marino with
passing statistics unparalleled in the history of professional
football.
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies the potential for conflict, or, at least,
agitation. Johnson feels he tried too long to compromise his own
preference for standard offensive game plan (run the ball) in order
to accomodate Marino's special talents. Now, it's Marino who feels
compromised even though he's doing his best to accomodate Johnson's
desires.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, in the wake of Miami's victory Sunday against Buffalo,
seemed to snipe at Marino by saying throws were made too often to a
covered receiver rather than an open one.
</P>
<P>
   The simplistic translation of Johnson's statement is that Marino
locks too quickly onto wide receiver O.J. McDuffie, with whom he
has worked the longest and feels most comfortable and confident.
And, in fact, Marino did aim 11 of his 26 passses vs. the Bills at
McDuffie.
</P>
<P>
   But examination of both games played by the Dolphins this season
reveals that McDuffie has been a target only 15 times on 50 passes
by Marino, and 30 percent is hardly a gluttonous slice of the
receivers' pie for someone considered a team's most reliable
catcher.
</P>
<P>
   McDuffie's his guy. So what?
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, both of Marino's touchdown passes have been caught
by wide receivers not named McDuffie _ Oronde Gadsden and Lamar
Thomas. Overall, he has thrown 27 times to wide receivers (15
connections), 12 times to tight ends (seven) and 11 times to
running backs (five).
</P>
<P>
   That seems a reasonable distribution.
</P>
<P>
   The fact of the matter is that Marino is still learning a new
system and how to implement it. And that may be slowing him down
just a tick, which, in the helter-skelter world of an NFL
quarterback dropping back to pass, is forever.
</P>
<P>
   So, maybe he's rushing.
</P>
<P>
   McDuffie, though, is astounded at any criticism of Marino.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous,'' McDuffie said. ``He's doing everything
asked of him, he's not bitching, and we're 2-0.''
</P>
<P>
   McDuffie did say defensive reads Marino made effortlessly in the
old system are, for now, necessarily more mechanical.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a `feel' thing, and that takes time,'' McDuffie said,
``but Danny's going to be Danny.''
</P>
<P>
   Danny being Danny has amounted to Miami being Miami for a very
long time. And even though Johnson has pulled the plug on that
strategy, he recognizes the value someone he says ``could very well
be the best quarterback ever.''
</P>
<P>
   And the 36-year-old Marino, in his 16th season, appreciates the
fact that his career could be extended if only because he ``won't
take as many hits'' if he's throwing fewer passes.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a buddy system.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't have to be, as long as they're able to smooth out
the other kinks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
