<HEADER>
A0123 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-VOLUNTEERS-MARTIN     09-17 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VOLUNTEERS-MARTIN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's Tee's time to shine as Vol's QB
 &HT;    By Craig Dolch
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early Saturday evening, Tee Martin will take a short walk to
Neyland Stadium. It will be an emotional time for Martin, who will
make his first home start as Tennessee's starting quarterback
against the hated Florida Gators.
</P>
<P>
   Then Martin will glance up at the street sign that reads: Peyton
Pass.
</P>
<P>
   That's the worst part about following a legend _ the legend
seems to follow you around.
</P>
<P>
   Martin knew it wouldn't be easy replacing Peyton Manning,
perhaps the most popular player to wear a Tennessee uniform. But
before the new guy can make a name for himself, does he really have
to walk down a street named for his predecessor?
</P>
<P>
   ``It only energizes me more and motivates me that much more when
people constantly throw Peyton in my face,'' Martin said. ``But
there's no way I can outshine him, nor do I want to. It's not a
popularity contest, because I would never win that.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin can win games, however. Two weeks ago the junior from
Mobile, Ala., drove the Vols 72 yards in the final seconds to set
up the winning field goal in a 34-33 victory over Syracuse. That
win became more impressive last week when Syracuse went on the road
and humbled reigning national co-champion Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stepped out of Peyton's shadow,'' receiver Peerless Price
said after the Syracuse game. ``Don't think that hasn't been
burning down inside of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, 20, wasn't fabulous in his first start, completing just
9-of-26 passes for 143 yards and two touchdowns. But he gave the
Vols a dimension they haven't had since Heath Shuler, running eight
times for 81 yards and a score. Martin's running ability is the
reason Tennessee coach Philip Fulmer allowed his new quarterback to
get hit during spring practice.
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer said Martin is taking the right approach to following
Manning, who set SEC career records for passing yards (11,201),
completions (863) and completion percentage (62.5) while ranking
second to Florida's Danny Wuerffel in touchdowns (89).
</P>
<P>
   ``Tee is a very level-headed man who knows he'll never put up
numbers like Peyton Manning did,'' Fulmer said. ``All he wants to
do is help this team win.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin knows he can accomplish something Manning never did: beat
Florida. The Gators have defeated the Vols five years in a row,
with Manning the starter in the last three meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say much about why we haven't beat Florida, but I know
we've lost those games because of turnovers and mistakes,'' Martin
said. ``We can't let that happen again this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin played sparingly his first two years at Tennessee,
completing 8-of-16 passes for 87 yards with one touchdown and one
interception. His most extensive playing time came when he led the
Vols to a touchdown in the final seconds of last year's 42-17 loss
to Nebraska in the Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The touchdown was meaningless to most, but not to Martin. The
80-yard scoring drive _ during which Martin completed 4-of-4 for 53
yards _ and subsequent two-point conversion triggered a change of
leadership at Tennessee. That became clear when his teammates
hugged him after the drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like they were accepting me as their starter,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the sixth-ranked Vols, however, won't accept another
home loss to the second-ranked Gators. Being placed in such a
pressure-packed situation might seem too much for Martin, but not
after what he's been through in his life.
</P>
<P>
   Martin grew up in a tough neighborhood in Mobile, where gangs
and drugs were constant sights. He says since he's enrolled at
Tennessee, he's lost 12 family members or friends to violent
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even cry anymore,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin said his background has helped him on the field and
in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I think about the pressures that come with getting
to the top,'' he said. ``I came from nothing and made it out. I
feel like there's nothing that can rattle me.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even walking down Peyton Pass as he prepares to try to pass
the biggest test of his college career.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will give me motivation, knowing how much he accomplished
to have a street named after him,'' Martin said. ``I'm going to
walk down that street with pride.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
