r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-PANTHERS-DVORAK18     09-17 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PANTHERS-DVORAK18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Panthers still waiting for Dvorak to blossom
 &HT;    By Brian Biggaine
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNRISE, Fla. _ The Florida Panthers' coaches and scouts didn't
know what to make of Radek Dvorak at his first training camp in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers' first-round pick (and 10th overall) that year,
Dvorak beat everyone in the 5-mile run, then stayed a step ahead of
the competition the rest of the week, leading the team with six
goals in five scrimmages.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, three years later, that remains the highlight of
Dvorak's NHL career _ that and the five-game point streak he put
together to close last season.
</P>
<P>
   First-year coach Terry Murray clearly expects that to change.
After stating Wednesday that he plans to play Dvorak on one of his
top two lines, Murray said, ``He's got great speed, he's got
experience now, and I think he can have a breakthrough year this
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Dvorak has generated that kind of optimism before. After he was
drafted and, particularly, after his first camp, General Manager
Bryan Murray said Dvorak could be a 30- 35-goal scorer.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed he might be on his way when he scored 13 and 18,
respectively, in his first two seasons, both of which he played as
a teenager. But when he slipped to 12 last year, Murray conceded
that he might top out in the 20-25 range.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to try to show him I'm better than that,'' Dvorak
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got all the skill to be a scorer,'' linemate Dino
Ciccarelli said. ``He's got great speed and size (6-foot-1, 195),
and that's something a lot of guys in this league don't have. Maybe
he should have the mindset to shoot more.''
</P>
<P>
   While Dvorak took the fewest shots of any Florida forward last
season (112, an average of 1.75 per game), he also was one of only
seven Panthers to convert better than 10 percent (10.7).
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to pass too much,'' he admitted. ``I'll get a 2-on-1 or
an open net and try to pass. But they've told me I have to shoot
when I get a chance. Kozzie (linemate Victor Kozlov) always shoots.
I have to do the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant coach Slava Lener, who coached Dvorak on the Czech
Republic under-20 team three years ago, said he sees three keys to
Dvorak's success: 1. Being strong on the puck; 2. Taking the puck
more to the net; and 3. Concentrating more on his defense.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Murray feels the best place for him to accomplish those
goals might be left wing, and promised to try him there in some
upcoming exhibition games. Dvorak has played mostly right wing
until now.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of potential, but there's a lot of work to be
done,'' Lener said. ``He's playing too relaxed so far; that's not
the way we want to have him.''
</P>
<P>
   Dvorak said one reason he's relaxed is the pressure has been
lifted since he signed a four-year, $4.5 million contract last
weekend. At 21, he knows his future is secure and he can
concentrate on playing hockey.
</P>
<P>
   But that future may not be in Miami. In discussing the contract
last week, Bryan Murray noted that Dvorak has a league-wide
reputation now and that, if a youngster such as, say, Marcus
Nilson, made a big impression, Dvorak could be moved.
</P>
<P>
   The message was clear: Perform and you've got a future in South
Florida. Come up short again and you'll be starting over somewhere
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that happens,'' Dvorak said, ``that's the business. But I
want to be with this team when it gets back to the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
