<DOCNO> NYT19980917.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0126 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINTER-COLUMN18-COX     09-17 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A different era in the air
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bob Christian, who covered baseball for The Atlanta Journal when
baseball was the Crackers in Ponce de Leon Park, recently retired
from airline consulting in Washington. He spends his time welcoming
visitors to Mount Vernon, keeping up with news from Georgia and
being the finest amateur historian I know.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the sports beat he became a Delta public relations
executive before joining rival Eastern as a vice president. His
latest dispatch included a reminder that this month is the 32nd
anniversary of the death of C.E. Woolman, Delta's founder. He hopes
some of Mr. Woolman's personality and management style survives all
the changes Delta has gone through in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I once had to drive over to the Hilton Inn from Delta
headquarters to pick up a senior editor from Forbes magazine in
town to interview Mr. Woolman,'' he wrote. ``The man was in a foul
mood because I had not been able to give him a definite time for
the interview. Mr. Woolman didn't make appointments. It was first
to the door, first in.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we drove up to the building, we saw Mr. Woolman get out of
his old Chrysler Imperial and send Robert, his driver, on his way.
But when we got to his office on the second floor, somebody had
beaten us to the door. We took our seat and waited. And waited.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could hear loud talk and laughter coming from Mr. Woolman's
office. Our guest from Forbes was fuming. Finally Mr. Woolman
appeared at his door. He had his arm around a large black man, a
skycap from Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ```Now John,' he was saying, `If you ever have that problem
again, just get on an airplane and come on down and we'll work it
out.'''
</P>
<P>
   Christian said the editor left happy, convinced there was
something unique about Mr. Woolman and his airline.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Woolman grew show-class orchids in his greenhouse. On his
birthday, Oct. 8, every woman in the building got one of his
orchids at an afternoon party. ``The orchids were a daily thing,''
Bob explained. ``Each day he brought two or three to work.
Throughout the afternoon he'd invite one of the women employees to
stop by his office so he could give them one of his orchids.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Woolman was famously frugal with company money. Christian
made many out-of-town trips with him and recalls riding in a
limousine only once. He normally hitched a ride on a Delta mail
truck or some other company delivery vehicle. He deviated only the
one time when he was in New York to accept the Newcomen Award, the
most prestigious honor a business executive can receive. John Shad,
Delta's director of sales in New York, insisted on the limousine.
``Darned if I was going to let my boss ride up to the Pierre Hotel
in the company mail truck,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, the Georgia General Assembly was looking for a new
source of revenue. Politicians were about to start charging a sales
tax on everything from equipment to food purchased by big
companies, even if the goods were bought out of state and never got
to Georgia. Southern Railroad was threatening to move its Atlanta
maintenance center to Chattanooga. Delta was worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right at this time Mr. Woolman had to make a speech at the
annual meeting of the Tampa Chamber of Commerce,'' Christian says.
``We flew down and stayed over the next day to have breakfast with
Scott Christopher, the president of the Tampa chamber. Scott drove
us to a big, beautiful, new office park.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be a lovely spot for some company's headquarters,''
was Mr. Woolman's comment to his Tampa host.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, back in Atlanta, Christian got a call from
John Pennington, the Journal's top reporter. ``What's this about
Delta moving its headquarters to Tampa?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's moving to Tampa in 1963 would have been at least as
devastating as Delta's moving to Tampa in 1998. Christian went
bounding up the steps to Mr. Woolman's office to find out what to
tell the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``He grinned and said. `Now Bob, you know we aren't going to
move, but don't deny it too strongly. Just say we always look at
proposals that are attractive to Delta's future.'''
</P>
<P>
   The sales tax threat evaporated as soon as the afternoon Journal
hit the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Woolman really was one of the most remarkable men I have
ever met,'' Christian wrote. ``One of the things that made him
unique was that from crop-dusting in Louisiana to running the
country's most envied airline, he had only one secretary. His
payroll number was 001. Catherine Fitzgerald, `Miss Fitz' in the
old Delta family, was No. 002. She died a multimillionaire from her
Delta stock, but never moved out of her garage apartment in College
Park.''
</P>
<P>
   Christian wonders if anyone in the new Delta rides the mail
truck in New York, or hands out orchids in the afternoon; or if a
reservations agent in Florida loves his company so much he lists
Delta as his middle name in the telephone book.
</P>
<P>
   Of course not. We all live in a different world in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
