<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0130 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIFORNIA18-COX     09-17 1966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIFORNIA18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Travel story on California
 &HT;    By Gregory Kallenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The descriptive term ``breathtaking'' is
overused. Admit it, we all hate it. The canopy of trees was
breathtaking. Her beauty was breathtaking. The new Mazda is
breathtaking.
</P>
<P>
   What does it mean, anyway? Is it a situation, person or panorama
where, witnessing it, one is prone to hyperventilation?
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, I'm traveling north on the Pacific Coast Highway
through Big Sur and I can't think of any other word to describe the
cragged cliffs, the crushing sea as it meets the rocks, the ocean
mist that hovers over the scene and makes it almost surreal. It's,
well, you know...the ``b'' word.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, my wife and I were about halfway through our trip
up the California coast. We were determined to shun the quicker,
multi- lane, mega-highways and stay ompletely on scenic,
turtle-paced, Highway 1 (or, by it's more romantic name, the
Pacific Coast Highway) from San Diego to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Coast Highway is a two-laned stretch of concrete and
asphalt that begins in San Diego and unravels along the Pacific
coast to Leggett, Calif. Our trip would take us past the posh
Hollywood mansions of Los Angeles, through Big Sur, Monterey and
Pescadero and end at the Golden Gate Bridge. On a regular day,
armed with coffee, Wow! Doritos and 10 CDs, you could make the trip
in about 11 hours. We decided to take nine days to make our
journey.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego: The journey begins. ``It's been kind of hot here,''
said my San Diego friend Mike Hojel when we arrived by plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah,'' I said, having just left a brisk 102-degree July
day behind in Texas. ``How hot has it been?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost 80,'' he said, sounding perturbed at having to use a
number so high. The temperature would be a recurring theme on our
trip, so let's get it out of the way now: While we were in the
Golden State, the median mid-afternoon temperature was a little
above 74 degrees. San Diego is a beautiful city situated at the
bottom of California, nestled next to the Pacific Ocean. With L.A.
being only 90 minutes north and Tijuana, Mexico just 40 minutes
south, both cultures tug at the city. It's cool and glamorous, but
it also has a rough, south of the border'' feel to it. This leaves
a unique final product. Our first night was a prime example.
</P>
<P>
   Hojel promised us a gourmet Mexican meal at El Callejon (The
Alley''), a bistro-esque spot in Encinitas just north of San Diego.
There, the beautiful people ate puntas de pollo and medallones
chipotle in the exclusive setting. The patrons, along with their
cellular phones, looked and felt like Hollywood. It wasn't until we
sat down that the Mexican influences of the restaurant became
apparent. Two-hundred and forty-three tequilas, ranging from $3.75
a shot to $45, sat on shelves along the wall. By the time we had
gotten to tequila No. 7 on the list (a beautiful Patron Anejo), it
felt like we were banditos holing up in a border town.
</P>
<P>
   On our last day in San Diego, we visited the San Diego Zoo,
arguably the best zoo in the world. After seeing a Chinese Blue
Sheep give birth (really, we did), Pygmy Chimps play with dead
ducks (really, they did) and the giant panda Ling-Ling sleep, we
decided to begin the 2 1/2-hour drive to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   After passing through some interesting ocean towns separated
only by signs reading, ``Welcome to ...,'' we stopped in Cardiff to
take in a bit of beach culture at a cafe called Swami's (''Every
bite is a vegan's delight!''). There, a waitress named Charity,
awash in glitter, and a guy named Regular Joe bantered over
consumerism and its effects on the ocean's ecosystem. It was kind
of like being in Austin with sand.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles: The jocund conspiracy
</P>
<P>
   It was apparent we had arrived in Los Angeles when the traffic
got bad and the people stopped smiling. Again, we were staying with
some friends. The Rhodes' live in Century City, down the street
from 20th Century Fox Studios and around the corner from Lucille
Ball's old house. Their abode is a quaint 1,250-square-foot,
two-bedroom, one- bath affair and (take note all who whine about
Austin real estate prices) would sell for about $600,000. After we
settled in, we sat in the cool dusk eating guacamole and drinking
grape juice under their lemon tree right next to their flowering
rose garden just feet away from their artichoke bush. This would be
yet another theme of our trip: everything, especially things you
eat, grows in California.
</P>
<P>
   The next day was spent riding down Sunset Boulevard, seeing the
'Hollywood'' sign (to which my wife commented, It's so small!''),
cruising by Groman's Chinese Theater on Hollywood Boulevard, and
winding up at Disneyland in Anaheim. The traffic going out was
horrendous and put us both in sour moods, but those moods
disappeared once we entered the Magic Kingdom. Here, smiles weren't
optional and everyone seemed to wear one, so we reluctantly joined
in. Though it was nice to see so many happy people in one place, it
felt like some sort of jocund conspiracy. I actually spent a lot of
my time at Disneyland watching Mickey's little helpers joyfully
dish out ice cream and gleefully clean the streets just waiting for
their faces to fall. It didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   The night ended on an exciting note. While making our way to the
newly refurbished Tomorrowland, power went out in half of the park.
A driver on the Harbor Freeway had run into a transformer. Disney
refunded everyone their money as they left.
</P>
<P>
   The downside was this: It just made everyone smile all the more.
</P>
<P>
   Carmel: The long and winding road
</P>
<P>
   We left Los Angeles early in the the morning with Carmel as our
destination. This day would take us up into the heralded Big Sur
National Park and Los Padres National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   The year has been a rough one for this portion of the Pacific
Coast Highway. Mudslides from torrential rains closed portions of
the road. Recently, the passage was reopened, but we were warned to
expect some delays on the way up.
</P>
<P>
   If the stretch of road to Carmel was straightened, the swank
town would take two hours to reach from L.A. However, the intricacy
of the highway as it twists around mountains, the intermittent road
construction delays and stops in some of California's most charming
towns meant our trip took about six hours.
</P>
<P>
   The gateway to this stretch of road is Santa Barbara, where we
refueled and ate a four-pound breakfast burrito at a highly
recommended taqueria called El Bajio on Milpas. From there, we
passed through the picturesque San Luis Obisbo; the
not-picturesque-but-worth-the-stop-to-see dormant volcano, Morrow
Bay; and the sort of picturesque Buellton, which lays claim to
being the ``Home of Split Pea Soup.''
</P>
<P>
   I had been told how breathtaking'' (there's that word again)
this road was and once the tiny burgs were left behind and the
Escheresque roads began, it was clear there had been no
exaggeration. Woe be those who bring only one roll of film on this
portion of the trip; it's definitely a three roller. If nothing
else, stop and enjoy the array of wildflowers that adorn the side
of the road along with the wild fennel and rosemary.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic delays were frequent because of bulldozers clearing the
road of debris, but these seemed to be welcomed by travelers as
they took full advantage of the downtime: posing dangerously close
to a cliff' s edge or taking snapshots down the rocky coast. With
the drama of the sea meeting land on one side and tall woolly
forests and mountains on the other side, the Pacific Coast Highway
provides the kinds of photo opportunities where you can blow up
your prints and your will friends ask, ``Where did you buy that?''
</P>
<P>
   After traveling into the tiny town of Big Sur, we stopped at
Nepenthe, a restaurant near the new-age Esalen Institute where
spanking as therapy was made famous. Nepenthe is a touristy little
stop with terraces overlooking the Big Sur coast. Here, we supped
on $10 hamburgers while taking in a view that was worth 10 times
that.
</P>
<P>
   The next stop was Carmel, the fabled golfing village by the sea.
In Carmel we finally had the opportunity to stay in a hotel. La
Playa was originally an oceanfront mansion. It proved to be the
best part of the town, along with the beach that was within walking
distance. Carmel is a bit stodgy and white bread for my taste.
Everywhere you look, you either see people dressed for golf in
light pastels or entire families with matching argyle sweaters
draped around their necks. It was spooky.
</P>
<P>
   Sonoma: The Wine Country beckons
</P>
<P>
   The next day we had a change in plans. Instead of ending with a
four- day stint in San Francisco, we decided to head into the Wine
Country for a couple of days. Through Monterey with its stellar
aquarium, to Pescadero where we stopped at the soon to be famous''
Duarte' s Cafe for its artichoke soup, over the Golden Gate Bridge
and into Napa and Sonoma, just an hour and a half north of San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Our first night was spent in Sonoma at a hotel called El Dorado.
Sonoma is a beautiful place with a town square picturesque enough
to be on a cereal box or bread label but, unfortunately, the town
square sits alongside busy Highway 12. The same highway fronted our
hotel and our night was spent listening to semis, souped-up pickup
trucks and motorcycles make their way up and down the road. It was
a good thing we had been properly fed and sedated at Babbette's, a
tres cool cafe across the square.
</P>
<P>
   The next day we decided to move to Napa, which was also a
mistake. Every hotel was booked, so we ended up staying at the
Silverado Country Club. Once the tony place to stay in Napa, the
hotel hasn't aged well and looks like the backdrop for a
``Caddyshack'' sequel. I could just imagine Rodney Dangerfield
standing next to me and looking at the golfers waiting to tee off.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is this? A funeral?'' he would have said.
</P>
<P>
   The one thing that amazed me about the Wine Country is how
touristy the place is. People are everywhere: the roads are packed,
the restaurants are packed, even the most remote of wineries are
packed.
</P>
<P>
   What made it all worthwhile was the food at Tra Vigne in St.
Helena (dauntingly hyper-Italian decor but a fantastic menu) and
the tours at Beringer and Domaine Chandon. The hand-dug caves at
Beringer, Napa' s oldest winery, are a sight and the gardens and
tasting rooms at the Chandon sparkling winery are worth a couple of
hours.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco: Here we come
</P>
<P>
   The last leg of the trip was spent in San Francisco. After
checking in at our hotel, the Milano, we headed into the city. My
wife was gung ho on getting a boiled crab so we tried hiking up Nob
Hill with Fisherman's Wharf as our destination. Halfway up, we
hailed a street car.
</P>
<P>
   The first day was spent eating a crab at Wharfatude and drinking
Irish coffees at Buena Vista, a touristy spot made famous by the
drink. San Francisco was downright cold and the Irish coffees took
off the chill.
</P>
<P>
   Our last day was spent shopping for schlocky gifts in Chinatown,
stuffing ourselves at Yank-Sing (a dim sum restaurant in the
Financial District) and watching soccer with Italians in the North
Beach area of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, as we waited for our plane, we pulled out our
road atlas and retraced our journey up the coast. For a moment,
there was silence between us, trying to fashion some word that
described the whole experience. As our flight was announced we
turned to each other and simultaneously used that overused term
that I thought I always hated: ``Breathtaking!''
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Kallenberg is a staff writer for the Austin
American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 1017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980917.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0131 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTREAL18-COX     09-17 1929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTREAL18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Travel story on Montreal
 &HT;    By R. Michelle Breyer and Jody Seaborn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ When planning our trip to Montreal, we were told a
number of things about the Canadian city.
</P>
<P>
   It's like Paris, except friendlier.
</P>
<P>
   It's like New York, except they speak French.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Montreal offers a pleasant mix of European and American
sensibilities and features. With its museums, first-class shops and
ethnic neighborhoods, it does resemble a cleaner, smaller New York.
And because of its French heritage and largely French-speaking
population, Montreal does have a European flair.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans will feel they are in a European city.
</P>
<P>
   But in a European city in which language isn't a barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone we met could switch easily from French to English, and
did so with none of the reluctance of Parisians. In fact, no matter
the shop or restaurant we walked into, if we greeted their bon jour
with our own weak, badly accented bon jour, the reply was
inevitably in English and was made without condescension.
</P>
<P>
   The cheerful blend that makes Montreal such a wonderful place to
visit, however, includes not only New York and Paris, but also the
eclecticism of San Francisco and, thanks to the Casino Montreal,
the solid excessiveness of Las Vegas. And with an exchange rate
that has been especially favorable recently _ when we were there in
late July, one U.S. dollar bought $1.50 in Canadian currency _
Montreal is a relatively affordable city, perhaps only slightly
more expensive than what a visitor staying at a moderately priced
hotel and eating at moderately priced restaurants would find in
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal lends itself to spontaneity. We arrived without much of
a planned itinerary and suffered not in the least because of it. A
fast perusal of a couple of guide books and off we went.
</P>
<P>
   You'd be hard-pressed to lose your way in Montreal: The major
streets are quickly learned, the major sites are easily accessible,
and if you don't find that special restaurant you're looking for,
one just as good will be around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite all these great things about Montreal, the greatest
was its weather. Keep this in mind for next year before those
memories of this year's brutal June and July wane: Montreal is an
ideal summer escape _ mild days and cool nights, though slightly
humid.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the weather, the things we enjoyed about Montreal
were those things Austin doesn't offer, or doesn't offer very
often. Let the list begin with Montreal's excellent public
transportation system.
</P>
<P>
   The Metro
</P>
<P>
   Never fear getting around Montreal. It's easy. It's quick. And
it's cheap.
</P>
<P>
   The Metro, Montreal's subway system, can take you just about
anywhere in the city you want to go, or at least put you within
walking distance. (You will want to do most of your exploring on
foot anyway.) If necessary, you can also use your Metro ticket to
board the city's buses.
</P>
<P>
   There are 65 Metro stations _ the city will be expanding its
network of underground tunnels in the next decade or so _ placed
along four Metro lines. Each line is color-coded and easy to figure
out. Most visitors to Montreal will be primarily concerned with
stops along the green line, which covers downtown and the tourist
areas around Olympic Park, and the orange line, which covers Old
Montreal and the Plateau Mont-Royal neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Single rides on the Metro cost $1.30 U.S., while a three-day
pass costs about $8.50 U.S. We got our money's worth with our
three-day pass. And as we rode on the train, we often commented on
how nice it was not to have to rely on a car to get anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhoods
</P>
<P>
   Much of Montreal's charm lies in its diverse neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Our favorite was the eclectic, multi-ethnic Plateau Mont-Royal,
just north of downtown. Less touristy than Old Montreal, which
despite its history and Old World architecture has little to offer
beyond a pleasant stroll, and Rue Ste-Catherine, the heart of
Montreal's downtown shopping district and ground zero for the
inevitable Americanization to come (a Planet Hollywood opened off
Ste-Catherine while we were in Montreal), Plateau Mont-Royal
features offbeat shops, nightclubs and a variety of restaurants and
bistros, many of which open onto the sidewalk in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   This neighborhood has few if any of the tacky tourist shops
common downtown. You're more likely to find memorabilia related to
Tintin, the Belgian cartoon character; funky bookstores and thrift
stores; and European-style clothing stores.
</P>
<P>
   (An aside: Spandex shorts, pants and shirts, along with high
heels and soles two- to three-inches thick, were all the fashion in
Montreal. Perhaps the looks reflects the prevalence of discos. )
</P>
<P>
   Our most memorable meals were at restaurants within the Plateau
Mont- Royal neighborhood. One was a late-night dinner at a Greek
restaurant on Rue Prince-Arthur; the other was a mid-afternoon
feast of tapas and paella at a Portuguese restaurant on Rue Duluth.
Lack of time kept us from trying the many Middle Eastern, Japanese,
Vietnamese and Italian restaurants in the area.
</P>
<P>
   We wouldn't suggest staying anywhere but downtown, specifically
the area bordered by Rue University on the east, Rue Crescent on
the west, Rue Sherbrooke to the north and Boulevard Rene-Levesque
to the south. Though downtown had its Gap _ actually its Gaps and
its Starbucks (when we go to Mars, we will find a Starbucks there),
and now its Planet Hollywood _ it offered much more in terms of
shopping and dining, and much more at a later hour. Like New York,
Montreal may never sleep _ and it definitely likes the wee hours.
</P>
<P>
   We kept reading about Montreal's underground city,'' but when we
asked people how to get to this city, they looked at us as though
we were from Oz. Don't be fooled by the guide books: There is no
underground city per se. Rather, it is loosely connected Metro
passageways, corridors and store basements, an informally
structured defense against Montreal's long, bitter winters. In this
subterranean universe, residents can make their way from
restaurants to movies to concerts without stepping outside.
</P>
<P>
   The sites
</P>
<P>
   Montreal has several museums, a nice feature for people coming
from a city with few museums. We spent several hours one morning at
the architecturally interesting Museum of Fine Arts, touring an
exhibit of Alberto Giacometti's sculptures and paintings, and
wandering through the museum's permanent collection, which includes
work from the Middle Ages to the late 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   We also visited the Biodome, where plants and animals live in
reproductions of their natural ecosystems. The Biodome features a
tropical forest, a Laurentian forest, and marine and polar
habitats.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby is Montreal's botanical garden and insectarium, as well
as the Olympic Stadium, home of the Montreal Expos baseball team
and the Canadian Football League's Montreal Alouettes. (Montreal
hosted the 1976 Summer Olympics; the city has made good use of the
complex it built to host the games.)
</P>
<P>
   The McCord Museum of Canadian History, associated with McGill
University, showcases thousands of costumes, artifacts and
historical photographs. There's even the Just for Laughs Museum, a
by-product of the annual Just for Laughs comedy festival, held the
last two weeks of July. This museum includes video and film clips,
a 250-seat cabaret, a humor hall of fame, a shop and a cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was undergoing renovations during our visit, the
Basilique Notre-Dame is an awe-inspiring structure, big enough for
4,000 worshippers. While touring the 169-year-old cathedral, we
were treated to an impromptu performance by a Swiss a capella
choir. It was a beautiful moment.
</P>
<P>
   But there are times when art and culture and beauty need a
counterbalance, and for that Montreal has built a multistory casino
like no other. With almost 3,000 slot machines, the Casino de
Montreal is a grand place for anyone who likes to park their butt
on a stool and feed an electronic gadget their money.
</P>
<P>
   For those of us who prefer the gaming tables, however, the
casino is less grand. There are precious few blackjack tables _
precious fewer affordable blackjack tables _ and it was next to
impossible to get a seat at one of them. But get a seat we
eventually did. After a couple of hours entertainment, we parted
with $40 Canadian and with our gambling ways. At least for this
trip.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal's answer to New York's Central Park _ in fact it was
designed by Frederick Law Olmsted, the landscape architect who
created Central Park _ is Parc Mont-Royal. This 494-acre park
boasts miles of running and biking trails, observation points
overlooking the city, a small lake, a gorgeous chalet, and in the
winter, a small ski lift. We enjoyed a long, peaceful walk through
the park, as well as a few challenging runs up its gently sloping
hills.
</P>
<P>
   It might seem an odd place to visit, but just north of _ in
fact, across the street from _ Parc Mont-Royal is Montreal's
Catholic cemetery, Notre-Dame-des-Neiges Cemetery, a vast, serene
area of magnificent headstones. We spent two or three hours
wandering around, noting the names, the different ethnicities, and
how the arrangements and divisions within the cemetery reflect the
ethnic mix and socioeconomic arrangements within the city. Next
door is the city's Protestant (read: British) cemetery, another
clue into Montreal's past and present.
</P>
<P>
   Friendly (family-friendly even), unique, romantic, rich in
history and different enough to Americans for it to feel foreign,
yet not too foreign, Montreal is an ideal travel destination. IF
YOU GO: GETTING THERE: Many major airlines go to Montreal's Dorval
International Airport, including Air Canada, American, Continental,
Delta and Northwest. There was even a direct flight between
Montreal and Austin, with one stop in Dallas. It's about a
five-hour plane ride, not including stops. Leave extra time on the
way back to the United States, because it can take some time to get
through customs. WHEN TO GO: Quebec has warm summers and severe
winters, with snow lasting from mid-December to mid-March. During
August, while Austin hovers in the 100s, the average temperature in
Montreal is 76 degrees, falling to 61 degrees at night. Eastern
Canada also has beautiful springs and falls. LANGUAGE: Canada's two
official languages are English and French. Although English is
widely spoken, it is helpful to know some basic French. Many of the
street signs and Metro signs are in French. MONEY: Although U.S.
money is accepted many places in Canada, visitors are encouraged to
exchange some of their money for Canadian dollars. It can be done
at the airport or at any bank, where the exchange rates tend to be
better. Be aware that American tourists in Canada are eligible for
a General Sales Tax refund on purchases taken out of the country
and on short- term accommodations. Rebate forms, which must be
submitted within 60 days of leaving Canada, may be obtained from
certain retailers, duty-free shops and customs officials. The GST
on each receipt must be at least $3.50 and visitors must claim at
least $14 in tax per rebate application form. MORE INFORMATION: For
visitor information, you can call Tourisme Quebec at (800) 363-7777
or the Greater Montreal Convention and Tourism Bureau at (514)
844-5400.
</P>
<P>
   R. Michelle Breyer and Jody Seaborn are staff writers for the
Austin American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
