<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Travel story on Scandinavia
 &HT;    By Michael Barnes
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSLO, Norway _ On balance, we visit Scandinavia for the pretty
scenery and the pretty people.
</P>
<P>
   Not for the vaulting monuments (there are few), nor for the high
art (there is little), and certainly not for the famously bland and
expensive food of Norway, Sweden and Denmark (mostly dairy and
fish, without much attention paid to preparation or presentation).
</P>
<P>
   Yet Scandinavia deserves an extended stay. Because these
countries were spared the full brunt of modern wars, their physical
pasts remain remarkably intact. Thus, the culturally curious
visitor should make special efforts to visit some small historical
or art museums in the cities of Oslo, Bergen, Stockholm and
Copenhagen.
</P>
<P>
   Envision dragon-shaped Viking vessels that skimmed the far seas
and tall-masted warships meant to ferry Swedes to the bloody Thirty
Years War. Discover the barracks of the Hanseatic League, a
mysterious guild that monopolized Baltic Sea trade for centuries,
and linger in a bizarre museum, built by a beer tycoon to display
his extensive collection of historical sculpture. Examine
well-preserved wonders, such as the jewel-like theater at Sweden's
Drottningholm Palace, and the exotic instruments on display in a
Danish musical museum.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, you should tour the majestic fjords, sample the local
beers, but before you leave, rummage through Scandinavia's cultural
attic by spending a few stray hours in these nine small museums.
Vigeland Park and Museum, Oslo, Norway
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most memorable spot in Norway, outside of the
fjords, is Vigeland Park, a few minutes on the tram from the center
of Oslo. Its designer, sculptor Gustav Vigeland (1869-1943), viewed
art on a scale both grandiose and humane. The large, popular park,
opened in 1950 after more than 40 years of design and construction,
is organized around a corridor of bronze and stone sculptures of
human figures. At first glance, Vigeland's hundreds of nudes
suggests a Rodinesque eye for handsome, smooth, large-limbed men
and women. After a few moments of inspection, one realizes Vigeland
was plumbing for deeper insights into the human condition. Men toss
babies through the air, or pull women viciously by their braids.
Figures young and old drip with a dignified eroticism. The bridges
and fountains, covered with real children at play, are capped by a
huge monolith of piled bodies, depicting humankind competing for
top position. High pedestals also hold men and women embraced by
dragon-like lizards. If the park makes one wonder what kind of
character would create this art, the nearby Vigeland Museum keeps
the man mysterious, with only a few clues to crack his
psychological code. Here we see his studios, built by the City of
Oslo, packed with small studies, plaster casts, drawings, woodcuts,
sketches and plans, as well as prints of the army of craftsmen who
executed his fantasies. Although most Americans have never heard of
Vigeland, the work of this strange artist deserves a much closer
inspection, and perhaps a good explanation. Viking Ship Museum,
Oslo, Norway
</P>
<P>
   Of all the cultural prizes of Scandinavia, the most familiar to
Americans is this museum, built especially for three ninth- century
Viking ships discovered in the 19th century. The building itself is
one of the most graceful solutions to the problem of bending
architecture to historical display. A cruciform of barrel vaults
gently encloses the amazing remains of seagoing oaken ships, as
well as Viking artifacts. One problem: Small balconies force
visitors to crowd together to view the decks from above. You get a
real sense of the power and utility of these long, curved vehicles
by approaching them from different directions in the diffuse light.
This splendid little museum is surrounded by other attractions,
such as the Norse Folk Museum, Kon-Tiki Museum and Fram Museum
(another ship museum) on the Bygdy peninsula in southwest Oslo; all
are easily reached by ferries which leave the Rdhus (Oslo city
hall) at regular intervals. Munch Museum, Oslo, Norway
</P>
<P>
   The single Scandinavian painter to make an impact on the larger
world of art was Edvard Munch, a moody master of color and
distorted line. While Norway's boring National Museum owns some
fine Munchs, one must travel to Tyen, in what passes for a scruffy
neighborhood in well-scrubbed Oslo. The 1963 building feels much
like an American museum, with prominent gift shop and oversized
lobby, but the actual galleries are aptly proportioned for Munch's
vivid artwork. One also learns about the man, who suffered from
years of depression and bruising affairs, since one large gallery
is devoted to a detailed account of Munch's life. But the reason to
go is paint, great smears of it, evoking unavoidable emotions,
mainly through psychologically suggestive color. I never really
understood the association of the color green with the feeling of
envy until I saw the way Munch depicts the faces of jealousy. Most
art museums in Scandinavia underwhelm, but, perhaps because of its
narrow focus, the Munch Museum leaves you feeling aesthetically
satisfied. Vasa Museum, Stockholm, Sweden
</P>
<P>
   Rising from Stockholm's inner harbor is a modern building with a
roof that resembles the sails of a tall ship. Mastheads peek out of
the concrete arcs. Made skeptical by this architectural gimmick, I
was in no way prepared for the overwhelming experience of viewing
the vast warship, Vasa, enclosed in the Vasa Museum. The wooden
warship, commissioned by Swedish warrior-king Gustav II Adolf, sank
in the harbor on its maiden voyage in 1628. You cannot walk on the
Vasa's decks, but the novel shape of the museum allows you to view
everything close-up through several stories of amply shaped
balconies. Each floor also contains instructive exhibits on
shipbuilding, figure carving, military arms. What happened to the
Vasa? One of the most interesting exhibits is a slide show about
the trial after the disaster. It seems the king demanded an extra
battery of cannons, without increasing the hull's width, so,
despite warnings from experts, the navy sailed a ship that simply
tipped over in the lightest wind. The ship was amazingly well
preserved in the harbor's mud, until raised in the 1950s and '60s,
an epic story in itself. Of all the historical sites on the fair
islands of Stockholm, this one is the best interpreted and the most
invigorating, and most material is available in English.
Drottningholm Court Theater, Stockholm, Sweden
</P>
<P>
   There are only a few pilgrimage stops required for the lover of
theatrical history. One is the court theater, or Slottsteater, at
the Drottningholm Palace on Lovn Island, just outside Stockholm. A
scenic ferry shifts tourists to the 17th-century ``queen's
palace,'' built in the style of Versailles, only much smaller.
Between the palace and its formal gardens is a unique theater and
museum. There's a great story here: A former German princess, Queen
Lovisa Ulrika of Sweden, missed the civilized graces of her
homeland, so she commissioned a theater. Yet she failed to pay the
architect, Carl Fredrik Adelcrantz (so he lived in the building as
repayment). The Slottsteater glowed with activity after it opened
in 1766, reaching its apex of grandeur during the reign of Gustav
III, who staged his own operas. After the 1790s, it was mothballed,
a storage house for royal artwork and, for a time, potatoes. Then,
in the 1920s, an enterprising art historian uncovered the perfectly
preserved 18th-century theater, a unique treasure. Tiny, dark, it
contains the original ``wing-and-drop'' scenery, operated with
ropes, with the wings sliding in floor slots, the unframed fabric
drops streaming overhead. Nowadays, a guide demonstrates some of
the theatrical machinery, although I was disappointed not to see
the ``sea'' or ``cloud'' simulations. Nearby is a theater museum,
which contains dozens of scene designs, models and images of shows.
The wall texts are not in English and the displays are hardly
fashionable, but it's a trove of theatrical memorabilia. The
Slottsteater is a ``working'' museum, so the operas of Gluck,
Haydn, Handel and Mozart are staged in historically inspired
productions, but you must plan well in advance to attend one of the
festival performances. Hanseatic Museum, Bergen, Norway
</P>
<P>
   Do you recall any but the dimmest references to the Hanseatic
League from high school or college history classes? This all-male
guild of merchants monopolized trade in Northern Europe until the
18th century. Sound boring? Not if you visit the Hanseatic Museum
in Bergen, one of the league's northern outposts and Norway's
second largest city, located on the western coast. What survives on
the Bryggen, or old waterfront, are fabulous timber buildings,
including the museum's structure, which served as offices and
dormitories for the league. In the low-ceilinged, dark-wood, dimly
lit rooms, one learns all about the collecting of dried fish, the
main export from northern Norway, and the import of just about
every other kind of consumer goods, which, to this day, Norwegians
don't grow or make. This museum is not crammed with explanations,
but it makes up for it in authentic character, each room with the
tools of the Hanseatic trade. You really want to climb into the
beds and pretend you were tapped into the league. Bryggens Museum,
Bergen, Norway
</P>
<P>
   Archaeological sites of varying interest speckle Scandinavia,
and, after a while, they begin to amalgamate in the mind. Tiny
coins and medallions begin to look alike; fragments of wood and
stone objects lose their magical powers to imaginatively rearrange
themselves into weapons, tools and other signs of culture. What's
powerful about this one is its location over the 12th-century site
uncovered in the middle of Bergen. The museum concentrates on the
medieval years, with maps, implements and fragments of fabric and
building materials displayed with care and sensitivity. Here is the
place to take kids with a hankering for the Middle Ages, since
everything is arranged to replicate daily life eight centuries ago,
this despite sitting in a stark, modern structure. Music History
Museum, Copenhagen, Denmark
</P>
<P>
   This is an odd little curiosity, almost untouched by 20th
century concepts about museum display and education. High-quality
specimens of musical instruments line three narrow floors of a
modest building on a Copenhagen backstreet. Although smaller
instruments are masked behind glass casing, others are (almost too
temptingly) placed right before the spectator. No attempt is made
at sophisticated presentation -- some of the time-curled wall cards
are attached to the wall with straight pins, not even map tacks.
All this adds to the charm. It's like being set loose in an attic
of an eccentric uncle to gape at outlandish monstrosities --
zithers, psalters, antique horns, drums, keyboards, harps and a
healthy array of instruments from exotic lands. I felt a childish
awe at the sight of these music-making objects, but left wishing
for a deeper understanding that would have come with more
explanation of these rare finds. Ny Carlsberg Glyptotek,
Copenhagen, Denmark
</P>
<P>
   Do not visit the Ny Carlsberg Glyptotek exclusively for its
sculpture, despite the thousands of examples from Greece, Rome,
Egypt, the Near East and elsewhere on display. Truth be told, the
examples collected by Danish beer (Carlsberg) magnate Carl Jacobsen
(1842-1914) are substandard, measured against the masterpieces
horded by British, American, French, German and Italian museums.
(Military empires facilitate artistic imperialism more than mere
commercial profits.) The reason for visiting this large museum is
the building, which looks like a sober palace from the outside, but
is a lost world on the inside. Each display attempts to put the
sculpture into an appropriate context, so the colors of the walls,
the execution of the floor mosaics, are related to the materials
and styles of the art on display. A central atrium is styled after
the interior of a Roman building, but the real stunner is the
conservatory, a plant-filled public area where one can spend hours,
reading, snacking or watching the regular performances in the
space. The scent of great wealth permeates the Glyptotek, but what
sets this place apart from the major art museums of Scandinavia is
an obsession with a particular art form. You may wish the curators
were more selective, but you cannot help being amazed by the sheer
size of the collection and the impressive way that it is displayed.
For more information on these sites, contact the Scandinavian
Tourist Board, 655 Third Avenue, 18th Floor, New York, N.Y., 10017;
(212) 949-2333. Web site: www.globescope.com/nordic.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Barnes is a staff writer for the Austin
American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
