r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-YOGA18-COX     09-17 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-YOGA18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Welcome to your yoga vacation
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASSAU, Bahamas _ The boom of a gong pierced the silence of the
night promptly at 5:30 a.m., which is mighty early on Paradise
Island.
</P>
<P>
   This is the time to go to bed after a night at the casinos and
bars, not to get up to meditate and to do yoga positions that turn
your body into a pretzel.
</P>
<P>
   I obediently got out of bed.
</P>
<P>
   My legs were as stiff as a crab's, and a spasm in my neck, the
result of a recent backpack trip, ached when I turned my head. I
bent down to see if I could touch my toes - not even close - and
then stumbled half-asleep down a path through 5 acres of lush
gardens to the yoga temple overlooking Nassau Harbour.
</P>
<P>
   I joined two dozen other retreaters, who sat cross-legged in the
dark in front of an incense flame. I tried to meditate,
concentrating on the Sanskrit word Om (meaning something along the
lines of what was, what is and what will be).
</P>
<P>
   But it was hard to focus longer than 15 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Ommmmmmm.
</P>
<P>
   I need a cup of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Ommmmmm.
</P>
<P>
   My legs are going numb and my knees feel like they're
calcifying.
</P>
<P>
   Ommmmmmm.
</P>
<P>
   Do people really want to do this on vacation?
</P>
<P>
   The Sivananda Ashram Yoga Retreat is not for everyone, but it is
definitely the ticket for those seriously looking for some peace
and serenity.
</P>
<P>
   For 30 years it has been a tranquil oasis for a steady stream of
people including ex-Beatle George Harrison, Crocodile Dundee star
Linda Kozlowski, high-powered execs, physicians and regular
stressed-out folks like me.
</P>
<P>
   The ashram embraces all ages, nationalities and religions. The
head of the ashram, Swami Omkarananda, who is from Israel,
describes the retreat as ``a greenhouse to learn how to live life
properly. It gives you the right conditions to exercise properly,
breathe properly, eat properly, relax properly and teaches you how
to think positively and to meditate.''
</P>
<P>
   The price is also soothing - $85 a day for a single private room
($70 each for two people in a beach cabin), two vegetarian meals a
day, two two-hour yoga sessions a day (mandatory for guests) and
two two-hour meditations (also mandatory).
</P>
<P>
   Life here is simple.
</P>
<P>
   My room in a rambling wood house, which had a long veranda
facing a coconut palm grove and the ocean, was so small that a man
with long arms could touch the two parallel walls.
</P>
<P>
   The bed was a cotton pallet on a plywood platform. Pickled pine
walls rose to a high ceiling; a large window framed a view of palm
trees; and a ceiling fan and a screen door opening to the veranda
kept the room cool.
</P>
<P>
   At this Bahamas resort, there is no alcohol - you don't sip
margaritas on this beach - no coffee, tea, meat, fish, cigarettes,
radios, TVs or air-conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Bathrooms are off an outside porch and signs tell guests to mop
after use - all the conveniences of home.
</P>
<P>
   It reminded me a lot of the summer camp I went to as a kid, and
I liked it instantly.
</P>
<P>
   What I, and the other campers, didn't like were the cold showers
- not room temperature but cold enough to make you scream for
mercy.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors of hot showers ran rampant through the ashram. My new
friend Carl told me he had found a shower with warm water in the
bathrooms near the staff cabins.
</P>
<P>
   Exhilarated at this news, I immediately went there and stood
under the shower-head ready for hot water that would soothe my
aching thighs. Not only was there no hot water, there was no water
at all.
</P>
<P>
   At that point it was hot water or nothing, so I went back to one
of the showers in the main house and poured out a plastic gallon
jug of mineral water, filled it with hot water from a sink in the
bathroom and poured it over my head in the shower. I discovered I
was a five-gallon-shower person. I even steamed up the mirror,
which must have amazed the person who came behind me.
</P>
<P>
   Another guest told me he walked up the beach to Pirate's Cove
Hotel and used the Jacuzzi.
</P>
<P>
   Guests are expected to wash their plates after meals, and are
given opportunities to help out at the ashram. One day we were told
we could help the staff paint the tiny wooden cabins on the beach.
That's called ``karma yoga,'' selfless service.
</P>
<P>
   The food was simple - whole-wheat pancakes, fruit, cereal and
baked tofu for breakfast, spaghetti, bean soup and salad for
dinner. There were no spices, garlic or onions.
</P>
<P>
   I went from 121 pounds to 118 in three days, and I even cheated
one afternoon and went to the Poop Deck in Nassau for a big plate
of fried cracked conch.
</P>
<P>
   The down-to-earth simplicity of the ashram, not to mention the
experience of seeing your fellow campers at 5:30 a.m., makes for a
relaxed and social group. We ate outdoors on picnic tables and got
to know each other.
</P>
<P>
   My group included two computer experts, a couple in their 30s
from Munich, Germany; a flight attendant from Madrid; a lawyer from
Vienna, Austria; a chic woman in her 20s who worked at a
high-powered modeling agency in New York City; two middle-aged
women from Montreal; a student from Boston; and a man in his 60s,
who was there on the advice of a physician to help cure a bad back.
</P>
<P>
   We had varying degrees of yoga abilities. The man with the bad
back could barely touch his knees, but a young Canadian woman could
balance on her forearms and rest her feet on her head.
</P>
<P>
   A yoga instructor gently reminded us not to be competitive and
helped us into positions, asanas, we couldn't do on our own.
</P>
<P>
   The morning yoga class was held from 8 to 10 a.m. on a wooden
deck overlooking one of the prettiest white sand beaches in Nassau.
Guests at Club Med, which was next door, would come to a standstill
on the beach and watch us.
</P>
<P>
   After brunch at 10 a.m. we were free to go into Nassau or sit on
the beach until the next yoga session at 4 p.m. The ashram is not
accessible by road, but a boatman is available to ferry people
across the harbor to town.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the third day I not only could touch my palms to
the floor but could do some pretzel-type asanas. When I woke up on
the second and third mornings my legs weren't stiff.
</P>
<P>
   And my neck spasm was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Next time, I'll come here for two weeks like most of my fellow
campers, and I'll learn how to touch my feet to my head while
balancing on my forearms.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   The Sivananda Ashram Yoga Retreat: For reservations and
information, call (242) 363-2902. Single rooms in the main house
are $85. Cabins on the beach are $70 each for two people. Tent
sites are $50. Children of all ages are welcome. One of the
instructors had a 15-month-old.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Major airlines fly to Nassau and Paradise Island
airports. There is no road access to the ashram, so when you make
reservations ask them to make arrangements for a water taxi from
Nassau to the ashram's pier.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
