<HEADER>
A0134 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHAN-BIO18-COX     09-17 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAN-BIO18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How does Jackie Chan get his kicks?
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ Jackie Chan is conducting a tour of his
broken bones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, three times,'' he says, pointing to his bumpy, pug nose.
``Many teeth, gone,'' he says, touching his chin. ``The shoulder,
the bone comes out.'' He extends his long, but gnarled fingers,
saying, ``Broken, broken, broken,'' as if it were a children's
counting game. ``There, broken,'' he says, gesturing to his right
leg. ``Toes broken and ankle twisted and broken.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely there must be an easier way to make a living. But Chan _
the short, compactly built star of such Hong Kong chop-socky
tumbles as ``Rumble in the Bronx,'' ``Operation Condor'' and ``Mr.
Nice Guy'' _ wouldn't consider it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to show off,'' he says softly during an interview at a
Fort Lauderdale hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Chan, 44, originally named Chan Kong-sang, which means ``Born in
Hong Kong,'' devises and executes all of the daredevil,
gravity-defying and occasionally bone-fracturing action sequences
that have made him Asia's No. 1 box office attraction. And when his
movies get dubbed into English, they bring in additional millions
over here.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with a new as-told-to autobiography, ``I Am Jackie Chan: My
Life in Action,'' and his first leading role in a U.S. studio
feature _ ``Rush Hour,'' which opens Friday _ Chan is making his
bid for Hollywood stardom.
</P>
<P>
   More than the money, he wants to conquer Hollywood for the sake
of his people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I can retire,'' says the man who commands $4
million per picture. ``Before, when I make a movie, I want to do
something for myself, for my family. To make my father proud. (Now)
I'm going to do something for my Chinese community.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people are talking about movies, I want them to say, `We
have a Spielberg.' I want to be like Spielberg for China. People
will say, `Jackie, he's conquered Hollywood. He's one of the big
stars in Hollywood now.' Then I'll feel satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not Chan's first assault on American movies. In the
early '80s, he appeared in a tepid action film called ``The Big
Brawl'' and, thanks to pal and admirer Burt Reynolds, he was
featured in ``Cannonball Run'' and ``Cannonball Run II.'' Although
Chan already had some 30 Asian films under his martial arts belt by
then, he became frustrated by Hollywood's ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time, nobody listened to me. Everybody thought I was a
new actor,'' he says, rolling his eyes in exasperation. ``I had to
listen to stunt men who worked for only two years, who tell me how
to punch. Now, these days, I can change the stunt men.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Chan remains puzzled by the Hollywood moviemaking
process, and its painstaking emphasis on safety. ``When I'm doing a
stunt, they spend like four hours to make sure a tree doesn't
break.''
</P>
<P>
   Chan is used to self-insuring his Hong Kong movies. Over here,
he has to contend with insurance representatives who have to
approve the stunts and the safeguards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say, `Hurry up, hurry up.' The stunt coordinator says,
`Jackie, don't worry. We have time, we have money. The most
important thing is your life.' In Hong Kong, they say, `OK, set up
the camera. Ready, go!' ''
</P>
<P>
   When he directs movies in Asia, Chan works quickly, often
putting in much longer days than American unions allow. In
Hollywood, it is hurry-up-and-wait-in-your-trailer, but Chan uses
the down time to practice his English.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the most important for me,'' he says, with a distinct,
but halting delivery. ``Everybody on the set is fooling around _
ha, ha, ha. Me? I'm in the trailer, working on the dialogue all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, Chan's fans wouldn't care if he fumbled his lines
as long as he kept performing those acrobatic stunts. But he
wonders how long he can keep doing that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I come to Hollywood now,'' Chan explains. ``Besides
making a movie, I want to learn something from Hollywood _ computer
graphics, special effects. When I retire, I want to be an action
director in Hollywood. To teach people how to make my kind of
action, but with special effects.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a logical career progression. Chan's amazing physical
agility _ and some would add his foolhardiness _ began at the age
of 6 1/2, when his cook and cleaning woman parents sent him off to
the Chinese Opera Research Institute for 10 years. He learned
singing, dancing, acting, acrobatics, sword fighting and kung fu,
all under a system of deprivation and corporal punishment that has
been described as Dickensian.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he left school, the opera's popularity had waned,
but Chan found his skills were needed in the Hong Kong movie mill.
He moved up from stuntman to fight choreographer to supporting
roles, playing a villain in kung fu king Bruce Lee's ``Enter the
Dragon.'' When Lee died suddenly in 1973, Chan was tapped as his
successor. Yet it was not until he was allowed to inject movies
with his comic flair _ taking pratfalls and wincing in pain after
throwing punches _ that he rose to stardom.
</P>
<P>
   Chan's Asian fans are known to be fanatical about him. So he is
wary of talking about his personal life, including his 14-year,
on-off marriage to Taiwanese actress Lin Fung-chiao and his
13-year-old son Chen Zuming. In 1985, when he mentioned that he was
dating, a Japanese girl committed suicide. A year later, when
another female fan proposed to him and he turned her down, she
drank a vial of poison. It's not easy being an Asian superstar.
</P>
<P>
   Or to cross over to Hollywood stardom. Chan's latest Asian
movie, ``Who Am I?,'' in which he plays an amnesiac cop tracking
diamond smugglers, was so popular in Singapore it outperformed
``Titanic'' at the box office. In the United States, however, it is
expected to be dumped onto HBO.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different culture,'' says Chan with a mystified shrug.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Rush Hour,'' Chan plays a Hong Kong detective who flies to
Los Angeles to help nab the kidnappers of the Chinese consul's
daughter. He teams up with Chris Tucker, a loose cannon cop
assigned to keep Chan's character out of the way. It's a familiar
antagonistic buddies formula, so geared to American tastes that
Chan doubts it will be popular in Hong Kong. ``We don't like movies
with too much dialogue,'' he notes.
</P>
<P>
   With the release of ``Rush Hour,'' Chan is cautiously, even
nervously, awaiting his American future. ``I tell my manager . . .
if `Rush Hour' is good, everything will be good.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
