<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-DRINKING18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FSU given money to combat binge drinking
 &HT;    By Charles Elmore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASEE, Fla. _ Florida State University, named America's No.
1 party school two years ago, announced recently it will receive up
to $750,000 in grants to combat binge drinking.
</P>
<P>
   FSU and nine other schools, including Nebraska, LSU and Georgia
Tech, are eligible for grants totaling $10 million from the Robert
Wood Johnson Foundation, group that supports public health efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the money likely will be used for advertising to counter
heavy marketing by local bars, similar to what's going on with
anti-tobacco advertising in the state, school officials said.
</P>
<P>
   FSU officials said they did not know if they received the money
because of the recent party-school crown conferred by the Princeton
Review, based on student surveys and statistics such as the
freshman dropout rate. FSU slipped to No. 3 in the survey last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wonder about why we get grants,'' said Jon Dalton, FSU vice
president for student affairs. ``I do think Florida State's visible
as a high-profile university, not simply a party school.''
</P>
<P>
   One part of FSU's plan probably will be training beverage
servers when to cut off drinks to people already intoxicated, and
how better to avoid serving underage drinkers. Details will be
worked out by a group including university officials, students,
police and city leaders.
</P>
<P>
   FSU banned open fraternity parties last year. But binge drinking
is still more prevalent in Tallahassee than at the average U.S.
university, a 1997 Harvard survey shows.
</P>
<P>
   The survey defined binge drinking as five drinks in a row during
the past two weeks for men, and four drinks in a row for women.
Nationally, 42 percent of college students acknowledged binge
drinking. At FSU, it was 47 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Just over half, or 52 percent, of college students nationally
said the main reason they drink is to get drunk. The number at FSU
was 61 percent.
</P>
<P>
   School officials are looking closely at bars near campus _
particularly specials for free drinks or 99-cent cocktails on
certain days of the week. The bars say they welcome the program if
it does not go too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we start restricting normal business competition, such as
saying you can't have specials or happy hour, that's a lot of tax
revenues lost to the city,'' said Steve Bailey, general manager of
Bullwinkle's Tavern in Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Moreli, a 22-year-old FSU student with feet up and sipping a
beer on a bar porch near campus Wednesday afternoon, questioned
whether it was case of overreaction. He said students at Florida
State are not really much different at other large schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are they going to do with all that money?'' Morelli said.
``The more restrictions you put on something, in spite of that,
people are going to want to do it that much more.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
