A0137 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DNA-WOODS18-COX     09-17 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNA-WOODS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Detectives refused to let case go
 &HT;    By Laylan Copelin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Fourteen years ago, Austin police Detective
David Parkinson had to release murder suspect Richard Alan Woods
because he didn't have the physical evidence to link him to the
abduction, rape and slaying of a 21-year-old Austin woman.
</P>
<P>
   But Parkinson, who initially investigated the 1984 murder of
Lauren Marie McCarty, stayed in touch with Woods. At first, they
talked almost daily. Woods' phone calls to Parkinson's house were
so routine that the officer's children would simply say, ``Daddy,
it's Richard.''
</P>
<P>
   They would talk for hours. Woods would invite Parkinson to visit
him at his South Austin apartment where he lived with his mother _
but he warned him always to come alone. Woods didn't like most
cops. Detectives would wait in the parking lot as their colleague
played a cat-and-mouse game with the street-smart Woods. At times,
Parkinson said, Woods was almost confessional.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought he wanted to tell me,'' Parkinson said. ``He
was just showing us that he was in control of the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   This week's arrest of Woods is being hailed as a testament to
the wonders of DNA testing. Technology finally advanced so that
police said they now can match hair, blood and saliva samples taken
from Woods 14 years ago with a minuscule amount of physical
evidence _ no more than a pinpoint _ from the murder scene. Yet
this week's arrest also is the culmination of a tale of two
detectives, Parkinson, now a lieutenant, and Sgt. Paul Johnson, who
wouldn't let go of the case even as Woods played games with the
minds and emotions of investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he had any sympathy for his victims,'' Johnson
said Wednesday. ``He may have felt the need to brag _ but not to
clear his conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarty's abduction just a week before Christmas 1984 stunned
the city. She had left work at the Texas Municipal Court Training
Center at 812 San Antonio St. to mail some letters and eat a late
lunch, police said. Officers believed she made it to the post
office, but they could not trace her from there. For six days, the
police and McCarty's family searched but found nothing. Finally, an
officer spotted her car behind Westgate Shopping Center. Her body,
bludgeoned and stabbed, was in the trunk. She was wearing only her
lavender T-shirt, and her hands were bound.
</P>
<P>
   The police quickly targeted Woods, a former mental patient with
a violent past, as their primary suspectafter two women said they
saw a man who looked like Woods in the parking lot of McCarty's
office. Other witnesses said Woods had told them that he had
committed ``five felonies in one,'' without ever saying what he
did.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks after the slaying, police questioned Woods but had
to let him go. Investigators hoped to match samples, especially
blood, from McCarty's car and body with the hair, blood and saliva
taken from Woods. The tests _ rudimentary by today's standards _
could not make a match, especially because McCarty had been dead
for six days. The police were left with a circumstantial case with
no physical evidence tying Woods to McCarty or to her car.
</P>
<P>
   They had to let him walk.
</P>
<P>
   The police were convinced that they were in a deadly race with
time before Woods would be charged in another crime. They lost the
race in 1986 _ just a little more than a year after McCarty's death
_ when Woods was convicted of the sexual assault of a woman. He was
sentenced to 15 years in prison. From prison, Woods stayed in touch
with Parkinson, writing him frequently.
</P>
<P>
   That same year Parkinson transferred from homicide, but he
returned in 1992 as a homicide lieutenant. Austin police, however,
never closed the McCarty file. As is common procedure, the unsolved
homicide case was handed off several times as new detectives
rotated into the division.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Johnson inherited the case. There was a greater sense
of urgency than ever before because Johnson knew Woods would soon
be released on parole. Yet the detective had nothing new to go on.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many years go by, and it's unlikely you'll find new
witnesses or new physical evidence,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   But he found a notation in the file that gave him hope.
</P>
<P>
   Four years earlier, in 1993, a detective had the state crime lab
try again to match Woods' hair, blood and saliva samples to the
evidence from the crime scene. The technology had improved enough
that the scientists found microscopic evidence from someone other
than the victim. But it had not improved enough to link it to
Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson first phoned the state lab a year ago to see whether the
technology had advanced to the point that the link from a pinpoint
of evidence could be made. Not yet, he was told. Perhaps in a few
months.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Johnson transferred from the homicide division this
year, he kept calling the lab. ``I had started it,'' Johnson said.
``I wanted to finish it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Woods was released from prison this year, first to a
halfway house in El Paso, then to one in Austin. When he came to
the Police Department to register as a sex offender, as required by
law, he asked to see Parkinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We visited for about three hours,'' Parkinson said. Woods
continued to tease his investigator. ``He almost told me, then
said, `I've got to go away and think about it,''' Parkinson said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Unknown to Woods, time was running out. The state had purchased
10 new genetic analyzers, at a cost of $780,000, that could
decipher DNA from the minuscule amount of decayed material. DNA _
deoxyribonucleic acid _ is an essential ingredient in human cells.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a state lab technician paged Johnson, now working as
a street detective. The test matched Woods to the evidence. There
is a 1-in-16,000 chance that the samples could match anyone else,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt terrific,'' Johnson said. ``You get your hopes up that
maybe, after all these years, you can do something.''
</P>
<P>
   But where to find Woods, who had been released from the halfway
house? The police found him nearby: in jail, charged this month
with an aggravated robbery of a woman in Zilker Park.
</P>
<P>
   After 14 years, the low-key Parkinson was surprised by the
melancholy he felt. ``You expect to feel happy, and you do,'' he
said. ``But all you can remember is a poor girl who died.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-09-17-98 0003E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
