<HEADER>
A0138 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWERBOAT-FOREMAN18-C     09-17 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWERBOAT-FOREMAN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A winner by design
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It's no accident that Roddy Foreman is having
his best year in power boat racing, capturing another national
championship recently. But an accident last year, the most
frightening one of his 17 years of racing, helped make his current
dream season possible.
</P>
<P>
   Foreman, an architect of network design and messaging systems
for IBM, races power boats in the SST-60 class. The boats aren't as
big and bad as Miss Budweiser and other roostertail-spewing
monsters in the unlimited hydroplane class, but SST-60 boats can
still have their 800 pounds whipped over the water at speeds in
excess of 100 mph by their 170-horsepower motors.
</P>
<P>
   Foreman said that in the course of his racing career he has had
his boat blown over backwards and done some barrel rolls. But in
the very first event last year, his boat apparently hit something,
suffered a puncture and then went violently out of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly it just spun and flipped; it just exploded,'' Foreman
recalled. Although he wasn't hurt too badly, the boat was lost. A
six-time national champion and former world champion, Foreman had
his worst season as he missed events while trying to find another
boat.
</P>
<P>
   A friend, Kevin Beaulier, designed a new boat for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cockpit is offset to the left, and the boat turns on a
dime,'' Foreman said. ``We feel we have an advantage. We've been
able to dominate.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreman's new boat has become the talk of the circuit as he's
won nine of the 11 races he has entered this year. He said that
several competitors have already tried to come up with something
similar, but haven't yet been able to match its performance. Once,
he said, when the boat was left unattended out of the water, he
returned to find someone underneath it going over it with a tape
measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are pretty competitive,'' Foreman said. ``We try to
keep the boat covered and under lock and key.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to having the best boat on the water, Foreman said,
``I think my experience helps. My driving has improved every year.
I think it was Dale Earnhardt who said you learn something every
race.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weekends ago, in Kankakee, Ill., Foreman won another
national championship. This past weekend in Clarksville, Tenn., he
finished second in what is the next-to-last event of the season for
him. He's already wrapped up the point championships for both the
American Performance Racing Series and the American Power Boat
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Foreman said, ``It's been a dream of mine to accomplish what
I've done this year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
