<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAILSEND18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Travel story on Trail's End, Minnesota
 &HT;    By Chris Riemenschneider
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRAIL'S END, Minn. _ It's abundantly clear paddling into the
Boundary Waters Canoe Area Wilderness that the name refers to more
than just the border between the United States and Canada. This is
the boundary line past which superfluous things like money and cars
and TV Guide don't matter _ or even are usable. What's needed
instead is a desire for serenity and the hope of setting aside
``real life,'' as if it gets any more real than this.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a light canoe helps in that quest, as we found out
the hard way.
</P>
<P>
   This wilderness encompasses more than one million acres of
glacial waterways and thick, Crayola-green forest near where Lake
Superior ends and Minnesota's land of 10,000 other lakes begins.
It's an unspoiled land, the kind you see in old Hamm's Beer signs
(''From the land of sky blue waters'') and history films on
explorers looking for a passageway west.
</P>
<P>
   Two hundred years after the first explorers arrived, the canoe _
man's original sport utility vehicle _ is still the only way to get
around in the Boundary Waters. There are 12,000 miles of canoe
routes within its boundaries, but no roads. Hiking trails are few
and far between. Motorboats aren't allowed, though the lack of
roads would contain them on the outermost lakes anyway.
</P>
<P>
   There's even a law limiting airplanes from flying overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, it's a wild place and has the wildlife to prove it.
Moose, timber wolves, black bears, bald eagles and beavers reside
in this rocky, glacier-scraped land. The most prevalent creature,
however, is the operatic loon, which is to Minnesotans what an
armadillo is to Texans. The peaceful, high-pitched calls these
red-eyed, black- and-white-speckled ducks regularly make are the
stuff of Zen nature tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Having grown up in Minnesota, I knew the deep, inner pull of the
Boundary Waters by the time I was 13. Years later _ 11since I had
last been there and 10 since I moved to Texas and found out the
unnatural dullness that is a manmade lake _ I let the placid,
unbridled appeal of the Boundary Waters pull me in once more.
</P>
<P>
   Four of us, including my dad, brother and a friend from Austin
who had never been in a canoe, were going in for four nights. Some
visitors do two-nighters. Some do two-monthers. Theoretically,
excluding a few minor obstacles such as winter and hunger, a
paddler could start at one of the Boundary Waters' 86 entry points
and keep paddling for a year without seeing the same lake twice.
</P>
<P>
   Four nights and 20 of the 1,100 lakes were enough for us,
though, and we made the reservations that would solidify that plan.
</P>
<P>
   Reservations are required for each entry point to prevent
overcrowding and to ensure that campsites will be available for
everyone. The most popular entries generally fill up months in
advance, so the policy requires that you plan ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The entire nature of the Boundary Waters calls for planning,
though. Before you leave, you've got to figure out the food
situation: ``Let' s see, if we have freeze-dried spaghetti on
Tuesday, will we want the dehydrated chicken teriyaki on
Wednesday?'' Then comes packing, which requires waterproofing
everything, as well as finding a bag for the food that can be hung
between two trees at night so bears can't get to it. Many
wilderness outfitters in northern Minnesota have guide services
that will take care of all of this for you, but, of course, you pay
a lot for what could otherwise be an inexpensive vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Having borrowed one canoe _ an aluminum one _ we got up at 5
a.m. and left the Twin Cities for our destination near Trail's End,
about 15 miles from the Canadian border. After the breathtaking
drive along Lake Superior's North Shore and up the historic
Gunflint Trail, made of logging roads and trails carved by 18th-
and 19th-century French trappers, we said goodbye to the Blazer. A
nearby outfitter, which had dropped off a second aluminum canoe at
our first lake, charged $20 a day for the Alumacraft. The extra $15
a day a lighter Kevlar model would have cost us seemed like a fee
for wimps in this rugged land.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what we thought until our first portage.
</P>
<P>
   Portages are the pesky stretches of land that get in the way of
your paddling and require you to carry your canoes and equipment.
The most popular routes are generally the ones with the least
and/or smallest of these paths, but we chose our paddling loop
based on scenery. The only time we regretted this decision was when
we were grunting and puffing with a canoe resting on our shoulders,
like turtles clumsily carrying their shells made of aluminum.
</P>
<P>
   On the first day, that occurred often. First, we had a 3/4-mile
portage between Round and Missing Link lakes. Soon after, came the
1 1/2-miles portage to Tuscarora _ the longest on our trip, which
took us about two hours. Two long hours.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard work, but as we learned when we pulled up to our
remote, picturesque campsite, the portages were worth it.
</P>
<P>
   The Boundary Waters campsites are dutifully designed. Each comes
with a fire grate surrounded by chairs (OK, they're just logs you
sit on), two or three flat spots for tents, and the obligatory
latrine, which amounts to a hole in the ground covered by a plastic
or wood box. Hey, it works.
</P>
<P>
   The campsites, like the portages, are noted on the must-buy
Boundary Waters topographical maps (available at ranger stations
and outfitting stores). The sites are first-come, first-serve,
which meant we missed out on the island spot we wanted on Tuscarora
Lake but landed one nearby on a point that was just as scenic. The
thing you eventually learn in the Boundary Waters is that no matter
the entry point, lake or campsite where you end up , it's all good.
Each camping spot, for instance, is set up out of sight and earshot
from all others, so it appears you have the lake to yourself.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly how we felt that first night as the sun set,
offering colors thought only possible on canvas or in Technicolor.
We dipped our sweaty bodies into the lake water, clean enough to
drink (though we, like many, used a filter-pump to be safe) and
cool enough to feel it deep down inside. For certain latitude
reasons, the western horizon stayed lit until past 10 that night,
and we savored every minute of it.
</P>
<P>
   Here, you have to take nature as it comes, which meant that
instead of the Northern Lights we had hoped to see after nightfall,
we got swarms of mosquitos. Throughout the trip, even after we
coated ourselves with mysteriously strong bug spray that my dad
proudly boasted was taken off the market, the mosquitos and the
biting black flies continued to bother us. If they weren't biting
us, they were flying in our mouths every time we tried to complain
about them. We were told it was an especially bad year, but the
bugs are always something to prepare for when headed to the
Boundary Waters.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, we woke up and tried to get something besides
the bugs to bite: preferably the tasty walleye. Other common fish
in the Boundary Waters include small-mouth bass, lake trout and
northern pike (just ``northerns'' to northerners). After finding a
still, hidden pond connected to Tuscarora Lake by a small channel,
we cast. Eventually, Fisherman Dad was the only one who got lucky,
reeling in a three- pound northern. Satisfied we had some fillets
for dinner, we headed to our next campsite.
</P>
<P>
   We spent the next two nights on Gillis Lake, taking more time to
fish and go on a day-trip. That meant paddling without all the
equipment. It also meant we were able to cover about 16 gorgeous
miles in one day, taking in the rather large and island-strewn
Little Saganaga Lake (you should see the big Saganaga) and spotting
a nervous moose calf, a nesting bald eagle and one working beaver
in the same outing. Despite a couple more hours of fishing, we only
caught one more northern. It was good enough to spice up the
freeze-dried dinner, but the real treat was the hours spent
floating from lake to lake, like wanderers without a purpose.
</P>
<P>
   By the final night, we had a purpose: to get beer. After a long
haul completing our loop, which meant crossing a total of eight,
mostly short portages and nine small lakes, we returned to our
starting point, near our beer-packed Blazer, and camped nearby.
</P>
<P>
   While still beautiful, this final night was too much like a
typical camping experience. Gone was the feeling of total
isolation, the equal parts thrill and uneasiness that the nearest
phone _ heck, the nearest buzz of electricity _ was at least 20
miles away by canoe, and that you were ruled by the water.
</P>
<P>
   If there's a place that offers more solitude and beauty in the
lower 48 states, take me there. And then strap a canoe to my back,
because I'm convinced paddling is the best way to be carried into
wild territory, carried across that boundary.
</P>
<P>
   Next time I go, though, I'm going to seriously think about the
lighter canoes. IF YOU GO: WHAT: Boundary Waters Canoe Area
Wilderness reservations: A must. Call (800) 745-3399. Check permit
availability at www.bwrc.com. GETTING THERE: Northwest Airlines and
several other carriers offer flights into Minneapolis/St. Paul and
Duluth. From the Twin Cities, most Boundary Waters' entry points
are four to five hours by car. From Duluth, most are one to two
hours away. WHEN TO GO: June-August is warm enough for shorts and
swimming. The tradeoff in April-May or September-October is that
the bugs aren' t around. Winter months are for (brave)
cross-country skiers only. WHERE TO GO: With 86 entry points, the
possibilities are endless. The most popular areas from which to
start are off the Gunflint Trail (Minnesota Highway 12), near the
town of Ely or in the Sawbill Lake area. MORE INFORMATION: The
Gunflint Trail Association, (800) 338-6932 or
www.gunflint-trail.com; Ely Chamber of Commerce, (800) 777-7281 or
www.ely.org; Sawbill Canoe Outfitters, (218) 387-1360 or
www.sawbill.com; Explore Minnesota, (800) 657-3700 or
www.exploreminnesota.com.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Riemenschneider is a staff writer for the Austin
American-Statesman.
</P>
