<HEADER>
A0142 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD18-COX     09-17 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WOODWORKING COLUMN: New book praised by writer
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Taunton Press's coffee table book for this holiday season is
``The Art of Fine Tools,'' by Sandor Nagyszalanczy, and it is a
truly beautiful work from every standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy is perhaps the finest pure writer of all woodworking
authors; he was an editor at Fine Woodworking for a good many years
before packing it in to return to his own shop. He must have had a
wonderful time putting this book together.
</P>
<P>
   At $37 in hardcover, is it scarcely overpriced. Any lover of
fine tools, especially old fine tools, will be hard put to be
without it. The tools shown, all in lovely color, range from
hammers dating to about 55 B.C. to the exquisite miniatures being
made by Phil Hamler in Snellville.
</P>
<P>
   I've got a couple of nice Starett rules, one and two-footers. I
paid a fairly high price for them. They look like a kid's first
measuring stick compared to the 12-inch rule made in 1849 of ivory
with a frieze of mostly mythical figures in gilt copper let into
the side.
</P>
<P>
   In the days when plastic was new, it was all the rage. Perhaps
the most remarkable example of this is a fancily-boxed Bakelite
six-foot tape measure, called, curiously enough, the Lady's Man
pocket tape measure.
</P>
<P>
   There is a collection of dancing master calipers, mostly
shop-made in the 18th and 19th centuries, in the shape of human
legs, sometimes with stockings, garters and boots engraved on them.
</P>
<P>
   An unexpected delight are the axes, often astonishing in form
and beautiful in execution. Among the most remarkable of the latter
is the 18th-century boarding ax, ornately decorated and intended
not for chopping wood but for bloody mayhem in hand-to-hand combat
during the boarding of an enemy ship.
</P>
<P>
   An entire section is devoted to Asian tools. Most of these, of
course, are Japanese, but the most wonderfully ornate are the
Indonesian and Indian planes.
</P>
<P>
   Another section is given over to amazing and even bizarre
mechanical contrivances. There are several pages devoted to the
Holtzapffel ornamental lathe, but more charming are things like the
tool that is, at once, a try square with a bevel gauge, a level, a
marking gauge, a butt gauge and a small rabbet plane.
</P>
<P>
   The most enchanting of all, however, is the section on decorated
tools. here we have planes with carved dragon heads rearing up from
their leading edges. There is everything from the most primitive
but earnest European country chip carving to very sophisticated
carving and inlay. An early French brace has a photograph of a man
let into its head, protected by isinglass.
</P>
<P>
   In the miniature section, there is no work finer than that of
Hamler; indeed, several pages are devoted to his exquisite _ and
very expensive _ work. All of Hamler's miniatures are complete
working models, not mere dummies. Sandy reports that Hamler's 4
1/2-inch model of the complicated Tidey Patent plane, intended to
bevel two edges of a board at once, recently sold at auction for
$27,000.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I could go on and on about this book, but you get the
idea. A very fine Christmas present for any tool freak.
</P>
<P>
   -- E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   We want to hear from you but are unable to acknowledge every
message.
</P>
