 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No 2482 - September 17, 1998  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To publish any of the special ``separate buy'' articles listed
below, it must be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from
one of these New York Times sales representatives:
</P>
<P>
   _ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 33-1-47-42-17-11;
fax, 33-1-47-42-80-44 or 33-1-47-42-18-81. e-mail: nyt &LR; calva.net
</P>
<P>
   _ Mexico, Central America, South America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los
Angeles, 310-996-0075; fax, 310-996-0089.
</P>
<P>
   _ U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas NEWS AND
FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2482 -- Sept. 17, 1998 We are offering the
following articles for sale. Please contact us for availability
your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. BONES PROVIDE EVIDENCE OF TORTURE Many men and women seeking
political asylum claim to have been tortured. But because their
injuries may have been inflicted months, even years earlier, it is
often difficult to confirm their stories with a medical exam or
standard x-ray studies. Sceptical immigration officials, citing the
lack of physical evidence, may reject their asylum requests.
Austrian researchers now report that a bone-imaging technique
called scintigraphy, which is able to detect subtle bone damage,
can be used to corroborate many such claims, even if the beatings
occurred years earlier. By M. McCarthy. The Lancet News Service.
1,000 words 2. DON'T LET DISTASTE ENDANGER THE PRESIDENCY The issue
is no longer Bill Clinton's behaviour and evident character flaws.
It is about governance and constitutional precedent, not so much
the President but the presidency. The paralysis of the White House
sex-and-lies scandal is striking not only the U.S., but all the
countries affected by its role in the world. In the desire to
punish Clinton, should the U.S. and indeed the rest of the world be
punished by distorting or incapacitating the U.S. political system?
By Flora Lewis. 800 words. 3. FOR LEWINSKY, IT WAS ABOUT THE CAREER
LADDER The most striking revelation of the Starr report is the
lurid detail it goes into - not about sex, but about jobs. Large
parts of the report are devoted to Monica Lewinsky's career
pursuits and reveal her ambitious streak. There should be a term
connoting the opposite of sexual harassment : When a person of less
power uses her sexual attractiveness or personal relationship with
a person of greater power to get ahead. By Katie Roiphe. New York
Times Op-Ed. 800 words. 4. IN NURSES' LIVES, A TREASURE TROVE OF
HEALTH DATA More than 20 years ago, a doctor in the U.S., curious
about the effects of long-term oral contraceptive use, sent
questionnaires to 370,000 registered nurses. The answers since
received have turned into the largest and longest study ever of a
group of women. With many of the original participants now entering
their 60s and 70s, the study promises an even greater wealth of
knowledge, much of it otherwise unattainable, about how a lifetime
of choices in food, drink, exercise and medications can translate
into protection from or increased risk of deadly and debilitating
diseases. By Carol Kaesuk Yoon. New York Times Science Times. 2,000
words.
</P>
<P>
   5. START A CONVERSATION AND KEEP IT GOING The tips in this quiz
will help you develop the skill of talking to anyone about
anything. By Valerie Sokolosky. From Spirit magazine. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
PREVENTING MULTIPLE MISCARRIAGE Losing a pregnancy once is
miserable enough, but going through it repeatedly, without a clue
as to why, is sheer emotional torture. Fortunately, doctors are
discovering that multiple miscarriages may be easier to prevent
than was once thought. By Suzanne B. Gleason. From Child magazine.
1,200 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
POPULAR RELEASE OF BUTTERFLIES PUTS TROUBLE IN THE AIR Some brides
and grooms in the U.S. are not showered with traditional rice or
confetti when they leave church -- they are surrounded by hundreds
of butterflies. It is the latest fashion at weddings and sometimes
at memorial services, grand openings, divorces and prison releases.
But while some people may view the release of butterflies as an
uplifting celebration of natural beauty, others see it as a
misguided practice that poses serious risks. By Carol Kaesuk Yoon.
New York Times Science Times. 1,800 words + photo. 8. ASKMARTHA
Lifestyle expert Martha Stewart explains: How to organize a family
photo collection ; How to clean and care for wooden kitchen tools ;
A Brief History of Tapas (the appetizers and snacks commonly served
in Spanish bars and restaurants.) 1,000 words + photo. 9. INFECTED
HEARTS What causes heart disease? Some researchers believe that
infectious bacteria probably play a role in a significant number of
cases. By Josie Glausiusz. From Discover magazine. 1,100 words +
photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 10.
IN THE COUNTRY OF THE BLIND Far from being less good than sighted
people at using sounds rather than sights to map space, some
totally blind people have developed capacities in this respect that
sighted people do not usually have at all. By Eleanor Lawrence.
Nature News Service. 600 words. N/A France and Spain.
_______________________________________________________________
</P>
