A0177 &Cx1f; tad-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV20-C     09-17 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: SUMMER'S FADING STARR
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Sept. 20.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the end, public opinion may decide whether
President Clinton serves out the rest of his term. But, for now,
public opinion is having little impact on the nasty doings here.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of new stuff out there that's still going to
come out,'' Sen. Orrin Hatch told me, even as House Republicans
were tossing more dirt from Ken Starr's deep multimedia pits to a
ravenous press corps.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the Utah Republican had sought to persuade his
friend, the independent counsel, to show up for a CBS ``60
Minutes'' interview in order to counter White House assertions that
Starr was a vindictive creep.
</P>
<P>
   By September, the drama had moved to the point that Clinton's
lawyers were going on TV talk shows to claim they were normal
people, despite their convoluted definitions of Clinton's
extramarital sex life.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not where this sad drama will remain.
</P>
<P>
   All the video screens and all the paper pulp in the world that
gird the pundits' huge daily fix cannot alter the next step: a vote
in early October by the 37-member House Judiciary Committee over
whether to pursue impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The real issue facing the panel's chairman, Rep. Henry Hyde of
Illinois, is how many, if any, of the committee's Democrats would
go along with a request to the full House for authority to open
such a formal review.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, with the political roles reversed, an adroit Democrat,
New Jersey's Peter Rodino, persuaded six Republicans on his
committee to support one of three impeachment counts lodged against
Richard Nixon. At the time, Rodino thought that was the minimum he
needed to spread a bipartisan cloak over those historic events.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde knows he can throw only so much political red meat to the
party's rabid anti-Clinton wing, because major Republican errors of
timing and judgment could ``nationalize'' the November election
over the impeachment issue.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than a rout of dispirited Democrats that's now assumed,
voters could then send Clinton's tormentors (including the media)
another message. If that happens, Rep. John Conyers Jr. of Michigan
would steer the 1999 investigation, in the unlikely event that he
finds anything to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Should Hyde remain at the helm after November, his likely
priority would be to broaden the probe beyond Starr's
lying-about-sex package. Both Hyde and Speaker Newt Gingrich have
told confidants that they won't go before the Senate and prosecute
a case against Clinton on Starr's laundry list alone.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, of course, Clinton's
``I've-been-hired-to-do-this-job'' strategy may also need to be
updated. Should the campaign finance questions that Hyde will want
to examine directly hit a legal artery, then a fresh line of
defense will be required. And should a former Little Rock lawyer
who is married to the president become a criminal target, public
sympathy could turn against the First Couple.
</P>
<P>
   One possible scenario: Clinton makes Al Gore acting president
while he undergoes therapy for clinical depression. Impeachment
proceedings are put on hold. Some weeks later, doctors pronounce
Clinton cured, to the great joy of the people.
</P>
<P>
   Please stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
