A0192 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN20-CO     09-17 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Awash in 'lost' episodes and manuscripts
 &HT;    (For release Sept. 20, 1998)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Late at night, awakened by a dog's bark or a painful indication
from my bladder, I sometimes find it difficult to return to sleep.
To abet slumber, I usually go to the front room and turn to one of
those non-network cable stations to watch reruns of decades-old
sitcoms, those being slightly more sleep-inducing than a West Coast
baseball game.
</P>
<P>
   It is there that I come across what TV syndicators have come to
describe as lost episodes. There are lost episodes of ``The
Honeymooners,'' lost episodes of ``I Love Lucy,'' lost episodes of
just about any timeworn sitcom that markets cheaply for 2 a.m. or
so viewing.
</P>
<P>
   Television is not alone in this gambit. The book publishing and
music industries have long been practicing the art of finding
previously lost or, more likely, discarded efforts by authors and
composers.
</P>
<P>
   Even baseball statistics freaks are getting into the act. This
summer, when a player looked like he might break the existing
runs-batted-in record of Hack Wilson, not one but two ``lost''
runs-batted-in were claimed on his behalf by a surviving member of
Wilson's 1930 team.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, it was announced that Ernest Hemingway's last
unpublished book is going to be published, coincidentally in time
for the 100th anniversary of his birth next July.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the fourth posthumous book by Hemingway, who
committed suicide in 1961, and like others, I wonder if they had
not been published during his lifetime because he did not want them
published. Perhaps he did not think them worthy of publication.
</P>
<P>
   When it was revealed in August that ``True at First Light''
would be published, it was said this really was the last
unpublished Hemingway, the previous last posthumous book being
``The Garden of Eden'' in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   I would find it hard to imagine that Hemingway was working on
all these books at the same time. So, if they were incomplete at
the time of his death, it must have been for a reason. I would
suspect that reason was that Hemingway thought little of his work,
may even have killed himself in despondency over the unfinished
manuscripts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Garden of Eden'' was not a success. No less than
Hemingway's granddaughter Lorian, reviewing ``Eden'' for Rolling
Stone in 1986, wrote that the novel ``is as dead as the man. ... It
is not just bad. It is God-awful.''
</P>
<P>
   Quote and unquote.
</P>
<P>
   As described by the future publishers, ``True at First Light''
was 850 pages long until pared by Hemingway's 70-year-old son
Patrick. Similarly, ``The Garden of Eden'' was 1,500 pages until
the editors got their hands on it.
</P>
<P>
   The drama behind this latest book, a fictionalized account of
one of Hemingway's African safaris, is that the manuscript has been
under seal in two libraries since his widow, Mary, went to Havana
to retrieve it after his death. In the intervening years, according
to the story, only relatives, scholars and publishers have cast
eyes on the manuscript.
</P>
<P>
   When I think of all the tender care Hemingway gave to his ``Old
Man and the Sea,'' the careful massaging of words and sentences
over and over until it was near perfection, I cannot accept that
someone other than Hemingway, son or not, can prune 1,500 of the
master's words into a book worthy of the Ernest Hemingway name.
</P>
<P>
   No one ever had the audacity to finish Gilbert Stuart's portrait
of George Washington, and I don't believe anyone should be messing
with Hemingway's unfinished work.
</P>
<P>
   We've already got too many ``lost'' Hemingways.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
