<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE REVIEWS (Move with an ETA of 4 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-THING _ Review of ``One True Thing,'' with Meryl Streep.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution) and (Austin American-Statesman) and
(Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-RUSH _ Review of ``Rush Hour.'' Jackie Chan. Grade: B.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution) and (Austin American-Statesman) and
(Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-MIDNIGHT _ Review of ``Permanent Midnight.'' Grade: D
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-FOOLS _ ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love.'' (Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-FUNNY _ ``Funny Games.'' German film about two criminals
who kidnap and torture a vacationing family. (Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-SAMURAI _ ``Six-String Samurai.'' Buddy is as skilled
with his guitar as he is with his samurai sword. Thrown together
with a kid whom he saves, the two of them must now escape to Las
Vegas, the rock 'n' roll capital of this future world. (Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   CHAN-BIO _ With a new as-told-to autobiography, ``I Am Jackie
Chan: My Life in Action,'' and his first leading role in a U.S.
studio feature _ ``Rush Hour,'' which opens Friday _ Chan is making
his bid for Hollywood stardom. (Erstein, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-SYMPHONY _ WASHINGTON _ When National Symphony
Orchestra conductor Leonard Slatkin decided to focus on Beethoven's
choral work for his second Beethoven festival, who would he call
but Atlanta's own Robert Shaw? Pegged to this weekend's (Sept.
17-19) Kennedy Center performances, we observe the 82-year-old
cultural institution at work. We'll catch final ``Missa Solemnis''
performance and watch Shaw prepare a new chorus for this weekend's
performances. Also hanging out in his dressing room and talking to
him at his suite at the Watergate. (Brock, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTO. ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   MORRISON-SOUTH _ Toni Morrison will read from ``Paradise'' at
the Georgia State University conference on Toni Morrison and the
South. Brief interview with Carolyn Denard, organizer of the event,
about how the South _ of all places _ has influenced the Ohio
writer's Nobel-winning work. (Warmbold, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TV-SURFER _ Fox's ``The Simpsons'' and CBS's ``Touched By An
Angel'' start their new seasons on Sunday; CNN to start youth (high
school-college) program that has potential of having their work
air. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   SIBLEY-COLUMN _ If you or any of your relatives took pictures at
the ``Gone With the Wind'' premiere in December 1939, Herb Bridges
wants to hear from you. He's putting together a book about the
premiere, to be published in 1999. (Sibley, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-LANG _ Day 4 of the New York Fashion Scene. Designers:
Helmut Lang (1 p.m.); Searle ( 2:30 p.m.); Violet (4 p.m.) (Walton,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ The Taunton Press's coffee table book for this
holiday season is ``The Art of Fine Tools,'' by Sandor
Nagyszalanczy, and it is a truly beautiful work from every
standpoint. Sandy is perhaps the finest pure writer of all
woodworking authors. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-DRINKING _ TALLAHASEE _ Florida State University, named
America's No. 1 party school two years ago, announced recently it
will receive up to $750,000 in grants to combat binge drinking. FSU
and nine other schools, including Nebraska, LSU and Georgia Tech,
are eligible for grants totaling $10 million from the Robert Wood
Johnson Foundation, group that supports public health efforts.
(Elmore, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   SCANDINAVIA _ OSLO, Norway _ On balance, we visit Scandinavia
for the pretty scenery and the pretty people. Yet Scandinavia
deserves an extended stay. Because these countries were spared the
full brunt of modern wars, their physical pasts remain remarkably
intact. Thus, the culturally curious visitor should make special
efforts to visit some small historical or art museums in the cities
of Oslo, Bergen, Stockholm and Copenhagen. (Barnes, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA _ SAN FRANCISCO _ The descriptive term
``breathtaking'' is overused. Admit it, we all hate it. The canopy
of trees was breathtaking. Her beauty was breathtaking. The new
Mazda is breathtaking. Nonetheless, I'm traveling north on the
Pacific Coast Highway through Big Sur and I can't think of any
other word to describe the cragged cliffs, the crushing sea as it
meets the rocks. (Kallenberg, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Montreal offers a pleasant mix of European and
American sensibilities and features. With its museums, first-class
shops and ethnic neighborhoods, it does resemble a cleaner, smaller
New York. And because of its French heritage and largely
French-speaking population, Montreal does have a European flair.
(Breyer/Seaborn, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-YOGA _ NASSAU, Bahamas _ The boom of a gong pierced the
silence of the night promptly at 5:30 a.m., which is mighty early
on Paradise Island. This is the time to go to bed after a night at
the casinos and bars, not to get up to meditate and to do yoga
positions that turn your body into a pretzel. Do people really want
to do this on vacation? (Blackerby, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TRAILSEND _ TRAIL'S END, Minn. _ It's clear paddling into the
Boundary Waters Canoe Area Wilderness that the name refers to more
than just the border between the United States and Canada. This is
the boundary line past which superfluous things like money and cars
and TV Guide don't matter _ or even are usable. Of course, a light
canoe helps in that quest, as we found out the hard way.
(Riemenschneider, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KINGSVILLE-TX _ The getaway just keeps getting better, as the
Youngs take B-Bar-B in Kingsville, Texas, from its beginnings as a
hunting lodge into a year-round resort stop for hunters, birders,
tourists and adults just wanting to hide out in comfort for a few
days. (Leggett, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   PHYSICAL-EXAMS _ The annual physical has become more than just
checking for blood pressure and heart condition. There is a growing
list of tests directed at a specific age. When should one have a
colon screen? What about the frequency of complete blood workups
and what does ``complete'' mean. (Martin, Austin
American-Statesman) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   DNA-OLDSLAYING _ AUSTIN, Texas _ This week's arrest of a suspect
in a murder many years old is being hailed as a testament to the
wonders of DNA testing. Yet this week's arrest also is the
culmination of a tale of two detectives, Parkinson, now a
lieutenant, and Sgt. Paul Johnson, who wouldn't let go of the case
even as Woods played games with the minds and emotions of
investigators. (Copelin, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
