</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980917.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0229 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTLAND-SCOTCH-$ADV2     09-17 1695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTLAND-SCOTCH-$ADV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SINGLE MALT SCOTCH INDUSTRY SHRINKING, DESPITE GROWTH IN DEMAND
 &HT;    With SCOTCH-MALT-$ADV20.
 &HT;    With photos and graphic to be placed in the International folder
on the Cox Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Sept. 20 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENLIVET, Scotland _ Standing on the grassy bank, Robbie Hughes
casts a stainless steel canister into the still, clear water.
</P>
<P>
   Dapples of sunlight break through the 100-foot trees around the
pool, which holds water from four springs that come up through the
rocks up the side of the steep hill. From time to time, a trout
will break the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Tugging on a white cord, Hughes reels in the full canister and
places it on top of a cabinet built of stone and lumber. He opens
the cabinet and finds three small glasses and sets them out on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the finest bar in the whole world,'' Hughes, 32, tells
a pair of visitors who offer no arguments. He pours the cold,
crystalline water into the glasses. ``Taste that,'' he says,
reaching again into a cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   He uncorks a bottle of 10-year-old Tormore single malt scotch
and pours two fingers worth of the pale, golden whisky in each
glass. ``Now,'' he says, ``taste this.''
</P>
<P>
   When sampled this way, one right after the other, the connection
between the water of this unique burn and the drink it yields is
unmistakable.
</P>
<P>
   However, this is perhaps the only place on Earth where Tormore
is still served. The brand has fallen victim to the realities of
doing business in the booming single malt trade.
</P>
<P>
   The distillery's owner, Allied Distillers Ltd., whose parent
firm also owns Dunkin' Donuts and Baskin-Robbins, has dropped
Tormore as an independent brand and intends instead to use it in
its blended whiskies, merging its distinctive flavors with others.
</P>
<P>
   A surge in single malt price, demand
</P>
<P>
   A novelty in the United States just a few years ago, single malt
scotch well may be the drink of the '90s. While sales of spirits --
including blended scotches -- have been generally flat in recent
years, single malts have surged.
</P>
<P>
   In the years between 1992 and 1997, U.S. sales more than doubled
from 4.3 million bottles to 8.7 million bottles, according to the
Edinburgh, Scotland-based Scotch Whisky Association. Last year
alone, U.S. sales jumped 14 percent making single malt scotch the
fastest growing category of liquor. Americans consumed nearly 20
percent of the single malt scotch sold worldwide
</P>
<P>
   Its prices range from $30 to $100 in stores, making it well in
to the high end of liquors. Prices can reach dizzying heights.
Christie's Scotland auction house holds regular sales, with vintage
malts going for $1,000 to $10,000 a bottle. The magazine Malt
Advocate reported that a Japanese tourist recently paid about
$16,000 for a bottle of 60-year-old Macallan from a specialty shop
at London's Heathrow Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, two men were arrested on charges of trying to
scam investors eager to get into the hot market. Using a
Gibraltar-based company, Hamilton Spirit Management, the men sold
shares in little-known single malt brands at $1,600 to $5,000 with
promises of returns of 18 percent a year when the brands took off.
The scotches were of little value, yet the men still managed to
take in more than $11 million from investors.
</P>
<P>
   Evan Campbell, a spokesman for the Scotch Whisky Association,
believes the increased demand in scotch whisky is partly cultural
-- people are looking for new experiences -- and partly smart
marketing of a fine product.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a bit of a backlash to the '80s,'' Campbell said.
``People have decided in the '90s that it's OK to consume spirits
in moderation, and they're looking for a good quality drink. At the
same time, malt is becoming more available to them.''
</P>
<P>
   To promote their brands, single malt makers are employing the
techniques of California vineyards. They want people to sample the
products firsthand and learn enough to know what it is they are
tasting. Single malt aficionados seem to travel in the same social
tribes that seek out expensive cigars, wines and cognacs.
</P>
<P>
   Bars and restaurants offer scotch tastings and lectures on the
complexities and variations of single malts, which vary
dramatically in flavors from a powerful iodine sting to a honey
richness. Cultivated wine drinkers tend to appreciate the nuances
and individuality of single malts, finding a certain fascination in
regional influences on both.
</P>
<P>
   Appropriate for the drink of the '90s, the scotch industry has
had a wave of mergers and acquisitions, involving huge players such
as Seagram, United Distillers and Allied Distillers.
</P>
<P>
   More than 150 brands are now produced, but the number is being
reduced as corporate managers seek efficiencies in their marketing
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is a natural product of market forces, Campbell said.
``In some cases, they are deciding to put their marketing efforts
behind a single, or fewer brands rather than across the board,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, fine brands such as Tormore and Dallas Dhu now exist
only in storage and on a few shelves, making scotch drinkers fret
about the future.
</P>
<P>
   One whisky store in Dufftown, the heart of the Speyside whisky
country, offers more than 100 brands, but the store owner lamented
the other day that 26 were no longer in production.
</P>
<P>
   Searching the shelves for lost brands, Robert Burns -- an
Aberdeen salesman and whisky lover, not the poet -- expressed a
common worry: ``I just hope that I don't live to see the day when
they take the individuality out of what is the world's most
individualistic drink.''
</P>
<P>
   A product of its environment: It's the water, stupid!
</P>
<P>
   While some spirits can be made virtually anywhere -- vodka and
gin for example -- single malts are products of their environments.
Each represents a place.
</P>
<P>
   And what places. There are four major Scotch producing regions:
The Lowlands, The Highlands, Campbelltown and the Isle of Islay.
</P>
<P>
   The highest concentration of distilleries is in the Highland
district known as Speyside, so named because the River Spey snakes
through it. The water in Speyside has attracted scores of
distillers over the past 200 years. It falls on the hills and
filters through the rocks and soil, giving it a peaty taste that
remains with the scotch. Speyside whiskies have come to be known as
the ``premier grand cru'' of single malts, and there is growing
demand for those aged more than 25 to 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   It is an area of rare, sometimes eerie natural beauty, with
broad emerald glens surrounded by hills that in late summer are
sided by patchworks of deep violet heather. Looking from narrow
roads like tiny cotton puffs, sheep graze on the hillsides. Here
and there are stone farmhouses and barns, occasionally the ruins of
an ancient church or castle. Everywhere there is water, from rivers
with names such as the Livet and the Fiddich.
</P>
<P>
   It is a place to be explored -- languidly -- by car. Many
distilleries offer tours or at least tolerate visitors.
Glennfiddich has an elaborate gift shop and tourist complex at its
honey-and-gray stone distillery house with the pagoda-shaped roof
that is common among distilleries. Glennfiddich, one of the few
family owned brands, is a pioneer in the business; in 1963, the
company was the first to export its single malt. The conventional
wisdom at the time was that it was too powerful for tastebuds owned
by anyone but a Scot.
</P>
<P>
   The attempt at whisky-related tourism here is thankfully minimal
but there are many other reasons to visit, not the least of which
is its charm and serenity.
</P>
<P>
   This is what lured Brett and Christine Holmes to buy the Minmore
house, an elegant country estate bed and breakfast that is said to
have been the residence of the founder of the Glenlivet distillery
next door.
</P>
<P>
   Minmore House gets some traffic in guests on the Scotch Whisky
Trail, a route marked along the winding roads that work between
glen and burn, but most of the business comes from hunters and
fishermen, for whom this must be some kind of heaven. A log in the
hotel's lobby lists accounts by guests of landing large trout and
15-pound salmon in the River Avon.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent visit, its guests were obviously well-to-do older
couples from England and Edinburgh and Aberdeen. Holmes offers his
guests a handsome array of Speyside scotches in his bar, with its
large front window overlooking an expanse of meadows.
</P>
<P>
   The guests joked in the bar that one of their aims is to sample
each scotch at least once -- with the goal of testing them all
before consolidation in the industry leaves the world with only one
single malt scotch.
</P>
<P>
   Single malt's disappearing act
</P>
<P>
   Robbie Hughes lives in a house that sits in a row that once was
a sort of commune for the distillery workers. He is the only
Tormore employee who lives there, with his other 10 co-workers
commuting in from surrounding villages.
</P>
<P>
   The distillery remains one of the most elegant in Speyside, with
pristine white buildings, decorative dormer windows, a belfry and
musical clock with a curving lake in the front surrounded by
sculpted topiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Built during a scotch boom in 1958, it was the first completely
new malt distillery to be built in the highlands this century.
``They built it here by this wee burn, the Achvochkie,'' Hughes
says as he leads some visitors up the hill to the natural spring
pool.
</P>
<P>
   While Tormore no longer exists as an independent brand, Allied,
which also produces Ballantine, Scapa and Laphroig, has given no
indication that it will close the distillery.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Hughes worries that this and other unique shades of malt
are disappearing all too quickly just as the market, particularly
the American market, is finding the joy of variety.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't think it was 'in your face' enough, so they
decided not to keep it around,'' Hughes says, taking a last
mournful sip by the pool. ``It's a crying shame, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
