<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTCH-MALT-$ADV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE MAKING OF SINGLE MALT: SO SIMPLE, IT'S SPECIAL
 &HT;    With SCOTLAND-SCOTCH-$ADV20.
 &HT;    With photos and graphic to be placed in the International folder
on the Cox Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Sept. 20 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENLIVET, Scotland _ No one knows when distilling began in
Scotland. Ancient Celts using rudimentary stills made a fiery
liquid they called ``uisge beatha;'' the root of the word
``whiskey,'' it means ``water of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the centuries, stills flourished in out of the way places,
and many modern distillers date back to these. Wandering from
distillery to distillery, blwhisky making is a human being.
</P>
<P>
   After decades in the trade, distillers observing the spirit
coming from the stills make their adjustments by checking
temperature and faint changes in the smell and color.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
