<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980917.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0354 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SEASON-COX     09-17 2549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SEASON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    From cop chases to animal attacks, Fox's specials are the
brainchild of the World's Scariest TV execH
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _He's an hour late. New baby, traffic. He calls from
a car phone. ``Be there in 10 minutes!'' Twenty minutes later, he
shows. He's a bit of a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``In September of '96, I remember saying, `Who's the guy in
charge of specials?''' Peter Roth, Fox's entertainment president,
recalls of the first time he met Mike Darnell, the guy in charge of
specials. ``And in walked this 5-foot-2, shaggy, longhaired,
extraordinary guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Darnell, maybe the scariest guy in TV, shows up late this
morning at his office on the Fox studio lot pretty much as Roth
described: 5-foot-2 (more or less), long brown ringlets loafing
around his shoulders, sport coat, black T-shirt, jeans, ostrich
boots. He's 36, looks maybe 26. Seems like he talks a lot faster
than he actually does. That whiff of helium in his voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``You seen the tumor? You gotta see the tumor. We'll show you
the tumor.''
</P>
<P>
   Darnell _ already behind a schedule, he'll stay behind all day _
is excited. He loves, loves this tumor segment that aired on the
premiere of ``Guinness World Records: Primetime'' in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guinness'' is the latest program from Darnell's department,
and the latest entry on a resume some think qualifies Darnell for
the title of World's Scariest TV Specialist _ the guy dinged by
other networks (NBC entertainment chief Don Ohlmeyer calls
Darnell's oeuvre ``snuff TV'') even as they contort themselves to
ape the success of such souped-up Fox specials as ``When Animals
Attack'' (I through IV), ``Magic's Biggest Secrets Revealed'' (I
through III), and, of course, ``World's Scariest Police Chases!''
(I, II, III, IV, V and counting).
</P>
<P>
   If TV has become more like an endless carnival midway, then
Darnell is one of its leading barkers. He's made lowbrow art out of
a hook 'em and hold 'em, get-'em-in-the-tent sensibility that in
the last few years has seeped into programming as wide ranging as
PBS (``Wild Weather Night!'') and network newsmagazines.
</P>
<P>
   Reality programming is hardly a Darnell invention, but he has
helped escalate it into a cultural imperative. In a 70-channel
universe, you better grab people's attention now.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have a hard time having a discussion about specials with
other network executives that does not eventually get to Mike
Darnell,'' says Bob Bane, once Darnell's boss at Fox and now an
independent producer
</P>
<P>
   of specials and events for all the networks. ``They're all
comparing themselves to him _ he's doing so much better than they
are. He's the only one who's rung the bell.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Guinness'' premiere that has Darnell excited this morning
features a segment on the World's Largest Tumor. At 302 pounds, it
is larger than the woman to whom it's attached. It really is an
awesome tumor. And through the miracle of video tape, we watch as
this awesome tumor is surgically removed _ you know, all very
professional, all very, you know, scientific.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have something gross in each episode,'' Darnell
explains of the strategic role in the summer series that has become
such a success that Fox has ordered a full season of episodes (at 9
p.m. Tuesday, the show will feature flesh-eating bacteria). ``Gross
is one of those things people go, `Ooh ...,' but there are no
coalitions out there against gross.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fascinating,'' Darnell adds. ``Some people can't watch
fascinating.''
</P>
<P>
   `Everybody's a fan'
</P>
<P>
   Here is the world's scariest thing about Mike Darnell: He gives
people exactly what they don't want to admit they want. An hour of
nonstop car chases. An hour of nonstop stunt crack-ups. An hour of
animals going haywire. Hours and hours of how a rabbit is pulled
out of a hat; Tonya and Nancy staring grimly at each other from
chairs not 10 yards apart; Mark Furhman hooked up to a lie detector
machine as host Marcia Clark asks if he planted the bloody glove
(the machine backed up his denial).
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I watched `World's Scariest Police Chases,' it
was nonstop police videos, from the first to the last, and I was
left gasping in my seat by the end,'' says Tim Brooks, a longtime
network researcher and author of a TV history. ``It's the car wreck
thing: you can't take your eyes off it, even though you know you
shouldn't be watching it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody moans about it,'' Darnell adds, ``but everybody's a
fan, whether they admit it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly the TV industry is watching. Among the 18 to 49 age
demographic that TV advertisers covet most, the entertainment
Darnell dreams up and solicits for Fox outperforms just about every
other network special that isn't a sports event, an awards show or
part of a regular series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surviving the Moment of Impact,'' ``World's Scariest Police
Chases'' and ``Magic's Biggest Secrets Revealed'' all ranked higher
last season among those age 18 to 49 than the season's
highest-rated TV movie (ABC's ``Oprah Winfrey Presents: The
Wedding'') and highest-rated news special (John Stossel's ``Love,
Lust and Marriage'' on ABC). And Fox's ``Busted on the Job'' and
``World's Deadliest Swarms'' weren't far behind.
</P>
<P>
   After ``Guinness'' premiered in August, it started beating
everything else on every network on Tuesday nights in prime time.
``Magic'' more than doubled the ratings of programming it replaced,
with its impact so far-reaching that an upcoming NBC magic special
reportedly will reveal the identity of Fox's ``masked'' magician.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Darnell) is the reason I come to the office early and leave
late,'' says Michael Davies, Darnell's specials rival at ABC.
``What Mike has done is change the specials business on network TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great for all of us that he's having so much success,''
adds Davies, who says ABC's successful summer replacement ``Whose
Line Is It Anyway?'' is the kind of ``outside the box'' thinking
that Darnell has prompted in him and others. ``When prime time is
so dominated by sitcoms, dramas and news magazines, people are
crying out for this type of programming. Now (the networks) are
going back to the more creative programing of the '50s and '60s.''
</P>
<P>
   The recent demise of TV movies has prompted the big broadcast
networks to fill the vacuum with news magazines, and many observers
see a kind of Darnellian devolution in their content: a greater
reliance on the sensational, the hyped, the adrenaline-driven
video. Darnell says video he's criticized for airing often shows up
on ``Dateline,'' trussed up as ``news.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The other networks want to do it under a more legitimate
banner, so they have the `Datelines,' the `PrimeTime Lives,' the
`48 Hours,''' says Steve Marks, a Los Angeles agent with many
clients who produce reality programming. ``If you took them
shoot-out, for the most part they won't touch it _ it's too
exploitative, too on the nose. It scares them. But then ABC's doing
`Deadliest Volcanoes,' `Deadliest Storms' _ stuff that's more
nature oriented, so they can get away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even PBS isn't immune from at least a mild case of the Darnell
bug. GPTV (which includes Atlanta's WGTV) sometimes repackages
reruns of shows into event nights sold to viewers with a taste of
the sensational, as when it cobbles together a three-hour block on
extreme weather, or UFOs and aliens, or predatory animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the intelligent version of that concept,'' allows BaBette
Davidson, GPTV program manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Fox does real police chases or `When Animals Attack,' it
sends a message to the people who produce our shows nationally that
people want to see wilder weather, more dangerous animals,'' she
adds. ``It's more of a trickle-up effect _ more of what the
audience wants to see. So when a producer looks at a nature
special, they might want to add video of a crocodile taking down a
hyena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an intangible.''
</P>
<P>
   TV, TV and even more TV
</P>
<P>
   Here's the world's quaintest thing about Mike Darnell: he loves
TV. Watches, sometimes, 14 hours a day. Good, bad _ ``Frazier,''
infomercials _ doesn't matter. He has five TVs in his house, one in
a bathroom, one in the baby's room, where the 3-month-old already
raises her head to watch. His wife Carolyn says Darnell ``is not
one of those parents who believes kids shouldn't watch TV.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never met anyone here who at the end of the day goes home
and watches more TV,'' adds Gavin Glynn, Darnell's manager of
specials. ``He's not jaded. You're never going to meet anyone who
loves TV more than Mike Darnell.''
</P>
<P>
   Darnell was a child actor whose family moved to Southern
California from Philadelphia when he was 12. He appeared on
commercials and in a parade of guest roles (``Welcome Back
Kotter,'' ``Sanford and Son,'' ``Kojack''), and starred in a
short-lived Saturday morning show called ``Big John, Little John.''
</P>
<P>
   He watched TV all the time back then, too. Handicapped TV
Guide's fall preview issue. Read and interpreted ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most actors like acting,'' he recalls. ``I liked TV.''
</P>
<P>
   His size kept him in kids' roles until he was 20, when he
started looking like a mighty old kid. So he got sort of serious
about college (``Anytime I could write on TV I did, no matter what
the subject'') and eventually became a video librarian at L.A.'s
Fox station. On his own time he put together a ``where is he now''
piece on Burt Ward, who played Robin on the old ``Batman'' TV
series. Barry Diller, the media mogul who at the time ran Fox, saw
the piece while channel surfing and Darnell was promoted to field
producer.
</P>
<P>
   He produced Rose Bowl parades, pre-Emmy shows, entertainment
segments. His biggest success was a tongue-in-cheek comparison of
the TV series ``Beverly Hills 90210'' and the just-released
``Beverly Hillbillies'' movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got me noticed,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Darnell landed in the Fox specials department in 1994. Weird
time at Fox. The mission then was more ``quality'' programming.
Specials wasn't part of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no vision,'' Darnell says of his plans when he arrived.
``I felt I would instinctively know what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   An unlikely special called ``Alien Autopsy: Truth or Fiction?''
kick-started those instincts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Autopsy'' began when Darnell got a call from a producer who'd
found some film supposedly shot in Roswell, N.M., of an alien
undergoing a military autopsy. The guy slipped the tape into
Darnell's office VCR, Darnell recalls, ``and damn if it didn't look
like 18 minutes of an alien being autopsied. You can see the guts
coming out, the head being sawed ...''
</P>
<P>
   Darnell told the guy to prove the film was shot when it claimed,
in 1947. The guy returned with proof that it it could have been
shot in 1947 _ or 1927, or 1967.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was enough for me,'' says Darnell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Autopsy'' was a smash. Believers loved it (``My wife thought
it was a real autopsy for two years,'' Darnell says). Nonbelievers
loved it (Jay Leno, David Letterman, ``Seinfeld'' all joked about
it). And with its huge ratings, the network loved it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized there's something to breaking the mold,'' Darnell
says. ``Something to getting controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is the world's scariest thing about our world, as seen
through the prism of Mike Darnell: There are ideas out there he
does not buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy came in, quite seriously, and pitched ``World's Most
Embarrassing Throw Up Moments,''' he says. ``I said, `I don't
understand.' He said, `Everybody has a story like that.' I said,
`What are they? Re-creations?' He said, `Yeah.'
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lines I will not cross.''
</P>
<P>
   Though most ideas come from Darnell and his staff, he listens in
his darkened office to about 25 pitches (ideas from producers) a
week. His reputation is as a quick, smart, un-Hollywood (``He's not
interested in having dinner with any agent in town,'' says L.A.
agent Ari Greenburg), in-fighting straight-talker who knows what he
wants and can deconstruct in seconds an idea that won't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like he's talking geometry; he knows what the theorems
are,'' says Tom Sheets, an assistant to Darnell.
</P>
<P>
   Darnell took five pitches this day. He bought none _ pretty
typical, considering he buys maybe one or two out of a hundred.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one:
</P>
<P>
   Producer: ``You're going to love this idea. `Killer Instinct.'
Inside the mind of the world's most terrifying serial killers.''
</P>
<P>
   Darnell: ``This may be too dark. Most of the stuff we do is more
adrenaline than dark.''
</P>
<P>
   Producer: ``We'll make the serial killer a funny guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Darnell: ``In the back of my mind, I'm thinking of something
less male and more female driven. There was that comedian who was
raping college students. No one dies. People were fascinated. ...
Anything else?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel if you can get me to watch it, hopefully an audience
will want to watch it,'' Darnell says later. ``I'm the opposite of
an elitist.''
</P>
<P>
   But is Darnell the opposite of responsible? Many observers
question how far this kind of programming will go _ whether the
real ``snuff TV'' that NBC's Ohlmeyer talks about is just around
the bend. Even Fox's recent magic specials, in which a masked
magician revealed secrets behind dozens of age-old illusions, was
jeered in some circles as unnecessarily exploitative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will do almost anything for a good number (big rating), as
long as it doesn't hurt me, the company, or my audience,'' Darnell
says. ``I don't cross into human suffering, making fun of a hurting
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Darnell is on the rise at Fox, where he's seen as more than a
clip-job artist, his notes valued by writers on other shows. He
recently added late-night to his specials and alternative program
duties. He's behind several Fox series that will appear in
mid-season, including a much-anticipated ``The PJ's,'' a kind of
claymation sitcom that features Eddie Murphy's voice. Darnell's
description: ```Larry Sanders' meets `Good Morning America' meets
puppets.'' With instincts even rivals such as ABC's Davies call
``incredible,'' Darnell could be that bridge between cable
sensibility and network mass appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all those people waiting for Mike Darnell to burn out,''
says ex-boss Bane, ``I'd be willing to bet he's at the front of the
line waiting to figure out what the next thing is.''
</P>
<P>
   It's late now inside Darnell's office. His wife and baby arrive.
</P>
<P>
   But Darnell still hasn't shown a visitor that giant tumor video.
So he grabs the tape. It's moments like these that Darnell the
shaggy-haired TV exec looks a lot like what Darnell the kid TV
junkie must have looked like, glued in front of the family set, a
dog-earred TV Guide on his lap.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's part of that. For better or worse, he's leaving a mark.
He's been called TV's P.T. Barnum. Fine with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love TV so much, that to carve out a niche that's mine, it's
an accomplishment,'' he says. He jokes of his epitaph: ``However he
died, I hope he caught it on video.''
</P>
<P>
   Darnell then slips the tumor tape into his VCR. It really is an
awesome tumor. The four or five other people in the office squirm,
moan, laugh, wince.
</P>
<P>
   But not one of them, including Darnell, stops watching.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
