<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SEASON-CRITICS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This season, let caution be your TV guide
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL SEPTEMBER 20: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Bob Longino, Phil Kloer, Lyle V. Harris, and Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TV's new fall season officially starts Monday, and the onslaught
of 36 new dramas and sitcoms begins in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   What's a viewer to choose? ABC's rehash of ``Fantasy Island''
with new devilish twists? WB's new critical darling ``Felicity'' _
a college drama that many critics are hailing as this year's answer
to ``Ally McBeal''?
</P>
<P>
   Our TV critics _ Drew Jubera, Lyle V. Harris, Phil Kloer and Bob
Longino _ have handicapped this season's new shows from 1 to 35
(NBC's new Nathan Lane sitcom ``Encore! Encore!'' was unavailable
at press time).
</P>
<P>
   WORTH IT
</P>
<P>
   1. ``Felicity'' (WB; debuts Sept. 29). Smart but naive girl goes
to college and messes up her life. Keri Russell stars in the best
pilot of the fall, one that's been compared to ``My So-Called
Life'' and ``Ally McBeal,'' but is really more like
``thirtysomething: the early years.''
</P>
<P>
   2. ``Sports Night'' (ABC; debuts Tuesday). What if they made a
sitcom about working at EPSN (which Disney owns) and put it on ABC
(which Disney owns)? Well, they did. It's a smartly written,
promising show that moves with the speed of ``ER.''
</P>
<P>
   3. ``Will &AMP; Grace'' (NBC; debuts Monday). He's gay, she's
straight, they're likable, although not as much as Julia Roberts
and Rupert Everett in ``My Best Friend's Wedding,'' the obvious
inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   4. ``The King of Queens'' (CBS; debuts Monday). ``Everybody
Loves Raymond'' without the kids. So far.
</P>
<P>
   5. ``Trinity'' (NBC; debuts Oct. 16). The best of the three new
shows about big Irish families: a cop, a priest, a crook, a
druggie, but no leprechaun in John (``ER'') Wells' family drama.
</P>
<P>
   6. ``Cupid'' (ABC; debuts Saturday). The god of love helps
singles in the '90s in a sweetly whimsical romance.
</P>
<P>
   7. ``The Hughleys'' (ABC; debuts Tuesday). Salt 'n' pepper in
the burbs. A comedy.
</P>
<P>
   8. ``That '70s Show'' (Fox; debuted Aug. 23). Already generating
a buzz for its goofy spin on Midwest teens in the mirrored-ball
years.
</P>
<P>
   9. ``Buddy Faro'' (CBS; debuts Friday). Retro-hip, swingin'
series about an aging detective (Dennis Farina) out of mothballs
and back in business in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   WORTH A FLIP
</P>
<P>
   10. ``Fantasy Island'' (ABC; debuts Saturday) ``De plane'' still
brings de guest stars, but they're confronted by a darker, stranger
island. Malcolm McDowell is Mr. Roarke.
</P>
<P>
   11. ``Jesse'' (NBC; debuts Thursday). Christina Applegate (Kelly
Bundy on ``Married ... With Children'') says bye-bye bimbohood,
hello decent sitcom about a working single mom.
</P>
<P>
   12. ``Two of a Kind'' (ABC; debuts Friday). The Olsen twins are
back in another TGIF sitcom aimed squarely at their young fans.
</P>
<P>
   13. ``L.A. Doctors'' (CBS; debuts Monday). ``Marcus Welby,
M.D.'' meets ``L.A. Law'' as four docs (led by Ken Olin of
``thirtysomething'') struggle with the money vs. medicine debate.
</P>
<P>
   14. ``Martial Law'' (CBS; debuts Saturday). More fun than a
roundhouse kick in the nose.
</P>
<P>
   15. ``Brother's Keeper'' (ABC; debuts Friday). Straight-arrow
single dad learns life's painfully fun from his always-in-trouble
sibling.
</P>
<P>
   WORTH HAVING ON IN BACKGROUND
</P>
<P>
   16. ``Brimstone'' (Fox; debuts Oct. 27). The devil sends a dead
cop (Peter Horton) back to Earth to hunt escapees from hell. Call
it ``Touched by a Devil.''
</P>
<P>
   17. ``DiResta'' (UPN; debuts Oct. 5). ``Everybody Loves
Raymond'' with just a trickle of its humor.
</P>
<P>
   18. ``Seven Days'' (UPN; debuts Oct. 7). Loud, hokey and
ridiculous sci-fi thriller about time travel. But kinda cool in its
hokey way.
</P>
<P>
   19. ``Living in Captivity'' (Fox; debuted Sept. 11). Salt 'n'
pepper in the burbs. A so-so comedy.
</P>
<P>
   20. ``To Have &AMP; to Hold'' (CBS; debuts Sept. 30). Irish cop hunk
marries Irish lawyer lass. They smolder; the rest of it molders.
</P>
<P>
   21. ``The Brian Benben Show'' (CBS; debuts Monday). He's a local
news reporter covering dumb stories. In case you can't wait till
11.
</P>
<P>
   WORTHLESS
</P>
<P>
   22. ``Charmed'' (WB; debuts Oct. 7). Three sisters are witches.
Somewhere between ``Buffy'' without the hipness and ``Sabrina''
without the glitter.
</P>
<P>
   23. ``Hyperion Bay'' (WB; debuts Monday). Revenge of a nerd.
</P>
<P>
   24. ``The Secret Lives of Men'' (ABC; debuts Sept. 30) Divorce,
golf, beer _ what's the secret?
</P>
<P>
   25. ``Conrad Bloom'' (NBC; debuts Monday). Conrad's a sweet
mensch, surrounded by females demanding, dysfunctional or both.
</P>
<P>
   26. ``Wind on Water'' (NBC; debuts Oct. 17). Surf 'n' jerks.
</P>
<P>
   27. ``Guys Like Us'' (UPN; debuts Oct. 5). The boys of bummer.
</P>
<P>
   28. ``Mercy Point'' (UPN; debuts Oct. 6). Kind of like ``ER''
with aliens and way, way out in space.
</P>
<P>
   29. ``Legacy'' (UPN; debuts Oct. 9). ``The Big Valley'' with a
``Titanic'' soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   WORTH GOUGING EYES OUT
</P>
<P>
   30. ``Costello'' (Fox; debuted Tuesday). Loud louts in a Boston
bar. The anti-``Cheers.''
</P>
<P>
   31. ``The Secret Diary of Desmond Pfeiffer'' (UPN; debuts Oct.
5). A sex comedy about Abraham Lincoln that's worse than it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   32. ``Maggie Winters'' (CBS; debuts Oct. 30). Faith Ford
(``Murphy Brown'') goes back to her small town where her friends
are re-living their high school years. As fun to watch as it would
be to live.
</P>
<P>
   33. ``Vengeance Unlimited'' (ABC; debuts Sept. 29). Violence
unexpurgated.
</P>
<P>
   34. ``The Army Show'' (WB; debuted Sept. 13). Oh, for the
sophisticated wit of ``Gomer Pyle.''
</P>
<P>
   35. ``Holding the Baby'' (Fox; debuted Aug. 23). Uh-oh, it fell
on its head.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
