</P>
<P>
   Q. How does it work?
</P>
<P>
   A. The House adopts ``articles of impeachment'' by a majority
vote. The Senate meets as a ``court of impeachment'' to consider
the charges. Conviction requires a two-thirds majority of those
voting.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Can members of Congress be impeached?
</P>
<P>
   A. No, they lack protection of the impeachment process. Either
the Senate or the House can act alone to expel any of its members
at any time by a two-thirds vote.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Among the impeachable charges, treason and bribery seem
pretty clear, but what are ``high crimes and misdemeanors?''
</P>
<P>
   A. Whole books have been written about that. The phrase was used
in England to describe very serious wrongdoing that threatened the
king, who embodied the state. In the United States, where
impeachment involves both precise legal and broad political
judgments, there is general agreement that high crimes and
misdemeanors consist of corrupt activities as serious as treason
and bribery.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is the narrowest legal definition?
</P>
<P>
   A. While all sides agree that a grave, indictable crime can be
grounds for impeachment, some argue narrowly that nothing other
than a criminal act can be grounds for impeachment. ``If we cannot
state upon paper a specific crime, how are we to carry this case to
the Senate for a trial?'' Rep. James Wilson argued during the
House's debate on Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is an example of a broader, political definition?
</P>
<P>
   A. Judge John Pickering, whose nephew informed Congress that the
judge was insane, was removed from office after he was impeached
and convicted on charges of being drunk and using profanity on the
bench. None of his offenses was an grave crime.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, when Gerald Ford was Republican minority leader of the
House, he said that in the case of judges, ``an impeachable offense
is whatever a majority of the House considers it to be at a given
moment in history.'' The cynicism implicit in that argument is
generally considered to be one reason that a House committee
squelched Ford's effort to impeach Supreme Court Justice William O.
Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What were Andrew Johnson's high crimes and misdemeanors?
</P>
<P>
   A. In 1867, the House Judiciary Committee charged that Johnson
failed to carry out some laws that Congress had passed after the
Civil War as a way to protect freed slaves and loyal Republicans,
punish leading rebels and restrict Democrats. The committee report
was rejected by the House.
</P>
<P>
   In 1868, the House voted to impeach Johnson, and then asked a
committee to draft some articles of impeachment. Eventually, the
House approved 11 articles with a mixture of legal and political
offenses. Besides reviving the earlier charges, the articles
charged that he disobeyed a law requiring congressional approval of
any decision to replace a patronage appointee and that he tried to
arouse public hatred and contempt for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate abandoned the trial after votes on three of the
articles all came up one vote short of the two-thirds margin needed
to convict.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What were the charges against President Richard Nixon?
</P>
<P>
   A. Before Nixon resigned, the Judiciary Committee had voted to
recommend that he be charged with obstructing justice by using the
FBI and CIA to help conceal his links to the Watergate break-in,
abusing his presidential powers by arranging illegally to spy on
and harass Americans he did not like, and refusing to honor
congressional subpoenas. The committee rejected a charge that he
concealed four years of bombing in Cambodia and decided that his
cheating on income taxes was not an impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What would the charges be against President Clinton?
</P>
<P>
   A. Nobody knows. If the House does give its Judiciary Committee
permission to start an inquiry, it might or might not instruct the
committee to confine its hearings to matters publicized by
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What did Starr do?
</P>
<P>
   A. With the permission of a three-judge panel to which he
reports, Starr submitted documents, tapes and a 458-page summary to
the House. In his summary, Starr said some of Clinton's actions
``may constitute grounds for impeachment.'' While asserting that
his office uncovered ``substantial and credible information'' that
the president committed perjury and obstructed justice while trying
to conceal his marital infidelity, Starr noted, ``It is not the
role of this Office to determine whether the president's actions
warrant impeachment by the House and removal by the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Q. Has the House ever received a similar report?
</P>
<P>
   A. Not a public report. But during the Judiciary Committee's
impeachment inquiry in 1974, it received a less opinionated
confidential report. At the request of the grand jury investigating
the Watergate cover-up, Federal Judge John J. Sirica gave the
committee a briefcase full of evidence and a sealed grand jury
report that consisted of an index of the contents. ``The grand jury
sent nothing of an accusatory nature to the House committee,''
Special Prosecutor Leon Jaworski told the Supreme Court. ``What the
grand jury sent to the House committee was the evidence that had
been accumulated.''
</P>
<P>
   Q. How are impeachments conducted?
</P>
<P>
   A. Each ``article of impeachment,'' or related set of charges,
must be adopted by a majority vote in the House. The Senate has the
sole power to conduct trials. Its members meet as a ``Court of
Impeachment,'' and conviction on any article requires approval of
two-thirds of those voting. Conviction on one article is sufficient
to remove someone from office.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Does that mean the House acts as a grand jury?
</P>
<P>
   A. Not exactly. A grand jury must merely decide that it is more
likely than not that an offense has been committed. But the House
usually acts only if, first, a majority of the committee that
conducted an inquiry, and then, a majority of all House members are
convinced that an impeachable offense was definitely committed.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Does the Senate act as a trial jury?
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, but one with far more powers. It decides not only
matters of fact, but procedural questions, and could even decide
that the House was wrong when it described an activity as an
impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   Each impeachment trial has its own set of rules. But in the
past, the rules have let senators debate each other, walk out
during boring parts, cross-examine witnesses, negotiate with the
president privately, urge their constituents to lobby senators on
the other side, quiz defense lawyers or the prosecutor-like
``managers'' who represent the House during the trial, change the
rules in mid-trial and reserve the right to vote to overrule any
procedural or substantive rulings by the presiding officer.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Who presides?
</P>
<P>
   A. Normally, the vice president. But if the president is on
trial, the Constitution provides that the presiding officer is the
Chief Justice of the United States. The founding fathers thought it
wouldn't be a good idea to have a president's trial presided over
by someone in line to replace the accused president.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How common are impeachments?
</P>
<P>
   A. There are hardly any. Since 1800, the House has launched more
than 60 inquiries, but only 14 people _ one president (Johnson in
1868), one cabinet member (Secretary of War William Belknap in
1876) and 12 judges _ have been impeached. One of the judges
resigned. In the 13 Senate trials, Johnson, Belknap and four judges
were acquitted, and seven judges were convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What are the penalties for conviction?
</P>
<P>
   A. There are only two. The Constitution says, ``Judgment in
Cases of Impeachment shall not extend further than to removal from
Office, and disqualification to hold and enjoy an Office of Honor,
Trust or Profit under the United States.'' The disqualification is
optional.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Does that mean that if their impeachable offenses included a
crime, they get immunity from criminal prosecution?
</P>
<P>
   A. Not automatically. The Constitution goes on to say, ``but the
Party convicted shall nevertheless be liable and subject to
Indictment, Trial, Judgment and Punishment, according to Law.''
</P>
<P>
   Q. What are the advantages to resigning, rather than facing the
impeachment process?
</P>
<P>
   A. It saves the president, Congress and the country weeks of
agony, and allows the departing president to keep his federal
pension and lifetime health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Practically speaking, doesn't even the mention of impeachment
lead to social ruin and political disgrace?
</P>
<P>
   A. Not necessarily. There are bound to be loyalists who will
always believe the accused person got a bum deal. Johnson was
elected to the Senate after completing his presidential term.
Nixon's funeral was well-attended. U.S. District Judge Alcee
Hastings, who was convicted on impeachment charges, was later
elected to and still serves in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
