<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-RYAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RYAN'S LONG SHADOW  
 CARDINALS STILL HAUNTED BY REGIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Three years later, the damage former Coach Buddy
Ryan inflicted on the Cardinals remains.
</P>
<P>
   Seen the NFL rushing statistics? Ex-Cardinals back Garrison
Hearst of the San Francisco 49ers leads the league with 325 yards
and three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never wanted to get rid of Garrison Hearst,'' a Cardinals
coach said. ``We had to get rid of him or we couldn't sign our
draft picks. He was strictly a salary-cap casualty.''
</P>
<P>
   It was one example of how Ryan ran amok. His abuse of power
still is being felt at the corner of Warner and Hardy in Tempe as
team officials try to dig out from Hurricane Buddy.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals cut Hearst in training camp two years ago so they
could sign first-round pick Simeon Rice to a four-year, $9.3
million deal.
</P>
<P>
   The next week, the Cardinals released defensive end Clyde
Simmons, whom Ryan had signed to a five-year, $14.9 million
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons' contract and the identical one given to linebacker Seth
Joyner, released 15 months ago, left the club with salary-cap
troubles it couldn't get out of until this year.
</P>
<P>
   The two teams Ryan directed in the NFL, the Cardinals and
Eagles, play each other Sunday at Sun Devil Stadium. Both are 0-2
and desperate for a win.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan can't be blamed for the Eagles having the worst offense in
the league and the Cardinals at 28th. But he left both with huge
messes on the offensive line, and neither have been fixed.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't one offensive lineman on the current Cardinals team
left from Ryan's two-year reign of terror, but look around the
league.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Coleman, a 1993 first-round draft pick, is starting at left
guard for one of the best offensive lines in Jacksonville. Ryan cut
him midway through the '95 season. Rich Braham, a 1994 third-round
pick, is starting at guard for the Cincinnati Bengals, who claimed
him on waivers early in '94 season when Ryan, foolishly, thought he
could sneak him through waivers.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, running back Fred McAfee and cornerback Chris Oldham?
Ryan cut both in 1994. Each helped the Pittsburgh Steelers get to
the Super Bowl the next season and still are with the team.
</P>
<P>
   There are only seven Cardinals players left who joined the team
during Ryan's tenure _ wide receivers Rob Moore and Frank Sanders,
linebackers Jamir Miller and Terry Irving, defensive tackle Bernard
Wilson, safety Kwamie Lassiter and backup quarterback Stoney Case.
Ryan's best three moves were trading for Moore and drafting Sanders
and Miller.
</P>
<P>
   His first two picks, Miller and Chuck Levy, both were suspended
their second seasons for substance-abuse violations but remain in
the league. Miller is the Cardinals' best linebacker and could get
a big free-agent deal in the off-season. Levy is the 49ers' return
specialist and plays behind Hearst at running back.
</P>
<P>
   In Ryan's two drafts, he picked five defensive backs. None
remain with Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Team owner Bill Bidwill gave Ryan unlimited power. He was in
charge of every football decision, a move that continues to haunt.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan gave a $1 million offer sheet to journeyman offensive
tackle Larry Tharpe, who was making the league minimum at the time.
There may have been a reason for the big deal: Tharpe's agent was
Ryan's son, Jim.
</P>
<P>
   After telling other rookie free agents that the Cardinals
couldn't offer them any signing bonuses, Ryan gave Mike Gentry of
Eastern Kentucky an $8,000 bonus. Gentry's father was a mutual
friend of a Kentucky veterinarian who worked on Ryan's horses.
</P>
<P>
   That abuse of power is one reason the Bidwills haven't given
anyone complete control of the football operation since. They were
right to give a football man complete control. They just gave it to
the wrong guy.
</P>
<P>
   The many layers of power contributed to first-round draft pick
Andre Wadsworth's long holdout this summer. If someone were in
charge, the deal likely could have been done much sooner.
</P>
<P>
   It's understandable why the Bidwills are uneasy about
relinquishing control. What went on during Ryan's regime was
juicier than the details of Kenneth Starr's report on Clinton's
scandalous behavior.
</P>
<P>
   One assistant under Ryan said he had to miss work because of
abdominal surgery but really had penile implants, according to club
sources. The team paid for the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Another coach, in charge of enforcing player fines, didn't give
the money to charity, which is customary. He had the players buy
cosmetics from his wife.
</P>
<P>
   A couple hours before Ryan's last game, a Christmas match-up
against Dallas on ``Monday Night'' Football,'' ABC-TV analyst Dan
Dierdorf, a former Cardinals offensive lineman, walked into the
locker room. Middle linebacker Eric Hill and defensive end Chad
Brown were brawling.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few months, team officials discovered that Ryan's
son, Rob, the defensive secondary coach, had padded the defensive
statistics. He had credited Cardinals defensive backs with
deflections on all opposing passes that were incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan announced at his first news conference that the Valley
``had a winner in town.''
</P>
<P>
   He's a big reason Valley sports fans still are waiting. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
