<SLUG> BC-BOX-CARBAJAL-COMEBACK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARBAJAL TRAINS FOR COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Michael Carbajal turns 31 today with a hope of turning
back the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Carbajal, one of the best fighters of the mid-1990s, is training
for a comeback bout late in October.
</P>
<P>
   His brother, manager and trainer, Danny Carbajal, said he is
putting together a bout for Oct. 23 or Oct. 30 at a casino near
Biloxi, Miss., a site of several nationally televised cards during
the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Carbajal said he is reviewing potential opponents for his
brother, who last fought July 19, 1997, and lost by technical
knockout to South African Jake Matlala.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to get back in,'' said Carbajal, a former
International Boxing Federation and World Boxing Council
junior-flyweight champion (108 pounds), who plans to make his
comeback at flyweight (112.) ``I watched all the competition at
112, and I didn't see too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Carbajal said he is motivated by a desire to regain a major
title at a heavier weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want something that you lost, and you want it real bad,''
Carbajal said Wednesday after sparring at his Ninth Street Gym.
</P>
<P>
   He nearly attempted a comeback last spring, but a bruised right
hand prevented him. The hand, he said Wednesday, is healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Carbajal quickly rose to the top of the boxing world after a
silver medal at the 1988 Olympics. He's the first in the lightest
divisions (108-126 pounds) to get a $1 million purse. In all, he
earned about $7 million over 49 fights (45-4, 30 KOs).
</P>
<P>
   Money is not considered a key factor in his comeback, according
to people close to him. He is currently earning about $80,000 a
year from a retirement fund established from ring earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I can win another title,'' said Carbajal, who, as ``The
Ring's'' 1993 Fighter of the Year, is the lightest ever to win an
award that is older than the Heisman Trophy. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 1237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
