<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-LEFT-WING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF TKACHUK'S GONE, WHO'LL BE LEFT FOR COYOTES?  
 ISBISTER, ADAMS EXPECTED TO TAKE UP SOME SLACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. - General Manager Bobby Smith is on record as
saying the Coyotes can win without Captain Keith Tkachuk, the
recalcitrant left wing who refuses to honor the remaining two years
of his contract until it's renegotiated.
</P>
<P>
   Brave talk, no doubt. But can the Coyotes walk his talk?
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes have right wings and several centers who also can
play the left side, but if they are to prove Smith's stance
correct, chances are the onus is going to fall on newly acquired
left wing Greg Adams and bigger, stronger port-sider Brad Isbister.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got 40 goals last year from Keith, but other than that, we
really didn't get much production from our left side,'' Smith said.
``I think Isbister got nine goals and Darrin Shannon had two, so
there's going be a bigger responsibility for all of our forwards to
pick up the goals Keith Tkachuk won't score.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, it's not like subtracting 50 goals from our
lineup. Somebody is going to be on that power play. It's not like
whoever we choose to have on that first-unit power play is going to
get none. They're not going to get Keith's 50, but it's not like
saying, `We're going to start next year and we're going to have 187
goals.' Somebody is going to pick those up.''
</P>
<P>
   In Adams, 35, and Isbister, who's 22 and starting his second NHL
season, the Coyotes have the potential to pick up much of the
slack. The troble is, potential always carries questions. And with
this pair, the ``if'' factor isn't small.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impossible for me to set a goal for them,'' Smith said.
``If he stays healthy, Adams could score 35 goals. Isbister is a
young kid who's just emerging, but he seems more involved. It's
unfair to speculate.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Adams missed the Stanley Cup playoffs because of
a neck injury that caused his hands to go numb. Last year, his
season was limited to 49 games by a knee injury and a sporadic
recurrence of the neck problem.
</P>
<P>
   Isbister, who started last season in Phoenix but was sent down
to minor league affiliate Springfield for nine games and a
confidence boost before returning to finish with 17 points, is
trying to make his sophomore season a breakout year.
</P>
<P>
   The signs that he can do so are good.
</P>
<P>
   If any Coyotes' player benefited from a rigorous off-season
training program in Southern California that included many NHL
stars, it's him. At 6 feet 2, he's now 225 pounds of chiseled
muscle and looks like a totally different player in scrimmages,
Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more confident,'' Isbister said. ``Just working with all
the guys who were down there made a difference. I realized I could
lift as much, if not more, than a lot of them. Just hanging around
with them rubs off on you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, I learned a lot from last year. Looking back on it, I
realized some things I could have done better and must do to be
successful. I have to play a big forward's game and go to the net,
go into the corners and take control and get the puck to my
teammates for plays, or just take it to the net.''
</P>
<P>
   Isbister said the pressure will remain the same whether Tkachuk
returns or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll put pressure on myself, regardless,'' he said. ``I'm
pressuring myself to score more, anyway. If he's not here, I'll
probably get a little more chance to play and a little more ice
time, which means there's also more chance to produce.''
</P>
<P>
   Little question exists about Adams' scoring ability. The former
Northern Arizona star has scored 30 or more goals four times and 20
or more five times during his 15-year career. He had 14 goals and
32 points in little more than a half-season last year. His biggest
question is durability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've really felt good in camp,'' he said Tuesday. ``I went
through my physical, and everything was fine. I'm fine and ready to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he doesn't feel pressure to pick up the missing
production that might be left by Tkachuk's absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The slack can't be picked up by one or two guys,'' he said.
``When a guy like that is missing, it has to be picked up by the
whole team. A couple of guys are not going to replace him.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
