<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0397 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-GOMEZ-SOSA-RACISM     09-17 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GOMEZ-SOSA-RACISM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL WASN'T RACIST IN SOSA'S RUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - C'mon now, there isn't really a rising tide that
believes Sammy Sosa is being slighted because he is a black Latin
American, is there?
</P>
<P>
   Please say it ain't so, America.
</P>
<P>
   The single-season home run record had stood for 37 years without
anyone seriously challenging it. So when Mark McGwire reached the
magical number of 62 first, naturally he received the lion's share
of attention.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's home run record is the most sexy and desirable in all
of professional sports. So when McGwire broke Roger Maris' record,
the nation's eyes were glued to the St. Louis Cardinals slugger's
every move. That's why a whopping 43 million people watched the
event live on television, captivated for one glorious evening by a
remarkable accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa came along and hit his 62nd home run five days later. A
record that stood for 37 years was bettered twice in only five
days. That, folks, was the reason the same circuslike atmosphere
didn't surround Sosa's equally remarkable accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, all of the festivities that took place at Busch
Stadium the night McGwire eclipsed Maris were staged by the
Cardinals franchise, not Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning it was Sosa who repeatedly said, ``McGwire is
the man.'' Everyone knew the first to reach 62 would be the more
celebrated of the two. In the end, whoever winds up with more home
runs will get his due.
</P>
<P>
   Take a close look at Sosa's infectious and never-ceasing smile.
Do you see a man who feels pain?
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at the crowds outside of Chicago, those in St.
Louis, San Diego and everywhere else the Cubs play. See how they
stand and give Sosa long ovations every time he steps to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Racism?
</P>
<P>
   Please.
</P>
<P>
   Even Sosa scoffed at such a thought when asked whether he felt
slighted by all the attention McGwire had received leading up to
the night the record was broken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course he should be getting all the attention,'' Sosa said
that night. ``He's the first to get there. Like with your children,
the first always gets more attention than the second and so on. I
have no problem with it, I don't see why anyone else should.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this is not to say Major League Baseball didn't make a
grievous error when Sosa hit No. 62 last Sunday at Wrigley Field.
Unlike McGwire's home run balls, which had distinguishable infrared
markings on them, baseball took no such precautions with Sosa's
home runs. Now we have three people claiming they have the genuine
article.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there was no one from baseball at Wrigley Field for
Sosa's historic blasts. Another faux pas on the part of baseball,
especially considering Commissioner Bud Selig was lounging at his
home only 80 miles away in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   But both of those blunders were a case of baseball again finding
a way to show its ineptitude, a serious problem that has afflicted
the game for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Racism, it was not.
</P>
<P>
   If Sosa had reached the 62 plateau first, all of the hoopla that
surrounded that magical night in St. Louis would have occurred
wherever Sosa had been playing. Bet on that.
</P>
<P>
   These days, baseball officials are especially sensitive to even
the slightest appearance of favoritism toward anyone. Front offices
and coaching staffs are more diverse than at any time in the
history of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, I'm for Sammy Sosa. I would love to see a fellow Latin
become the single-season home run record holder. I'm also for Mark
McGwire, having covered his feats for six years.
</P>
<P>
   To say I'm pulling for Sosa over McGwire or vice-versa would be
a lie. I'm pulling for baseball, which is riding this incredible
Sosa-McGwire wave all the way back to the top of the sports heap.
</P>
<P>
   We should all be celebrating the accomplishments of two of the
greatest current players in the game. Instead, a vocal minority is
doing its best to tarnish what's going on, and that's sad.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City and south Florida, the Dominican communities
are considering organizing a protest march against Major League
Baseball over what it deems a slight against Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   Radio talk shows in Latin communities are screaming
discrimination. The thrust being that if Sosa were White or even an
African-American like, say, Ken Griffey Jr., that baseball would
have treated him differently.
</P>
<P>
   This should not be a Black-White issue. It should solely be an
issue of two men hitting white baseballs over green fences. To make
it anything else only diminishes what's taking place on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of trying to throw a sopping wet blanket on the fabulous
achievements that have taken place, maybe some of the people who
constantly yell racism whenever they can should look around and see
the joy on everyone's face.
</P>
<P>
   Racism definitely occurs in our society. It's up to everyone of
us, including people in baseball, to make sure those responsible
for such vile actions are shown for what they are.
</P>
<P>
   This, however, is not one of those times.
</P>
<P>
   Don't let the party-crashers get away with acts of stupidity and
ignorance. This is one hell of a party and it's not even near
closing time yet, not with the playoffs still on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   To Mark and Sammy: Party on, dudes! &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at 602-444-2364 or at
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
