<HEADLINE>
GOOD PERFORMANCES, DIRECTION ELEVATE `ONE TRUE THING' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TThe film version of Anna Quindlen's novel, ``One True Thing,''
is a textbook case of how vibrant movie-star performances and
sensitive direction can elevate predictable, overly familiar
material into something reasonably special.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the film is classic soap opera, divided between strong,
noble and long-suffering women and weak, philandering and abusive
men. It's also driven by conflicts that are actually
misunderstandings capable of being sorted out in a couple of frank
conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the film does a solid job of exploring the complications
of post-childhood family relationships, and there's no denying the
effectiveness of its performances or its power on an audience. Each
of its three stars would seem to be an instant Oscar contender.
</P>
<P>
   The film opens in late 1988, as Ellen Gulden (Renee Zellweger),
a Harvard-educated, twentysomething investigative reporter is being
questioned by a police detective about the recent death of her
mother, with the hint that a mercy killing may be suspected.
</P>
<P>
   As the interview continues, we flash back to the year before, as
Ellen, who works for New York magazine, returns to her small-town
family home for the 55th birthday of her father (William Hurt), a
college teacher, writer and winner of the National Book Award for
his critical study of T.S. Eliot.
</P>
<P>
   We quickly see that Ellen has an uneasy relationship with both
her semi-celebrity father, whose approval she desperately seeks but
can't quite get, and with her 47-year-old mother (Meryl Streep),
who is a kind of ditzy, June Cleaver-like, '50s-style happy
homemaker and everything Ellen doesn't want to become.
</P>
<P>
   When they learn her mother has cancer, her somewhat selfish
father demands that Ellen quit her job, move back home and take
care of her. She unhappily assumes the burden and the rest of the
film chronicles the series of discoveries she makes about her
parents and how it changes her own view of life.
</P>
<P>
   It's familiar territory, with no real surprises along the way
and more than its fair share of highly Hollywoodized elements,
including the entire small college town setting (which seems as
impossibly idealized as Frank Capra's Bedford Falls) and several of
those family screaming matches in the street you only see in
movies.
</P>
<P>
   The two leads are cast against type, and it doesn't completely
work. The Streep character is supposed to seem weak in the
beginning and gradually appear strong, and yet Streep-the-star
projects nothing but strength. Hurt's transition in our eyes is the
opposite, but his persona projects intellectual weakness from the
get-go.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even if their individual persona work against the overall
dramatic effectiveness and believablity of the characters, Streep
and Hurt are such mesmerizing presences that they're always a
pleasure to watch. Emotionally, they pull us into the family drama
and keep us riveted to the screen as only first-rank movie stars
can do.
</P>
<P>
   Director Carl Franklin (``One False Move,'' ``Devil in a Blue
Dress'') wisely underplays many of his scenes and does an
exceptional job of establishing his relationships and telling
background subtly, through nuance and suggestion. He doesn't shy
away from the depicting a slow death by cancer in (depressing)
detail.
</P>
<P>
   He's also smart enough to allow Zellweger to carry the movie,
despite the higher marquee pedigree of his older stars. She's
terrific every step of the way, communicating all the frustration,
suppressed trauma and sense of self-survival the character needs to
be totally believable and totally sympathetic as the audience point
of view.
</P>
<P>
   One True Thing. Directed by Carl Franklin. Screenplay by Karen
Croner. Cast: Meryl Streep, Renee Zellweger, William Hurt, Tom
Everett Scott. Universal. 127 minutes. Rated R for terminal-cancer
theme.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
