<HEADLINE>
DIRECTOR'S CUT OF `TOUCH OF EVIL' IS BETTER ONLY IN SOME WAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Orson Welles' 1958 thriller, ``Touch of Evil,'' was the last
film he would ever direct for a Hollywood studio, and _ though he
would go on to make a number of low-budget, independent films
during the next 27 years _ it was the last to be widely regarded as
a masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   By this time in his career, he was already anathema to studio
heads, and he got the job largely through the hard lobbying of the
film's star, Charlton Heston, who was a longtime Welles admirer and
not afraid to use his clout to pressure the Universal Studios brass
into giving him another chance.
</P>
<P>
   The story is that Universal ultimately relented because it
regarded the film _ a melodrama about a Mexican crime buster
(Heston) who falls into a web of evil in a Tijuana-like border town
_ as a B-movie programmer that Welles couldn't much hurt.
</P>
<P>
   It was, for Welles, a remarkable smooth moviemaking experience,
with no budget problems and little studio interference until he
turned in a rough cut. At this point, Universal _ confused by
Welles' narrative _ had another director shoot 10 minutes of
(mostly linking) footage, and rework the cut.
</P>
<P>
   By this time, Welles was off to other things. It was his pattern
throughout his career to lose interest in his projects during the
editing process, and _ as his biographers unanimously agree _
something in his psychology needed to be an artistic martyr.
</P>
<P>
   But when he saw Universal's cut in December 1957, he did dash
off a pleading 58-page memo to studio chief Edward Muhl outlining
the changes he thought would make the movie smoother and more
accessible _ which Muhl promptly ignored.
</P>
<P>
   When the film was released, it was an instant and overwhelming
flop. Audiences found it cold, unpleasant, impossible to follow and
rather ridiculous _ especially the casting of the Heston and
Marlene Dietrich as Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, of course, that decision was reversed.
Championed first by French critics, the film has become almost
universally accepted as one of Welles' most uncompromising and
accomplished works, and the stylistic summation of Hollywood film
noir.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Welles' performance as the incorrigibly corrupt,
relentless despicable, 300-pound villain has been lauded as his
most daring performance _ a genuinely harrowing portrait of pure
evil at the very heart of American democracy that singlehandedly
transforms a cheap thriller into a tragedy of Shakespearean
proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the legend of the Welles memo, and the director's own
stories told in a thousand interviews and talk show appearances
about the ``Touch of Evil'' that should have been, have echoed down
through the decades. In effect: ``If you think the movie is good
now, you should've seen it before it was butchered.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, finally, we can. The occasion of the film's 40th birthday
this year has inspired a team of eminent Wellesians _ including
critic Jonathan Rosenbaum and Oscar-winning movie sound editor
Walter Murch (``Apocalypse Now'') _ to get Universal's approval to
re-edit the film to the specifications of the Welles memo: a
director's cut, as it were, from the grave.
</P>
<P>
   The results, ``The Re-edit of `Touch of Evil,''' are on display.
At 113 minutes, it's 20 minutes longer than the 93-minute release
version, and five minutes longer than the 108-minute ``preview
version'' that appeared in the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   How different is it? As Heston always strongly maintained, the
Welles cut is in no way a different film _ both go to the same
place in much the same way. But there are some noticeable changes,
with some artistic gains and, more surprisingly, some losses.
</P>
<P>
   The most glaring change comes right away _ the titles and Henry
Mancini's jazzy score have been removed from the famous tracking
title sequence in which Welles skillfully chronicles a murder,
introduces his main characters and explores his two (Mexican and
American) border towns _ all in a single, unbroken shot.
</P>
<P>
   This surgery heightens the sights and sounds of the border
towns, and gives the film some A-movie dignity. On the other hand,
it removes some of the sleaziness that Mancini's deliberately
tawdry score establishes for the film, and takes us a big step away
from the '50s.
</P>
<P>
   The second most noticeable difference is in the cross-cutting,
pacing and arrangement of scenes in the parallel stories of the
film's husband and wife (Janet Leigh) protagonists _ as he is swept
up in the murder investigation and she is kidnapped and terrorized
by Mexican hoodlums.
</P>
<P>
   This was the part of the studio cut that irked Welles the most,
and which he argued against most strongly in his memo. And he was
right: his cut builds more suspense, gives equal weight to the two
story lines, and makes the film seem more balanced and much less
jarring to the senses.
</P>
<P>
   The other changes are smaller and harder to spot. Frames have
been removed from the shot of a corpse to heighten dramatic effect
here, a reaction shot has been moved there. The sound is clearer,
some of the non-Welles footage is gone, several of the supporting
players come into sharper focus, and the narrative generally makes
more sense.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, while all this is definitely an improvement on one level,
the changes also detract from the ``Touch of Evil'' experience on
another, and could even _ one suspects _ harm the film's critical
reputation and vaulted place in film history.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the thing that generations of critics have loved
about the film is its deceptive B-movie sleaziness, its fuzzy
character motivations, its jarring and convoluted cross-cutting,
its lack of narrative sense, its sheer unconventionality.
</P>
<P>
   Just think of how betrayed all those essayists and critics are
going to feel when they find out that much of that bold stylistic
murkiness they've been praising for four decades was unintentional!
Maybe, when all is said and done, it's never a very good idea to
tamper with a masterpiece.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
