<HEADLINE>
`CLOCKWATCHERS' IS A DARK COMEDY GEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Clockwatchers'' opened in New York months ago and it's already
slated to be released on video in October, so who knows why its
distributor waited so long to give it a wider release.
</P>
<P>
   It's a shame this little dark comedy gem may not have the chance
to find its audience because it's quite appealing and features a
nuanced, movie-stealing performance by art-house darling Parker
Posey.
</P>
<P>
   It might be easy to dismiss ``Clockwatchers'' as another
absurdist comedy like ``Nine To Five,'' but there are more things
happening in Jill Sprecher's sharp, detailed exercise about four
temps, or ``corporate orphans,'' who become friends and buck the
system while working for Global Credit.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the women has a dream. Margaret (Posey) is one of those
over-qualified rebels who really just wants (and deserves)
recognition and a title. The film's narrator, Iris (Toni Collette),
likes to write and observe, while Paula (Lisa Kudrow) fantasizes
about becoming an actress and Jane (Alanna Ubach) is about to be
married to a seemingly perfect guy.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of the story, written by Sprecher and her sister
Karen, is that it gives each woman a private life and a full
personality. And the characters aren't always pretty. There is a
real pathos at the core of the movie _ a statement on the way some
companies chew up their workers, continuing to hire contract labor
for whom there are no benefits or security, while demandiing the
same attitudes and professionalism as from the select group of
regular staffers.
</P>
<P>
   A clock ticks through most of the movie. It's a reminder that
time never stops, though in a job like this, it moves very slowly.
The four women find comfort in their bond, but soon it seems the
company is out to get them. A rash of thefts have immobilized the
office and because they're ``temps,'' and none of the staff people
who depend upon their skills even know their names, they're
immediately suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly the system breaks them apart with suspicions, doubts and
accusations. There will be no fraternizing while working, no
personal phone calls, and certainly no unwarranted socializing.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, watching ``Clockwatchers,'' which feels akin to Billy
Wilder's ``The Apartment'' in its depiction of the dashing of
corporate hopes, is almost like being at work instead of at the
movies. We're thrust into the grind with the women. It's to the
credit of the cast and director that we feel like we're buried in
the monotonous minutia handled by administrative ``assistants'' day
in and day out.
</P>
<P>
   All of the cast are terrific and bring a wonderful sense of
humanity and complexity to roles that get darker and more difficult
as the film progresses. Though Australian actress Toni Collette is
the focal point, and she's fun to watch as an insecure dowdy who
blossoms (much like her role in ``Muriel's Wedding''), it's Posey
who brings the real heart and soul to the party.
</P>
<P>
   She's funny, heart-breaking and deep as a smart cookie who can't
find a place in the work world because she's more capable than her
bosses. Her refusal to let them break her is her downfall as well
as her strength.
</P>
<P>
   Clockwatchers. Directed by Jill Sprecher. Written by Jill and
Karen Sprecher. Cast: Toni Collette, Parker Posey, Lisa Kudrow,
Alanna Ubach. Artistic License Films. 96 minutes. Rated PG-13 for
language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 1300EDT &QL; 
