<SLUG> BC-FILM-WAR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A MERRY WAR' IS A REASONABLY ENGAGING LIGHT SATIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Orwell is so synonymous with his downbeat look at the
future, ``1984'' (and to a lesser extent, his send-up of communism,
``Animal Farm'') that his very name has come to stand for absurdly
oppressive political misrule _ Orwellian.
</P>
<P>
   But he had a lighter side as well, and many Orwell scholars
actually prefer his cycle of semi-autobiographical novels written
in the early '30s: ``Down and Out in London and Paris,'' ``Burmese
Days'' and ``Keep the Aspidistra Flying.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Merry War'' is a film version of this last novel. In the
hands of British director Robert Bierman (``Vampire's Kiss''), it
makes a reasonably engaging light satire and '30s nostalgia piece,
if not exactly a laugh-out-loud comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Set in 1934 London, the surrogate Orwell character is Gordon
Comstock (Richard E. Grant), an angry young man who, as the film
opens, is in the process of quitting his job as the ace copywriter
of the New Albion Publishing Company for the higher calling of
poetry.
</P>
<P>
   The film follows his downward spiral as he tries to live the
bohemian life and is increasingly torn between his ideals of
poverty, art and honesty on the one hand, and middle-class
respectability and conformity (represented by a aspidisatra plant)
on the other.
</P>
<P>
   He's also a bit of a pompous twit, whose self-destructive streak
constantly forces him to bite the various hands that attempt to
help him: his waitress sister (Harriet Walter), his publisher best
friend (Jim Carter) and his long-suffering fiance (Helena Bonham
Carter).
</P>
<P>
   It's a movie that's likely to disappoint anyone who comes into
it with too high expectations. As satire, biography, or star
vehicle for the second-billed Helena Bonham Carter (who's basically
wasted in thankless role), it's nothing to get excited about.
</P>
<P>
   At its best, ``A Merry War'' is a literate, vaguely humorous,
never overly ambitious slice of '30s London life with pleasing
period detail, glitzy deco interiors and a slight Noel Coward edge
to the dialogue. Anglophiles should revel in it.
</P>
<P>
   So should fans of Richard E. Grant _ who's more commonly a
supporting player and the best thing in any movie he happens to be
in (``The Player,'' ``Ready to Wear''). His clever and
multi-leveled comic performance here makes this self-obsessed,
rather insufferable surogate-Orwell amazingly sympathetic, and
worthy of our attention.
</P>
<P>
   A Merry War. Directed by Robert Bierman. Screenplay by Alan
Plater. Cast: Richard E. Grant, Helena Bonham Carter, Jim Carter,
Harriet Walter. First Look Pictures. 101 minutes. Unrated.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 1300EDT &QL; 
