<HEADLINE>
`PERMANENT MIDNIGHT' OFFERS SOME EXCELLENT PERFORMANCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A couple of excellent performances are showcased in the
problematic story structure of ``Permanent Midnight,'' based on the
autobiographical tell-all of a double life by Jerry Stahl.
</P>
<P>
   Stahl was a novelist and writer in Hollywood who script-doctored
TV shows during the day while simultaneously addling his mind and
body with heroin and cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   As adapted by director David Veloz, the film uses a flashback
and narration format that doesn't work very smoothly, yet Ben
Stiller and Elizabeth Hurley turn in wonderfully gritty and
accomplished work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to shoot heroin, drink wheatgrass, run five miles every
day _ I was an L.A. junkie. I stayed fit,'' notes Jerry (Stiller)
to Kitty (Maria Bello), a fellow rehab veteran and ex-junkie. Kitty
picks Jerry up at a hamburger joint, where he's working a
low-paying job while doing his outpatient stint. He's in Phoenix
and is about to head home to L.A., the place where his high life
began and ended.
</P>
<P>
   The two begin a romance in a seedy motel. Jerry tells Kitty
about his pitiful descent in drug hell. Slowly, in flashbacks, he
unfolds his darkly tragi-comic tale, which includes a marriage of
convenience to the British Sandra (Hurley), who grows to love him
and becomes pregnant by him; his promising career and the
high-powered agent who wants to represent his work, and about the
birth of his daughter, Nina.
</P>
<P>
   Painfully, Jerry relays how each of these extraordinary
occurrences turns sour and unravels because of his addiction. His
story is funny, sad, harrowing, senseless and steeped in
self-loathing and anguish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Permanent Midnight'' refuses to romanticize Stahl and opts to
explore the despair and worthlessness behind the addict's need.
Unlike ``Leaving Las Vegas,'' a movie to which it bears more than a
passing resemblance, it refuses to turn its protagonist into a
lovable if wayward hero. Jerry is selfish and unable to care about
the people who believe in him or his talent. The film is more an
epistle about tough love than an elevation of bad behavior into
something to cheer about.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the credit goes to Ben Stiller. He is becoming a
surprisingly unconventional leading man these days though he's not
cut out of the usual movie star cloth and he doesn't emanate a lot
of warmth onscreen. Still, despite his willingness to go all out on
a limb, the relationships in the movie don't feel entirely true.
</P>
<P>
   While it's a cinematic staple to use a stranger as the catalyst
who changes a character's luck, Kitty isn't real _ she's Jerry's
fantasy projection. And Jerry's marriage to Sandra is given such an
off-handed, simplistic telling that we never understand their bond
or why Sandra sticks around as long as she does.
</P>
<P>
   While such flaws aren't fatal, they keep the film from having
the emotional depth and impact it might. Instead, like its
protagonist's life, the movie ultimately succeeds best at keeping
the viewer at an arm's distance.
</P>
<P>
   Permanent Midnight. Directed and written by David Veloz. Cast:
Ben Stiller, Elizabeth Hurley, Maria Bello, Owen Wilson, Cheryl
Ladd, Janeane Garofalo. Artisan Entertainment. 90 minutes. Rated R
for language, scenes depicting drug use.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
