<SLUG> BC-TV-FARMERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FARMER'S WIFE' A TOUGH ROW TO HOE FOR VIEWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Farmer's Wife'' is billed as a love story, and it is most
definitely a stirring account of one woman's commitment to her
marriage, her faith and her husband's dream.
</P>
<P>
   But David Sutherland's film about Juanita and Darrel
Buschkoetter's struggle to keep farming in the face of overwhelming
obstacles is not entirely successful because, for most of its
three-night run, it is unceasingly gloomy.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't Sutherland's fault. The filmmaker virtually lived
with the Buschkoetters for long periods over three years (1994-97)
to achieve a cinema verit &UR; gfacute &LR; e feel that is arresting and
alluring. But, over that three-year period, people with less
courage than Juanita Buschkoetter would have been driven todivorce,
maybe even violence. As a result, staying with the Buschkoetters
for just 6{ hours takes enormous willpower.
</P>
<P>
   Most disappointing is that Sutherland's camera missed the one
event _ an emotional outburst by Darrel Buschkoetter _ that
ultimately may have been the catalyst that changed the
Buschkoetters' lives. Still, for those of sturdy constitution,
``The Farmer's Wife'' provides more honest, intimate drama than a
month's worth of fictional prime-time fare.
</P>
<P>
   And, in the fine journalistic tradition of ``Frontline,'' the
film's real strength may lie in the questions it raises about the
wisdom of clinging at all costs to a noble but possibly outdated
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   The Farmer's Wife. A three-night, 6{-hour ``Frontline'' portrait
of a struggling young farm family in Nebraska. Check local listings
for times and air dates.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 1301EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
