<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-RUSH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAN ATTEMPTS TO BROADEN INTERNATIONAL APPEAL WITH `RUSH HOUR' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The collapse of the Hong Kong movie business during the last few
years has left Jackie Chan the biggest star of an industry that is
no longer solvent enough to pay him what he's worth on the world
market. As one journalist put it, he's become ``a head without a
body.''
</P>
<P>
   So, even though he's still that city's official tourist symbol,
he's increasingly become an American-financed international star _
transplanting his comic kung fu to the occidental settings of films
such as ``Rumble in the Bronx'' and ``Mr. Nice Guy.''
</P>
<P>
   And his new film, ``Rush Hour,'' is a calculated attempt to
significantly broaden that international appeal. For the first
time, he's teamed with an American comic _ Chris Tucker _ in a
formula Hollywood comedy with no kung fu credentials behind the
camera.
</P>
<P>
   It could pay off at the box-office, but die-hard Chan fans will
definitely find it one of his lesser efforts. He's so subdued and
overwhelmed by Tucker that he barely seems to be in the film, and
the Pacific Rim casting chemistry never really clicks.
</P>
<P>
   He plays a gentle Hong Kong cop who is sent to L.A. to help the
FBI and LAPD track down his old enemy, an ex-Hong Kong gang leader
(Ken Leung) who moved east after the '97 takeover and has just
kidnapped the 11-year-old daughter (Julia Hsu) of the Chinese
Consul (Tzi Ma).
</P>
<P>
   Considered a nuisance by the FBI, he's pawned off on the
maverick of the LAPD, an impossibly incompetent detective (Tucker),
who guides him around the city and gets him in heaps of trouble as
they bumble their way toward solving the case.
</P>
<P>
   Chan's natural sweetness shines through pleasantly here and
there, and he has one clever routine _ a sequence in which he tries
to save two gigantic, tottering Tang Dynasty vases at the same time
he's fighting off a small army of bad guys.
</P>
<P>
   But it's Tucker's movie, and most of it has the lanky star
abusing everyone in sight in a screechy, high-pitched voice that
plays like fingernails on a blackboard. The publicity (accurately,
for a change) bills him as ``the biggest mouth in the West.''
</P>
<P>
   Even by the loose standards of a throwaway action comedy, the
script is an insult to all reason, and the direction of Brett
Radner (Tucker's director in ``Money Talks'') is limp and
uninspired _ nothing close to the zip Sammo Hung gave Chan's last
film, ``Mr. Nice Guy.''
</P>
<P>
   With its explicit child abuse, its race-baiting humor and its
gleeful climatic destruction of a museum full of Chinese art
treasures, ``Rush Hour'' is also the first Jackie Chan movie that
often seems deliberately mean-spirited and distasteful.
</P>
<P>
   Rush Hour. Directed by Brett Ratner. Screenplay by Jim Kouf and
Ross LaManna. Cast: Jackie Chan, Chris Tucker, Tom Wilkinson, Chris
Penn, Elizabeth Pena. New Line Cinema. 97 minutes. Rated PG-13 for
violence and language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 1301EDT &QL; 
