<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-RITE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FIRST LOVE, LAST RITES' LOSES SOMETHING IN THE TRANSLATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hot, humid swamps of Houma, La., aren't the only thing that
are buggy and stagnant in this inert _ if atmospheric _ screen
adaptation of Ian McEwan's 1975 short story.
</P>
<P>
   The British writer has had other works transferred to the screen
with more success. ``The Comfort Of Strangers'' intrigued because
of its fine cast (and Venice setting) and ``The Cement Garden''
creepily transported the viewer into a world without adults where
lines cross and the story's teenage siblings can never return to
innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately ``First Love, Last Rites'' has none of those
beguiling concepts. This slight story of first love between two
young adults _ Sissel (Natasha Gregson Wagner) and Joey (Giovanni
Ribisi), who shack up in a single room and play house over the
long, hot summer _ initially engages with a creepy enough
undercurrent as Sissel's intense, scary father, Henry (Robert John
Burke), tries to ferret out Joey's intentions toward his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The two men have gone hunting, and are knee deep in the slime of
the bayou with eels and snakes skirting by. Henry shoots a bird and
orders Joey to fetch it, same as he might a dog. An ominousness
permeates the air. Will he shoot the boy because he's sleeping with
his daughter?
</P>
<P>
   No such luck. There are several hints of similar foreboding and
doom, but director Jesse Peretz chooses to skim over them and lands
with a thud in the end. All the gothic, over-the-top metaphors _ a
pregnant rat scratching in the wall that is a statement on Sissel's
female fecundity; eels snaking through Joey's nocturnal dreams of
Sissel, floating in red water, symbolizing his fear and desire _
are thrown to the wind in favor of a flat, conventional ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``First Love, Last Rites'' turns into a maudlin movie about the
``joys and sorrows of lovers everywhere'' and the tame attitude
that while love can be bliss, it can't last forever.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest lapse in judgment was trying to turn a short
story devoid of dramatic impetus into a feature-length movie in the
first place. David Ryan's script can't sustain itself and resorts
to repetitious, lingering filler shots of the couple sweatily
making love again and again.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the film becomes as claustrophobic as the squalid
single room the couple inhabit. And that's doubly infuriating. This
study in the decomposition and erosion of that first flush of
desire perfectly parallels the course of the movie itself. It's a
waste of time that makes us feel not only dulled, but duped.
</P>
<P>
   First Love, Last Rites. Directed by Jesse Peretz. Written by
David Ryan. Cast: Giovanni Ribisi, Natasha Gregson Wagner, Robert
John Burke, Jeanetta Arnette. Strand Releasing. 93 minutes. Rated R
for nudity, sexual content, language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
