FOR CLINTON, FORGIVENESS -- AND CONSEQUENCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Mike McManus is a syndicated columnist whose ``Ethics &AMP;
Religion'' appears in almost 100 newspapers)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or
fax her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By MIKE McMANUS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    A letter this week to The Washington Post by Rich Davis of
Lawrence, Kan., begins, ''If actions speak louder than words, here
is what our children can learn from our president:''
 &HT;    --Women are sex objects.
 &HT;    --Honesty is not the best policy.
 &HT;    --Rules are for losers.
 &HT;    --If you are contrite, they can't indict.
 &HT;    --Never accept responsibility for your wrongdoing.
 &HT;    --Character doesn't matter.
 &HT;    Yet what have adults have learned from reading the ghastly Starr
Report? Absolutely nothing. They still approve of Clinton's job
performance by 66 percent in an NBC poll Wednesday.
 &HT;    Where are the nation's clergy, America's moral leaders on this
issue? With few exceptions they are either beguiled by his charm;
or, if outraged, have remained scandalously silent.
 &HT;    At a White House prayer breakfast, Clinton made his best
confession yet: ``I don't think there is a fancy way to say that I
have sinned. It is important to me that everybody who has been hurt
know that the sorrow I feel is genuine,'' mentioning Monica
Lewinsky for the first time.
 &HT;    He smoothly talked about the need for ''genuine repentance, a
determination to change and to repair breeches of my own making.''
Using David's phrase in Psalm 51, he spoke of having a ''broken
spirit.''
 &HT;    Oh, he was crushed, all right. Five sentences later he announced
what he would do about his sin: ''I will instruct my lawyers to
mount a vigorous defense using all available, appropriate
arguments.''
 &HT;    What arguments? Over the weekend, his lawyers continued to
maintain Clinton's contention that he was ''legally accurate'' in
stating that he did not have sexual relations with Ms. Lewinsky. So
the lies of his hired guns continue, in flat contradiction to his
confession of sin.
 &HT;    Yet pastors who heard him last Friday were moved. The Rev. J.D.
Jakes, a popular Dallas preacher, said, ''Americans can relate to
his human frailty and are looking to see if it's possible to
restore fallen people.''
 &HT;    Rev. Robert Franklin, director of Atlanta's Interdenominational
Theological Center, gushed, ''It was a scene of biblical
proportions.''
 &HT;    Such clergy are confusing forgiveness with justice.
 &HT;    Chuck Colson, a White House aide to President Nixon, recalls:
''Twenty-five years ago, I became a Christian in the midst of
Watergate. I asked forgiveness for my sins and I knew God forgave
me.
 &HT;    ``But I also knew I had to pay the consequences for breaking the
law. I pled guilty and went to prison.''
 &HT;    If the president were truly contrite, he would not only
acknowledge that he has committed perjury, encouraged Monica
Lewinsky to lie, and tried to silence her with gifts and a New York
job, but he would put the nation ahead of his own desire to be
president, and resign.
 &HT;    Since he is unlikely to take this honorable step, Congress must
impeach him.
 &HT;    Colson says, ''Impeachment, remember, is essential to preserve
the rule of law because under our Constitution, a sitting president
cannot be indicted for crimes. So the only way to make him subject
to the law, and preserve the rule of law, is through the
impeachment process.''
 &HT;    Colson prays Clinton is repentant, and that Americans will
forgive. ''But that doesn't mean he's entitled to avoid the
consequences of his sin. If the law has been broken, justice
demands a penalty be paid. Congress therefore must do its duty and
decide if the facts warrant impeachment.''
 &HT;    The Rev. Terry Fullam, an Episcopal priest and my former pastor,
recalled that the thief hanging on the cross next to Jesus showed
both contrition and justice in saying, ''We are punished justly,
for we are getting what our deeds deserve. But this man has done
nothing wrong.''
 &HT;    In an interview, George Gallup noted that at the beginning of
the Watergate hearings in June 1973, a Gallup Poll found only 19
percent of the American people felt Nixon should be impeached.
 &HT;    By the end of the year, it rose to 35 percent, still quite low.
 &HT;    But after a House committee voted for impeachment, 65 percent
supported the step, Gallup said.
 &HT;    Let the hearings begin.
 &HT;    As one insider put it, ''President Clinton can not be trusted in
any decision. He should go. He has lost all credibility, all moral
leadership. Why limp along for two more years?''
 &HT;    Or our children will learn more lessons, as Rich Davis puts it:
 &HT;    --Anything goes if you are not caught.
 &HT;    --A clever lie is admirable.
 &HT;    --Blame others if you are caught doing something wrong.
 &HT;    --Break your marriage vows with impunity.
 &HT;    --You may not judge others (hear that, parents?) if you are not
perfect.
 &HT;    --Sex has nothing to do with love.
 &HT;    --Falsely swearing under oath carries no penalty.
 &HT;    --Cheaters usually prosper.
 &HT;    --Apologies serve as punishment.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.1998 Mike McManus
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
