<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0441 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-17 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT TAKES A VILLAGE TO RAISE AN IDIOT 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As hard as it is to believe, there are a few
things that haven't been said about Bill Clinton. Here are some
questions I haven't heard, and they're questions for both Clinton
apologists and the First Apologist himself:
</P>
<P>
   What if a married, 50ish professor had an affair with a young
woman at his university? How would the parents of the student feel?
What if the professor was president of the university?
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is the parent of a young woman attending a university.
He probably would understand the anger that would be directed at a
university president who violated the trust of parents, students,
the university and the community at large by having such a
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   A university president could not escape responsibility by
claiming it was a private affair.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, we have higher expectations of college
presidents than the president of the country. If a college
president had an affair with a student, he'd be fired, with no
chance of keeping his job by taking weekly ``spiritual counseling''
sessions with pastors.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what Clinton is doing now that his affair with
Monica Lewinsky is an open 445-page dirty book. Spiritual
counseling? That's more embarrassing than impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   One of Clinton's pastors is the Rev. Gordon MacDonald, who wrote
a book about recovering from adultery called ``Rebuilding Your
Broken World.'' He says Clinton has read it twice. There's a
self-help book that doesn't help, or else says ``Help yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Other embarrassments: Clinton called Sammy Sosa to congratulate
him on his 62nd home run. Can anybody really talk to Clinton on the
phone again?
</P>
<P>
   You see how much this scandal has cost us.
</P>
<P>
   You know, Americans have peculiar ideas about the power of their
presidents.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, Americans think a president controls the
economy, and vote for or against him accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Americans excuse a president for failing to
control his urges when a needy young woman flashes her
big-and-beautiful thong underwear.
</P>
<P>
   And we let him have a button that can end the world, hoping it
isn't in a place where someone can accidentally lie down on it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, we keep hearing the same stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Not counting ``Everybody lies about sex'' (which everybody says
without giving personal examples), the three most popular phrases
of the month are: ``Kennedy did it too,'' ``Let's move on'' and
``He's doing a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kennedy did it too.'' There's an excuse. ``I read that another
guy ran a red light, officer, so you can't give me a ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, Clinton has been caught in the act, even if it was
by monomaniacal Kenneth Starr. And he was stupid enough to perform
the act while he was being sued for sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, Roosevelt and Jefferson weren't caught. Reporters may
have gone easy on Kennedy and Roosevelt, but there were Matt Drudge
equivalents in Jefferson's day, and they hounded the Founding
Father with unfounded rumors about whom he had fathered.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was a champ at cheap womanizing, but we didn't know it
at the time. If we had known he was unfaithful to Jackie, he would
have been keelhauled beneath the Honey Fitz.
</P>
<P>
   People forget that Kennedy didn't become a really popular
president until after he died. Clinton will be popular forever _
unless the economy goes down as fast as his zipper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's move on.'' As if.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, we want this mess to go away. It won't. Republicans
are constructing an impeachment process that, if they time it
right, should last until approximately 8 p.m. of Election Day in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment will fail. The Republicans don't have enough on
Clinton except embarrassing his party and the country. Clinton will
never resign. He doesn't have a dime. He doesn't have anywhere to
go, except to the Clinton Library &AMP; Peep Show.
</P>
<P>
   A resolution to censure Clinton could have the same effect it
had on Andrew Jackson _ put his picture on our money.
</P>
<P>
   We're stuck with the incredible shrinking president for the rest
of his term. At least his adventures are fun to watch.
</P>
<P>
   It's like an action movie where the bad guys can't kill the
leading man, no matter how many bullets they shoot at him. Like
those action movies, Clinton's presidency has no content.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing a good job.'' Yes, he's doing a good job of being a
vacuum of principle, creating teeny-tiny policies that do nothing,
distributing more wealth to the rich, taking benefits away from the
poor and destroying any chance Democrats might have against the
real Republicans, as opposed to Clinton's imitation Republicanism.
</P>
<P>
   From the first month of his presidency, when he dumped Zoe Baird
and Kimba Wood as nominees for attorney general because they had
nanny problems, he's done a good job of selling out his allies for
personal advantage. He's done a good job being the president for
the '90s. Tall. Sensitive. Articulate. Intelligent above the waist.
Flawed. Fake.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, that's what the people want. To quote the man
himself, I'm sorry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
