<HEADLINE>
TAKE COVER: TV LAUNCHES ITS AUTUMN BOMBS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 20)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's get right to it. This is what you need to know about the
fall network television season:
</P>
<P>
   _ The vast majority of the new shows are either mediocre, bad,
or oh-well-these-shoes-are-ruined bad. That's the way it is every
year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Still, I counted eight shows (out of 35 reviewed) worthy of
getting a good review: ``That 70's Show'' (Fox), ``Trinity'' (NBC)
``Buddy Faro'' (CBS), ``Felicity'' (WB) ``Seven Days'' (UPN) and
``Sports Night,'' ``Fantasy Island'' and ``Cupid'' (ABC).
</P>
<P>
   When you count the two ABC summer series _ ``Whose Line Is It
Anyway?'' and ``Maximum Bob'' _ which may return at a later date,
it was a great off-season for that network.
</P>
<P>
   _ All that said, half the shows I listed above probably won't
catch on. In fact, three out of four of the new shows will end up
as tough trivia questions in two years.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you had a project about Irish, or with characters with
Irish-sounding names, or with characters who just know someone who
knows an Irishman, odds are it got on the air this fall. I counted
a half-dozen, with more coming up as mid-season replacements.
</P>
<P>
   _ Work-centered shows still dominate. But this season will see
more programs focused on families.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you have ever appeared on television before, including in a
crowd shot at a college basketball game, chances are you're
returning to TV this year. We said goodbye to Jerry, Larry, Murphy,
Dr. Quinn, Ellen, even Urkel. Now we get to say hello again to some
old characters, or at least the people who played them. Among the
returning veterans: Linda Lavin (``Barney Miller,'' ``Alice'') is
back. So is Steve Landesberg, whose Detective Arthur Dietrich on
``Barney Miller'' may have been the most interesting cop on
television. Both will be on ``Conrad Bloom.''
</P>
<P>
   Others resurrected include Bo Derek (the movie ``10'') and Lee
Horsley (``Matt Houston''), both of ``Wind on Water'' (here's a
suggestion: watch the show soon, before it gets canned), and Brian
Benben, the former star of ``Dream On'' who has a self-named sitcom
on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the younger crowd there are familiar faces. Shannen
Doherty, late of ``90210,'' is back with Aaron Spelling on the WB
show ``Charmed.'' When we last left Mark David Gosselaar, he was
the blond kid on ``Saved By the Bell.'' Today he is all grown up, a
brunette, on WB's ``Hyperion Bay.'' And Christina Applegate
(``Married ... With Children'') shows surprising range _ and brains
_ as a single mom in ``Jesse.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's not forget Rick (nee Ricky) Shroder, who has traded in his
silver spoons for a silver shield as a detective on ``NYPD Blue.''
Then there is the youngest crowd, and a crowd unto themselves: the
Olsen twins who star in the new show ``Two of a Kind.'' Scary as it
seems, cute little twins Mary-Kate and Ashley are now 11 and on the
verge of teendom.
</P>
<P>
   What else? Roseanne will have a talk show. ``Hollywood Squares''
is back, as is ``Fantasy Island.'' After last year's remake of
``Love Boat,'' anything '70s is fair game. Watch for ``Return of
The San Pedro Beach Bums.''
</P>
<P>
   This season will see four female actors from ``Twin Peaks'' on
various shows, including Sheryl Lee (``L.A. Doctors''), who played
the late Laura Palmer. Even dead people can rise again on
television.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same with bad television. It keeps coming back.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
