<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0470 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-PREVIEWS-FALL-$A     09-17 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PREVIEWS-FALL-$ADV20-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE AT PEAK AT SOME PROMISING MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 20)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As usual, fall arrives with a flood of new movie releases. And,
as usual, critics across the land respond by making vague
predictions about which films might actually prove worth seeing.
</P>
<P>
   Who really knows? In the movie industry, today's good buzz is
tomorrow's bomb (remember ``54''? You mean, you don't remember
``54''?). The only forecast worth reading _ or writing _ is one
that claims no inside knowledge whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   This claims none. With no further ado, and in the spirit of
unsullied moviegoing enthusiasm, what follows are a handful of fall
movies that this viewer looks forward to seeing.
</P>
<P>
   YOU'VE GOT MAIL. The notion of remaking James Stewart's ``The
Shop Around the Corner'' might be sacrilege for some, but think
about it _ who better to whip up a frothy Yuletide concoction than
director Nora Ephron and her cutie-pie stars from ``Sleepless in
Seattle''? Tom Hanks and Meg Ryan play bookshop rivals who
unwittingly woo via e-mail. Look for smart repartee and lots of
crinkling eyes. (Dec. 18).
</P>
<P>
   BELOVED. There are so many reasons to get excited about this
one: Jonathan Demme (``Philadelphia,'' ``The Silence of the
Lambs'') directed it; Oprah Winfrey, Thandie Newton and Danny
Glover star; Richard LaGravenese, who turned out elegant
screenplays for ``The Horse Whisperer'' and ``The Bridges of
Madison County,'' co-wrote the script; and it's based on the novel
by Toni Morrison, whose vivid, intensely emotional fiction has
never before been translated to the screen. The story concerns a
slave (Winfrey) haunted by the ghost of a dead child, so expect to
be devastated. (Oct. 16).
</P>
<P>
   THE PRINCE OF EGYPT. A grown-up cartoon from DreamWorks? About
the Israelites' enslavement in Egypt? Starring Val Kilmer as Moses,
and Ralph Fiennes as Ramses and Helen Mirren as the Queen of Egypt?
(Plus Steve Martin, Michelle Pfeiffer, Martin Short and Patrick
Stewart in supporting roles?) With music by Oscar-winning lyricist
Stephen Schwartz (``Pocahantas'')? What, no Happy Meals? No
adorable, wise-cracking sidekicks? Why not? (Dec. 18)
</P>
<P>
   THE THIN RED LINE. Terrence Malick's first movie since 1978's
``Days of Heaven'' _ and only his third, period (the other being
``Badlands'') _ is already getting plugged as That Other World War
II movie, a look at an American battalion at Guadalcanal. It's
based on James Jones' novel, and it boasts a monstrous cast: Sean
Penn, Adrien Brody, Ben Chaplin, Elias Koteas, George Clooney and
scads of others. No, it probably won't be ``Saving Private Ryan'';
Malick is a much less traditional storyteller than Spielberg, and
his films have genuine cult cache. That's why we're interested.
(Dec. 25).
</P>
<P>
   WHAT DREAMS MAY COME. Start weeping now: Robin Williams plays a
loving husband who croaks in a car accident, goes to Heaven, hooks
up with celestial angel Cuba Gooding Jr. and spends the rest of the
movie searching for his wife (Annabella Sciorra), who killed
herself in despair and has plunged straight to hell. From the
trailers, the film looks heavy on computer-generated Elysian
scenery and chest-thumping melodrama _ what makes it fascinating is
its director, Vincent Ward, who gave us the radiantly romantic
``Map of the Human Heart.'' Can't wait. (Oct. 2)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 1334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
