<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0502 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-GOVERN-BOS &LR;      09-17 1425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GOVERN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON BACKERS FEAR A POWERLESS PRESIDENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Key Democrats and several White House advisers now
believe that if President Clinton survives his crisis with a
censure, he will be rendered virtually ineffective for his final
two years in office, forced by a Republican Congress to abandon his
agenda and left without a moral pulpit from which to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, aides acknowledged, won't trust him. Republicans
won't respect him. And the public, though appreciative of his job
performance, won't hold him in a high enough personal regard to
allow him to represent the will of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton arrives in Boston this evening for several hours of
fund-raising, there is an uneasy but increasing sense of hope among
White House strategists and Democratic lawmakers that he will
overcome attempts to impeach him for his adulterous affair with
Monica S. Lewinsky and his subsequent pattern of lies. Still, that
hope is entangled in the reality of what Clinton's survival might
actually mean, and Democrats publicly and privately portrayed even
the best case scenario in a skeptical light.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Senator John F. Kerry of Massachusetts said Clinton's
ability to function as president would be ``seriously diminished.''
Former Labor Secretary and Clinton confidant Robert Reich said
Wednesday that Clinton ``wouldn't be so much a lame duck as a dead
duck.''
</P>
<P>
   And Democratic Leadership Council President Al From, who worked
with Clinton to inject values into the party over the last several
years, declared, ``It doesn't help to have the leader of the
movement not exactly live up to the values of his politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The country is just not going to listen to him on any serious
internal matter,'' said Marc Landy, a professor on the modern
presidency at Boston College. ``People are focusing on the
immediate matter of the release of the tapes and that kind of
thing, but the big issue for the nation is a badly crippled
presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   One key Clinton adviser said the White House is warily looking
ahead to the November congressional elections and bracing for a
backlash if there are significant Democratic losses. At the same
time, Democratic leadership aides on Capitol Hill said that as
recently as early summer, they were anticipating a five- or
six-seat gain, but now fear a loss of 20 seats or more.
</P>
<P>
   All told, the Democrats hold 54 fewer seats in the House and 11
fewer seats in the Senate than when Clinton first took office, and
have lost majority control of both chambers under Clinton's
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``One fear is the toll of the losses,'' said a Clinton ally,
speaking on the condition of anonymity. ``How much water does the
party take on before it says we have to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Though aides said they are too consumed with simply fighting the
potential for impeachment to draw plans for the coming year,
several predicted Clinton will focus increasing swaths of his time
on economic problems and foreign affairs and the worldwide
financial crisis where the two issues meet. They expect he will
travel abroad even more than he has this year, but he may be unable
to gain congressional support on funding for the United Nations and
the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hope is he will find a way to carve out a sanctuary for
foreign policy,'' said David Gergen, a former adviser to Clinton at
times of crisis. ``He faces the very real process of a hollowed out
presidency. His chances of survival have gone up, but what price,
survival?''
</P>
<P>
   Other leaders and some scholars, pointing to Clinton's
propensity to do his best work when faced with his gravest crises,
declined to paint his presidency as virtually over. They routinely
point to other low points in his career, citing his loss of the
Arkansas governorship in 1980 followed by his comeback victory two
years later. Clinton badly fumbled his proposal to overhaul health
care in 1994 and saw his Democratic majority in Congress swept away
with his miscues. Shortly after, he seemed to plead for his own
relevance. But two years later, after compromising with Republicans
on welfare reform, he won reelection overwhelmingly in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He is perhaps the most chronicled president in modern history,
his strengths and failings analyzed in reams of books, novels,
documentaries and movies, his most obscure and deeply personal
characteristics bared for a nation to see. It is at times of public
humiliation, some analysts said, that Clinton summons his most
fervent desire to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a guy who's entire career has been a roller coaster,''
said Fred Greenstein, a presidential scholar at Princeton
University. At times of adversity, ``his remarkable talents then
become less a Slick Willie thing and instead focus on real problem
solving.''
</P>
<P>
   To many allies, Friday's release of the report by independent
counsel Kenneth W. Starr marked the beginning of a third
presidential campaign for Clinton _ the first two being about his
election, the current one for his redemption.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like we've gone back into election mode,'' said
Skip Rutherford, a Clinton friend and confidant from Little Rock,
Ark. ``And that's where he does his best work. Clinton has always
done best in a crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Representative Martin Meehan of Lowell said, ``He has
a better grasp of the challenges we face in the global economy and
the steps we need to take to restore growth than any president
we've had in a long, long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, meanwhile, are already sending signals that they
may force Clinton's hand in a compromise, if they are willing to
deal with him at all. Some members of the GOP already said Clinton
could affirm his belief in marriage by signing onto the Republican
plan to reduce taxes for married couples.
</P>
<P>
   ``Effectively govern? That remains to be seen,'' said Mike
Collins, a spokesman for the Republican National Committee. ``He
could sign our plan to eliminate the marriage penalty, for
starters.''
</P>
<P>
   Scholars have debated the actual importance of the so-called
moral pedestal or bully pulpit, with some believing it represents
the vast bulk of a president's power, especially when he faces a
Congress controlled by the opposing party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moral authority is a huge part of the presidency and has been
since the beginning, and he doesn't have any,'' said Landy, in an
opinion echoed by such noted presidential historians as Michael
Beschloss.
</P>
<P>
   But others argued that the bully pulpit is an overrated aspect
of the presidency _ ``mythology,'' declared Greenstein _ and that
moral leadership is no longer expected from a chief executive. Some
scholars point to Jimmy Carter, who always received high personal
favorability ratings from the country, but his job performance
ratings _ below 30 percent when he was defeated by Ronald Reagan in
1980 _ doomed his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very hard to count the number of times that moral
leadership is crucial to the presidency,'' said Stephen Hess, a
presidential scholar at the Brookings Institution. ``We are really
going overboard on the moral leadership we get or should expect
from the president.''
</P>
<P>
   In Clinton's case, he has spent years preaching the importance
of personal responsibility, and such a doctrine may no longer be
valid coming from his lips, analysts said. He has also become
increasingly comfortable in the last three years exercising his
moral authority from a bully pulpit, so much so that one of his
favorite speaking venues is the inside of a church.
</P>
<P>
   ``It now becomes harder to go to the public and ask for
sacrifice,'' said Gergen.
</P>
<P>
   Gone, aides conceded, will be Clinton's attempts at education
reform, including a multibillion-dollar request to rebuild
crumbling schools. Social Security reform will probably be lost, as
will efforts to mandate tighter regulations on health maintenance
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   If the Republicans do launch impeachment proceedings, Clinton's
entire ability to garner favorable news coverage on his policies
will be crippled for the next few months. If he recovers, he will
have less than a year before the nation begins focusing on the
primary campaigns for the 2000 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is going to have a hard time shifting public attention away
from these proceedings,'' Reich said. ``He has also lost a great
deal of respect and moral authority. His extraordinarily reckless
behavior is still not fully explained.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
