<HEADLINE>
MASSIVE CONCRETE SLAB FALLS ON EMPTY FIREHOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYCHE HENDRICKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A massive concrete slab plunged 32 stories from
a hotel construction site onto an adjacent firehouse, ripping
through the sleeping quarters and landing in the ground-floor
engine bay, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   But rescue personnel who responded to the firehouse Wednesday
night enjoyed a laugh of relief. The 15 firefighters who would
ordinarily have been getting ready for bed at Station No. 1 had
moved out three days earlier, in advance of structural work.
</P>
<P>
   The firefighters shook their heads as they surveyed the wreckage
caused by the 19,000-pound slab of concrete, measuring
8-feet-by-10-feet. It tore through the building about 9:30 p.m.
Wednesday. No one was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had crews been in the station, we would have had a very
different situation,'' Lt. Ed Campbell said. ``It would have been
really tragic.''
</P>
<P>
   The concrete slab had been destined for the side of the 32-story
Starwood Hotel, which is being built at the corner of Howard and
Third streets, next to the firehouse.
</P>
<P>
   A construction worker, who declined to give his name, said he
and his co-workers had been unloading several of the big panels
from a truck and using a crane to raise them to the top of the
roof. Working at night is standard practice, he said, because there
is less traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, two computer technicians were loading up
their van after an evening wiring computer networks in a bank
branch when they saw the panel fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We watched them take it off the street and saw them swing it
along the side of the building,'' said Robert Lynch, one of the
technicians. ``Then the cable snapped, and it came crashing right
down through the firehouse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There were strands of cable raining down _ like this,'' said
Lynch, holding up an eight-inch length of frayed and twisted wires.
``We jumped out of the way and ran for cover.''
</P>
<P>
   Station No. 1 is ordinarily one of the busiest in the city,
Campbell said. Because of the construction planned for the
firehouse, the firefighters had been reassigned to other stations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
