<HEADLINE>
INSULATION OLD HAT? NOT WHEN IT SAVES HEATING COSTS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ho hum. Insulation again? It may be old hat to owners of new
houses that are insulated and tightened up wonderfully. It may be
old hat to those who have slaved and worked and spent good money to
have their old houses insulated.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not old hat to thousands of homeowners who know
nothing about insulation or whose houses are not insulated or only
partially insulated.
</P>
<P>
   So, herewith the annual sermon on insulation. One often reads
many stories about where you should put insulation, but too often
these stories mention nothing on how to put that insulation in
place.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
What, where, how much, and how
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So, today's sermon will not only suggest what and where to put
it in, but also how much, and how to put it in.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that insulation is the chief way to save
heating fuel. You can put in a magnificant heating system, but if
there is no insulation or inadequate insulation, that fancy system
is simply pumping heat into the house, and right out again.
</P>
<P>
   OK, where to put insulation? What kind? And how much?
</P>
<P>
   In 25 words or less: in the attic floor, in walls and in the
basement ceiling. And, in the roof over an open space, such as a
room with a cathedral ceiling. (Sorry, it took 27 words.)
</P>
<P>
   What kind? Fiberglass is still the state-of-the art material,
because it is not only a good insulator but also is flexible, able
to be put into virtually any space snuggly but not too snuggly, and
certainly not too loosely. And it is the best and easiest material
for the do-it-yourselfer to work with.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Protective clothing
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One word of caution: When dealing with any kind of insulation,
wear a mask and protective clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Cellulose is also a good choice, but mostly for blowing in the
walls or blowing into the attic floor.
</P>
<P>
   There are rigid insulations such as Styrofoam or (get this
word): polyisocyanurate, a modified urethane foam with brand names
such as Thermax and High R Sheathing. These are generally used in
new construction, and not commonly in old houses. They could be put
on the inside or outside walls of such old houses, but that would
require rebuilding walls indoors or applying new siding walls
outdoors, an elaborate, expensive undertaking.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Both types are ``best buys''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So, fiberglass and cellulose are the most common materials to
use, in new or old construction. Both are ``best buys,'' the least
expensive building materials that do the most good. Insulation
costs 25 cents and up per square foot, depending on its thickness.
That is inexpensive, if you do it yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor that complicates the insulation process is a
house that is partially insulated. We will get to that, too.
</P>
<P>
   How much insulation? Often it's what fits in the cavity. But in
places like attic floors, the sky's the limit; you can put in as
much as 18 inches of fiberglass. That gives an R factor of 57,
virtually maximum. There is little point in adding more because you
will get diminishing returns; anything additional will do less
good.
</P>
<P>
   We are not going to get into R factors, because they don't mean
a lot; more important is the thickness of the insulation, which is
restricted in all places except attic floors. An R factor, for the
record, is a measurement of resistance (that is where the R comes
in) to passage of heat from a heated area through a barrier to a
cold area. The more that barrier is insulated, the less heat will
be lost.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Attic floor: A good place to start
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shall we begin? On the attic floor. Buy fiberglass batts or
rolls 6 inches thick and as wide as the space between joists; You
can get insulation 15 and 23 inches wide, enough to fit snugly
between joists 14 1/2 and 22 1/2 inches apart, respectively. Make
the fit snug, but not so snug that it undulates, or so loose that
it leaves gaps.
</P>
<P>
   If there is no insulation on the floor, buy insulation backed by
kraft paper, or foil, which is a vapor barrier. This backing goes
down touching the ceiling below. In fact, all vapor barriers go on
the side of the space facing the heated space.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Add a little, too
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You can add another 6 inches of unbacked insulation, or
8-inch-thick Poly-wrap, Owen Corning's insulation wrapped in
perforated polyethylene. Other companies make similar products. The
poly makes it easy to move, especially over existing insulation,
and easier and safer to handle. If the insulation comes up to the
tops of the joists, add a second layer at right angles to the
joists. You can add a third layer of 6- or 8-inch insulation, but
that is enough.
</P>
<P>
   I know of one man who said the insulation in his attic floor
comes up to his belly button. That is too much.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
