<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
_IN SURVEY, GUN OWNERS BACK TOUGHER LAWS   
 _FOR SOME, MENOPAUSE IS CHANGE FOR BETTER   
 _SUPERMARKET REMEDY TOPS FOR TOOTH PAIN  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 
 In survey, gun owners back tougher laws
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New England Journal of Medicine is focusing on an issue not
always considered foremost as a question of public health _ gun
control _ with a survey showing strong support, even among gun
owners, for restricting gun sales and toughening gun safety
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Every hour, guns are used to kill four Americans. Studies
sponsored by the American Medical Association and American College
of Physicians estimate medical treatment cost $145,000 per 1997
gunshot survivor. The Physicians for Social Reponsibility asserts
gun violence costs the United States $20 billion a year, including
medical costs and lost productivity.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Gun Policy and Research at the Johns Hopkins
School of Public Health in Baltimore conducted two telephone
surveys of 1,200 adults over the last three years, and found:
</P>
<P>
   _88 percent of respondents favor laws to make new guns
childproof, including 80 percent of gun owners.
</P>
<P>
   _71 percent favor ``personalization'' devices allowing only
rightful owners to use guns, including 59 percent of gun owners.
</P>
<P>
   _Between 83 and 95 percent of respondents _ and more than seven
of 10 gun owners _ favor banning gun sales to people convicted of
domestic violence, assault, menacing someone with a gun, or drunk
and disorderly conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``To make progress in preventing deaths and injuries from
firearms, it is necessary to break the existing stalemate in the
debate on gun policy'' over the constitutional right to own guns,
the survey team led by Hopkins's Stephen P. Teret writes in the
current journal. They urged ``serious consideration'' of measures
to ``make it more difficult for guns to be passed from legal to
illegal users.''
</P>
<P>
   In an accompanying editorial, David Hemenway of the Harvard
School of Public Health said that the same strategies that have
been used to ensure safer use of automobiles, chainsaws, and lawn
mowers should be brought to bear on ``the gun, which, per minute of
use, is probably the most dangerous of all such products.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; For some, menopause is change for better
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From the tone of most medical news coverage, it may sound as
though menopause is an unending horror show of plunging estrogen
levels, hot flashes, moodiness, osteoporosis, and heart disease.
But a survey suggests many women find it is not so bad.
</P>
<P>
   A new Gallup survey of 752 US women aged 50 to 65 who had
reached that time of life found that 51 percent said they had never
felt as ``fulfilled and happy'' as they do now. When the other 49
percent were asked to name the most satisfying time of their lives,
10 percent said their 20s, 17 percent their 30s and 16 percent
their 40s.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was released Wednesday at the beginning of the North
American Menopause Society annual meeting in Toronto. The group's
executive director, Dr. Wulf H. Utian, told the Associated Press
that despite the frequent news about ``the negative impacts of
growing older ... when we ask women, we continually hear that they
view menopause as the beginning of many positive changes in their
lives and health.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Supermarket remedy tops for tooth pain
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two studies on tooth and jaw pain: Ibuprofen and other common
pain relievers may work better than prescription narcotics in
easing the pain of tooth extraction, contends a Minnesota oral
surgeon who led a $1 million federally funded study of wisdom tooth
removal operations.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Q. Swift of the University of Minnesota School of
Dentistry said at an oral surgeons' conference in New Orleans
Wednesday that patients who were not told what they were getting
enjoyed twice as much pain relief from ibuprofen as from
prescription painkillers such as codeine. But in practice, Swift
said, the ``placebo effect'' makes people think something the
doctor prescribes works better than a supermarket remedy.
</P>
<P>
   Other research being presented at the American Association of
Oral and Maxillofacial Surgeons meeting indicates that chlamydia,
the sexually transmitted disease that can make women infertile,
also aggravates temporomandibular joint, or TMJ, jaw pain. Dr. Alan
Hudson of the Wayne State University School of Medicine, one of the
researchers, found that chlamydia bacteria were 100 to 200 times
more likely to be found in women TMJ patients than the general
population, so more TMJ patients should be screened for chlamydia
and the link between it and TMJ studied further.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
