<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUFFOLK TRIES OUT NEW TRACK SURFACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Suffolk Downs opens its fall meeting Sept. 26, it will
become the first track to test the Polytrac surface. Polytrac is
composed of sand treated with an oil-based polymer, and the East
Boston track has installed a 100- by 80-foot section covering the
6-furlong chute. The chute is the straightaway past the backstretch
where sprinters start before reaching the main track.
</P>
<P>
   Polytrac was developed by Chuck Beardon, president of North
Carolina-based Polytrac Systems Inc. Polytrac, which will never
turn sloppy, is a successor to Equitrack, which was tried several
years ago at Remington Park. Equitrack also prevented sloppy tracks
but turned to molasses under the broiling Oklahoma sun and was
abandoned. Beardon was called in as a consultant during the
Remington trial and has found a way to keep Polytrac from melting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to see how the horses do with it,'' said Suffolk
vice president Lou Raffetto, who has been working with Beardon on
the project and believes his track will one day be entirely covered
with Polytrac. ``It will help sore horses because it has bounce to
it. In that way, it will be therapeutic. There is no bounce in
plain sand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, the horses should get a better break at the start
because the material is firm; it won't break away under their
hooves. That's why we started with the chute.
</P>
<P>
   ``There won't be any slop with Polytrac because the surface
becomes like that of a Teflon pan _ water just beads on it and runs
right off. What broke down Equitrack was the ultraviolet rays of
the sun. Chuck went back to the lab and found a way to keep that
from happening. Plus, Equitrack broke down in extreme heat,
temperatures of 100-110 degrees in Oklahoma. We don't have that
kind of heat around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Suffolk purchased 12,600 square feet of Polytrac on an
experimental basis. It was put down over Labor Day weekend. Patrons
will be able to spot it with ease because it is considerably darker
than the regular sand portion of the track. Raffetto estimates the
cost of covering the entire surface would by upward of $400,000,
but he feels the advantages of having a near ``all-weather'' track
might be worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of it,'' he said. ``If this material works, there will
be no scratches because of a sloppy track. Sore horses can race
more often because the track is so kind. There would be fewer days
with a bias, less inside-outside stuff, because the surface would
be so consistent. The only days we would lose a card to weather
would be when it snows.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
