<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEWINSKY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN VOICE WIDE RANGE OF OPINION ON LEWINSKY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN O'BRIEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When little was known about Monica S. Lewinsky, it was easy to
cast the White House intern as the wide-eyed ingenue with a crush,
wearing a Donna Karan black beret to catch the eye of the president
of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Now Lewinsky is just as well known for her thong underwear and
her aggressive sexual attitude, revealed in the testimony she
provided about a seduction she wanted desperately to continue, and
complete.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Lewinsky's place in history will be decided mainly
by women. They will be the ones to say whether she should find a
seat among the women who have been used by men in positions of
power _ men who have indulged in women's crushes and immature
fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   Or they'll decide whether Lewinsky, like Clinton, should
apologize to the country for her behavior. And whether she should
take responsibility for making a mockery of her opportunity to
work, and network, in the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   The White House scandal has launched yet another set of bad
office jokes, and disgusting Internet games, centered on sex and
women in the workplace, and many who have fought for equal
oppurtunities in offices _ and equal partnerships in sexual
relationships and marriages _ say Lewinsky has provided a sorry
image of young professional women.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a curious kind of dilemma you are in if you are a
feminist,'' said Anne Bernays, a Boston &UR;  &LR; novelist.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are a feminist, the word `slut' doesn't figure because
women should have the same sexual freedom as a man does, and if she
wants him, she should be able to do whatever she can.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bernays believes Lewinsky's attempts to manipulate Clinton
into providing her a better job flies in the face of feminist
principles that frown on women who buy into a system that
encourages them to sleep their way to the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you add the fact of the employer and the employee, then
it complicates things. And she felt that he owed her something _ a
job? Where does that come from? She is as far from being a feminist
as almost anybody can be. It's very complicated for us.''
</P>
<P>
   But for some women, the issue is clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had a lot of women tell me `Well, she is a kid,'' said
Dotty Volpe, 49, a former Democratic Party worker who owns ``The
Redecorators,'' a Boston &UR;  &LR; home-improvement business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I was married at 21, and I knew right from wrong,'' said
Volpe, who is married to her second husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not to say that I have always made right choices, but
no one can tell me that Monica Lewinsky didn't know what she was
getting into. I really think she owes everybody and apology _ the
whole country.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston attorney Susan Howards, 44, who specializes in
sexual-harassment cases, said she has tried, but cannot find much
sympathy for Lewinsky, and considers her more of a vixen than a
victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had a chance that many young women of her generation would
have relished, and she didn't use it properly,'' Howards said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am appalled,'' she added. ``If that were my daughter, I
would be on television, apologizing to the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   But others are slower to blame the girl whose inexperience came
shining through the pages of the report prepared by Independent
Counsel Kenneth W. Starr, with Lewinsky's references to the movie
``Titanic,'' so popular with lovestruck teens across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Many women shared a collective groan, some recognizing
themselves, when they read that Lewinsky fantasized about Clinton's
life changing so that they might be together.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's emotional, young, naive and starstruck,'' said Amy
Mcdonald, a 40-year-old mother of one who has delved into
Lewinsky's psyche with female friends in recent days. ``Yes, she's
aggressive and manipulative. But I don't blame her. I don't blame
her at all. He was responsible for saying `No.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Lauren Walker, a Philip Johnson Associates Inc.
marketing writer, went as far as to congratulate Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she has showed a lot of integrity for someone her
age,'' said Walker, 40. ``I think it's interesting that, in her
testimony, she has never portrayed herself as a victim. You know,
for a kid, that is not bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most women are fairly harsh about it. I think they
sort of sound like she is some kind of bad person, or an idiot,''
said Walker. ``Instead, I see her as human.''
</P>
<P>
   With age, there is apparently more empathy for Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Blackham is Republican committeewoman for the 2nd Middlesex
District, and, in the early 70s, headed the Governor's Commission
on the Status of Women. She disagrees with those who say Lewinsky
should shoulder half the blame for the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say that I have a lot of pity and compassion for her,''
said Blackham, who heads Ann Blackham Inc. Realtors in Winchester.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she is a wild-eyed and impressionable woman,'' said
Blackham.
</P>
<P>
   She said many healthy young women could fall prey to Clinton, or
other men with extroardinarly clout.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was about that age, I was just getting involved in
politics,'' said Blackham, who is 71. ``You are kind of mystified
by the whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it, if he's attractive, and seems to be coming on
to you, at that age, you feel so complimented.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoki Bacon, a Boston socialite and self-described
Depression-era Democrat, said she and her grown daughters have
lamented Lewinsky's actions, and her having confused the issue of
``real'' victims of sexual harrassment and abuse in schools and
workplaces.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, she said, is not a victim in the traditional sense,
but a product of a system that encourages young women to identify
themselves with a man in power.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as men hold all the power, there will be this
temptation,'' Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that is the great tragedy here, that there was an
attempt at power through intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a setback.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
