<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE POSTPONES VOTE ON VISAS FOR HIGHLY SKILLED IMMIGRANTS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By CHRISTI HARLAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republican leaders Thursday postponed a
planned vote on increasing the number of H-1B visas for highly
skilled foreign workers, citing a shortfall in Democratic support
for the measure.
</P>
<P>
   At least 30 Democratic votes are needed, because Republicans
don't have the full support of their members for a measure that
would immediately allow 30,000 more foreign workers into the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation has been awaiting a full House vote since May
20, when the House Judiciary Committee approved a bill that would
raise the number of visas from the current annual cap of 65,000.
The committee's version also required employers to attest that they
had tried to hire U.S. workers and that no U.S. workers had been
laid off from jobs being filled by foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
   House leaders, bowing to pressure from the computer industry and
other business groups that want the additional visas, are pushing
for passage of a bill that will provide more H-1B visas without
demanding more from employers. The next attempt at a vote may come
Wednesday, when the House reconvenes after Rosh Hashanah, the
Jewish New Year.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
