<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILENE'S BASEMENT PLANNING WEEKEND-ONLY CHAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Filene's Basement Corp., its sales sputtering and its stock
marked down to just over 2, will soon roll out a new chain of
discount stores that will open only on the weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Steven R. Siegel, Filene's Basement chief financial officer,
said in an interview that the company planned to open eight of the
new stores next year, starting in the spring. He wouldn't discuss
locations except to say all will be east of the Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Others are playing at the weekend-warrior retailing game.
Dallas-based Tuesday Morning Corp. has nearly 300 deep-discount
closeout stores that carry everything from housewares to toys to
seasonal items and open just four times a year for six- to 10-week
``events'' during peak selling seasons. Atlanta-based K&AMP;G Men's
Centers Inc. has 29 apparel superstores, operating only on the
weekends. And the Westwood, Mass.-based Frugal Fannie's chain
operates seven women's stores that open only on the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The point is to be open when people shop and keep payroll costs
low. Wellesley, Mass.-based Filene's Basement, like the others,
will put its stores in low-cost strip malls and even industrial
space. Those in the commercial real estate business say such
part-time retailers often end up with leftover locations because
other tenants in a strip mall, for instance, don't like having the
stores closed most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that it is executed well, it is a very, very
good concept,'' says Kurt Barnard, president of Barnard's Retail
Trend Report in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel said the stores would be far larger than the traditional
Filene's Basement outlets and far cheaper to open. The stores,
including warehouse space, would be up to 80,000 square feet, with
about 50,000 square feet devoted to selling. By contrast, the
newest Filene's Basement, set to open Oct. 1 in Ft. Lauderdale,
Fla., is just 28,000 square feet. Siegel estimated the cost of
opening one of the new stores at a third or less than a traditional
Basement store.
</P>
<P>
   The new chain will carry women's and men's apparel and
housewares and emphasize brand names, Siegel said. The stores will
be open Friday through Sunday. He would not discuss the name.
</P>
<P>
   Filene's Basement could use a boost.
</P>
<P>
   The stock has been crushed even more than other retailers in the
big market sell-off, falling 65 percent since May to 2 1/4. George
Sutton, a retail analyst for Dain Rauscher Wessels, said Filene's
Basement ``has consistently missed the plan'' for both sales and
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   August was a particularly bad month, when sales at stores open
more than a year, a key retail measure, fell 6 percent compared
with the year earlier. Those same-store sales had been up for the
previous six months. ``We had a terrible August for a variety of
reasons,'' Siegel said.
</P>
<P>
   For the first six months of the year, the company earned
$255,000, or 1 cent a share diluted, down from earnings of $1.75
million, or 8 cents a share diluted, in the same period in 1997.
The company's results have been hurt, in part, because of a
February fire at its Auburn, Mass. distribution center; the company
has said it expects to recover those losses through its insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Even as it plans to launch a new chain, Filene's Basement has
pushed ahead with its traditional stores. It has opened five stores
this year and will open the sixth in Florida next month, its first
move into the Southeast. That will push the total to 51.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Talk about September slumps. The Red Sox look like absolute
champs compared with the market for initial public offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Through Wednesday, the IPO market was 0 for 16 for the month of
September; not one of the initial offerings in the pipeline has
been completed this month.
</P>
<P>
   With the stock market in flux, the last IPO came Aug. 27; the
last Massachusetts IPO was July 31, says Richard J. Peterson of
Securities Data Corp. IPOs were booming in June, when there were 63
deals worth $9.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The average loss since the offering date for Massachusetts's 11
IPOs this year is 6.2 percent, compared with a loss of 15.3 percent
for all such deals, says Securities Data.
</P>
<P>
   Look for some deals still to happen this month. No deals, no
fees for investment bankers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
