<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980917.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0525 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSH-HASHANAH-SHTETL-     09-17 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSH-HASHANAH-SHTETL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR JEWS A TIME TO REPENT -- AND REMEMBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York Times
Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative CONNIE
WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or fax
her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By RABBI ELI HECHT  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Sunday night, Jews will gather in homes and houses of prayer to
usher in the Jewish New Year, called Rosh Hashanah; literally the
beginning of the year.
 &HT;    The holiday is marked by prayer, the blowing of a ram's horn,
called a shofar, and the dipping of an apple in honey, symbolic of
wishes for a sweet year. A festive meal includes kosher chicken and
wine, making it a special day.
 &HT;    It is considered by Jews as a day for repentance, an auspicious
time to make new resolutions.
 &HT;    This Jewish New Year I hope and pray that many of my Jewish
brothers and sisters will find time to attend a Rosh Hashanah
service, giving thanks to Almighty God and to this great country
where we can pray freely in our houses of worship.
 &HT;    Living in a free country where we can practice religion of our
choice is one of our greatest assets.
 &HT;    However, I am reminded of the times when this could not be done,
when Jews would have to hide their religion in order to practice.
 &HT;    Let me share a sad story I heard while growing up with
post-World War II refugees in Brooklyn. My teacher, a survivor,
would tell us this most horrifying story.
 &HT;    In a small shtetl called Eisysky, over 4,000 Jews were gathered
around their synagogue. There they were met by their Lithuanian
neighbors, who had joined the German tyrants in carrying out the
Final Solution eradication of the Jewish presence in that area. The
day was the Jewish New Year, Rosh Hashanah, September 1941.
 &HT;    Drunken Lithuanian guards packed the synagogue with as many Jews
as possible. Families stood in fear as the guards formed them into
groups. You could see a mother, father, son, daughter, grandson,
granddaughter, and even some great-grandchildren all huddled
together.
 &HT;    The groups were then taken to open ditches near the Jewish
cemetery, stripped of their clothing and killed. The Lithuanian
guards took their time in shooting indiscriminately, killing
generations of people, ending the 800 years of Jewish existence for
the town of Eisysky.
 &HT;    Local neighbors, some of whom had been friends of the
unfortunate Jews, were caught up in the wholesale slaughter. Some
cheered while others robbed the homes of the unfortunate victims.
 &HT;    Yet there were the few who cried inwardly, not knowing what do.
 &HT;    The volleys of the rifle shots felled family after family.
Bodies of the dying and the dead would be rolled into the pit and a
fresh group would be brought, stripped naked, and shot.
 &HT;    The diabolical commander of the guards, a man named Ostrovaks,
wore an immaculate uniform covered with a starched white apron and
matching gloves. All day, he would personally give the order to
shoot.
 &HT;    When he saw the respected Rabbi Shimon Rovowsky come dressed in
his Shabbos clothing, together with the town cantor who was wrapped
in a Jewish prayer shawl, holding the Torah scrolls, Ostrovaks
announced that he must do the killing himself.
 &HT;    He took great pleasure in shooting the rabbi, the cantor and
then the children. He loved shooting them as they were thrown over
into the ditches. It was a strange and horrible time in the killing
fields of Eisysky.
 &HT;    On this sad day a young boy, Zevy, stood naked with his father
at an open pit. Any second now the bullet would arrive, ending his
life.
 &HT;    By the mercy of God the 16-year-old Zevy fell into the pit
alive. He fell upon a group of bodies. The bullets rang out and a
new wave of bodies piled on top of him.
 &HT;    Lying there, he heard cries of anguish and pain into the night.
Zevy was completely covered with blood and dead and dying people.
 &HT;    In the middle of the night he cautiously climbed out of the pit.
The silence of the dead was deafening.
 &HT;    As far as he could see were the bodies of his fellow Jews. What
had been a vibrant Jewish community was now gone forever.
 &HT;    Naked and bloody, he began his walk out of the cemetery, toward
the homes of his friends.
 &HT;    Arriving at the home of Pavel, a peasant, he was surprised to
see piles of booty taken from the Jews. Looking through the window
he saw the Lithuanians eating and drinking.
 &HT;    What could he do? he thought. He banged on the door and yelled
``Let me in, Pavel.'' The door opened and Pavel stood there with
his family.
 &HT;    At first they were quite frightened, but then they quickly
slammed the door shut. The window opened and Pavel yelled out,
``Jew, go back to your grave, there is no hope.''
 &HT;    Each home refused him entry. Zevy knew that soon he would die
from the cold and hunger.
 &HT;    Being at his wit's end he came up with a plan. At the end of the
dark forest lived a very old religious widow. She would pray early
in the morning and then would light the candles in the church on a
daily basis.
 &HT;    He came to her home, arriving at the doorstep looking more dead
than alive. He tapped on the door gently. It cracked open and the
old Christian lady looked out.
 &HT;    Zevy said, ``I am your Lord Jesus Christ. I have come down from
the cross. I am in deep pain. See my blood for the sacrifices of
the innocent. I must enter your home. I am on a special mission.''
 &HT;    The frightened widow uttered ``Yes, my Lord.'' Looking at Zevy's
blood-stained feet she quickly covered her eyes, crossed herself
and ran to bring a basin of warm water.
 &HT;    The widow fed him and provided him with shelter and clothing.
 &HT;    Portraying himself as Jesus, Zevy blessed the livestock and the
household. ``Remember,'' he said, ``you must never tell anyone of
my secret mission on earth. The Lord's missions are special during
these times.''
 &HT;    It was raining outside as Zevy left. It seems on this Rosh
Hashanah holiday the heavens cried.
 &HT;    How macabre and eerie that the Jew is saved as a suffering Jesus
Christ. Zevy, celebrating his sixteenth Rosh Hashanah, eating bread
at the home of a Christian.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, Ostrovaks and his henchmen feasted on kosher food and
wine, singing and dancing in Jewish homes. Dipping the apples in
bowls of honey -- their hands stained with fresh blood from their
New Year's sacrifice.
 &HT;    On Rosh Hashanah I'll be in synagogue with my congregation.
There I will remember the little towns and shtetls that are long
gone and forgotten.
 &HT;    I will resolve that besides repenting for my misdeeds I will
promise to help make this world a better and safer place for all
mankind.
 &HT;    According to tradition, Rosh Hashanah is also the day on which
man was created. It would be wonderful if mankind would celebrate
by inviting God to enter their hearts.
 &HT;    I wish all mankind a happy birthday.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    c.1998 Rabbi Eli Hecht
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Rabbi Eli Hecht is vice president of the Rabbinical Alliance of
America and past president of the Rabbinical Council of California.
He is the director of Chabad of South Bay in Lomita, Calif. and
writes a monthly Op-Ed column for the Long Beach Press-Telegeam.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
