<HEADER>
A0529 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-CAPUANO-BOS &LR;      09-17 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-CAPUANO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE LONG RUN, PERSISTENCE WINS   FOR MIKE CAPUANO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANTHONY FLINT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOMERVILLE, Mass. _ Michael Capuano was looking downright
congressional, walking into the Rosebud Diner in Davis Square
Wednesday in his crisp white shirt and dark red necktie,
surprisingly fresh after only a few hours of sleep.
</P>
<P>
   People looked up from their tuna melts and cups of minestrone to
congratulate this new celebrity _ the mayor of Somerville, who
became the last-minute choice of so many voters in Tuesday's 10-way
Democratic primary for the 8th Congressional District that he is
suddenly empowered to follow in the footsteps of John F. Kennedy
and Thomas P. ``Tip'' O'Neill Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Rivals wondered how someone so little-known outside his
hometown, who had made enough enemies in five terms at City Hall
that questions were raised in the late stages of the campaign about
his temperament and his record, could pull away from the pack so
convincingly.
</P>
<P>
   But Capuano may have had the perfect ingredient for the race: a
restless persistence. He kept running for mayor after being
rebuffed by the political establishment twice. He was undeterred by
an unsuccessful run for secretary of state, when he tried to change
the rules for nominating candidates at the Democratic convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my father ran for office, he wasn't accepted by a lot of
people around here. He was always the outsider,'' Capuano said over
a ham and cheese sandwich at 3 p.m., his first meal of the day. ``I
didn't have as many elected officials with me as others in this
race. I didn't have as many unions. The teachers weren't with me.
We just did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Capuano held a one-point lead over former Boston mayor
Raymond L. Flynn in polls before Tuesday's voting, he wound up
beating Flynn 23 percent to 18 percent, with the others bunched up
behind Flynn. In earning his 19,301 votes, his powerful
organization made sure the Somerville base was a solid foundation _
almost 40 percent of his support came from his hometown _ but he
drew surprising strength across the district, as voters settled on
him as the alternative to others. Although he did not carry another
city in the district, he pulled more than enough from his rivals to
win the nomination. Capuano will face Republican C. Phillip Hyde
and Independent candidate Anthony Schinella in November's general
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``He put together the base, added the Italian ethnicity piece,
and went out and won outside of Somerville as well. He ran a
perfect race, given his positioning,'' said Michael Goldman,
consultant for former radio talk-show host Marjorie Clapprood, who
with former state senator George Bachrach and environmental
activist John O'Connor became the candidates who voters assessed
and passed up as the Flynn alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, like others, said Capuano was perceived as slightly
more moderate than those contenders, but not as conservative as
Flynn. ``He didn't have the ideological liberal rhetoric that
Marjorie or George or Susan Tracy were perceived to have. In any
other circumstance, you'd have to say he's a liberal. But in the
spectrum of this race, he was left-center. We had a bunch of
left-fielders, one guy (venture capitalist Chris Gabrieli) in
center, and one guy playing right. And the ball got hit to the guy
in left-center.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Shea, Capuano's lead consultant, said voters outside of
Somerville were convinced by his message, hammered home in his TV
ads and in candidate debates, that he had deep roots in the
district and had improved the Somerville public schools as his
chief achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a clear message and he kept repeating it. But I think
he was also the best person to carry the message. He was the real
thing. He's an innovative, urban populist. People saw in him a
combination of Dartmouth and Somerville, the best of both. He was
feisty and we didn't try to polish him or change him,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   Born and raised in Somerville, living in a house on Porter
Street, Capuano, 46, graduated from Somerville High School and went
on to Dartmouth College. He describes himself as an ``average
student. I didn't take any leadership roles. I graduated, much to
the surprise of some.''
</P>
<P>
   From Dartmouth he moved on to Boston College Law School, though
he decided to take a yearlong break after only a few weeks of
classes. ``I was never enamored of the law, or a student of the
law,'' he said. But he returned to BC Law School and graduated.
From there, he went to the State House, working as a staffer for
the Joint Committee on Taxation. When his first son, Michael, was
born, he left to join the Beacon Hill firm of Joyce &AMP; Joyce.
</P>
<P>
   Capuano ran for mayor of Somerville in 1979, and again in 1981,
both times unsuccessfully.
</P>
<P>
   His first win was in 1989, ``when everybody was against me,'' he
said. Determined to consolidate power, he ran City Hall in an
unflinching manner, with few scores left unsettled.
</P>
<P>
   In his unsuccessful run for secretary of state in 1994, Capuano
was dogged by campaign finance questions that continued in the 8th
District campaign. The questions centered mostly on city workers
making big contributions to his campaign. But Capuano portrays the
run as taking on the Goliath of the Democratic establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, Capuano is part of the Democratic establishment.
He got phone calls from Senator Edward M. Kennedy and House
minority leader Richard A. Gephardt, a Missouri Democrat, first
thing Wednesday. He has checked in with delegation dean J. Joseph
Moakley, 9th District US representative.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scary. It's daunting,'' Capuano said of his probable move
to Washington. But he didn't really look scared.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
