<SLUG> BC-FASHION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLEASE DO TRY THIS AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tracking makeup trends can be bewildering. First brown lipstick
is in, then pink, then plum. All the hues look good on models. But
how many of us have the time and money to spend shopping in stores,
investing in colors like cappuccino and lavender, only to find out
that _ on us _ the trendy colors look horrible?
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the fashion industry has a time-saving solution that
doesn't require leaving your home.
</P>
<P>
   In the September issue of Allure magazine, a panel of makeup
artists _ not advertisers _ has compiled what they think are the
best colors for fall. In what the publication is calling a
first-of-its-kind magazine spread, Allure offers eight samples of
products for readers to test, in little packages with lift-up
flaps.
</P>
<P>
   The interactive makeup story includes berry-colored lipstick by
Revlon, a pink blush by Almay, a bronze eyeshadow by Chanel, and a
gray eyeshadow by Prescriptives.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, we've all seen magazines with perfume and
moisturizer samples inside them. But this really is different. Says
Allure, ``It gives readers a chance to try the colors we've chosen
in a real context. In natural light, for instance, at home, while
wearing jeans. (Pesky salesclerk trying to push the matching nail
polish not included.)''
</P>
<P>
   Glamour magazine is trying to offer consumers even more. In its
October issue, it will provide 12 product samples for readers to
test, including a liquid eyeliner by Clinique. Once readers decide
what they like, they can call Bloomingdale's on an 800 number and
order the goods by code.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's one-stop shopping.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The upscale Italian menswear design house Ermenegildo Zegna will
open its first Boston store Sunday, Sept. 20.
</P>
<P>
   You might recall the published reports last month that Monica
Lewinsky gave President Clinton a $110 Zegna tie.
</P>
<P>
   Other celebrities who have sported the clothes include Al Pacino
and Keanu Reeves in ``The Devil's Advocate,'' Eddie Murphy in ``Dr.
Dolittle,'' and Kenneth Branagh in ``The Gingerbread Man.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trivero, Italy-based company, which operates seven US
stores, is known for fine fabrics and fit. It began as a fabric
maker in 1910 and expanded over the years to include tailored men's
clothing and sportswear.
</P>
<P>
   Zegna _ whose line is also sold in Neiman Marcus _ decided to
open a Boston store because ``Boston has a strong and
well-established Zegna customer base,'' said Richard Cohen,
president and CEO of Zegna, North America.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fashion industry has long been criticized for using teenage
girls as a symbol of ideal beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the aging of the baby boomers, cosmetics company
Revlon Consumer Products Corp. has decided to use a spokesmodel its
customers can identify with: 48-year-old actress Cybill Shepherd.
</P>
<P>
   Shepherd will star in a series of new TV and print ads for the
brand Ultima II. She says, ``I've always thought that women are
beautiful at all stages of their lives. In the next decade, almost
50 million of us will be 40-plus. I think it's really exciting to
be associated with ... a company that recognizes the individual
beauty of women like me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
