out volatile food and energy costs, rose by the same amount. The
trade deficit in goods and services widened a bit in July as
exports fell at a faster pace than imports. The deficit grew to
$13.92 billion from a revised $13.64 billion in June. Exports fell
1.3 percent in July, to $75.42 billion, the lowest level since
February 1997, reflecting a drop in shipments of auto parts,
industrial supplies and consumer goods. Imports fell eight-tenths
of 1 percent, to $89.338 billion, the lowest since November,
reflecting lower oil prices and a drop in purchases of autos, foods
and industrial supplies.
