<HEADER>
A0535 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-ALCOTT-BOS &LR;      09-17 1363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-ALCOTT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUISA MAY ALCOTT'S STUDY RECAPTURED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARGO MILLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, Mass. _ Fans of Louisa May Alcott _ and they extend all
the way east to Turkey and west to Japan _ have their own mental
image of the March family home she evokes in ``Little Women.'' It
comes as a shock to many to see the Victorian reality of Orchard
House, where part of the novel was written in 1868. The room most
recently transformed is Bronson Alcott's study. Although Louisa
would dip into her considerable royalties to provide ``Marmee'' and
the homestead with central heating, &UR;  &LR; it was her artistic &UR;  &LR; sister
May who undertook to redecorate their father's study.
</P>
<P>
   This he recorded with satiric good humor in his diary for April
1874:
</P>
<P>
   ``May finds my study needs to be put into fresher costume. She
has purchased a new carpet, and new sofa and arm chair are to be
crimsoned to match and she is to do the working of spreading the
same and covering with such assistance as I can render. When the
carpet is spread, and the sofa and chair are covered, it will be
found the paper needs recovering to match, and then perhaps the
paint for the doors and summers (boxed beams) and casements to say
nothing of the mantlepiece.''
</P>
<P>
   The usual picture of Amos Bronson Alcott (1799-1888) is of a
certifiably double-domed Transcendental philosopher who sometimes
didn't know enough to come in out of the rain. He was an
educational reformer _ ``The Child Is the Book,'' not the pedagogic
system _ and he was right-minded. When he was criticized for
admitting a black child to his Boston school, a fellow
Transcendentalist, Ralph Waldo Emerson, came to his defense. At
Fruitlands, the utopian community Alcott helped establish in the
town of Harvard, all would share the work. That none of them knew
how to farm brought the little commune to near starvation.
</P>
<P>
   But around the house, Alcott was full of good ideas, some
practical, some decorative. It helped that he was a good carpenter.
Before the 20th century, few houses had storage closets; Alcott
reconfigured the upper staircase hall to give Louisa room for her
books. Other built-ins included a writing desk for her. Bronson's
study had bookcases made to frame the door to May's art studio. The
parlor and study acquired elegant niches for statuary; in the 1875
stereopticon slide of Bronson in his study he is posed reading
while his likeness, a portrait bust by the young Daniel Chester
French, peers out from the fireplace wall. May had been French's
first art teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Bronson Alcott had also been a friend and admirer of Andrew
Jackson Dowling, who died tragically young, but not before giving
America's new middle classes some pointers on how to live in
harmony with self and nature. The villa was Dowling's architectural
preference. He circulated up plans for their construction and the
gardens to be planted around them, and he had ideas about colors
for interior decoration. The new wallpaper in Alcott's study may be
one of the neutrals that Dowling's books advocated for airy
serenity. Richard Nylander, chief curator of the Society for the
Preservation of New England Antiquities and wallpaper consultant
for Orchard House, thinks the Alcott study chimes with ``one of
Dowling's `fawn' colors.''
</P>
<P>
   Restoration is a form of archeology. Like the seven layers of
Troy, Orchard House had seven wallpapers; as part of her research,
Heather Wager, the house's former curator, has preserved and
displayed swatches for documentation. Four patterns post-date the
Alcotts who left Orchard House in 1882. The two earliest papers,
dating from the 1850s, were fake wood grain. It was this graining,
fashionable in its day, that May replaced with what she considered
the more stylish ``diaper,'' or diamond pattern, enclosing
fleur-de-lis, or lilies. Though the 1875 photo doesn't catch the
effect, the flowers seem to shimmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If in Emerson's study perpetual twilight reigns,'' wrote a
visitor to Orchard House in 1874, ``in Alcott's it is always noon.
The great sun shines in it all day, the great fireplace roars, and
the warm crimson hangings temper the sunlight and reflect the
firelight.''
</P>
<P>
   The wallpaper that May Alcott chose went back to the 1790s. In
the days of illumination by candle and fireplace, people went to
enormous lengths to introduce more light into dark rooms. The
secretary-desk in Bronson's study, had it been a grander piece,
would have had mirrored door panels to reflect candle light. By the
process of ``satining'' wallpapers, rooms got the same glow as the
shiny dress fabric. Satining required two steps, says Nylander, a
leading historian of wallpapers. ``The whole paper was first glazed
to create a very shiny finish. Then you printed over this with a
flat color, and that flat color became the background.'' Such
papers were popular in the 1840s and 1850s. When revived again in
the 1860s, the use of aniline dye made the colors very brilliant.
By the 1870s, the calming influence of Dowling was apparent. With
firelight dancing over May's new paper, the lilies glowed silver.
By day, this receded and the walls turn buff with a light brown
pattern of diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   Against this, Bronson Alcott's red carpet comes as a shock. Just
as noisy was the new emerald green carpet for the Alcott parlor.
This too was a fashion of the times, to carpet the principal living
rooms in complementary colors. But as Nylander says, the idea of
house museums ``is to educate people to period taste, rather than
what we've become comfortable with.'' For further information about
Orchard House and its guided tours and many programs, telephone
978-369-4118.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the study's wallpapers, samples of its carpeting have not
survived to the present day. To find a period reproduction, Orchard
House turned to John Burrows, whose J.R. Burrows &AMP; Company of
Rockland deals in Victorian carpets, many of which are still in
production in England. When Burrows blew up the 1875 photo, he
could see the red carpet had a vigorous arabesque pattern. He found
something similar at Woodward Grosvenor &AMP; Co, Ltd., of
Kidderminster, near Birmingham, whose patterns go back to the
mill's founding in 1790.
</P>
<P>
   There would soon come a time when the Alcotts' bright carpets
were out of fashion. Already the Arts &AMP; Crafts movement in England
was frowning on primary and secondary colors, says Burrows, and a
sort of podge would take over. Gilbert &AMP; Sullivan satirized it in
``Patience.'' Yet for the Alcotts to choose a green carpet took
daring of another kind. A few decades earlier the color had been
associated with arsenic poisoning and there was a public health
campaign warning of greens. ``Even though arsenic was not used in
carpet-making,'' says Burrows, ``the color green disappeared for 20
or 25 years.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next few years, Orchard House will be very much a work
in progress. The next room to be restored will be May's bedroom.
She grew up to be a talented artist and Allison Leopold's
forthcoming biography will give May her due. Royalties from
``Little Women'' _ May was the novel's Amy _ paid for her European
training and she was good enough to have a still life displayed at
the Paris Salon in 1877. At a time when copying famous paintings
had its place in the art world, she was famed for hers of the great
English romantic, J.W.M. Turner. Marriage to a Swiss businessman
and musician, Ernest Nierker, she delivered the bliss of
``painting, music, love'' but it was short-lived. She died in 1879,
six months after the birth of her daughter, Louisa May. Called
Lulu, the child was sent to Concord to be raised by ``Aunt Weedy.''
</P>
<P>
   May's room at Orchard House is noted for her murals ``after
Flaxman'' of ancient Greek scenes. As a girl, she'd been entranced
with Emerson's volume of Flaxman engravings and would study them
under his library table. ``Take them home with you!'' Emerson said
and she did; and one reason why so many of May's Flaxman murals
feature chariot horses may be because she adored riding. She and
the future ``Aunt Weedy'' would ride for hours over Concord's lanes
and fields.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
