<DOCNO> NYT19980917.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0538 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-PROJECT-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     09-17 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... is too much.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember, do not put insulation in the overhang of the roof,
into the eaves. This would block any vents there, and even if there
are no vents, it could cause serious condensation, with resulting
water that could soak insulation and ruin it. If there is
insulation in your eaves, take it out.
</P>
<P>
   If there are floor boards in the attic, you can blow cellulose
or fiberglass into the cavity. That is all you can get in, maybe 5
1/2 to 9 1/2 inches, below the recommended thickness. When blowing
insulation under the floor, take special care not to let it spew
into the overhang.
</P>
<P>
   You could put more insulation on top of the floor boards, but
it's not recommended. To add insulation, remove those boards.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The basement ceiling? Sure
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Next easiest place is the basement ceiling. But why bother?
Doesn't warm air rise? Yes, but heat can be lost through a barrier
in any direction: up, down, and sideways.
</P>
<P>
   Put 6-inch backed insulation between the joists, with the
backing (vapor barrier) up, touching the floor above. Hold the
insulation in place with pointed wires, called insulation hangers;
they come in lengths to accommodate 14 1/2- to 22 1/2-inch spaces.
The points grab the joists, and the wires almost always stay in
place.
</P>
<P>
   Or, in a basement ceiling, staple polyethylene plastic to the
ceiling, then install 8-inch Polywrap with the hangers. This will
give an extra bit of insulation and also, because it is wrapped in
poly, keep the fiberglass out of your hair if you happen to brush
against it.
</P>
<P>
   If you have just insulation in the basement ceiling, and don't
like the idea of exposed fiberglass, and don't plan to finish off
the basement as living space, staple Tyvek on the bottom of the
joists. It will not only keep the fiberglass where it belongs but
also, being white, will make the basement lighter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Toughest way: in the walls
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The final place for insulation is in the walls. One way to do it
is to have cellulose or fiberglass blown in the walls by an
installer.
</P>
<P>
   Professionals do it by removing clapboards or shingles at
appropriate places, drilling holes through the sheathing into the
wall cavity, inserting a hose into each hole, and filling the
cavity. Holes must be drilled between studs at the top and bottom
of each stud space, so that means a helluva lot of holes. Can't be
helped.
</P>
<P>
   The holes are then covered and the clapboards and shingles
returned, so you really don't know anything was done, except when
you check your heating bills. Insulation can be blown in virtually
any house _ sided with vinyl, aluminum, brick, stucco, even
asbestos cement siding and other materials).
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the holes are made inside, particularly on brick
and asbestos cement sided houses. This is OK, except that the
insulation men are installers, not plasterers, and the patching of
the holes may leave much to be desired.
</P>
<P>
   In the early days of blowing in insulation (60 years ago), the
blown-in material often sagged over time, leaving gaps at the top
of the stud space. Even a small gap reduces the value of the
insulation. Today, the material is blown in under pressure, and
sagging is minimal.
</P>
<P>
   You can do this yourself, renting a blower and cellulose
insulation at rental stores. But if you find that there are too
many holes to drill, it might pay to have a pro do it.
</P>
<P>
   Blown-in insulation does not provide a vapor barrier. However,
you can paint the walls with a vapor barrier paint; most interior
wall paints are vapor barriers. And, vinyl-coated, foil, and
Wall-Tex type (vinyl-coated cloth) wall coverings are also vapor
barriers.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to insulate walls is to take off the plaster or
plasterboard wall, put in the insulation and vapor barrier, and put
up new walls.
</P>
<P>
   Ugh. That's a lot of work. Although, it has been done, but for
other reasons, and if you don't have those reasons, you really
don't want to do it, do you?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Cathedral ceilings
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One more place to insulate is a cathedral ceiling, although most
cathedral ceilings are in new houses, which are already well
insulated.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, to insulate this space, you have to take off the
ceiling, and install insulation with 1 inch of air spce between
insulation and roof boards; that insulation should have a vapor
barrier facing the room. Then put up a new ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   A complicating feature in this project is that that 1-inch air
space must be ventilated, which means you have to put in soffit
vents (a soffit is the underpart of the roof overhang) and a ridge
vent on the roof to get that air moving.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve that 1 inch of air space, and keep it open, staple
proper vents or rafter chutes on the inside of the roof. The vents
provide automatic spacing and keep the space open.
</P>
<P>
   Well, there is a way of getting around this complicated
business. Install 1- or 2-inch Styrofoam or polyisocyanurate
directly on the old ceiling, then put on a new ceiling. Two inches
of this will provide an R factor of 10 to 14, less than 6 inches of
insulation in the cavity itself, which provides an R factor of
about 19.
</P>
<P>
   Still another way is to install 2- to 4-inch rigid insulation on
the roof, then reroof over that. That's pretty good in new
construction, but pretty expensive as a retrofit.
</P>
<P>
   That's about it for insulation and vapor barriers, but that is
not all for saving heat. You could save up to 50 percent of your
heating costs with the insulation suggested above, but you can save
even more by tightening up the house: caulking and
weatherstripping.
</P>
<P>
   And that is the subject of next Sunday's sermon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
