<P>
   CLINTON-CROWD _ CINCINNATI _ How the Ohioans received Clinton.
(Bebbington, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TV _ If the Clinton video is released today, analysis of
the coverage. (Harris, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-RICE _ WASHINGTON _ Donna Rice Hughes, the woman in the
sex scandal that brought down Sen. Gary Hart, talks about how she
has rebuilt her life. Now a crusader against Internet smut, she
also addresses the posting of the Starr report. (Dart, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECONOMY _ MOSCOW _ American businesses in Russia have so
far lost $500 million in the current economic crisis and some are
contemplating pulling out of the market. ``Do you want us here or
not?'' the head of the American chamber of commerce told a news
conference, in a blunt message to Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov
and his new government as it contemplates how to deal with the
crisis. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving by 3 p.m. EDT in both the (i) International and (f)
Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   USAFRICA-TRADE _ WASHINGTON _ Congressional sponsors of the
African Growth and Opportunity Act will have a news conference to
highlight the support the bill has received from U.S. religious
leaders. The bill, meant to address three decades of U.S. economic
neglect for sub-Saharan Africa, has become steeped in controversy
since congressional Republicans have tied its fate to passage of
presidential ``fast-track'' trade authority. The latter is a no-no
among Democrats, who have championed the Africa trade bill.
(Monroe, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving by 5:30 p.m. EDT in both the (i) International and
(f) Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   ANIMAL-WASTE _ WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration announces
Thursday a national strategy for managing livestock waste that
requires large farms to obtain operation permits and to develop
detailed waste-management plans. The first-ever attempt to
federally regulate the waste is largely a response to cries from
environmental groups who say that animal manure is contaminating
water supplies and has contributed to massive fish kills. Farmers
and livestock producers aren't thrilled but were fearing more
drastic measures. (Moscoso, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   TECH-VISAS _ WASHINGTON _ Republican leaders in the House on
Thursday cancelled a planned vote on increasing the number of H-1B
visas for highly skilled foreign workers, citing a shortfall in
Democratic support for the measure. (Harlan, Cox News Service 200).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO _ TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ The way Gov. Lawton Chiles sees
it, Florida's settlement with cigarette makers won't be a done deal
until it gets $1.7 billion sweeter.
</P>
<P>
   Chiles planned a news conference Thursday to announce that the
state's take from its settlement with Big Tobacco will be nearly
$13 billion under a renegotiated agreement aimed at matching the
better settlements reached by other states. Since Florida reached
its original $11 billion settlement, Mississippi, Texas and
Minnesota have all settled lawsuits against the tobacco industry to
recoup the cost of treating sick smokers and to stop cigarette
makers from targeting children. (Date, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPICS-HISTORY _ ATLANTA _ Athletes, officials, ACOG staff and
volunteers and myriad VIPs will assemble for two days this weekend
at the Atlanta History Center to record the first-ever oral history
of the Olympics. The recollections of real people, along with the
Olympic VIPs, will be videotaped for inclusion in the official
archives of the Games. (Turner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FALL _ The dry weather is good for some things. Fall leaf color
will be exceptional in the Southeast mountains this year, say
experts, or the best in 10 years. (Harmon, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TRANSPORTATION-BILL _ Three months after Congress passed a new
multi-billion dollar federal transportation bill, it's still not
clear how much Central Texas will get out of it. There were some
specific earmarks in the bill for Texas 130 but there was the
potential for more money if the region applied for trade corridor
money. We'll talk today with U.S. deputy transportation secretary
Gloria Jeff about the Austin area's transportation needs and how
well the region is situated to pick up some of that extra cash.
(Hiott, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
