<HEADLINE>
BOOK STIRS DEBATE OVER ROLE OF PEERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just how important are peers in the lives of our children? Not
nearly as important as Judith Rich Harris says.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, a New Jersey grandmother and former college textbook
writer, has created quite a stir with her book, ``The Nurture
Assumption: Why Children Turn Out the Way They Do'' (Free Press).
She argues that, except for the genes we pass on, parents don't
count. Peers do.
</P>
<P>
   If ever there was a frightening thought for parents, this is it.
Undoubtedly, that's why the media has jumped on this book; it
certainly isn't because of her original research (she hasn't done
any) or her academic credentials (she doesn't have any). But while
her concept may be appealing to media types for its controversy and
sensationalism, Harris and her theories are being widely
discredited by researchers and professionals who work with parents
and children.
</P>
<P>
   Child psychologist Jerome Kagan of Harvard University,
nationally known for his work on children's temperament, has been
the most vocal and the most blunt. ``What she says is just silly,''
he says. ``Any parent knows that intuitively.''
</P>
<P>
   Gail Biancucci, a mother of two, certainly does. Her 4
1/2-year-old daughter, Stephanie, is a social child, the kind of
little girl who would be next door at her friend's house at 7 a.m.
every day, whether the family was awake or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teaching her that you can't have free reign in someone else's
house, that there are boundaries and rules about how you interact
in the world, this is part of my role. Lately, she turns down
invitations to go there until she checks with me,'' says Biancucci.
That alone is proof to her of the myriad of known, unknown, and
unknowable ways she influences her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   That Harris discounts the influence parents like Biancucci can
see for themselves puts her in a minority except among a body of
scientists known as biogeneticists, who stress the importance of
genetics and evolution in human development. Harris's detractors
agree each child is born with an individual temperament, but they
say that's only half the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personality is what you are born with. Character is what
parents shape,'' says researcher and developmental psychologist Bob
Selman of Harvard and Judge Baker's Children's Center in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Peers play a role in how a child develops, too, agree Selman,
Kagan, and their Harvard colleague, Howard Gardner. But Kagan
notes, ``To say it happens to the exclusion of parents is a flawed
argument.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the nation's top researchers on peer relationships also
say Harris goes too far. ``Peers are important, I've been saying
that for years,'' says psychologist James Youniss of Catholic
University in Washington, D.C. ``But I also believe you need the
parental relationship. Harris uses my work but drops that piece of
it,'' he says, noting that Harris did no original research of her
own. She also has no academic credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologist William Damon, a professor at Stanford University
who also is well known for his work on peer relationships, says the
fact that children are even able to enter into friendships is
because parents lay the groundwork for them in their first six
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way parents relate to a child shapes the way a child
relates to others,'' says Damon. For instance, babies and toddlers
whose parents engage in verbal turn-taking and who are generally
reliable in their mood and response _ when they want hugs, you
don't push them away one day and embrace them the next _ are more
likely to engage in turn-taking with peers and less likely to be
moody, inconsistent, and temperamental. In other words, they make
good playmates.
</P>
<P>
   That parents provide a sense of orderliness to the world is also
critical. ``You wake up and eat breakfast and you eat cereal, not
candy. This structure gives a child security,'' says Youniss, and
it's what enables him or her to feel safe enough to operate in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Parent educator Linda Braun, a professor at Wheelock College and
director of Families First in Cambridge, Mass., says a child also
needs a positive sense of herself to be able to engage peers. This
comes from parents, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn how you appear in the world, what you can do in the
world and how to evaluate the world from the mirror image of
yourself that parents reflect back to you,'' says Braun. ``Just a
minor adjustment in a parent's response can change a child's
outlook on the world. I see it happen all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   If parents do a good job laying the foundation, at about age 7,
children begin to evolve from being playmates brought together by
circumstance into friends who choose peers based on mutual
admiration and interests.
</P>
<P>
   And guess what? Who they choose has a lot to do with us.
</P>
<P>
   Harris says the most parents can do is live in a good
neighborhood so that the pool peers come from is of high quality.
Developmentalists say our role is far less passive.
</P>
<P>
   ``How intellectual is your home?'' asks Gardner. ``Do you talk
about books, movies? How truthful is your home, how responsible is
it? Are you honest in your dealings? Do you act on your values? If
a child is used to interesting conversations, to people who tell
the truth and pull their weight, she won't want friends who are
boring or who lie or are unreliable.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometime between the age of 8 and 12, the power of peers'
influence increases. Ours, however, doesn't necesssarily decrease.
``It just becomes different,'' says Gardner.
</P>
<P>
   Damon's research shows there are certain things children learn
better from peers than from us, for instance, cooperation, loyalty,
a sense of fairness, and even some cognitive skills. ``They're
better able to learn some abstract math skills like ratios and
proportions from peers in a cooperative context than they are from
adults who teach forumulas,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also things they only learn from us. It's our job
to provide the moral overlay for the relationships, according to
Damon. ``Without discussions about what constitutes legitimate
authority, justice, and kindness, kids are lacking in social,
historical, and cultural perspective. They're wild and
undisciplined,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   They also don't feel good. Many studies, including Selman's,
show that children who feel like they're on their own, whose
parents aren't supportive, caring, or involved, are panicky and
insecure, have difficulty with relationships, and are more likely
to act out in aggressive, antisocial ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in this period of 8 to 12, when she says her best friend
is the most important person in her and you feel like you don't
count, she still needs to know you are present in spirit,'' Selman
says.
</P>
<P>
   It's in this context that researchers say Harris's book is
potentially dangerous. ``It gives parents permission not to pay
attention,'' says Selman. ``My research shows, if you pull the
invisible hand away, all hell breaks loose.'' This is true for all
children but especially for those with emotional and/or behavioral
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Because Harris is also an adoptive parent who says her theory
was formed in part by the lack of influence she says she had on her
adopted daughter, specialists in the adoption community are
particularly worried about the book. Cambridge psychologist Joyce
Pavao of the Center for Family Connections says it is emotional
abandonment if adoptive parents buy into Harris's thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was destructive 20 years ago to believe genetics has
nothing to do with who (adoptive) kids are, and it's destructive,
flippant, and offensive to think the parents who raise a child have
nothing to do with how that child turns out,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Youniss says the bottom line is that parents and peers are both
important in children's lives, each in a different way, each with a
different function. Damon says, ``I want parents to know ... (your
influence) doesn't stop, ever.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SUGGESTIONS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _With children 3 to 7, parents' role vis a vis peers is to serve
as middlemen, helping children connect to each other and then
interpreting the connections.
</P>
<P>
   _With older children, our role is mediator, helping them reflect
on friendship issues, problem-solving with them and putting issues
in a context that reflect our values.
</P>
<P>
   _That American children pay so much attention to peers is a
cultural phenomenon, not a developmental one.
</P>
<P>
   _Research shows that children under 7 years of age assume a
parent's qualities also belong to them. Thus, positive qualities
(warmth, responsiveness) have a positive influence on a child's
sense of self and therefore on how she relates to others, and
negative attributes, a negative one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Barbara Meltz's e-mail address is meltz(at)nws.globe.com. Her
columns are now on line at Boston.Com, keyword ``parenting.'' For
photocopies of past columns, send a self-addressed, stamped
envelope to Barbara F. Meltz, The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston,
MA 02107-2378. Please specify the column.)
</P>
</TEXT>
