<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LEAKING'S OVER, FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; You could almost sense an air of desperation in some of the
last news stories before the Sept. 11 release of Ken Starr's report
on the White House scandal. After nine months of relying on media
accounts from mysterious ``sources,'' the public was finally going
to know what the reporters knew. So for journalists, it was a last
call for leaks.
</P>
<P>
   NBC reported that ``a law enforcement source'' said the semen on
Lewinsky's dress matched the president's DNA. USA Today cited ``a
lawyer'' saying Starr will allege obstruction of justice but no
suborning of perjury. The New York Times said ``lawyers familiar
with Mr. Starr's plan'' indicated that he would try to prove
perjury, obstruction of justice, and abuse of power. In a matter of
hours, such speculation would be a matter of record.
</P>
<P>
   When the report was made public last Friday, viewers saw
television correspondents rushing to spit out the details even as
their role of information middlemen was being phased out.
(According to pollster Andrew Kohut, an impressive 13 percent of
the citizenry took the report directly off the Internet.)
</P>
<P>
   For Craig Crawford, editor of the Political Hotline newsletter,
the sight of the scrambling TV journalists marked a turning point
in the story. ``Suddenly, they're out of the picture,'' he says.
``If you're really interested in finding out something, you don't
have to wait for Dan Rather.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for the first in nine months the media was reporting
about allegations,'' says Kohut, of the Pew Research Center.
``Since nine months have passed, the baby's born.``
</P>
<P>
   And with the birth of that baby _ the Starr report that CNN
Washington bureau chief Frank Cesno calls the great ``leveller
because everybody's got it'' _ the media landscape changed
dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   No longer can journalists dole out the crucial currency of
forbidden or secret information. For the first time since January,
that dynamic will not drive the story. Instead, the Lewinsky saga
now moves into the public domain _ to presidential press
conferences, Congressional deliberations, new releases of
Starr-related information, and most importantly, to the court of
public opinion. Information has suddenly been democratized. The
journalism becomes more reactive, and as a consequence, journalists
may become more popular.
</P>
<P>
   Both admirers and detractors of the press understand the new
circumstances. ``The Lewinsky reporters are now liberated from
their role of lap dogs,'' says media analyst Andrew Tyndall. ``All
of these people have depended on this drip of leaks. They become
reporters now rather than repositories of leaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Newsweek's Michael Isikoff, who did most of the serious work in
unearthing the Clinton/Lewinsky mess, says ``The story has changed
... from doing real reporting. ... It moves into a forum, Congress,
where there's a lot more sources. Before, there was a finite number
of sources who knew something.''
</P>
<P>
   In the week since the release of the Starr report, the tenor of
coverage has been noticeably different. Pulse-taking headlines like
``Women Voice Sympathy and Disgust,'' ``Nation Showing its Dismay
and Reluctance,'' and ``Most Support is for Censure,'' have
replaced breathless revelations about grand jury testimony and
possible tryst eyewitnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Even the punditocracy has evolved. Back in January, people like
NBC's Tim Russert, opining that Clinton had very little time to
respond to the allegations, or ABC's Sam Donaldson, suggesting his
presidency could be ``numbered in days,'' defined the dialogue.
Last weekend's lineup of television talking heads was loaded down
with the lawyers and lawmakers who will actually decide the
president's fate.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, polls show a disconnect between the media's avid
pursuit of the scandal and the public's stubborn resistance to it.
``There is a public disgust with the story,'' acknowledges Isikoff,
even as he points out how accurate much of the reporting has been.
And though he believes public opinion on the issue may be fluid,
Cesno admits that many citizens think the media have ``taken this
and beaten it to a pulp.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts, however, view the media's new role _ chronicling
the fallout from the Starr report instead of trying to preempt it _
as an opportunity to get back in the public's good graces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reporters will be able to present the president's case and the
critics' case,'' notes Rob Snyder, editor of the Freedom Forum's
Media Studies Journal. ``That should actually redound to the credit
of the press. People get suspicious of reporters who overmediate
the event.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The public wants a press that's less intrusive and reports the
controversy instead of drives it,'' adds Kohut.
</P>
<P>
   But Tom Rosenstiel, vice-chairman of the Committee Of Concerned
Journalists, warns that with a story this volatile, all media
cycles are fleeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right at the moment we are in one of those fortunate phases,''
when reporters are content to do the reaction stories, he says.
``We get into trouble when the amount of new facts begin to dry up
and we have a lot of pent up expectations ... I'm continually
surprised by how fast things happen and how little patience we
have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
