<HEADLINE>
STAMP EVOKES ERA OF STYLE, ELEGANCE ON RAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIMOTHY CAHILL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In the 1930s, the 20th Century Limited delivered
first-class train travel. Now it delivers first-class mail.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most famous images of the celebrated bullet-shaped
train, an icon of railroading glamour and power, is part of the
collection of the Albany Institute of History &AMP; Art. Earlier this
month, the U.S. Postal Service announced that the depiction, a
color lithograph poster by Leslie Ragan, had been transformed into
one of its newest 32-cent stamps.
</P>
<P>
   The institute's image of the 20th Century Limited, from a
promotional poster for the New York Central Railroad, was used by
the Postal Service as one of 15 images in the Postal Service's
``Celebrate the Century Collection'' of 1930s people, events and
imagery.
</P>
<P>
   The commemorative stamp honors ``Streamline Design'' as one of
the symbols of the '30s. Other images in the stamp line include the
Empire State Building, Franklin Roosevelt, the Depression, Superman
and the game Monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a classic mid-1930s look,'' says Tammis Groft, chief
curator at the institute. The 1938 poster was created, she adds,
``to encourage passengers to look to the railroad for elegance and
modern travel.'' The poster is on display at the institute.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as depicted on the 2-foot-by-3-foot poster painting, the
20th Century Limited was not simply a train. Its round-nosed
locomotive, pulling a long line of opulent and state-of-the-art
passenger cars, was a rolling metaphor of efficiency, confidence
and brute will, not just for the New York Central, but for the
country as well.
</P>
<P>
   Ragan was a graphic artist for the railroad company, given the
assignment to announce the train's 16-hour service between New York
and Chicago. He depicted the 20th Century barreling down the track,
into the sunshine glinting on the nose of its engine. Ragan's train
was no mere people-hauler, but a roaring juggernaut racing into the
light of an unlimited future.
</P>
<P>
   Ragan, who died in 1972, was a celebrated illustrator of
travel-related imagery before and after World War II. In addition
to working for the New York Central, he had many clients in the
railroad and steamship industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through his images of rail, he's entered the public
consciousness,'' Groft says. His image of the 20th Century Limited
found its way into Hollywood and the popular imagination. The
train's streamline design, with its rounded edges and curvaceous
lines, found its way into products from automobiles to blenders in
the '30s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It characterizes a national style,'' says Groft, that ``came
to symbolize progress and the elimination of all kinds of
friction.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Central Railroad was headquartered in Albany until
1959, when it closed its offices here and offered its artifacts to
the Albany Institute. More than 1,000 items, from tickets to
original paintings, were obtained by the museum, among them Ragan's
wood-framed poster.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service approached the institute two years ago about
using the image. ``We were sworn to secrecy,'' Groft says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very famous poster,'' says Postal Service spokesman Don
Smeraldy. ``It represents well the bullet shape and modernistic
design of that period.''
</P>
<P>
   The stamp was chosen from among thousands of designs and
subjects studied by the Citizens Stamp Advisory Committee, a group
appointed by the postmaster general.
</P>
<P>
   Ragan's poster contains advertising copy in the sans-serif
typeface of the day. The stamp crops out not just the type, but
much of the foreground of Ragan's original, emphasizing the
locomotive's sleek lines.
</P>
<P>
   The poster is a chromo-lithograph print of an original
watercolor painting. Groft says she does not know the location of
the original painting, or even if it still exists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
