<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0559 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EZZARD-COLUMN18-COX     09-17 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Overstepping the bounds of privacy
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Atlanta -Only the U.S. Supreme Court has shaped our democratic
institutions, construed our Constitution _ until now. But the
impeachment process as the forefathers envisioned it _
deliberative, fair, dignified, cautious _ is forever changed by a
prosecutor lacking the discretion and restraint that distinguishes
powerful officials.
</P>
<P>
   I have difficulty understanding why President Clinton or any
leader who cared about his family and country would not resign,
given the nature of his behavior in the Lewinsky affair and the
public revelation of it.
</P>
<P>
   But that view does not prevent me or thousands of other
Americans from believing that independent counsel Kenneth Starr has
permanently damaged some democratic institutions. He has utilized
seedy tactics and caused unnecessary harm to innocent people in an
investigation that should have been of a higher caliber. The
``sieve'' operation that Starr's lawyers provided to news media of
secret grand jury testimony (the media is not blameless in taking
full advantage of the illegal leaks) is itself abusive of the
public trust. As House Speaker Newt Gingrich (R-Ga.) was declaring
last week that no one would have access to the Starr report until
Congress voted to release it, Starr's lawyers were leaking it bit
by bit to top Washington news reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Even those early leaks demonstrated that the literary writers
Starr hired (at taxpayer expense) were effective and colorful _
more suited for the The National Inquirer than a serious legal
document. But Starr is a study in overkill, even on the claims
devoid of lurid sexual details.
</P>
<P>
   And example is the claim of abuse of the power of high office.
The president, the report claims, waged court fights ``to impede
the grand jury investigation.'' But I believe a president or any
high official who failed to challenge Starr's exceptions to
historic precedents in Anglo-Saxon law would be neglecting his own
responsibility to the people and the justice system. Questioning
invasion of lawyer-client privilege and the time-honored
relationship between the Secret Service and the president is hardly
abuse of power. All former presidents who are still living had
publicly opposed Starr's quest to make the Secret Service testify
before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has always seemed to lack a dimension of judgment that
someone in his place of unlimited power should have. He exhibited
that lack of discretion when he continued to represent Brown &AMP;
Williamson Tobacco Corp. against the federal government (the
people) while he was representing the people in investigating the
president. He had no problem advising the Republican Party while he
was supposed to be above partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   Starr seemed to relish giving the public the sordid details of
Clinton's behavior. He is, in part, the reason for the demeaning
public conversation that continues ad nauseam _ the dirty jokes at
the water coolers in workplaces all over the country, the incessant
gibberish of tabloid sex promoters.
</P>
<P>
   I wish Bill Clinton had resigned to save us and our children
from having to hear the details of his immoral behavior. And I wish
Kenneth Starr had to write 100 times a day the rest of his life the
1928 definition of the right to privacy crafted by Justice Louis
Brandeis: ``The makers of the Constitution ... sought to protect
Americans in their beliefs, their thoughts, their emotions, their
sensations. They conferred as against the government the right to
be let alone, the most comprehensive of rights and the right most
valued by civilized man.''
</P>
<P>
   While Starr and his literary advisers grovel around in the
sordid details of Clinton's sexual encounters with Lewinsky,
Brandeis towers. The presidency itself will survive Bill Clinton.
The question is whether the right to privacy can survive Ken Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Ezzard is a columnist for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   e-mail:mezzard(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
