<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-RUSH18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't rush to catch Jackie Chan's latest
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an opening scene of ``Rush Hour,'' Hong Kong police detective
Lee (Jackie Chan) playfully says goodbye to his star martial-arts
pupil, the adorable 11-year-old daughter of the new Chinese consul
to the United States. Lee wishes her luck in America, calling it
``a friendly place.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the far-off, noisy, nasty nation she arrives in turns
out to be anything but friendly, and the girl is soon kidnapped on
her way to school. Nor is this alien land all that friendly to
Chan, encasing the likable chop-socky action stunt performer in a
wheezy Hollywood formula odd-couple buddy picture, making him take
a back seat to his hot-shot comic co-star, Chris Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   There was something terribly endearing about Chan's earlier,
badly dubbed, awkwardly acted Asian supercop sagas (``Rumble in the
Bronx,'' ``First Strike,'' etc.) that have not translated well to
Western ways. Entertaining, at least in a guilty pleasure sense,
they possess a naive exuberance that gets knocked out of them when
money and cinematic polish are thrown their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rush Hour'' _ an odd title for a movie that isn't going
anywhere _ contrives to pair Chan with a loose cannon, egotistical
cop named James Carter (Tucker). They're two misfits who bungle the
case, wreaking havoc on the streets of Los Angeles, until they
eventually bring the bad guys to justice.
</P>
<P>
   Carter is a loudmouth embarrassment to the L.A. police, a sorry
collection of civil servants who are not easily embarrassed.
(``We're the most hated cops in the free world,'' says Carter. ``My
mother tells people I'm a drug dealer.'') Tucker, who re-teams with
director Brett Rattner after last year's overloud, underfunny
``Money Talks,'' must be an acquired taste. If you like him, you'll
be pleased to know there's a lot of him in ``Rush Hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, to keep Carter busy, he is assigned to babysit Detective
Lee, who is just another nuisance as far as the police and FBI are
concerned. Reluctantly, Carter takes Lee to such tourist spots as
Mann's Chinese Theatre, where Lee gives him the slip and heads off
to rescue the girl.
</P>
<P>
   Reunited, Carter teaches Lee a few cool, street-smart moves;
they bond singing Beach Boys songs; and a few buildings blow up
real good. Chan gets to scale a few walls, does a little
kick-boxing and manages a free-fall off an exposition center
catwalk. Somehow, it doesn't add up to much.
</P>
<P>
   Chan fans will be pleased to hear that director Rattner includes
a handful of outtakes of botched action sequences _ a Chan
trademark _ at the end of ``Rush Hour.'' But even they seem flat
and false, as if someone got an idea for an amusing misstep, and
then Ratt-ner filmed it until he got it wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
