<HEADER>
A0561 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-THING18-COX     09-17 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-THING18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No false notes: 'True thing' uses fine cast, moving tale
 &HT;    By Gary Schwan
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``One True Thing'' could have struck many false notes. The plot
is perilous _ a mother fighting cancer and a daughter whose
feelings toward her grow from resentment, to understanding, to
acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   A tear-jerker? Amazingly, no, even if it is adapted from a novel
by the former New York Times sob sister, Anna Quindlen. Even a
choir warbling Silent Night doesn't turn the movie to mush.
</P>
<P>
   Why? It has actors of some note _ Meryl Streep, William Hurt and
Renee Zellweger, who is excellent in a role requiring a multitude
of emotions. Add the moody yet sober direction of Carl Franklin
(``Devil In A Blue Dress''). He largely forgoes visual showboating
for close-quarters observation of the human beings at the heart of
this melodrama _ people whose most fleeting expressions speak
volumes.
</P>
<P>
   The film also has a narrative structure that keeps a real
mystery percolating in the audience's mind until the final frame.
Finally, the story offers several truisms about the human heart and
the meaning of marriage. They aren't profound truths, but they are
presented in non-preachy fashion. They spring from the
circumstances and characters, and are startling in their
common-sense wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   This movie is about the people more than their predicament,
which is all too familiar, alas, and thus could have been milked
for cheap sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   Streep plays Kate Gulden. She's a loving, Martha Stewart
homemaker, whose very cheeriness is irksome to her daughter Ellen
(Zellweger). Ellen is an ambitious rookie writer at a New York
magazine who has vowed not to lead a life like her mother's.
</P>
<P>
   Hurt is paterfamilias George Gulden, a tweedy, somewhat
self-absorbed professor who has won acclaim as an essayist but who
still yearns for recognition as a novelist. When his wife is
diagnosed with cancer, he simply assumes that his daughter will
move back in with the family and serve as a kind of nurse.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen's resentment is put on boil. As Kate's illness inexorably
progresses, Ellen's conflicted emotions affect her relationship
with her mother, father, brother and boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen's shifting sensibilities are traced through an
accumulation of telling minor domestic incidents. Although
judgmental by nature, she comes to see her family as human beings,
with human frailties, even suspecting her father of having affairs.
But she also makes more than peace with them. She grows to love
them in profound and surprising ways.
</P>
<P>
   The story is told in flashback, with Ellen speaking to an
investigator. We realize that her mother has died, and we
eventually figure out that there is some question about whether the
death was natural.
</P>
<P>
   Streep's Ellen is a woman whose eternal optimism and
unconditional love could easily prove annoying. A consummate
actress, Streep doesn't employ accents or even remarkable tics or
gestures to convey character. It is her entire physical presence
that is impressive _ the many different ways she carries her body
as the cancer eats at her.
</P>
<P>
   With his crinkly eyes and deliberate manner, Hurt makes a good
intellectual with a sly sense of humor. He manages to create a
character who is both very sympathetic and slightly suspicious. And
sadly human. Watch his face fall when he realizes that his
intellectual hero has no idea or interest in the fact that he is
writing a novel.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these two heavyweight actors, it's Ellen's story at
bottom, and Zellweger's movie. As her mother withers, she grows.
Although a young professional woman, she is still really a kid as
the movie opens. Her resentments, confusions, disappointments and
insights are all conveyed with admirable under-state-ment. A nice
decision is filming her in extreme close-up during the
interrogation scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``One True Thing'' rises above a simple story to become a very
true thing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
