<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCHING FOR MEANING WITH MISS AMERICA
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   There are so many ways to amuse yourself while you watch the
Miss America pageant this Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   You could try to reach a consensus about which contestant is
most likely to be abducted by aliens.
</P>
<P>
   Or which is most convinced that God is on her side.
</P>
<P>
   Or which has spent the most money on electrolysis.
</P>
<P>
   You can work up a point-by-point comparison of pageant hosts
past and present, Bert Parks versus Boomer Esiason.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming you're old enough to remember Bert Parks.
</P>
<P>
   And if you are, you know there's no comparison.
</P>
<P>
   You can compose your own Big Questions for the finalists.
</P>
<P>
   Example: ``If you were Hillary Clinton would you run for
president in 2000?''
</P>
<P>
   Or, ``What would you, as an individual, do to solve the Y2K
problem?''
</P>
<P>
   Or, ``With three games left in the season, the Red Sox have a
four game lead for the American League wild card spot. Explain how
they can lose.''
</P>
<P>
   You can think up interesting platforms that might be adopted by
future contestants.
</P>
<P>
   Pedestrian rights.
</P>
<P>
   Or stamping out phobophobia, the fear of fear itself.
</P>
<P>
   Or changing the name of the pageant to Ms. America.
</P>
<P>
   You can speculate wildly about which contestants have had
cosmetic surgery and what they've had done.
</P>
<P>
   Then you can decide if the results are worth it.
</P>
<P>
   You can try to figure out how many finalists are taking Prozac.
</P>
<P>
   And how many should be taking it.
</P>
<P>
   You can guess who's suffering from PMS.
</P>
<P>
   Or who's nervous about her tattoo showing.
</P>
<P>
   Or who's thinking: There must be an easier way than this to win
a college scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Stage a mini-debate. Resolved: Intelligent life doesn't begin
before age 30.
</P>
<P>
   Have a lively discussion about what exactly people mean when
they use the word ``normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Compare and contrast theories about why it's been 65 years since
someone from New England was crowned Miss America. What does this
say about us as a people?
</P>
<P>
   You can sit there and quietly hope that one of the finalists
will be a ventriloquist.
</P>
<P>
   Or somebody who plays ``Dueling Banjos'' on the accordian.
</P>
<P>
   Or roller skates to ``Amazing Grace.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, when you're disappointed, you can try to guess what the
contestants real talents are, as opposed to the ones on display.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Vermont: cow-tipping.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Delaware: parallel parking.
</P>
<P>
   Miss California: ``X-Files'' trivia champion, Western states
division.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Connecticut: currently memorizing the opening paragraphs of
the 100 greatest novels of 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Mississippi: has assembled the world's largest collection
of deviled egg plates.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Maine: juggles lobsters.
</P>
<P>
   You can try to guess how many contestants are dog people and how
many are cat people.
</P>
<P>
   And how many have actually described themselves as ``people
persons.''
</P>
<P>
   Decide which finalist looks the most different in real life,
i.e., when she's not wearing big hair and makeup.
</P>
<P>
   And which is most likley to be in big hair and make up all the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Be grateful that you never had to parade around in a swimsuit in
front of 50 million people.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
