<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TED JOHNSON SAYS PATRIOTS DEFENSE OUT OF SYNCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Patriots had decisively beaten the
Indianapolis Colts, 29-6, Sunday night in Foxborough, but you
wouldn't have known by looking at Ted Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   He looked beat. Disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt like we couldn't get into a rhythm on defense,''
said Johnson. ``They were hurting us on first down. And there's no
need for that. We weren't real sound in our rough zone and they
creased us. It's frustrating when you have second and third and
short the whole game. It's no fun. We did what we had to do on
second and third downs, but it seemed on first down, we were just
awful.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Faulk ran for 127 yards on 29 carries, breaking the
defense's streak of 11 games without allowing a 100-yard rusher.
This was a great source of pride to the defensive players,
particularly those like Johnson who are considered run-stoppers.
</P>
<P>
   The skinny was that the Patriots allowed only one touchdown, and
that was by the second defense. Johnson's group didn't allow a
point. The defense also executed the game plan of forcing Peyton
Manning into mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Johnson has the sense that the Patriots are capable of doing
it all. They must do that this week against the Tennessee Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers' offense had one of its worst days last week in a
13-7 loss to San Diego, but the Patriots still have to contend with
one of the best running backs in the NFL, Eddie George, and the
emerging Steve McNair, who led all quarterbacks in rushing (674
yards) last season and is a threat to escape pursuit and throw on
the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll say it every week,'' said Johnson. ``We have to shut down
that running attack. We know what Eddie is capable of doing. He
might have had an off week last week, but I know they're probably
not happy with their offensive line. We have to shut down Eddie and
make McNair beat us throwing the ball. We have to contain McNair
and not let him get first downs by running the ball on third
down.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair is the best runner among NFL quarterbacks, but he's not
quite at the level of John Elway, who can escape pressure and make
the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still got a lot to learn,'' said Johnson. ``As far as his
ability to run, he's as good as Elway. But as far as creating plays
after he's been contained, he's not in Elway's class yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson thinks the game plan will be a little different on
defense this week. Last week's was more specifically designed to
disrupt Manning. The Patriots had had so much success against Faulk
that they may have overlooked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we got a little bit too aggressive in our thinking (on
Manning), and Marshall was able to crease us,'' said Johnson. ``The
Colts were expecting that from us and they did what they had to do
to protect Marshall. They kept us off balance with the run, and
when it was time for the pass, they decided to mass-protect and
keep Peyton clean. It was tough to get going.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is aware that every time a running back has a big week,
people will point to him as the one who couldn't stop him.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, of course, people look at the running statistics and
they equate that with my play,'' he said. ``I was frustrated
because we'd always had success against Marshall. He's a hell of a
back, don't get me wrong, but he had a really good game against us.
We should have done better than we did.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots haven't faced the Oilers since 1993, so none of the
players from the Drew Bledsoe era are familiar with them. All they
have to go by is film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie George has got real explosion in the hole,'' said
Johnson. ``He's not the fastest guy, but he has good quickness and
he explodes out of his cuts really well. I'd say he's not on the
level of Terrell Davis, but he reminds me a little bit of him
because of his leg strength. He has that vision. He's a very good
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is more determined than ever not to let a running back
beat the defense. He thinks the Patriots were fortunate to escape
with a win against Indianapolis, given the way the defense played.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one's panicking,'' said Johnson. ``There was some good
play-calling on their part. We got our butts kicked. For Marshall
Faulk to have as many yards as he did was disappointing to me.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, George had his worst day as an Oiler last week,
running for 11 yards on 15 carries. Bad news for the Patriots:
George has produced seven of his 12 100-yard games after losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our running game has been our strong point,'' said George via
conference call from Nashville. ``We'd like to throw more to
balance our attack and keep the defense on their heels. I think the
defense will have to respect Steve's ability to throw downfield and
our ability to run.''
</P>
<P>
   George said his offensive line has done a great job opening
holes the past two years, but that wasn't the case against San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't see too many 10-man fronts against the Chargers. We
didn't have a rhythm. We shot ourselves in the foot with penalties.
We became predictable after a while.''
</P>
<P>
   George respects the Patriots' defense and considers it the
toughest the Oilers have faced. He's already seen film of the
Patriots and considers Willie McGinest, Chris Slade, Johnson,
Lawyer Milloy, and Ty Law the best run-stoppers on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their front seven is incredible,'' said George. ``It's going
to be a challenge for us to get the ball downfield.''
</P>
<P>
   What Johnson would like more than anything is for George to
utter those words after Sunday's game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 1422EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
