<DOCNO> NYT19980917.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0566 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-17 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMAS JUST AS ADEPT AT TEACHING AS PLAYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Brandon Mitchell is standing in a Foxboro
Stadium parking lot, pretending to be Allen Iverson. He is bobbing
his head and flailing his arms, saying, ``Sometimes instead of
trying to run over your man, you gotta finesse him. It's like when
you're playing basketball, you try to fake him one way and go the
other.''
</P>
<P>
   The imaginary crossover dribbles continue for the Patriots
tackle. At one point, the 289-pound Mitchell laughs and says,
``Allen Iverson, baby. You gotta have that crossover.'' Mitchell
then tells you that bulky linemen such as himself sometimes have to
take on the mentality of tightrope-thin point guards like Iverson.
You ever see Iverson, who is roughly half the size of Mitchell,
turn a basketball into a blur in less than a second? The 76ers
guard has a vault of moves. Mitchell wants to be like that.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't always think that way while he was at Texas A&AMP;M. But
when he came to the Patriots last season, he met a man every young
defensive lineman should meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry,'' says Mitchell. ``Henry taught me a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yep,'' says the 23-year-old Mitchell. ``Henry's older. He's
been around a long time. He knows a lot. When a question needs to
be answered, everybody asks Henry. And me? I'm right on his hip.
Like, `Hey, Henry, explain it to me, talk to me.' You know? He's
been real patient with me, teaching me a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Thomas, 33, is the oldest Patriot. Older than Bruce
Armstrong and Zefross Moss and Tom Tupa. When he was in Minnesota,
he took aside John Randle and Roy Barker and showed them a few
secrets. He is doing the same with Mitchell and anyone else who
wants to listen. You might think he does this because he wants to
coach when he finishes his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he bellows. ``They work too damn hard, man. When I'm
finished playing this game, I'll be done with it. I'm definitely a
player. You know that old saying? It's better to burn out than fade
away.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas says coaching comes to him naturally. And Mitchell is
right: The man seems to know everything. Sometimes he rides down
Route 1 on a Harley-Davidson he redesigned and rebuilt. He turned
himself into a 19-handicap golfer, down from 27, in one offseason.
Since he lives in Houston, he told himself he needed to take
Spanish lessons (don't ask him anything in Espanol yet; he's
working on it). And he has three guitars in his home because he
wants to learn how to play lead blues guitar, a 277-pound John Lee
Hooker or B.B. King. His wife bought him his third guitar, a
limited-edition Harley-Davidson, for his 32d birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're on display at my house. Everybody comes over and says,
`You can play the guitar?' I say, `Yeah. I can play the first part
of the national anthem,''' Thomas says.
</P>
<P>
   He is told that if he learns just a few chords, he could get by
in a band or something.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to know just chords.'' He frowns. ``That's the
guy who stands in the back and just goes ...'' He begins imitating
a backup guitarist. The point is clear. He wants excellence. It's
the same way for himself and the young men he has watched learn the
defensive line. He tells them all that football is mostly mental,
since everybody in the NFL usually is physically prepared to be
there. He also tells them that if they accept criticism and study,
they can gain an advantage over the men across from them, men
trying to protect quarterbacks and create holes for runners.
</P>
<P>
   Once Randle heard the encouraging words of Thomas, the Viking
became nearly unstoppable. We're talking about unstoppable on the
field. And running his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah,'' Thomas says. ``He's a chatterbox. You get him
charged up and you can't shut him up. What does he say? You don't
want to know. Everything. A few years ago, they were going to try
and mike him for TV. They thought about it and decided it wasn't a
good idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Since there are 53 players on NFL rosters, it is clear that
every team needs someone like Thomas. You can point to Pete
Carroll's 15 assistant coaches and assume that players already have
enough instruction. But there are things Thomas sees and
experiences that make him a favorite of the players. Thomas told
Mitchell he didn't have enough moves and needed to expand his
strategy of simply trying to overpower people. Mitchell listened.
He improved so much in the offseason that he helped create true
depth on the line, so much so that popular veteran Mike Jones was
traded to the Rams before the season.
</P>
<P>
   Now Mitchell, Thomas, and the rest of the line have to focus on
the Oilers and running back Eddie George. You can be sure Mitchell
listened to Thomas when the older player said George will be angry
Sunday since he didn't play very well against the Chargers. And
Thomas is sure Mitchell will do all right for himself. And not just
here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brandon Mitchell is going to be _ in the next year or so _
he's going to be a definite force to be reckoned with,'' Thomas
says. ``He has great talent. He's explosive off the line of
scrimmage. He's strong. He's smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Aren't there a lot of guys like that in the NFL?
</P>
<P>
   ``But he wants to do it,'' Thomas says. ``You have a lot of guys
who have the talent and don't want it. You have guys who can rush
the passer, guys who can play the line. He can do both. And he's
very smart. He learns very well from his mistakes and he learns
from, you know, just being coached.''
</P>
<P>
   Take it from Henry. He knows a lot. But if you want to stump
him, ask him about Mitchell's progress. In Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Michael Holley is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
