<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-THEROUX-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LONGING FOUND IN THE DISCARD PILE OF LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DICK LEHR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Would the woman named Leslie who met the writer Alexander
Theroux at a wedding in the winter of 1989, if she reads this,
would she please try to contact us?
</P>
<P>
   We're curious to know what happened, exactly.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because, well, because we recently came across a used copy
of one of Theroux's novels, and inside was a steamy note he sent to
Leslie. Now we have on our hands this story within a story, and so
far we know only this: that Alex and Leslie met briefly nine years
ago, and afterward the writer, enchanted, sent a novel and a note
to her.
</P>
<P>
   We found the novel, titled ``An Adultery,'' at a used-book sale
in Chilmark on Martha's Vineyard, Mass., its back up, in a long row
of worn-out paperbacks. The going price for the 1987 work was the
same as all the other books on the table: 25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Leslie, with all my love,'' Alex Theroux had inscribed on
the cover page. We skimmed the pages, realizing we'd never actually
read anything by Theroux but still knew about him: not as well
known as his younger brother, the writer Paul Theroux, but the
author of a number of literary novels acclaimed for their wit,
style, and linquistic command.
</P>
<P>
   Then the handwritten note fell from the book's pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dearest Leslie,'' began the private correspondence, ``I told
you Wednesday I'd send you a book of mine, so here it is.'' Further
on, the writer urged: ``Please stay in touch with me _ I thought
you were the dearest person.
</P>
<P>
   ``Write to me. Let's do something fun!''
</P>
<P>
   Nine years ago the writer had put these words into circulation,
albeit privately, dispatching them on faith, almost like a message
in a bottle. He imagined and surely hoped for a certain kind of
response _ a letter, perhaps, or a phone call (``Hello, Alex? Alex,
this is Leslie....''). But here it was, this message in a book
washing up from a sea of tattered tales at a midsummer sale.
</P>
<P>
   We wondered whatever happened to Alex and Leslie?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Theroux lives alone in a white Victorian house on Cape Cod, and
at the appointed hour he at first didn't hear our knocking at his
door. By this time, a week after discovering the old book, we'd
read up a bit on Theroux and, in particular, the novel, ``An
Adultery.'' Writing for The New York Times in 1987, author Ron
Hansen called Theroux's look at infidelity a ``bitter, brooding,
Jacobean tragedy of being used and getting even. Exhausting,
sexist, perversely cloistered, relentlessly expository, it is
nevertheless a serious and perceptive novel, an odd and hynoptic
pleasure to read, a book you dislike and can't do without,
simultaneously.'' For The Los Angeles Times, author Susan Cheever
praised the novel as ``fascinating and eloquent'' and said
Theroux's prose style was ``orchestrated like a full symphony.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides his half-dozen or so novels, Theroux, now 59, has
written essays, poems, short stories, and plays, and he has taught
at Harvard, Yale, MIT, and Phillips Academy in Andover. Next year
he expects to publish a new novel, ``Laura Warholic, or The Sexual
Intellectual.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Come in, come in,'' he greets us, finally, the author standing
tall in the frame of his front door. He's wearing blue jeans, a
sky-blue T-shirt, and tinted eyeglasses. His unruly hair, once
black, is now rust. He ushers us inside and after a quick tour of a
study and library that are jammed with books, and during which he
points out the neatly typed manuscript of his new novel resting on
a desk, he settles into a chair at a table in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leslie?'' he had asked on the telephone when we called and
told him about the note. ``Is that a man or a woman?'' But he, too,
was intrigued and willing to excavate this long-ago moment.
Presented now with our findings, he takes the note and reads it
aloud, right through to the end, slowly turning over the words used
in his come-on to Leslie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a lot of love in my heart for you, even though I talked
to you a few minutes,'' says Theroux, reading the closing to the
note. Now Theroux puts down the card. ``Oh my God.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea who this is.''
</P>
<P>
   No idea?
</P>
<P>
   No idea, he says, beyond the vaguest recollection of a woman at
a wedding. Nothing else, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what's particularly interesting to me is to read a letter
of such semi-passion and not remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Say again?
</P>
<P>
   He continues. ``If you have ardor for someone, but they don't
meet you on that _ don't answer you, for instance, and she surely
did not answer this letter _ how can you even remember them?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is bread upon the water, a potential love of my life,
someone I badly wanted to meet, and maybe wanted to continue
seeing. The overture here is a bit strained, in my opinion, and she
just completely said, bugger it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Theroux is on his feet, the note a fuse, his circuitry now
afire. He disappears into his study and returns in a flash.
``There's a poem I wrote that speaks to this,'' he says as he opens
up the collection and flips through its pages until he finds the
poem he has in mind, ``Contrasting Fruitage.''
</P>
<P>
   He clears his throat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Begin poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Would the girl I took to see
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH PACIFIC in 1957, if she reads this,
</P>
<P>
   Please try to contact me.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One rainy Saturday night,
</P>
<P>
   We took my parents' old maroon Dodge.
</P>
<P>
   I had two tickets in the loge.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You had on wicked silver shorts,
</P>
<P>
   Were shy, wore a gardenia in your hair,
</P>
<P>
   Whose scent went down inside me. ...''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ten more sensual stanzas follow, and afterward Theroux says,
``This is about a girl I took to the movies and, seriously, she was
a beautiful Italian girl from Medford where I was born, and I could
never remember her name.'' Indeed the poem ends: ``And I can't
remember your name.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
