<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANN HOPES HE HAS STAYING POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In the fall of 1995 when Cameron Mann participated in
his first NHL training camp, he played on a line with Ted Donato
and Steve Heinze. No one expected Mann to make the Boston roster
then. He had been drafted with the Bruins' fifth pick (fourth
round, No. 99 overall) that year, and after a taste of pro camp, he
was on his way back to his junior team in Peterborough, Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday Mann was teamed with Heinze and second-year center Joe
Thornton in an intrasquad scrimmage at the Ristuccia Center in
suburban Wilmington. But now the situation is different. With
Donato, Jason Allison, and Anson Carter sitting out in contract
disputes, Mann has the opportunity to make an impact.
</P>
<P>
   His four camps have seemingly brought him full circle. His first
one was just for the proverbial cup of coffee. His second was
pressure-filled _ he was regarded as the second coming of Cam
Neely, who had been forced to retire. Last year he was a
disappointment and spent most of the season in Providence. This
year Mann wants to stay in Boston, and his play so far bears that
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time that he has to really come forth and make himself
seen,'' said coach Pat Burns. ``He had his year in the American
League and he's coming off high hopes in junior. If he's prepared
to step up, we'll give him the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns is looking for more consistency from the younger players,
including Mann, who in the past looked strong at times and was
invisible at others.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't come up and impress and taper off,'' said Burns.
``You've got to come up and impress and continue to impress. Their
agents will tell them they're great, they're mommies and daddies
will, their girlfriends will, but I might not necessarily tell them
they're that great.''
</P>
<P>
   Mann admits that in the past, he hasn't reached his potential.
Most of the reason, he said, had to do with focus and how he
handled pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to let some little things bother me, but now that I've
got my feet wet, I've got more confidence in my game and that I can
play,'' said Mann, who collected 21 goals and 47 points in 71 games
with Providence. ``Maybe I had started doing some things that
weren't my game (in an effort to be noticed). I've got to play my
game; that's what I have to bring to the table. Maybe I was putting
too much pressure on myself, but I've learned a lot these past
three camps. Last year was a bad year but it was a a good year at
the same time. I was on a losing team in Providence. You don't want
to be there again. You realize how bad you want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Mann, 21, was eased into the Boston mix last season for a short
time. He was brought up from Dec. 18 to Jan. 4 and had one assist
in eight games. He was then recalled for the playoffs as a taxi
squad player.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first game last year, I played against Philly,'' he said.
``It was a dream come true.''
</P>
<P>
   That stint and watching what went into his teammates'
preparation for the postseason whet Mann's appetite for a full
season in Boston. His performance in the early going of training
camp has him on track for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're never satisfied,'' he said. ``I can say I've worked
hard and the bounces have gone my way. I'm enjoying myself out
there. I'm joking around a little bit more, just trying to stay
focused and relaxed. It's a big opportunity. If the spot is there,
I'm ready to take it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it puts a little pressure on the guys who are out right
now to want to get in there because maybe the spot is being
jeopardized. I don't know for sure but I hope they come back.
They're a big part of the team. In the meantime, I'm capitalizing
on the opportunity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
