<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL STUDY FOCUSES ON HEREDITARY PROSTATE CANCER IN AFRICAN
AMERICANS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LESLIE SOWERS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Horace Woodard was not experiencing pain. His family doctor had
done the suggested screenings for prostate cancer. And an
ultrasound revealed nothing amiss. He felt fairly secure about his
health, though his family's death toll from this disease always
nagged at the back of his mind.
</P>
<P>
   His nephew, Raleigh Woodard, 54, didn't like the odds and the
slight, but unexplained elevation in his uncle's PSA (prostate
specific antigen) test. Both men had watched so many other family
members suffer and die.
</P>
<P>
   They name fathers, sons, uncles, nephews, cousins, who have been
lopped sadly and too soon from the family tree. All shared a
familial form of prostate cancer that seems to hit particularly
hard in African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   At Raleigh's urging, Horace sought a second opinion about his
prostate condition at M.D. Anderson Cancer Center, where Raleigh
had already had prostate cancer surgery. As a result of a thorough
screening, Horace learned his prostate gland was, indeed,
cancerous. Today, after recent surgery to remove it, the
68-year-old Woodard announces he is ``flying good.'' He no longer
has that fear nagging at him.
</P>
<P>
   The surgeon told him his prostate gland was the size of a
baseball when removed. Normally, this gland that produces the fluid
that carries and nourishes sperm cells, is about the size of a
walnut.
</P>
<P>
   Both Woodards and some of their relatives participated in a
study of hereditary prostate cancer in African-American men ongoing
in seven cities, including Houston. Several local institutions are
participating. The $3.5 million national research project seeks to
identify the gene or genes involved in the familial form of the
disease. The ultimate goal is development of a genetic test to
identify those at high risk.
</P>
<P>
   Woodard appreciates the irony that participating in a medical
study led to his life-saving treatment. Memory of the infamous
Tuskegee Syphilis Study still fuels misgivings in the black
community about participation in medical research. In the Tuskegee
study, black men with syphilis were misled and deliberately left
untreated for decades, leading to a congressional investigation in
1973.
</P>
<P>
   This resulted in federal regulations that incorporate ethical
standards for human research subjects, and a $10 million settlement
for the Tuskegee victims. Nonetheless, the erosion of trust has
never been fully repaired.
</P>
<P>
   To promote trust for the prostate cancer study, funded by the
Human Genome Institute and Howard University, the lead
investigators have sought minority involvement at all levels.
</P>
<P>
   African-American urologists were recruited. Blood samples and
DNA extractions are sent to Howard University, a leading black
institution. From clerical to administrative to scientific staff,
the bulk of the study personnel are themselves African-American.
</P>
<P>
   ``The familial form of prostate cancer strikes earlier, more
aggressively and at a higher grade in African-Americans,'' said Dr.
Curtis Pettaway, principal investigator in Houston and a physician
at M.D. Anderson. ``We'd like to find out why.''
</P>
<P>
   The study seeks confirmation of earlier research findings
linking an area on chromosome 1 with the familial form of prostate
cancer in African-Americans. It will also attempt to narrow the
area of the link to a specific gene or genes. The study supports a
White House initiative announced earlier this year to eliminate the
disparities in health between racial and ethnic minorities and
white Americans by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Pettaway said prostate cancer is curable when it is confined to
the prostate gland. This makes earlier, asymptomatic detection
crucial. But since the cancer may not be detectable until men reach
their 40s, Pettaway said the development of a genetic test would
improve survival rates by earlier identification of those at high
risk. They could then seek earlier, more frequent testing and make
lifestyle changes that promote cancer prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Pettaway said the hereditary link might be responsible for
perhaps 3 percent of all cases of prostate cancer, a disease which
will develop in an estimated 184,000 men this year. About 39,000
will die from it. More than twice as many African-American men are
expected to die than Caucasian men. Hispanic men are also at
significantly higher risk of being diagnosed with advanced disease,
according to the Prostate Cancer Education Council.
</P>
<P>
   The council advocates a digital rectal exam performed together
with the PSA blood test as the most effective way to detect this
cancer at an early, potentially curable stage. Since early prostate
cancer has no symptoms, following screening guidelines based on age
and race may help save lives.
</P>
<P>
   Because black men die more frequently with this cancer, the
American Cancer Society recommends they begin getting annual tests
at age 40, compared to 50 for white men. Yet only one in four black
men get annual tests for prostate cancer, compared to one in two
white men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most members of the community are not educated to prostate
cancer running strongly in families,'' said Raleigh Woodard. ``They
are blind to the situation. When you feel pain, it's too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Both uncle and nephew have made certain their own sons have been
screened early, and they work on friends and acquaintances as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has hit so many males in our family, and now another
generation is starting,'' said Raleigh. ``Now, maybe they can come
up with a solution. I'm willing to participate because it might
help my two sons or maybe somebody else's family.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettaway hopes to recruit at least 14 high-risk families over
the two-year study period. Families should have three to four
members with prostate cancer available for testing. Physicians at
Baylor College of Medicine, Kelsey-Seybold Clinics and MacGregor
Medical Association will also be recruiting participants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that having African-Americans at all levels will
dispel the myths about blacks participating in clinical trials,''
Pettaway said.
</P>
<P>
   Study participants will receive prostate screening, any
necessary follow-ups, biopsy if recommended and necessary medical
attention, once enrolled and accepted. Call Pamela Roberson,
713-792-4639 if interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a lot of nephews coming along,'' said Raleigh
Woodard. ``That's the reason I'm not afraid or ashamed to
participate. And I'm glad to be alive.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 1426EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980917.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0577 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-THEROUX-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     09-17 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-THEROUX-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... remember your name.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do you see the connection? he asks. We do. But Alex cannot even
recall Leslie, so haven't we hit the end of the line? Maybe not.
Theroux keeps going. He is full of possibilities. Ever the
novelist, he fills in the empty space, creating all kinds of
storylines and what-ifs to explain Leslie's failure to respond _
and we are swept up in the sheer pleasure of a Therouxvian
performance. It's a monologic rumination on memory, on ardor, on
the artist, and unrequited romance, on writers and the hurt of
coming across rejected books. In Theroux's hands, stories harvest
stories, and so we decide to kick back, loosen our gumshoes and let
our own orginal storyline metamorphose.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
-------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what's interesting?'' Theroux says, grasping the book
he actually cannot remember ever sending to Leslie. ``This novel
(``An Adultery'') is a very dark book.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very dark and labyrinthian novel, psychological
darkness. She might well have read the novel _ I don't know if she
liked me to begin with or even thought about it _ but after reading
the novel, she might have thought, `God, that's like going into a
black hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know another interesting detail, since we're rinsing out
this, squeezing out this sponge: She kept the letter! She kept the
letter, probably as a bookmark! There's another great question you
could ask: Was the letter kept as a bookmark, which is hideous, or
as a momento?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because there is a huge difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Next, sinking into his chair, Theroux sighs deeply.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the fact that she never got back in touch with me is _
typical. And sad. You know, it's like a tennis ball not coming back
over the net; there's no game.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been a player in many a game, he acknowledges, although
adding he has never married. ``I was thinking of the movie, `Love
Is a Many Splendored Thing.' If I can make an analogy of myself to
Jennifer Jones, who's this Eurasian doctor, and she meets William
Holden and she says she's just involved in her work, that she's
given her heart to her work, and that's kind of the case with me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really go out with anybody. I just write, and, I mean,
I would like to meet some nice person ...''
</P>
<P>
   To him, the overture becomes metaphor for the risk-taking that
characterizes artists generally. ``It's really that the artist is
always flirting with the possible. It's kind of like living on the
edge, because _ have you read ``Death In Venice'' by any chance?
It's really like that writer Gustave von Aschenbach, lives in
Munich and goes down to Venice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's entirely possible that at this wedding, or this social
event, I had met this person, that I was just _ she might not have
even looked at me twice. But it might have been a total projection
of what I wanted, of pursuing beauty in a way, if I can make the
analogy, that Aschenbach is pursuing that beautiful boy (Tadzio) in
that story.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, it's the pursuit of El Dorado.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time he's done, Theroux displays a full arc of emotions:
irked, offended, dismissive, and comic. He cross-references himself
into movies and novels, a dissertation that practically needs
footnotes for the unread.
</P>
<P>
   He places Leslie's book into a larger context. ``Every writer
has had the ignominious experience of seeing his book under less
than illustrious conditions, in a bin, or selling for a quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   In his own past, there was the time a Cambridge bookseller
disclosed to him that a teaching colleague of Theroux's, to whom
Theroux had given an inscribed copy of his first novel, had come
into the store and sold the book for $2.50. ``You have to
understand that preceeding my giving this man the book was a year
of his hectoring me for it,'' exclaims Theroux. ``So I thought it
was particularly humiliating _ then I was thinking, then wracking
my brain, because this is the kind of ontological worry you have:
Did I offend him? I mean why would anybody _ $2.50! It's not even
enough for a Buddy's Sirloin Pit hamburger.''
</P>
<P>
   More recently, there's the discarded-book story making the
rounds in writing circles involving his brother, Paul, and V.S.
Naipaul. ``Authors can get very upset. I don't know if you're aware
of my brother Paul and Naipaul?'' In his new book about the two
writers' long friendship _ and the end of it _ Paul Theroux
describes the betrayal felt upon discovering that a novel he'd
inscribed to Naipaul as a gift in 1968 was being marketed by a
bookseller.
</P>
<P>
   But Alex Theroux circles back to the intrigue presented by his
own chance encounter with a woman, and now, no matter what Leslie
might really have thought of him, her failure to respond is a cold
fact that eventually provokes Theroux.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lack of imagination,'' he decides. ``I think, on a
literary level, that woman Leslie should have responded to me, if
only to just drive down that highway for five minutes, see what I
was about. If I sound like anger, I'm not in the slightest bit. But
I've always thought the lack of imagination, not talking to the
person in a given circumstance, is a real flaw ... It's spiritual
sloth, it's lack of vision, it's an amazing inability to be
alive!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the hour, the Therouxvian deconstruction has been,
as critics have called his prose, exhausting, odd and hypnotic.
``You know, this is like seeing a wedding gown: For Sale, Never
Used.'' Like that wedding gown, a mystery hovers about Leslie _
still _ as our encounter with Theroux has turned out to be about
nothing and everything, simultaneously. Thus our call for Leslie to
contact us remains outstanding, just as Theroux long ago importuned
in a poem for his date from 1957 to get in touch with him.
</P>
<P>
   But for now an unfinished story is finished. Leaving Theroux, he
refuses our bid to give him back the book and note. ``You know what
you should do with this book?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You should keep this book, and when you write the article, put
it in here and just keep it in your shelves, and, are you married?
When you get married and have kids, sell the book. For your kids,
sell the book. The book is going to be worth some money, because my
ship is going to come in next year, I promise, and the book will be
worth some money. That's what I would do with the book.''
</P>
<P>
   He's smiling, and so he's asked if he makes the same prediction
for his El Dorado each time he has a new book coming out.
</P>
<P>
   He confesses, yes indeed. ``I'm long overdue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
