<DOCNO> NYT19980917.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0580 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-NELSON-ART-BOS &LR;      09-17 1387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NELSON-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BYRON NELSON: A GOLFING LEGEND _ AND A GENTLEMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANTON, Mass. _ The swing that rarely failed him, so automatic
and so fluid, is a distant memory, but the dignity that has defined
his life is very much present. He is, at 86, the ultimate gentleman
in a sports world that has too few of them, an ambassador who
represents so much of what is great about golf.
</P>
<P>
   Byron Nelson, his passion for golf dating back to 1925, hasn't
competed competitively for more than 50 years, but his spirit has
never been stronger. ``I love the game, love to be around it,'' he
said. ``Always have, ever since I first played when I was 13.''
</P>
<P>
   The man affectionately called Lord Byron graced the
Massachusetts golf landscape Wednesday, a visitor to Ponkapoag Golf
Course, where his stepson, John Tangeman, is a member. Had it not
been for an accident in his woodworking shop, Nelson would have
teed it up, as he has in other visits; instead, his left thumb
wrapped in a bandage thanks to 16 stitches, he was content to
reminisce, to answer questions, to watch his stepson play golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does he ask you for advice?'' Nelson was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course. Oh, sure he does,'' said Nelson. ``But he plays
pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   Polite praise from a man who has spent his life around this
game; a man, it must be said, who at one time came closer than
anyone to doing the impossible _ playing perfect golf. It was 1945.
Between March 8 and August 4 Nelson won every tournament he entered
_ 11 straight. No one has come close and doubtful anyone ever will.
In this summer when a treasured home run record got a double
smashing, let it be said with confidence that Nelson's feat of 53
years ago is not only the sport's most remarkable, it is
unbreakable.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson agrees, but he is so very humble, he says the record will
survive not because the players aren't good enough, but because the
sports world in 1998 is far different from 1945. ``There's so much
pressure today,'' said Nelson. ``I feel sorry for Tiger Woods. I
really do. He needs an escort to get to the practice tee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter Jacobsen won two straight tournaments a couple of years
ago and he told me, `I don't know how you did it. (The pressure) is
already getting to me.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But it never bothered me. Golf wasn't that big back then. When
I won the Masters in 1937, I went to the locker room and there was
one reporter. One. O.B. Keeler. That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   There are those who will try and discredit Nelson's incredible
feat and tell you the competition was thin, that the war years took
some great players (Ben Hogan in particular) away from the Tour. To
those cynics, there is only one response, and it came from Jackie
Burke years ago, after he had won four straight Tour stops, the
closest anyone has come to matching Nelson: ``I don't care if he
was playing against orangutans, winning 11 straight is amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Equally incredible is the fact that Nelson, a year removed from
11 straight wins and 18 in the season, called it quits, retiring at
34 to a ranch just north of Fort Worth that is still home. ``I had
set goals in my mind. I decided it was important to win all the
major tournaments (the 1939 US Open; two Masters; two PGAs) and I
had done that. But I didn't make any money.''
</P>
<P>
   So he became a cattle farmer and lived happily away from the
rigors of travel and competition. But he has never really left the
game of golf, for which the sport should be entirely grateful. We
know Ken Venturi is. So, too, Tom Watson. And Phil Mickelson makes
three pros who owe many thanks to the quiet gentleman who has
walked with golf's giants, from Bobby Jones to Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Forever, though, Nelson will be linked with Hogan. They grew up
in Fort Worth, caddied at the same course, got into pro golf around
the same time, and for many years they and Sam Snead made up the
sport's greatest trio, each so very different. Hogan was the
recluse, Snead flamboyant, Nelson the consummate gentleman.
</P>
<P>
   While they were not the closest of friends, Nelson and Hogan
shared moments that will live forever in golf folklore. Their
Masters playoff in 1942 (Nelson won), for instance. Or their
four-ball match against a couple of amateurs in the 1950s, for
another.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Lowery, who caddied for Francis Ouimet in his epic US Open
triumph in 1913, owned a hugely successful auto dealership in the
San Francisco area in the 1950s, and two of his employees were
Venturi, then an amateur, and Harvey Ward. ``Venturi had beaten
Ward in the finals of the San Francisco City Championship,'' said
Nelson, whose friendship with Lowery was the reason he came out of
retirement just to play in the Crosby Pro-Am. (Even today, Nelson
keeps in touch with Margaret Lowery, Eddie's widow.)
</P>
<P>
   At a dinner party, Lowery was talking great things about Venturi
and Ward. ``He said they could beat anybody. George Coleman, one of
Eddie's friends and a friend of mine and Ben's, said: `Anybody.'
And Eddie said: `Anybody.'''
</P>
<P>
   The wheels started turning, said Nelson, and Coleman went to
work. He called Hogan at a hotel (``Of course, Ben wasn't at the
party. Not Ben.'') and the guys from Fort Worth accepted the
challenge. ``George told Eddie he had two guys, and Eddie asked
who. George said, `Hogan and Nelson.' There was quiet for a moment,
then Eddie said, `They'll beat them, too.'''
</P>
<P>
   And they nearly did, as the match went to the 18th hole at
Cypress Point and wasn't decided until Hogan made a birdie on top
of Ward's birdie to clinch a 1-up win. ``Best four-ball match I
ever saw,'' said Nelson. ``The four of us were 27 under. We didn't
get our first lead until the 10th hole when Ben holed out for an
eagle-3. Ben and I shot 59.''
</P>
<P>
   His life is one great memory after another, nearly all of the
details intact in his razor-sharp mind.
</P>
<P>
   The 1939 playoff loss to Henry Picard in the PGA Championship?
``I was 1-up and put a chip shot to about 3 feet on the 36th hole.
Picard knocked it to about a foot, absolutely stymied me. Now I'm
trying to be as honest as possible, though losers always
exaggerate.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1937 British Open, his first appearance in that event? ``I
finished fourth and won $187. It cost me $3,000 to make that trip
and take a month off from my job at a club in Reading, Pa.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1939 Massachusetts Open at Worcester CC? His good friend,
Jugs McSpaden, was the head pro and Nelson laughs: ``The only
reason he invited me was because it was his home course and he
figured he could beat me.''
</P>
<P>
   But McSpaden, who made himself famous for finishing second to
Nelson in many of those memorable 11 tournaments, came up short.
``On the 16th hole we were tied, but I holed out from a bunker.''
More laughter. ``I stayed with him and ate his food and beat him.
Jugs was a great friend.''
</P>
<P>
   He is a legend, yes, but he's a legend from an era long before
ESPN and teleconferences, pregame shows, and talk radio. Certainly,
Nelson was a legend long before million-dollar contracts were
handed out like politicians hand out fliers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``In 1945, I got one endorsement that year,'' said Nelson.
``Wheaties, for $200.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson let that sink in. Years later, he said, he met people who
told him Pete Rose had just signed with Wheaties. ``For $880,000.''
Nelson laughed heartily, not a hint of bitterness in the warped
irony: A player who disgraced his sport being paid so much more
than a player who added so much class to his.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Nelson appreciates the great life he has had, and
continues to live. He shared ``50 years and 4 months'' with his
beloved first wife, Louise, who died in 1985. About a year later he
married Peggy, and the two make quite a team; yesterday she drove
the cart as they watched her son and some friends play golf.
</P>
<P>
   Not much of a fuss was made about Nelson's appearance. A few
women two fairways over yelled out their best wishes and some
gentlemen stopped by to tell Nelson that it was their pleasure to
meet him. He smiled, shook hands, and somehow you got the feeling
that Nelson felt the honor was his.
</P>
<P>
   True legends are like that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
