<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0586 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-DELA-HOYA-BOS &LR;      09-17 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELA-HOYA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURT BY COMMENTS, DE LA HOYA WANTS TO MAKE CHAVEZ PAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LAS VEGAS _ It is not often that The Businessman takes things
personally. There is no room for such emotion in Oscar De La Hoya's
world because such a thing could blow the deal and everything he
does and says is about creating the next deal.
</P>
<P>
   Everything, it seems, but what he has been saying this week and
plans to do Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Then The Businessman will fill the Thomas and Mack Center with
friends and enemies, both of whom will be there to see him destroy
Julio Cesar Chavez, the once proud Mexican champion who has not
been what he used to be for a long time. Certainly, Chavez wasn't
two years ago when De La Hoya sliced him open 90 seconds into their
first meeting by hitting his eyebrow with a jab that caused a cut
sustained in sparring several weeks earlier to split wide open.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez had hidden the injury from Nevada boxing officials with
makeup because he wanted the more than $8 million he figured to
earn and because he believed he was still Chavez and De La Hoya was
merely a mijo, a small boy from the barrios of East Los Angeles who
meant nothing to him but a payday.
</P>
<P>
   But the mijo busted him up, breaking his nose and leaving his
face a sea of red before the bout was stopped in the fourth round.
When it was over, he had seemingly also broken Chavez's heart
because instead of acting like a fallen champion, he acted like a
spoiled brat, refusing to give De La Hoya even an ounce of respect.
</P>
<P>
   That night, Chavez dismissed De La Hoya with a wave of his hand
at a postfight press conference, then launched into a litany of
absurd excuses.
</P>
<P>
   He blamed the loss on his sparring partners, his unwillingness
to postpone the fight, and even his young son, who Chavez said
reopened the cut the week before the bout while roughhousing with
him. All these things had conspired against him, Chavez whined, but
De La Hoya?
</P>
<P>
   ``He hits like nothing,'' Chavez snapped.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the tirade, De La Hoya was an afterthought, something
he had not been since long before he won a gold medal at the 1992
Olympics in Barcelona. He did not like it, and unfortunately for
Chavez, he has not forgotten it, which is why he insisted this week
that Friday night's pay-per-view match for the World Boxing Council
welterweight title is not a business meeting, as most of his other
fights have seemed to be.
</P>
<P>
   This fight is not about a championship or the $6 million purse
he figures to gross or even about the prospect he and Chavez might
set a pay-per-view record for sales of a non-heavyweight title
fight.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, such things consume De La Hoya, who once modeled a
line of sportswear bearing his name a day before he was to defend
one of his titles. But this time boxing's Ultimate Businessman
insists it is not about business.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is personal,'' the undefeated (28-0, 23 knockouts) De La
Hoya said Wednesday. ``The first fight, I went in with respect for
him. This fight, I'll show no respect. I'll not be satisfied unless
I have a devastating knockout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe this guy had the nerve to make all those
excuses. If he was a real champion, he would have said, `Oscar beat
me tonight, but there'll be another night.' He was my idol once,
but I found out he wasn't what I thought he was. I didn't lose
respect for his accomplishments but I have no reason to respect him
outside the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is bad blood between us. I don't respect the guy. He's
not my next opponent. He's my next victim. That's the way I see the
guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to know what kind of person he was the first fight, and
I just don't like the guy. He's very arrogant. That's his choice,
but I don't have to like it. He don't like me and I don't like him.
Inside that ring, I'll hate him more.''
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to believe such words are coming from the mouth
of boxing's Golden Boy. Although his image has been tarnished in
recent months with the birth of a son out of wedlock and news that
his promoter, Bob Arum, believes he has enough of a gambling
problem to ask Las Vegas casinos to hold him to a $25,000 limit, De
La Hoya never speaks this way.
</P>
<P>
   He has always honored his opponents publicly _ the greats like
Chavez and Pernell Whitaker and the near greats like James Leija
and the not so great like Patrick Charpentier and David Kamau. All
have been covered with De La Hoya's charm, both before they fought
him and after he destroyed them.
</P>
<P>
   All, that is, until now, because this time something is
different. This time the mijo wants to be a man, so he brags that
he will destroy a fighter who once was his idol.
</P>
<P>
   He says he will knock out Chavez not for a 10 count but ``for a
20 count,'' to prove to him who is the better man. From most
fighters, such talk would mean nothing. It would be what you expect
of them, what they do in the days leading up to a confrontation
like this to steel themselves as much as to con their opponent.
Most often, it is meaningless air.
</P>
<P>
   But Oscar De La Hoya is not most fighters. He is the sport's
rising ATM machine, a fighter everyone wants to do battle with
because along with the beating comes a big payday and a smile.
</P>
<P>
   He is, as he says, his own conglomerate, a man-child at 25 who
made $38 million last year and figures to make more this year not
because he can fight but because he can smile and fight and charm
and fight and model and fight and talk and fight and sell and fight
and persuade women to buy pay-per-view to watch him fight.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, he does all these things before a fight, but this time
he has not. This time he has glowered. This time he seemed nervous
at the final press conference and filled with something bad for
Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   This night, he says, he will come to the Thomas and Mack with
bad intentions. He will go there to do only one thing. Not to fight
the legend of Julio Cesar Chavez, but to destroy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of fighters can't admit it's over,'' De La Hoya said.
``It's tough to accept. Being on top so long, you don't want to
admit you're losing it. That's when they start to get hurt. A
fighter like Chavez will never admit he lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm taking nothing for granted. I'm well prepared. But I'm
faster. I'm stronger. I've prepared like for no other fight. The
first fight, there was more respect because of his name and his
record, but now I know what kind of fighter he is. I've felt his
power and seen his speed. There won't be any respect for him this
time. He says he's ready to die up in that ring. Good. I'm dying to
knock him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``After this fight, Julio Cesar Chavez should retire. He knows
this is his last big event. He knows that. After this, it's over
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   A businessman doesn't talk like that about his partner unless
they are to become partners in only one thing. Pain.
</P>
<P>
   That is the business boxing's Ultimate Businessman will be about
Friday night. The pain business ... on the inflicting end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
