<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEDDING-CAKES-$ADV20-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK IN VOGUE, DESSERT TAKES THE CAKE AT WEDDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 20)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, N.Y. _ It's Saturday morning of Labor Day weekend and
wedding bells are ringing.
</P>
<P>
   Which means this is crunch time for Dan Raymond, the one-man
wedding cake decorator at Vanilla Bean Bakery. He has booked 26
cakes for the weekend, with 16 of his butter cream creations due to
be delivered this day.
</P>
<P>
   A disco beat from a portable CD player sends waves of energy
throughout the ground floor of the anonymous red brick building, a
former garage, across from the Fourth Street bakery. This is
Raymond's shop. At 10 a.m. he has been on the job for four hours, a
workday that promises to continue through the early evening.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond sits in front of a white-frosted cake, a parchment paper
cone for applying frosting in his right hand, his wrist squeezing
in rhythm to the lively disco sound as he applies a ruffle border
to one tier of the cake. The faded tattoo of a dragon on his right
forearm pulses with each squeeze.
</P>
<P>
   ``The faster the beat,'' he says, ``the faster I decorate.''
</P>
<P>
   In less than 15 minutes he will add butter cream string and lace
to the border, pearls, and plastic columns coated with frosting on
which the next tier of the cake will rest. The finished product, a
chocolate mousse five-tier traditional Simple Treasury-style white
cake, all 90-degree angles, is not scheduled to be delivered until
4:30.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to give it a personal touch, so it has a little oomph
to it,'' Raymond says, putting flourishing decorations on one of
the layers. ``I don't want it to be just roses.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the cake is the second most important thing to the
wedding. The bride should be the most important. It's her day, and
I'm not trying to upstage her. But the cake is the showpiece of the
room.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't dismiss Raymond's observation as mere artist's pride.
Wedding cakes, a symbol of both bounty and good luck, have been a
centerpiece of wedding celebrations since the 17th century, when a
French pastry chef invented the first tiered, edible cake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the piece de resistance at every wedding reception,''
says Millie Martini Bratten, editor-in-chief of Bride's magazine.
``The cake is very, very important to people. They're eager to have
something beautiful and memorable and something the guests will
comment on.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla Bean Bakery, like most cake suppliers, charges on the
estimated number of servings, with the price increasing based on
extra decorations requested. Vanilla Bean's basic price range is
$1.35 to $3 per person; its cakes for a 250-person reception
generally cost between $500 and $600. If this sounds like a pretty
penny for dessert, consider that in 1998 the average cost for a
wedding of 200 of your closest relatives and friends is $19,104,
Bratten said.
</P>
<P>
   Before hiring Raymond three years ago, Vanilla Bean owners
Buster and Debbie Alberino decorated all of their wedding cakes
themselves. It was tedious and time-consuming for the Alberinos,
whose business was growing quickly.
</P>
<P>
   They needed to find someone who could turn their cakes into
treasures to remember. They found Raymond, and it has by both
accounts been a solid marriage, with the wedding cake business more
than doubling during the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   In August they turned out 147 wedding cakes, and that might have
been a mere warm-up. September and October are among the busiest
months of the year for weddings. This particular part of the bakery
has been so successful that later this fall the Alberinos will open
a wedding cake gallery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt Dan could bring something more to the table for us. In
the industry, his peers know he's very good,'' Buster observes.
``He's very professional. He's seen everything and he can handle
the stress and the pressure very well.''
</P>
<P>
   As organized and efficient as he is artistic, Raymond, 35, is
also the bakery's administrator for all wedding cakes. He takes the
orders, preferably at least three months in advance, and works with
the bride-to-be and her family as they try to determine exactly
what style of cake they desire as well as how they want it
decorated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brides of today, for the most part, know what they want, and I
think Martha Stewart is a major reason why,'' he explains. ``She
does a book every year on weddings and wedding cakes, and it's had
a huge impact. Most of the families that walk in here have a good
idea what they want for a wedding cake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, I think Martha Stewart has helped make the wedding cake
important again. I think not so long ago it didn't used to be such
an important issue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
