<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0613 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ECONOMY-0918-C     09-17 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECONOMY-0918-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    $500 MILLION-PLUS IN THE HOLE, US BUSINESSES MULL FATE IN RUSSIA
 &HT;    (ED: With optional add beginning at 750 words.)
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ American and other multinational corporations doing
business in Russia have lost nearly $500 million so far in the
country's severe economic crisis, and some companies could pull out
of the shriveling market altogether.
</P>
<P>
   In a disastrous month that began with the ruble's devaluation on
Aug. 17, many American and other Western firms -- including
SmithKline Beecham, R.J. Reynolds International and Proctor &AMP;
Gamble -- have been forced to lay off hundreds of Russian employees
and stop bringing goods to the Russia market because of the
paralyzed banking system.
</P>
<P>
   The situation could turn bleaker if Russia's new government
implements protectionist measures and Soviet-style currency
controls being considered to weather the crisis, business leaders
in Moscow warned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you want us here or not?'' Scott Blacklin, president of the
495-member American Chamber of Commerce in Russia, told a news
conference Thursday. It was a blunt message for Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov as he continues to form a new government and
construct a crisis plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We -- all of us -- believed in the reform process, believed
that real progress was being made, and it turned out that we were
wrong,'' Blacklin said.
</P>
<P>
   The further fall Thursday of the ruble did nothing to change
attitudes. The ruble ended the day at an official rate of about 15
to the dollar, and traded as low as 17 on the street. The Russian
currency was 6.2 to the dollar in mid-August before the crisis
erupted.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's central bank, now headed by a Soviet-era banker Viktor
Gerashchenko, announced that it would print more rubles to pay
state debts and wages to public employees, raising fears that
rampant inflation could follow.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Deputy U.S. Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers
told the House International Relations Committee Thursday that
Western creditors would only advance fresh money to Russia if it
fulfilled reform pledges.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (Russia authorities) must resist pressures to spend and
lend which will doom the economy to another bout of high, perhaps
hyperinflation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Banking and finance companies have been hardest hit by the
economic crisis so far, laying off as much as 75 percent of their
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be a lot of empty office space,'' said Neil
Greer, chief executive officer of Regent European Securities Ltd.,
which has fired about 40 percent of its Moscow staff.
</P>
<P>
   The makers of consumer goods and food products also have
suffered, mainly because their Russian distributors have been
unable to pay them since their money has been frozen in Russian
bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The situation has prompted foreign companies in Russia to
essentially suspend business -- selling off inventories already in
the country, but holding off on further incoming shipments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've stopped importing stock,'' said Paul Carter, of
SmithKline Beecham, the cosmetic and pharmaceutical giant that
imports Aquafresh toothpaste and other products to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of Russians still want to buy products. But the company
is currently owed $20 million by its Russian distributors.
</P>
<P>
   SmithKline Beecham is not alone. About 50 major companies have
lost nearly half a billion dollars in Russia since the crisis
began, according to a chamber of commerce survey.
</P>
<P>
   The losses already could reach into the billions of dollars
figuring unpaid debts and the decline of potential sales for the
hundreds of American companies in Russia, Blacklin said.
</P>
<P>
   RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp.'s R.J. Reynolds International tobacco
unit, which has invested more than $400 million opening production
facilities in Russia since 1992, told Reuters news agency that it
has temporarily ceased making cigarettes at its factories there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you today there's no production going on,''
spokesman Adam Byran-Brown said, adding that he could not say when
production would restart. ``There's very little trade going on.
We're still selling cigarettes, but it is a struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials with Proctor &AMP; Gamble, the No. 1 advertiser last year
on Russian television, declined to be interviewed. But the
consumer-products company said in a statement that it, too,
``halted shipments'' for a period and that the economic turmoil
``made it very difficult to determine the appropriate pricing.''
</P>
<P>
   A multinational like Coca-Cola Co., which has built a network of
regional bottling plants in Russia, is more immune from the
problems than a company which must import to replenish its
inventory. But a spokesman acknowledged that it also has suffered
problems in the turbulent market.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   There is little that American and other foreign companies can do
to recover the money owed them. The Russian court system is flawed
and overburdened, meaning it is unlikely that firms could
successfully sue to seek money owed them.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian banking freeze also means that some foreign and
Russian companies have had difficulty paying their local employees,
whose salaries were directly deposited in Russian accounts before
the crisis and now cannot be withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a business point of view, it is simply horrible. We've
worked years training local staff, building relationships with
Russian clients, earning trust and learning who to trust. Now
that's all vanishing,'' said the Moscow head of a Fortune 500
company doing business in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Yet one segment of the market is relishing the crisis. Shipping
and moving companies say they are turning away business because
demand is so great.
</P>
<P>
   Vladislav Dubov, sales manager for the Allied Pickford moving
company, said business has increased 40 percent since late August.
</P>
<P>
   The new clients are mainly investment and finance companies who
are moving out -- in some cases moving employees' belongings, but
keeping the staff in Moscow for now, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most major firms have decided to remain in Russia, awaiting to
see how Primakov and his new government deal with the crisis. But
decisions on whether to dramatically cut staff and expenses will
soon be made, said officials at several multinational companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, the business community feels like it was hit by
a neutron bomb, and we've all been irradiated, which means that we
are all alive today, but in 30 days, 60 days, 90 days some of us
are going to die. And the rest of us will recover, but will have to
lay around and throw up for a while,'' said Blacklin, of the
chamber of commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
