A0638 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POP-BEAT-LADN     09-17 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POP-BEAT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO BRANDY-MONICA BRAWL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Rumors that teen r&AMP;b queens Monica and Brandy
duked it out during rehearsals for the 1998 MTV Video Music Awards
were strenuously denied by the singers' management.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Post and various Internet gossip sites reported
without attribution that the divas _ duet partners on the smash hit
``The Boy Is Mine'' _ got physical at the Universal Amphitheatre
last week, resulting in a shiner for Brandy and a swollen lip for
Monica.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, there are certain individuals who are trying to
create a rift between Brandy and Monica,'' said a joint statement
issued by the respective camps. ``Such ongoing negativity is
totally unfair to these two gifted teen-agers, both of whom are
simply working hard to build successful careers in a very tough
business.''
</P>
<P>
   The managers said Brandy and Monica spent substantial time
together at the awards show, participating in interviews, posing
for photos, sitting side by side in the audience and holding hands
and praying together prior to going on stage to perform the
chart-topping duet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've even been talking about the possibility of going on
tour together,'' the statement added.
</P>
<P>
   For three years, the r&AMP;b stars have been painted as adversaries,
although their managers insist such talk is simply unfounded
gossip.
</P>
<P>
   However, there was no denying that the Jesus and Mary Chain's
Reid brothers were at it again last weekend at the House of Blues.
</P>
<P>
   The battling siblings knocked over microphone stands and got
into a shouting match during an aborted show that ended after just
15 minutes, audience members said.
</P>
<P>
   After the brief, sloppy gig, the elder Reid, William, jumped on
a plane and returned to London, leaving brother Jim and the rest of
the gang to carry on after just two U.S. tour dates.
</P>
<P>
   PHONING IT IN: Josh Wink used the mail to collaborate with Nine
Inch Nails' Trent Reznor on the Philly DJ's new album, ``Herehear''
(Ovum/Ruffhouse).
</P>
<P>
   ``With Trent, we sent tapes back and forth and spoke on the
phone a lot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wink, who splits his time as a recording artist and party disc
jockey, threw a variety of dance styles into the current album,
including drum 'n' bass, electronica and dub rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure I'm an artist who is also a DJ,'' Wink said. ``I make
music out of music, and I like to create mood. I'm someone who
shapes others' moods. I have a passion for what I do, and I balance
making music and DJ-ing.''
</P>
<P>
   Wink _ who will spin at an all-ages show Sept. 26 at the Shrine
Expo Hall downtown with the Crystal Method and Doc Martin _ got his
start working for a mobile DJ service at age 13.
</P>
<P>
   The gigs weren't glamorous, but he learned to make the
temperature of a party soar.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, he hooked up with fellow Philly native and disc jockey
King Britt, whose interests included rap and acid-jazz.
</P>
<P>
   MORE FROM LESS THAN JAKE: The six-member Gainesville, Fla.-based
ska outfit Less Than Jake releases its second album for Capitol on
Oct. 6. ``Hello Rockview'' marks the lively band's fifth
full-length disc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
