<HEADER>
A0642 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANGELS-VIDEO-LADN     09-17 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGELS-VIDEO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE ANGELS GET DOWN TO EARTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The idea of heavenly beings perched above the city
of L.A. is a comforting thought. In the film of the same name, the
City of Angels becomes a literal image as we see celestial beings
in long coats sitting on signs over the whirl of a freeway or
standing sentry atop a high-rise as a breathtaking city panorama
spreads out below. L.A. never seemed so, well, heavenly.
</P>
<P>
   While no one will mistake the Nicolas Cage-Meg Ryan film for a
heavy meditation on life, death and the afterlife, its lightness is
mildly intoxicating.
</P>
<P>
   Based on German director Wim Wenders' 1987 film ``Wings of
Desire,'' ``City of Angels'' tells the story of an angel named Seth
(Cage) who falls in love with a troubled young surgeon, Maggie
(Ryan). It is the loss of a patient on the operating table that has
Maggie questioning her profession. ``I feel like none of this is in
my hands. And if it isn't, what do I do with that?''
</P>
<P>
   Seth comes upon her when he escorts the spirit of the dying man
``home,'' as he calls it. He is immediately taken by her as she
anguishes over the loss. But Seth is like the other angels who
spend their time at the downtown library eavesdropping on the
thoughts of the readers or congregating at the beach each morning
to hear music in the sunrise: He is unable to experience physical
sensations. What good is having wings, asks a little girl he is
escorting, if you can't feel the wind on your face?
</P>
<P>
   One day, Maggie spots Seth outside the door of one of her
patients, Nathaniel Messinger (Dennis Franz). Amazed that she sees
him, Seth begins showing up around her, asking her questions (``How
does a pear taste?''), fascinated with the sensual. His questions
remind us how much we take for granted. Seth then finds that he _
like humans _ has free will (something else we take for granted),
and that he can choose to ``fall'': give up his celestial powers
for the life of a human, a life he can share with Maggie. But it's
also a life of feelings, including pain.
</P>
<P>
   For those who have seen ``Wings,'' there will be inevitable
comparisons, but ``City'' can stand on its own. There is a
sincerity about it that overcomes its few schmaltzy aspects, and
Ryan and Cage keep their characters interesting in a low-key way
that avoids the delicate balance the film tries to maintain. And
any notions that the film might be too precious, however, are
easily dispelled by lively performances by Franz and recent Emmy
winner Andre Braugher, who plays Seth's celestial friend, Cassiel.
</P>
<P>
   Wenders' ``Wings'' is also worth checking out. Starring Bruno
Ganz, the film, with its stark black-and-white photography, has a
more meditative and less sensual feel than ``City.'' But it has
been called a ``visual poem,'' which is an accurate way to describe
its lyrical qualities. Wenders won the 1987 Cannes Film Festival
award for best director.
</P>
<P>
   SPEAKING OF HEAVEN: Twenty years ago, there was another film
that dealt with angels, romance, Los Angeles and was a remake.
Warren Beatty's ``Heaven Can Wait'' was a remake of the 1941 film
``Here Comes Mr. Jordan,'' starring Robert Montgomery, not director
Ernst Lubitsch's 1943 ``Heaven Can Wait,'' starring Don Ameche.
</P>
<P>
   Confused?
</P>
<P>
   Don't be. They have three things in common: They picked up
numerous Oscar nominations, they're all delightful, and they're all
worth renting.
</P>
<P>
   Beatty's ``Heaven Can Wait'' tells the story of Joe Pendleton
(Beatty), a Rams quarterback (remember when L.A. had a pro football
team?) who is spirited out of his body too soon by an overzealous
angel (Buck Henry, who co-directed) when it looks like he's going
to die horribly in a crash. Since it wasn't Joe's time to die, the
powers that be must find another body for Joe to live out the 50
more years he was slated for _ and not just another body but one in
which he can continue his pro career. The romantic complication
ensues when Joe in his new temporary and out-of-shape body _ that
of a wealthy industrialist _ falls in love with a woman (Julie
Christie) protesting his company's policy.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Jordan,'' Joe (Montgomery) is a boxer who was fighting for
the world heavyweight crown.
</P>
<P>
   In the other ``Heaven,'' the newly deceased Henry Van Cleve
(Ameche), a Casanova, finds himself asking the devil for a passport
to hell. To decide if he qualifies, they look back at his rakish
life.
</P>
<P>
   One of our greatest directors, Lubitsch was a master of light
satire (``the Lubitsch touch'' as it was called), and like Van
Cleve, this ``Heaven'' is wickedly charming.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 1459EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
