<SLUG> BC-ENTERTAINMENT-NYT-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Weekend Section stories in sight at this hour from The New York
Times News Service for Friday, Sept. 18.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867. And be sure to look for other entertainment stories from
our partners: Bloomberg News The Boston Globe, Cox News Service,
Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona Republic,
Kansas City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News,
San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GERSHWIN-BIRTHDAY (New York) _ Was George Gershwin America's
greatest composer? In the arts, such questions are futile and
ultimately unimportant. What can be said, perhaps, is that Gershwin
was the most American composer, in the democracy and eclecticism of
his idiom, and in the brash energy and earthy imagination that
boiled from his musical melting pot of pop, blues, jazz and
classics. He has been gone so long, dead at 38 in 1937, that it is
hard to believe he would only now be turning 100. Next Friday is
the big day, although many revelers have jumped the gun. Everyone,
it seems, is eager to celebrate, and few, so far, are inclined to
complain. To show the remarkable range, music critics of The Times
_ pop, jazz and classical _ have compiled a list of their favorite
recordings of Gershwiniana.
</P>
<P>
   ROTHKO-EXHIBIT (New York) _ With the Rothko retrospective now at
the Whitney, a question arises: what has changed about our
perception of him since the Guggenheim's big survey 20 years ago?
By Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   APPLES-SANDIEGO (San Diego) _ This is a hard city to squeeze
into a sentence. It has been a Navy and Marine Corps base ever
since 1846. It is a tourist town, with a neo-Victorian Gaslamp
District, beloved of convention-goers and families on vacation, and
an equally tourist-saturated Old Town, full of adobe buildings, old
and new. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVIES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAB-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Chicago Cab'': Mary Cybulski, John
Tintori, directors; with Paul Dillon, John Cusack, Laurie Metcalfe,
Gillian Anderson, Julianne Moore, Reggie Hayes. Reviewed by Stephen
Holden.
</P>
<P>
   TRUE-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``One True Thing'': Carl Franklin,
director; with Meryl Streep, Renee Zwellweger, William Hurt.
Reviewed by Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   RUSH-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Rush Hour'': Brett Ratner,
director; with Jackie Chan, Chow Yung-Fat, Chris Tucker, Charlie
Sheen. Reviewed by Janet Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   SOLDIER-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``A Soldier's Daughter Never
Cries'': James Ivory, director; with Kris Kristofferson, Barbara
Hershey, Leelee Sobieski, Jesse Bradford. Reviewed by Janet Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   CITY-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Somewhere in the City'': Ramin
Niami, director; with Sandra Bernhard, Robert John Burke, Ornella
Muti, Bai-Ling, Paul Anthony Stewart, Peter Stormare. Reviewed by
Anita Gates.
</P>
<P>
   AT-THE-MOVIES (Hollywood) _ News of the silver screen. By
Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-IN-BRIEF (Undated) _ Capsule reviews by New York Times
critics.
</P>
<P>
   HOMEVIDEO (Undated) _ Short items on what's news in home video
and short reviews of what's new in home video. By Peter M. Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PATTEN-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``East and West'' by Christopher
Patten, Times Books. Reviewed by Richard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   RADIO-FLOPHOUSE-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Sunshine Hotel,''
documentary on NPR's ``All Things Considered.'' By Ron Wertheimer.
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-NOTES (Undated) _ News of The Great White Way. By Rick
Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   ART-NOTES (New York) _ Art world news and notes. By Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES-COLUMN (New York) _ The Antiques Column. By Wendy
Moonan.
</P>
</TEXT>
