<P>
   GERSHWIN-BIRTHDAY (New York) _ Was George Gershwin America's
greatest composer? In the arts, such questions are futile and
ultimately unimportant. What can be said, perhaps, is that Gershwin
was the most American composer, in the democracy and eclecticism of
his idiom, and in the brash energy and earthy imagination that
boiled from his musical melting pot of pop, blues, jazz and
classics. He has been gone so long, dead at 38 in 1937, that it is
hard to believe he would only now be turning 100. Next Friday is
the big day, although many revelers have jumped the gun. Everyone,
it seems, is eager to celebrate, and few, so far, are inclined to
complain. To show the remarkable range, music critics of The Times
_ pop, jazz and classical _ have compiled a list of their favorite
recordings of Gershwiniana.
</P>
<P>
   ROTHKO-EXHIBIT (New York) _ With the Rothko retrospective now at
the Whitney, a question arises: what has changed about our
perception of him since the Guggenheim's big survey 20 years ago?
By Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   APPLES-SANDIEGO (San Diego) _ This is a hard city to squeeze
into a sentence. It has been a Navy and Marine Corps base ever
since 1846. It is a tourist town, with a neo-Victorian Gaslamp
District, beloved of convention-goers and families on vacation, and
an equally tourist-saturated Old Town, full of adobe buildings, old
and new. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
