<SLUG> BC-BBA-HOMERS-RACE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE FANS CAUGHT UP IN HOMERUN RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Between swings, sips and shift changes Wednesday,
Seattle tapped its chest a few times and blew a two-fingered kiss.
The object of this affection was Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   People who live in and around the Emerald City decided, at least
on a Wednesday afternoon under lazy blue skies, that this man _ not
Mark McGwire _ should own baseball's single-season record for home
runs when the last ball has been crushed 11 days from now.
</P>
<P>
   A random sampling by the Post-Intelligencer of those buying
espresso drinks, pumping gas, hitting baseballs themselves or
simply soaking up the sun showed that 57 percent favor the Chicago
Cubs slugger rather than McGwire. Both players have 63 home runs,
surpassing Roger Maris, Babe Ruth and every other player who has
put on a major league uniform.
</P>
<P>
   They fans like Sosa because he is the underdog. They like him
because, unlike McGwire, he is drug-free.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sorry for the man,'' said Sai Tausili, a Franklin High
School freshman, as he ate a greasy mini-mart chicken wing. ``When
he hit No. 62, there was no 10-minute delay for him. Besides, he
takes Flintstone vitamins like I do.''
</P>
<P>
   From the Rainier (Ave.) Laundromat to Alladin Rug Collection in
Pioneer Square, more than 60 people were asked for their opinion on
this matter of national importance. Forty-two had a definitive
answer, though many of them expressed disappointment that Ken
Griffey Jr. wasn't involved in the chase. Ten people said they
wanted Sosa and McGwire to share the record. At least 10 others,
including a quaintly dressed couple from Germany, had no idea what
any of this meant.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was fairly well split between men and women, young and
old, Caucasians and African-Americans. However, there was no
fence-sitting among the half-dozen people of Latino ancestry
encountered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sosa 67, McGwire 65,'' predicted rug-store employee Jorge
Santos, like Sosa, a native of the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Santos had been leaving work early to watch his hero at home on
television. Since the homer-related games left the network
airwaves, he has followed Sosa on the internet, getting a
pitch-by-pitch account. In the meantime, he practically drove his
boss, Sharam Assary, an Iranian-American, crazy until Assary swore
his allegiance to Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody here is a Sosa fan,'' Assary said. ``That's all we
talk about all day long.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jose Camarena, a Mexican-American: ``Latins are close to
him because of the spirits.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the Kingdome Wednesday, there were only Sosa backers at
mid-afternoon, clutching newly purchased Mariner tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighter Franklin Russell was one. A 48-year-old
African-American man, he suggested that racial overtones were
responsible for McGwire receiving a more pronounced celebration for
his record-breaking efforts than Sosa. He said the same thing
happened to Hank Aaron when he overtoook the career homer record
that belonged to Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   Also buying tickets was Nate Watson, a 30-year-old neurology
resident at the University of Washington. Drugs helped him pick his
hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see Sosa do it because he's not taking
androstenedione, which is illegal in the Olympics,'' Watson said.
``I think it's unhealthy.''
</P>
<P>
   At laundromats and bus stops across the city, people recite the
most intimate details about both sluggers, gleaned from a bevy of
news accounts. Sosa, one of 10 children, once used a catcher's mitt
to play elsewhere. McGwire, doting father, Ruthian power.
</P>
<P>
   All it takes is a lot of home runs to shrink the world a little.
Anastasia Diamond is a 24-year-old Seattle woman, Midwest
transplant and Cubs fan as long as she can remember. Sosa ties her
past and present together, brightening her day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just like his attitude,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 1526EDT &QL; 
