<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR RAISES GENERATION X ISSUES, BUT FALLS SHORT OF TITLE'S
PROMISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Teresa McUsic 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So, you're having trouble understanding kids.
</P>
<P>
   It's a classic problem, with one generation of middle-age
managers trying to figure out what motivates and inspires
fresh-faced college graduates in their first years on the work
force.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's time for baby boomers to plumb the minds of the
post-boomers entering the workplace _ the members of the so-called
Generation X who are beginning to put their stamp on the work
world.
</P>
<P>
   For a glance at the mind-set of the youngest work-force members,
read ``Rational Exuberance: The Influence of Generation X on the
New American Economy'' (The Penguin Group, $24.95, 274 pages).
</P>
<P>
   Meredith Bagby neatly outlines the social and economic pressures
facing the group born after 1964, portraying the generation not as
slackers living in their parents' basements, but as a group driven
to self-reliance and entrepreneurship by fear that no one else will
support them.
</P>
<P>
   Bagby, 25, writes that her peers are consistently told that
their generation will be the first to be poorer than its
predecessors. Bagby blames the situation on a new structure driven
by ballooning Social Security entitlements.
</P>
<P>
   One statistic highlighted in the book is telling. For every $5
spent on government programs for the elderly, $1 is spent on
educating and improving the lot of younger people, Bagby writes.
Many young people don't vote, so they lose out when it comes time
for handouts from Washington, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through programs like Social Security and Medicare, the
government has become a kind of intergenerational Robin Hood _
taking money from the young and giving it to the old,'' Bagby
writes.
</P>
<P>
   What Bagby writes is true enough. But most of it is hardly news
to business-oriented professionals who stay even mildly aware of
big-picture issues.
</P>
<P>
   The book is disappointing in some ways, because from its title
and its first 50 or so pages, readers can begin to hope that they
are sinking their teeth into a classic work that clearly defines
the working psyche of a generation.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the writing quickly turns into an inside-the-Beltway
check list of political issues supposedly presented through the
prism of Generation X thinking. It's all covered: income
inequality, welfare, national debt, free trade, affirmative action,
educational performance. It's a work that would make any
self-respecting lobbyist proud.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Bagby promised to tell us how Generation X will
change the economy _ either through different work styles, buying
patterns or saving habits.
</P>
<P>
   What the reader gets instead is a book that asserts, in detail,
that Generation X is a victim of the economy. The issues certainly
are important and should be discussed. But this book is being
packaged and marketed as a glimpse at the work style and the psyche
of Generation X, and it falls short of delivering what is promised.
</P>
<P>
   A few nice touches make the book worthwhile. One-page profiles
of young entrepreneurs are sprinkled throughout, lending a human
face to the generational trends.
</P>
<P>
   But better editing could have made for a more palatable read.
Bagby cites some very relevant points, such as a survey showing
that more Generation X members believe in UFOs than believe that
they will someday collect Social Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   But she takes those nuggets and mentions them over and over and
over, turning a clever insight into an annoyance.
</P>
<P>
   Bagby provides a good overview of the economic life and times of
Generation X but falls short of delivering a readable, useful look
at the generation's work psyche.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Upstart Start-ups: How 34 Young Entrepreneurs Overcame Youth,
Inexperience, and Lack of Money to Create Thriving Businesses''
</P>
<P>
   By Ron Leiber
</P>
<P>
   Broadway Books, $19.95
</P>
<P>
   Learning by example is one of the best ways to be inspired and
pick up some great business tips. This book looks at 34
entrepreneurs who run businesses from a trendy New York spa
franchise to a company producing those magnets that let you put
your poetry on the fridge. Chapters on marketing, finance, business
partners, customers and consultants as they pertain to start-up
businesses are also included. Ron Leiber is a ``Fortune'' magazine
writer.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Smart Marketing: 52 Brilliant Tips &AMP; Techniques to Boost Your
Profits and Expand Your Business''
</P>
<P>
   By Jeff and Marc Slutsky
</P>
<P>
   Career Press, $12.99
</P>
<P>
   This book has some good ideas presented in 52 quick-hit
chapters. Example: make customer complaints turn into more
customers by resolving problems on the spot, the authors suggest.
The complainer will tell an average of five people how the problem
was taken care of, they say. That chapter then goes on to talk
about resolving customer complaints, with a few pages of ideas. The
chapters are called ``thought starters.'' The authors run a
consulting firm called Street Fighter Marketing.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Leadership Lessons from General Ulysses S. Grant: Cigars,
Whiskey and Winning''
</P>
<P>
   By Al Kaltman
</P>
<P>
   Prentice Hall Press, $22
</P>
<P>
   President Grant joins the ranks of Machiavelli, Attila the Hun,
and even Winnie the Pooh as subject matter for management books.
Although Grant was certainly an interesting historic figure, his
autobiography would probably be more informative than this attempt
at turning his story into management lessons. The book is scheduled
to come out in mid-October.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 1529EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
