<HEADLINE>
HEARST, NBC, COX INTERACTIVE INVEST IN TALK CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Hearst Corporation, NBC and Cox Interactive Media
announced Thursday that they have made or increased equity
investments in Talk City and have chosen Talk City to provide
select community services for their respective online offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Talk City is the Internet's fastest-growing community site,
offering an integrated collection of home pages, live events and
chat rooms, according to the joint announcement. The service has
the leading usage pattern of all community sites as determined by
average time per visit, and is acknowledged as the industry leader
in providing a civilized, moderated online culture, the
announcement said.
</P>
<P>
   In the investment deal, Hearst, NBC and Cox were joined by Intel
Corporation, CSK Japan, and Media Technology Ventures. Existing
investors that also participated in the round include: Quantum
Group (Soros Fund Management), Patricof &AMP; Co., and New York Life
Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst will be integrating Talk City community services into the
HomeArts Network (http://homearts.com), a Web site for women. Talk
City also will offer chat rooms for all properties on HomeArts as
well as for a selection of Hearst's magazine, broadcast and
newspaper Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Talk City will manage online live celebrity events
for NBC on NBC.com and will provide home pages, discussion boards
and chat rooms for Cox's portfolio of local and special-interest
Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Talk City has more than 1.6 million regular users, more than
900,000 home pages and racks up more than 4 million hours of online
usage monthly, according to the joint announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth A. Bronfin, Hearst New Media &AMP; Technology senior vice
president and deputy group head, will join Talk City's board of
directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk City provides a `clean and well lit' community for Hearst
to grow our extensive stable of trusted brands,'' Bronfin said.
``Our partnership with Talk City provides HomeArts Network users
with a superior online experience where they can talk with like
minds and find useful information that impacts their families and
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Friedman, CEO and chairman of Talk City, said the new
relationship was ``a huge step in transforming the Information
Superhighway into Main Street _ and underscores how central
community will be in bringing mainstream users and business to the
Internet,'' said
</P>
<P>
   Hearst New Media &AMP; Technology is the unit of The Hearst
Corporation responsible for building and managing Hearst's
interests in new media and the technology that surrounds it. Hearst
manages a wide variety of consumer and business- related Internet
sites and holds equity stakes in a number of Internet-related
companies including Broadcast.com, E Ink Corporation, Exodus
Communications, I/ Pro Corporation, and Zip2 Corporation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
