<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0766 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIANT-REDWOOD-CUT-ART     09-17 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIANT-REDWOOD-CUT-ART-450&AMP;ADD-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON HUMBOLDT'S AVENUE OF THE GIANTS, A DYING REDWOOD IS FELLED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mich.)   (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MIKE GENIELLA   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press-Democrat   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEPPERWOOD, Calif. _ Three dozen awed spectators watched Tuesday
as a special team of state loggers brought down a majestic but
dying redwood tree that officials feared would fall onto motorists
along the famed Avenue of the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the only sign of the tree's demise was a slight
creaking that pierced the silence of southern Humboldt County's
redwood forest.
</P>
<P>
   Then a deafening staccato of explosion-like sounds erupted as
the 185-foot-tall giant splintered and came crashing down, leaving
the ground shaking.
</P>
<P>
   For several minutes, a thick cloud of dust and debris showered
down on spectators who had waited all morning to witness a
spectacle that few outside the timber industry ever see.
</P>
<P>
   It had taken two experienced timber fallers just 75 minutes to
fell the towering tree, which for 1,000 years had stood sentinel
over Holmes Flat, along the scenic route that is part of Humboldt
Redwoods State Park. The redwood, which measured 43 feet around,
was so large that had it been hauled off to a mill it would have
taken eight logging trucks to remove the wood, which could have
been worth as much as $80,000.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, state officials will leave much of the huge trunk where
it fell in the midst of other redwoods. A section of the tree that
dropped into a clearing will be salvaged for park projects.
</P>
<P>
   Loggers Bob Murdock and Darin Sullivan brought the huge tree
down. They used chain saws to slice through the tree's thick bark,
revealing the ruby-red interior that distinguishes the world's
tallest trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``''What an incredible sight! It was truly a once-in-a-lifetime
experience,'' declared Althea Relyea.
</P>
<P>
   Relyea and George Fielding, both Kelseyville residents, were
among about 35 utility workers, park employees and others who
gathered early Tuesday at the site after reading about plans by the
California Transportation Department (Caltrans) to fell the redwood
because of safety concerns. There were no protesters.
</P>
<P>
   During the past winter's storms, the towering tree began to lean
across the Avenue of the Giants, a 35-mile-long route that attracts
travelers from around the world. After months of monitoring, state
park officials last week finally approved the tree's cutting after
it tipped another foot within three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Few trees the size of the giant felled Tuesday are left
anywhere. In the surrounding Humboldt Redwoods State Park, home to
the largest contiguous tract of ancient redwoods left in the world,
the old trees are permanently protected from chain saws. They are
most likely to fall from old age or when their shallow roots give
way to strong winds.
</P>
<P>
   In some rare instances, however, a timber faller is allowed to
intrude.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We try to avoid cutting any redwoods within the state and
federal park system, especially the giants. But sometimes in areas
of heavy public use, we have no choice,'' said Ken Anderson, a
state park resource ecologist.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who reluctantly approved the tree falling after
prodding from worried Caltrans officials, breathed a sigh of relief
Tuesday after viewing the rotted core of the giant redwood's base.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the right decision,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   To make the final cuts, Murdock and Sullivan wielded their
6-foot chain saws while standing on a half-circle of old-fashioned
``''spring boards'' about 25 feet up the tree's base. They decided
upon the seldom-used technique because state park officials wanted
the towering stump to remain.
</P>
<P>
   Murdock is the master tree faller of a six-man Caltrans tree
crew that works along state highways from Sonoma County to the
Oregon border. Sullivan recently moved to Eureka from Ukiah. The
other crew members who practice a dying art include Jason Hayes of
Willits, Brennan Ladao of Redwood Valley, Carl Snibbe of Ukiah and
Shad Rose of Boonville.
</P>
<P>
   ``''It's not often that we get to tackle a tree this size. We
usually take turns so each of us get the experience,'' Murdock
said.
</P>
<P>
   Murdock has been falling big trees since he was 19 and fresh out
of the Marine Corps in his native Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``''We don't do this because we like to take down redwoods. We
do this because sometimes they simply have to come down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Among spectators Tuesday, the adrenalin was pumping when Murdock
and Sullivan, their ``''tree saddles'' secured by thick ropes to a
nearby tree, swung free of the towering giant as it began to
splinter and crash.
</P>
<P>
   Murdock, once back on the ground, took it all in stride:
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, as a young man I felt a thrill when I cut my first big
tree. But now, I'm sobered by the fact that we can within minutes
cease existence of something that has lived for centuries. It
doesn't seem right. But I understand why I have to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Geniella writes for The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa,
Calif.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
