<SLUG> BC-SOLDIER-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A SOLDIER'S DAUGHTER': AN IVORY-MERCHANT STROLL ALONG A YOUNG
LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I'm a (italics)writer's(end italics) daughter,'' the young
heroine of ``A Soldier's Daughter Never Cries'' finally insists,
though her father, a World War II veteran, has always repeated the
title phrase in times of trouble. ``It's okay then,'' he assures
her. (italics)``They(end italics) cry all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   On the evidence of James Ivory's latest film, another thing
writers' daughters do is recall with abundant sensitivity the
experience of growing up in the shadow of literary celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   Adapted by Ivory and Ruth Prawer Jhabvala from an
autobiographical novel by Kaylie Jones, daughter of the author of
``From Here to Eternity'' and ``The Thin Red Line,'' the film
describes how Charlotte Anne Willis (Leelee Sobieski) reaches her
own maturity while closely watching the world of her father. He is,
like James Jones could be, described as a writer of ``brutal but
honest'' prose.
</P>
<P>
   In a film that, like ``Jefferson in Paris'' and ``Surviving
Picasso,'' creates a colorful panorama of people and places while
also suffering from autobiographical sprawl, the
Merchant-Ivory-Jhabvala team brings as much careful detail to this
young girl's story as they have to E.M. Forster or Henry James.
</P>
<P>
   But with no real narrative shapeliness and a loosely anecdotal
pace, ``A Soldier's Daughter Never Cries'' must rely on more than
historical interest to hold attention. In Ms. Sobieski, who was
only 14 when the film was made and has the cool, alert look of a
younger Helen Hunt, the story finds a sympathetic adolescent
heroine.
</P>
<P>
   But Charlotte Anne (nicknamed Channe) remains a more slender and
peripheral figure than the film's wide-ranging ambitions require.
</P>
<P>
   If this anecdotal account of Channe's formative years lacks an
essential focus, it's also broad enough to accommodate a large and
interesting cast in supporting roles.
</P>
<P>
   The film begins with the lovely French actress Virginie Ledoyen
writing a message to her unborn baby, an image that will take on
added meaning years later when her son arrives at Channe's home.
The boy's name is Benoit, and he is welcomed in (for Channe)
bewilderingly short order by her parents, Bill and Marcella Willis.
</P>
<P>
   As Bill, Kris Kristofferson makes a gruffly affectionate
literary lion who can't easily pull off a line like ``I should be
there more for you, but this book's driving me crazy.'' As
Marcella, Barbara Hershey flaunts a garish exoticism that makes her
the most unpredictable figure in the story.
</P>
<P>
   In narrative sections that are named for three male figures
around whom Channe's life revolves, the film dwells first on the
events in Paris that cement Benoit's place in the Willis family.
(By his own request, he is eventually renamed Billy.)
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, with a diarist's thoroughness, Channe notices the
culture clash at her bilingual school, the boozily flirtatious
circle of friends around her parents, the startling vulgarity of
American children who come visit and an encounter with a budding
French rapist who tries to seduce Channe with the help of large
snails. (He insists that she take off her shirt and let them crawl
on her skin.)
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Ivory vividly conjures the family's bustling
existence on the Ile St.-Louis and watches as Channe forms an
important friendship in the film's middle chapter. ``I'm
(italics)crazy(end italics) about opera!'' exclaims Francis
Fortescue, a musical prodigy with a merrily bohemian stage mother
(Jane Birkin), as he blusters his way eagerly into Channe's life.
</P>
<P>
   Though Francis, played exuberantly by the newcomer Anthony Roth
Costanzo (who does his own operatic singing), is seen only in this
middle section and not heard from again, his character is treated
with particular fondness and fascination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Francis, both as a small boy and later as a teen-ager,''
Ivory has said, ``I lived a life of constant self-dramatization, a
fact most people meeting me now might not imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   The last and least centered part of the film chronicles the
Willis family's move back to the United States, where the film
describes high-school cheerleading as dutifully as it has an
avant-garde Parisian performance of ``Salome.''
</P>
<P>
   It is here that Channe's sexual awakening coincides with her
father's physical decline. ``I can't take any more emotion,''
someone says during this fraught stage of the story, but in fact
even the film's most dramatic moments are presented with
decorousness bordering on detachment.
</P>
<P>
   If this soldier's daughter never cries, that may be because the
colorful, rambling tale of her early years has few obvious moments
of high drama. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)``A Soldier's Daughter Never Cries'' is rated R (Under
17 requires accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes
mild profanity and sexual references.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A SOLDIER'S DAUGHTER NEVER CRIES
</P>
<P>
   Directed by James Ivory; written (in English and French, with
English subtitles) by Ivory and Ruth Prawer Jhabvala; director of
photography, Jean-Marc Fabre; edited by Noelle Boisson; music by
Richard Robbins; production designers, Jacques Bufnoir and Pat
Garner; produced by Ismail Merchant; released by October Films.
Running time: 120 minutes. This film is rated R. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Kris Kristofferson (Bill Willis), Barbara Hershey
(Marcella Willis), Leelee Sobieski (Channe Willis), Jane Birkin
(Mrs. Fortescue), Jesse Bradford (Billy Willis), Anthony Roth
Costanzo (Francis Fortescue) and Virginie Ledoyen (Billy's
Mother). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
