<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SOMEWHRE IN THE CITY': A TENEMENT TESTAMENT LAUGHS IN THE
SHADOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Che, a gorgeous young revolutionary with a cell phone, is always
being interrupted by calls from his mother. Graham, a truly
talented actor and acting coach, is constantly being horrified by
students who know nothing (``Have you ever done any Chekhov? Ibsen?
Strindberg? O'Neill? Williams? Sam Shepard? Mamet? Neil Simon? Have
you (italics)heard(end italics) of these guys?'').
</P>
<P>
   Frankie, a determined but incompetent crook, tries to pull off a
jewel heist but is persuaded to stop and deliver a baby. Lu Lu is a
young virgin from China who is willing to marry just about anybody
for a green card. Betty is a single white vegetarian who talks to
teddy bears and screams a lot during sex. She appears to be a
therapy patient but turns out to be the therapist. There are
others.
</P>
<P>
   These characters live in the same dumpy Manhattan building and
inhabit ``Somewhere in the City,'' a well-intentioned but basically
baffling film billed as a ``noir screwball comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Great concept, but easier to imagine than to pull off. Ramin
Niami, the director, co-writer and co-producer, an Iranian living
in New York, says he was inspired by Maxim Gorky's ``Lower Depths''
(which he felt he was living while staying in an illegal sublet on
East Third Street).
</P>
<P>
   Some of the vignettes are funny, and Niami has a good eye for
the residents of the city's underbelly. But in the end, the result
is a jumble of sketches trying a little too hard to be delightfully
wacky.
</P>
<P>
   The cast generally does a nice job. Peter Stormare is
particularly strong as Graham, who is strong and completely in
charge until a young man he is obviously secretly in love with
walks in. Paul Anthony Stewart is also appealingly helpless as Che.
</P>
<P>
   But Sandra Bernhard, a brilliant comedian and a star attraction,
plays Betty in a sort of throwaway acting style that makes her
stand out like a self-conscious diva in a chorus line. The former
Mayor Ed Koch turns up in a cameo as a kidnap victim. For a guy who
can't act and knows it, he does very well. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SOMEWHERE IN THE CITY
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Ramin Niami; co-written by Patrick
Dillon, inspired by Maxim Gorky's ``Lower Depths''; director of
photography, Igor Sunara; music by John Cale; production designer,
Lisa Albin; produced by Niami and Karen Robson; released by
Artistic License Films. At the Quad Cinema, 34 West 13th Street,
Greenwich Village. Running time: 90 minutes. This film is not
rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Sandra Bernhard (Betty), Paul Anthony Stewart (Che) and
Peter Stormare (Graham).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
