</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV20-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYDE AND RODINO FORM THE LINK BETWEEN NIXON AND CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For Release Sunday, September 20)   (For Use By the New York Times News Service Clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c. 1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the evening of July 27, 1974, after the House
Judiciary Committee had approved its first article of impeachment
against President Richard Nixon, committee chairman Peter Rodino of
New Jersey hurried to his office to telephone his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pray that we did the right thing,'' said the shaken and
perspiring 65-year-old New Jersey congressman. ``I (had) hoped it
didn't have to be this way.''
</P>
<P>
   According the account of the incident contained in ``The Final
Days,'' by Bob Woodward and Carl Bernstein, Rodino, a Democrat and
decorated World War II combat veteran, was trembling and his eyes
were filled with tears when he emerged from the committee room. By
a vote of 27-11, the committee had charged Nixon with obstruction
of justice in trying to coverup the Watergate scandal.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt said last week is that the
power of impeachment is, next to a declaration of war, the most
important action the members of Congress can take.
</P>
<P>
   Only once in U.S. history has the House voted to impeach the
president. That action in 1868 was led by Republican radicals
seeking to oust Andrew Johnson from the White House because of his
post-Civil War policies of reconciliation with the defeated South.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's embattled presidency was saved by a single vote in the
Senate, which sits in judgment in impeachment trials and must
muster a two-thirds tally to convict. The charges against Johnson,
who succeeded to the presidency on the death of Abraham Lincoln,
were purely political and had nothing to do with the constitutional
requirement that a president can be impeached only for treason,
bribery or high crimes and misdemeanors.
</P>
<P>
   Rodino in 1974, like the courageous senators who helped
exonerate Johnson in 1868, met history head-on and etched his name
forever in its pages. After the July 27 action, the Judiciary
Committee passed two more articles of impeachment and, on August 9,
Nixon resigned before the full House had even taken up the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is Henry Hyde's turn. He was elected to the House from
Illinois three months after Nixon bowed out. When he took his seat
on the Judiciary Committee, Rodino still was chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, an articulate, white-maned 74-year-Republican from
suburban Chicago, found himself in controversy last week over an
extra-marital affair he had with a married woman from 1965 to 1969.
Hyde dismissed the revelation, saying: ``The statute of limitations
has long since passed on my youthful indiscretions.''
</P>
<P>
   History's important events sometimes are stitched together in
improbable ways. In the case of Nixon's troubles and those of
Clinton, the continuity is embodied in two men from very different
backgrounds and different political parties, Hyde and Rodino.
</P>
<P>
   But they have some qualities in common. Both are regarded by
their congressional colleagues as men of integrity and fairness.
Both also are Catholics who saw military service in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   In the current House, no member on either side of the aisle is
more highly regarded than Hyde. If a Democratic president must
trust his fate to a Republican, he could find no more decent
Republican than the gentleman from Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   As with Rodino, Hyde must undertake an onerous task that could
lead to the president of the United States being found guilty of
conduct that falls under the umbrella erected by the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   He and the committee's top Democrat, John Conyers of Michigan,
have pledged to conduct the probe in a strictly bi-partisan manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this ordeal is over,'' Hyde told the House, ``...we will
have vindicated the rule of law...(which) is the only alternative
to tyranny.''
</P>
<P>
   But the impeachment process is not one that every member of
Congress wants to be involved with _ especially when public opinion
polls continue to demonstrate that roughly 60 percent of the public
supports Clinton's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   In his memoirs, the late Speaker of the House, ``Tip'' O'Neill,
recorded a similar attitude toward the impeachment of Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, most members in both parties were bitterly opposed
to the idea of impeachment proceedings,'' wrote O'Neill, who was
majority leader at the time. ``For a long time, nobody even wanted
to talk about it. Congress hadn't dealt with a situation like this
for a century, and most of the members didn't want to touch it.
Perhaps, if they ignored it, the whole sordid business would just
go away.''
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, it didn't go away.
</P>
<P>
   It was O'Neill's opinion that Nixon's downfall ``was almost
guaranteed'' in 1972 when 30-year-old Elizabeth Holtzman beat
84-year-old Emanuel Celler, the long-time Judiciary Committee
chairman, in a Democratic primary in Brooklyn. With Celler out,
Rodino moved up to the chairmanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celler was no friend of the president,'' O'Neill explained,
``but he would have insisted either that the charges against Nixon
were too weak to be taken seriously or that the whole issue was
beyond the scope of his committee.''
</P>
<P>
   The former speaker conceded that he gave Rodino a hard time
because the new chairman moved so cautiously and so slowly during
the Watergate investigation. But, O'Neill added, ``when the rest of
us are all forgotten, he's the one who will be in the history
books. People forget who worked behind the scenes, but they
remember what the results were...And they remember that Peter
Rodino performed his duties so carefully and so well.''
</P>
<P>
   If Henry Hyde fulfills his pledge to conduct hearings into
Clinton's behavior fairly and in a bi-partisan manner, someday the
same can be said of his performance in a constitutional crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the House, Hyde recalled Theodore Roosevelt's
declaration that ``no man is above the law and no man is below the
law.'' Paraphrasing Roosevelt, he then said that ``no man is above
the Constitution and no man is below the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution is in good hands when those hands belong to men
like Henry Hyde of Chicago and Peter Rodino of Newark.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 1559EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
