<DOCNO> NYT19980917.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0782 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSH-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      09-17 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSH-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RUSH HOUR': KICKS, SWIVELS AND WISECRACKS ON HOLLYWOOD BOULEVARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the set of funny outtakes that end the Jackie Chan vehicle
``Rush Hour,'' Chan is seen delighting in the way Chris Tucker, who
appears with him in this kick-happy buddy film, messes up his one
line of Chinese dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Ha! Now somebody else knows how it feels. Chan's own struggle
with the language barrier has made him not only the current author
least likely to have written his own English autobiography (``I am
Jackie Chan'') but also a relatively silent partner in this film.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, being the Buster Keaton of martial arts, he makes a
doleful expression and comedic physical grace take the place of
small talk.
</P>
<P>
   In a story that treats cliche as a virtue, Chan and Tucker play
one of those odd-couple police teams who grouse and fight for the
first half-hour, then turn into pals for the rest of the adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Chan plays an ace Hong Kong detective who is summoned to America
when the Chinese consul's daughter is kidnapped. He arrives here as
a trim, extremely sporty tourist, the sort who can hang on to a
Hollywood Boulevard road sign from the top of a double-decker bus,
then vault through a mobile home and flip into a taxi.
</P>
<P>
   At regular intervals the film stops short for similiarly nifty
Chan choreography, letting the star flip, swivel, scamper up walls
and hurl large objects with his feet.
</P>
<P>
   His prankster's ease at such moments is the biggest selling
point of Brett Ratner's lively but routine action story, which
involves a conspiratorial Hong Kong crime lord whose tentacles
reach across the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Much screen time is also devoted to Tucker's more manic and
truculent version of Eddie Murphy's ``Beverly Hills Cop''
character. Tucker wisecracks tirelessly and works references to the
human posterior into just about everything he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rush Hour,'' a fancier than usual showcase for Chan's poise
and agility, features all the obligatory scenes in which the two
main characters enhance their buddyhood. Chan shows Chinese food to
his partner; Tucker teaches Chan to dance; Chan perfects a delicate
little glide for hopping into Tucker's black Corvette convertible.
</P>
<P>
   These minor bits of business are often more amusing than the
putative plot, which holds less mystery than it ought to. Third
billing for debonair Tom Wilkinson, who was so wonderful in ``The
Full Monty'' and appears only fleetingly in the film's first hour,
gives too much away. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)``Rush Hour'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly
cautioned). It includes jokey, balletic violence and jive profanity
from Tucker that's mild but nonstop.(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RUSH HOUR
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Brett Ratner; written by Jim Kouf and Ross LaManna,
based on a story by LaManna; director of photography, Adam
Greenberg; edited by Mark Helfrich; music by Lalo Schifrin;
production designer, Robb Wilson King; produced by Roger Birnbaum,
Arthur Sarkissian and Jonathan Glickman; released by New Line
Cinema. Running time: 94 minutes. This film is rated PG-13. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Jackie Chan (Lee), Chris Tucker (Carter) and Tom Wilkinson
(Griffin/Juntao).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 1559EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
