<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0791 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PERJURY-IMPEACHMENT-$     09-17 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERJURY-IMPEACHMENT-$ADV20-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT QUESTION: IS PERJURY AN IMPEACHABLE OFFENSE? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 20)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With President Clinton widely accused of perjury
for twice denying under oath that he had sex with Monica Lewinsky,
the House Judiciary Committee will have to determine whether lying
under oath is an impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   How that issue is resolved will be crucial when the House
Judiciary Committee measures the charges in the report by
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr against the constitutional
definition of impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton legal team is claiming that perjury in the context
of private misconduct is not an impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Private misconduct, or even public misconduct short of an
offense against the state, is not redressable by impeachment,''
Clinton's lawyers, David Kendall and White House Counsel Charles
F.C. Ruff, argued in their rebuttal to Starr.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, lying under oath about official government
business would be impeachable, but lying to cover up an
inappropriate relationship would not be.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall and Ruff cited Alexander Hamilton's statement that
impeachment is appropriate for ``the abuse of violation of some
public trust,'' and that the misdeeds of the accused must ``relate
chiefly to injuries done to the society itself.''
</P>
<P>
   To Starr, however, adherence to the law is the very essence of
the president's public function.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the president's constitutional responsibility to ``take
care that the laws be faithfully executed,'' the Starr report said:
``The president has a manifest duty to insure that his conduct at
all times complies with the law of the land.''
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the Judiciary Committee have already debated
whether lies to cover up an illicit sexual relationship are ``high
crimes and misdemeanors'' that warrant impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-Calif., tended to side with the president's
lawyers. She told CNN's ``Crossfire'' last week that the purpose of
impeachment ``is not to punish misbehavior on the part of the
president, but to protect the country from serious misbehavior that
would threaten the constitutional form of government,'' said
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., on the same program, responded that
perjury is not something that can be brushed off lightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though it might not affect the constitutional form of
government, it certainly ... has a tremendous impact on our
institutions of democracy and our criminal justice system,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Starr report alleges Clinton lied when he:
</P>
<P>
   _ Denied in his January deposition in the Paula Jones sexual
harassment case that he had sex with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   _ Repeated that denial in his Aug. 17 grand jury testimony when
he continued to insist his previous testimony was truthful. Clinton
also denied he touched or fondled Lewinsky despite her grand jury
testimony to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   _ Claimed not to recall whether he had ever been alone with
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   _ Claimed not to recall the quantity and type of gifts the two
exchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, legal scholars also disagree on whether perjury
about private activities could amount to ``high crimes and
misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Low Bloch, a constitutional law professor at Georgetown
University, leans toward Starr's position when she argues that
presidential perjury can be impeachable because ``he is the person
who is supposed to take care that the laws are faithfully
executed.''
</P>
<P>
   However, she added, ``just because something is impeachable
doesn't mean you have to impeach ... The purpose of giving Congress
impeachment power instead of the courts is to give the country a
mechanism if the public loses confidence in the president.''
</P>
<P>
   A contrary standard was voiced by Mark Tushnet, associate dean
at Georgetown University law school.
</P>
<P>
   While lying under oath is ``a public act,'' Tushnet said,
Clinton's lawyers appear to argue that since ``private conduct'' is
at issue, perjury about that conduct is not impeachable because the
lying is ``bound up with private activity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
