<P>
   CLINTON-SCANDAL (Washington) _ The House moves toward releasing
at least some of President Clinton' sexually explicit testimony in
the Monica Lewinsky investigation. Despite sharp divisions between
Republicans and Democrats, a compromise appears to be at hand that
would allow only portions of the four hours of taped testimony to
be made public. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   GRAND-JURY-SECRECY (Washington) _ As the House Judiciary
Committee debates whether to release more evidence from Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr's grand jury, legal experts examine how grand
jury secrecy rules are being disregarded and hithero secret
material is about to come into the public realm. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-FUND-RAISING (Washington) _ Before heading to Ohio and
Massachusetts on a fund-raising trip, President Clinton attacks
Republicans for wanting to use the anticipated budget surplus to
cut taxes. By NANCY MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   HYDE-DEFENSE (Washington) _ Republicans take to the House floor
to defend Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, who acknowledged
having had an extramarital affair more than 30 years ago. Much of
the criticism is aimed at the White House. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   LATE-ABORTION (Washington) _ In a victory for abortion rights
advocates, the Senate is expected to vote Friday to uphold
President Clinton's veto of legislation that would outlaw a
controversial late-term abortion procedure known by critics as
``partial-birth'' abortion. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HEARST-NEWMEDIA (New York) _ The Hearst Corporation, NBC and Cox
Interactive Media announce they have invested in Talk City,
described as ``the Internet's fastest-growing community site.'' By
The Hearst Newspapers. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ It is sad to bid political farewell
to Geraldine Ferraro _ but not tragic. American women owe her a
debt of gratitude for her pioneering role as the first and only
female vice presidential nominee, but New York voters did not owe
her a Senate seat. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PERJURY-IMPEACHMENT (Washington) _ With President Clinton widely
accused of perjury for denying that he had sexual relations with
Monica Lewinsky, the House Judiciary Committee will have to
determine whether lying under oath is an impeachable offense. The
White House is expected to argue that perjury in the context of
private misconduct is not an impeachable offense. By DAN FREEDMAN.
(Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Impeaching the president is a
decision that House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt said is next to a
declaration of war in terms of the most important action the
members of Congress can take. Congress' first brush with
impeachment occurred in 1868, when Republican radicals sought
unsuccessfully to oust Andrew Johnson from the White House because
of his post-Civil War policies of reconciliation with the defeated
South. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NFCEAST (Undated) _ With three of its teams winless and none
of the five above .500, the once-proud NFC East has degenerated
into the NFC Least so far this season. The division that ruled over
the NFL in the 1980s and early '90s appears to be worse than ever.
By JODY GOLDSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-UCLA (Undated) _ Under the guidance of former Texas A&AMP;M
assistant Bob Toledo, the UCLA football program has elevated itself
into the elite of college football. And the No.-5 ranked Bruins
have done it largely on the strength of a quick-striking, versatile
offense. By JERRY WIZIG.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-NORTHWESTERN (Undated) _ Three years ago, Northwestern was
the darling of college football as the long-dormant Wildcats rode a
dream season to the Rose Bowl. Now, coach Gary Barnett is trying to
put the pieces back together as Northwestern heads to Houston to
face Rice this weekend. By NEAL FARMER.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Houston) _ The impact of the Randy Johnson trade has
been felt in many ways for the Houston Astros. The team won 31 of
its next 40 games to vault into the upper echelon of baseball. The
franchise has drawn the five biggest crowds in team history since
Johnson's arrival. But the biggest impact has been on his
teammates, who have collectively lifted their game to a new level.
By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
