<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECK-CASHERS-$ADV19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHECK-CASHING INDUSTRY SEES OPPORTUNITY ON THE HORIZON
 &HT;    With CHECK-DATA. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories for release Saturday, Sept. 19.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD and ELLIOT JASPIN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an odd twist of economic fate, a new federal
program to do away with paper checks is benefiting check-cashing
stores, which charge stiff fees to provide cash for a mostly
low-income clientele.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates and anti-poverty activists say the government
program, designed to save taxpayers about $100 million a year and
cut down on fraud, is inadvertently spawning what the Boston-based
Organization for New Equality calls an ``unholy alliance'' between
banks and check cashing stores that will cost the poor dearly.
</P>
<P>
   But the check cashers say they are merely providing a
much-needed service to people who have been abandoned by the
banking industry. ``We are brick and mortar'' in marginal
neighborhoods long deserted by banks, said Henry Shyne, executive
director of the National Check Cashers Association.
</P>
<P>
   And check cashers are fighting hard to maintain their hold on a
lucrative and nearly risk-free part of their business that will
begin in January 1999 when the federal government hopes to start
paying a majority of Social Security, veterans' and income
supplement benefits electronically instead of sending out paper
checks.
</P>
<P>
   Check-cashing stores, which are largely unregulated, have
traditionally existed at the fringes of the banking industry. Kept
at arms length by state and federally chartered banks, they have
prospered in low-income neighborhoods where, for a stiff fee, they
offer cash immediately for almost any check.
</P>
<P>
   But fearful that they will no longer be cashing the
approximately $16 billion the government sends out yearly to
Americans who have no bank accounts _ economists call them the
''unbanked'' _ check-cashing stores are making alliances with
financial behemoths.
</P>
<P>
   These alliances have already taken several forms as the U.S.
Department of the Treasury develops regulations for full-scale
electronic fund transfers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the SecureCheck program run by a check cashers association
in Illinois, for example, check-cashing stores anywhere in the
United States can set up special accounts for their customers at
Illinois-based Corus Bank . The sole purpose of these accounts is
to receive electronic funds from the federal government. Once the
money is in the account, the check-cashing store has the authority
to print a check for the recipient, then cash it. In addition to
the normal check-cashing fee, usually 1 or 2 percent, customers
must also pay a ``bank handling'' fee of approximately $1.10 if the
check casher is in Illinois and $1.60 if the store is out-of-state.
</P>
<P>
   Under another arrangement scheduled to begin next month, this
one sponsored by Shyne's New Jersey-based organization,
check-cashing companies will provide their customers ATM-like cards
to withdraw money from bank accounts controlled by Citibank into
which government benefits have been wired. Even though the
cardholders do not have traditional bank accounts, they can use ATM
machines or check-cashing companies and withdraw their money _ for
a fee.
</P>
<P>
   Shyne said fees will vary from state to state but could go as
high as $1.50 per withdrawal. He also said there may be
restrictions on how much money a person can withdraw at any one
time. That would allow allied check cashers and banks to reap
additional profits through the use of the funds without paying
interest to the customers _ a prospect Senate Banking Chairman
Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., has called ``outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar ATM-style check-cashing programs are also charging
customers a monthly maintenance fee of as much as $9.95.
</P>
<P>
   Shyne argues that his group's fees are justified because of the
convenience they offer customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We provide location, service and convenience,'' Shyne said.
``Many check cashers are open seven days a week ... 10 to 12 hours
a day. They are located in neighborhoods where there aren't any
banks. I believe we are entitled to a fee for providing those
services.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials are not so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's an environment where the check casher has no risk of
non-negotiability,'' explained Donald Hammond, acting fiscal
Assistant Secretary at the Treasury Department. ``They know the
money is in the account. They know the individual recipient is the
appropriate recipient for the funds. Yet they may charge a typical
check-cashing fee for turning that piece of paper into cash. That
seems at best a market inefficiency and at worst a potentially
abusive practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Hammond acknowledged that the federal government is concerned
about the alliances between check cashers and banks. However, ``We
don't at this point have any regulations governing those types of
relationships,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The unfolding relationships between check cashers and banks is
yet another step in the development of parallel financial systems
that has accompanied the income gap between rich and poor in
America: one for the affluent and a separate, more expensive
alternative for low-income families. These check cashers have
become more important for many middle- and lower-income Americans
as their real wages have shrunk over the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The number of check-cashing stores has more than doubled to
about 5,600 since 1986. As they have expanded, check-cashing stores
have taken on a bank-like feel, offering a host of financial
``products,'' ranging from money orders to the latest promotion _
``payday loans'' with annual interest rates that typically range
from 400 percent to 1,024 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Today, annual business in what economists call NBFI _ ``non-bank
financial industry'' _ accounts for approximately $200 billion in
transactions, with check cashing the most profitable component at
just over $1 billion in profits on $55 billion worth of checks a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups are as outraged with the federal government as
with the check cashers and banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If alternative providers of financial services are permitted
to be conduits of federal payments, that would constitute the
federal government's blessing of grossly abusive practices against
low-income and elderly people,'' Margot Saunders, managing attorney
of the National Consumer Law Center in Washington, recently told
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In a study published in March, the Organization for a New
Equality concluded that unless the Treasury Department builds in
safeguards, including federal and state regulation of check
cashers, poor Americans will become increasingly reliant on
financial institutions that charge them stiff fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless something is done to protect poor people without
banking relationships, the cost to them could be enormous,'' said
Charles Stith , the organization's president.
</P>
<P>
   Check cashers have benefited from the consolidation of an
increasingly electronic banking industry with its minimum balance
requirements and rising fees for individual account holders and ATM
users. In some urban areas, check cashers, pawn shops and
rent-to-own franchises outnumber banks according to Stith.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Department estimates as many as 10 million
Americans, or 20 percent of U.S. families, are ``unbanked.'' They
are the prime customers of check-cashing outlets. According to the
Federal Reserve Bank in Washington, four of every 10 ``unbanked''
Americans they don't have enough money to open or maintain a bank
