<SLUG> BC-CAB-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHICAGO CAB': THE BEST TIP OF ALL: GET ANOTHER JOB AND TAKE THE
BUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is 6 a.m. and 20 degrees below zero on a late December
morning in the Windy City, and an unidentified cab driver (Paul
Dillon) picks up his day's first passengers, a middle-class couple
and their squirming young daughter who are on their way to church.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes of entering his vehicle, the husband and wife
begin prating about Jesus and pressuring the driver to worship with
them. After nastily ordering their little girl to say how old she
was when she was ``saved,'' the hostile child mumbles, ``4.''
</P>
<P>
   These obnoxious, unbelievable religious fanatics are only the
first in a long list of irritating caricatures who come to occupy
the back seat of the battered, dirty taxi in which most of
``Chicago Cab'' was filmed.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, which opens Friday at the Quad Cinema, purports to
show a typical day in the life of the driver, who is driven into a
screaming fury by the collective demands of his rude, often
pathological clientele.
</P>
<P>
   The overdrawn stereotypes include a taloned lawyer who claws at
him from the back seat and invites him home with her; a raving
crackhead in search of a connection; an adulterous couple in
sunglasses who exchange dirty talk and have quickie sex; a
shrieking, pregnant woman who begins to give birth on the way to
the hospital, and a couple of drunken businessmen from New York who
pick a fight by slinging crude anti-Chicago insults.
</P>
<P>
   All together there are more than three dozen passengers, most of
them walking (or should I say riding) nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with ``Chicago Cab,'' which Will Kern adapted from
an original play, isn't that these characters aren't recognizable.
It's that they're shrill one-dimensional exhibits in a cinematic
freak show that bellows a hackneyed one-note message: Hell is other
people.
</P>
<P>
   Kern's overwrought dialogue has the hammy desperation of
kitchen-sink realism trumped up for a playwriting exercise.
</P>
<P>
   The actors do their best to bring their designated passengers to
life, and occasionally they succeed against the odds. Some of the
better-known actors with cameo roles include Laurie Metcalf,
Gillian Anderson, John Cusack and Julianne Moore. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO CAB
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Mary Cybulski and John Tintori; written by Will
Kern, based on his play ``Hellcab''; director of photography,
Hubert Taczanowski; music by Page Hamilton; production designer,
Maria Nay; produced by Paul Dillon and Suzanne De Walt; released by
GFT Entertainment. At the Quad Cinema, 34 West 13th Street,
Greenwich Village. Running time: 96 minutes. This film is not
rated. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Paul Dillon (Cab Driver), Michael Ironside (Al), Laurie
Metcalf (Female Ad Exec), John C. Reilly (Steve), Gillian Anderson
(Southside Girl), John Cusack (Scary Man) and Julianne Moore
(Distraught Woman). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
