<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAREWELL TO A PIONEER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c. 1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It is sad to bid farewell to Geraldine Ferraro,
finished now in politics but immortalized forever in history as the
first and only woman to become the vice presidential nominee of a
major national party.
</P>
<P>
   More than a decade ago, she stood alone as an inspirational
professional beacon for women struggling to shake off the
traditional cultural and political shackles of gender
discrimination. And she did not let women down, despite some
predictable hooey about whether she knew how to bake muffins.
</P>
<P>
   But the defeat of her comeback bid this week is not a tragedy.
American women owed her a debt of gratitude for her political
breakthrough, but New York voters did not owe her a Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro, 63, was trounced in a three-way Democratic Senate
primary by a more energetic and articulate candidate, veteran Rep.
Charles Schumer, who is 16 years her junior. She said this would be
her last campaign effort to return to public service.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, it had seemed that her celebrity would make her the
strongest Democrat to take on incumbent GOP Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, a
tough street fighter. But she had been out of public service for so
long she couldn't remember how to run a campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, by contrast, forgot nothing.
</P>
<P>
   In politics, timing can be everything. Ferraro's time had
passed.
</P>
<P>
   It was 14 years ago this summer that Walter Mondale picked
Ferraro, then a congresswoman from Queens, as his running mate. The
ticket carried only one state and the District of Columbia against
President Ronald Reagan, but nobody blamed her. Given Mondale's
weaknesses, he would have lost even if the Pope had been his
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   American politics has undergone a sea change in the subsequent
decade. International geopolitics has been transformed by the end
of the Cold War and the collapse of the Soviet Union. Domestically,
the nation has become steadily more conservative, moving away from
the traditional liberalism of Mondale and Ferraro.
</P>
<P>
   With many of their early goals achieved, today's feminists are
less strident and more pragmatic than those who were stirred by
Ferraro's nomination. Even Ferraro's pioneering role seems in
retrospect more like a quaint stunt than the powerful feminist
symbol it was regarded at the time.
</P>
<P>
   She demonstrated that she could hold her own in the rarefied
male-dominated atmosphere of presidential-level politics, shredding
a widely held public notion that women couldn't hack it.
</P>
<P>
   But her impact was limited to a brief moment in the sun. Back
then, she alone most embodied female empowerment. Now, there are
thousands of female role models, giving most women encouragement to
feel they may have the opportunity to go to the top themselves.
</P>
<P>
   It is the hordes of women elected to local and statewide offices
in the past decade who have made gender discrimination
unacceptable, both through their own example and the policies they
have pursued. Although Ferraro helped to lead the way, the real
work of integrating women into the major political power circles
and of advancing issues of particular interest to women was left to
others.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, when Mondale tapped Ferraro for the national Democratic
ticket, she was one of only 21 women in the House of
Representatives. There were only 2 women in the Senate. Women in
the Cabinet or other top-ranked federal jobs were rare. The
political dialogue did not include issues like sexual harassment,
family leave and day-care assistance.
</P>
<P>
   This year, 53 women sit in the House, where their presence is
increasingly felt on major issues and in leadership positions.
There are nine female senators. The secretaries of State, Health
and Human Services and Labor as well as the attorney general are
women. Two governors and 18 lieutenant governors are women.
</P>
<P>
   There was about Ferraro a sense of the distant past, rather than
the imminent future. She also tried to get to the Senate in 1992
and lost that Democratic Senate primary, too. It didn't get better
the second time around.
</P>
<P>
   Her presence in the marble halls of Congress might have evoked
some fond memories. But her absence sends no signal that the
growing importance of women in politics is ending. That goes on
without her.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
