 ATTENTION: Managing editors, business editors, weekend editors 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following personal finance stories moved during the last week.
</P>
<P>
   For retransmissions of these stories, please call 888-346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INVESTING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INVESTMENT-CLUBS-HNS (Saratoga Springs, N.Y.) _ For this
investment club, the devil was in the details, not in the Dow. The
Willow Tree Stocks Investment Club, an all-female group, is cashing
out its joint investments just a couple of years after organizing.
By Jo-Ann Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ Boston's bad news bears, the
stock analysts who have warned that the market was headed down, say
there's more to come. By Steven Syre and Steve Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   INVESTMENT-CLUB-BOS (Boston) _ Few of the anguished cries
ringing through Wall Street have reached the Mothers and Daughters
Investment Club. The club is buying, not selling. By Lynnley
Browning.
</P>
<P>
   MUTUAL-FUNDS-BLOOM (New York) _ Neuberger &AMP; Berman LLC plans to
go ahead with its initial public stock sale, undeterred by a U.S.
stock market that's down 6.2 percent since the money-management
firm unveiled its plan one month ago. By Tim Quinson.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-GOSSIP-BIO-NYT (Undated) _ Profile of a Wall Street
gossip-monger, Charles A. Payne of Wall Street Strategies. By James
A. Anderson. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-STABLE-VALUE-NYT (Undated) _ A slew of super safe
so-called stable value funds, which invest in Guaranteed Investment
Contracts, is coming to market. Should you bite? By Abby Schultz.
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-MENGEL-NYT (Undated) _ United International and Waddell
&AMP; Reed International Growth manager Thomas Mengel discusses
international investing. By Lawrence Strauss. Graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CORPORATE-BOND-DISCLOSURE-BLOOM (New York) _ Trading bonds of
companies such as Boeing Co. and Xerox Corp. now is a private
affair with prices known only to buyers and sellers. The SEC is
moving to clear some of the secrecy from the $2.3 trillion
corporate bond market by making securities firms disclose the
prices at which bonds trade. By Neil Roland.
</P>
<P>
   TAKING-STOCK-BLOOM (New York) _ ``Roll-ups'' _ publicly traded
companies that combine several competitors in a fragmented business
into one supposedly more efficient enterprise _ have been among the
biggest victims of the stock market decline. By Per H. Jebsen.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ-SELECTNET-BLOOM (Washington) _ Institutional investors
have direct electronic access to the Nasdaq Stock Market's main
trading platform, letting pension and mutual funds trade all Nasdaq
stocks through a computer rather than having to call a broker. By
Neil Roland.
</P>
<P>
   RATES-OF-RETURN-BLOOM (New York) _ Led by high-rated companies
such as Toyota Motor Credit, Emerson Electric and Abbott
Laboratories, the corporate bond market is returning to life after
a month-long lull in sales. By Kathleen Spillane.
</P>
<P>
   MUTUAL-FUNDS-BLOOM (Boston) _ Don't misinterpret veteran money
manager James Gipson's decision to open a new equity mutual fund as
a sign that he's suddenly bullish about the outlook for U.S.
stocks. By Tim Quinson.
</P>
<P>
   VARIABLE-ANNUITIES-BLOOM (Marietta, Ga.) _ Sales of variable
annuities, tax-advantaged retirement plans sold by life insurers,
will probably rise between 5 percent and 9 percent in the third
quarter, an industry group said. Growth slowed from recent quarters
as U.S. stock market declines dampened investors' interest in the
plans. By Michael Nol.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONSUMER NEWS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ Tips on how to deal with the
vexing phenomenon of unsolicited goods that come and are followed
by very soliciting bills. By Patricia Wen and Bruce Mohl.
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL-WEALTH-NYT (New York) _ Many American families dreading
massive college tuition costs are turning to a new tool _ state-run
savings college savings plans that defer taxes until the child hits
college. By Tom Cahill.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMERWATCH-COX (Undated) _ Will you, credit card, take this
home equity line as your legal debt to hold and pay? Millions of
Americans owe billions of dollars to credit cards and home equity
lines. Now, a Detroit-based bank has married the two types of
debts. By Gene Tharpe.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS (Boston) _ Companies offering products in
the mail always want you to accept and pay. And in an effort to
maximize their success, they are increasingly using dubious methods
to convince themselves that you wanted what they sent. By Patricia
Wen and Bruce Nohl.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-COLUMN-HNS (Undated) _ The year 2000 computer problem has
spawned a community of survivalists convinced that bad software
will have apocalyptic consequences. Although they are entitled to
their beliefs, this isn't a time for financial planning
Armageddon-style. By Pamela Yip.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS (Undated) _ Retirees portfolio has a core
holding in Ginnie Maes, balanced at either end by holdings that
offer greater and lesser risk. By Kenneth Hooker.
</P>
<P>
   CAROLINE-BAUM-BLOOM (New York) _ In a matter of a few weeks,
Wall Street economists have done a complete about-face on their
expectations for Fed policy. Commentary. By Caroline Baum.
</P>
