<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HYDE-WOMAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN SAYS SHE DIDN'T KNOW HYDE WAS MARRIED AT TIME OF AFFAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HENRY KRAUSSE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTIONO _ The woman who had an affair in the 1960s with Rep.
Henry Hyde, the head of the House Judiciary Committee, said she
didn't know Hyde was married when they began their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Cherie Soskin said Wednesday that she had had an affair with
Hyde, who in turn acknoweleged ``youthful indiscretions'' after a
political magazine on the Internet reported the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, R-Ill., will lead the investigation of allegations that
President Clinton committed perjury, abused his power and tried to
obstruct justice in an effort to conceal an extramarital affair
with a young intern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the process of starting divorce proceedings ... I was
no longer living with my husband,'' Soskin, now 62, said in a
telephone interview from her San Antonio home.
</P>
<P>
   She said Hyde had told her he was single.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not know he was married. He portrayed himself as a
single person and I didn't bother to check or anything like that,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Soskin declined to say at what point she found out Hyde was
married, and declined comment when asked if the revelation ended
the affair.
</P>
<P>
   Soskin did say her relationship with Hyde ended on amicable
terms. She couldn't recall when she last talked to Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even remember. You're going back over 30 years,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco-based Salon magazine reported the affair,
prompting Hyde, who is now 74, to acknowledge ``youthful
indiscretions.'' Hyde's wife, Jeanne, died in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have accused the White House of investigating the
private lives of key members of Congress, and characterized the
Internet magazine as being aligned with the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said Wednesday the magazine article was ``an obvious
attempt to intimidate me'' and vowed it wouldn't affect any
impeachment proceeding against the president.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of her affair with Hyde, Soskin was married and had
three children. Her former husband, Fred Snodgrass, told Salon that
the relationship hurt their children.
</P>
<P>
   Calling Hyde a ``super hypocrite,'' Snodgrass said he suspected
his wife was having an affair when she began staying out until 3
a.m. and coming home drunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was so miserable; she said she loved us both,'' Snodgrass
told the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Soskin denied coming home drunk and said her ex-husband was
publicizing her affair with Hyde out of ``revenge.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a blamer. He could never accept responsibility for his
own actions and blamed everything on Hank,'' Soskin said.
</P>
<P>
   Soskin also said she did not want to become part of a media
circus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a very great life down here and I don't want it ruined
with all this craziness right now ... and my (former) husband would
like nothing better than to do that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The affair reportedly lasted from 1965 to 1969 at a time when
Hyde was just beginning his political career in the Illinois House
of Representatives. He was first elected to Congress in 1974.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
