<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO; KIDDIE-ORIENTED VIDEOS THIS FALL; OTHER NEW RELEASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fall Zombies And Ghosts
</P>
<P>
   Autumn sounds a klaxon in video circles: holidays, gifts, a raft
of low-priced titles.
</P>
<P>
   In an era when videos of big action films and other so-called
adult titles sometimes sell as well as they rent, this year's
selection of movies-to-buy moves far afield from the fare parents
traditionally scoop up for the littlest ones to watch over and
over. How grown-up they are depends on one's definition, but this
fall movies like ``The X-Files,'' ``Armageddon,'' ``Godzilla'' and
``The Mask of Zorro'' will all be officially priced from $15 to
$23.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with so many small children clustered at the sales
bull's-eye, stores are a sea of comic book action figures, ghosts,
witches, goofy-looking dogs and the goofier people who dote on
them. They've changed, though: as a genre, video entertainment for
the 8-and-under set has never been more accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, for example, Warner will release ``Addams Family
Reunion,'' a live-action feature starring Tim Curry and Daryl
Hannah, and ``Scooby-Doo on Zombie Island,'' a well-made 77-minute
animated feature based on the long-running television series.
</P>
<P>
   Next week Fox will issue ``Casper Meets Wendy,'' another live
feature, starring Cathy Moriarty, Shelley Duvall, Teri Garr, George
Hamilton (portraying a comically evil warlock who, like a
counterpart from another fairy tale, takes tips from a seer in a
mirror), and Hilary Duff as a child witch who, in a warming of
usually chilly witch-ghost relations, befriends the young (and
animated) ghost Casper.
</P>
<P>
   None of these films appeared on the big screen. ``Casper Meets
Wendy'' and ``Addams Family Reunion,'' of course, are derived from
bigger movies that played in theaters, following the lead of ``The
Return of Jafar'' (1994), Disney's straight-to-video sequel to
``Aladdin'' (1992).
</P>
<P>
   The hound Scooby-Doo and his human companions, from the reporter
Daphne Blake to Scooby's handler, Shaggy, who is known to eat dog
food, are also proven commodities. ``We have a library of
franchises we know people love,'' said Dan Capone of Warner Home
Entertainment. The idea is to cut costs, with savings passed along
to the consumer. ``Entertain the family without going to the
theater and spending, say, 8 bucks times four,'' Capone said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scooby-Doo on Zombie Island'' is officially priced at $19.95,
but straight-to-video titles often sell for $10 to $15. ``Quality''
means that the movie has recognizable stars and high production
values. ``It needs to be an idea that should get made,'' said Pat
Wyatt, president of Fox consumer products.
</P>
<P>
   A straight-to-video movie isn't necessarily cheap to make. Fox
won't divulge the exact figure, but ``Casper Meets Wendy'' cost
about $10 million. Ms. Wyatt said that sales should reach several
million copies. Promotion is important, especially with a multitude
of children's and cartoon faces grinning from the boxes of more
cheaply produced videos.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the promotion approximates that given a larger feature
film. Capone and Ms. Wyatt said that if the characters are familiar
and the film appealing, customers don't care whether it had a
theater release. ``People understand that direct-to-video isn't
what it was in the 80's,'' Capone said.
</P>
<P>
   NEW VIDEO RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   Mercury Rising
</P>
<P>
   With a smirk on his face, Bruce Willis (left) does his periodic
duty to swell studio coffers, this time in the role of a defrocked
FBI agent named Art Jeffries. When a 9-year-old autistic child
named Simon (Miko Hughes) inadvertently cracks a code that protects
the identity of U.S. undercover agents, he becomes the target of
the oily Nicholas Kudrow (Alex Baldwin), perhaps the only National
Security Agency official with his own goon squad. Enter Willis'
Jeffries as the boy's protector. ``Someone's got to do the dirty
job of being an action hero,'' Stephen Holden wrote in The New York
Times, ``and it sure beats whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   1998. Universal. $107.37. 112 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   My Giant
</P>
<P>
   In his own quest to be a movie star, Max (Gheorghe Muresan)
learns to wear sunglasses and say, ``Thanks, man.'' Fired in
Romania by a petulant client, Sammy the agent (Billy Crystal) needs
another client. Up (and up) pops Max, who on size alone (almost 8
feet tall) makes good action-epic material. Max is also able to
vomit on cue, which can't hurt in a Hollywood movie. Even Steven
Segal (quite funny in a cameo role) feels threatened by Max's
height and won't appear on the same set. But Max is such a sweet,
loving soul that even Sammy is inspired to change his wheedling,
gouging ways in a film that ``affectingly describes the plight of a
good-hearted pariah'' (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1998. Warner. $100.71. 103 minutes. Closed captioned. PG.
Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Suicide Kings  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Four prep school boys (Sean Patrick Flannery, Henry Thomas,
Jeremy Sisto and Jay Mohr) and a friend (Johnny Galecki) kidnap a
Mafia boss (Christopher Walken) in the hope that in return for his
own freedom, he will quickly raise the $2 million needed to release
the recently kidnapped sister of one of the boys. But only Walken
stays cool in a film that desperately wants to be hip. Though
there's nothing wrong with the performances, other principal
characters seem out of step with an ``uneven comic suspense film''
(Holden).
</P>
<P>
   1997. Artisan. $83.33. 106 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   Wide Awake
</P>
<P>
   Meet the Beals, an insufferably perfect Mom-Dad-Sis-and-Junior
team living in smug affluence in a mansion outside Philadelphia.
Mom and Dad (Dana Delany and Denis Leary) are doctors. In addition
to being named cute, the children, Neena (Julia Stiles) and Joshua
(Joseph Cross), are exemplary. But then one day a cloud forms, when
another member of the family, a cuddly old granddad, actually dies.
This particularly disturbs young Joshua, who badgers clergymen with
questions about death and heaven and even encounters a yuppified
angel. Heart-warming, but you still ``have to look hard to uncover
a single moment of truth and genuine feeling'' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   1998. Miramax. $104.16. 88 minutes. Closed captioned. PG.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time or appeared on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``JACK PAAR: AS I WAS SAYING . . . AND MORE.'' The 1997
``American Masters'' presentation on PBS, drawn from Paar's Friday
shows through 1965 and other material, makes up two 60-minute
tapes. For this video series, he helped put together a third hour
of his favorite moments throughout his career. Not to drop names,
but there are stories of dinner with Robert Kennedy and moments on
air spent with the likes of Judy Garland and Muhammad Ali. 1997.
White Star. $49.95 for three cassettes. Release date: Tuesday.
Information: (800) 458-5887.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE EVIL DEAD.'' Back on tape after an eight-year hiatus, Sam
Raimi's first feature film makes George Romero's ``Night of the
Living Dead'' and subsequent Romero bloodbaths (inspirations all to
the college-age crew who worked on the Raimi film) look like a
first-aid class. A camping expedition stumbles on slumbering
demons, striking geysers of gore. Depending on the demographics of
your neighborhood, the video's box will show one of three pictures
of the star, Bruce Campbell, on the front. In one he's a camper in
the L.L. Bean mold, unsoiled and looking alertly into the distance;
in another, obviously some scenes later, he's bloodied up and
wielding a chainsaw. 1983. Anchor Bay. $9.95. 87 minutes. No
rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE VICAR OF DIBLEY.'' In a series currently on PBS, Dawn
French stars as Geraldine Granger, an ebullient clergywoman who
wakes up the sleepy village of Dibley with her sprightly and
unorthodox ways. 1998. BBC Video. Four 60-minute episodes on two
cassettes. $19.98 per cassette.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 1634EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
