<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-CONGRESS-$ADV19 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TECH INDUSTRY FRETS AS ISSUES LANGUISH IN CAPITAL
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories for
release Saturday, Sept. 19.
 &HT;    By MARY BETH REGAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At the Upside technology ``summit'' this week at
the swank Mayflower Hotel, tech industry executives were offered a
field trip dubbed ``the DC Scandal Tour'' by a comedy troupe called
the Gross National Product.
</P>
<P>
   But the industry isn't chuckling at recent Washington
distractions, because lawmakers have failed to pass key technology
legislation in the midst of the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to do any business in Washington these days,''
grumbled Eric Benhamou, chairman and CEO of the $5.6-billion 3Com
Corp. of Santa Clara, Calif. ``And that's having an impact on
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Execs were counting on lawmakers to use the last weeks of this
Congress to push through bills on a number of key issues. But with
lawmakers caught in a constitutional crisis, the high-tech agenda
is getting bumped to back burner.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Trent Lott, R-Miss., admitted: ``We aren't doing
anything that takes two or three days of discussion. We just don't
have time.''
</P>
<P>
   The impact on the tech sector could be major, because even
free-market advocates admit some government direction is needed.
``These are very tough balancing acts,'' said Roberta R. Katz,
senior vice president and general counsel for Netscape
Communications Corp. ``Some say let the Net regulate itself, but
others acknowledge government has a role to play.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are issues that need to be addressed,'' agreed David W.
Dorman, a former Atlanta executive who heads PointCast Inc. in
Sunnyvale, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   High on the industry's agenda:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Internet taxes. Companies such as America Online Inc. fret
that states may stall the growth of electronic commerce and the
Internet with burdensome local taxes. A ban on Internet access or
sales taxes is expected to become law, but the House and Senate
still need to decide on the duration of the ban, expected to be
between three and six years.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Visas for tech workers. Companies facing a shortage of workers
are pressing for an increase in the number of H-1B visas for
high-skilled foreigners. A measure that raises the ceiling to
115,000 per year in 2001 is pending in the House, but the White
House is holding out for additional protections for U.S. workers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Encryption. Programs needed to safeguard business information
and reassure customers in electronic commerce. Despite efforts by
the White House on Wednesday to relax export controls on encryption
codes, U.S. companies want to sell software and hardware with the
most powerful codes available globally.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Copyright protections for digital material. Business leaders
claim pirated software costs U.S. companies $11.2 billion a year in
lost revenue.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Digital signatures. The debate likely won't be settled in this
Congress, but next year, the Commerce Department may be directed to
set standards for digital signatures to be used for government
transactions such as renewing drivers licenses.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tax credits. Republican lawmakers are pushing to reinstate a
tax credit equal to 20 percent of research spending above an amount
tied to company receipts. Clinton has threatened to veto the entire
$80 billion tax package.
</P>
<P>
   To get tech issues back in the ball game, at least two dozen
CEOs blanketed Capitol Hill this week to press this agenda, as well
as broad issues such as fast-track trade authority.
</P>
<P>
   While the industry won't come to a standstill if bills languish
on Capitol Hill, whatever bills fail to pass before the 105th
Congress adjourns will die, and lawmakers will have to reintroduce
them in January.
</P>
<P>
   The outlook for the tech agenda is mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Executives will watch the White House closely for a shift on the
issue of increasing visas for foreign-born skilled workers, which
may win final congressional passage as soon as Wednesday. The
increase is critical, they say, because the current cap was reached
in May, seven months after the current fiscal year began last Oct.
1, and congressional staffers believe U.S. firms will gobble up
fiscal 1999's allotment even faster if the ceiling isn't lifted.
</P>
<P>
   The White House is balking at an increased cap unless a federal
regulatory agency is given authority to ensure that U.S. firms
aren't overlooking American workers to hire foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton is under pressure to please the tech industry, a
major financial supporter of the Democratic Party. Benhamou, a
member of the industry's TechNet lobbying effort, says it would be
``very unfortunate'' for Clinton to tarnish his relationship.
</P>
<P>
   On Internet taxes, most observers expect a moratorium to be
signed into law.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't cigarettes, and we're not trying to keep people
from inhaling tobacco,'' says Ross Garber, chairman of Vingette, an
Austin, Tex.-based software startup. ``We want to get people on the
Net as quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Case, chairman and CEO of America Online, agreed: ``It
would be a big mistake to have 30,000 taxing jurisdictions impose
their own laws, rules and rates on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   It also appears likely that Congress will revive the R&AMP;D tax
credit, which expired June 30. But Clinton is threatening to veto
the GOP's entire $80 billion tax cut, arguing that projected budget
surpluses should be used to preserve Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   But there likely will be disappointment on copyright protections
and encryption. Some lawmakers, such as Rep. Rick Boucher, D-Va.,
put chances of passing a digital copyright bill at only 50-50. The
House and Senate have approved measures to give digital works more
protection and they've extended liability protection to online
service providers for pirated software. But there's still debate
over the public's ``fair use'' of some information.
</P>
<P>
   Even optimists say legislation to address the encryption problem
isn't going anywhere. The Clinton administration took a step toward
relaxing export restrictions Wednesday by saying companies could
export software and hardware that uses 56-bit encryption codes to
all countries except seven suspected of terrorist activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's encouraging,'' said Gordon Eubanks, CEO of the $500
million Symantec Corp. of Cupertino, Calif., ``but it still doesn't
address all the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
