<HEADER>
A0935 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-17 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUES: FURNITURE PACKED WITH SURPRISES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The stars must be in an odd alignment. Normally, you
would have to go to the Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Louvre, the
Victoria and Albert or the Hermitage to see a Roentgen antique.
Now, for some reason, the firmament has released a few stellar
examples.
</P>
<P>
   Who is Roentgen?
</P>
<P>
   David Roentgen was probably the greatest German furniture maker
and certainly one of the most successful 18th-century cabinetmakers
in Europe. Goethe said his cabinets were like palaces in fairyland.
His 24-person workshop made furniture, clocks and musical
instruments for Louis XVI and Marie Antoinette, Pope Pius VI and
Catherine the Great of Russia, yet he never abandoned his hometown,
Neuweid, a port on the Rhine north of Koblenz.
</P>
<P>
   In May, at the Christie's sale of the collections of the Princes
Reuss in Germany, there were three Roentgens for sale, including a
writing table with ormolu mounts, circa 1780, that sold for just
under $400,000, the top lot in the sale.
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan, Dalva Brothers on East 57th Street has two
important Roentgen secretaries, for $180,000 and $725,000. In
Paris, the dealer Didier Aaron has a pair of Roentgen mahogany
games tables, circa 1780-1790, at the XIX Biennale Internationale
des Antiquaires, which opens today and runs through Oct. 4. In
Munich, Konrad Bernheimer is selling a marquetry Roentgen table
with hidden drawers for $290,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely rare to find Roentgens, especially the late
18th-century neo-classical pieces,'' said Antoine Cheneviere, a
London dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the most famous ``French'' cabinetmakers of the 18th
century were Germans. Masters like Carlin, Molitor, Oeben, Riesener
and Weisweiler all set up workshops in Paris. Roentgen is so
associated with them that Christie's has put a tulipwood and
sycamore marquetry Roentgen games table in its ``Arts of France''
sale in New York on Oct. 23.
</P>
<P>
   The Roentgen story starts with Abraham, David's father, who was
sent to apprentice in the Netherlands and Britain in the 1730s.
While in London, he became a master at marquetry (veneers of wood
mosaic) and a religious convert. When he returned home, he joined
the Moravian brotherhood in Neuwied. He opened a workshop in 1742
and trained his sons. David, the only son to share his father's
religious devotion, took over in 1772.
</P>
<P>
   As Cheneviere writes in ``Russian Furniture'' (Vendome Press,
1988), David Roentgen had ``all the assets necessary for success: a
highly developed esthetic sense inherited from his father, fluent
French, polished manners, freedom from restrictions imposed by the
German guild (he refused to join), a talent for speculation and
audacity.''
</P>
<P>
   Though individual pieces of furniture may look spare, in general
the work is sumptuous in materials, design, decoration and
execution. The Roentgens excelled at trompe l'oeil marquetry, which
were pieces veneered with bits of wood or ivory to create pictures
in wood, mostly chinoiserie or allegorical scenes. They used
Caribbean mahogany, cherry, walnut, rosewood, beech, birch and
maple. The casework was enhanced with ormolu mounts, inlaid brass
flutes and brass fillets.
</P>
<P>
   The Roentgens were also known for their innovative mechanical
devices. Furniture doors would magically spring open, revealing
hidden drawers, music boxes, and writing compartments. Each games
tables that Didier Aaron has, for example, has three tops. Push a
button and up pops the first top, a square felt-lined surface for
playing cards. The second top is fitted with ivory and ebony inlaid
boards for chess, checkers and backgammon. The third has a
leather-covered top that can be inclined to become a writing desk.
The price for the pair is $900,000.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron's son Herve said Roentgen is back in fashion. ``David
Roentgen was forgotten in the 19th century because his work was too
simple,'' he said. ``Today people appreciate that simplicity, its
modernity, the superb quality and the sophistication of the
mechanisms.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Marino, a New York designer, said: ``Roentgen's
neo-classicism was the first breath of modernism. Americans like
his work the same way they like Russian furniture; they are both
knockoffs of the French, but the lines got straighter.'' (This may
also explain the admiration of Adolf Loos, the famous Austrian
architect who developed functionalism and denounced ornament in the
early 1900s.)
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Roentgen furniture costs a fortune. It may have
been unfashionable in the 19th century, but in this century
Consuelo Vanderbilt, wife of the Duke of Marlborough; Marjorie
Merriweather Post, and Baron Hans Heinrich Thyssen-Bornemisza have
all collected it. ``Roentgen was always the pinnacle,'' said Leon
Dalva of Dalva Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1964, a Roentgen marquetry commode a vantaux (a chest
of drawers with doors) sold at Sotheby's for $176,400, the record
for a piece of furniture at that time.
</P>
<P>
   David Roentgen was a good salesman. In 1783, he lugged 50 pieces
of furniture to St. Petersburg when he first called on Catherine
the Great. He presented her with a mahogany desk decorated with
gilt bronze mounts. It also played music, with two flutes and a
clavichord accompaniment. According to Hans Huth's book ``Roentgen
Furniture'' (Sotheby Parke Bernet, 1974), the Empress was
impressed; she paid him 20,000 rubles plus a bonus of 5,000 rubles
and a fine gold snuff box.
</P>
<P>
   But their next meeting didn't go so well, Cheneviere said. The
Empress received Roentgen, and they were conversing in German when
he started to proselytize. He told her he was against slavery. The
Empress got up and stomped out. The next day, she told him she
would buy two desks but pay for only one, to punish him. As she
later wrote to a friend: ``The furniture paid for, keys delivered,
he had to pack up his beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Roentgen sold dozens of pieces to Russian nobility,
which is why the Hermitage has a roomful of his masterpieces.
</P>
<P>
   Fate ultimately turned against Roentgen. During the French
Revolution, his stock was liquidated in Paris. Furniture he had
made for the royal family was sold at official auctions. In 1795,
French Revolutionary troops invaded the area near Neuwied and,
according to Cheneviere, burned half of his workshop. He tried to
move his operation to Prussia but failed. He died in Neuwied in
1807.
</P>
<P>
   But the Roentgen legacy lives. On Oct. 15, the John Widdicomb
Company of Grand Rapids, Mich., will introduce an adaptation of a
Roentgen table in its new V &AMP; A Museum Furniture Collection. The
original, which was donated to the Victoria and Albert Museum in
1882, has an oval parquetry top (a geometric pattern in marquetry)
with satinwood and mahogany veneers and square tapered legs.
Widdicomb says it will cost about $4,900, making it the only
affordable Roentgen on earth for most of us.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
