<HEADER>
A0942 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROTHKO-EXHIBIT-NYT &LR;      09-17 1485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROTHKO-EXHIBIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: GAINING PERSPECTIVE ON A GLOOMY ELEGANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the Mark Rothko retrospective now at the
Whitney, a question arises: what has changed about our perception
of him since the Guggenheim's big survey 20 years ago?
</P>
<P>
   Well, among other things, the messy legal battle over his
estate, which after several years was finally settled in favor of
his orphaned children over his dealer and trustees, is history. A
whole generation has grown up that either knows nothing about it or
doesn't care, as happens with all basically irrelevant affairs
eventually.
</P>
<P>
   We are also a generation removed from Rothko's original
hagiographers, writers steeped in the transcendental prose of the
1950s who dutifully followed his erratic lead. Volumes of citations
were culled from Jung, Nietzsche, Heidegger, Joyce, the cabala _
whatever could be used to prop up Rothko's messianic desire that
his colored rectangles be regarded as sublime mythic expressions of
a spiritual dimension.
</P>
<P>
   By the early '60s, the rhetoric began to cause even some of his
admirers to squirm. As Robert Hughes once put it, Rothko's life was
a ``long, troubled preparation for a failure that eluded him'':
increasingly rich and successful but always unstable and paranoid,
Rothko insisted on seeing himself as a victim. If anything, he was
a victim of the impossible pronouncements made on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   About his late paintings, for example, in which his palette,
like his spirits, darkened increasingly to gray and black, it
became a given among Rothko's biographers that these pictures were
ineffable tragedies on the order of Aeschylus, a view grimly
supported when he killed himself in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   The curator of the Guggenheim show wrote that Rothko ``had
attained a harmony, an equilibrium, a wholeness in the Jungian
sense that enabled him to express universal truths in his
breakthrough works, fusing the conscious with the unconscious, the
finite and the infinite, the equivocal and the unequivocal, the
sensuous and the spiritual.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't think so. People still sometimes write these sorts of
things about his art, but at least conditions have changed enough
that it is now conceivable to see his pictures in comparative
silence.
</P>
<P>
   Today, his last paintings above all seem gloomily elegant, an
expression of creative exhaustion: Rothko apparently had taken his
art as far as he could. He had spent more than two decades, since
hitting upon his signature mode in the late '40s, doing variations
on pretty much the same thing, and finally he ran aground, not
because there were no more color combinations to be tried or
arrangements of fuzzy rectangles to be fiddled with but because he
refused to concede that his art might be, in the end, about colors
and forms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only that subject matter is valid which is tragic and
timeless,'' was his famous remark, which left him with the problem
that abstract art of the kind he produced could not, despite the
incantations of his worshipers, sustain all he had hoped for.
</P>
<P>
   It was resonant but obstinately vague. It could be awesomely
beautiful (Rothko's best paintings are some of the most beautiful
paintings by an American artist). but beauty can attach itself to
the sublime (Titian, Rembrandt) or to the merely decorative, and
Rothko's pictures have always looked alarmingly good hanging over
sofas in Upper East Side apartments.
</P>
<P>
   We forget how many New York School painters ended up facing this
problem. Motherwell, Still, Newman, Gottlieb: they all invented
trademark styles, apocalyptically symbolic but formulaically
repeated, which became the stuff of corporate lobbies. A painter
like Guston seems all the more remarkable in the context of this
generation for having abandoned, against everyone's advice, what
had made him identifiable. I suspect he was just trying to keep
himself alive as an artist.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest change in Rothko's later years was to embark upon
murals. This must have seemed like a natural step. He'd made
increasingly big paintings, partly because he wanted his works to
envelop the people looking at them. But even the biggest pictures
were never quite wide enough to span a viewer's visual field.
Murals commanded a whole environment. In his mind the idea recalled
Pompeii and the Renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the projects never quite panned out as he
envisioned them. He withdrew from the commission to decorate the
Four Seasons restaurant, giving some of the works to a museum
instead; his murals in a Harvard dining hall ended up ruined. A
restaurant and a college dining hall aren't exactly dream sites for
a painter of his spiritual aspirations. Then there is the Rothko
Chapel in Houston, which many people admire. It seems theatrical
and strained to me, a vacant space.
</P>
<P>
   Do I sound down on Rothko? I am not, but his case, more than
most, begs for careful modulation. If he had died in 1948, when he
was already 45, he would be virtually unknown today. He began in
the 1930s as a fairly inept painter of unremarkable landscapes and
moody sub-Ashcan urban scenes that in retrospect obviously
contained elements of his mature pictures in embryo: architectural
spaces flattened into discrete rectangular forms or planes, the
forms stacked, with figures standing in front of them or apart.
It's a little as if these figures became the viewers that Rothko
later imagined looking at his abstractions.
</P>
<P>
   A Surrealist phase in the 1940s produced swimmy watercolors of
vague twittering shapes barely distinguishable from what artists
like Gorky, John Graham and Andre Masson were doing, except that
Rothko made something different of his thin washes and scraped
surfaces when, in 1947, he suddenly began to paint colored pictures
of diluted, randomly disposed blurs.
</P>
<P>
   He'd been looking at Matisse, and Milton Avery was always a
major influence. Who knows whether, to a lesser degree, someone
like Bonnard affected him, too, although Bonnard was regarded as a
decorative lightweight then, and Rothko, in the way that people
tend to reject whatever they are naturally inclined to, hated his
own work to be thought of as decorative.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, it took a couple of years before he stripped
away the squiggles and handwriting marks that were holdovers from
Surrealism and simplified his compositions to arrive at what we now
know as a Rothko.
</P>
<P>
   At the Whitney, the rooms of pictures from the next several
years of his career are astonishingly, breathtakingly moving. The
colors all seem to be ecstatic and springlike: chartreuse, pink,
peach, orange, saffron, lavender and white, layered in veils with
the quality of breath on a pane of glass.
</P>
<P>
   They radiate light. The images seem to project off the walls.
You stand in front of them as if before the sun, basking. There's a
sense of surrender by Rothko to some exquisite and mysterious new
discovery _ a feeling akin to new love. And it's shocking to see
after the rooms of his dour and unoriginal early work. Rothko's
progress had been incremental, building on itself, until he
underwent this change between the mid-'40s and the early '50s that
was his leap into history.
</P>
<P>
   Then what? Jeffrey Weiss, who organized this exhibition for the
National Gallery of Art in Washington, has tried to diminish any
sense that Rothko just kept doing the same thing over and over.
Quite intelligently, he stresses discrete groupings of works and
motifs. As the show was installed in basement rooms in Washington a
few months ago, it still seemed repetitive. At the Whitney, on two
upper floors in spaces of varied sizes, the same pictures somehow
look much better.
</P>
<P>
   Someday it would be good to see a Rothko exhibition in natural
light. It's not that he always painted in it _ sometimes he did,
sometimes he didn't _ but I suspect that changing as it does,
natural light would reveal how the pictures can seem to be organic,
shifting in appearance, chameleonlike. Part of their strange magic
is a palpitating luminosity whose particular meaning floats freely.
</P>
<P>
   About the Guggenheim show 20 years ago, Hilton Kramer said that
if, ultimately, there is a religious dimension to Rothko's art, it
is its estheticism. I agree. In Rothko's own depressive terms, this
may have constituted a failure, but it is a condition of his
abstraction.
</P>
<P>
   Important artists often don't achieve the goals they set for
themselves, but they achieve something else, which they may not
appreciate. Rothko was one of those artists.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark Rothko'' remains on view at the Whitney Museum of
American Art, 945 Madison Ave., at 75th Street, through Nov. 29. It
has been installed by Adam Weinberg of the Whitney in collaboration
with Jeffrey Weiss of the National Gallery of Art. The show travels
this winter to the Musee d'Art Moderne de la Ville de Paris.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
