<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following travel features and columns moved during the last week.
</P>
<P>
   For retransmissions of these stories, please call 888-346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PLACES AND DESTINATIONS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-RESERVATION-TOURISM-NYT (Umatilla Reservation, Ore.) _
American Indian reservations, long considered economic deserts
amidst a landscape of general prosperity, are finding that they
have a lot more to offer the world than casinos and art galleries _
they have their homes, their backyards, their stories. Visitors,
especially a growing number of Europeans, are traveling to some of
the country's most remote places, like this Indian reservation in
central Oregon, in search of life many Americans overlook on their
vacations. By Timothy Egan. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLLINS-BOS (Antwerp, Belgium) _ St. Peter has confided
to a Belgian pal of mine that the commandment Moses overlooked _
the Eleventh _ is to be found right here. By Bud Collins.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COSTARICA-COX (Alajuela, Costa Rica) _ How did I get
myself into this? Here I am, pedaling a 21-speed ``hybrid'' bike up
and down the mountains of Costa Rica. I'm bouncing along jagged
roads and squeezing the hand brakes at every downhill turn. It
sounded like a good idea at the time By Dale Fuchs.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-TOLUCA-COX (Toloca, Mexico) _ Toluca, Mexico, 40 miles
southwest of Mexico City, weaves an authentic spell. By Kristin
Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   LIMERICK-COX (Limerick, Ireland) _ even though Limerick ``and
the surrounds'' offer a treasure of Irish history, music, museums,
castles, gorgeous green hillsides _ and, a little farther out,
stunning ocean vistas _ the city's image has been that of a gritty,
blue-collar city.
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH-COLUMBIA-COX (Vancouver) _ During late July and early
August, Sally and I spent three nights in Vancouver, and two nights
in Victoria, on Vancouver Island, which is an hour-and-a-half ferry
ride from Vancouver. The only unkind words we heard during our
whole trip were from an old lady who was ragging on her husband on
the ferry from Seattle to Victoria, aboard the Princess Marguerite
III.
</P>
<P>
   SCANDINAVIA-COX _ (Oslo) _ On balance, we visit Scandinavia for
the pretty scenery and the pretty people. Yet Scandinavia deserves
an extended stay. Because these countries were spared the full
brunt of modern wars, their physical pasts remain remarkably
intact. Thus, the culturally curious visitor should make special
efforts to visit some small historical or art museums in the cities
of Oslo, Bergen, Stockholm and Copenhagen. By Michael Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA-COX (San Francisco) _ The descriptive term
``breathtaking'' is overused. Admit it, we all hate it. The canopy
of trees was breathtaking. Her beauty was breathtaking. The new
Mazda is breathtaking. Nonetheless, I'm traveling north on the
Pacific Coast Highway through Big Sur and I can't think of any
other word to describe the cragged cliffs, the crushing sea as it
meets the rocks. By Greg Kallenberg.
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL-COX (Montreal) _ Montreal offers a pleasant mix of
European and American sensibilities and features. With its museums,
first-class shops and ethnic neighborhoods, it does resemble a
cleaner, smaller New York. And because of its French heritage and
largely French-speaking population, Montreal does have a European
flair. By R. Michelle Breyer and Jody Seaborn.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-YOGA-COX (Nassau, the Bahamas) _ The boom of a gong
pierced the silence of the night promptly at 5:30 a.m., which is
mighty early on Paradise Island. This is the time to go to bed
after a night at the casinos and bars, not to get up to meditate
and to do yoga positions that turn your body into a pretzel. Do
people really want to do this on vacation? By Cheryl Blackerby.
</P>
<P>
   TRAILSEND-COX (Trails End, Minn.) _ It's clear paddling into the
Boundary Waters Canoe Area Wilderness that the name refers to more
than just the border between the United States and Canada. This is
the boundary line past which superfluous things like money and cars
and TV Guide don't matter _ or even are usable. Of course, a light
canoe helps in that quest, as we found out the hard way. By Chris
Riemenschneider.
</P>
<P>
   KINGSVILLE-TX-COX _ The getaway just keeps getting better, as
the Youngs take B-Bar-B in Kingsville, Texas, from its beginnings
as a hunting lodge into a year-round resort stop for hunters,
birders, tourists and adults just wanting to hide out in comfort
for a few days. By Mike Leggett.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-ALCOTT-BOS (Concord, Mass.) _ _ Fans of Louisa May Alcott
have an image of the March family home she evokes in ``Little
Women.'' It comes as a shock to many to see the Victorian reality
of Orchard House, where part of the novel was written in 1868. By
Margo Miller.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-SAFRICA-NYT (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ South Africa
learns that tourism is fragile. By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS-REGULAR FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS (Undated) _ I was visiting some time ago with
a fellow travel journalist whose main expertise is the Caribbean.
Her favorite island is Jamaica. ``Don't you find some people there
a tad aggressive toward tourists?'' I asked. ``Oh, they don't
bother me ... I only go to the all-inclusive resorts and never
leave until it's time to fly home.'' How sad. By Harry Shattuck.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ Everyone's favorite question at
this time of year: ``Where's the best foliage?'' By Jerry Morris.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-NOTES-BOS (Undated) _ ``The Massachusetts Legacy: 150
Landmark Events That Shaped Our Nation'' explores many events with
Massachusetts connections. By Richard Carpenter.
</P>
<P>
   CYBER-TRAVEL-NYT (Undated) _ Surfing the net. By L.R. Shannon.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-NYT (Undated) _ Converting UPS planes:
packages to package deals. By Betsy Wade.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS-NYT (Undated) _ Through customs in 15 to 20
seconds; Minneapolis celebrates enlarged art museum; A coming-out
party for Grand Central.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-NYT (Undated) _ Questions and answers on travel. This
week: New Year's in Paris; Hudson Valley in the fall; Newsletter
for diabetics. By Suzanne MacNeille.
</P>
