<HEADER>
A0954 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     09-17 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J., Md.)   (af)  
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Shortly after he finished the film ``Happiness'' Todd
Solondz, its writer-director, changed the telephone listing in his
New York apartment and got an unlisted number.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am nervous,'' the 38-year-old filmmaker said quietly. ``The
film is unsettling. It's disturbing. There are crazy people out
there. There are people who may have a strong reaction to it.''
</P>
<P>
   No one would disagree with him.
</P>
<P>
   The two-hour and 15-minute film, which opens next month, has
been the talk of the Toronto Film Festival. A startling and
depressing vision of the middle class, the film largely focuses on
the lives of three sisters in New Jersey (as well as their unhappy
parents in Florida) and the secrets that shape them.
</P>
<P>
   One of the sisters, the most chirpy and self-satisfied, is a
married homemaker whose husband, a psychiatrist, molests little
boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not interested in pedophilia, per se, I don't know
anything about it,'' Solondz said. ``It was a way of me exploring
themes of greater interest to me, themes of alienation, desire,
connection, disconnection.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``As far as that subject goes, there's nothing taboo
in this movie that you can't see addressed or discussed in any
tabloid or talk show any day of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   Solondz made another bleak but far less controversial 1995 film,
``Welcome to the Dollhouse,'' about an 11-year-old girl with
unloving parents and no friends. The relative success of that film
_ it cost less than $1 million and grossed $5 million _ opened the
way for October Films to spend $2.5 million on ``Happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   But October Films was forced by its parent, Universal Pictures,
to drop the movie because of its content. It will be released by
Good Machine, a production company, with no rating.
</P>
<P>
   The film has several overlapping stories about relationships,
all of them, more or less, hopeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially the film is a series of love stories on the
simplest level,'' Solondz said. ``I never wanted to shock _ that
doesn't interest me.''
</P>
<P>
   The film has no nudity, but it has several powerful scenes, none
more shocking than a dialogue near the finale between the
pedophile, who has been unmasked, and his young son who questions
him as brutally as the father answers the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Solondz said the idea of writing about a pedophile came several
years ago when he read a newspaper article about a fact-based HBO
drama, ``Citizen X,'' which dealt with a Russian investigation of a
serial killer of children. ``What struck me was that the article
said that he had a wife and two children _ and I had to know, what
is that really about, what does that mean, how does that exist?''
</P>
<P>
   Solondz said he was aware that many viewers will be repelled.
``What excites me, what gets me moving, is trying to look at
characters who in any other movie would be the villain or a
demon,'' he said. ``There's nothing more bracing than in fact
trying to dig underneath that veneer and discovering what makes
them tick.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that before making the movie, he assessed classics like
Fritz Lang's harrowing ``M,'' in which Peter Lorre played a child
murderer, as well as Alfred Hitchcock's ``Strangers on a Train,''
and the Valadmir Nabokov novel ``Lolita.'' He said: ``It's not
about sympathy. Forgiveness is not an issue here. But to understand
and recognize that there is a human here with a tragic condition,
to recognize that makes us more human for that ackowledgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Solondz, who grew up in Livingston, N.J., made it plain that he
has a warm spot for the state, where he made the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like that New York snobbery, cheap shots at New
Jersey, which are tiresome and never funny,'' Solondz said. He
acknowledged, though, that as a young adult he disparaged the
split-level ranch home community in which he was reared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then about 10 years ago, some Russian relatives who had
emigrated came to visit us in the suburbs and we took a walk and
they looked around at the vista and said, `This is my dream, one
day I'll live here.' And I realized, I couldn't argue. It wasn't so
bad, after all.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Waters is offended. When a reporter asked if he was raised
in the kind of blue-collar Baltimore neighborhood that he depicts
in his films, the 52-year-old creator of such trashy and
hilariously offensive movies as ``Pink Flamingos'' and ``Female
Trouble'' (starring the female impersonator Divine), and the more
recent ``Hairspray'' and ``Serial Mom,'' seemed quite taken aback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't grow up in blue-collar Baltimore but in middle-class
Baltimore,'' Waters said. ``I was raised to praise and almost
worship good taste. And that's why I made a career out of
glorifying bad taste.''
</P>
<P>
   He exclaimed: ``My parents voted for _ and look like _ George
and Barbara Bush. And they don't get mad when I say so.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Waters' newest movie, ``Pecker,'' was shown at the Toronto Film
Festival and is set to open next week. It is a surprisingly gentle
(for Waters) film without the grossouts of, say, ``Pink
Flamingos.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie deals with a slightly goofy sandwich shop employee
named Pecker (so-named because of his childhood habit of pecking at
his food), who takes photographs of his family and friends, and
stumbles onto fame when a fancy New York art dealer discovers him.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, some of the subjects of his pictures rebel at their
unwanted attention _ something that happened in real life to Waters
after he used some quirky Baltimore residents in his films.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some loved the attention, others didn't, they felt used by
it,'' Waters, 52, said. ``Everyone says this is autobiographical,
but it's not, it's really not.''
</P>
<P>
   The film's cast includes Edward Furlong as Pecker and some
Waters regulars like Patricia Hearst and Mink Stole. There are
familiar Waters touches: an older sister works in a gay bar; a kid
sister is addicted to sugar; his grandmother engages in prayer
sessions with a a talking statue.
</P>
<P>
   Waters, who seems as shrewd as he is charming, said he remained
close to his Republican parents, who gave him thousands of dollars
in the early 1970s to complete the notorious ``Pink Flamingos,''
which turned Waters into a cult celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've never seen the movie _ it would be parent abuse for
them to watch it,'' said Waters, whose first film was an 8-mm short
in high school called ``Hag in a Black Leather Jacket,'' that he
made while in high school. ``It's taken my parents really 30 years
to begin to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Waters said he attended New York University in 1966 for one
month. ``I was thrown out in a pot bust.'' He returned to
Baltimore, and never left. His films, which often eke out a small
profit, are especially popular ``around places with water,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do fine in New York and L.A., they do fine in Chicago
where there's a lake, where there's water, it works.'' He laughed.
``I mean, if there's a stream, I do well. Don't ask me why. It has
to be a puddle. It can be a leak. That's all I ask for. Please, let
it rain the day I open. Just give me some water.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Janet Leigh saw Orson Welles only once after they made ``Touch
of Evil,'' but she's still disturbed, even angry, at the way
Hollywood treated him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Touch of Evil,'' the masterful 1958 film about a murder
investigation in a sleazy Mexican border town, was re-edited by
studio executives before its release, causing a furious Welles to
flee Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   The movie has now been restored to be closer to its original
form, based on a 58-page memorandum written by Welles describing
his suggested changes to the studio cut.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Leigh, in Toronto to promote the re-release of the restored
film, which also starred Charlton Heston, Marlene Dietrich,
Mercedes McCambridge and Akim Tamiroff, said working on the movie
was one of the more pleasurable experiences of her career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started with rehearsals; we rehearsed two weeks prior to
shooting, which was unusual; we rewrote most of the dialogue, all
of us, which was also unusual, and Welles always wanted our
input,'' she said. ``It was a collective effort, and there was such
a surge of participation, of creativity, of energy. You could feel
the pulse growing as we rehearsed.''
</P>
<P>
   She continued: ``You felt you were inventing something as you
went along,'' she said. `` Welles wanted to seize every moment, he
didn't want one bland moment. He made you feel you were involved in
a wonderful event that was happening before your eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Leigh said Hollywood's treatment of the director of the
classics ``Citizen Kane'' and ``The Magnificent Ambersons'' was
appalling. Welles never directed another film in Hollywood after
``Touch of Evil.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After his version of the film was taken away, he went to
Mexico and Europe,'' she said. ``I was so saddened. I was angry.
When I saw this version, and saw the reaction by critics and
moviegoers, it made me angry when I thought that if this had been
released in his form, and had been accepted, he would have gone on
and made the five-picture deal they had offered him. Even now I
think: What have we been robbed of? What have we been cheated of?
We might have had five more masterpieces. We'll never know. It's a
shame.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
