   CONNECTICUT -- TAX. Despite the threat of a presidential veto,
Rep. Barbara B. Kennelly joined most of her Democratic colleagues
on the House Ways and Means Committee in voting for a GOP tax cut
plan. Maggi
</P>
<P>
   IDAHO -- KEMPTHORNE. Sen. Dirk Kempthorne is expected to attach
his Endangered Species Act as an amendment to the Interior
Appropriations bill. Critics say this is a sneaky, last-minute ploy
to get the bill passed without having to fix some serious
environmental concerns. (Working.) Brown
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA -- TOX. Almost half a billion tons of toxic chemicals
are being dumped into the Mississippi River by just three Louisiana
petrochemical companies, according to a just-released study. But
Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-Chackbay, said through a spokesman that most
of the alleged danger of such dumping is unclear. Stricherz
</P>
<P>
   MAINE -- ABORT. On the eve of another controversial vote on
late-term abortions, a group of moderate Senate Republicans and
Democrats try to forge a middle-ground approach that would outlaw
many abortions after the fetus has reached the point of viability.
But Sens. Olympia Snowe and Susan Collins admit that their plan
won't become law any time soon. Kane
</P>
<P>
   MASSACHUSETTS -- COURT. The U.S. District Court in Springfield
is not safe for judges or jurors, and a new courthouse needs to be
built, a federal judge from Massachusetts told a Senate committee
Thursday. Preston
</P>
<P>
   MULTICHANNEL -- SMUT. A bill aimed at protecting children from
online smut passed a House subcommittee Thursday, despite some
lawmakers' claims that the measure would expand the Federal
Communication Commission's jurisdiction over the Internet. Maggi
</P>
<P>
   OHIO -- APPALACHIA. Rev. Jesse Jackson joined labor officials
Thursday to kick off a bus tour of the Appalachia region, including
stops in Ohio, and a march in Athens County. Gorman
</P>
<P>
   -- FARMERS. With dueling philosophies, Ohio farm group
representatives descended on Capital Hill this week to lobby for
solutions to the farm crises facing rural America. While the
National Farmers Union pushed for removing loan caps and
re-evaluating the 1996 Farm Bill, the Pork Producers Council and
Farm Bureau concentrated on increasing trade opportunities by
getting funding for the International Monetary Fund and passing
fast-track legislation. Will include quotes from Reps. Oxley, Ney
and Boehner. Hurt
</P>
<P>
   -- TRAFICANT. Calls have been flooding congressional offices
since the Starr Report became public last Friday. A look at calls
to Rep. Jim Traficant's office. (Possible.) Gorman
</P>
<P>
   -- EPA-LIVESTOCK. (Re-sent.) The EPA and USDA Wednesday released
their long-awaited national strategy proposal for dealing with
water pollution associated with waste from livestock farms
Wednesday. The draft strategy proposes all livestock and poultry
operations develop and implement comprehensive nutrient management
plans in the next 10 years that will reduce water quality and
public health impacts. Hurt
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA -- CALLS. Call it an information overload. Like the
Schuylkill Expressway at rush hour, the Capitol Hill e-mail system
has been backed up for hours on end since the Starr report was
unveiled a week ago. At the same time, congressional staffers
haven't had a moment's rest as their phones have been ringing off
the hook. Unlike any issue since maybe the Persian Gulf War, the
public has just seen and heard too much about the escalating intern
scandal and have been calling, e-mailing and writing their
lawmakers to express their outrage. Kane
</P>
<P>
   -- CALL. Calls have been coming in at a heavy load to Rep. John
Murtha's office ever since the Starr report was released a week
ago. With about a 50-50 split, Murtha's constituents appear divided
over whether President Clinton should finish out his term. But
those calls are nothing compared to what some Republicans are
hearing. While Murtha's office has fielded about 250 calls all
week, Rep. Bud Shuster, R-Everett, received almost that many in one
day -- and there was an overwhelming tilt against the president.
</P>
<P>
   -- HILL. Just a few hours after the latest congressional
peccadillo was unveiled on the Internet -- Rep. Henry Hyde's
long-since-passed affair in the 1960s -- an aide to a Senate
Democrat put down his beer Tuesday night and reflected: ``Who's
Next?'' Kane
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS -- AID. House Republicans announced a $3.9 billion aid
package for farmers and ranchers hit by drastically low commodity
prices and severe drought conditions. Brown
</P>
<P>
   VIRGIN ISLANDS -- GRANT. The Virgin Islands Housing Authority
will use most of a $6.7 million federal grant to repair property
damage caused by hurricanes Marilyn and Bertha. Williams
</P>
<P>
   -- FORUM. V.I. Delegate to Congress Donna Christian-Green is
taking part this afternoon in a Congressional Black Caucus forum on
U.S.-Caribbean policy. (Working.) Williams
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN -- SENSENBRENNER. Democratic members of the Judiciary
Committee say that Rep. Jim Sensenbrenner, R-Wis., is unfit to be
head of the panel he most wants to lead. Is that partisan animosity
or the blatant truth? (Working.) Marlin
</P>
