<SLUG> BC-LATE-ABORTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EFFORT TO SAVE ANTI-ABORTION BILL EXPECTED TO FAIL IN SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Anti-abortion forces in the Senate conceded
Thursday they do not have the support to overturn President
Clinton's veto of a bill that would outlaw a controversial
late-term abortion procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert C. Smith, a key supporter of the bill to ban what
opponents call ``partial-birth abortion,'' said he did not have the
67 votes needed to override the veto.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are three votes shy and there are a dozen senators that are
looking inward,'' Smith, R-N.H., told a news conference. The vote
is expected Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Several Democrats identified as possible swing votes _ including
Joseph Lieberman and Christopher Dodd of Connecticut, Dale Bumpers
of Arkansas and Tom Harkin of Iowa _ said they intended to vote to
sustain the veto.
</P>
<P>
   The House has twice overridden the president's veto, but the
Senate could not muster the two-thirds majority needed for an
override when it last voted on the issue in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The late-term abortion procedure involves a physician pulling
the fetus out of the birth canal feet-first, puncturing the back of
the head and removing the brain. That allows the skull to be
partially collapsed and removed from the birth canal.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa., a vocal opponent of the procedure,
described it as ``shocking,'' and ``barbaric'' and said it ``has no
place in civilized society.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bill Frist, R-Tenn., the only physician in the Senate, said
the procedure ``is inhuman and painful to the fetus'' and is not
taught at any medical school in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely unnecessary and ethically unacceptable,''
Frist said, adding that the procedure is dangerous to the mother
because it can cause hemorrhage and infection. ``It's too close to
infanticide to justify its continued use.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, Sen. Richard J. Durbin, D-Ill., introduced
legislation that would ban all post-viability abortions except when
both the attending physician and a second doctor certify that
continuing the pregnancy would threaten the mother's life or risk
``grievous physical injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Physicians consider a fetus viable at about 23 or 24 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation is unlikely to come up for a vote until a new
Congress convenes next year.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Olympia J. Snowe, R-Maine, a co-sponsor of the Durbin bill,
said the legislation was narrowly drawn to allow late-term
abortions in cases where the mother may suffer from cardiac
failure, hypertension, uterine rupture that may lead to
infertility, or may require chemotherapy for breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said the bill appropriately balances ``the moral
anxieties we feel about abortion with the law of the land.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1973 Roe vs. Wade Supreme Court decision legalized abortion
prior to fetal viability.
</P>
<P>
   ``The line to draw here is the stage of the pregnancy, not to
begin making judgment on a particular procedure,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
