<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1040 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-DONNA18-COX     09-17 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DONNA18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DONNA RICE HUGHES TALKS ABOUT OVERCOMING SCANDAL
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Before Monica, there was Donna.
</P>
<P>
   The explosive mixture of politics and sex and scandal and media
is a familiar story in the nation's capital, and not one that Donna
Rice Hughes is anxious to rehash.
</P>
<P>
   More than a decade has passed since the tabloids ran a picture
of her sitting on Gary Hart's lap on the yacht ``Monkey Business,''
and the ensuing uproar forced the married Democratic senator from
Colorado out of the 1988 presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Rice gained worldwide notoriety almost instantly.
Obscurity has been harder to achieve. After an unfortunate
experience modeling ``No Excuses'' jeans, the aspiring actress
altered the course of her life _ changing careers, turning down TV
talk shows and million-dollar book deals, and ``returning to faith
to seek God's guidance.''
</P>
<P>
   She married a man with a teenaged son, moved into a house in
suburban Virginia, and went to work for a non-profit
anti-pornography group called ``Enough Is Enough.'' A few years
ago, she ventured online and found a crusade _ protecting kids from
smut and sexual predators in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked when someone showed me what was on the
Internet,'' she recalled. ``Kids can get for free what their
parents would have to buy in a triple-X rated bookstore.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, as fate would have it, 40-year-old Donna Rice Hughes is
promoting her new book, ``Kids Online: Protecting Your Children in
Cyberspace,'' at the time the nation is riveted by a new sex
scandal. For cybersmart kids, the lurid details are just a click
away after Congress put the report by Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``That does a couple of things in respect to issues I'm dealing
with,'' she said in an interview Thursday. The release demonstrated
``the power of the Internet to disseminate vast amounts of
information quickly. And it also raised the visibility to parents
... that much of this information is perhaps inappropriate for
their children to see.''
</P>
<P>
   She is comfortable and knowledgeable talking about the dangers
of cyberspace and the need for parents to bridge the
``technogeneration gap'' to guide and protect their children on the
Internet. She said her book teaches even technophobic grown-ups how
to keep up with cybersavvy kids and how to use a ``digital
toolbox'' to regulate what they can see on their computer screens.
</P>
<P>
   She is less comfortable taking about the 1987 scandal that
prompted publishers to offer her ``a blank check'' to write a
tell-all account of her brief affair with Hart. She offers no
advice to Monica Lewinsky, whose agent is reportedly shopping
proposals for a book on her White House relationship with President
Clinton and the resulting scandal that continues to unfold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the decision early on to make all the pain and trauma
count for something,'' she said. ``I was not going to exploit the
notoriety.''
</P>
<P>
   An honors graduate and former cheerleader from the University of
South Carolina, then-Donna Rice was a commercial actress living in
Miami when she met Hart. Indeed, she recalled that when the scandal
broke, she was appearing as a young mom in a Sears commercial and a
wife in two Folger's coffee spots that were airing on TV. So, after
unintentionally and unexpectedly becoming a household name, she
accepted an offer to model No Excuses Jeans in an advertising
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agreed to do it as an actor. It was what I did for a living
at the time,'' she recalled. ``As it turns out, it was very much
exploited. I learned that I couldn't just be a no-name person in a
commercial again.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said turned down offers to appear in TV movies and
rejected a $1 million offer to do a question-and-answer session
with Playboy Magazine _ ``no posing'' required. She did a TV
interview with Barbara Walters, but decided to put it all behind
her, she would have to get out of the public eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was being painted as someone I wasn't,'' she said, so she
``went underground'' to regain a private life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was out of the public eye until I started working on these
high-tech issues,'' she said, explaining that her book was written
as a ``service'' rather than to make money. Published by Revell, it
costs $11.99. However, Hughes said most of the information can be
found for free at her Web site (http://www.protectkids.com).
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really a tool and a resource,'' she said. ``There's a
challenge because children are more computer-literate than their
parents. But if you don't understand the Internet, you don't know
the risks.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
