<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DIVERSITY PROGRAM FOCUSES ON CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing; moved 9/15)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How do you eliminate bias?
</P>
<P>
   ``You begin with the children,'' says workplace diversity expert
Julie Baskin Brooks of New York-based QED Consulting.
</P>
<P>
   A former director of diversity at Xerox Corp. in Stamford,
Conn., Brooks came to this realization two years ago after her
7-year-old son was attacked by three fifth-grade boys who held a
pocketknife to his neck and declared, ``You're no good because
you're burnt.''
</P>
<P>
   Kameron Brooks is African-American. The boys who accosted him
are white.
</P>
<P>
   For Kameron, the experience was devastating. He withdrew from
his family; he became sad and angry; and his school work suffered.
Even more troubling, recalls Brooks, was the boy's declaration that
he hated himself. ``I'm tired of being invisible,'' he told his
mother.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of a therapist, Brooks and her son got through a
difficult period, but the experience still troubled her.
</P>
<P>
   Convinced other parents and children could use help with racial
and diversity issues, Brooks approached Xerox about developing a
way to help change attitudes about race, gender, and other
differences.
</P>
<P>
   With a $68,000 contribution from Xerox, Brooks and Arlene
Tannenbaum of WFD Inc. of Brookline, a corporate work-life services
provider, created a diversity tool kit for children age 3 to 8 and
their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Called ``Who Am I? Who Are You? Raising Children In a Diverse
World,'' the kit includes an audio cassette tape of conversations
with parents, construction paper in shades similar to skin colors,
multicultural crayons that include white, brown, beige, burnt
sienna, and black, a list of books for children, and two workbooks
designed to help adults expand their children's horizons and their
own.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, thousands of Xerox employees and nonprofit
organizations have used the tool kit. In January, the diversity
tool kit will be made available to companies served by WFD, which
has clients nationwide. Brooks says she also has received inquiries
from schools, churches, the Girl Scouts, and other groups
interested in promoting diversity.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, the package seems little more than a game. Take
a closer look and certain activities do more than entertain. In a
section called Questions to Ask Yourself, the authors urge parents
to take a close look at themselves Among the questions:
</P>
<P>
   _What kind of role model am I for my children? How do I respond
to a racist or biased remark. What do I say when someone else makes
a thoughtless or demeaning remark about my own background?
</P>
<P>
   _Do I show a positive attitude toward people who are different
from me? Do I invite them home?
</P>
<P>
   _Have I made assumptions about an entire group of people based
on my experience with one person from that particular group?
</P>
<P>
   While racial and gender biases readily come to mind when
thinking about diversity in the workplace, Brooks wanted children
to understand that differences are more complex and include
education, style, language, the way you carry and express yourself,
your height, weight, beliefs, and values.
</P>
<P>
   With those differences in mind, the tool kit offers several
activities for engaging children. Among them: construction of a
family heritage album that encourages children to talk to various
family members about their lives and work experiences; creating a
costume box with props that permit children to be someone else; and
a recipe for ``people cookies'' _ homemade gingerbread cookies
fashioned with a dough that ``lets your children make cookies that
look more like real people.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like fun, but can a workbook, a cassette tape, and a few
games really make a difference?
</P>
<P>
   Tannenbaum believes they can. ``Some people may see this as a
tangential or back-door way of getting into the issue, but in order
to work with children you really have to examine yourself,'' she
says. ``Sometimes people are willing to take a harder look at
themselves because of their love for their children than they would
if the employer said, `You've got to do this.'''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Brooks: ``When I learned what had happened to my son, I was
appalled. And yet, I did not want him to see how upset I was. I
said to him, `We will figure out how to fix this.' I also told him
that I needed him to be very honest about his feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have very easily encouraged my son to be violent, but
I did not want to send that message. There was a lot of therapy and
the message to Kameron was that there are many, many different
people in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Will adults get the message?
</P>
<P>
   ``The adults who will get it are the ones who are sensitive and
want to send the right message to their children,'' concedes
Brooks. ``The others won't. But that's OK. Some people cannot be
saved. So, if the kit makes a difference to one child and one
adult, it will be worth it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
