<SLUG> BC-COALITION-INFLUENCE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP KICKS OFF EFFORD TO COUNTER CHRISTIAN COALITION'S INFLUENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As more than 3,000 Christian Coalition activists
descend on the capital Thursday to lobby Congress and prepare for
their national convention this weekend, another organization has
announced a national effort to counter the group's political
influence among churchgoers.
</P>
<P>
   Americans United for the Separation of Church and State, a
private nonprofit group, said it intends to warn congregations and
pastors throughout the country about alleged partisanship in the
coalition's upcoming election voter guides.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Lynn, the group's executive director, said it would use
activists, mailings and the Internet to get out its message.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition's guides that often are distributed just before
election day, he said, traditionally make ``Republicans appear
nearly saint-like and Democrats looking like they're the biggest
sinners in town.''
</P>
<P>
   Denying partisanship, coalition spokesman Arne Owens described
the guides as ``supplements'' to the candidate information found in
the news media and in campaign advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no endorsement, either implied or direct,'' he said.
``It's all in line with both the law and spirit of the law. These
efforts on the part of Americans United are really thinly veiled
efforts to paint our organization with negative messages so our
voice can be marginalized during the election season. We recognize
what up they're up to.''
</P>
<P>
   For November's election, the coalition expects to distribute 45
million voter guides.
</P>
<P>
   While not specifically addressing the issue, Christian Coalition
President Randy Tates told an audience at the National Press Club
on Wednesday, ``The Christian Coalition does not endorse
candidates. We support individual issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Coalition is expected to be the target of another
broadside Thursday when People for the American Way, a private
nonprofit civil rights organization, attacks the group for
allegedly ignoring or circumventing election laws.
</P>
<P>
   And the Federal Election Commission asked a federal judge this
week to rule that the coalition improperly aided Republican
candidates through its election guides and other activities during
the 1990, 1992, and 1994 elections. In the meantime, the Internal
Revenue Service continues to investigate whether the coalition
deserves tax-exempt status.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Coalition, which has asked the courts to dismiss
the FEC lawsuit, says its voter guides typically highlight issues
of concern to its members. The 1998 questionnaires sent to
candidates contained more than 100 questions on a variety of
subjects, including abortion, homosexual rights, pornography,
health care, taxes, foreign policy and government reform.
</P>
<P>
   Milton Cerny, a Washington tax attorney who handled tax-exempt
issues at the IRS for 28 years, said a church receiving an election
guide must ensure that the guide is nonpartisan.
</P>
<P>
   In a memo prepared for Americans United, he said, ``A voter
guide may implicitly favor a candidate even though it does not tell
people how to vote or evaluate candidates with a `plus' or `minus'
signs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 1750EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
