A1118 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEATHPENALTY-COSTS-KA     09-17 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATHPENALTY-COSTS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECISION TO APPROVE THE DEATH PENALTY FOR MORE CRIMES CAN BE
COSTLY, PANEL FINDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The decision of Congress to mete out the federal
death penalty to a wider range of criminals has meant a much higher
cost to taxpayers, according to a judicial panel.
</P>
<P>
   Defense of a death penalty case costs an average of $218,112,
compared to $55,772 if the death penalty is not sought.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecuting death cases cost even more, about $365,000 for each
defendant, according to the report released this week by a
subcomittee of the Judicial Conference of the United States. The
group was asked to recommend ways to save money on capital cases.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the 1994 crime bill, the number of cases where
the attorney general has approved seeking the death penalty has
grown from five in 1993 to 31 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Federal death penalty prosecutions are large-scale cases that
are costly to defend,'' the report said. ``They require more
lawyers, working more hours at a higher hourly rate than other
federal criminal matters.''
</P>
<P>
   The results of the study came as no surprise to those in favor
of the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knew that,'' said Allan Kagnoli, spokesman for Rep.
George Gekas, a Pennsylvania Republican and sponsor of the crime
bill. ``These are the ultimate cases and they bear the ultimate
costs.''
</P>
<P>
   The growth in death penalty cases stirred concern among some
judges and lawmakers, especially in the wake of the highly
expensive defense of Timothy McVeigh and Terry Nichols for the 1995
Oklahoma City bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The Judicial Conference appointed a subcommittee to look at the
costs and submit a report to Congress, which reinstated the federal
death penalty in 1988 and broadened it six years later in a
tough-on-crime movement.
</P>
<P>
   Cost can be a practical argument against the death penalty, said
David Bruck, a South Carolina criminal defense lawyer who advises
defense lawyers in capital cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The death penalty is one of those things people think of in
the abstract _ are you for or against it?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way you have to think about it is: Is it the best way to
use scarce law enforcement dollars?'' Bruck said. ``Then the issue
looks a little different. How many laid-off police officers is one
execution worth?''
</P>
<P>
   In passing the Federal Death Penalty Act of 1994, Congress added
about 50 types of murder and drug related crimes to what is subject
to the death penalty, including charges of conspiracy to commit
murder even if no murder occurred, Bruck said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, there were 153 federal defendants charged with
offenses punishable by death in 1997 compared to 28 in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more cases we have, the more it's going to cost,'' Bruck
said. ``There's no gimmick or cost-saving mechanisms that will
change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the death penalty said Congress responded to the
public's will in expanding death penalty offenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's akin to defense spending _ there are certain things the
government must do,'' said Charles Orndorff, administrative vice
chairman of the Conservative Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee of judges who wrote the Judicial Conference
report do not pass judgment on the death penalty nor do they allege
wasteful spending. In the report, the judges emphasize the need to
appoint competent lawyers who have experience in death penalty
cases, but those lawyers can be expensive and the cases can be
prolonged, the judges said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruck said death penalty cases take so much time and attention
that lawyers usually have to shut down the rest of their practice.
</P>
<P>
   Jury selection and the trial itself take longer in death penalty
cases, partly because there are two phases _ one to determine guilt
and then another to decide if the death penalty is warranted.
</P>
<P>
   There also tends to be much more research and analysis of the
defendant's personal and criminal background to argue for or
against death. Expert witnesses are more prevalent in such cases,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Among money-saving recommendations from the judges committee:
</P>
<P>
   --The Department of Justice should speed up review of cases
where the death penalty is requested but seems unlikely to be
approved. An early decision not to seek the death penalty would cut
defense costs.
</P>
<P>
   --Courts should not appoint more than two defense lawyers, but
should permit use of other lawyers on a limited basis when time and
expertise demands.
</P>
<P>
   --Courts should work closer with public defenders and community
defender organizations to identify attorneys that can be hired for
death penalty cases.
</P>
<P>
   --Federal defender organizations should consider creating
salaried positions for investigators in the penalty phase rather
than hiring experts an hourly rate.
</P>
<P>
   --Judges should keep closer track of costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
