<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKE CHARITY INSPIRING, NOT TIRING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every time I see a little yellow rubber duck, I think about
grocery shopping at 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there's a connection.
</P>
<P>
   The yellow ducks are a common fund-raising gimmick. Buy a duck.
Stick it in a pond or a creek along with swarms of others. If yours
bobs to the finish line or gets plucked out first, you win the
raffle prize.
</P>
<P>
   The more people buy ducks, the more money is raised for the
sponsoring charity. This is good. These raffles provide vital
support for philanthropies.
</P>
<P>
   But there comes a point in the lives of most working stiffs when
even someone who's congenitally unable to walk past a Salvation
Army kettle without dropping something in is maxed out. And
sometimes, despite good will, the answer isn't to give time instead
of money.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what I think when I'm dodging midnight stock
boys in the grocery store's aisles. That's when I know that my best
time-management tip _ sleep less _ is not going to help me be a
better philanthropist. In short, I have no more time to give.
</P>
<P>
   All this raced through my mind _ faster than those duckies swim
_ as I listened to Stacy Palmer, editor of ``The Chronicle of
Philanthropy,'' speak recently. Palmer talked about national trends
in personal giving, technology, corporate giving and volunteering.
</P>
<P>
   The trend that burrowed into my rubber-ducky synapse was ``the
elevated role of the corporate volunteer manager.'' In other words,
Palmer said staff members charged with being cheerleaders and
organizers of staff volunteer work were getting busier.
</P>
<P>
   This, too, is good. Getting more people off their couches and
into do-gooder activities is a wonderful thing _ for society and
for the individual. But the increased call for worker commitment is
exacting a price.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just that many lives are so full that midnight food
shopping becomes a necessity. It's that many workers would really,
truly like to volunteer but feel stretched as tight as a cheap
celery band as it is.
</P>
<P>
   Workers are getting tired of being asked by their employers (or
their designated volunteer managers) to commit more volunteer time.
They don't have enough time for self and family as it is.
</P>
<P>
   There's also growing resentment in a work force that's already
being asked to ``do more with less'' on the job. Some employees
admit (though not very loudly) that they're miffed at being prodded
to spend more of their precious commodity _ time _ to carry their
employer's corporate-giving flag.
</P>
<P>
   The wisest employers, Palmer said, are solving the time crunch
by giving workers paid time off for volunteer work. Sometimes it's
an hour or two a week. Sometimes it's just one day a year.
</P>
<P>
   Wise employers also are finding out what volunteer work their
employees already do and providing paid time or direct financial
support for those philanthropies. That often sits better than
calling on workers to support the corporation's charitable choices.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the commitment, well-managed volunteer efforts are a
way for everybody to win. The philanthropic organization gets good
help. The corporation gets good PR. And the volunteer feels good _
not strained and drained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 1752EDT &QL; 
