<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL A GEM, DESPITE ITS ROUGH EDGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOWARD HOMER, ALASKA _ During a brief visit to Alaska a dozen
years ago, the impression gotten from two days on the road was of
disheartening clutter.
</P>
<P>
   The carcasses of old buses, converted to lodgings and then
abandoned _ artifacts of broken hopes _ rusted among the trees just
off the highway.
</P>
<P>
   Plastic trash bags, split at the seams, spilled their contents
along the ditches. Derelict cabins rotted and leaned.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska was, and is, the nearest thing we have to an American
frontier, and frontiers seldom are tidy. The northern winter is
long and hard. Outside the major towns, services are few. Other
needs take precedence over neatness. The worn-out and the useless
get flung aside.
</P>
<P>
   That's how it seemed the last time. But the intervening years
have brought noticeable change.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's a result of oil prosperity. Or maybe it's just a sign
of the frontier's maturing. But the traveler today is met by a more
orderly look.
</P>
<P>
   Which isn't to say the amenities are just like home.
</P>
<P>
   There's a book, available in better book stores here, titled
/{Outhouses of Alaska./} It's a hard-bound volume, not a flimsy
pamphlet. And, after bear attacks and death by freezing, the
subject it memorializes is one of the more terrible features of
Alaskan life.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier today we stopped for a stretch and a bit of refreshment
at a clutch of buildings beside the road. The gas station had no
restroom. In fact, it turned out that the hamlet was without any
running water at all.
</P>
<P>
   The lady at the tiny store where we bought homemade cakes
pointed the way to her sanitary facility, outdoors and around to
the side. I regret to say I visited the place. ``Treat this toilet
as you would your own,'' said a hand-printed sign on the door.
Well, if it were mine I'd dynamite it.
</P>
<P>
   In their capacity to inspire horror, the outhouses here are in a
class with those just across the Bering Sea, in Siberia. Indeed,
they are a reminder of the historical connection.
</P>
<P>
   First came Vitus Bering and the other Russian explorers in the
mid-18th century, followed in 1784 by the merchant-explorer Grigori
Shelikhov, who founded the Russian settlement at Kodiak.
</P>
<P>
   On their heels came a stream of fellow Russians, determined to
make their fortunes in furs and spread outhouse architecture
throughout the Alaska colony, perhaps even as far south as
California.
</P>
<P>
   This afternoon, after turning southwest at Soldotna to parallel
the shore of Cook Inlet, we find ourselves at Ninilchik village,
one of the places where those early colonists planted their hopes.
</P>
<P>
   The day is drawing on, the sun lowering, but with only a bit
more than 40 miles farther on to Homer, our night's stopping place,
there is time to linger and explore.
</P>
<P>
   Ninilchik was settled in the early 1800s, where a small river of
the same name runs down to the coast. More than 200 people once
called the place their home. They were fishers and hunters, and one
easily can imagine the hardness of their existence.
</P>
<P>
   Time has savaged most of the early log buildings, though some
look to be in various stages of restoration. From somewhere nearby
can be heard the rapping of a hammer, the whine of a saw, as one of
the weathered structures gets the promise of a new life.
</P>
<P>
   The original Russian Orthodox church burned, but was rebuilt
about 1900 on a promontory overlooking the village, and still is in
use. Until 1912, when Ninilchik got a territorial school, children
here got instruction only in Russian at the church school, taught
by the priest.
</P>
<P>
   We climbed the steep footpath to the handsome and well-kept
little structure. In the cemetery alongside, many of the names
echoed the place's history.
</P>
<P>
   There lay the Reverend Father Michael Garassim Oskolkoff, and
his wife, Matushka Zoya Oskolkoff. And others of that family:
Matrona and Simeon Oskolkoff, the latter having served 30 years as
church (ital)starosta,(end ital) or lay leader.
</P>
<P>
   Also Kvasnikoffs and Demidoffs. And, among all those, one Wayne
John Woodhead, whose headstone announced simply: ``Gone Fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Ninilchik has moved to higher ground, across the
highway, and has a prosperous look. But it's what remains of the
original village, nestled in its inlet, that stirs the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Late light sparkles on the water under a sky of deepening gold
and racing cloud. Blue with haze on the far side of Cook Inlet rise
the peaks of the Aleutian range.
</P>
<P>
   The distance from where we stand at this moment to the Siberian
mainland is 700 miles _ less than the distance to the nearest of
the other 48 U.S. states.
</P>
<P>
   Outhouses and all, it's one of the world's wonders, Alaska, a
jewel beyond price.
</P>
<P>
   One can easily understand why the untranationalist Russian
screwball, Vladimir Zhirinovsky, would burn so to claim it back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
