<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIO-FLOPHOUSE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 NPR FLOPHOUSE DOCUMENTARY: AGGRAVATION, BUT NO TOWELS OR SOAP 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember ``Grand Hotel''? Lewis Stone would sit in the plush
lobby, saying: ``Always the same. People come, people go. Nothing
ever happens.'' Well, the Sunshine Hotel is just like that, except
that its guests are life's losers, its beds rent for as little as
$4.50 a night, and the 4-by-6-foot rooms have chicken-wire
ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   But the real-life Sunshine, one of the last of the Bowery
flophouses, does have its own world-weary witness in the lobby.
He's Nathan Smith, the manager for the last 12 years. ``On the one
hand, it's probably as close as you can get to living in hell: 125
dysfunctional guys crammed together in a crummy old hotel,'' he
says. ``On the other hand, it's pretty interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith is the narrator of a radio documentary on the Sunshine to
be heard Friday on the National Public Radio program ``All Things
Considered.'' To assemble this sound portrait of a place you might
not want to look at, David Isay and Stacy Abramson, producer and
associate producer respectively, spent months with the lost souls
who inhabit the Sunshine's shadows.
</P>
<P>
   As they describe their shabby lives and quarters, these men
(women do not live at the hotel) speak sadly, but easily and
good-naturedly, about their fate. None is more eloquent than Smith,
who makes a remarkable tour guide.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you like aggravation, come to the Sunshine,'' he says, in a
voice that comes from the gut. ``But don't ask me for towels and
soap. We don't have those luxuries.''
</P>
<P>
   The place looks much like it did in the 1920s, when the Bowery
was full of such cheap refuges. Now the Sunshine, like its
denizens, is among the grizzled survivors.
</P>
<P>
   One resident, Arthur Morrison, says he came to the neighborhood
in 1960. ``Most of the people I knew on the Bowery are dead now,''
he says. ``I'm lucky to be alive.''
</P>
<P>
   His neighbors are not all so optimistic. ``I can't go no lower
than this,'' one says.
</P>
<P>
   The microphone picks up the sounds of the Sunshine: the ringing
of the single telephone inside Smith's cage of an office, the
belches of one man, the buzzing mechanical voice box of another and
some spontaneous doo-wop harmony down the hall. But mostly it hears
the words of the lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very popular with people being dumped,'' Smith says. The
residents tend to be guys just out of jails, psychiatric wards or
other places where they have just worn out their welcomes. ``And
then there are those of us who end up here because we are
dreamers.''
</P>
<P>
   Some men stay at the hotel for 30 years or more, others pass
through quickly, leaving abruptly, in a police car or ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   ``One tenant leaves, another checks in,'' Smith says, ``but the
hotel never changes.''
</P>
<P>
   He must have seen that movie, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
