<SLUG> BC-JOB-HUNT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS TO KEEP IN MIND WHEN LOOKING FOR A JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Whether you're looking for your first ``real''
job or are trying to recover from the jolt of being laid off, the
job market can be a puzzling and sometimes cruel place. Maybe the
market is the best it has been in years, but nobody could prove it
by you.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't done any serious job hunting in the last 10 or 20
years, consider yourself like someone straight out of high school
or college. The market has changed a lot, and many of the old rules
no longer apply.
</P>
<P>
   As you're doing your job hunting, make sure you know the answers
to these 10 questions:
</P>
<P>
   _ WHAT DO YOU WANT TO DO?
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest pitfalls for job hunters is being unfocused,
says Karen Culver, a career development counselor with Golden Gate
University in San Francisco. If your resume says you simply want
``challenging work,'' your biggest challenge is liable to be
finding work.
</P>
<P>
   Culver says that if you have a specific objective, list it on
your resume, particularly if you're applying to a medium-sized
company. That's not as crucial in small companies because
departments usually aren't as clearly defined, or at large
companies, where resumes are usually scanned in and then searched
by keywords rather than just the objective.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't know what you want to do, experts suggest making a
list of the skills you have and the types of tasks you enjoy, then
considering which jobs would involve those tasks. To open your eyes
to possibilities, check want ads in newspapers and on Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Color is Your Parachute?'' the classic job hunting book
by Alamo resident Richard Nelson Bolles, has extensive advice on
choosing careers. JIST Works Inc. (www.jist.com) has all sorts of
books on jobs and job hunting.
</P>
<P>
   _ HAVE YOU SENT OUT AT LEAST 100 RESUMES?
</P>
<P>
   It's a trick question. The correct answer is usually no. You're
better off targeting your resume to specific people at specific
companies, then following up to try to land an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sending out thousands of resumes that are not targeted is a
dead end,'' Culver says.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all is networking, talking with people you already know
and using contacts to line up interviews. They often will hear
about job openings before they are advertised.
</P>
<P>
   _ DO YOU KNOW THE COMPANY?
</P>
<P>
   Your research should tell you not only the basics about what the
company does and what kinds of jobs it has available, but what the
corporate culture is, says Ron Visconti, executive director of the
Career Education Center in San Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   _ ARE YOU OPEN-MINDED?
</P>
<P>
   Visconti calls it ``big-name syndrome'': Job hunters often limit
themselves to large, famous companies rather than thinking about
the range of experience they could get at smaller businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The fastest-growing part of the job market is the service
industry, which often has companies that are not widely known, says
Cindy O'Peka, regional human resources manager for American
Protective Services.
</P>
<P>
   _ DO YOU MAKE A GOOD FIRST IMPRESSION?
</P>
<P>
   That first impression usually comes through a cover letter, a
resume and a job application, three ways you can get tossed out of
the applicant pool in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an 8-second scan, can I see who you are, what you want and
why you should have it?'' asks Susan Ireland, who runs Susan
Ireland's Resume Service in San Francisco and Oakland and is the
author of ``The Complete Idiot's Guide to the Perfect Resume.''
</P>
<P>
   People aren't thinking enough about the position they're
applying for when they prepare a resume, she explains. ``They see
it as a historical document, which is a mistake. It should be about
your future, not your past.''
</P>
<P>
   Applicants often include too much rather than having bullet
points that are easy to read, Ireland adds.
</P>
<P>
   _ DO YOU REALLY WANT THE JOB?
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people fall into the habit of waiting for things to
happen,'' Visconti says. ``They wait for a job placement service.
They wait for an ad to pop up in the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Once you make it to the interview, you can also come across as
uninterested through your body language, Culver says. Dress
appropriately for the interview, offer a firm handshake, make good
eye contact and don't slump back in your chair, she says. Ask
questions about the company.
</P>
<P>
   _ CAN YOU TELL A GOOD STORY?
</P>
<P>
   Culver says companies use more behavioral questions these days,
asking applicants for specific examples of how they've worked well
under pressure or shown initiative or displayed teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``Run through the story'' before the interview, she says. ``Make
sure you have the beginning, the middle and the ending. Most of the
time, telling a vivid story is much more memorable than just
reciting what you've done.''
</P>
<P>
   Resolving conflict is another key topic for behavioral
questions. ``We might ask a question like `How did you handle an
irate customer?''' O'Peka says.
</P>
<P>
   _ WHAT'S YOUR BIGGEST WEAKNESS?
</P>
<P>
   O'Peka hates that question, but has been in plenty of interviews
where others have asked it. ``I get people who say, `I'm too much
of a hard worker.' I know they're blowing smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   When you do mention a weakness, though, make sure to explain how
you're improving the situation.
</P>
<P>
   _ SHOULD YOU MENTION SALARY?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sell them first on you,'' Visconti says. ``Don't be a
mercenary.''
</P>
<P>
   When the employer mentions a salary, he says, you should know
whether it is reasonable through the research you have done. For
those who need to do more research, salaries for many jobs are on
the Web at jobsmart.org.
</P>
<P>
   ``Know your industry and know what the market bears,'' Culver
says. ``Answer it with a range.''
</P>
<P>
   _ WOULD YOU HIRE YOU?
</P>
<P>
   Job hunters often forget to make it clear to the interviewer how
they would help a company, Visconti says. ``They forget the other
side. They forget to look at it from the perspective of the
employer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 1800EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
