<HEADER>
A1138 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASERATI-RETURN-ART-N     09-17 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASERATI-RETURN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN AMERICA REDISCOVER MASERATI? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD FEAST   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A once-proud automotive name, Maserati, will be seen once again
in the United States, if the company follows through on its plan to
return to the American market in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Maserati stopped selling cars in the United States in 1993, the
year it fell under the control of Fiat SpA. Last year, another Fiat
subsidiary, Ferrari, assumed management control of Maserati, its
longtime rival on the race track.
</P>
<P>
   An important milepost in Maserati's long, turbulent history will
come at the end of this month, when the Italian automaker's new
coupe makes its debut at the Paris Auto Show. The coupe, whose name
has not been announced, will be the first truly new Maserati model
since Fiat bought the company five years ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This coupe, along with a convertible version to be shown later,
will be the main weapons in Maserati's assault on the U.S. market.
They will later be joined by a new-generation four-door sedan,
which is scheduled for Europe in 2000. The cars, which will be
priced from $75,000 to $125,000, are likely to be sold by Ferrari
dealers now that the two old rivals are part of the same industrial
group. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The conservatively styled coupe is the work of Giorgio Giugiaro,
one of the world's most respected car designers. It will use a
traditional front-engine, rear-drive layout and be powered by a
twin-turbocharged version of Maserati's V8. With anticipated output
of up to 400 horsepower, the cars will not be for the
faint-hearted. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After decades of steady decline, the automaker is ready for a
fresh start. Four brothers of a family named Maserati founded the
company to tune race engines in the north-central Italian city of
Modena in 1914. Another brother, an artist, got the idea for
Maserati's trident emblem from a popular symbol of Bologna, a major
city nearby. The symbol became famous on the world's race tracks
after Maserati made its first car in 1926 _ the Tipo 26 Targa
Florio. The company decided in 1949 to begin producing road cars,
about the time the Maserati brothers ceded control to the Orsi
family.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, the Orsis sold Maserati to Citroen of France, but the
change failed to provide stability. With oil crisis problems of its
own in the early 1970s, Citroen decided to shut down Maserati. But
it was rescued by an Italian state holding company and an Argentine
entrepreneur with grand ideas, Alejandro de Tomaso. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite the succession of owners, no one managed to put Maserati
on a firm commercial footing. The cars were strong on performance,
style and cachet, but short on practicality, quality and
reliability.
</P>
<P>
   Production, which peaked at more than 6,000 in the early 1980s,
fell two-thirds by the start of the '90s. An ambitious plan to make
10,000 coupes a year for Chrysler _ the TC by Maserati based on
Chrysler's plebeian K-cars _ was emblematic of the misjudgments. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maserati's volume was little more than 500 by 1993, when de
Tomaso, then in poor health, agreed to sell his remaining shares to
Fiat, which already owned a sizable stake. Fiat immediately began a
new-model program and reorganized the haphazard production
operations. Output crept up, and an attack was begun on Maserati's
low productivity and dubious quality.
</P>
<P>
   But program delays and continuing losses required more drastic
measures. They came last year, after Ferrari _ Maserati's old race
track adversary _ was put in charge.
</P>
<P>
   The destinies of both companies are now the responsibility of
Luca Cordero di Montezemolo, a confidant of Giovanni Agnelli, the
Fiat patriarch. Di Montezemolo, who was an assistant to Enzo
Ferrari in the mid-1970s, became Ferrari's chairman and president
in 1991. After taking on similar responsibilities at Maserati, one
of his first moves was to suspend output for five months while
modern production equipment was installed. Now, Maserati talks of
edging up production to perhaps 6,000 a year by early in the next
century. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To do so, Ferrari and Maserati must stop fighting over the same
wealthy customers. That means giving the marques complementary
roles. As di Montezemolo sees it, Ferraris are extroverts, the
ultimate in high-ticket, high-technology machines. Maseratis are
less expensive, though definitely not cheap, and are aimed at the
more sober-suited banker who likes an occasional burst of speed.
The visual difference is like the contrast between Versace and
Armani. The image difference is like the contrast between Hollywood
and the Hamptons. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That, at least, is the theory. The critical question is whether
fancy-car buyers care about Maserati anymore. That is particularly
true in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   When the cars go on sale in 2001, how many buyers will even
remember Maserati? Historians and racing aficionados know about
Maserati's racing heritage: Wilbur Shaw's Indy 500 victories in
1939 and '40; Juan Manuel Fangio's World Championship in 1957, and
Stirling Moss' fondness at Monte Carlo for the Tipo 61, known as
the Birdcage because of its multitube chassis construction. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those glory days, though, may be just for the graybeards.
Younger buyers with shorter memories recall only unreliable
Maserati grand touring cars and the questionable Chrysler TC.
Replacing that nightmare with the legend will require more than
just good products.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
