u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HISPANICS0918     09-17 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANICS0918 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GINGRICH REPORTEDLY TO PUSH FOR MORE MONEY FOR
``HISPANIC-SERVING'' COLLEGES
 &HT;    By CHRISTI HARLAN
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Speaker Newt Gingrich told a group of
Hispanic leaders Thursday that he will ask his colleagues to
approve more money for so-called ``Hispanic-serving'' colleges and
to pay for a full census in 2000, according to the group's
president.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's pledge was important because ``this Congress is
following down a path of being anti-Latino,'' said Arturo Vargas,
president of the National Hispanic Leadership Agenda, a coalition
of national Hispanic organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The group's meeting Thursday with Gingrich was its second this
year _ the first was in June _ and Vargas called the meetings ``a
historic development.'' Gingrich expects to meet with the Hispanic
leaders ``on a regular basis,'' said his spokeswoman, Christina
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although they may not agree on how to handle each issue, they
agreed that it's in everyone's best interest to continue the
dialogue,'' Martin said. ``Where there is agreement, the speaker
and the (Hispanic leaders) will work together as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   As Vargas put it: ``We recognize that we have differences, and
we also have areas where we can work together.''
</P>
<P>
   On the census, for instance, Hispanic groups have supported
``sampling,'' a scientific estimate that would allow the Census
Bureau to count households that don't respond to mail or
census-takers. In the 1990 census, Hispanics were undercounted, in
part because Hispanics immigrants who are living illegally in the
United States are reluctant to respond to census-takers.
</P>
<P>
   But House Republicans not only have voted to prohibit sampling,
they filed and won a lawsuit to stop the Census Bureau from using
the estimate. Gingrich on Thursday assured the Hispanic leaders
that he will press for enough money to allow the Census Bureau to
reach every household it can.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a commitment we will hold him to,'' Vargas said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich also offered to urge committee leaders in the House to
increase the pool of money available to the 202 so-called
Hispanic-serving colleges and universities _ those where 25 percent
or more of full-time students are Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``These institutions also serve a lot of other minorities,''
said Roger Campos, vice president of governmental relations for the
Hispanic Association of Colleges and Universities. ``They're the
ones who need the most and receive the least.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hispanic-serving institutions competed this year for a total
of $12 million, and that was parcelled out to 37 schools. The House
has voted to make $16 million available to the schools next year,
and the Senate has approved $17 million, Campos said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich said he would contact House committee leaders about
increasing the allocation to a minimum of $28 million, the amount
requested by the Clinton administration, according to Campos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very impressed with Speaker Gingrich's understanding of
our issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
