<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1143 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-USAFRICA-TRADE-0918-C     09-17 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USAFRICA-TRADE-0918-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RELIGIOUS, CONGRESSIONAL LEADERS PUSH FOR PASSAGE OF AFRICA
TRADE BILL
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    By NICHOLE MONROE 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Amid a bipartisan group of religious leaders and
U.S. congressmen, Sen. Phil Gramm on Thursday pledged to push
landmark legislation that would, for the first time in nearly 40
years, significantly upgrade trade policy between the United States
and sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm, R-Texas, said passage of the African Growth and
Opportunity Act, now awaiting a Senate vote, would be an
opportunity for Americans to buy African products and aid a region
that has been long neglected and beleaguered by poverty.
</P>
<P>
   The senator's statements came as religious leaders from across
the country met in Washington Thursday to show support for the
bill. The measure aims to strengthen and expand the private sector
in sub-Saharan Africa and increase trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe quite simply that Africa matters,'' said Rev. Joan
Campbell, general secretary of the National Council of Churches.
``This holds the potential for enhancing the overall economic
situation. It doesn't matter how imperfect it is. We may not have
the opportunity again if we don't do it now.''
</P>
<P>
   But those who oppose the bill, including South African President
Nelson Mandela, say the legislation has too many strings attached
and imposes unfair conditions on African countries while
benefitting large foreign corporations.
</P>
<P>
   A primary concern is the controversial ``fast track'' trade
legislation attached to the overall Africa trade bill by a
Republican-dominated Senate panel. The so-called fast-track trade
authority, which would allow the president to negotiate trade deals
without congressional approval, has been staunchly opposed by
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Another obstacle to the overall bill, however, is that it would
grant duty-free access to textiles from Africa only if the garments
are assembled and cut from American fabric.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm said the textile provision would ``kill the bill'' because
African countries would be unable to fairly compete if made to buy
U.S. fabric. ``I intend to get that provision out before it
passes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As time grows short in the current congressional session, there
has been increasing urgency to have the bill approved. In a letter
sent this week to a co-author of the trade bill, Rep. Charles B.
Rangel, D-N.Y., President Clinton expressed his desire to have the
bill approved, but made no mention of the fast-track provision.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Philip M. Crane, R-Ill., said although Clinton is not
pushing for fast-track, the authority should still be included.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need fast track in the legislation, otherwise its like
having icing without the cake,'' Crane said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
