<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-MASSACRE _ MEXICO CITY _ In an apparent mafia hit, gunmen
lined up 19 people including six children and a baby against a wall
and mowed them down after dragging them from their beds at a cattle
ranch near the U.S. border early Thursday, federal and local
officials said. They said only one man survived the shootings but
he was in critical condition. While police at the scene said a
preliminary investigation had yet to reveal a motive, but officials
immediately suspected a drug connection as the area is a major
corridor for smuggling cocaine into the United States. In addition,
the male head of one of the three households was allegedly a
marijuana grower for the notorious Arrellana Felix brothers drug
cartel _ which is at the top of U.S. drug officials' list of drug
smuggling operations in Mexico. Developing. (Ferriss, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 7 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECONOMY _ MOSCOW _ American businesses in Russia have so
far lost $500 million in the current economic crisis and some are
contemplating pulling out of the market. ``Do you want us here or
not?'' the head of the American chamber of commerce told a news
conference, in a blunt message to Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov
and his new government as it contemplates how to deal with the
crisis. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving by 3 p.m. EDT in both the (i) International and (f)
Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   USAFRICA-TRADE _ WASHINGTON _ Congressional sponsors of the
African Growth and Opportunity Act will have a news conference to
highlight the support the bill has received from U.S. religious
leaders. The bill, meant to address three decades of U.S. economic
neglect for sub-Saharan Africa, has become steeped in controversy
since congressional Republicans have tied its fate to passage of
presidential ``fast-track'' trade authority. The latter is a no-no
among Democrats, who have championed the Africa trade bill.
(Monroe, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving by 5:30 p.m. EDT in both the (i) International and
(f) Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   ANIMAL-WASTE _ WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration announces
Thursday a national strategy for managing livestock waste that
requires large farms to obtain operation permits and to develop
detailed waste-management plans. The first-ever attempt to
federally regulate the waste is largely a response to cries from
environmental groups who say that animal manure is contaminating
water supplies and has contributed to massive fish kills. Farmers
and livestock producers aren't thrilled but were fearing more
drastic measures. (Moscoso, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   TECH-VISAS _ WASHINGTON _ Republican leaders in the House on
Thursday cancelled a planned vote on increasing the number of H-1B
visas for highly skilled foreign workers, citing a shortfall in
Democratic support for the measure. (Harlan, Cox News Service 200).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
