   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO _ TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ The way Gov. Lawton Chiles sees
it, Florida's settlement with cigarette makers won't be a done deal
until it gets $1.7 billion sweeter.
</P>
<P>
   Chiles planned a news conference Thursday to announce that the
state's take from its settlement with Big Tobacco will be nearly
$13 billion under a renegotiated agreement aimed at matching the
better settlements reached by other states. Since Florida reached
its original $11 billion settlement, Mississippi, Texas and
Minnesota have all settled lawsuits against the tobacco industry to
recoup the cost of treating sick smokers and to stop cigarette
makers from targeting children. (Date, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   RAMSEY _ The media has been talking about the prospect of
exhuming jonbenet's body, but authorities are saying there are no
plans. how much of this is just media spreading rumors. In
addition, what would an exhumation require? How often does it
occur? What are the parent's rights? (Schneider/, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12-15. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   CNN-TAILWIND _ It was a tale of three cities Thursday for CNN,
echoing Charles Dickens' best and worst of times. On a video hookup
between CNN headquarters in Atlanta and Time Warner in New York,
the network announced a new public service initiative to train
young journalists. Meanwhile, in San Francisco, more lawsuits were
filed against CNN for its Operation Tailwind story. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
