<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1170 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLIND-LITERACY-COX     09-17 1617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLIND-LITERACY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    North Georgia farmer overcame blindness to become a literacy
legend
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINERAL BLUFF, Ga. _Twice blind and hurtling toward 70, Wendell
Cross figured it was a good time to learn to read. So he did. That
was back in the late 1980s, after he and his wife, Eula Mae, had
raised 11 children on a bountiful farm and an often iffy income.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Cross is something of a celebrity in adult-literacy
circles, his story an inspiration to those who cannot read. Too,
his story is one of redemption _ Cross admits he ``raised hell''
before finding God. And it is a story about will and grit, mixed in
with a serious sense of humor _ all of which served Cross well in
his long, painful, hopeful journey toward light and learning.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the mountains of North Georgia, his name comes up often
when people talk of overcoming adversity. ``You know about Wendell
Cross?'' a man in nearby McCaysville asked, as we finished talking
about another story. ``You ought to meet him.''
</P>
<P>
   To meet him is to meet a man who can tell a story with the best
_ in a speech pattern whose melodic mountain rhythms have been only
slightly diluted by his relatively new venture into academia and
speechmaking: Fewer ``a'' prefixes adorn words such as hunting and
plowing than before, for example. Acutely aware of the changes,
Cross loves to joke about them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to get mad!'' he thunders, pacing back and forth in the
living room, where his wife looks on, intently amused; she knows
what's coming. ``But now, I get fruss-trated,'' he says, drawing
out the word. ``Before I learned to read, I used to say 'fessional;
now I say professional. Used to be 'simmon. Now it's persimmon.''
</P>
<P>
   What a long, hard trip it's been.
</P>
<P>
   Cross, 75, was born in Cherokee County(N.C.), grew up in Polk
County(Tenn.), and moved to Fannin County at 15. Like a lot of
country folks in big families, he didn't get a lot of schooling;
farm work was considered more important. Moreover, Cross
acknowledges, he ``was lazy'' when it came to school. He attended
up to third grade but never learned how to read.
</P>
<P>
   He's matter-of-fact reciting these facts, but you can feel the
hurt when he tells how he lost his sight for the first time back in
the early 1930s, along with a piece of his left thumb and index
finger _ the ones holding the dynamite cap.
</P>
<P>
   He and one of his six brothers (he had seven sisters) were
playing with the cap at home, after finding it along a road where a
construction crew had been working. Cross, then 11, recalls:
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what the thing was. I was in the house a-pickin'
it with a bobby pin. When it hit the stove, it sparked. My mom
said, `Get that stinking thing out of here.' I went out of the
house and stepped off the porch. Then I struck fire to that thing.
They come running out, and I said, `Mommy, I can't see.'
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `Lord, have mercy, son, you're blowed all to
pieces.'''
</P>
<P>
   For almost a decade, he lived in darkness. Doctors in Knoxville
and Chattanooga could fix his hand, ``but they said I'd never
see.'' Cross differed, dreaming of one day regaining his sight. In
his late teens, he set out to raise enough money for an operation.
Cutting wood for 10 cents an hour, it took him two years to raise
$25. Two brothers gave him $25 apiece, as did a church, the Red
Cross and the Kiwanis Club.
</P>
<P>
   At age 20, Cross says, he got his operation at Georgia Baptist
Hospital in Atlanta, where doctors ``cut the burnt off'' his left
eye. Before the operation, ``I could see a shadow, but I couldn't
tell whether you were a man or woman or a poodle dog.'' His right
eye was ``ruint'' by the dynamite, then further damaged in 1963 _
he was working on a car when pliers holding a spring flew into his
eye. It was replaced with an artificial one.
</P>
<P>
   His better left eye went bad again in 1965 when he suffered a
detached retina _ resulting from frequent falls that had begun
after he was struck by lightning years earlier. Cast back into
blindness, he soon had surgery, at a different hospital, telling
doctors, ``The good Lord ain't told me yet that I'm going to be
blind.'' And again, he could see, with the aid of powerful glasses,
which he wears today (he usually wears a hat, too, often a black
cowboy model, even indoors, to avoid glare).
</P>
<P>
   After he and Eula Mae married in 1947, Wendell worked in a
string of short-lived jobs, such as janitor and wood hauler. He
grew food to feed the family. (He and Eula Mae still grow
everything from corn to cows to honeybees on four rolling acres,
canning fresh vegetables and collecting eggs by the dozens.) They
raised 11 children, got on Social Security and, in the 1980s, he
worked at the family filling station and store in Mineral Bluff.
Through it all, he simmered with a desire to read and anger that he
could not.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little kid would bring in a note to tell what he wanted, and
I couldn't read it,'' he says. ``I'd call Eula Mae (she has a
fifth-grade education) and spell it over to her and she'd tell me
what it was.'' He couldn't order food in restaurants. Couldn't read
signs in stores. Books, including the Bible, were impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Eula Mae remembers well what life was like before Wendell
learned to read. ``He wouldn't even go in the store because he
didn't know what to get,'' she said quietly. ``Wouldn't go to
restaurants.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was more. ``She wouldn't tell it, so I'll tell it for
her,'' Wendell thundered. ``She wouldn't go nowhere with me 'cause
I raised hell all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to read so bad I couldn't stand it. One day (in the
late 1980s) I got up and I went up on the mountain and I prayed,
`Oh, Lord, send me a teacher. I want to learn to read so people
won't laugh at me and think I'm crazy.'''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, he got help from several people, including
Oscar Poole, the barbecue baron of East Ellijay, whose
establishment is known for its ``Pig Hill of Fame,'' now sprouting
3,000 plywood porkers stuck in the ground with customers' names
painted on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little voice said, `Go by the Cross' station,''' Poole
recalled the other day. So he did, and the two men began talking.
Poole told Cross, ``I am the teacher.'' Poole, who has taught
school in Mineral Bluff, soon had Cross practicing his ABCs,
singing them to the tune of ``America, the Beautiful,'' and
learning sounds of letters. When paper wasn't available, lessons
were written in the sand.
</P>
<P>
   Relishing the telling, Cross recalls, softly: ``He said, `I'll
teach you the phonics: B _ baby. C _ car.' One day, he said,
`Wendell, today I'm going to teach you the vowels.' I said,
`Vowels? That's what's in cars.' I didn't know what he was talking
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Word of Cross' inspirational story got around Fannin County, and
he began making speeches. After his presentation at a church,
Barbara Smith, then the county's vocational education director,
encouraged Cross to join an adult literacy program.
</P>
<P>
   That's where he met Jill Key, who became his teacher and remains
his friend and helper, handling logistics for his speaking
engagements around the state. Key, executive director of the Fannin
Literacy Action Group, said Cross ``has the spark'' necessary to
learn. By contrast, she said, ``a lot of older people say, `I've
made it this far. . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Such people have been known to use ``a barter system, in which
someone will say, `Read this for me, and I'll fix your tire,'''
said Daphne Greenberg, associate director of Georgia State
University's Center for the Study of Adult Literacy.
</P>
<P>
   Not satisfied with bartering or settling, Cross always worked to
go higher, further.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of an hours-long visit, he pointed out a tiny
room in the same outbuilding as his gristmill, where he would study
reading on his own, often late into the night. It still contains a
big stuffed chair, a desk scattered with audiotapes. A telephone
with huge numbers. And ghosts of illiteracy. ``I don't use it
anymore,'' Cross said of the study room, ``because I'm not afraid
no more.''
</P>
<P>
   No, he's proud these days, showing off a stack of literacy
awards _ medals, proclamations; he's the ``permanent ambassador for
literacy'' for the Fannin literacy group. Letters have come from
Barbara Bush and Gov. Zell Miller. And Cross has a veritable
gallery of photographs with first lady Shirley Miller, impassioned
literacy advocate, as well as shots with a Miss America, actor
Danny Glover and the Atlanta Falcons cheerleaders.
</P>
<P>
   What does it all mean?
</P>
<P>
   Independence. Cross can read his own Bible, his own letters, his
own signs. No big deal for readers, such a huge one for nonreaders.
</P>
<P>
   Making the point, he again jumps to his feet and strides back
and forth, preaching in a big voice, as if for one of his
audiences: ``You guys don't appreciate reading like I do because
you've read all your lives. It's just handy. Buddy, go through all
these years when you can't order your meal, don't know whether the
sign says `get out' or `get in' or `go over yonder.'''
</P>
<P>
   Wendell Cross has gone through and come out on the other side,
gaining the best of several worlds. Sight. Extraordinary hearing,
developed when he was blind (he still automatically turns his ears
toward a person before his eyes). ``And I can read! Amen! Ain't
that great!
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to go around, saying, `Here, Eula Mae, read
this.' I just stop down there (at the roadside mailbox) and read it
and bring it up here and throw it on the shelf. Just like therest
of them do. I don't have to ask nobody what's in there. Ain't that
great!''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
