</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MSKUBE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: A guide to English for those who care about the language
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL SEPTEMBER 20: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The critic John Simon once wrote of the time he was editor for
W.H. Auden, Lionel Trilling and Jacques Barzun, an apprenticeship
that must have been akin to a young lawyer's clerking for a U.S.
Supreme Court justice. Simon, not yet the marauding tiger he would
later become, had the modest job of getting out a book club's
monthly newsmagazine. Auden, Trilling and Barzun were contributors
to the magazine, and it was Simon's job to correct their occasional
lapses in grammar and style _ a duty one imagines him shouldering
with the resoluteness of a Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   He told the story with much good humor, and what it had to say
about Barzun was revealing of a man certain in his judgment. By
comparison, Auden treated his fugitive pieces less seriously than
his poetry and cheerily left the straightening out of a miscast
sentence to his editor, ``whom he treated with a charming mixture
of gratitude and indifference.'' Not so Trilling or Barzun, at the
time eminences on the faculty of Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   Barzun was both a distinguished historian and an acknowledged
authority on English usage _ and, in the latter capacity, a ready
knuckle-rapper. ``He required very little editing,'' Simon wrote,
``and accepted less.'' Indeed, it was under Barzun's direction that
the classic work of Wilson Follett, ``Modern American Usage,'' was
finished after its author's death. On this side of the Atlantic,
the book that Follett conceived but did not live to complete stands
beside the original edition of W.H. Fowler's ``Dictionary of Modern
English Usage'' as an indispensable guide not just for writers but
for anyone who cares about the language.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler (as it's called), first published in 1926, is the better
known and was once as familiar in newsrooms as green eyeshades and
glue pots. Things change, not always for the better. Yet, as witty
and magisterially assertive as Fowler was, the tone and emphasis
were more British than American. Follett modeled his book on
Fowler, but addressed himself to the language as it's written and
spoken in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The importance of distinctions
</P>
<P>
   My own Follett, 32 years after its publication, still gives good
service, like a car that never fails to start. But a tuneup and
sometimes an overhaul can make a good car better, and Erik Wensberg
has achieved this with the first revised edition of ``Modern
English Usage: A Guide''(Hill and Wang, $25). Like Follett himself
and like Barzun _ who recommended him for the assignment _ Wensberg
is not wishy-washy. He prescribes without apology. He knows that
language changes, and with it the conventions of usage and niceties
of style. But he is wise enough to know that change for the sake of
change is chaos _ or worse.
</P>
<P>
   Degradation and abuse of the language are routinely
rationalized. Change, the ignorant advise us, is life. But change,
as Wensberg writes, ``means death too, and in our own bodies we
take steps to arrest or reverse certain changes by medicine,
inoculation, surgery and other strong measures. We choose what we
want to preserve and what we want to slough off.''
</P>
<P>
   In the evolution of a language, change often means the waiver of
distinctions that have aided clarity and sharpened precision. Thus,
many assume ``disinterested'' to mean ``uninterested'' rather than
``without self-interest.'' The hound, Wensberg writes by way of
example, might not be in a mood to hunt. But to call it
``disinterested'' is to liken a dog's indifference ``to the work of
a scrupulous presiding judge.''
</P>
<P>
   Here as in myriad other instances (enormity/immensity;
acknowledge/admit; farther/further; anxious/eager; assure/ensure),
distinctions exist for good reason, not mere whim. ``Almost
always,'' Wensberg writes, ``the move toward a distinction, the
positive work of a language, is a gain. The negative change, away
from distinct ideas, is generally the result of heedlessness or
ignorance, and hence a loss.''
</P>
<P>
   The seduction of science
</P>
<P>
   It should be no surprise that many of the changes since the
first edition of ``Modern English Usage'' are pseudo-technical.
Nothing impresses us more than science, and no one is more
susceptible to its linguistic influence than the fawning
nonscientist. Physicists, when they speak of a ``critical mass,''
mean something quite exact. The rest of us mean something vague
and, if anything, contrary to the idea behind the term. But it
sounds impressive, even if we don't know what we're talking about.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise journalese, a category that Wensberg _ a former editor
at The New York Times Book Review _ has revised extensively. The
tone of journalese, he writes, ``is the tone of contrived
excitement.'' When the subject we're writing about is of no
particular consequence, we call forth the adjectives and
superlatives. ``The return of a sense of proportion,'' Wensberg
writes, ``will perhaps be signaled when every good book, play, or
film need not be riveting, brilliant or scathing.''
</P>
<P>
   In language, purity is one thing and purism quite another. The
colloquial need not yield to the stiffly formal, but neither should
it embrace the slangy. Wensberg, like his predecessors, knows that
English accommodates old and new equally. What matters _ if we put
any stock in clear thinking _ is that sound and sense are in
balance.
</P>
<P>
   -- E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
