<SLUG> BC-JANETJACKSON-REVIEW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A wild child who aims to please
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Finally. The Janet Jackson fans fell in love with in
1986 reappeared Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   We've been wondering where you were. For the past year all we've
been reading about and seeing on Oprah is this Janet that was
deeply depressed, piercing everything - and frankly - beginning to
distance herself in the same fashion big brother Mike has. Then you
put out this The Velvet Rope'' record - obviously a reflection of
your troubled times _ and sales dropped some eight million less
than the previous one.
</P>
<P>
   Guess we all were getting worried.
</P>
<P>
   Then look, up on the Lakewood Amphitheatre stage, it was the
Janet that could bring some 14,000 people to their feet with a
single stare after her second song If''. It was a confident,
certain Janet who roared through her dance-oriented hits Control,''
Pleasure Principle'' and What Have You Done For Me Lately'' with a
flurry that never revealed she was having back trouble up until her
red velvet curtain came up at 9:50 p.m. And yet it was also the
Janet some got to know as Penny'' on Good Times'', giggling when
her sweet, small voice was about to hit one of the bigger notes at
the end of her Oscar-nominated single Again.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has always liked to appear vulnerable. But the key word
in the previous sentence is appear. The moment she stepped in front
of her eight-member band (including Atlanta drummer John Roberts)
and alongside her eight dancers, the tabasco red-haired Jackson in
current publicity photos was once again the black-haired Janet in
black that announced her Control'' on her 1986 album of the same
name.
</P>
<P>
   An album later she was the conscientious Janet on Rhythm Nation:
1814'', the one who made sure to conclude the two-hour show with
the uplifting Together Again,'' derived from her need to address
friends who have died of AIDS. Next it was janet.'', cursing and
unabashedly delving into her sexuality. Clearly it was that Janet
who summoned a young man from the audience to do a strip tease to
her tune about bondage, Rope Burn.'' Even the 32-year-old Janet who
decided to let us behind the rather production-heavy Velvet Rope''
proved more interesting when tunes like You'' and the theatrical
What About'' were set against her Broadway-like staging and always
engaging choreography.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the incarnation, most importantly, last night she was
the Janet we could recognize and appreciate again.
</P>
<P>
   Surely a great model for opening act Usher Raymond, the
19-year-old Atlantan whose My Way'' has actually sold 2 million
more than Jackson's current album. On his third tour since the
release of that album Raymond's show hasn't varied much from his
last Atlanta appearance with Mary J. Blige. It's a fine melding of
his three big hits - the title track, Nice and Slow'' and You Make
Me Wanna'' _with work from his obvious influence
entertainment-wise, Bobby Brown. Five costume changes in 50 minutes
might make you wonder whether the considerable vocalist questioned
hs ability to hold the audience's attention. But really all the
sinewy Raymond had to do was rip off his shirt for the many,
audible women. Attention held.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
