<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MIDNIGHT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This `Midnight's' a bad trip; just say no
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Know what's mortifying?'' asks the junkie protagonist of
``Permanent Midnight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Smack is like the leisure suit of the '90s.''
</P>
<P>
   Close but, Monica jokes aside, no cigar.
</P>
<P>
   What's mortifying is a movie like ``Permanent Midnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on the true-life adventures of Jerry Stahl, a successful
Hollywood writer who chronicled his struggle to kick the heroin
habit in a recent book, the picture is the ultimate give-us-a-break
Hollywood ego trip, right down to the potential money to be made
from its I-have-sinned confessional tone.
</P>
<P>
   When we first meet Stahl, gamely played by Ben Stiller, he's
serving fast-food burgers as a condition of his rehab program. But
Jerry is sooooo charismatic in his little McBurger outfit that he's
immediately picked up by a gorgeous blonde (Maria Bello) who drives
through the takeout window and orders Jerry ... to go.
</P>
<P>
   The two repair to a nearby hotel where, when they're not having
passionate sex, Jerry tells her his story. It turns out that she's
a reformed junkie, too, and there's nothing she'd like better than
to hear every little detail of his personal saga. And if that makes
sense to you, maybe this is your kind of movie.
</P>
<P>
   See, Jerry moved to Hollywood to write great movies and ``to get
away from drugs.'' Instead, he quickly gets a gig on a sitcom about
an alien puppet (Stahl actually wrote for ``ALF'') and starts doing
heroin. When he's not shooting up, he's being told by everyone in
sight what a genius he is.
</P>
<P>
   A big-time agent (Janeane Garofalo) begs him to sign with her.
His airhead producer (Fred Willard) worships his every word. A
slightly over-the-hill star (Cheryl Ladd) must have him on her
series. Even his luscious green-card wife (Elizabeth Hurley)
forgets that theirs is supposed to be a marriage of convenience and
falls madly in love with him.
</P>
<P>
   Gee, if it weren't for this nasty little drug thing, he'd be
king of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry ultimately comes clean. The movie never does. It remains a
self-serving vanity production that only pretends to explore the
lower depths, Hollywood-style. Ultimately, it's a self-protective,
preening bore that uses its needle-ridden scenes as shock-tactic
distractions and its pulled-from-the pages-of-Premiere dialogue as
a way to flatter audiences into feeling like insiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Permanent Midnight''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ben Stiller. Directed by David Veloz. Rated R for sex
and explicit drug use. At metro theaters. 1 hour, 27 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Needs to go to movie rehab.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
