<HEADER>
A1174 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-RUSH-COX     09-17 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-RUSH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This `Odd Couple' of cops clicks
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It never hurts to loosen up a bit.
</P>
<P>
   That, unlikely as it seems, is the message behind ``Rush Hour,''
an enjoyable new whack-'em-up, crack-'em-up adventure movie about a
mismatched pair of cops.
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely because neither star _ kick-boxing,
karate-chopping Jackie Chan nor motor-mouthed stand-up comic Chris
Tucker _ could ever be accused of holding back. ``The fastest hands
in the East vs. the biggest mouth in the West'' goes the film's
promotional one-liner, and for once, it seems, there's truth in
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Unlikely, too, because one doesn't exactly go into a movie like
``Rush Hour'' expecting to learn anything _ other than the
importance of covering little pitchers' ears and expensive
breakables whenever Tucker and Chan are around.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's something instructive about ``Rush Hour,'' in
which the good guys win largely by becoming more, um, flexible in
their respective approaches to crime fighting. Each struggles to
pick up some of the other's tricks. What's funnier, watching Chan
trying to be hip or Tucker nearly throwing his out in a fight
scene? The result is an entertaining ride for anyone not expecting
any mental heavy lifting.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it's hard to take too seriously this saga of a tough yet
modest Hong Kong police detective inspector, Lee (Chan), fetched
from afar when the Chinese consul's 11-year-old daughter is
kidnapped in Los Angeles. The consul thinks Lee is just the man to
help the FBI bring his little girl back alive; the rock-jawed G-men
are just as convinced he's the last person they want around.
</P>
<P>
   Make that the second-to-last person. The FBI agents don't know
rogue L.A. police Detective James Carter (Tucker) at first, but
they quickly come to understand why his captain has been so quick
to lend him out and let him play keep-away-from-the-investigation
with Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Carter is the sort of cop whose smart mouth gets him into
trouble even when his own peculiar brand of crime solving doesn't:
``Every once in a while, we have to let the general public know we
can still blow (stuff) up,'' he gloats to his captain after his
successful undercover arrest of a bomb merchant destroys a city
block.
</P>
<P>
   Much like the fried chicken wings and boiled eel that each tries
to tempt the other to sample, Carter and Lee don't go together at
first. But eventually, you just know they'll join forces to try to
find the girl and prove those doubting FBI-ers wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does ``Rush Hour'' show off each man's particular area
of acting prowess _ Chan flips off a speeding double-decker bus as
effortlessly as Tucker drops punch lines about working for the
much-maligned LAPD _ it also knows when enough is enough.
</P>
<P>
   So loosen up, enjoy the ride and, whatever you do, don't take
off before the airplane in the final scene. Those may not truly be
the fastest hands in the East or the biggest mouth in the West on
the screen, but the outtakes definitely make for some of the best
closing credits around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rush Hour''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jackie Chan and Chris Tucker. Directed by Brett Ratner.
Rated PG-13 for violence and language. 1 hour, 37 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: As fast and kicky as a Chan move _ and a lot less
painful.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
