<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-THING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Streep only true thing in tearjerker movie
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``One True Thing'' strikes too many false notes to be the
three-hankie weeper it wants to be. Based on Anna Quindlen's book,
it's notable for another pitch-perfect characterization by Meryl
Streep. Unfortunately, it's not Streep's movie.
</P>
<P>
   The drama centers on Renee Zellweger, playing career journalist
Ellen Gulden, whose drive has earned her the adjectives ``cold and
insensitive'' from colleagues. Her boss at New York magazine sums
it up: ``I know what you want: a new computer and Diane Sawyer's
job.''
</P>
<P>
   She's the opposite of her mother, Kate (Streep), a lifelong
homemaker whose sunny-side-up attitude Ellen sees as pre-feminist,
blinkered denial. If someone breaks a dish, Kate saves the
fragments for her mosaic table. She's a member of the Minnies, a
group of neighbor women who, in Ellen's disgusted estimation, run
around town doing ``all that do-good stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The two are brought into close quarters in Ellen's old
small-town home when Kate is diagnosed with cancer. Once there, the
movie begins its slightly synthetic campaign to make the young
woman appreciate her mother's life choices. Example: We have to
watch Ellen volunteer to cook for her mother, then burn the meal.
And the movie piles on secondhand Hallmark spectacles, such as a
colorful country fair and a Christmas jubilee that taps a choir
singing ``Silent Night'' for cheap emotional effect.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that ``One True Thing'' tries to take on too many
things, including the issue of euthanasia, Ellen's uneasy
relationship with her self-important professor dad (William Hurt),
and her boyfriend problems. (All the men in the movie are jerks, or
at best incidental, such as Tom Everett Scott as Ellen's brother.)
</P>
<P>
   When the movie keeps its focus on Kate and Ellen, it works.
That's mainly due to Streep, who layer by layer peels away Kate's
chipper Martha Stewart veneer to get to the woman's depth and
humanity. In the centerpiece confrontation between the two, Kate
tells her daughter, ``It's so much easier to be happy, my love ...
instead of always yearning for what you're missing.'' The line has
patness but also the undeniable profundity of ``there's no place
like home.'' (Not coincidentally, we first meet Kate while she's
wearing a Dorothy costume from ``The Wizard of Oz.'')
</P>
<P>
   Unintentionally, Streep's nuanced performance underscores the
film's general emotional shallowness. Karen Croner's screenplay
offers a mixture of the canned sass and softness you find in a
glossy women's magazine. Not that there's anything wrong with that,
but the movie needs to go deeper to earn our tears.
</P>
<P>
   Director Carl Franklin (``One False Move'' and ``Devil in a Blue
Dress'') delivers a good-looking mainstream movie without much
personality. Hurt, in an unsympathetic role, drifts through
aloofly. And while Zellweger is a good actress, she's overmatched
by Streep; she can't bring the kind of complexity that's needed to
flesh out her role's career-girl cliches.
</P>
<P>
   ``One True Thing''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Meryl Streep, Renee Zellweger and William Hurt.
Directed by Carl Franklin. Rated R for profanity. 2 hours, 7
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Doesn't ring as true as it should.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
