<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In full SWING
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL SEPTEMBER 20: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The temptation is to dismiss the trend toward dressing like
characters from ``Guys and Dolls'' and dancing to the music known
as swing as a delusional phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   When Gen X'ers by the thousands suddenly start combing the
thrift stores and vintage shops for skinny ties, spectator shoes,
bouffant dresses and bobby socks, it says something about their
inability to deal with present-day realities ... a need to retreat
mentally to simpler times, right?
</P>
<P>
   Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   According to Leslie Hancock, she and the others who have begun
dressing like swingers do so out of a growing sense of contentment
and optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you feel sophisticated and sexy,'' Hancock, 24, said
while waiting with a capacity crowd dressed in '50s-style fashion
for the recent Big Bad Voodoo Daddy show in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dressing like this just makes you feel good about yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``For so long, the same people you see here tonight were
dressing to show the angst they felt. But, as you see, those days
are over.''
</P>
<P>
   Dirk Shumaker, the Big Bad Voodoo Daddy bassist, said he
relishes being a role model for the group's fans, even though it
requires ``a lot of footwork'' to keep his wardrobe of zoot suits
and fedoras freshly stocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like this look in the sense that it's making people aware of
a very classy era in American history,'' Shumaker said.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the multitudes who are learning to dress like
swingers, ``class'' is back in session.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
