<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Two who hold the past in awe sending an SOS
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you or any of your relatives took pictures at the ``Gone With
the Wind'' premiere in December 1939, Herb Bridges, the foremost
collector of GWTW memorabilia, would like to hear from you.
</P>
<P>
   Herb, who has been collecting all kinds of Margaret Mitchell and
``Gone With the Wind'' artifacts for years, is putting together a
book about the premiere, to be published by Mercer University Press
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am seeking photographs concerning the `GWTW' premiere and
have located many at the Atlanta History Center, the Georgia
Archives and Georgia State University, plus those in my own `GWTW'
collection,'' he wrote. ``But I would like to obtain candid
snapshots made by individuals during the many `GWTW' activities.
Such snapshots may be hidden away in old photograph albums and
scrapbooks. ... Possibly these families might share the photographs
for this book project.''
</P>
<P>
   So here is Herb's request and my hope that you may help him. He
is curator for the ``GWTW'' exhibit in the Newnan-Coweta Historical
Society's collection. The address is P.O. Box 192, Sharpsburg, GA
30277.
</P>
<P>
   People tell me there are untold riches in memorabilia among
``GWTW'' fans, and I think it would be nifty if a lot of heretofore
unseen snapshots should turn up. I am sorry I cannot help Mr.
Bridges, although I have admired his zeal in collecting for many
years. I never had a picture of Margaret Mitchell, but I did have a
couple of notes from her. Alas, I lost track of them years ago. I
have worked in four buildings since I came to the Atlanta
Constitution, and three or four offices each. In the transition, I
have mislaid or lost many things I value.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Mitchell, as you've probably read, had a pleasant habit of
dropping you a note if you wrote something she liked. She had given
up autographing books after the first million sold, but she did
something better. She scribbled a personal note, suitable for
pasting on the flyleaf.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't get one of those, but when I wrote about old-time
Atlantans who had become street people, it interested her. She
would drop by the office on one of her trips to town and talk about
the old families of some of my eccentric friends. She knew the
Confederate background of the ancestors of my friend Lucy Gartrell
and her sister, Ina Mae Smith, and she rejoiced that they were
still spirited, independent women. I had a couple of notes from her
on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   If I could find those notes, I would contribute them to Mr.
Bridges and the Newnan-Coweta group. I would also send along the
invitation to Peggy's funeral. Since seating space at Patterson's
was fairly limited _ at least for a funeral that would draw mammoth
crowds of celebrity seekers _ John Marsh, Peggy's husband, and
Stephens Mitchell, her brother, decreed that attendance at the
funeral would be by invitation only. As I recall, the invitation
was a small pink card. Anyhow, although Harold Martin and I covered
the funeral, we did not stow away our invitations for safe-keeping.
</P>
<P>
   So much for ``GWTW.'' There's another request here for reader
help on an entirely different matter. Gloria S. Brown has a
``cakewalk'' doll, handed down in the family and believed to be
more than 150 years old and would like to know if any of you have
ever heard of such a thing. If so, write her at P.O. Box 11331,
Atlanta, 30310. We aim to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
