</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-CRUISE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Disney's special touch is everywhere on the company's maiden
voyage into the cruise business
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL SEPTEMBER 20: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD THE DISNEY MAGIC
</P>
<P>
   Studio Sea is rockin'. It's 10:45 p.m. in the family disco and
the same kids who were falling asleep in their spaghetti and
meatballs two hours earlier are bouncing to a fractious pop song:
``I get knocked down, but I get up again ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Then the mood changes. Slow dance time. As Celine Dion croons
``Every night in my dreams, I see you, I feel you. ...'' little
girls sweet-talk their daddies onto the dance floor. Cheek to belt
buckle, they close their eyes and fantasize they're dancing with
Leo DiCaprio. I nurse my nightcap, a frothy nonalcoholic drink
called the Gangster, described as ``Al Cappuccino in a vanilla ice
cream and chocolate chip thriller.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a moment to remember _ one of many as Disney Cruise
Lines' Magic put out to sea July 30 on its four-night maiden voyage
with a capacity 2,400 passengers aboard, marking the entertainment
giant's big splash into the cruise business. The Magic _ which
represents a reported $350 million investment _ will be joined by a
twin ship, Wonder, in March. In this venture, Disney goes
head-to-head with such established lines as Royal Caribbean,
Carnival and Premier Cruises, whose fleet includes the Big Red
Boat.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's floating kingdom is mostly magic, filled with surprises
big and small for the young _ and young at heart.
</P>
<P>
   Stacy Crawley of Tyler, Texas, treasures a moment when she and
husband Les returned to their stateroom to find her teddy bear
sitting on the turned-down bed sporting one of Les's ties. (Another
time, the bear is wearing sunglasses and lounging on a deck chair
on the veranda. A room hostess with a keen sense of playfulness is
the prime suspect.)
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the personal touch,'' says Stacy, 29. ``That is the
Disney magic.''
</P>
<P>
   There are not-so-subtle Disney touches as well _ such as a
restaurant that morphs from stark black and white to a riot of
color. That would be the whimsical Animator's Palate. Sketches from
Disney's animated features come alive in color on the walls, and
the giant paintbrushes that serve as columns in the room glow in
green, red and blues. Dessert is a grand finale featuring the
waiters (whose black and white vests reverse to a brightly colored
pattern) marching into the room with ``paint'' kits _ squeeze
bottles of flavored sauces to drizzle artistically on chocolate
mousse shaped like Mickey's head. Just plain goofy.
</P>
<P>
   A WHOLE NEW WORLD
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to Mickey and Co. to rewrite the rules when it comes to
cruising.
</P>
<P>
   There's no glib-talking, back-slapping cruise director working
the crowds to make sure Everybody's Having a Great Time. There's no
casino and no Vegas-style sequins-and-feathers floor shows. No
captain's dinner calling for black-tie and evening wear. No flaming
baked Alaska paraded through the dining room by smiling waiters. No
dapper gents hired to dance with unattached dames at sea. And,
sorry, gramps, no midnight buffet _ and not a single ice sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   What there is more than makes up for these traditional cruise
perks.
</P>
<P>
   The terrific children's program fills 15,000 square feet _
almost an entire deck. Children 3-8 are assigned to Oceaneer's Club
and those 9-12 are in Oceaneer's Lab. Both programs blend science
with fun and games. My 10-year-old daughter, Caroline, made a batch
of green slime called Flubber and played computer games the first
night. The programs are open from 9 a.m. until 1 a.m., and the
counselors will take the kids to lunch and dinner, so parents can
drop off the little darlings in the morning, get a pager and say,
``See ya later.'' Believe me, the kids don't mind being left. In
fact, you may have to drag 'em out.
</P>
<P>
   For older kids, a hip coffeehouse called Common Grounds is a
hangout off-limits to anyone younger than 13 or older than 17. And
there's a computerized arcade called Quarter Masters, where you
play till your prepaid card runs out. Then, there's Beat Street, a
mini-Pleasure Island filled with adults-only joints like Rockin'
Bar D, Sessions jazz/piano bar and Offbeat (with improv comedy and
karaoke). Sports fans (like my husband) have the ESPN Skybox
perched in the forward funnel for drinks, stadium-style snacks and
the Big Game (John caught the Atlanta Braves one afternoon). Bars
are scattered about the ship _ Outlook, Signal's and Promenade
Lounge (where I saw a guy playing piano with white gloves like
Mickey's one evening).
</P>
<P>
   There are excellent Broadway-style shows nightly, including
``Disney Dreams,'' a young girl's adventure with Peter Pan and
favorite Disney characters; ``Hercules the Muse-ical,'' a cheeky
sendup of the Disney animated feature with ad-libs relating to
shipboard foibles; ``Island Dreams,'' a prelude to the day at
Castaway Cay aimed at children; and, my favorite, ``Voyage of the
Ghost Ship,'' a swashbuckling shipboard melodrama with acrobatic
dancing and romantic ballads.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the cruise offerings are weighted toward families,
adults sans kids have special activities exclusively for them. They
can take part in bingo games, wine tastings, movies and
line-dancing lessons, pamper themselves with spa services (if
they're lucky enough to get an appointment), dine at the upscale
Palo by reservation (but available seatings are filled as fast as
spa appointments) and swim in the adults-only pool (a
cannonball-free zone).
</P>
<P>
   There's so much to do that anyone would be hard-pressed to fit
in even a sampling of all the activities during a four-night
cruise. Awaiting guests in their spacious staterooms (nearly half
of which have balconies) are Personal Navigators that include
dining room assignments and evening show times as well as a
detailed day-by-day list of what's happening when. I was back home
before I realized ``Hope Floats,'' a movie I'd been wanting to see,
was screened several times in the Buena Vista Theater. (I admit I
did see that Goofy was leading family fitness exercises at 8 a.m.
on the Wide World of Sports Deck; that, I chose to ignore.)
</P>
<P>
   TROUBLE IN WONDERLAND
</P>
<P>
   So what's not to like? Plenty, according to some mutiny-minded
Mickey maniacs who made reservations two years in advance to be a
part of Disney history and were sorely disappointed in everything
from service and food to the number of character sightings.
Although the inaugural sailing was fraught with start-up snafus, my
family shared few of the gripes registered by some vacationers.
</P>
<P>
   But even the detractors had to admit there's potential for tons
of fun _ 83,000 to be exact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in time it will be great,'' says Diana Walker of
Zionsville, Ind., who was not happy that she had to spend the first
three hours on board standing in line to sort out problems with her
family's dining assignments. ``The ship is beautiful. Our stateroom
is great. The shows have been great. But the service isn't ready
and, on a Disney voyage, I don't want to hunt Mickey down.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the Crawleys, who generally gave high marks to the Magic,
wished there were more organized activities for adults, but they
enjoyed a wine tasting and even took part in some family
activities, including the Nautical Mystery Tour.
</P>
<P>
   While I'm at it, I had really been looking forward to treating
myself to a pedicure or perhaps a massage in the Vista Spa &AMP; Salon.
But I was standing in line (a time-honored Disney tradition if
there ever was one) to sign up for shore excursions when I heard
the PA announcement that all spa services were booked through the
cruise. And the ship hadn't even left port! (I did manage to get a
mini-facial when some appointments opened up.)
</P>
<P>
   Later that evening on Deck 10, the top deck, as the ship was
slowly pulling out of Port Canaveral, Fla., to much fanfare both
onboard and on shore, I met Kate Bryan of Worthington, Ohio, who
had been looking forward to this moment for two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are going just fine,'' she says. ``If you're going to
be the first ones, you can't expect perfection.'' Her traveling
companion, John Bartenstein, also of Worthington and a collector of
Disneyana for more than 25 years, was on hand for the opening of
Toyko Disneyland in 1983 and EuroDisney (now Paris Disneyland) in
1992. He wasn't about to miss the Disney Magic maiden voyage, even
though it was twice postponed. ``I said, `It doesn't matter when it
sails, I want to be on it,''' says Bartenstein.
</P>
<P>
   So here we all were, full of anticipation, ready to embark on
our adventure in the blue Caribbean aboard the classy blue-black
and white 964-foot ocean liner with gold trim and twin red
smokestacks with white silhouettes of Mickey's head. Well-wishers
lining the harbor waved and we waved back, cheering and downing
champagne served in plastic cups. The ship's horn blasted out the
notes to ``When You Wish Upon a Star.'' As Goofy would say, ``Aw,
gorsh.''
</P>
<P>
   HISTORY IN THE MAKING
</P>
<P>
   Disney has come a long way since 1928 when Mickey Mouse took the
helm of a ship in ``Steamboat Willie,'' the first cartoon with
sound. Seventy years later, Mickey's back at the helm, and we are
happy to be a part of another magical Disney first.
</P>
<P>
   Call me an overgrown kid, but I loved sleeping under a poster
with the music and opening line to ``A Dream Is a Wish Your Heart
Makes.'' I loved making a game out of finding ``hidden Mickeys''
(look closely at the grillwork flanking the elevators in the
colorful three-story atrium). Also special: Ordering escargot at
the elegant French restaurant named Lumiere's after the debonair
candlestick in ``Beauty and the Beast'' and the ``Oh, gross, mom''
look on my daughter's face as I chewed on the garlicky morsels;
queuing up for ice cream at Scoops every afternoon at 3:30; sitting
on my veranda at night watching the ship slide through the inky sea
as a waxing moon illuminated the night.
</P>
<P>
   Although there were complaints about the quality _ and quantity
_ of the food (``I've actually been hungry on this cruise,''
groused Mike Tonsmeyer of Cincinnati), we found it generally to be
satisfactory. Granted, some dishes worked better than others (my
husband always liked what I picked best), portions weren't huge
and, except for a creme brulee at Lumiere's, desserts were
forgettable.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner is a game of musical chairs as guests rotate among
elegant Lumiere's, artsy Animator's Palate and calypso-happy Parrot
Cay _ and your servers go with you from place to place. We liked
having the jovial Anja from Germany and wry Alexander from Brazil
around every night. And the kids seem quite pleased with the
children's menus, which are the same in each restaurant. (Guests
also are assigned to restaurants for breakfast and lunch, but you
can opt for Topsider's buffet or snack shacks such as Pinocchio's
for pizza or Pluto's for burgers and hot dogs. None of these
fast-food spots rises above typical theme park fare.)
</P>
<P>
   WHEN IN NASSAU . . .
</P>
<P>
   The day in Nassau offered a chance to explore the colonial
capital city of the Bahamas with its famous Straw Market, duty-free
shops and restaurants. Several shore excursions were offered
through Guest Services, including a visit to the Crystal Palace
casino. We decided to go for the Crystal Cay Marine Park trip ($23
adult, $16.50 children) and snorkeling on the Caribbean Queen ($35
adult, $25 children).
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, we walked into town and were immediately
approached by women eager to braid our hair. We bit, and at $2 per
braid, Caroline was soon posing for photos under the palms with 16
plaits anchored with colorful beads. (And I'm looking a tad foolish
with my 10.) Feeling adventurous, we paid an islander _ a friend of
the hair-braider _ $25 to take us on a whirlwind tour of the island
in his rattletrap jalopy before we had to return for dinner. (And
we thought we had to go to Disney World for Mr. Toad's Wild Ride!)
</P>
<P>
   Safely back at the ship, a Junkanoo party is brewing, mon. We're
feeling giddy. Just the right mood for an island-style dinner with
silly drinks like Bahama Mamas in 2-foot-tall souvenir glasses.
</P>
<P>
   CASTING CARES AWAY
</P>
<P>
   If our shipmates were not sufficiently mellow by the last day, a
few hours on Castaway Cay, Disney's private island in the Abacos,
would surely do the trick. The boat docked before sunrise and
guests were allowed to debark by 8:30 a.m. Trams with recorded
fanciful histories of the island (made up out of whole cloth by
Disney Imagineers) take guests from the ship to the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Until 3:30 p.m., we could bake on the beach, rent snorkeling
gear to explore the developing manmade reef (complete with a
``shipwreck'' as only Disney could do it), bicycle along tropical
trails and chow down at Cookie's Bar-B-Q (where the picnic spread
includes hamburgers, hot dogs, ribs, baked beans, corn on the cob,
salads, cake, fruit and punch). A Caribbean band plays Jimmy
Buffett and Bob Marley.
</P>
<P>
   Kids can scale a three-story water-play fort and participate in
a ``dig'' at Monstro Point, where the skeletal remains of a 35-foot
``whale'' lies on the sand. Teens and adults also have their own
designated areas away from the family crowds. In keeping with the
island's laid-back theme, the Postmistress is May B. Tamara. And
the island speciality drink, the Conched Out, is aptly named.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving these 1,000 sandy acres of paradise, we find Goofy and
Pluto cavorting outside the ship, mugging with kids.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight we have reservations for dinner at Palo, the trendy
adults-only restaurant that offers a 270-degree ocean view and
California-contemporary cuisine (think Napa Valley meets Tuscany).
Afterward, we hit the clubs one more time while Caroline parties at
Oceaneer's Lab.
</P>
<P>
   When we awake Monday morning, we were already back at Port
Canaveral. After breakfast, I run into Les and Stacy Crawley,
sunburned from a day on Castaway Cay but grinning like a couple of
kids at a carnival. Wearing new Disney Cruise Line shirts, they are
loaded down with commemorative posters and other collectibles from
the maiden voyage to take back to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Their verdict: ``It was special,'' Les says. ``I'd come back.
Definitely.''
</P>
<P>
   Yep, me, too.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   The fares: Airfare is included in the package rate for a
seven-night vacation, which includes three or four nights at Disney
World, bus transfers to Port Canaveral with return to the airport
in Orlando and a three- or four-night cruise. Brochure rates for
seven nights start at about $1,300 per person based on double
occupany; children 3-17 sharing a cabin are $999 each. Cruise-only
rates start at $799 adults for a three-night cruise. Also, packages
without air are available. The price covers all meals and snacks,
including room service, but alcoholic beverages and soft drinks are
extra. You'll also be encouraged to tip your cabin host or hostess
and dining room staff. Call 407-566-7000.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: Get a peek at the Disney Magic at
http://www.disneycruise.com.
</P>
<P>
