<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1180 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANK-FEUD-COX     09-17 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANK-FEUD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Singer left behind a smoldering family feud
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   He had fame, money and a mess of kinfolks. So it's no surprise
that Hank Williams left behind one blowout of a family feud after
his death.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the cast of characters:
</P>
<P>
   Hank Williams died without a will, so his estate _ including
lucrative publishing rights _ reportedly went to two people: his
then-3-year-old son, Hank Williams Jr., and Williams' wife at the
time of his death, Billie Jean Jones. Jones, a 17-year-old divorcee
who had a taste for country music stars, had been married to
Williams only three months when he died. They were wed in what many
consider a garish public ceremony at the Municipal Auditorium in
Shreveport, La., where fans plopped down $2 to see them take vows.
</P>
<P>
   Many of his possessions _ report cards, family photos, etc. _
were left with his mother, Lillie Skipper Williams at her
boardinghouse in Montgomery. When she died in 1955, they were
passed to Williams' older sister, Irene Williams. In 1995, country
star Marty Stuart stumbled into Irene, who was living broke and
alone in a tiny duplex in Dallas. She invited him ``out to the
house,'' where she proceeded to open boxes of Williams'
possessions. Stuart purchased the items, which are now on display
at Nashville's Country Music Hall of Fame and Museum.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most significant people in Williams' life _ and after
his death _ was his first wife, Audrey Sheppard Williams, mother of
Hank Jr. Hank and Audrey married in December 1944 and had a
notoriously stormy relationship, even divorcing briefly in 1948.
According to biographer Colin Escott, when Williams was asked to
join the Grand Ole Opry later that year, ambitious Audrey had the
divorce annulled. In May 1952 she threw in the towel for good,
divorcing Williams just seven months before his death and four
months before he married Billie Jean.
</P>
<P>
   But Audrey wasn't out of the game entirely. In her divorce
settlement, she got rights to half of Williams' publishing catalog.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1954, Audrey bought Billie Jean's rights and interests in
Williams for $25,000. When Audrey died in 1975, the publishing
interests are believed to have gone to Hank Jr., the sole heir.
</P>
<P>
   But then came Jett.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was pretty busy that last year of his life. Not only
did he split from Audrey and marry Billie Jean, he had a fling in
the spring of 1952 with a Nashville secretary named Bobbie Jett.
She became pregnant and was stashed away at Williams' mother's home
to await the birth. He signed papers admitting paternity and made
arrangements for his mother to raise the child and pay Bobbie's
fare to California after the baby's birth. When Williams pulled out
of Montgomery for his final ride on New Year's Eve, witnesses say a
very pregnant Bobbie saw him off. She gave birth to a baby girl on
Jan. 6, 1953, five days after Williams' death.
</P>
<P>
   While Bobbie stepped out of the picture, never to be seen again
(she died in 1974), the little girl called Cathy Yvonne (after the
girl in ``Jambalaya'') lived with Williams' mother Lillie in
Montgomery for two years. When Lillie died in 1956, the story goes
that Williams' sister Irene felt it would be best for her to be
adopted so that no one knew where she came from. So Cathy was
raised by a couple in Mobile and was never aware of her famous
family tree.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, Cathy Yvonne received a mysterious check from the
Williams' estate for $3,000. Turns out that Williams' relatives
hadn't covered the trail completely: Papers instructed that his
illegitimate daughter receive money upon her 21st birthday. After
years of tracing her past and many ugly court fights with her
half-brother Hank Jr., Cathy Yvonne, in 1993, was finally awarded a
piece of the Williams' publishing and royalty empire. She changed
her name to Jett Williams and began pursuing a singing career.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's a new generation. Hank Williams III, the son of Hank
Jr., has decided to pursue a country music career. But he's mad,
too. Raised by his mother (who was divorced from Hank Jr. when Hank
III was 2), he reportedly doesn't speak to his father. At a recent
outdoor concert, he was billed on the same stage as his aunt Jett,
whom he had never met. But rather than mend fences, he laid down
the challenge that he was going to ``blow her off the stage.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be Billie Jean who gets the last laugh. Connived by
Audrey out of any claim to the Williams' estate, she got wind that
the publishing rights to Williams' songs were coming up for renewal
in the early 1970s. She sued for a share and won. So now, what's
left of Williams, is legally shared by three people who share
little history and no love _ Hank Jr., Jett and Billie Jean.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
