<DOCNO> NYT19980917.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1182 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATIONAL-SYMPHONY-COX     09-17 1920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIONAL-SYMPHONY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maestro is creating his own buzz in nation's capital
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON obert Shaw's place in the world of choral music is as
lofty as the Lincoln Memorial _ and, at 82, his face seems just as
timeless and wind-swept. His marble-veined hair brings to mind the
poetic comportment of Carl Sandburg, his self-deprecating humor the
aura of Will Rogers. Over the last few days, as the dignity of the
republic vanished into cyberspace, the image of this grand old man
conducting the National Symphony Orchestra's Beethoven Festival has
been a balm for the soul of this weary capital.
</P>
<P>
   A preacher's son who began his career with no formal training,
worked with mercurial conductor Arturo Toscanini while still in his
20s, conducted the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra from 1967 to 1988 and
won 15 Grammys, Shaw remains a beloved figure far beyond his
Georgia home. Not only are his Kennedy Center performances selling
out, but during the past two weeks of rehearsals, he's been mobbed
like a rock star by choristers trying to snap his picture and get
his autograph.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have that many real musical legends left,'' says
Washington Post classical music critic Tim Page. ``When you think
about it, (Leonard) Bernstein's gone, Aaron Copland's gone. There
aren't that many people with that kind of history around.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's schedule is full through 2002, and he averages working
about two weeks a month. On Oct. 29, 30 and 31, he'll conduct the
Atlanta Symphony Orchestra and Chorus in Dvorak's ``Stabat Mater,''
which is to be recorded on the Telarc label. In February, he'll
record the first English translation of Brahms' Requiem, with the
Mormon Tabernacle Choir. And for his Carnegie Hall workshops in New
York each January, he is planning an ambitious series of
commissions by composers such as Stephen Paulus, Michael Corigliano
and Dominic Argento.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would take us to 2008,'' he chuckles during an interview
at the Watergate Hotel. It is the end of a triumphant week in which
he has led some 270 musicians in a heart-rending version of
Beethoven's monolithic ``Missa Solemnis.'' Before this day is over,
he will begin rehearsing a new 175-voice choir for performances of
Beethoven's Choral Fantasy and Symphony No. 9, which close the
festival this weekend. Though a celebratory dinner kept him out
until 2 a.m. the night before, he is buoyant, happy and in the mood
for conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a navy button-down and a pair of cream-colored slacks,
he plops down onto a loveseat and recalls a life that spans the
globe, the 20th century and most of its major personalities. Except
for Kennedy _ who was assassinated before one of Shaw's State
Department tours would have earned him a White House reception _
he's known every president since Franklin D. Roosevelt. He
conducted for Margaret Truman's only record (``Her mysteries aren't
real great, but they are almost worth reading,'' he says of the
author of ``Murder at the Kennedy Center'' and ``Murder at the
Watergate''). He brought the first integrated choir to Constitution
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   As a kid, he sold Ladies' Home Journal and the Saturday Evening
Post for a penny. After high school, he spent nights wrapping bread
for $6.12 a week. Playing football at Pomona College in California,
he got his nose smashed by baseball's Jackie Robinson, who was then
playing football for UCLA. And during the Carter presidency, he
slept in Lincoln's bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were expecting our son Thomas, who is now a senior at Yale,
and I sat down wrote him a letter to be opened on his 21st
birthday, never thinking I'd live to see it,'' says Shaw,
describing the hand-written copy of the Gettysburg Address that
inspired him. ``That's proved to be true, and also I've had a
chance now to read that letter, and it's not nearly as beautiful as
I thought it was.'' At this point, he has broken into such laughter
that he can barely finish the thought. ``I was so moved by where I
was that I thought I was writing deathless prose, too.''
</P>
<P>
   He speaks affectionately of his late wife, Caroline, who died of
cancer in 1995. Alluding to his own mortality, he tells about an
incident at the concert the night before. A musician was
celebrating his 32nd birthday, and another one pipes up and says:
``You're just 50 years younger than Robert Shaw.'' It's an age
difference that time cannot change, Shaw says, and ``I hope it will
be 50 years for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   When Shaw speaks, it's like watching an old steam locomotive
start to crank up. His voice sputters, and slowly the machinery of
his mind begins to crawl, inching forward, releasing steam,
lurching, perhaps accidentally backing up a bit. Sometimes, he
comes to an abrupt halt before a sentence is finished, then spouts
a one-liner for comic effect. Losing himself in endless
digressions, he is nothing if not opinionated. He voices a disdain
for television, the ``mongrelization'' of the fine arts and the
decline of the great patrons. After every rage or mind-twisting
comment, he snorts: ``It's scary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no way of knowing what kind of people formed Bach's
congregation,'' he says, ``but it had to be a pretty healthy cross
mix of society, from the poor to the rich _ and the fact that those
people found both aesthetic beauty and food for their souls
represents a very high level of human intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   He puffs: ``Even gospel music has become commercialized to its
trashiest, its lowest common denominator. It isn't a really
first-class society. It isn't what I think the founding fathers
wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Gesturing to a television, he says: ``The kind of swill that
comes out of this tube over here _ from this morning on, from
California to Florida _ is just hash, if not having already passed
through somebody's digestive tract.''
</P>
<P>
   Quoting a speech he once heard when he was on the National
Council for the Arts, he says: ``Do you realize that when the great
cities of the world were built, 90 percent of the economically and
intellectually gifted gave 90 percent of their time to community
service? It's scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking toward Atlanta, he says he would like to be involved in
the creation of new work _ either with the ASO or some other
organization. ``We used to do more commissioning than I have any
responsibility for now,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   As for collaborating with another group to stage a new score by
a top composer, he says: ``That sort of a piece would be
extraordinary, and important, and in a certain sense what the arts
alliance started out to be. ... Given just a little bit of economic
support, you might be able to pull it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he thinks of Symphony Hall, he says, ``It's not in
the top 10 or 15 percent, but it's quite decent.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he adds: ``I was keenly disappointed, as a lot of others
were, when they got together some $21 to $23 million dollars to
recondition their lobby. That lobby was a beautiful space. ... It
was so vastly superior to our concert hall that I wished we could
give our concerts out there.''
</P>
<P>
   THE COMPOSITION OF ROBERT SHAW
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's antidote for the vagaries of the modern age has always
been the chorus. It is an emblem of the church, the community and
the equality of man.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chorus is egalitarian, the same way the Constitution is.
All men and women are created equal. Not absolutely equal in gifts
of talent or in gifts of mental acuity or agility but equal in
terms of enrichment of the human mind, and the realization that
together you can make something more beautiful than any one of you
could do standing up by yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Around dusk on this recent Sunday, he is driven to St. Alban's
Episcopal Church to begin rehearsing with the Choral Arts Society
of Washington for the festival finale this weekend. His assistant,
Nola Frink, accompanies him everywhere, handling the details so he
can focus on the music. ``I get the water ready so he can walk on
it,'' she jokes, unpacking the suitcase that contains his music,
baton and metronome.
</P>
<P>
   Choir director Norman Scribner warms up the ensemble with a
bunch of rapid-fire exercises, exhorting the group to sing from the
gut. The choir seems to be singing as loud as it can.
</P>
<P>
   Then Shaw gets up. He tells them to do the opposite. ``Shhhhh!
Shhhhh! Rest the voice!'' Then, it's his own chorus of one-liners:
</P>
<P>
   ``The right note at the wrong time is the wrong note!''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to hit the vowels a little sooner and the saliva a
little quicker!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Beethoven was a pianist, and not only that, he was a deaf
pianist!''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're singing the word zuchini!''
</P>
<P>
   During the break, chorister Marie Hyder appears with a record
that she made with Shaw at the Lincoln Center International Choral
Festival in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's nothing short of a national treasure,'' says the
47-year-old IBM employee. ``I guarantee if he looks at something
he's done 100 times, he'll find something new that he hadn't
thought of before. That kind of creative genuis always does. That's
what makes working for him such a treat. It's never the same
performance twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Page: ``He's the single most significant figure in the
history of American choral conducting. The technique he devised and
his passionate evangelism really put the discipline on the map.''
</P>
<P>
   At the rehearsal, Shaw carries on: ``You are riding on a bus
going to a voice lesson, and you don't want the person next to you
to know you are singing. Sing that loud!''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thinks he's revered more around the world than he is
home, Shaw says yes. But he doesn't hold it against anybody. ``If
you live in the southeastern United States and you grew up there a
generation ago, you were limited,'' he explains. ``You didn't hear
a symphony orchestra until you had graduated from college. ... The
great art of the South was literary.''
</P>
<P>
   So who are his favorite Southern authors?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know the Southern writers. They weren't around when I
was going to college.''
</P>
<P>
   The concerts
</P>
<P>
   -- IN WASHINGTON: 8:30 tonight (sold out) and Saturday. Robert
Shaw leads the National Symphony Orchestra in Beethoven's Choral
Fantasy and Symphony No. 9, with soprano Dominique Labelle,
mezzo-soprano Nannette Soles, tenor Richard Clement and
bass-baritone Nathan Berg. The Kennedy Center for the Performing
Arts, New Hampshire Avenue and Rock Creek Parkway. 1-800-444-1324.
</P>
<P>
   -- IN ATLANTA: 8 p.m. Oct. 29-31. Atlanta Symphony Orchestra and
Chorus: Dvorak's ``Stabat Mater,'' with soprano Christine Goerke,
mezzo-soprano Marietta Simpson, tenor Stanford Olsen and
bass-baritone Nathan Berg. Symphony Hall, 1280 Peachtree St. N.E.
For season tickets, 404-733-4800, single tickets, 404-733-5000.
Order online at http://www.atlantasymphony.org.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Shaw on:
</P>
<P>
   -- The Clinton brouhaha: ``Wouldn't I be a fool to say anything
for publication? The only self-respect you can earn is to say no
comment.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Conducting: ``None of the great disciplines of music are
conductible. They are playable. What one tries to do is create a
climate and a condition in which each person feels that his
contribution is important and the piece is important. It's got to
be common cause.''
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   -- Dining out: ``I enjoy Bone's (Restaurant in Atlanta) very
much. We find Nakato fun to go to now, and I love Japanese beer to
go with it.''
</P>
<P>
   _Wendell Brock, c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
