u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNN-TAILWIND-COX     09-17 0386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-TAILWIND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tailwind veterans sue CNN
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eleven Vietnam veterans connected to Operation Tailwind filed
suit Thursday in federal court in California against CNN and Time
magazine, seeking unspecified damages for their retracted stories
on Tailwind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report and companion article in Time ... were the
quintessence of journalism at its worst,'' the suit charged.
</P>
<P>
   It is the third lawsuit filed against CNN since its Operation
Tailwind report aired June 7, and the first by a group of veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm actually fairly oblivious to that,'' CNN/US President
Richard Kaplan said Thursday about the latest lawsuit. ``I'm sure
our lawyers are taking care of it. We've done everything we can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN originally charged in the first edition of its newsmagazine
``NewsStand'' that U.S. military forces used sarin nerve gas to
kill U.S. defectors in Laos in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   After protests from veterans and an in-house investigation, CNN
retracted the story, apologized to veterans and fired producers
April Oliver and Jack Smith, although CNN has never said the story
was wrong. Oliver also wrote a story for Time magazine, which was
retracted, as part of Time Warner's attempt to generate synergy
between CNN and its magazines.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs include the two pilots who dropped the gas, which
they maintain was tear gas rather than nerve gas; different pilots
who took the Tailwind participants to and from the Laos site; and
soldiers who were pictured or interviewed in the CNN story. They
are suing for libel, slander, invasion of privacy and intentional
infliction of emotional distress.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver, Smith and correspondent Peter Arnett are named in the
suit but are not listed as defendants; Oliver and Smith continue to
maintain the report was accurate.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was filed Thursday in California's Northern District by
attorneys Joseph Cotchett, Bruce L. Simon and Gwendolyn R. Giblin.
</P>
<P>
   Former Green Beret Sgt. Keith Plancich of Key West, Fla., whose
photos appeared in the report, filed suit in August for $100
million, and Maj. Gen. John Singlaub, who was quoted in the report,
filed suit Monday in Washington for $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
