A1184 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SURFER18-COX     09-17 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CNN giving the youth of America a chance to report
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CNN will launch a new program called its Student Bureau,
training high school and college students to report, and possibly
even air reports on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   The new idea, launched with Turner Learning, CNN parent company
Time Warner and several cable companies, will use CNN employees as
mentors, and provide video equipment to some schools and students.
Initially, the students' reports will air on ``CNN Newsroom,'' the
commercial-free 30-minute report that is provided free to schools.
They may also air on local cable operators' educational access
channels. Eventually, some reports might end up on CNN after they
are fact-checked, CNN Newsgroup chairman Tom Johnson said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, there's a lot of enligtened self-interest in
this,'' Johnson said. ``Hopefully, these high school and college
students will be helping us to develop more programming that will
be useful to them in the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner officials declined to put a price tag on the program. It
will start with 30 pilot schools, and expand up to about 200
schools by January.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Secretary of Education Richard Riley, at a press conference
at Time Warner headquarters in New York that was linked to the CNN
Center in Atlanta, called the Student Bureau program ``a clear
example of how a conscientous business can recongize education''
and ``enable students to get real-life learning experience.''
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   Times on T.V.
</P>
<P>
   t's a photo you don't see every day. There's Jerry Seinfeld _
tucked almost unneatly into bed and clad in an uncharacteristic
undershirt, cigarette dangling from his raised right hand. He's
smirking. And his bedmate is a TV with one rabbit ear bent, a
separate ciggie dangling from the tube's remote control.
</P>
<P>
   The photo is the cover of this Sunday's New York Times magazine,
which is devoted to television (Monday is the official start of the
1998-99 TV season). The headline: ``Now What?'' The articles
include Frank Rich's take on ``What the tube is for'' (it is,
perhaps, he writes, ``our one steady, loyal, reliable companion'')
and Bill Carter's reporting on how when NBC shelled out $13 million
per episode for ``ER,'' the network ``almost bought the farm.''
</P>
<P>
   Interspersed are some heady insights on TV from heady
individuals who name their favorite shows. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   -- Robert Pinsky, U.S. poet laureate, on ``The Simpsons'':
``Repeatedly, the show mocks and embraces its own genre. It even
mocks disruption itself.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Richard Ford, novelist, on ``Mister Rogers' Neighborhood'':
``Who doesn't long for a daily sampling of idyllic life, a little
good will, a little neighborhood of make-believe. Hey! Adult life?
I get plenty, thanks.''
</P>
<P>
   -- David Sedaris, author of ``Naked,'' on ``Cops'': ``It feels
wrong to watch 'Cops,' and that, in part, is why I love it so. It's
easy to look down on the car thieves and petty arsonists, but just
when I begin to feel superior, I think back on the fellow arrested
for breaking and entering. With his thinning hair and wandering
eye, he was my twin in both his appearance and his passion for
cheap canned beer.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Stanley Crouch, New York writer, on HBO's ``Oz'': ``To my
delight, it had a fully integrated cast, with a range of characters
who 'looked like America' and were conceived with impressively
realistic ethnic nuances, from the administrators all the way down
to the very lowest criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Ellen Gilchrist, author of ``Flights of Angels,'' on ``ER'':
``After I have kept myself awake, let us say, on a freezing cold
winter night in my glass-and-stone house. After I have wrapped
myself in blankets and am wearing my microfiber running suit for
pajamas. Half the time it's an episode I've already seen five
times. I don't care. I love 'ER.'''
</P>
<P>
   -- Daniel Menaker, author of ``The Treatment,'' on The Weather
Channel: ``The descriptions of Current Conditions always sound to
me like a poetry of American names. My Top 10 at the moment: Tulare
County, San Ysidro, Rapid City, Nogales, Onondaga, Lake
Pontchartrain, Mechanicsville, Flint, Helena and East Orange.''
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino, c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Simpsons on Sunday not spectacular
</P>
<P>
   Even great shows have their nights off, and the season premiere
of ``The Simpsons'' (8 p.m. Sunday on Fox (6339)) is definitely an
off episode.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, for the umpteenth time, Homer has one of his
mid-life, I'm-a-failure crises. This time out, he becomes obsessed
with Thomas Edison, determined to outdo him as an inventor. Along
the way he invents some cool stuff, such as hamburger earmuffs and
the makeup gun (``Try to keep your nostrils closed,'' he warns
Marge as he aims the blunderbuss at her face), but the show doesn't
have the zing that most ``Simpsons'' do.
</P>
<P>
   Look for a Heckle and Jeckle cameo, then look forward to seeing
if they've come up with anything funnier following ``The Simpsons''
on ``That '70s Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _Phil Kloer, c. 1998 Cox News Service
