</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAND-JURY-SECRECY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGAL EXPERTS ARGUE AGAINST RELEASING GRAND JURY MATERIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the House Judiciary Committee makes plans to
release President Clinton's videotaped grand jury testimony, some
legal experts complained Thursday that the traditional rules
governing grand jury secrecy are being trampled by partisan
politics.
</P>
<P>
   John Q. Barrett, a former associate independent counsel during
the Iran-Contra investigation, said the House should keep the grand
jury material secret until the any impeachment hearings begin.
</P>
<P>
   In such a case, the Judiciary Committee could release those
parts of the grand jury material that were relevant to the
proceedings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would help to keep the Congress from looking so partisan
and to protect innocent people,'' said Barrett, currently an
associate law professor at St. John's University.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that the House Judiciary Committee investigating
President Richard M. Nixon in 1974 held closed-door hearings and
that the voluminous findings of Watergate special prosecutor Leon
Jaworski have yet to be unsealed. The committee deliberated and
voted in public after the closed hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Under normal procedures required by federal court rules designed
to rigorously protect grand jury information from public
disclosure, the Clinton videotape and other evidence collected by
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr and the grand jury over seven
months would be kept secret.
</P>
<P>
   However, in July, Starr obtained a court order from the D.C.
Circuit Court of Appeals allowing him to turn over his grand jury
evidence to Congress. Since grand jury secrecy rules don't not
apply to Congress, the decision of whether to release any or all of
the documents was left to the members of the House.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, they voted 363-63 in favor of releasing the Starr
report. That vote also gave the House Judiciary Committee until
Sept. 28 to decide how much of the supplemental material _ which
includes Clinton's 4-hour, 12-minute videotaped grand jury
testimony _ to make public.
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders have argued that both House members and the public
have the right to examine all of the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a democracy, and this kind of proceeding must be
carried out in public,'' Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., said.
``Let the facts speak for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say the information released should give a fair and
balanced picture of the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not release evidence that is incriminating to the
president and hold back evidence that is exculpatory,'' said Rep.
Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., a member of the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But Julie O'Sullivan, a former federal prosecutor, said that by
releasing only portions of the grand jury evidence, the House was
attempting to paint a one-sided picture of the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most outrageous thing I've ever seen out of
Congress,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the House Judiciary Committee should only release the
grand jury material in a proceeding that would give lawyers for
Clinton a chance to present their side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm no fan of what the president did, but this goes beyond any
one person,'' O'Sullivan said. ``Congress is setting a precedent on
impeaching the president that is incredibly unfair and against the
very basics of our legal system.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY COULD END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under rule 6(e) of the Federal Rules of Criminal Procedure,
prosecutors, grand jurors and investigative staff are prohibited
from releasing grand jury material _ although witnesses and their
attorneys may freely reveal the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   David Cole, a law professor at Georgetown University, said the
rule was designed to stop ``out-of-control'' prosecutors who might
try to use grand juries to dig up information _ often times
unsubstantiated _ on people and then release it to the public. He
added that the rule also is designed to encourage witnesses to
testify truthfully, safe in the knowledge that what they say won't
be made public, unless they are later called as witnesses at a
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a quid pro quo,'' Cole said. ``The law forces citizens to
testify before a grand jury on the condition that our testimony
never sees the light of day if the case doesn't go to trial.''
</P>
</TEXT>
