<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART NOTES: HERMITAGE, SOTHEBY'S, ANDRE EMMERICH, GUGGENHEIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some Help For Hermitage
</P>
<P>
   The State Hermitage Museum in St. Petersburg, Russia, is so
beloved in the United States that a group called the American
Friends of the Hermitage is presenting the museum's director, Dr.
Mikhail Piotrovsky, with a $100,000 gift when he comes to New York
next week for the opening of ``Master Drawings from the Hermitage
and Pushkin Museums,'' at the Morgan Library.
</P>
<P>
   The gift will go toward the formation of a new decorative arts
department at the Hermitage, the first new department to be
established there since 1852. In it the Hermitage plans to display
its extraordinary collection of furniture, porcelains, costumes and
other decorative artifacts, which have been languishing in storage
for lack of exhibition space.
</P>
<P>
   But just how far can $100,000 go?
</P>
<P>
   ``We need millions,'' said Piotrovsky in a telephone interview.
``This is part of a larger project which we are calling `The Great
Hermitage.'''
</P>
<P>
   If the project proceeds as planned, the museum will expand
significantly, moving its precious collection of Impressionist and
post-Impressionist paintings, along with its sculpture, costumes,
arms and armor, jewelry and decorative arts collections, into what
is called the General Staff Building, a sprawling neo-classical
structure directly opposite the Winter Palace in Palace Square,
where the Hermitage is located. Piotrovsky said the project should
cost more than $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government owns the building and has agreed to give
it to the museum. And so the Hermitage is accepting proposals from
developers, becoming involved in feasibility studies and looking
for private support. A Russian bank that has survived the recent
financial crisis has promised to help, Piotrovsky said. He added
that he is planning to hold an architectural competition for the
renovation of the building.
</P>
<P>
   The director also envisions transforming the entire square,
including the General Staff Building, into an arts complex with
interactive displays, theater, cafes and shops.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to make this the center of cultural life here,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Piotrovsky admits that the museum's original building is
antiquated and not up to the highest standards in areas like
climate control. But he is determined to think beyond the immediate
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we just try to cover the holes, we will never move
forward,'' he said, adding that the museum also hopes to make
improvements in the Winter Palace. ``So far we have donations for a
new roof and improved lighting. But we have big visions. We are
working in all directions.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum plans to hold some temporary exhibitions in the new
building some time next year.
</P>
<P>
   Two for Sotheby's
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's has been on a roll recently.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week the auction house secured about $100 million
worth of Impressionist and modern art owned by the Reader's Digest
Association. The collection, which includes major paintings and
sculptures by Monet, Cezanne, Matisse, van Gogh, Modigliani and
Giacometti, and was amassed by the company's founders, Lila Acheson
Wallace and her husband DeWitt Wallace, will be sold Nov. 16.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the auction house has been chosen to sell modern
art from the collection of Mr. and Mrs. Morton Neumann. Mr.
Neumann, who died in 1985, was a Chicago industrialist who, with
his wife, Rose, began buying art in the late 1940s. Over the years,
they amassed works by Picasso, Miro, Dubuffet, Klee, Giacometti and
other artists.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980 the National Gallery of Art in Washington devoted an
entire exhibition to the Neumann collection, in the hopes of being
given some of the art. But when Mrs. Neumann died earlier this
year, the works went to the Neumann family, who chose to sell 27
pieces, estimated to bring in between $16 million and $23 million.
</P>
<P>
   The sale will be held as part of Sotheby' contemporary art sale
on Nov. 17.
</P>
<P>
   By far the star of the collection is a cubist Picasso, ``Nude''
(1909), which depicts the artist's mistress Fernande Olivier
wrapped in a cloth, and is expected to sell for $10 million to $15
million. It had been on loan to the National Gallery in Washington
for the last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Emmerich Is to Close
</P>
<P>
   When ``Kenneth Noland Circles'' closes at the Andre Emmerich
Gallery on Oct. 17, so will the 45-year-old gallery, at 41 E. 57th
Street in New York. Two years ago, Sotheby's bought the gallery and
made its staff Sotheby's employees, saying at the time that the
gallery would remain open under Emmerich's direction.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, when Sotheby's bought 50 percent of Deitch
Projects, the Soho gallery started by Jeffrey Deitch, Deitch was
put in charge of Sotheby's 20th-century art program, which included
overseeing the Andre Emmerich Gallery. (Emmerich was made a senior
adviser.) And now Sotheby's is closing the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an effort to consolidate our business operations we are
moving everything to Deitch Projects on Grand Street,'' said
Matthew Weigman, a spokesman for Sotheby's. ``Meanwhile we are
looking at possible spaces to hold exhibitions downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   Change at Guggenheim
</P>
<P>
   Peter B. Lewis, president and chief executive officer of
Progressive Corp., the Cleveland-based auto insurance company, has
been named chairman of the board of the Solomon R. Guggenheim
Foundation, which administers five Guggenheim museum sites
worldwide. Lewis, a foundation trustee since 1993, succeeds Peter
Lawson-Johnston, who will become the foundation's honorary
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   In April Lewis gave the Guggenheim a cash pledge of $50 million,
one of the largest cash gifts ever made to any visual arts
institution and the largest the Guggenheim, founded in 1937, has
ever received.
</P>
<P>
   ``This strengthens our leadership a lot and gives us a powerful
triumvirate,'' said Thomas Krens, the Guggenheim's director,
referring to Lewis, Lawson-Johnston and Ronald Perelman, the
foundation's president since 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
