<SLUG> BC-FBN-MATCHUPS-WEEK3-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL MATCHUPS: WEEK 3 
</HEADLINE>
   (Sunday, Sept. 20; Monday. Sept. 21)  
(jt) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; GAME OF THE WEEK: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Steelers (2-0) at Miami (2-0) Key Stats: Steelers have won last
five against AFC East; Dolphins lead series 8-7.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: Intriguing matchup because it pairs two of the best
coaches _ and staffs _ in football. The consumption of coffee has
shot up in both cities all this week as coaches stay up all night
trying to figure out how to stop two superstar quarterbacks in Dan
Marino and Kordell Stewart. That is key, but the edge in this game
goes to the Dolphins because they're at home and they have the
better running game. Karim Abdul-Jabbar has 183 yards rushing on 41
carries.
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins, 21-17
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUNDAY 1 P.M.GAMES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Lions (0-2) at Vikings (2-0) Key Stats: Detroit Coach Bobby Ross
is 3-0 against Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: That knocking sound you hear are the knees of
Detroit's rookie quarterback, Charlie Batch, who will get the start
over the beleaguered veteran, Scott Mitchell. Last week Mitchell
threw two killer interceptions that basically lost the game for the
Lions. Afterward, teammates ripped into Mitchell and that forced
Ross to make the change. But a rookie against a great Vikings pass
rush? This could be ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Vikings, 30-14
</P>
<P>
   Packers (2-0) at Cincinnati (1-1) Key Stats: Packers' first road
game this season; Bengals quarterback Neil O'Donnell has a rating
of 101.5.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: If the Packers are going to have a letdown, this will
be the week. Green Bay can't play much better than it has the first
two games: the Packers are the only NFC team not to throw an
interception, Favre is throwing the ball as well as he ever has and
Reggie White last week came back from the dead to have three sacks.
This game will be scary for the Pack, though, because O'Donnell
plays well in situations when there is little pressure on him. It
will be close but Favre will be the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Packers, 21-17
</P>
<P>
   Colts (0-2) at Jets (0-2) Key Stats: Bill Parcells is 53-25
all-time in the regular season at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: Parcells used to complain that O'Donnell didn't have
enough fire, but one thing O'Donnell did not do was constantly get
hurt. Glenn Foley is listed as questionable with a rib injury which
means his delicate body is rearing its ugly head again. Meanwhile,
the key to this game will be the Jets' defense, which will confuse
Peyton Manning so much he will think he's going against Florida. No
way Parcells loses to a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   Jets, 27-6
</P>
<P>
   Rams (0-2) at Bills (0-2) Key Stats: Rams quarterback Tony Banks
has 581 passing yards. Thurman Thomas and Andre Reed have 498
points each and could become the first Bills non-kickers to reach
500 career points.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: After his players nearly mutinied last week because
practices have been brutal and long, Coach Dick Vermeil relented,
saying practice would now end between 30 and 45 minutes earlier
than normal. How this entire scenario will affect the team, no one
knows. But Rams players will probably play hard because they want
to prove that easier practices make for fresher legs in games. The
Rams get an easy victory. Next week: Vermeil has the team make
running shoes for three cents an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Rams, 17-0
</P>
<P>
   Chargers (2-0) at Chiefs (1-1) Key Stats: Derrick Thomas has 6
sacks.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: When will the magic ride end for the Chargers'
first-year quarterback, Ryan Leaf? He is playing like Joe Montana,
not some rookie. But this will be Leaf's first dose of NFL reality.
Derrick Thomas and friends will batter Leaf like he has never been
hit before. Thomas is upset about being shut down by the Jaguars
last week so look for him to get at least two sacks.
</P>
<P>
   Chiefs, 35-17
</P>
<P>
   Oilers (1-1) at Patriots (1-1) Key Stats: New England linebacker
Chris Slade has 30.5 of his 39.5 sacks at Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: The Oilers just aren't talented enough to beat the
Patriots at home, where they have won 13 of the last 17 games.
Quarterback Drew Bledsoe is having a solid season, going 35 of 61
for 507 yards. He looks comfortable and his throws are sharp and
accurate. More importantly, running back Robert Edwards gives the
team a consistent running game.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots, 30-10
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUNDAY 4 P.M. GAMES: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ravens (1-1) at Jaguars (2-0) Key Stats: Ravens Coach Ted
Marchibroda is 0-4 against Jaguars Coach Tom Coughlin.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: Baltimore is for real this season. But just how good
the Ravens will be depends on what happens in Jacksonville this
week. If the Ravens can win, they'll look like a playoff team; a
loss doesn't mean they will not make postseason play but they need
to beat Jacksonville to get a jump start. These games have always
been close _ all four meetings have been decided by three points or
less. Because Baltimore quarterback Eric Zeier is good in the
fourth quarter, the Ravens will get the upset of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Ravens, 24-21
</P>
<P>
   Bears (0-2) at Buccaneers (0-2) Key Stats: Bears averaging 131
yards rushing a game.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: Tampa Bay has had the most ridiculous schedule of any
NFL team in years. Including preseason games, they have had seven
straight contests on the road. They finally come home to their new
home, the 65,000-seat Raymond James Stadium. So far, they have been
the most disappointing team in the league. They start their rebound
with a hard working but bad luck Bears team. Chicago will play hard
all year but because of poor drafting they lack talent and depth.
Unless Tampa Bay completely falls apart, they will win big.
</P>
<P>
   Buccaneers, 19-3
</P>
<P>
   Broncos (2-0) at Raiders (1-1) Key Stats: Bill Romanowski leads
the team with 2 sacks; Tim Brown has 13 catches; Terrell Davis has
266 yards rushing.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: The fact former Raiders coach Mike Shanahan and owner
Al Davis hate each other will have little bearing on this game
except that if Shanahan loses it he will be very, very upset. Watch
closely the health of John Elway, Denver's superstar quarterback,
who is playing with a sore hamstring. Those injuries often take up
to a month to fully heal and it could act up at any point during
the game. If he stays healthy, Denver wins a close one.
</P>
<P>
   Broncos, 24-17
</P>
<P>
   Redskins (0-2) at Seahawks (2-0) Key Stats: Warren Moon, 124.2
rating, first in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: The Redskins are in disarray and the Seahawks are
playing like the team many thought they would be last year. They
seek their first 3-0 start since 1986. Running back Ricky Watters
has 105 yards rushing, wide receiver Joey Galloway has 13 touchdown
catches in past 11 games and Seattle's defense has 7 takeaways,
tops in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Seahawks, 35-10
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY NIGHT GAME:
</P>
<P>
   Eagles (0-2) at Cardinals (0-2) Key Stats: Eagles have no
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: Ugly. Whichever quarterback makes the fewest mistakes
will win. That will probably be Jake Plummer for Arizona. He has
thrown nine touchdowns and just four interceptions in his last
three games at Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals, 14-13
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONDAY NIGHT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys (1-1) at Giants (1-1) Key Stats: Mike Strahan, Chad
Bratzke, 4 sacks each.
</P>
<P>
   Comments: When Troy Aikman went down last week with a broken
collarbone, the Cowboys' season went with him. Talk all you want
about how Jason Garrett is a solid backup, but he has no chance
against a Giants defense that loves to play the Cowboys and will be
pumped on Monday night. The Giants have won seven straight
divisional games at home.
</P>
<P>
   Giants, 21-14
</P>
<P>
