<P>
   &UR; BILL'S WORLD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Bill Tammeus, The Kansas City Star &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Old Farmer's Almanac,'' just out, predicts a bitterly cold
winter in the Midwest. We'll keep our copy handy in case we need it
for kindling.
</P>
<P>
   It's estimated that about 70.2 million Americans now have
Internet access. Maybe it's time to starting calling this the home
of the brave dot com.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the House committee that would conduct an
impeachment inquiry is Henry Hyde. Just for balance, maybe Mr.
Clinton should hire a lawyer named Seek.
</P>
<P>
   Despite promises of a nonpartisan approach to impeachment,
things already are divided. In fact, it's starting to sound like
imscreachment.
</P>
<P>
   We now know that Monica Lewinsky told 11 different people about
her affair with Mr. Clinton before it became public. This wasn't
kiss and tell. This was kiss and spam.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Clinton has asked some clergymen to help him fight
temptation. Maybe they'll suggest the religious benefits of
blindfolds.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Starr's investigation of the Lewinsky matter cost at least
$4.4 million, it's reported. Heck, that's no more than a dollar for
each time we've seen that video of Monica in a crowd hugging Bill.
</P>
<P>
   Aunt Ilse from Oelwein says the kind of people anxious to see
the video tape of Mr. Clinton's grand jury testimony probably also
own copies of O.J. Simpson's book, ``I Want to Tell You.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those considering a primary challenge to Al Gore is Bill
Bradley. He may rescue the Democrats in the Knick of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``One quarter of the world,'' says Mr. Clinton, ``is having
negative economic growth.'' Or, put another way, positive economic
shrinkage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to reinforce the safety net for farmers and
ranchers,'' Mr. Clinton says. And, he no doubt hopes, for
presidents.
</P>
<P>
   New polls show Americans want Mr. Clinton to stay in office but
be censured. How about this punishment? Release a transcript of
everything Hillary has said to him in the last month.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Campolo, a minister Mr. Clinton has asked for spiritual
help, has written a book called ``Is Jesus a Republican or a
Democrat?'' Good question for the president, who often seems
neither, but a Sindependent.
</P>
<P>
   Because scandal has hurt the president, is Alan Greenspan now
the most powerful person in America? We'd vote for Mark McGwire _
unless Greenspan, too, starts taking androstenedione.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel especially bad for the farmers,'' says Mr. Clinton,
``because it's been such a good time for the rest of the country.''
Like criminal lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't do something to help our farmers,'' Mr. Clinton
says, ``eventually all other Americans will feel it as well.'' For
instance, we all may have to listen to more sad country songs.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. House passed a resolution the other day praising Sammy
Sosa and Mark McGwire. Thank goodness for bold national leadership
on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   With her Senate primary loss in New York, Geraldine Ferraro's
political career is over. It took a long time. After all, it went
on the Fritz back in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   To give you an idea how amazing our office coed softball team's
9-0 record is, imagine Sammy Sosa or Mark McGwire hitting 70 home
runs _ this week.
</P>
<P>
   New figures show economic growth continues to slow. Aunt Ilse
from Oelwein says she wishes she could say the same of parts of
her.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DAVID-LETTERMAN ``LATE SHOW'' TOP TEN &LR;
