</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-CHAVEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAVEZ KEEPS THE FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ It is like it used to be for Julio Cesar Chavez. He
believes when no one else does.
</P>
<P>
   When Chavez first came out of the mountains around Culiacan,
Mexico, in 1980, few people knew who he was and fewer cared. He was
just the latest foot soldier in a long line of poor young Mexican
boys who would try to make their way in the world with their fists.
</P>
<P>
   But this boy would prove different. This boy whose professional
prizefighting career began at 16 would go from being Chavez to
becoming CHAVEZ! He would eventually win 101 fights and six world
titles in three weight classes and much more than that along the
way, because he would also win the hearts of Mexican fight fans
everywhere, rising to a position where he is today considered by
many the finest fighting machine Mexico ever produced.
</P>
<P>
   Yet all machines grow old. All machines wear out. All machines
ultimately come to a halt, and there are many who believe Chavez is
the latest in that long line, too: a nearly 36-year-old former
champion preparing for his final execution Friday night at the
sold-out Thomas and Mack Center.
</P>
<P>
   They believe Chavez is on the wrong end of a main event with
World Boxing Council welterweight champion Oscar De La Hoya, the
young Chicano superstar who two years ago stopped him in less than
four rounds, leaving him with a blood-smeared face and broken nose.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez had not looked good for nearly two years leading up to
that night, having already sustained his first loss to Frankie
Randall two years earlier, and things did not improve noticeably
thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Although he went on to win four of his next five matches after
the devastation by De La Hoya, Chavez barely managed a draw with
another former Mexican world champion, Miguel Angel Gonzalez, in
the fifth when they battled for the vacant WBC 140-pound
championship in March. None of those fights has led anyone to
believe that this one will end differently than the way De La Hoya
has predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows this is his last major event,'' De La Hoya said this
week. ``After this, it's over. There's no reason to respect him
outside the ring and there won't be any respect for him inside that
ring this time, either.''
</P>
<P>
   These are bold words spoken about a man De La Hoya once
idolized. Growing up in East Los Angeles, De La Hoya used to have a
poster of Chavez over his bed. Now there is no poster because, De
La Hoya would argue, there is no Chavez. There is only a shadow
left, a squat, 140-pound likeness that cannot do in the ring what
he once did.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez well knows that is what people think. He well knows he is
an 8-1 underdog at Vegas betting parlors because few believe he
still has the fire to train or the ability to slice up an opponent
the way he did as skillfully as a chef at Benihana's for so many
years.
</P>
<P>
   What they see instead is an old fighter who goes off to
Breckenridge, Colo., to train in secrecy for two months but
reportedly spends more time eating Haagen-Dazs ice cream bars than
doing roadwork.
</P>
<P>
   They see a fighter whose face has been cleared of all scar
tissue by plastic surgeons. But twice he had to be examined by a
surgeon before the Nevada State Athletic Commission would even
allow him to fight De La Hoya again because his face has sprung so
many leaks that he had worn makeup to hide the freshest cut before
their first fight.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when Chavez appears in a hotel room at Caesars Palace to
conduct an interview for a Mexican television station, it is as if
royalty has arrived. A buzz passes down the hall as he moves,
surrounded by a sea of bodyguards, sycophants, sons, and
hangers-on, and it continues even after he enters the room, greeted
by the television crew.
</P>
<P>
   There are kisses on the cheek for everyone, small talk and
jokes, and then he begins his interview and the real change in
Chavez's life becomes obvious.
</P>
<P>
   He is asked not about De La Hoya but rather about his tax
problems and his personal problems and his state of mind. He is
asked why he has performed so poorly in recent fights and why
anyone should believe he can win again. They are not questions fit
for royalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have my motivation,'' Chavez says of the fights since
the De La Hoya loss, fights in which he was cut several times and
looked uninspired in all of them. ``I had a lot of lawsuits and
people lying about me. But little by little, my problems have gone
and I'm strong again, mentally and physically.''
</P>
<P>
   His interviewer, a woman who seems charmed but unconvinced,
presses on, asking if recent problems such as his divorce and
seemingly endless tax struggle with a government that had him
arrested at the airport in Mexico City in June when he returned
from a fight have eased.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez smiles, but his eyes glower. He nods and says, ``Yes,
they have been made right. The one who screwed me up was my
accountants. Fortunately, that problem has been cleared up. That's
why I went to Colorado to train. Too many people were spreading
lies about me.''
</P>
<P>
   He claims that among those lies were newspaper reports of his
connections to what Chavez called the Mexican ``underground'' that
is battling the present regime and, in some cases, has been
portrayed as a gang of drug lords. He says he sued those newspapers
and won, but if he did, it seems news to the newscaster questioning
him.
</P>
<P>
   These questions and rumors have come as a shock to Chavez. It
was never like this when he was CHAVEZ! In those days, he partied
no harder than he does today and lived no differently. But back
then, he was the unbeatable champion, not a fading one, so all
things were different. Back then, he was CHAVEZ!
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not accustomed to all these rumors,'' Chavez says.
``They're trying to destroy my career. They talk too much. They
proved nothing against me.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon he is asked about being a 10-1 underdog, which he was when
betting on the fight opened, and he snaps, ``Two to one! It is 2-1
right now. That is the best you can get. But have them bet on Oscar
De La Hoya if they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``He isn't going in with a Chavez who is already cut. This is a
different Chavez. I'm very strong. I did much sparring for this
fight. I lifted weights and added some strength. No excuses for me
this time. I'm going to win the fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's conviction is obvious, but it is impossible not to
wonder if this is all just a game he is playing on himself. When he
arrived in Colorado with an entourage of 14 that included his
mother, his girlfriend, and two of his sons, he seemed like a man
trying to recapture the past for one last moment. There was an air
that this might be the last dance, so everyone close to him wanted
a piece of it.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a camp like De La Hoya's, who locks himself away in
his private cabin and training facility in Big Bear, Calif., before
each fight. While the young champion was there to focus on an old
fighter he says he has grown to hate, Chavez seemed to be in
Colorado in search of something no fighter can get back. He was
searching for the past.
</P>
<P>
   But where once it was the Golden Age for Julio Cesar Chavez, now
it is the Rust Age. He has grown old in a young man's sport, fat in
a svelte man's game, wealthy in a poor man's discipline. You don't
find many fighters in Beverly Hills and you don't find many
36-year-olds able to hold off their 25-year-old pursuers for long.
Not in a boxing ring, at least.
</P>
<P>
   But while the old lion may no longer have teeth, he still has
his pride, so he still can roar. That may do nothing for him here
when it is the crowd's turn to roar and the old lion's
responsibility to fight off the younger one, but it is all he has
today. So he roars loud and long, sounding as if he believes he is
still king of the jungle regardless of what the world may say and
write.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will break him up with punches,'' he says, punctuating his
words with a short hook to his inquisitor's ribs. ``I will use all
my experience but also all my youthfulness. This time his face will
not be clean when the fight ends. This time he will be scared like
a dog. This time he will see the warrior Chavez.''
</P>
<P>
   He spits out the words in rapid-fire succession, then smiles. It
is the smile of an assassin, the kind Pancho Villa used to wear
when he would ride out of the Mexican mountains to ambush
government soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   That is Julio Cesar Chavez's plan. He intends to ambush a young
champion who has no idea who the real Chavez is. His problem is
that he may no longer know who the real Chavez is, either, because
the CHAVEZ! of his memory is gone.
</P>
<P>
   Julio Cesar Chavez is the lion in winter, fighting to retain a
hold on what he no longer can control. Just three weeks ago, an
even older lion, Roberto Duran, tried the same thing in this same
town of broken dreams and was destroyed in four rounds by World
Boxing Association middleweight champion William Joppy, a fighter
of no particular skill.
</P>
<P>
   Joppy won that night because the real Roberto Duran existed only
in the old lion's mind. Now Julio Cesar Chavez will go into the
ring in the same circumstance. When he comes out, he will not be
CHAVEZ! anymore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
