<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1207 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HMO-SUITS-BOS &LR;      09-17 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMO-SUITS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLL SHOWS STRONG PREFERENCE FOR RIGHT TO SUE HMOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seven out of 10 voters favor an expanded right to sue health
maintenance organizations, according to a new poll from the Harvard
University School of Public Health that suggests evidence of
growing consumer outrage towards HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, sponsored by the Kaiser Family Foundation, shows
increasing public support for one of the most hotly debated
provisions of a comprehensive HMO package sponsored by Sen. Edward
M. Kennedy (D-Mass.) to boost patient protections.
</P>
<P>
   The HMO industry, which is protected by a 1974 federal law that
greatly narrows the rights of most patients to sue their managed
care plans, has argued that if the bill were adopted it would
unleash a torrent of litigation and jack up insurance premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Those arguments, however, are falling on deaf ears, said Robert
Blendon, chief author of the survey, which in August polled 1,200
adults nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are hearing the message, but they're not buying it,''
Blendon said.
</P>
<P>
   It is a dramatic turnaround for an amendment that once was so
controversial lawmakers had contemplated sacrificing it to push
through other HMO reforms. Last year, only 56 percent of
Republicans and 70 percent of Democrats supported an expanded right
to sue. That figure grew to 74 percent and 75 percent,
respectively, this year.
</P>
<P>
   Strong support of the provision is indicative of swelling public
ire over virtually all aspects of managed care. Those who felt HMOs
were doing a bad job grew to 42 percent this year versus 25 percent
in 1997. About one-third felt ``very worried'' that their health
plan was more interested in saving money than in providing them
with the best treatment if they were sick. Only 18 percent felt
that way a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Twice as many respondents _ about 37 percent _ said they based
their opinions on their own experiences than those who said they
relied on media coverage _ 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The managed care industry pointed out that the survey showed a
substantial drop in support if the changes result in increased
premiums. Public support for comprehensive legislation dropped to
40 percent from 78 percent when people are told it would raise
premiums by $200 a year for an average family.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are nervous about the government becoming too
involved,'' said John Murray, spokesman for the American
Association of Health Plans, an industry group in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also showed diminishing public patience with
politicians over the issue. Most people _ 66 percent of those
polled _ say politicians have been using the issue to gain
political advantage in an election year, while only 25 percent
believe politicians are making a serious attempt to protect
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, efforts to pass a comprehensive HMO reform
bill failed this year, despite unanimous votes in the House and
Senate for reform. Lawmakers, who did not vote on the issue until
the last weeks of the session, say they simply ran out of time.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton Thursday tried to respond to public concerns
by issuing a range of protections for about 15 million low-income
patients in Medicaid HMOs. The new rules include, among other
things, allowing patients with chronic or severe illnesses to go
directly to specialist physicians; giving patients expanded ability
to appeal insurance coverage denials; and, requiring HMOs to
provide more information on benefits and costs of using the plans.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, full debate on Sen. Kennedy's proposal was sidelined
Wednesday by senate Republicans. With just three weeks remaining in
the Senate session and Washington embroiled in the debate over
Clinton's affair with Monica Lewinski, some feel national HMO
reform is becoming less likely this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lewinski issue is drowning out everything else,'' said
Blendon. ``But our poll shows that this issue has legs for the next
session. It's going to be hard for politicians to come back to
voters two years from now and say they have done nothing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
