<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COHEN-READINESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COHEN SAYS US DEFENSE READINESS STRESSED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The defense secretary, William S. Cohen, cautioned
Thursday that US military readiness is ``fraying at the edges'' and
could ``turn into a tear'' without additional money for the
Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, speaking at a breakfast meeting of the Boston-area
Chamber of Commerce, said the armed forces have long grappled with
the problem of attracting and retaining capable and well-educated
recruits to operate increasingly sophisticated equipment and
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   And, joking that the business-people in his audience were
hurting the military's efforts, he said the nation's robust economy
makes it even more difficult to lure ``the best and the brightest''
into uniform because their job prospects are so good in the private
sector.
</P>
<P>
   The personnel issue is growing into a tough, persistent one for
the Pentagon. Cohen said, for instance, that the Navy will fall
short of its recruitment goals this year. And he said various
branches of the military already are taking money out of
procurement and putting it into readiness _ that is, taking steps
to upgrade compensation, medical benefits, educational
opportunities, and make other quality-of-life improvements designed
to keep troops happy and prepared for action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing some fraying at the edges,'' Cohen said Thursday,
adding that he did not think any alarm bells needed to sound yet.
``The danger is that the fraying will spread and turn into a
tear.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's comments represented a brief public airing of an
argument he and the Joint Chiefs of Staff have been making
privately to President Clinton: that the time has come to halt the
13-year decline in Pentagon budgets. News reports said military
leaders told Clinton this week that, unless some major programs or
overseas deployments are cut, their $250 billion budget may need an
extra $15 billion annually for several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to maintain that role,'' Cohen said of this
country's status as the world's sole superpower, ``are we willing
to pay the price for it?''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's avowed desire to stop pulling money from weapons
programs was welcome news for Dennis J. Picard, chairman and chief
executive officer of Raytheon Co., the nation's third-largest
defense contractor, based in Lexington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to hear that,'' Picard said. ``I think he'll work
hard to get a bigger budget this year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What they've been doing is taking money out of procurement
budgets, and that's what killed us,'' Picard said, referring to the
massive defense cutbacks that forced Ray-theon and other companies
to lay off thousands of workers in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Joann Muller of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 1834EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980917.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1228 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERSHWIN-CENTENNIAL-6     09-17 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERSHWIN-CENTENNIAL-6TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE IS ONE LONG JUBILEE: FAVORITE GERSHWIN RECORDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Was George Gershwin America's greatest composer? In the arts,
such questions are futile and ultimately unimportant. What can be
said, perhaps, is that Gershwin was the most  &UR; American &LR;  composer,
in the democracy and eclecticism of his idiom, and in the brash
energy and earthy imagination that boiled from his musical melting
pot of pop, blues, jazz and classics.
</P>
<P>
   He has been gone so long, dead at 38 in 1937, that it is hard to
believe he would only now be turning 100. Next Friday is the big
day, although many revelers have jumped the gun, as New York's
Carnegie Hall is to do on Wednesday, opening its season with a
Gershwin concert by the San Francisco Symphony Orchestra, conducted
by Michael Tilson Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone, it seems, is eager to celebrate, and few, so far, are
inclined to complain. But is there a danger? Gershwin did not
produce Mozartean or Schubertian reams of music in the time
allotted him, and most of what he wrote will be heard repeatedly in
the coming months. Can there be too much of this good thing?
</P>
<P>
   Not necessarily. The saving grace would seem to be the
tremendous variety of approaches that this music not only
withstands but also invites. To show the remarkable range, music
critics of The New York Times _ pop, jazz and classical _ have
compiled a list of their favorite recordings of Gershwiniana. Their
choices and comments are on page 4.
</P>
<P>
   As always with such lists, the term ``favorite'' should not be
taken to mean ``best.'' (See ``greatest,'' above.) But these are
all excellent recordings of fine and lively music. Who could ask
for anything more?
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES R. OESTREICH
</P>
<P>
   Here are some favorite George Gershwin recordings of the
classical music and pop and jazz critics of The Times. Compact
disks range in price from $10 to $17 for a single disk; $25 to $35
for a two-disk set; $48 for a three-disk package and $68 for a
four-disk collection.
</P>
<P>
   BERNARD HOLLAND:
</P>
<P>
   Naming one's favorite Gershwin performances is a bewildering
task. It's a little more straightforward with his written-out
classical pieces, especially the composer's surviving performances
of them, but the compact disks I have been listening to suggest
that the ``definitive Gershwin interpretation'' has changed from
day to day.
</P>
<P>
   Gershwin's songs, on the other hand, are both permanent artifact
and the vernacular's plaything. They hover between private property
and public domain, for each song has its own essence yet
collaborates with the singer or player.
</P>
<P>
   One comes best across a Gershwin song by riffling through
singers' albums by the hundreds: ``Someone to Watch Over Me'' in
Linda Ronstadt's cool, pure big-band version with Nelson Riddle
(``What's New'' for Asylum), so different from Jimmy Scott's
anguished, wavering tenor (on ``All the Way'' for AAD). Andre
Previn makes ``Isn't It a Pity?'' into brilliantly imaginative
pianism (``We Got Rhythm,'' Deutsche Grammophon). But to appreciate
Ira Gershwin's wonderful lyrics, skip to the singer Shirley Horn
(``Here's to Life,'' Verve).
</P>
<P>
   There is no better way to feel the tensions between Gershwin's
concert and popular music than to compare Helen Jepson's operatic
diction in ``Summertime'' from 1933 (``George Gershwin Plays
Gershwin'' on Magic Talent) with Leontyne Price's utter naturalness
many years later (Selections from ``Porgy and Bess'' on RCA Victor.
And there is no better way to hear Gershwin's posthumous symbiosis
with the jazz styles of the 1940s and '50s than to go through
Previn's daring, subtle and deeply felt piano versions for Deutsche
Grammophon.
</P>
<P>
   Vestiges of Gershwin's own performing styles pop up everywhere.
The Columbia Jazz Band and Michael Tilson Thomas accompany an old
piano roll of the composer's in the original version of ``Rhapsody
in Blue'' (``Classic Gershwin'' on Sony Music ). His playing,
frenetic and flighty here, is more measured in the 1927 radio
transcription with Paul Whiteman's concert orchestra (again on
Magic Talent). Archeology tells us that Gershwin played faster than
we tend to do, but I wonder if that is any reason for us to change.
</P>
<P>
   Stumped as to which recordings to single out, I went to the
record store and took a little pot luck. I am persuaded by Leonard
Bernstein's leisurely tempos in ``An American in Paris'' with the
New York Philharmonic (``The Bernstein Century'' for Sony) though
his similar approach in ``Rhapsody in Blue'' with the same players
seemed patient to a fault.
</P>
<P>
   My most dismal purchase was Oscar Levant's collection of piano
pieces recorded in the 1940s with various orchestras and conductors
(CBS). The playing is pushed, jagged and panting for breath, though
the inclusion of the wonderful ``I Got Rhythm'' Variations
compensates a bit.
</P>
<P>
   On the ``Classic Gershwin'' release, avoid Cleo Laine's phony
histrionics in ``Embraceable You'' and Jean-Pierre Rampal's silly
flute transcription of ``Liza.''
</P>
<P>
   JON PARELES:
</P>
<P>
   George Gershwin was a category scrambler: the composer who made
orchestras find blue notes, who spurred jazz composers to try
extended forms, who built an opera on African-American voices and
styles, and whose songs for Broadway and Hollywood musicals easily
escaped their original formats to become jazz standards.
</P>
<P>
   But his music hit a wall when rock arrived. It was identified
with the Tin Pan Alley style that rock set out to overthrow, and
with an adult sophistication that made rockers uncomfortable.
Maturing rock singers, like Linda Ronstadt and Sting, have turned
to standards in general and Gershwin in particular,
self-consciously imitating previous generations. But one Gershwin
song has been wholeheartedly taken up by rhythm-and-blues and rock:
``Summertime,'' the lullaby from ``Porgy and Bess.''
</P>
<P>
   It may not be Gershwin's best song _ no one has to make that
impossible choice _ but it turned out to be his most adaptable.
``Summertime'' suited rock's purposes with its relatively basic
harmony and for the way that, although it's not a 12-bar blues,
it's steeped in blues feeling. The song's built-in irony, the way
its optimistic lyrics are made wishful and uncertain by its minor
key, gives interpreters a pretext to play it sassy or sultry,
languid or filled with longing.
</P>
<P>
   Billie Holiday's version (on Columbia's ``Quintessential Billie
Holiday, Volume 2'') is a New Orleans-flavored stomp that has her
swaggering and growling. On Ella Fitzgerald and Louis Armstrong's
version of ``Porgy and Bess'' (Verve), she has a warm come-hither
tone while even his scat-singing seems tender and fatherly. John
Coltrane's version, on ``My Favorite Things'' (Rhino/Atlantic),
bends the song to his obsession, new at the time, with modal
scales, probing the harmonies with a breakneck solo that unites
be-bop, blues and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Rockers have carried the song to new extremes. Janis Joplin's
version with Big Brother and the Holding Company on ``Cheap
Thrills'' (Columbia) breaks through the band's shaky,
semi-classical arrangement with a voice of pure tragedy, unable to
believe any of the reassurance in the lyrics. Billy Stewart's
rhythm-and-blues hit version (on Chess) from 1966 has a nutty
exuberance, with stretched-out rolled S's and gospel leaps. Al
Green, on ``Green Is Blues'' (Hi), turns the song into a slow
seduction, squeezing out the notes for a long, steamy summer night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Summertime'' shows up twice on the new ``Red Hot and
Rhapsody'' (Antilles), a benefit album (for AIDS research) of
Gershwin interpretations by rock, hip-hop and jazz musicians.
Morcheeba, a trip-hop group, and the flutist Hubert Laws approach
the song in breathy slow motion, coyly making a switch: now mama's
rich and daddy's good-looking.
</P>
<P>
   And the soul singer Bobby Womack, collaborating with the backup
band from the Roots, rasps through ``Summertime'' as chattering
down-home funk. Both versions are a little gimmicky, but they're
signs that ``Summertime'' could last for many seasons more.
</P>
<P>
   PAUL GRIFFITHS:
</P>
<P>
   My favorite Gershwin record is no longer available. It was an
album of numbers by George and Ira Gershwin recorded in the early
1970s by a third member of the family, their sister, Frances. She
brought a refreshing simplicity to their songs. With just a piano
to accompany her, she made most other singers sound vulgar. She had
style, and she had grace. But there we go.
</P>
<P>
   Of what remains in the catalog, the Glyndebourne Festival
Opera's ``Porgy and Bess,'' recorded by EMI in 1989, is
outstanding. The recording was made after a run of performances in
the theater, and the sound is still hot with stage excitement. In
the title roles, Willard White and Cynthia Hamon are proud and
wonderful, and there are no weak members in the supporting cast.
Simon Rattle conducts the London Philharmonic with a rare balance
of aptitudes. He seems to love every detail in the score, which he
delivers as brilliantly as if it were by Ravel, but he can also
swing and swoon.
</P>
<P>
   Gershwin's other ``classical'' compositions are forgettable. I
would give ``An American in Paris,'' the Piano Concerto in F and
all the other orchestral pieces for just the three minutes of ``I
Got Rhythm'' _ especially as sung by Judy Garland in 1943 with
bewitching humor and confidence in her voice. Her recording is a
highlight of ``George Gershwin: 'S Wonderful: The Great Decca
Songbook,'' a fascinating and diverse collection of tracks from the
quarter-century after Gershwin's death, re-released on MCA for the
centenary of his birth.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the items here are cheerfully hideous (the Andrews
Sisters' ``Nice Work if You Can Get It'') and some have a sort of
camp appeal (``Embraceable You'' with Helen O'Connell and the Jimmy
Dorsey Orchestra), but some are marvelous: the Garland
contribution, Louis Armstrong's ``Love Walked In,'' Connee
Boswell's ``Soon,'' Peggy Lee's ``Somebody Loves Me,'' Jeri
Southern's ``Someone to Watch Over Me.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a similar mix of the ugly, the bad and the good on
``George Gershwin: The Ultimate Collection,'' a London compilation
of older recordings, most from the 1950s. Some of the same artists
are represented _ Ella Fitzgerald and Billie Holiday, whose ``They
Can't Take That Away From Me'' is cut with experience _ but there
are no direct overlaps.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from Holiday, other singers who excel here are Blossom
Dearie (``Someone to Watch Over Me'' in her faux-naif style), Nina
Simone (``I Loves You, Porgy'' done with a fabulous command of
microtonal slides), Anita O'Day (a smoky, joyous ``Who Cares?'')
and Dinah Washington (``I've Got a Crush on You''). This is a
two-disk album, but you can throw away the second, which features
orchestral pieces.
</P>
<P>
   The composer himself should also be heard. ``Gershwin Plays
Gershwin: The Piano Rolls,'' an Elektra Nonesuch release, offers
several of his piano rolls, realized by Artis Wodehouse on a Yamaha
Disklavier. Some early and unfamiliar songs are included, along
with ``Rhapsody in Blue,'' all proving that Gershwin's musicianship
was unaffected and dapper, not unlike his sister's.
</P>
<P>
   STEPHEN HOLDEN:
</P>
<P>
   Among the eight classic songbook albums Ella Fitzgerald recorded
for Verve in the 1950s and '60s, ``Ella Fitzgerald Sings the George
and Ira Gershwin Songbook,'' released in 1959, towers above the
rest, not only for its length (nearly three hours) but for its
perfect match of singer, songwriters and arranger (Nelson Riddle).
</P>
<P>
   The slightly impersonal quality of Ira Gershwin's lyrics matches
the singing style of a jazz-pop classicist who never overtly
personalized lyrics. Ms. Fitzgerald's readings of 53 Gershwin songs
are models of musical clarity, balance and emotional restraint; the
breathtaking beauty, warmth and naturalness of her singing infuses
the songs with a radiant optimism and sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   Riddle's arrangements fall into two types: elegantly
orchestrated ballads with a light swing pulse, and mid-tempo
big-band swing, sometimes embellished with strings. The readings of
``But Not for Me,'' ``The Man I Love,'' ``Love Walked In,''
``Embraceable You,'' ``They All Laughed,'' ``A Foggy Day'' and
``They Can't Take That Away From Me,'' among many others, are close
to definitive, with the meltingly wistful ``Embraceable You'' the
collection's exquisite peak.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as impressive is Sarah Vaughan's ``Gershwin Live!'' (Sony
Music ), recorded in 1982 with Michael Tilson Thomas conducting the
Los Angeles Philharmonic. The most operatic of jazz singers,
Vaughan curls her dark luscious contralto with its husky baritone
edges around songs from ``Porgy and Bess'' and gives the ``The Man
I Love'' a genre-bending treatment that begins with semi-operatic
wordless vocals and builds into a powerhouse scat solo. In her
playfully sexy, growling version of ``Do It Again,'' she lives up
to her nickname, ``Sassy.'' Marty Paich provided the semi-classical
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
