<HEADLINE>
COHEN SAYS US DEFENSE READINESS STRESSED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The defense secretary, William S. Cohen, cautioned
Thursday that US military readiness is ``fraying at the edges'' and
could ``turn into a tear'' without additional money for the
Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, speaking at a breakfast meeting of the Boston-area
Chamber of Commerce, said the armed forces have long grappled with
the problem of attracting and retaining capable and well-educated
recruits to operate increasingly sophisticated equipment and
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   And, joking that the business-people in his audience were
hurting the military's efforts, he said the nation's robust economy
makes it even more difficult to lure ``the best and the brightest''
into uniform because their job prospects are so good in the private
sector.
</P>
<P>
   The personnel issue is growing into a tough, persistent one for
the Pentagon. Cohen said, for instance, that the Navy will fall
short of its recruitment goals this year. And he said various
branches of the military already are taking money out of
procurement and putting it into readiness _ that is, taking steps
to upgrade compensation, medical benefits, educational
opportunities, and make other quality-of-life improvements designed
to keep troops happy and prepared for action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing some fraying at the edges,'' Cohen said Thursday,
adding that he did not think any alarm bells needed to sound yet.
``The danger is that the fraying will spread and turn into a
tear.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's comments represented a brief public airing of an
argument he and the Joint Chiefs of Staff have been making
privately to President Clinton: that the time has come to halt the
13-year decline in Pentagon budgets. News reports said military
leaders told Clinton this week that, unless some major programs or
overseas deployments are cut, their $250 billion budget may need an
extra $15 billion annually for several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to maintain that role,'' Cohen said of this
country's status as the world's sole superpower, ``are we willing
to pay the price for it?''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's avowed desire to stop pulling money from weapons
programs was welcome news for Dennis J. Picard, chairman and chief
executive officer of Raytheon Co., the nation's third-largest
defense contractor, based in Lexington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to hear that,'' Picard said. ``I think he'll work
hard to get a bigger budget this year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What they've been doing is taking money out of procurement
budgets, and that's what killed us,'' Picard said, referring to the
massive defense cutbacks that forced Ray-theon and other companies
to lay off thousands of workers in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Joann Muller of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 1837EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980917.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1235 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERSHWIN-CENTENNIAL-3     09-17 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERSHWIN-CENTENNIAL-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: semi-classical arrangements.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maureen McGovern's tasty album ``Naughty Baby: Maureen McGovern
Sings Gershwin'' (Sony Music ) was recorded before an audience in a
studio in 1988 with a first-rate jazz-pop quintet. Many familiar
standards are given careful but expressive readings that range in
style from straight pop (``How Long Has This Been Going On?'') to
jazzy coloratura (``Little Jazz Bird'') to the semi-operatic
(``Summertime''). The album's title song, a flirtatious gem, is a
little-known number from the obscure Gershwin show ``Primrose.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris Connor Sings the George Gershwin Almanac of Song''
(Rhino) is a far-ranging two-disk survey that includes 36 songs
recorded in the late 1950s and early '60s with six different,
mostly excellent small jazz groups. Ms. Connor's dreamy,
lost-in-a-fog style may not seem the ideal instrument to interpret
Gershwin's largely sunny music. But her cocktail languor has always
had a strong swinging undertow.
</P>
<P>
   The best anthology of Gershwin standards presented in their
original theatrical settings is ``George and Ira Gershwin:
Standards and Gems'' (Nonesuch/Roxbury), a just-released collection
of songs, many extracted from Nonesuch albums of five Gershwin
musicals (``Girl Crazy,'' ``Strike Up the Band,'' ``Lady, Be
Good!,'' ``Pardon My English'' and ``Oh, Kay!'') reconstructed with
their original orchestrations. In keeping with the period, the
tempos are faster and the spirit of the music perkier than on later
collections. The performances by Audra McDonald (``How Long Has
This Been Going On?''), Dawn Upshaw (``Someone to Watch Over Me'')
and Judy Blazer (``But Not for Me''), among others, are as
impeccable as they are effervescent.
</P>
<P>
   ALLAN KOZINN:
</P>
<P>
   Because Gershwin lived into the age of radio and recording, and
because he was an eloquent pianist, listeners curious to hear his
thoughts on his own music are in luck. ``Gershwin Performs
Gershwin'' (Musicmasters) includes two installments of NBC's 1934
``Music by Gershwin'' radio show and a 1932 appearance on Rudy
Vallee's ``Fleischmann Hour.''
</P>
<P>
   In these extraordinary period pieces _ even the commercials and
melodramatic opening announcements are preserved _ Gershwin offers
anecdotes about his songs, jokes with Vallee, plays several works
on the piano (including the ``Fascinating Rhythm'' and ``Liza''
Variations) and oversees orchestral performances of others.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the disk are revelatory rehearsal recordings of his
``Second Rhapsody'' (1931) and selections from ``Porgy and Bess''
(1935), with Gershwin conducting from the keyboard and, in the case
of ``Porgy,'' directing singers from the original cast. Both were
works in progress, and they were altered in small but noticeable
ways between these recordings and the final versions.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, there is surface noise from the original
transcription disks on these recordings, but one can also hear
Gershwin perform, more or less, in thoroughly modern digital sound.
Using his 1920s-vintage piano rolls and a computerized reproducing
piano that allows for greater subtlety than old-fashioned player
pianos, Artis Wodehouse has prepared several ``Gershwin Plays
Gershwin'' disks.
</P>
<P>
   The most compelling is the first volume (Nonesuch), which
includes solo piano arrangements of ``Rhapsody in Blue,'' ``An
American in Paris'' and an appealing selection of songs.
</P>
<P>
   There are several ``Porgy and Bess'' recordings to choose from,
but none is more compellingly sung and beautifully played than the
first complete version, released by Columbia in 1951 and just
reissued as part of Sony Classical's superb Heritage series. The
chemistry between Lawrence Winters' Porgy and Camilla Williams'
Bess is electrifying, and the other singers _ Inez Matthews as
Serena, June McMechen as Clara, Warren Coleman as a blustery Crown
and Avon Long as a wonderfully oily Sportin' Life _ offer vivid
characterizations that make Catfish Row come alive.
</P>
<P>
   The young American conductor and pianist Andrew Litton has
recorded several Gershwin disks and has a good sense of what makes
the orchestral works swing. On ``Dayful of Song'' (Delos), he leads
the Dallas Symphony Orchestra in several favorites _ ``Rhapsody in
Blue,'' ``An American in Paris,'' ``Cuban Overture'' and the
``Promenade'' _ as well as the graceful ``Lullaby,'' an early,
rarely heard piece. But the main attraction is the title track, a
12-minute suite of unknown but stylistically unmistakable songs
found among Gershwin's manuscripts in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Singers of every stripe have long been partial to Gershwin, yet
choosing a single song collection is surprisingly easy: ``Ella
Fitzgerald Sings the George and Ira Gershwin Songbook'' (Verve) is
incomparable.
</P>
<P>
   Recorded in 1959, this survey of Gershwin's best theater songs
has everything. Fitzgerald's voice is exquisitely silken and at its
most flexible, and her phrasing infallibly illuminates the
singularity of spirit captured in George's music and Ira's lyrics.
Nelson Riddle's lush arrangements support it all brilliantly.
Verve's packaging is worthy of its contents; in addition to the
original five-LP set, this version includes a disk's worth of
outtakes and variants, as well as copious notes and complete
discographical information.
</P>
<P>
   JAMES R. OESTREICH:
</P>
<P>
   As so often, first impressions are crucial. For a listener
immersed in jazz and just discovering classical music in young
adulthood, Gershwin came along at exactly the right time, in
Leonard Bernstein's late-'50s Columbia recording of ``Rhapsody in
Blue'' and ``An American in Paris'' with the New York Philharmonic.
</P>
<P>
   Although many slicker, hipper versions of both pieces have since
appeared, these performances, now in Sony Classical's ``Bernstein
Century'' series, still seem quintessentially right in the cocky
swagger imparted by pianist (also Bernstein), conductor and
orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``Porgy and Bess'' arrived by a less orthodox route, in the
exquisite jazz stylings of Oscar Peterson and his trio, from 1959
(Verve). Without need of voice or words, these players sing most
eloquently, starting with the great bassist Ray Brown in a supple
account of ``I Got Plenty o' Nuttin'.'' The 40 minutes of music
hardly filled an LP, let alone a CD, yet they offer a rich
experience of the opera in all its variety, with ``Strawberry
Woman'' and ``Here Come de Honey Man'' as inspired punctuation, and
surely no one could feel cheated after hearing such a magnificent
outpouring of spirit.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 1837EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980917.0301 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1237 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERSHWIN-CENTENNIAL-4     09-17 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERSHWIN-CENTENNIAL-4THTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: of spirit. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those two building blocks left many gaps, which have since been
largely filled in, never more fascinatingly than in a release of
the Gershwin memorial concert of September 1937 at the Hollywood
Bowl, as broadcast on CBS Radio (North American Classics; two CDs).
</P>
<P>
   The music here ranges from ``Swanee,'' in Al Jolson's inimitable
rendition, vividly recalled from a musically oblivious childhood,
with no awareness that it was Gershwin, to the Second Prelude, with
Otto Klemperer conducting the Los Angeles Philharmonic in his own
orchestral arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Here, too, is the Concerto in F, played by Oscar Levant and
conducted by Charles Previn, a cousin of the latter-day Gershwinite
Andre Previn; ``They Can't Take That Away From Me,'' tenuously but,
oh, so stylishly sung by Fred Astaire, and ``Rhapsody in Blue,''
played and conducted by Jose Iturbi. Hardly less compelling from
this historical distance are the spoken tributes by George Jessel,
Oscar Hammerstein 2d and others.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the quaint material to which William Bolcom and Joan
Morris have turned their hands and voice, Gershwin has not
invariably made for the best chemistry. Still, their CD of Gershwin
piano music and songs (Nonesuch) offers small charms aplenty along
with essential Bolcom and Morris classics: ``Someone to Watch Over
Me,'' ``The Man I Love'' and ``Love Is Here to Stay.''
</P>
<P>
   But here is a gap: Revisiting all these splendid recordings, I
realized with a start that I didn't have my favorite Gershwin
rendition on record, though it still plays on the grooves of the
brain, remembered from nights at the late, lamented Carnegie
Tavern. Undoubtedly, Ellis Larkins' `` 'S Wonderful'' exists on CD,
though a quick canvass of New York stores failed to turn it up.
</P>
<P>
   Larkins can be heard, more or less, with Ella Fitzgerald on
``Pure Ella'' (Decca), with its nine tracks of Gershwin. The purer
Larkins experience is available on ``Ellis Larkins at Maybeck''
(Concord Jazz), but with only one track of Gershwin, ``Oh, Lady, Be
Good!'' Back to the search.
</P>
<P>
   BEN RATLIFF:
</P>
<P>
   I'm avoiding some of the most obvious jazz versions of Gershwin,
not only because they've been so thoroughly analyzed and celebrated
(from Gunther Schuller's diagrammatic reading, in his book ``The
Swing Era,'' of Lester Young's ``Oh, Lady Be Good!'' solo to the
deep knowledge of the millions who own Ella Fitzgerald's Gershwin
songbook or the Miles Davis-Gil Evans treatment of ``Porgy and
Bess''), but also because I can barely hear them anymore, so cooled
and hardened are their meanings.
</P>
<P>
   All these recordings, however, seem to resist rigidification.
</P>
<P>
   Joao Gilberto's `` 'S Wonderful,'' from ``Amoroso'' (Warner
Brothers/WEA, 1977), is not jazz. But in a completely introverted
reading of an exultant lyric, surrounded by a string orchestra and
a samba rhythm that only exaggerates his impenetrable solitude, in
English that sounds as if he learned the words phonetically,
Gilberto made the most alarmingly romantic moment I can think of in
popular music.
</P>
<P>
   Also noteworthy is the recording by Ella Fitzgerald and Louis
Armstrong of ``They Can't Take That Away From Me,'' from ``Ella and
Louis'' (Verve/Polygram, 1956). The vast difference between their
voices, deep and froggy versus high and clear, as the lyrics
ping-pong back and forth, make the album, and everything else they
did together, weirdly fascinating. As a mismatched but somehow
just-right duo, they're almost too real, and they keep breaking
through the screen of show business glibness. Here, in particular,
they own the song; it remains touching on the thousandth listen,
and it's pop that's completely at ease with itself.
</P>
<P>
   Thelonious Monk's ``Nice Work If You Can Get It,'' from ``Genius
of Modern Music, Volume 1'' (Blue Note/Capitol, 1947), opens with
an aggressive, gapped snare-drum volley from Art Blakey; this
brilliant three-minute flash is a neat compromise from Monk, a
pianist who didn't bother much with other people's music. On the
theme, he respects the rhythmic shape of the original; on the solo
choruses, he hangs as loose as he ever did.
</P>
<P>
   Billie Holiday's ``I Loves You, Porgy'' (Decca, 1948, from
``Lady's Decca Years,'' Volume 2) is an intimate, chorusless
version of the song that boils down to one line, ``Don't let him
handle me with his hot hands.'' Try to listen to the shapely honk
of Holiday's voice singing those words without feeling fascination
and revulsion about those hands.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the title track from Sonny Rollins' 1962 album
``The Bridge'' (RCA). Of all the jazz tunes that borrowed the chord
changes from ``I Got Rhythm'' _ Rollins himself wrote ``Oleo,''
probably the most diabolical _ this one may be the most
unduplicable. With two-bar insertions that chop up the rhythm, and
both Rollins and the guitarist Jim Hall playing at a frenetic pace,
it's a weird exercise that hangs together.
</P>
<P>
   ANTHONY TOMMASINI:
</P>
<P>
   ``Porgy and Bess,'' though a subtle and sophisticated opera, has
always been claimed by nonoperatic singers. And rightly so, for its
music is imbued with the vernacular speech and soulful vitality of
the great American musical theater tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the recording that moves me the most is the classic 1963
account of highlights with a fine cast topped by Leontyne Price and
William Warfield (RCA Victor). The acclaimed 1953 revival of
``Porgy and Bess'' conducted by Alexander Smallens, who had
presided over its 1935 premiere, brought the young Ms. Price to
international attention, and her singing here is thrilling, earthy
and deeply moving.
</P>
<P>
   True, her less than clear diction does not do wonders for Ira
Gershwin's lyrics. But, ravished by her impassioned voice, you
won't care. Warfield is a compelling Porgy. And John W. Bubbles,
the vaudeville veteran who created the role of Sportin' Life,
repeats it here memorably.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
