<HEADER>
A1240 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERSHWIN-CENTENNIAL-5     09-17 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERSHWIN-CENTENNIAL-5THTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: here memorably.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the other hand, I can't do without the selections from the
opera recorded in 1958 by Ella Fitzgerald and Louis Armstrong, with
orchestrations by Russell Garcia, who conducts (``The Complete Ella
Fitzgerald and Louis Armstrong on Verve,'' three disks). Fitzgerald
may not be sufficiently operatic for some, but she is a sublime
vocalist and incomparable artist. And Armstrong, with his sandpaper
voice, very nearly outsings her, at least in terms of inflection,
swing and feeling.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991 Pearl Records released an invaluable two-disk set,
``George Gershwin Plays George Gershwin,'' which fortunately is
still available. Most noteworthy are two versions of the composer
as soloist in the ``Rhapsody in Blue'' with the Paul Whiteman
concert orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   The second version, from 1927, recorded electronically, offers
better acoustics than the first, from 1924. But the earlier version
better captures Gershwin's restless, vibrant and wonderfully
capricious playing.
</P>
<P>
   The collection also offers the composer in some fabulous solo
performances, and excerpts from ``Porgy'' with the great opera
singers Lawrence Tibbett and Helen Jepson. These pieces were
conducted by Smallens under Gershwin's supervision, and recorded in
1936 in the aftermath of the premiere. But my favorite tracks are
several songs with Fred and Adele Astaire from the 1920s. The
consensus on Fred Astaire as a singer holds that his urbane style
makes up for his limited voice. But the way the man bends a phrase,
puts a spin on words and colors his tone is great singing in my
book.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I recommend the conductor Michael Tilson Thomas' perky
and loving CBS recordings of the 1930s musicals ``Let 'Em Eat
Cake'' and ``Of Thee I Sing'' on two disks. The casts are
wonderful, with Maureen McGovern, Larry Kert, Jack Gilford and
other Broadway veterans. And the Orchestra of St. Luke's plays like
some zippy yet elegant pit band. ``Of Thee I Sing'' miraculously
manages to be at one joyous and cynical: a show about a
presidential candidate and his handlers who stir the public with a
campaign theme of love, something that ``everyone is interested
in'' but ``doesn't matter a damn.'' It eerily anticipates ``I feel
your pain.''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   UPCOMING GERSHWIN CENTENNIAL EVENTS IN NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   Here is a listing of events in New York City in celebration of
the 100th anniversary of the birth of George Gershwin:
</P>
<P>
   Friday
</P>
<P>
   ``THE MEMORY OF ALL THAT _ GERSHWIN ON BROADWAY AND IN
HOLLYWOOD,'' Algonquin Hotel, 59 W. 44th St., Manhattan. Featuring
Mary Cleere Haran, singer; Richard Rodney Bennett, pianist and
singer; Linc Milliman, bass player. 9 and 11 p.m. Through Oct. 10,
with performances Tuesdays through Thursdays at 9 p.m. and Fridays
and Saturdays at 9 and 11 p.m. Music charge, $35; minimum, $15.
Reservations: (212) 840-6800.
</P>
<P>
   ``GEORGE AND IRA GERSHWIN: NICE WORK IF YOU CAN GET IT,'' Rose
Museum, Carnegie Hall. An exhibition of manuscripts, letters,
photographs, recordings and documents chronicling the lives of the
brothers. Daily, except Wednesdays, 11 a.m. to 4:30 p.m., and
during concerts for ticket holders. Through Nov. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday
</P>
<P>
   ``CELEBRATING GERSHWIN'S 100TH,'' 92nd Street Y, at Lexington
Avenue. A walking tour in midtown Manhattan past sites notable in
Gershwin's career, including the former Aoelian Hall. 1 p.m. Fee,
$18. Reservations and meeting place: (212) 996-1100.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday
</P>
<P>
   ``OF THEE I SING _ GEORGE GERSHWIN AT 100,'' Park Restaurant,
Hotel Lombardy, 111 E. 56th St., Manhattan. Julie Wilson, with
William Roy, pianist. 9 and 11 p.m. Performances Tuesdays through
Saturdays at 9 and 11 p.m. Music charge, $25 Tuesdays through
Thursdays; $30 Fridays and Saturdays; $15 minimum for all shows.
Reservations: (212) 758-2272.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday
</P>
<P>
   ``GEORGE GERSHWIN AT 100,'' Carnegie Hall. Gala opening
featuring the San Francisco Symphony; Audra McDonald, soprano;
Brian Stokes Mitchell, baritone, and Frederica von Stade,
mezzo-soprano; Michael Tilson Thomas, conductor and pianist. An
all-Gershwin program with the overture to ``Of Thee I Sing,''
Second Rhapsody for Piano and Orchestra, ``Catfish Row'' Suite with
scenes from ``Porgy and Bess,'' ``An American in Paris'' and
selected songs. 7 p.m. Benefit tickets from $400 (includes
pre-concert reception) to $2,500 (includes post-concert dinner).
Other tickets range from $30 to $120. Information: (212) 247-7800.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 24
</P>
<P>
   ``FEINSTEIN SINGS GERSHWIN,'' Lincoln Center, Fountain Plaza. A
free concert with Michael Feinstein, pianist and singer, and a
50-piece orchestra. 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 26
</P>
<P>
   ``SALUTE TO GEORGE GERSHWIN,'' Manhattan. A walking tour of
locations associated with George and Ira Gershwin, including the
former Aeolian Hall, where ``Rhapsody in Blue'' was first
performed; the old Alvin Theater, where ``Strike Up the Band'' and
``Of Thee I Sing'' were played, and Carnegie Hall, site of the
world premiere of ``An American in Paris.'' Sept. 19 at 9 a.m. Fee,
$5. Sponsored by Adventure on a Shoestring. Information: (212)
265-2663.
</P>
<P>
   ``A BIRTHDAY TOAST TO GERSHWIN,'' Weill Recital Hall, 154 W.
57th St., Manhattan. New arrangements of Gershwin songs by the
Eaken Piano Trio, with narration by Dana Ivey. 2 p.m. Tickets, $25;
$15 for students and the elderly. Information: (212) 247-7800.
</P>
<P>
   ``GERSHWIN IN HOLLYWOOD,'' Turner Classic Movies. Daylong
screenings on the cable network of movies with Gershwin music,
beginning at 6 a.m. with ``Girl Crazy'' (1932).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL PUBLIC RADIO CELEBRATES GERSHWIN'S 100TH BIRTHDAY, a
24-hour broadcast beginning 12:01 a.m.that includes live
performances by the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra, the pianists Jon
Kimura Parker and Michael Feinstein, the U.S. Coast Guard Band and
others, as well as documentaries about the composer and other
recorded programming. Some of the programming can be heard on
WNYC-FM (93.9) as well as on New Jersey and Connecticut Public
Radio.
</P>
