<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEATER NOTES: `RENT'; JOHN GUARE; ROBERT SELLA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another Claim Upon `Rent'
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With last week's news that the estate of ``Rent''
author Jonathan Larson had reached an out-of-court settlement with
dramaturge Lynn Thomson over her claims of partial authorship of
the Broadway musical, the squabble that dogged the show seemed to
be over. But a forthcoming book may reopen the issue.
</P>
<P>
   In her book, ``Stagestruck: Theater, AIDS and the Marketing of
Gay America,'' Sarah Schulman, a novelist and playwright, contends
that ``Rent,'' based on Puccini's opera ``La Boheme,'' also
contains characters and scenes plagiarized from her 1990 novel,
``People in Trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the similarities she cites are a love triangle among a man
and two women, and an interracial gay couple in which one man dies
of AIDS. Ms. Schulman also says Larson lifted a pivotal moment in
the end of the musical's first act when a performance artist's song
precipitates a riot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically `Rent' had two plots: the straight half was from
Puccini, and the gay half was from me,'' Ms. Schulman writes.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Harris, a lawyer for the Larson family, said that Larson,
who died in 1996, had read Ms. Schulman's book and that there were
some ``minor similarities.'' But rejecting any suggestion of
plagiarism, he said the parallels were coincidental. ``She didn't
invent AIDS or gay people or triangular relationships or
protests,'' Harris said. ``She's just trying to sell her book.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schulman said in an interview that she considered legal
action several times but was afraid of professional repercussions.
She added that she was not publicizing her suspicions about
``Rent'' to make money but to show ``how AIDS is being represented
in the culture of America.''
</P>
<P>
   The book is to be published in October by Duke University Press.
</P>
<P>
   A Guare Trilogy
</P>
<P>
   Publicity agents and producers guard details of a theater
company's season like nuclear arms codes. But leave it to John
Guare to drop a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, when the Signature Theater Company, which devotes
each season to a single writer, officially welcomed Guare, this
year's playwright, he casually announced that his season would end
with three full-length plays known as the ``Lydie Breeze'' series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess John kind of made the announcement for us,'' said
James Houghton, the Signature's artistic director. He said the
troupe would stage the three plays _ including ``The Book of
Judith,'' just completed _ in repertory, starting March 18,
contingent on approval by Actors' Equity of a repertory contract.
</P>
<P>
   The plays tell the story of a young woman, Lydie Breeze, and a
group of idealistic friends, from the Civil War to the turn of the
century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim is crazy, wanting to do three plays,'' an excited Guare
said. ``But I love him for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Center Man Now
</P>
<P>
   Ask Robert Sella how he's feeling lately, and this is what he
says: ``I'm thrilled.'' A pause. ``Or is it terrified?'' He can be
forgiven for being a little confused. After all, in the course of
less than a week, Sella has gone from playing the sensitive
narrator in ``Side Man'' to portraying the raunchy M.C. in
``Cabaret.'' Gone are the high-tops; here come the combat boots.
Goodbye, black hair; hello, blond.
</P>
<P>
   It has not been a bump-free transition; his debut was delayed
for two days after several rehearsals had to be rescheduled. Then
there were the psychic adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really hit home the other day in rehearsal, when I finished
a song and was standing upstage left,'' he said. ``The
choreographer was like, `You're supposed to be dead center.' I
thought, `Wow.' I'd never think to stand dead center in `Side
Man.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sella, 36, said the thought of replacing Alan Cumming, who won a
Tony in the role and is taking a two-month leave, was daunting.
</P>
<P>
   But when he saw the understudy, Vance Avery, play the role on
Tuesday, he was reassured. ``They lapped him up like cream,'' Sella
said. ``They didn't want their money back.''
</P>
<P>
   By the Book
</P>
<P>
   As the season develops, it seems the nation's stages are going
to be filled by writers whose work is most commonly found on
bookshelves.
</P>
<P>
   The first is U.S. Poet Laureate Robert Pinsky, who has adapted
his acclaimed translation of Dante's ``Inferno'' for a two-week run
at the 92nd Street Y beginning Sept. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Next up is Reynolds Price, winner of the 1986 National Book
Critics Circle Award for his novel ``Kate Vaiden.'' In October, the
Mint Theater will present the New York premiere of his trilogy,
``New Music,'' about 40 years of a North Carolina family.
</P>
<P>
   In February, ``The Cider House Rules,'' Peter Parnell's
adaptation of John Irving's epic 1985 novel, will begin
performances at the Atlantic Theater Company. The six-hour piece,
currently at the Mark Taper Forum in Los Angeles, was conceived and
directed by Tom Hulce and Jane Jones. At the Atlantic, the play
will most likely be performed over two nights, said Neil Pepe, the
company's artistic director. ``Or maybe three,'' he said with a
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   In Cambridge, Mass., Don DeLillo's second play, ``Valparaiso,''
will open in January at American Repertory Theater. The work is
described as the story of a man who arrives in a strange land, only
to be besieged by requests for interviews. (DeLillo declined a
request for comment.)
</P>
<P>
   In April, the theater will stage ``Charlie in the House of
Rue,'' by the novelist Robert Coover.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Europe it used to be you couldn't be considered a
philosopher until you'd written a play,'' said Robert Brustein,
artistic director of American Repertory. ``Maybe Americans are just
catching up.''
</P>
<P>
   A Hot Ticket
</P>
<P>
   LaMama Annex, on East Fourth Street in the East Village, was
unveiled on Tuesday after a yearlong, $3 million renovation. The
opening came off in typical off-off-Broadway style: the paint was
still wet, the programs were still being folded, and the air
conditioning broke down a few hours before the start of the
premiere show, ``Kwaidan.'' But the audience didn't seem to mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gentlemen are invited to take off their jackets if they
please,'' said LaMama's founder, Ellen Stewart, sweating. ``Ladies,
too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
