<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1250 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     09-17 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The Times of new or
noteworthy movies and film series playing this weekend in New York
City. Ratings and running times are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE AVENGERS,'' starring Uma Thurman and Ralph Fiennes.
Directed by Jeremiah Chechik (PG, 100 minutes). Sometimes major
movie studios should be afraid to screen expensive fiascoes for the
press, but they go ahead anyway. ``The Avengers'' is Warner
Brothers' would-be blockbuster that actually had its light hidden
beneath a bushel until opening day, and no wonder. With
pseudo-suave repartee that would make Austin Powers blush and with
so many shades of ``Howard the Duck'' that one scene depicts
man-size pastel teddy bears sitting around a conference table, it's
a film to gall fans of the old television series and perplex anyone
else. I can't remember another Friday morning show where I heard
actual cries of ``Ugh!'' on the way out the door (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``BLADE,'' starring Wesley Snipes and Stephen Dorff. Directed by
Stephen Norrington (R, 120 minutes). Vampires are plotting to take
over the world, and the only person who can save the planet is a
vampiric half-human superhero named Blade. So much fake blood
drips, gushes, explodes and congeals in this hyperkinetic
science-fiction horror film adapted from a popular comic book that
there's barely a scene that isn't drenched in red. Snipes' Blade is
a low-rent Arnold Schwarzenegger imitation dressed in a ludicrous
mixture of black leather and what look like car seat belts. There's
lots of morphing and Hong Kong action movie-style acrobatics. Dorff
is the bratty leader of the young vampire rebels. The visuals are
garish, the acting wretched (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``DANCE WITH ME,'' starring Vanessa L. Williams, Chayanne and
Kris Kristofferson (PG, 126 minutes). A likable mess of a movie,
``Dance With Me'' wants to be the ``Saturday Night Fever'' of salsa
dancing, and in the smoldering-eyed young Puerto Rican star
Chayanne it has found a charismatic Latino answer to John Travolta.
But the story of an ambitious young Cuban who works in a Houston
dance studio run by a man who may or may not be his biological
father ( Kristofferson) meanders so much that the movie never
gathers dramatic momentum, and the dance sequences are hopelessly
choppy and poorly framed. Even a percolating Latin American score
and a winning performance by Ms. Williams as the object of
Chayanne's affection can't hold the pieces together (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``54,'' starring Ryan Phillippe, Salma Hayek, Neve Campbell and
Mike Myers. Directed by Mark Christopher (R, 89 minutes). Mark
Christopher's botched-up history of Studio 54, the notorious
late-'70s disco and celebrity hangout, should have been a depraved
Manhattan answer to ``Saturday Night Fever.'' Instead, it is a
juiceless mishmash that can't decide whether it's a nightclub
history, a comedy ( Myers' crude ``Saturday Night Live''-style
caricature of Steve Rubell) or a contemporary variation on the
fable of the prodigal son. Phillippe, playing a 19-year-old Jersey
City nobody who ascends from busboy to star bartender at the club,
does throw off an occasional spark. But the movie is so afraid to
confront the character's self-promoting bisexuality that he never
really comes alive (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``FIRELIGHT,'' starring Sophie Marceau and Stephen Dillane.
Written and directed by William Nicholson (R, 103 minutes). Stella
Dallas meets Jane Eyre in this high-toned Victorian-era
bodice-ripper about a beautiful Swiss governess (Ms. Marceau) who
is hired by a married English aristocrat to bear a child when his
wife is unable to conceive. Years later, she tracks him down and
becomes the governess to his spoiled young daughter, who doesn't
know that her teacher is also her biological mother. Using flash
cards, she tricks the intransigent little brat into learning to
read, among other good deeds. Ms. Marceau and Dillane strike
sparks, and the movie's canny mixture of sex and suds makes for
slick, low-grade ``Masterpiece Theater''-style entertainment
(Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``THE GOVERNESS,'' starring Minnie Driver and Tom Wilkinson.
Directed by Sandra Goldbacher (R, 114 minutes). It is the early
1840s, and Rosina (Ms. Driver), a headstrong young Sephardic Jewish
woman living in London, poses as a Gentile to get a job as a
governess for the Cavendish family on a remote Scottish island.
Falling in love with the skittish, devoutly Christian head of the
household (Tom Wilkinson), a gentleman inventor with whom she has a
stormy affair, she becomes his collaborator in the invention of
photography. The ravishingly handsome film works on several levels:
as a proto-feminist fable, a meditation on still photography and
its relation to real life, and a portrait of lovers whose religious
difference becomes an unbridgeable emotional gap. Ms. Driver holds
the picture with a solid performance that falls short of great
(Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``HOW STELLA GOT HER GROOVE BACK,'' starring Angela Bassett,
Taye Diggs and Whoopi Goldberg. Directed by Kevin Rodney Sullivan
(R, 99 minutes). This silly soft-core fantasy in which 40-year-old
Stella (Ms. Bassett) meets and falls in love with 20-year-old
Winston ( Diggs) while on vacation in Jamaica is part Caribbean
travel brochure (fly to Jamaica and meet the hunk of your dreams)
and part diluted Chippendales-in-the-Caribbean strip show floated
on a bathtub full of suds with some light comedy thrown in. Ms.
Bassett brings real fire to the role of a beautiful
divorced-with-one-son San Francisco stockbroker whose resistance to
romance is broken down in the tropics. But Diggs' nearly perfect
boyfriend is a vapid romance-novel fabrication. Ms. Goldberg
shamelessly stirs up the suds as Stella's raunchy best friend, who
is secretly dying of liver cancer (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``A MERRY WAR,'' starring Richard Grant and Helena Bonham
Carter. Directed by Robert Bierman (not rated, 101 minutes).
Skillfully adapted from George Orwell's satirical 1936 novel,
``Keep the Aspidistra Flying,'' the witty period piece, set in
1930s London, follows the descent into poverty of Gordon Comstock
(Grant), a successful London ad man who quits his copywriting job
to be a full-time poet. The subjects skewered include young artists
with delusions of grandeur and snobbish aristocrats with socialist
pretensions. Ms. Bonham Carter is Gordon's sweetheart who patiently
waits out a narcissistic seizure that Grant portrays with an
engaging comic buoyancy (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``NEXT STOP WONDERLAND,'' starring Hope Davis and Alan Gelfant.
Directed by Brad Anderson (R, 111 minutes). Will Erin (Ms. Davis),
an attractive, introspective night-shift nurse, and Alan (
Gelfant), a plumber and aspiring marine biologist who was obviously
meant for her, collide on the streets of Boston and live happily
ever after? The setup of this romantic comedy about dating in the
'90s may seem cliched, but the witty, beautifully acted and edited
film refreshes the genre with the acuteness of Anderson's
observations about people and middle-class urban life in general.
Ms. Davis creates a wonderfully complex portrait of an idealistic
introvert coping with loneliness, disappointment and pressures from
all sides, including (in the movie's funniest scenes) some ardently
self-centered suitors who answer a personal ad. A rich Brazilian
bossa-nova score gives the movie exactly the mood of bittersweet
longing (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``ROUNDERS,'' starring Matt Damon, Edward Norton, John Malkovich
and John Turturro. Directed by John Dahl (R, 120 minutes). Though
this tale of poker fever finally adds up to less than meets the
eye, what does meet the eye (and ear) is mischievously
entertaining. Inspired by Martin Scorsese's brand of irresistible
lowlife and aided by a splendid rogues' gallery of a cast, the
director of ``The Last Seduction'' takes his audience into a poker
demimonde of abundant color. As the actors make the most of
rascally roles ( Malkovich has a field day with a Russian accent),
the story leads to settings as varied as the Elks Hall in
Binghamton and a Russian Turkish bath. Dahl may not have new
thoughts on the gambler's life, but he makes this guided tour worth
the trip (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``SAVING PRIVATE RYAN,'' starring Tom Hanks, Matt Damon, Tom
Sizemore, Jeremy Davies and Edward Burns. Directed by Steven
Spielberg (R, 168 minutes). Spielberg's soberly magnificent new
film is the finest war movie of our time. Turning back the clock to
restore passion and meaning to the genre, he works in a spirit of
urgent communication to look at war as if it had not been looked at
before. Tour-de-force battle scenes are frank without
sensationalism, and the same great storyteller who made you believe
there was an extraterrestrial hiding in the closet has made this an
irresistibly vibrant, gripping tale. Hanks continues to astonish
with admirable modesty, and the rest of the casting is comparably
inspired. As he did with ``Schindler's List,'' Spielberg has made a
landmark film of devastating power (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``SNAKE EYES,'' starring Nicolas Cage and Gary Sinise. Directed
by Brian De Palma (R, 99 minutes). An assassination, a fixed
heavyweight boxing bout and a perfectly timed hurricane named
Jezebel collide apocalyptically one night in Atlantic City, where
hellfire rains over a hotel and casino appropriately called the
Millennium. Here is where Rick Santoro ( Cage), the sleazy police
detective in charge of security, discovers that his best friend (
Sinise) could also be his nemesis and he has to make hard moral
choices. This entertaining pop fable, which recalls the director's
``Blow Out,'' isn't believable for a second, but it has a pulpy
energy that keeps on chugging (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``THERE'S SOMETHING ABOUT MARY,'' starring Cameron Diaz, Ben
Stiller and Matt Dillon. Directed by Peter and Bobby Farrelly (R,
119 minutes). Sometimes Western civilization declines in
deliriously funny style. Hence this proudly obnoxious comedy is a
hoot in every sense, deserving a smidgen of disapproval and a whole
lot of helpless laughter. Set in motion by a prom, a crush and a
cruel, cruel zipper, this paean to low humor works ridiculously
well because it never stoops to being mean-spirited or (despite all
appearances) authentically inane. The principal cast is bright and
appealing, with Ms. Diaz at her most beautiful and blithe. Do note
that this film strives hard for something to offend everyone, and
that a tolerance for zit jokes is unfortunately required (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``WITHOUT LIMITS,'' starring Billy Crudup and Donald Sutherland.
Directed by Robert Towne (PG-13, 118 minutes). In telling the story
of the mercurial track star Steve Prefontaine, a screenwriter known
for enriching screenplays with unruly, unpredictable life creates a
surprisingly resonant portrait. Thanks to Crudup's charismatic
performance as a runner with the attitudes of a rock star, this can
be watched as one more sports film, complete with exciting race
sequences. But it's not truly about winning, losing or even playing
the game; instead, Towne considers the philosophical distance
between the brash Prefontaine and his formidable coach, Bill
Bowerman (expertly played by Sutherland). The film's wisdom lies in
its thoughtful way of balancing these two (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``YOUR FRIENDS AND NEIGHBORS,'' starring Jason Patric, Ben
Stiller, Aaron Eckhardt, Catherine Keener, Amy Brenneman and
Nastassja Kinski. Written and directed by Neil LaBute (R, 100
minutes). Three men obsessed with one another's sexual performance
are at the core of this second film from the director of ``In the
Company of Men.'' The new movie is so blunt at times, and so
unrelievedly talky and dark at others, that it cries out for the
velvet glove of ``Manhattan,'' a much more seductive film about
sexual opportunism and urbane cruelty. Yet even when LaBute's
material feels mannered or unremittingly sour, it sustains a
psychic ferocity that commands attention. The intricate web of
lies, failures and brutal revelations here is strong stuff, and
it's the work of an original filmmaker who takes no prisoners
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``CHINESE CINEMA 1933-1949.'' Cinematic rarities are in the
spotlight at the Walter Reade Theater, where the Film Society of
Lincoln Center is presenting a series devoted to Chinese films of
the 1930s and '40s. Although the country was engulfed in war during
much of that period, its filmmakers continued to create, but
domestic and international upheaval kept most of their work from
release abroad. This weekend, the series is highlighted by two
works by the naturalistic director Sun Yu. Saturday and Sunday
bring screenings of ``Volcano in the Blood'' (1932), about the lust
for revenge of a young man whose fiancee, a beautiful peasant, is
carried off to be the concubine of a local tyrant. Friday and
Saturday bring screenings of the director's ``Lights of 10,000
Homes'' (1949), about familial warfare in late '40s Shanghai. The
series continues through Sept. 25 at the Walter Reade, at Lincoln
Center. Tickets: $8.50; $5 for Film Society members and children
under 12; $4.50 for the elderly at weekday matinees. Information:
(212) 875-5600 (Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
