   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, Sept. 18. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Developments in Congress:
Abandoning any pretense bipartisanship, the House Judiciary
Committee is expected to vote to make public an edited version of
President Clinton's videotaped grand jury testimony and reams of
documents delivered by the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DAY _ The president's day: Clinton is helping raise
$200,000 for a congressional candidate in Ohio; later, a Boston
dinner is expected to bring the party $1 million. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-REPORT (Washington) _ After more than 15 months of work,
the Advisory Board on Race has produced a modest report whose major
recommendation is that President Clinton institutionalize efforts
to promote a dialogue on race by establishing a Presidential
council on race. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECON (Moscow) _ Russia's new Communist-influenced
government indicates that it plans to satisfy old debts and bail
out old friends by printing billions of new rubles, drawing a swift
and strong reaction from President Boris Yeltsin's old capitalist
allies. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-AIDS-ORPHANS (Lusaka, Zambia) _ The AIDS epidemic has
been raging here for nearly two decades, and as the deaths pile up
so do the number of orphaned children. By Suzanne Daley. A special
report of 2,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
