<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1267 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAYER-CHIRON-NYT &LR;      09-17 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAYER-CHIRON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAYER AG TO BUY PARTS OF CHIRON AND CROMPTON &AMP; KNOWLES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Mass.)   (bl)  
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Bayer AG, the German drug and chemical giant that has
been shedding assets to focus on life sciences, will buy the
American diagnostics business of Chiron Corp. and a 50 percent
stake in the farm seed subsidiary of Crompton &AMP; Knowles Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In an announcement Thursday, Bayer also said it would raise
fresh financial resources for reorganization by selling to the
public up to 75 percent of Agfa-Gevaert, its imaging unit. Analysts
said the sale, which was expected and is scheduled for some time in
next year's second quarter, could bring as much as $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Bayer, Germany's No. 2 chemical company after Hoechst AG, is
shedding chemical businesses to focus on more profitable
activities, including health care and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreements announced Thursday, Bayer will pay $1.1
billion in cash for Chiron Diagnostics, which had sales of $587
million in 1997. Rolf Classon, head of Bayer's diagnostics unit,
said the deal would give Bayer ``a global customer base, know-how
and additional research capacity.''
</P>
<P>
   To improve its position in the expanding agricultural seed
business, Bayer also announced it would take a 50 percent stake in
a joint venture with Gustafson Inc., in a cash transaction whose
value was not disclosed. Gustafson, based in Plano, Texas, is a
unit of Uniroyal Chemical Co., a subsidiary of Compton &AMP; Knowles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bayer is clearly driving its life sciences business at the
expense of chemicals,'' said Tony Cox, an analyst with Dresdner
Kleinwort Benson in London.
</P>
<P>
   Bayer needs the drive. Last month, the company reported that its
second-quarter profits fell an unexpected 13.9 percent, to $486
million, mainly because of reorganization charges and weaker sales
in embattled Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's steps reflect efforts by Bayer to reposition itself
in two increasingly competitive businesses, agriculture and
diagnostics, following in the footsteps of big European rivals like
Novartis and Roche Holding of Switzerland and Rhone-Poulenc of
France.
</P>
<P>
   These giants have been scrambling to consolidate the industry by
buying up smaller companies. Earlier this year, for instance,
Roche, the world's No. 1 maker of diagnostic kits, acquired
Boehringer-Mannheim of Germany, a maker of diagnostic products, in
a deal worth $7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Investors seemed pleased with Bayer's moves. Though the
Frankfurt DAX index slumped by nearly 5 percent, Bayer's share
price stood its ground at 65 marks, or $38.50. Shares of Chiron
rose 56.25 cents, to $17.4375, in Nasdaq trading. Crompton &AMP;
Knowles fell 81.25 cents, to $16.625, on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the potential for growth in the deal with
Gustafson was in the growing market for treating new genetically
engineered seed varieties to protect them against insects.
</P>
<P>
   Bayer, whose crop protection unit generated revenues last year
of $2.3 billion, boasts products like Imidacloprid, the No.
1-selling pesticide worldwide, which is used not only as an
insecticide spray but also to treat seeds before they go into the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   The joint venture, which will be built on Gustafson's existing
operations, will enable Bayer to market products in the United
States, Mexico and Canada, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the acquisition of Chiron, which is based in
Walpole, Mass., would help give Bayer the critical mass it needs
for its diagnostics business by bolstering sales of its diagnostics
products worldwide to about $2 billion next year. Michael Stone, an
analyst at Credit Suisse First Boston in London, said that would
give Bayer about 10 percent of the $19-billion-a-year market for
diagnostic equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Bayer and Chiron fit well, he said. While Chiron is strong in
immunal testing and systems to detect hepatitis C and the human
immunodeficiency virus, or HIV, Bayer excels in tests of urine for
conditions like diabetes. Geographically, Chiron focuses on the
United States, Britain and Japan, while Bayer is strongest in
Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   By divesting itself of Agfa, Bayer evidently hopes to give the
unit the mobility it needs to reinvest its profits and raise cash.
</P>
<P>
   Manfred Schneider, Bayer's chief executive, said Agfa would
obtain ``entrepreneurial independence and new financing options.''
In return, he said, Bayer will get ``greater room to maneuver, and
more resources to strengthen core businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Agfa is a market leader in commercial imaging and businesses
like graphic arts and medical imaging, which are becoming
increasingly competitive thanks to the development of digital and
chemical-free ways of printing images.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
