<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-ELECT-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSNIAN SERBS, UNHAPPY IN SERB REPUBLIC, FEAR RETURN TO BOSNIA  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE O'CONNOR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VOJKOVICI, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ Not knowing what else to do, the
elderly Bosnian Serb widow just sat down on a rock beside a green
stagnant pool, in the middle of a field less than a mile from the
home that once was hers.
</P>
<P>
   Radojka Jovo, 71, frantically reviewed the red folder of
documents she had carried, along with a loaf of bread and about $4,
on the five-hour bus ride across the Bosnian Serb Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am desperate,'' she said. ``I hope these papers are enough
proof the home is mine. They say there is no money to pay my
pension. All I have is my home, over there.'' Her feet planted in
the part of Bosnia where the Serbian authorities now govern, her
hand pointed across the boundary to Muslim territory.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jovo, a refugee, made the trip home Thursday, but did not
try to reclaim her home. It was fear that stopped her.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what if I go there and the Muslims kill me?'' she said,
voicing the unfounded fear expressed by many Bosnian Serbs. ``So I
am here because there is no where else.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jovo, her hands trembling as she held up her eyeglasses to
look, once again, at the documents, seemed to be in the same
position as many of her fellow Bosnian Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Deeply afraid of what could happen if they made serious efforts
to rejoin Bosnia, the country torn apart principally by their
leaders, the Bosnian Serbs are stuck with the Bosnian Serb
Republic, a desperately poor semi-autonomous statelet that Western
diplomats say has been run by incompetent and crooked officials.
</P>
<P>
   Voters have just elected a president who represents some of the
most extreme nationalist and corrupt forces at play here, according
to Western officials, who had supported a more moderate incumbent
by starting many aid projects and promising many more.
</P>
<P>
   The election results, still unofficial, stunned Western
diplomats, some of whom say the results show a profound failure of
their strategy to pull Bosnian Serbs away from their most
nationalistic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Jovo, who says she cannot survive in the Bosnian Serb
Republic but is too afraid to go to the other half of the country,
may have an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Serbs only have each other _ no one else cares,'' she said.
``And for Serbs, the Serb Republic is the only thing that will
protect us. It is more important that our leaders are strong than
that they are honest or good.''
</P>
<P>
   Though many Bosnians _ Serbs, Muslims, and Croats _ had begun to
move sharply away from the distrust and hate of the 1992-95 war,
the national elections last weekend seemed to revive the old,
deeply held fears among many of Bosnia's Serbs. And the most
nationalistic politicians played right to those fears.
</P>
<P>
   Nikola Poplasen, the man who seems to have defeated the West's
candidate, Biljana Plavsic, told voters that he would insure that
the Bosnian Serb Republic stayed strong and independent of both
Muslim influence and Western manipulation.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Radoslav Skrba, in his front yard where he keeps a
cow, chickens and pigs in order to eat, said the prospect of
continued poverty was not enough to make Serbs bow to the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``The West doesn't like us so much, not the Serb people,''
Skrba, 45, said. ``They support the Muslims, and they wouldn't care
at all what happened to us except they think this is a good place
for their companies to put up factories.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How is it that all these Western armies now have bases here?''
Skrba asked, referring to the bases of the NATO-led peace force
that helped stop the war. ``Could it be that it was their strategy
all along?''
</P>
<P>
   ``During the Communist time we were warned that the West wanted
to come here and now here they are,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Skrba, and his neighbors, thought that Western support of
President Plavsic failed because her indebtedness to the West for
its financial help was obvious and raised suspicions, but the
benefits were not evident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it got better for the people around Banja Luka,'' Slavko
Gavric said, referring to the city Mrs. Plavsic made her capital.
``But we didn't see any improvement here.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Muslims and Croats in Bosnia were pleased when Mrs.
Plavsic's government, which took office last year, was much more
cooperative in efforts to reduce the divisions between the Serbian
part of the country and the other half, known as the Muslim-Croat
Federation.
</P>
<P>
   When Muslims and Croats could drive through the Serbian part
with little fear of police harassment, or visit their former
neighbors in towns from which they had been expelled, they felt
their old country coming back a bit. It made them feel less afraid
of the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   But nationalist politicians told the Serbs that the small breaks
in the barrier around the Serbian Republic were signs of weakness
and steps toward Muslim domination.
</P>
<P>
   It worried even moderates in this village, like Gavric. ``I
don't hate Muslims, not the people,'' he said. ``I would have to
say for most of my life they were my people because we lived
together. But their government is radical and extreme, and I am a
Serb. That's enough for me to be in danger if they have power over
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Serbs think that if Mrs. Plavsic had been re-elected, the
West would have forced her to allow several hundred thousand Muslim
and Croat refugees to return to their homes. That would have meant
a crisis for Serbs who are now living in the refugees' homes and
who are afraid to return to their own homes in the other half of
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Western diplomats calculated that most Bosnian Serbs
would reject their hard-core leaders and take the gamble that
moderation and cooperation with the West would be the best
guarantee for their future.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the two cafes here, Zoran Askraba, 30, a professional
musician, was making that same point to Dragan Stankovic, a
government worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have gotten money and had a hope,'' Askraba said
angrily. ``I can't accept the fact that my country has to be run by
criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   Stankovic replied: ``Look, I don't care. The SDS created the
Serb Republic.'' He referring to the original hard-line Bosnian
Serb party, now considered to the power behind the likely new
president, Poplasen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average man believes we can't take a chance on living with
the Muslims because we would be too unprotected,'' he continued.
``The SDS will protect the Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
   Askraba retorted: ``You are a Serb, and they are not protecting
you. You haven't been paid for five months.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 1902EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980917.0317 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1283 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ECON-345&AMP;ADD-N     09-17 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECON-345&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S NEW GOVERNMENT TO PRINT RUBLES TO PAY DEBTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's new Communist-influenced government indicated
Thursday that it plans to satisfy old debts and bail out old
friends by printing billions of new rubles, a decision that drew a
swift and strong reaction from President Boris Yeltsin's capitalist
allies.
</P>
<P>
   The deputy head of the central bank said Thursday that the bank
intends to bail out many of the nation's bankrupt financial
institutions by buying back their multibillion-ruble portfolios of
government bonds and Treasury bills. The government temporarily
froze $40 billion worth of notes when the fiscal crisis erupted
last month because it lacked the money to pay investors who hold
them.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by Reuters how the near-broke government would find the
money to pay off the banks, the deputy, Andrei Kozlov, replied:
``Emissions, of course, emissions.'' ``Emissions'' is a euphemism
for printing money.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later in Washington, Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence
Summers told a House subcommittee that Russia was heading toward a
return of the four-digit inflation rates that savaged consumers and
almost toppled Yeltsin's government in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's new leaders cannot repeal ``basic economic laws,'' he
said. ``They must resist pressures to spend and lend which will
doom the economy to another bout of high, perhaps hyperinflation.
Just as important, they need to take on the failings of the
financial system and finally put in place the core institutions and
policies of a private market economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most pointedly, Summers spoke out against what he said
was pervasive corruption that was hobbling not just the economic
system, but the evolution of democracy. It is up to Russia, he
said, to show that its fiscal policies will affect the lives of
ordinary people, and ``not just enrich offshore bank accounts.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's actions, against the backdrop of continued jockeying
between Communists and capitalists in the new government, suggested
that actions favored by Summers and other free-market economists
are increasingly a longshot.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Summers also said it was unlikely that the $4.3 billion second
tranche of an International Monetary Fund bailout package for
Russia would be paid as planned.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the dire warnings of Summers and Russian
reformers, however, a team of West European ministers in Moscow on
Thursday said that the West should wait before passing judgment on
Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov's economic intentions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the impression that the Russian government has
absolutely no intention to engage the reverse gear in any shape or
form,'' said Germany's Foreign Minister, Klaus Kinkel, at a news
conference with Austrian and British officials.
</P>
<P>
   Kinkel said Primakov fears, ``not entirely without grounds,''
that failure to deal with social spending could lead to a political
explosion here.
</P>
<P>
   Austrian Foreign Minister Wolfgang Schuessel also advised
caution. ``Give them a chance,'' he said. ``I have the impression
there is a readiness on their side to act.''
</P>
<P>
   The central bank's proposed bailout would offer a special deal
to bankers, including the so-called oligarchs who frequently built
vast financial empires around banks that have since fallen on hard
times.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, banks would move to the front of a long line of
domestic and foreign investors who bought government bonds only to
see their prices collapse when the crisis struck.
</P>
<P>
   Western experts generally argue that the major beneficiaries of
such a bailout would be financiers, not the economy, since almost
none of Russia's banks have built the extensive networks of
checking, savings and consumer lending services that are a building
block of western trade. Instead, most have plowed their money into
buying industries or speculative investments.
</P>
<P>
   The central bank's statement was not the only suggestion
Thursday that Russia's government is about to embark on a serious
spending program. Yeltsin told his defense advisers to prepare to
pay soldiers and other military workers half of the 16 billion
rubles in back wages that they are owed. At today's exchange rates,
that totals about $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the reformers whose hopes for free-market capitalism
here collapsed with the August fiscal crisis were acid in their
criticism of the new government Thursday. Boris Nemtsov, a deputy
prime minister until recently, greeted the apparent turn in fiscal
policy with sarcasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``To print a lot of money, that's the first message,'' he said.
``To print money, that's the second message, and to print money,
that's the third message,'' he told Reuters Television.
</P>
<P>
   And in Moscow, the head of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce in
Russia said American companies already have lost a half billion
dollars during this crisis _ and are heading for the exits because
they do not like the look of the new financial scene. The same
tensions over the fiscal policy of the new communist-capitalist
government hobbled efforts Thursday to fill out the last positions
in Yeltsin's new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin said he may miss the legal deadline of Friday for
finishing selection of his new cabinet because he needs more time
to choose a finance minister. Acting Finance Minister Mikhail
Zadornov was a leader among the free-market advocates in the last
cabinet whose push for full-fledged capitalism broke down with this
autumn's financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Few believe that Primakov will keep Zadornov in the government,
and there were fresh indications Thursday that Primakov's men may
nudge other reformers out as well.
</P>
<P>
   The new deputy prime minister, Alexander Shokhin, repeated his
statement of Tuesday that Boris Fyodorov, another key reformer who
was a deputy prime minister and head of the state tax service, had
quit. Fyodorov, who developed a reputation for pugnacity as tax
collector, was quiet after Tuesday's announcement. But Thursday he
dispatched an aide to effectively dare Primakov to fire him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have strong nerves and will not resign,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If he does go, it will be viewed by many as an indication that
the new government is moving further from western-style economic
policies that encourage competition and fiscal restraint and toward
communist tenets such as state control of industry and greater
spending on welfare, even at the cost of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The flip side of those concerns, however, is that failure to
spend money on such pressing demands as back wages for soldiers
will only increase the already mounting prospects for a social or
political upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   One of the major reasons Russians have diminishing confidence in
their government is that it has failed to provide basic services
such as pensions, welfare and wages to state employees. At least
some of those payments have gone by the wayside because Yeltsin's
last two governments, committed to keeping inflation low, have
refused to print money to pay for services the government could not
otherwise afford.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist Party is organizing what it promises will be a
peaceful mass protest against the Yeltsin government for Oct. 7.
But its leaders have said they cannot keep a lid on popular anger
if the government does not begin to respond to citizens' demands.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Yeltsin ordered his interior ministry to make
preparations to keep public order during the protest and to prevent
certain types of actions, such as blockades of railways, that could
disrupt the economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
