<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS-ASSESS (Washington) _ It is not just the
Clinton presidency that hangs in the balance in these fevered
Washington days. Before the eyes of the nation, Congress itself is
on trial. Even in normal times Congress can seem a maddening
institution, but the task now before it is extraordinary. Could the
founders have ever have pondered what a national inquest might turn
into in this new age of round the clock cable talk shows and the
Internet? Could they have foreseen that the House and Senate would
be exmaining the most private, intimate actions of a public man?
These are the uncomfortable circumstances that Congress now has to
deal with in an atmosphere made more poisonous and hysterical by
the suddent realization that the private life of anyone in the
House and Senate rapidly seems to have become fair game in the
press. A news analysis by Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-EDITORIALS (Undated) _ Dozens of American newspapers
have called for Clinton's resignation even though most people still
say he should remain in office. We look behind the editorials to
the internal debates and responses to editorials. By Felicity
Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   Moving by  &UR; 8:30 pm. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BOSTON (Boston) _ Clinton arrives in Boston and finds
more criticism. By Michael Janofsky. (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-RELEASE (Undated) _ While most Americans approve of the
way Congress is performing its job overall, the public disagrees
with the recent decision to release all of the independent
counsel's report, according to the latest New York Times/CBS News
poll. The sexual details in Starr's report are seen by most of the
public as ``inappropriate,'' information designed to embarrass
President Clinton. There is even less support for the possible
release of Clinton's videotaped grand jury testimony. Seventy
percent of all Americans polled Tuesday night by CBS News disagreed
with the release of the grand jury testimony. By Marjorie Connelly.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GINGRICH (Washington) _ House Speaker Newt Gingrich has
tried all week to portray himself as the impartial observer waiting
for his lawyers on the Judiciary Committee to sort out the facts
and set the policy on how to deal with President Clinton's
transgressions, while he deals with the people's business. But
behind the scenes, according to other Republican lawmakers, not a
step is taken or a decision made without the approval of Gingrich,
possibly the most partisan and certainly the most dominant speaker
in the last generation. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   Moving by  &UR; 9 p.m. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MINISTER (Undated) _ Clinton chooses his own pastor in
Washington to be the third of his spiritual counselors. By Laurie
Goodstein. (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS-TV (Undated) _ What networks and news channels
are planning for three hours of Clinton testimony.
</P>
