<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1312 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-NYT &LR;      09-17 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTIES TELL CANDIDATES TO REFRAIN FROM CHARACTER ASSASSINATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-DAY, CLINTON-CONGRESS-SLEAZE,
CLINTON-CONGRESS-ASSESS, CLINTON-EDITORIALS, CLINTON-BOSTON,
CLINTON-RELEASE, CLINTON-GINGRICH, CLINTON-CONGRESS,
CLINTON-MINISTER, CLINTON-CONGRESS-TV) 
(JT) 
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The leaders of the Democratic and Republican
committees that help finance campaigns for the House of
Representatives promised Thursday to withhold money from any
candidates who attack the private lives of their opponents in the
November election races.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Martin Frost of Texas, the chairman of the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee, and Rep. John Linder of Georgia,
the chairman of the National Republican Congressional Committee,
made the commitment on the House floor Thursday morning and
directed their staffs to write a letter to candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The two chairmen said they wanted to discourage a spiral into
character assassination and mudslinging at a time when the
political scene is dominated by discussion of President Clinton's
involvement with a White House intern, and when the sexual lives of
politicians seem to be coming under ever wider scrutiny in the news
media.
</P>
<P>
   What promoted their initiative was widespread outrage over the
disclosure on Wednesday that Rep. Henry Hyde, the chairman of the
House Judiciary Committee, had an affair in the 1960s with a
married woman. That disclosure arose not in Hyde's re-election
campaign, but in an article in an online magazine that was quickly
echoed by other news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third time in recent days that a Republican member of
the House, confronted by the press, had confirmed a past adulterous
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't happen very often,'' Frost said of campaigns using
smear tactics, ``but it is certainly possible that it would happen
this year, because of everything that has happened. If they engage
in it, they engage in it at their own risk. There are a lot of
things those of us in politics can't control, but this is one thing
John Linder and I can control.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Senate's Republican and Democratic campaigns
said they did not know whether similar policies would be
considered.
</P>
<P>
   The House campaign committees solicit donations of thousands of
dollars from other political action committees and from individual
donors, then funnel the money into the campaigns of Congressional
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The maximum donation each committee is allowed to make to a
single campaign is $70,000; the typical House race costs much more
than that, and some cost millions of dollars. The congressional
committees also spend tens of millions of dollars in advertisements
advocating issues rather than candidates, and on other political
activities.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, the two committees spent more than $100 million
during the 1995 and 1996 election cycle, according to Federal
Election Committee records, with the Republicans spending more than
twice as much as the Democrats. Linder said today that his
committee expected to contribute $7 million to 100 Republican
candidates in the coming election. Frost said his committee would
support 50 to 100 Democratic candidates, but not always to the
legal limit.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of using their campaign chests to restrain personal
attacks was first suggested by Frost in an appearance this morning
before the National Association of Manufacturers. Linder, who was
also at the meeting, immediately agreed, and on the way back to the
House they decided to write a common policy, they said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
