<SLUG> BC-MARKET-SLIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US STOCKS JOIN THE RIDE; DOW DROPS 216 POINTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ US stocks followed those of Europe, Asia and Latin
America in tumbling Thursday after Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan poured cold water on the idea of a coordinated interest
rate cut to spur growth. The Dow Jones industrial average snapped a
four-day rally by losing 216 points.
</P>
<P>
   Among the hardest hit were shares of banks and financial service
companies, many of which have fallen by as much as half from their
mid-July highs, and consumer product companies like Proctor &AMP;
Gamble Co. whose overseas sales are expected to suffer because of
the current global turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market has bounced around within a comparatively
narrow range for almost three weeks as investors have tried to
fathom what the overseas financial crisis, President Clinton's
political troubles and stalling corporate profits mean for
investments. While some analysts said the pattern sets the stage
for a comeback, others warned of continued jumps and plunges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see these problems going away very quickly. You can
see how fragile the market is,'' said Michael W. Clark, US equities
trading chief for Credit Suisse First Boston Corp. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's tumble began in Asia where renewed worries about
Japanese banks sent Tokyo's Nikkei 225 Index down 2.4 percent to a
12 1/2-year low, and Hong Kong's Hang Seng Index down 3.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble spread quickly to Europe where most major indexes
were off about four percent, at least in part on news that French
Alcatel SA, the world's fourth largest telephone equipment maker,
would not hit profit targets. Alacatel shares plunged 38 percent,
shaving more than $11 billion from the company's market's value.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the Dow dropped 216.01 points, or 2.7 percent, to close at
7873.77, ending a four-day, 474-point rise. Every company in the
30-stock index saw its shares fall. Other market indexes traced a
similar pattern; the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index dropped 26.62
point, or 2.6 percent, to 1018.86, and the Nasdaq Composite Index
skidded 43.67 points, or 2.6 percent, to 1646.24.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among local companies hurt by the slide was Gillette Co.
whose shares had already tumbled 11 percent Wednesday on news that
overseas sales were being damaged by economic trouble in Russia,
Asia and Latin America. The company's stock fell 3 7/16, or another
8.5 percent, Thursday to close at 36 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Thursday's trouble stemmed from Greenspan's comments in
congressional testimony Wednesday that the US was not leading the
so-called G-7 industrial nations in a coordinated interest rate cut
to combat global slowdown. Investors had assumed that such a cut
was in the works and were surprised by US central banker's remarks,
according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that no issues have been resolved in the
global economic or political crisis,'' said Tony Dwyer, chief
markets strategist for Ladenburg Thalmann &AMP; Co. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   For the US, there was some good economic news; the trade deficit
widened less than expected in July and consumer prices barely
budged in August. Analysts said that both were signs that outside
of the manufacturing sector, which has been hurt by tumbling
overseas sales, the economy is holding up well in its eighth year
of expansion.
</P>
<P>
   But US economic stability is apparently not enough to help other
countries. The International Monetary Fund reportedly sliced its
prediction for world growth this year from its May forecast of 3.1
percent to a weak two percent.
</P>
<P>
   And domestic stability may not be enough to help some US
workers. Travelers Group Inc and Citicorp, which are preparing to
merge, said they will cut as many as 8,000 employees, or five
percent of the combined firms's workforce by year &UR;  &LR; end. A spokesman
for the companies said many of the cuts would be in headquarters
and emerging markets staff, which means they are likely to fall
heavily on New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
