<SLUG> BC-CHIRON-BAYER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIRON SELLS MASSACHUSETTS UNIT TO BAYER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM   AND RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chiron Corp. Thursday said it has agreed to sell its medical
diagnostic business in Walpole, Mass. to Bayer A.G., a German
chemical and pharmaceutical company, for $1.1 billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Chiron Diagnostics, which employs 1,200 in Massachusetts and
2,200 in Ohio, California, and Great Britain, records $560 million
in annual sales of its blood screening tests for the hepatitis C
and human immunodeficiency viruses.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition, expected to be completed by early next year,
will transform Bayer into the world's fourth-largest purveyor of
medical diagnostic kits. It also gives Chiron, based in Emeryville,
Calif., a major cash infusion, an estimated $800 million after it
pays income taxes on the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   The deal boosts Bayer's ability to compete in the $19 billion
global market for medical testing kits. Bayer, whose $1.1-billion
diagnostic business is based in Tarrytown, N.Y., collects $500
million from sales of its self-test, glucose monitoring kits for
diabetics. The remainder of its diagnostic sales come from Bayer's
central laboratory business, which has some overlaps with Chiron
Diagnostics. There are no immediate plans for layoffs, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``The diagnostic business is consolidating pretty rapidly, as
each of the major players has made key acquisitions, creating
somewhat of a feeding frenzy,'' said Richard Barker, president of
Chiron Diagnostics, who will remain with the business under Bayer.
``So we knew we needed a critical mass if we wanted to be a major
player.''
</P>
<P>
   For Chiron, the sale represents a 100 percent return on
investment. Chiron paid just $350 million in 1995 for the company,
which was owned by Ciba-Geigy Corp., a Swiss pharmaceutical
company. After investing over $100 million of its own product lines
into the business, it doubled its money in the cash deal with
Bayer.
</P>
<P>
   Chiron had spent the better part of a year searching for an
equity partner for its diagnostic division, which contributes about
half of the company's annual sales. But Chiron executives
ultimately decided to sell the operation to focus exclusively on
its drug and vaccine business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear they wanted to refocus and become more of a
specialty drug company,'' said Tom Brakel, analyst with Mehta
Partners in New York, who had estimated Chiron would get just $560
million for its diagnostic business. Brakel said Chiron has been
streamlining its business in an aggressive effort to propel its
stock to the $40 range. With Chiron shares closing at 17 7/16, up
9/16, Thursday, Brakel acknowledged the company has a ways to go.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Sheffery, analyst with Orbimed Advisors in New York,
said his level of enthusiasm for the deal will depend on what
Chiron will do with its newfound money. ``I am enthusiastic about
the deal, but am taking a wait-and-see attitude to see what they do
with the cash before I become super-enthusiastic about Chiron as an
investment idea.''
</P>
</TEXT>
