<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S OHIO VISIT IS NORMAL--ON THE SURFACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-CONGRESS-SLEAZE, CLINTON-CONGRESS-ASSESS,
CLINTON-EDITORIALS, CLINTON-BOSTON, CLINTON-RELEASE,
CLINTON-GINGRICH, CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-MINISTER,
CLINTON-CONGRESS-TV) 
(mk) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ On the surface, it was a perfectly normal
presidential visit, with all the symbols of power on display.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton landed at lunchtime at the Greater Cincinnati
Airport, across the Ohio River in Kentucky, in his imposing
blue-and-white jet, Air Force One, with the big presidential seal
on its side. A pair of Air Force enlisted men snapped to attention
as a ramp rolled into place. A long black limousine with flags
flying from its fenders stood ready, along with a queue of local
politicians and officials, some of them carrying umbrellas in a
light rain.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a dark gray double-breasted suit, Clinton chatted with
each person in the group, smiling warmly if less broadly than
usual. As usual, he was late _25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But it was, in fact, a most abnormal visit. Back in Washington,
the House Judiciary Committee was meeting to decide whether to
release the videotape of the president giving testimony about
Monica Lewinsky to a grand jury. Rep. Steve Chabot of Cincinnati, a
Republican, sits on the committee.
</P>
<P>
   After a long debate within her campaign organization about
whether being seen with Clinton Thursday would help her or hurt
her, Mayor Roxanne Qualls of Cincinnati, Chabot's Democratic
opponent this fall, turned up at the airport. Clinton asked her to
ride into the city with him, and she did.
</P>
<P>
   But she had told a reporter pointedly earlier this week, ``I am
not a close personal friend of the president in any sense of the
phrase.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Democratic politicians in the region who might have found
a way to be there, had the president not been in such deep
political trouble, stayed away Thursday, for whatever reason. Gov.
Paul Patton of Kentucky sent the lieutenant governor, Steven Henry.
Neither Mary Boyle, the former county commissioner from Cleveland
who is running for the Senate in Ohio this fall, nor Rep. Ted
Strickland, a centrist Democrat whose district runs eastward across
southern Ohio from the Cincinnati exurbs, found their way to the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   In the best of circumstances, this would be a tough year for
Ohio Democrats. Gov. George Voinovich, a popular Republican, is
strongly favored over Ms. Boyle in the Senate race, and the Ohio
secretary of state, Bob Taft, the possessor of a magic Republican
name, is running well ahead in the contest for Voinovich's job. But
Democratic candidates are getting jumpier by the day.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton wondered why, he could have scanned the front page of
Thursday's Cincinnati Enquirer. There were photographs of six area
residents, together with comments they sent in response to the
paper's invitation. Two were more or less supportive of the
president, but the rest were highly critical. Two called on him to
resign and another, Jennifer Weber of Oxford, Ohio, wrote: ``How
can you stand for a moral and ethical country and help people live
the American dream when you are the epitome of America's
problems?''
</P>
<P>
   The paper received 1,464 messages and printed three full pages
of them. It said three of four people who sent faxes and letters
wanted Clinton to go; those who sent e-mail messages, mostly
younger, were more forgiving.
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial last Sunday, the paper itself was harsh.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Bill Clinton has lied his way out of the most
powerful office in the world,'' The Enquirer declared. ``To endure
such a dishonest man as our national leader is more shame and
humiliation than our nation can tolerate. He needs our prayers. But
he cannot remain in the White House. If he lacks the basic decency,
honor and sense of duty to resign, he should be impeached.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite national, regional and local polls showing that a
majority of respondents want neither a resignation nor an
impeachment, those calling the Washington offices of Ohio lawmakers
obviously feel otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   A ``large volume of calls'' to Sen. John Glenn, a Democrat who
said this week that it would be ``reckless and injudicious'' for
him to join ``the rush to judgment'' in the Lewinsky matter, have
run 2-1 in favor of resignation or impeachment. Chabot's office
said the tally there was 425-15 against Clinton since Kenneth Starr
issued his report a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the president lacks vocal supporters in this state. The
Ohio Democratic chairman, David Leland, said, ``The vast majority
of Ohio Democrats want to see this president continue in office,
because they know a political lynching when they see one.''
</P>
<P>
   Even conclusive proof that Clinton lied to the grand jury in the
Lewinsky case ``wouldn't change anyone's minds here,'' Leland said
in a telephone interview on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton got an equally fervent vote of confidence Thursday
afternoon from Stanley Chesley, the host of a fund-raising luncheon
at his house in the city's northern suburbs. Chesley praised the
president for ``monumental'' courage in the face of repeated
attacks and added: ``We need you. I need you.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the nation's leading trial lawyers, who has made a
fortune from contingency fees in cases like the Bhopal chemical
disaster and the Dow Corning implants failure, Chesley has raised
millions of dollars for Democratic candidates in recent years.
Thursday's goal was $500,000 for the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee. Considerably more than that was raised last
March at a similar event for the Democratic National Committee at
Chesley's house.
</P>
<P>
   The president contrasted his stands on Social Security, the
world economy, public education and health care with those of the
Republicans on Capitol Hill. He urged his listeners to ``look your
friends dead in the eye'' and tell them: ``It's not about
Washington. It's about America and these issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington, he said, is obsessed with scandal and with itself.
</P>
<P>
   On the way to the luncheon, Clinton passed a small group of
supporters and a larger group of opponents calling for him to
resign.
</P>
<P>
   But he talked to no ordinary voters. Qualls invited him to visit
one of the Cincinnati neighborhoods that have applied for a federal
``empowerment zone'' grant. But the mayor said White House
officials had rejected the idea on the ground that a visit to one
applicant would be unfair to others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
