<SLUG> BC-TEAPOT-DOME-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE AMERICA'S KUWAIT, WYOMING OIL REGION AWAITS A DUSTY DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic locator
map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By JAMES BROOKE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDWEST, Wyo. _ The 55-year-old president had intimate
encounters with a 24-year-old campaign volunteer in a cloak closet
off the Oval Office in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But the scandal that really smeared the memory of President
Warren Harding bubbled 75 years ago from Teapot Dome, a vast pool
of oil below treeless sagebrush flats just south of here.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the 1920s, Teapot Dome _ a classic tale of oil
tycoons, $100 bills and a jailed Cabinet member _ was the talk of
the nation. But, today in this dusty town of 495 people, the last
oil camp site left from the roaring '20s, some residents fret that
they are also losing their toehold on history. The Starr Report
could dethrone the Teapot Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scandal today isn't nothing compared to Teapot Dome,''
Pauline Schultz insisted, at her local history museum. ``It was
President Harding, Cabinet Secretaries, there were many, many
dignitaries involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Schultz deflected conversation about Harding's long string
of mistresses. She said she was unaware of new scholarship that
places Nan Britton, the former campaign volunteer, in the White
House for secret liaisons with Harding.
</P>
<P>
   On one museum wall, the 83-year-old museum curator has posted a
jazz-age photograph of herself posing coyly, draped only in the
pelt of a mountain lion. Despite this whiff of spice, she dismissed
sex scandals as second rate. Showing visitors around today, she
lectured insistently: ``The Teapot Dome scandal was the largest in
the United States. This new one would be second.''
</P>
<P>
   At the town offices next door, Melvin Dimick, a plumber who
doubles as mayor, defended Teapot's primacy, saying: ``It's right
up there at the top. That was one big financial scandal. This new
one's a little different.''
</P>
<P>
   But, even before Monica Lewinsky came along, time had not been
kind to the Teapot Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Wyoming's famous winds battered the signature landmark, a beige
sandstone formation named Teapot Rock by passing cowboys. In 1930,
a windstorm blew off the handle. In 1962 another storm blew off the
spout. Today, it is merely a garden variety butte.
</P>
<P>
   At the oil field, officially called Naval Petroleum Reserve No.
3, guard shacks stand abandoned. Next year, Lt. Doug Tunison, the
last Navy officer to be stationed here, is to leave. His departure
will end a tradition, started in 1915, of having a Navy officer
supervise the old fields.
</P>
<P>
   Today, although the reserve's valley floor is dotted with 450
working wells, the average production of each well has dribbled to
a little over a barrel a day.
</P>
<P>
   The decline of the Teapot Dome field is part of a wider oil
implosion in Wyoming, a state heavily dependent on energy royalties
to pave highways and pay for schools. Suffering from the same $12 a
barrel oil prices that have helped destabilize Russia and
Venezuela, Wyoming expects to see its government oil royalties drop
this year $40 million. Without higher oil prices to pay for new
investments, production in Wyoming, the nation's fourth largest
oil-producing state, is expected to drop by 40 percent by 2006. In
Casper, 35 miles south of here, two out of the city's three oil
refineries have closed in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Today, surveying this arid landscape where there are more capped
wells than active ones, it is hard to imagine the days when the
nation's attention burned on this 15-square-mile patch of rocks, a
barren place with such names as Dead Horse Road and Dead Dog Draw.
But in the early 1920s, this oil-soaked corner of central Wyoming
was America's Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   In 1923, Midwest had 15,000 inhabitants, many working nearby at
the Salt Creek Field, which produced 740 million barrels that year
for Casper's seven refineries. Mrs. Schultz, the daughter of a
driller, said the field here used the leading oil technology,
becoming the first in the world to use welded pipelines, and the
first to use electric motors to pump oil. A brochure for French
investors sang praises of ``le Wyoming.''
</P>
<P>
   But, about 10 miles south of Salt Creek lay Teapot Dome, an
untapped reserve on federal land that was off limits to private
companies. In 1915, with World War I raging in Europe, President
Woodrow Wilson reserved this field and others in the West to create
a secure supply for oil-burning Navy ships. Oil experts of the day
had warned that the world oil supplies were nearing exhaustion.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In April 1921, only days after Harding's inauguration, Harry
Sinclair, owner of Sinclair Oil Co., privately negotiated a lease
on the Teapot Dome with the new Interior Secretary, Albert Fall.
Immediately, rival oil companies complained about the absence of
competitive bidding. By the time Harding died on Aug. 2, 1923,
apparently of a heart attack, the whistle was blowing on Teapot.
</P>
<P>
   A Senate inquiry discovered that after negotiating the Sinclair
contract, Fall had taken possession of Liberty Bonds that once
belonged to the oil magnate and that he had bought a large ranch in
New Mexico, making payment with a stack of $100 bills. In all,
Senate investigators said, Fall received $400,000 from two oil
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Convicted of bribery, Fall spent one year in jail, becoming the
first Cabinet member to go to prison. Sinclair spent six months in
jail for refusing to testify before the Senate inquiry. In 1927,
Harding's place in history was definitively tarnished when the
Supreme Court annulled the Sinclair contract, and Miss Britton
published a memoir, stating that Harding fathered her daughter in
1919 and that they kept up a sexual relationship while he was
president.
</P>
<P>
   After the high court's ruling, the Navy closed the field (though
an officer remained), and it was not reopened until the oil crisis
of the mid-1970s. Oil from the reserve never went to a Navy ship
but was sold by the government on the open market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The paradox of Harding is that he died as one of the most
beloved and popular presidents, yet within a few short years, his
legacy as president and his personal reputation became permanently
damaged,'' said Carl Sferrazza Anthony, author of ``Florence
Harding: The First Lady, the Jazz Age and the Death of America's
Most Scandalous President'' (William Morrow, 1998). ``For the
general public, the revelation of a mistress and an illegitimate
child was easier to grasp than the Teapot Dome.''
</P>
<P>
   But, here the consequence of Teapot Dome was as easy to grasp.
``The scandal was so great, they had to wipe Teapot Dome off the
map,'' Mrs. Schultz said of the Navy's decision to shut the oil
field. ``We just had antelope and deer out there until 1975.''
</P>
<P>
   Without the oil field, the town of Teapot Dome vanished, leaving
only a few foundations visible today. Following a rootless pattern
of human habitation that has marked much of Wyoming in the 20th
century, residents of Teapot simply moved their houses down the
road, heading to the next boom town.
</P>
<P>
   After producing 20 million barrels since 1976, the field now has
only half a million barrels of easily recoverable oil. A Department
of Energy team works capping old wells and cleaning up
environmental damage. The department is converting the field,
equipped with 120 miles of dirt roads and about 1,000 miles of
underground pipes, into a research center on oil pipelines, working
with private companies.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government, in fact, wants to sell Teapot Dome. But,
unlike the frenzied 1920s when there was so much oil that one
drilling dispute had to be settled by a detachment of Marines, the
reserves have dwindled to the point that government officials fear
that if they open Teapot Dome to competitive bidding, they may not
get a bidder.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
