A1345 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOB-HEARING-BOS &LR;      09-17 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOB-HEARING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-FBI AGENT COULD FACE CRIMINAL CHARGES, PROSECUTOR SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Defending the government's decision not to grant
immunity to former FBI agent John Connolly, a federal prosecutor
Thursday said Connolly might face serious criminal charges that
outweighed defense lawyers' desire to get Connolly on the witness
stand.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Assistant US Attorney James D. Herbert  &UR;  &LR; reminded Judge Mark
L. Wolf &UR;  &LR; that a federal prosecutor from Connecticut _ Deputy US
Attorney John Durham  &UR;  &LR; _ is leading a criminal investigation into
Connolly's dealings with informants.
</P>
<P>
   While the probe is in its early stages, Herbert said Connolly
``hypothetically'' could face charges of conspiracy to obstruct
justice, racketeering or harboring a fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly, a retired FBI agent who cultivated Winter Hill
gangsters James ``Whitey'' Bulger and Stephen Flemmi as top-level
informants, has repeatedly denied doing anything illegal and has
charged he is being used as a scapegoat in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly has been at the center of much of the testimony during
lengthy &UR;  &LR; hearings in federal court but he has refused to testify,
citing his Fifth Amendment protection against self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, as the hearings wind down, lawyers for Flemmi and
his co-defendants want Wolf to order the government to immunize
Connolly, claiming his testimony could help Flemmi's case and clear
up discrepancies between Flemmi's version of events and that of
Connolly's former supervisor, John Morris.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``There are a variety of important issues that Connolly can
address,'' argued defense attorney Martin G. Weinberg, who
represents Winter Hill gangster John Martorano. ``The hole (in the
evidence) is Connolly.''
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi has claimed Morris granted him and Bulger immunity for
all crimes except murder in exchange for information on the Mafia.
Morris, testifying under a grant of immunity, has denied the claim.
</P>
<P>
   All but one of the alleged crimes in which Connolly has been
implicated _ such as tipping off Bulger and Flemmi to
investigations or being the conduit for $2,000 that Morris received
in payoffs _ occurred too long ago to be prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   And the one alleged crime that occurred within the statute of
limitations _ the possibilty that Connolly tipped Bulger and Flemmi
to their January 1995 indictment _ is undercut by Flemmi's
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi has said the tip came came from Morris, who has denied
the charge.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  But Herbert said ``the notion that any tip came from John
Morris and not John Connolly is silly.'' Morris, he noted, was
working in the bureau's San Diego office at the time Bulger and
Flemmi were indicted, while Connolly, though retired, was still in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Herbert suggested that Flemmi was trying to protect his longtime
handler by attributing the tipoff to Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the January 1995 tip, Herbert suggested that a phone
call Connolly allegedly made to former agent Dennis Condon in April
1997 could support a charge of conspiracy to obstruct justice.
</P>
<P>
   During the call, Connolly allegedly advanced the notion that it
was a drunken Morris and not him who gave Bulger and Flemmi
permission to commit crimes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
