<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONETRUETHING-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TRUE THING' IS MISSING SOMETHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - You expect the tears to start flowing at any minute in
``One True Thing.'' The emotional ingredients are there: dying
mother, sinning father, a daughter trying to do the right thing no
matter how tough it is. But the drama about how families come
together _ or don't _ during times of crisis stays surprisingly
dry.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is also curiously unengaging, unless you've been
through similar struggles and can project more into the story than
the director projects onto the screen.
</P>
<P>
   For a film dealing with the obligations of love, ``One True
Thing'' is missing something at the heart, perhaps because the
talents of the two older co-stars overshadow the lesser powers of
the star, who cannot hold onto the movie's core.
</P>
<P>
   If Meryl Streep and William Hurt had produced a daughter, I
remain unconvinced that she would turn out to be Renee Zellweger.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Jerry Maguire,'' Zellweger was a good match for Tom Cruise,
but she seems out of her depth in this more demanding drama.
</P>
<P>
   Zellweger stars as Ellen Gulden, am ambitious magazine writer
who is forced to sacrifice her career plans when she learns that
her mother Kate (Streep) is dying of cancer and her father George
(Hurt) expects Ellen to move back home and take over the nursing.
</P>
<P>
   George is a pompous college professor who has always depended on
his wife. Kate is the Martha Stewart of faculty wives, if less than
perfect as a mother.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen has spent her life trying not to become her mother,
although neither Zellweger nor director Carl Franklin ever makes
clear exactly why the daughter resents her mother so strongly.
</P>
<P>
   As Ellen struggles with her matrilineal anger, she must also
deal with revelations of her father's weaknesses over the long
months of Kate's decline.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Ellen finally comes to terms and tears with her
family issues, the movie has lost its emotional momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Zellweger plays Ellen as too sullen and unchanging to gather up
our sympathies. Her resentments of her mother seem petty, adding to
the urge to want the movie to be more about Kate and less about
Ellen.
</P>
<P>
   It's quite easy to imagine how much more power a young Streep
would have brought to the role of the conflicted daughter. Even an
older Streep has the power and grace to dominate every scene she's
in, as she takes us through the physical deterioration of a bright,
vibrant woman withering away from the inside.
</P>
<P>
   Streep's performance makes the movie worth seeing. That's true
of nearly every movie she has made over the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Hurt (``Michael'') plays the remote father somewhere between
befuddlement and pain. His struggles play stronger than his
daughter's even though he has less to work with.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a woman director would have been better able to bring
more focus to the daughter's anger toward her mother.
</P>
<P>
   But Franklin (``Devil in a Blue Dress'') does manage to keep the
long movie from growing stagnant. He quickens the scenes and moves
the story, based on the Anna Quindlen novel, through time and
place.
</P>
<P>
   While ``One True Thing'' is notable for dealing seriously with
the losses that can heal a family or separate it, the film is not
as emotionally swaying as ``Marvin's Room,'' in which Streep also
starred but was balanced by the equally moving Diane Keaton.
</P>
<P>
   ``One True Thing'' is rated R for profanity. 3 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 1942EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
