<SLUG> BC-AIRTRAN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AirTran forecasts quarterly loss
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- AirTran Airlines says unchecked predatory pricing
this summer by Atlanta rival Delta Air Lines has ``destroyed'' its
chance for a profitable third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The low-fare carrier also blamed the Department of
Transportation, which it said ``completely abandoned'' efforts to
rein in predatory pricing by major airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prior to the DOT's total capitulation, AirTran was on plan for
a solidly profitable year,'' AirTran said in a statement Thursday.
``Beginning in June, predatory pricing by our major competitor has
now cast serious doubt on whether the airline will be profitable
for the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``So dramatic was this action by our major competitor that it
has destroyed our opportunity for a profitable third quarter,''
said the airline, which will post the quarterly results next month.
</P>
<P>
   Delta and the DOT, in separate responses, rejected AirTran's
assertions as unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the free enterprise system works, and it's not for
the weak or meek of heart,'' said Delta spokeswoman Laura Gillig.
``If you give customers what they demand, they'll respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the culprit, red ink for the summer would be a
step backward for AirTran. In the spring quarter the airline,
formerly ValuJet, logged its first profit in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Executive D. Joseph Corr said then he expected the profits
to continue as new marketing programs attracted passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Most airlines will post strong summer profits, thanks to high
demand, steady capacity and low fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
   PaineWebber analyst Samuel Buttrick said AirTran's inability to
sustain profits is foreboding: ``If you're not making money in the
current environment, it's not exactly clear to me when you're going
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Orlando-based AirTran's major flight hub is in Atlanta, where it
competes head to head with Delta, which typically offers some seats
at matching prices.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran executives have periodically complained Delta's
practices qualify as predatory pricing. The term has a hazy legal
definition but generally means swamping routes with matching fares
to soak up low-fare demand. AirTran said Delta this summer
escalated its activities, though it cited no specific cases.
</P>
<P>
   The DOT, acting on complaints by several small airlines, last
spring issued proposed rules to better define predatory pricing and
punish violators.
</P>
<P>
   Delta and other major airlines attacked the rules as
``re-regulation.'' At their request, the DOT twice extended the
comment period, now set to end Sept. 25. AirTran fears the
guidelines are being effectively tabled.
</P>
<P>
   Corr, in AirTran's statement, said the agency's message is
``resoundingly clear: It is now open season on carriers providing
affordable fares, and the DOT will dismiss any complaints of
anti-competitive practices ... as `whining.'''
</P>
<P>
   A DOT spokesman said, ``When our guidelines are final we will
take vigorous action when warranted'' to stop unfair practices.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
