<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    French authorities block Coke's plan
 &HT;    By Mickey H. Gramig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- French antitrust authorities have blocked Coca-Cola
Co.'s $883 million purchase of Orangina from Pernod Ricard SA, a
decision rival Pepsico hailed as ``a victory for consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pepsico, which first cried foul about the deal in December
when Atlanta-based Coca-Cola announced its plans to buy the fizzy
French citrus drink, may face a second round.
</P>
<P>
   The Conseil de la Concurrence, France's antitrust authority,
``has indicated that there's an open door for further
consideration,'' said Coca-Cola spokesman Rob Baskin. ``We're going
to continue to evaluate our options.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico had argued Coca-Cola's purchase of Orangina would lead
to its ``immediate eviction'' in France because Orangina bottles
and distributes its beverages for sales at cafes, hotels and
restaurants throughout the country. These ``on-premise
consumption'' sales make up about 50 percent of Pepsico's French
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Before Thursday's ruling, the odds for approval appeared to be
in Coca-Cola's favor. The French government reviews about 45
competition cases a year and had blocked only three acquisitions
outright since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of the earnings impact, it's irrelevant, but
psychologically, it's a blow to Coke,'' said Caroline Levy, a
beverage analyst with Schroder Wertheim. ``I can't remember the
last time that they lost a deal that they wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Chief Executive M. Douglas Ivester told analysts and
investors in June that the company planned to expand Orangina's
distribution. ``In the hands of the Coke system, Orangina could be
turned into a successful niche product,'' Levy said.
</P>
<P>
   Already, it's the No. 2 soft drink in France, second only to
Coke, and it's extremely strong in the United Kingdom, Orangina's
second-largest market.
</P>
<P>
   Orangina loyalists in the United States, where the drink barely
registers a blip on the sales charts, hoped the acquisition would
mean easier access to the beverage. It's made with 12 percent
orange juice and 2 percent pulp. The brand sells 53 million cases a
year worldwide, including an estimated 1.5 million in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Antitrust authorities said the acquisition would give Coke an
unfair competitive advantage in France, where data from industry
tracker Beverage Digest show Coca-Cola has a 49.6 percent share of
the overall carbonated soft drink market, compared with Pepsico's 9
percent.
</P>
<P>
   For drinks consumed outside the home in France, the Orangina
purchase would give Coca-Cola a 99 percent market share for
carbonated orange drinks, a 98.7 percent share for cola drinks and
a 98.5 percent share for lemon-lime drinks.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, as it now stands, will probably ``further
embitter'' Coca-Cola and Pepsico against each other, said John
Sicher, publisher of Beverage Digest. ``The nature of the
competition and the level of adversarial feelings between these two
companies will now be ratcheted up a few notches.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides their battles in the marketplace, Pepsico and Coca-Cola
have ongoing court fights over Pepsico's claim its rival has stolen
employees and bottlers in India, and that Coca-Cola is using unfair
trade practices to dominate the U.S. fountain soft drink market.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
