<SLUG> BC-DOW18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Headlines halt markets' rallies
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The buying rally that gave Wall Street a four-day, 6
percent-plus gain early this week fell apart on the eve of today's
quarterly ``triple witching'' session.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts blamed a series of events for the Thursday turnaround,
starting with sharp losses in foreign markets after Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan's congressional testimony that U.S. and
other central banks are not planning coordinated interest rate
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese officials subsequently appeared to yield to opponents
of an important government-sponsored bank reform plan, sending
Japan's Nikkei stock index to a 12-year low.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton increased the likelihood of a
congressional impeachment by saying Wednesday he will remain in
office.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee, meanwhile, was reported to be on
the verge of releasing the president's videotaped testimony to
Kenneth Starr's grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Investors responded to all this on Thursday with a broad
sell-off that depressed all major stock averages.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark Dow Jones industrial average dropped back below
8,000 again, losing 235 points in early trading before late program
buying trimmed the loss to 216.01 points.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expect today's session to be volatile if nothing else
because of ``triple witching,'' the quarterly expiration of stock
options, index options and index futures.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's events undid the brief buying rally initiated last
Friday when Starr's report was released, showing no new surprises
about the president.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 6.2 percent in that
four-day rally, the S&AMP;P-500 stock average by 6.7 percent, the
technology-weighted Nasdaq composite by 6.6 percent and even the
beleaguered Russell 2000 small-stock index by 4.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Now, analysts at Standard &AMP; Poor's say in their latest market
forecast that stocks are likely to trade within a wide price range
for months to come, with stock averages ending the year only
``modestly above the current level.''
</P>
<P>
   John J. White, research director for Interstate/Johnson Lane,
agreed ``what we're seeing are elements of a trading range,'' Dow
Jones News Service reported.
</P>
<P>
   He said major stock indexes will not be able to break out of the
range, either up or down, ``until there's some reason to feel
better or worse.''
</P>
<P>
   In this environment, investors paid little attention on Thursday
to two favorable government economic reports: that the
international trade deficit widened by a less-than-expected 2.1
percent in July to $13.9 billion, and that the Consumer Price Index
rose only 0.2 percent, just slightly above analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Bank and consumer stocks got hammered in Thursday's trading.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the next round of third-quarter earnings reports
that are released next month will have a lot to do with where the
market goes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
