<SLUG> BC-FORMAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Men's couture set falling for white
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The bride won't be the only one wearing white next
spring, thanks to a flashy new line of men's formal wear by
Athens-based tuxedo maker Men's Apparel Group.
</P>
<P>
   Men's Apparel Group, which manufactures tuxedos under the labels
After Six, Oscar de la Renta and Raffinati, unveiled its new styles
Thursday at the Marriott Marquis downtown, where formal wear
manufacturers and buyers gathered for their annual convention and
trade show. The prime buying opportunity of the year, this year's
expo is the biggest in the group's 25-year history.
</P>
<P>
   The company's Rainbow Collection is a new wrinkle in the
traditional black tuxedo market, a $1 billion industry that stays
alive by dressing up the two big fashion events in a man's social
life _ prom night and wedding day. Men's Apparel Group jazzed up
its tux line with a patented zip-in collar that allows the wearer
to mix and match lapel colors with vests, ties and bridesmaid's
dresses in a variety of colors ranging from pink to avocado green.
</P>
<P>
   Renting vs. buying
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bold statement. White is becoming more important, but
I'd have to say we're cautiously excited about it,'' said Dan
Santucci, president of the International Formalwear Association and
vice president of Sacino's Formalwear, a 23-store chain based in
St. Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers and specialty stores are also eyeing the growing
retail segment of the industry. Men who rent tuxedos more than
three times a year are starting to realize that buying a tux makes
more sense, said Jack Springer, IFA's executive director. ``If
you're over 30, you should buy a tux,'' Springer said. ``You can
wear it over and over and it never goes out of fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   Men's Apparel Group, which sells its tuxedos for $300 to $1,500,
has just expanded its retail business to include accessories and
designer cologne.
</P>
<P>
   Norcross-based Marbella International was launched six years ago
with a strict commitment to the retail end, said Chief Executive
Karl Chiu. Marbella, which makes its own Gianni line in two
overseas factories, sells basic black tuxedos for $300 to $350,
predominantly in Gingiss Formalwear.
</P>
<P>
   While disastrous for some apparel manufacturers, the corporate
casual look that is in vogue has been good for the formal wear
industry, said Bennett of Men's Apparel Group. ``Today there are
more formal weddings than ever before,'' he said. ``When you're
casual all week, you want to dress up,'' said Bennett, who added
that the company also has started making black and navy suits for
rental because men don't own as many suits now.
</P>
<P>
   Demographic trends suggest a steady business for the industry
over the next five years. The pool of high schoolers is on a steady
increase, creating demand first for prom and graduate wear and
weddings that likely follow. The number of weddings has stayed
fairly steady over the past five years, peaking in 1997 at 2.4
million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
