u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-COX     09-17 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida deal with tobacco companies get sweeter
 &HT;    By Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE _ Florida will more than double its take from
cigarette makers over the next five years, courtesy of Minnesota's
recent settlement with the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of $1.46 billion between this fiscal year and 2002-03,
Florida will get $3.21 billion _ a 120 percent increase, Gov.
Lawton Chiles announced Friday. Overall, the state will receive
$12.75 billion instead of 11 billion over 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have pounded another nail into tobacco's coffin,'' Chiles
boasted.
</P>
<P>
   Other provisions in Minnesota's agreement that would apply to
Florida include a prohibition of payments from tobacco companies to
film producers for the appearance of their cigarettes in movies as
well as a ban on promotional gear like backpacks and T-shirts
bearing tobacco logos. Florida's own settlement last year banned
tobacco billboards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big tobacco will no longer be using our kids as walking
billboards,'' Chiles said.
</P>
<P>
   The additional money and restrictions come to Florida because of
a ``most favored nation'' clause in last August's settlement, which
guarantees that Florida will benefit from all such provisions in
the industry's subsequent agreements with other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``An already outstanding deal for Floridians just got better,''
said Attorney General Bob Butterworth, who appeared with Chiles at
a Capitol news conference announcing the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Butterworth also detailed an arbitration agreement that he hopes
will end an attorneys' fees squabble that has marred the
multi-billion dollar victory. Eight of the 11 private trial lawyers
who represented the state have signed on to a deal that would pay
them for their work as early as December.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers who agree to the arrangement would share in a $100
million advance in coming days and weeks, to count toward whatever
the industry and trial-team chosen arbitration panel chooses to
award, Butterworth said.
</P>
<P>
   Chiles' victory over tobacco has been sullied by the insistence
by some of the lawyers the state hired to honor their contract that
promised them 25 percent of whatever the state got.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer's settlement agreement called for the industry to
pay all attorneys fees; the dissident lawyers point out that their
contract was with the state, not the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got no contract with tobacco,'' said West Palm Beach's Bob
Montgomery. ``They are my enemies. I tried to put them out of
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery, as well as Pensacola's Bob Kerrigan and Fort
Lauderdale's Sheldon Schlesinger, are the three lawyers still
holding out for the full 25 percent. The state Supreme Court is
scheduled to hear arguments on Nov. 5 whether a quarter of all
tobacco industry payments should continue to be set aside in an
escrow account for attorneys fees.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the state can expect $123 million in January, $465
million in January 2000, January 2001 and January 2002 and $233
million in January 2003, in addition to the already scheduled
payments from the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have the extra money, sure,'' said Rep Jim King,
R-Jacksonville, who as budget chairman will have an extra $93
million next year and $348 million the year after, even after 25
percent is set aside. ``That's very nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
