<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-TECH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Techno-savvy audiences take in two days of sessions for women
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- This is definitely not your brother's technology
conference. The Women in Technology regional conference under way
at the Cobb Galleria Centre through today aims to give its
attendees more than just the latest facts about hyperlink
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in the early '90s to address the needs of women working
in technology fields, the organization's goal is to help women and
girls pursue careers in technology. An estimated 400 to 500 women
from as far away as Massachusetts and California and as nearby as
Clayton County will attend the two-day seminar. Topics such as
emerging technologies and electronic commerce and issues concerning
women of color and how young girls can profit by technology will be
addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to provide a certain amount of diversity in the
speakers and topics we address,'' said Cathryn Gawne, chief
operating officer of WITI International. She said attendees at
previous WITI events had requested more basic workplace speakers
and sessions to compliment the high-tech component of the show.
Gwane also said WITI's approach attempts to give women business
skills as well as technical skills.
</P>
<P>
   The WITI approach was highlighted by morning keynote speaker
Debra Benton, president and founder of Benton Management Resources
Inc. Her company specializes in teaching presentation skills and
overall effectiveness in the workplace. ``Make sure the message you
send is the message you intend,'' she told the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Benton's motivational speech on workplace tips was followed by
breakout sessions. Attendees sat elbow-to-elbow at the emerging
technologies seminar. Because this was WITI's first pass through
Atlanta, speakers were unsure how techno-savvy the audience would
be, which led to some uneven presentations. However, the highly
technical questions about download time, embedded encryption
technologies and Netscape's open standards proved Atlanta's women
in technology are as plugged in as their peers in New York, San
Francisco or anywhere in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Bridging the ``digital divide'' was the topic of Mayor Bill
Campbell's lunchtime keynote. ``Besides the Civil Rights struggle,
nothing (else besides technology) has the ability to (do more to)
unite and divide society,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell also spoke about his own 9-year-old daughter and her
future in the world of work and technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want all doors to be open to her,'' he said as he praised
the audience for its technology savvy, adding more young women
should be encouraged to pursue science and technology careers and
WITI was an excellent place to help foster girls' enthusiasm for
high-tech.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
