<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1359 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HARLEM-ART-850(2TA     09-17 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HARLEM-ART-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFFLUENT BLACKS DRAWN TO HARLEM BY PROPERTY BARGAINS AND HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By LISA W. FODERARO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Howard Sanders had garnered the trappings of American
success: a degree from Harvard Business School, a position with a
high-powered Manhattan investment firm and an apartment on Central
Park West.
</P>
<P>
   But Sanders, who is black, felt so strongly about one day owning
a home in Harlem, where he had grown up, that it became a condition
of his marriage proposal. Today, he and his wife, Karen, live in a
five-bedroom brownstone with a Japanese garden on West 147th
Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to live next to a white family,'' Sanders, 32,
said. ``I effectively have integrated. I've gone to predominantly
white schools. I work in a white firm, and I can live anywhere I
want. It really is psychologically soothing for me to be in
Harlem.''
</P>
<P>
   What started in the early 1990s as a trickle of young
African-American lawyers, doctors, professors and bankers moving
back to Harlem and other historically black neighborhoods seems now
to have reached the flood stage.
</P>
<P>
   Black professionals are snatching up 5,000-square-foot
brownstones off avenues named for black leaders. And their
financial commitments extend beyond new boilers and restoring
woodwork; they are also looking to bring the amenities they had
found in Soho and the Upper West Side to neighborhoods that, while
on the upswing, are still marked by abandonment and a dearth of
shops and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Falling crime rates, relatively low housing prices, striking
residential architecture and signs of economic renewal are all
factors in the influx of affluent young black people to
historically black neighborhoods. But certain intangibles _
Harlem's storied place in the black consciousness, a new
generation's changing sensibility about integration, simple
idealism _ have played a role as well, scholars and new arrivals
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an economic incentive because you can basically get
housing for 30 to 40 percent of what you'd pay 25 blocks away,''
said Darren Walker, who gave up a doorman building in midtown
Manhattan and a career in the bond department of a Swiss bank to
move to Harlem and become a vice president of the nonprofit
Abyssinian Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I have always had a fascination with the Harlem of legend
and folklore,'' he said. ``Reading the writers of the Harlem
Renaissance created a lot of mythologies in our heads. I just feel
this visceral kind of connection that I don't know how to
describe.''
</P>
<P>
   Real estate brokers say there has also been a parallel increase
over the last five years in buyers without those connections _
white families and a small number of Asian-Americans _ who are
simply attracted by the amount of space and bygone splendor their
money can buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got houses up there with Honduran mahogany and 24-karat
gold leaf molding in the dining rooms,'' said Willie Kathryn Suggs,
a broker who estimates that buyers who are not black now account
for about 30 percent of her clients for row houses and
condominiums. ``To be able to have that kind of house in the city
is attractive to all kinds of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Other brokers say that the percentage of new buyers who are not
black is probably lower, between 10 and 15 percent, but that the
number is increasing more rapidly than the number of black buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Suggs cited as one example a white couple _ the husband is a
lawyer and the wife is a business consultant _ who closed last
month on a row house in the Hamilton Heights neighborhood, and who
told her they were interested in attracting theater companies to
the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Brokers say they have seen the effects of Harlem's pull. Housing
prices in West Harlem have risen 20 percent in five years,
according to R. Kenyatta Punter, a broker with the Harlem-based
Myers, Smith &AMP; Granady realty agency. Hard to market in the early
1990s, brownstones are now selling briskly, at prices ranging from
$80,000 for an abandoned shell to $450,000 for a house in perfect
condition.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the homes predate the Harlem Renaissance of the 1920s,
which is when many black people moving to New York chose to live in
Harlem, in part because it had a surplus of rental apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in the 1930s and accelerating through the '40s and
'50s, large numbers of black professionals left Harlem, although a
small middle-class presence remained through the decades, said
Winston James, an assistant professor of history at Columbia
University who specializes in the Harlem Renaissance. Their
departure followed the decay of apartment buildings during the
Depression and new opportunities for integration in places like
Brooklyn and Queens.
</P>
<P>
   James said the recent return of well-to-do blacks began in the
early 1990s and now seems ``to be expanding tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a sense of idealism among a large number of black
professional young people,'' he said. ``There is a terrible
frustration about the condition of black people in the society
despite the progress of many members of the professional class. I
suppose one of the ways people attempt to make some kind of
contribution is by their physical presence.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That is certainly true of Dr. Michael Jones. A 29-year-old ear,
nose and throat resident at Mount Sinai Medical Center, Jones said
he decided to move to Harlem after receiving both his undergraduate
and medical degrees from Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important for me to be in Harlem because I needed a
sense of purpose,'' he said. ``Being in Chelsea or Tribeca or the
Upper East Side, I wouldn't feel that my presence could make a
difference. Children on my block say, `Hey, Doc.' They see me
working hard. And because they can see it and touch it, they may
feel it's something they can attain.''
</P>
<P>
   His home, on West 147th Street between Convent and St. Nicholas
Avenues, is a handsome 6,000-square-foot brownstone in the leafy
section known both as Sugar Hill and Hamilton Heights.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
