<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TAPES-NET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAPES, IF RELEASED, TO GO ON THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the House Judiciary Committee releases the videotape of
President Clinton's Aug. 17 grand jury testimony, many people will
see it for the first time on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   CNN Interactive and other Internet news services drew millions
of computer users to their Web sites last weekend, in search of
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's report on Clinton's affair with
former intern Monica S. Lewinsky. Now CNN and another news site,
MSNBC, hope to repeat the feat by broadcasting the Clinton video on
cable television and the Internet at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will stream it live as it goes on air,'' said CNN
Interactive spokesman Kerrin Roberts. ``Then our team will be
turning it into on-demand video segments.'' These snippets of
testimony will be left up on the Web site, so that visitors can
replay them at will.
</P>
<P>
   CNN will work with other Internet companies to host the video.
Broadcast.com Inc. of Dallas will use its servers to pump the video
signal onto the high-speed backbone circuits of the Internet. Henry
Heflich, the company's chief technology officer, said that his
company's computers will be able to handle tens of thousands of
viewers, and can add additional capacity as needed. Real Networks
Inc. of Seattle will also carry an Internet feed of the Clinton
video.
</P>
<P>
   To see the video, computer owners will need a computer connected
to the Internet, with a modem that can receive at least 28,800 bits
of data per second. That's the speed of most home computer modems.
Also needed: software for viewing Internet videos. The two standard
viewers, the Real Player and the Microsoft Windows Media Player,
can both be downloaded for free, and are pre-installed on many
computers.
</P>
<P>
   As with the Starr report, it's expected that the Internet has
ample capacity to handle the video. Once again, problems will arise
only if large numbers of people log on to watch the video and there
isn't enough server capacity to handle it. If that happens, viewers
will be able to watch the video on cable TV.
</P>
<P>
   No time has been set for showing the video. The House Judiciary
Committee is expected to release it in some form, but adjourned
Thursday evening without reaching a decision.
</P>
<P>
   To reach the CNN Web site:
</P>
<P>
   http://cnn.com
</P>
<P>
   The MSNBC Web site:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.msnbc.com
</P>
<P>
   To get the Real Player:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.real.com/products/player/
</P>
<P>
   To get the Microsoft Media Player:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.microsoft.com/windows/mediaplayer/download/
</P>
<P>
   default.asp
</P>
</TEXT>
