<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1369 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREDIT-NYT &LR;      09-17 0371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURIES RALLY AS INVESTORS FLEE STOCK MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury bond prices rallied Thursday as investors
sold stocks and sought the safety of U.S. government securities.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year bond rose 22/32, to 104 29/32. The bond's yield,
which moves in the opposite direction from the price, dropped to
5.18 percent, from 5.22 percent Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the last three months, the 30-year bond's yield has fallen
more than half a percentage point, or 50 basis points, as global
stock markets tumble, Russia's economy falters and investors grow
more concerned that the financial crisis might spread to Brazil.
They are now at their lowest level in 30 years. (A basis point is
1/100 of a percentage point.)
</P>
<P>
   Bonds were bolstered by a government report showing that
consumer prices were little changed during August and a regional
Federal Reserve survey indicating that manufacturing activity is
beginning to slow.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Fine, chief market analyst at Chase Asset Management,
said, ``The rally in the bond market continues, spurred by
increasing evidence of an economic slackening, a continued
auspicious inflation outlook, a flight-to-quality resulting from
declining stock prices, and the growing market perception that a
near-term Fed easing move is clearly on the horizon.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Tuesday's testimony by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan to the House Banking Committee did not add much to
previous comments about the vulnerability of the nation to the
global crisis, nor shed any light on whether the policy-making
group will change interest rates when it meets Sept. 29. Fine
predicted that at that meeting the Federal Open Market Committee
will adopt a bias toward easing from a neutral stance. Whenever the
federal funds rate, which has remained at 5.50 percent since March
1997, is lowered, Fine said it will in all likelihood be a
25-basis-point cut, as the Fed tends to move slowly.
</P>
<P>
   In the junk bond market, Calenergy Co., an electricity
generation and distribution company, sold $1.4 billion of senior
notes in four parts, breaking a month-long drought of new sales in
the junk bond market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
