u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-MASSACRE-0918-     09-17 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-MASSACRE-0918-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICAN POLICE PURSUE DRUG LINK TO BRUTAL SLAYINGS OF 19 IN BAJA
REGION
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Mexican police are investigating whether notorious
drug traffickers ordered gunmen to pull three families from their
beds in Baja California state Thursday, line them up against a wall
and kill 19 of them in a hail of gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   The cold-blooded killings, which included seven children and a
baby in its mother's arms, shocked Mexico with its brutality.
</P>
<P>
   One of the lines of inquiry into the crime, according to Mexican
press reports, is whether the killings were ordered by the Arellano
Felix brothers, a Tijuana-based drug cartel, wanted in Mexico and
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Arellano Felix is on the FBI's ``Most Wanted List'' and
United States officials are offering up to $2 million for help in
his capture.
</P>
<P>
   The victims in the grisly pre-dawn shootings in Baja California
lived in the community of El Sauzel, which is near the Pacific
Coast city of Ensenada and about 60 miles south of the
Mexico-California border.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to describe something like this,'' said Mexican
Televisa television reporter Jaime Nieto, who observed spent
casings of AK-47 assault weapons scattered about pajama-clad bodies
and a blood-stained patio.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all the years I've been in this business I've never seen
anything like this,'' Nieto said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican government news agency Notimex reported that Baja
California Attorney General Marco Antonio de la Fuente indicated
that the killings may be linked to a dispute over drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Notimex reported that de la Fuente said one of the victims --
Fermin Castro, who is hospitalized in critical condition -- may
have been a marijuana grower for the Arellano Felix brothers.
</P>
<P>
   However, during a press conference in Baja California after the
killings de la Fuente refused to comment on Castro and said drug
trafficking was only one line of investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Baja California Gov. Hector Teran Teran was more blunt in a
statement released to the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state and county are in a state of consternation over the
killings of 19 people,'' he said. ``Based on the characteristics of
the action, it appears to be related to narcotics trafficking.''
</P>
<P>
   Teran Teran added that the crime's link to trafficking was
strong because Castro appeared to have a connection to the Arellano
Felix family.
</P>
<P>
   Castro, 35, was identified as a rodeo promoter in the Ensenada
area. Police said in addition to a narcotics connection, they will
also investigate whether Castro may have been a target of vengeance
because of a death that occurred at a rodeo he sponsored about a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Castro has gunshot wounds to the head and may not
survive.
</P>
<P>
   Television images of the death scene showed children's toys
scattered about yards and horses and cows grazing placidly, while
police and Red Cross workers scurried about.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the dead children included a two-year-old boy, a
four-year-old boy, and an eight-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   A girl of 12 was identified as one of four who survived the
killings.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported that a 15-year-old girl may have
survived by rolling under a bed; she is now in protective custody.
</P>
<P>
   Overturned chairs and broken glass in the yard where the
killings took place indicated that the victims may have struggled
with their killers.
</P>
<P>
   The three families lived on a ranch called El Rodeo, outfitted
with several large homes built in a Southwestern style. The ranch
reflected a rural but affluent lifestyle, not uncommon in the
seaside resort area along Baja California's Pacific Coast.
</P>
<P>
   The border city of Tijuana, which is to the north, is one of the
heaviest sites of cocaine and other drug smuggling into the United
States. The influence of drug dealers has spread south into the
Ensenada area, which is generally a quiet tourist area.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican authorities suspect that the Arellano Felix brothers,
considered extremely violent, may have been involved in the recent
slaying of Rafael Munez Talavera, a rival drug dealer in Ciudad
Juarez, across the border from El Paso, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
