<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1374 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-ASSE     09-17 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: CONGRESS ON TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Calif., N.Y., S.C., Fla.)  (See also: CLINTON-DAY, CLINTON-CONGRESS-SLEAZE,
CLINTON-EDITORIALS, CLINTON-BOSTON, CLINTON-RELEASE,
CLINTON-GINGRICH, CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-MINISTER,
CLINTON-CONGRESS-TV) 
(mk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It is not just the Clinton presidency that hangs in
the balance in these fevered Washington days. Before the eyes of
the nation, Congress itself is on trial.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans still tell pollsters that they yearn for the
sordid story of President Clinton's relationship with Monica
Lewinsky to go away. Yet in an all-day meeting Thursday, a sharply
partisan House Judiciary Committee battled inconclusively over the
release of thousands more pages of documents from Whitewater
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr as well as the release of the
videotape of Clinton's testimony before a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's quarrelsome session served as a prologue to the most
extraordinary of congressional duties _ impeachment. In the
Federalist papers, Alexander Hamilton called impeachment ``a method
of national inquest in the conduct of public men,'' and the
founders wrestled with who should have the awesome power to sit in
judgment on impeachments. They rejected the judiciary as too small
and possibly too subject to corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Yet could Hamilton have ever have pondered what a ``national
inquest'' might turn into in this new age of round-the-clock cable
talk shows and the Internet? Could he have forseen that the House
and Senate would be examining the most private, intimate actions of
a public man?
</P>
<P>
   These are the uncomfortable circumstances that Congress now has
to deal with, in an atmosphere made even more poisonous and
hysterical by the fact that the personal life of anyone in the
House and Senate these past few days seems to have become fair game
in the press.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, Judiciary Committee officials said they were
studying the 1974 Watergate inquiry as a model. It proved that the
nation could survive the disruption of impeachment proceedings,
even though Richard Nixon resigned before he could be voted out of
office. And it created national folk heroes like Sam Ervin, who ran
the Senate Watergate Committee, and Barbara Jordan, the freshman
congresswoman whose eloquence captivated the nation when she said
``today I am an inquisitor and hyperbole would not be fictional and
would not overstate the solemness that I feel right now.''
</P>
<P>
   But Watergate is a flawed model, in part because Watergate
itself changed Congress, journalism and the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The Congress of 1974 was one in which the leaders of opposition
parties could play golf together. It was not the highly partisan
Congress of Thursday where each side nurses grudges and looks for
payback for scandals stretching from Watergate to Iran-Contra, for
the forced resignation of Speaker Jim Wright, under an ethical
cloud, or the reprimand of Speaker Newt Gingrich on ethics charges.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was the Watergate inquiry taking place in an environment
where the presumption was that everything would somehow leak to the
press. The report of the Watergate special prosecutor Leon Jaworski
remains under seal to this day in the National Archives. But
Thursday some lawmakers say they have rushed to make everything
Starr assembled about Clinton public because they saw how much of
the Whitewater independent counsel's investigation found its way
into the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had shown they could keep from leaking stuff from the
grand jury I might have had a different position,'' said Rep.
Charles Stenholm, D-Texas, who favors the fullest release of the
materials before Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In this charged atmosphere, two sharply different approaches
have already emerged as the House moves ahead with a process that
is at once quasi-judicial and at once political.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans are playing for the court of public opinion,
acting like the entire nation is the grand jury. ``Impeachment is
intended to be a public process,'' said Rep. Christopher Cox,
R-Calif. ``It should not be more secret than a court proceeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are viewing the House itself as the grand jury and
fighting to protect the rights of the president until and unless
impeachment _ the equivalent of indictment _ takes place. ``The
normal procedure is that unless there's a damn good reason, you
don't release grand jury material,'' said Rep. Jerrold Nadler,
D-N.Y., who serves on the House Judiciary Committee, as he worried
about the precedent being set by the House.
</P>
<P>
   Politics too underlies the position of both parties, with a
national election just seven weeks away and Republicans and
Democrats alike aware that an impeachment inquiry could affect the
balance of power for a generation.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton's job approval ratings in polls still remains
confoundingly high, Republicans believe that a constant drumbeat of
revelations about the president's behavior with Ms. Lewinsky in the
Oval Office and attempts to cover the affair up will bring his
ratings down as the midterm election approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats know that to avoid a total rout, they have to turn the
spotlight away from the president and stop the scandal from
subsuming their attempts to talk about issues.
</P>
<P>
   A difficulty for all involved is that while Starr has raised
serious constitutional questions about perjury and obstruction of
justice, this coverup is all about sex, not about a burglary
against a political party or using the CIA to hinder an
investigation by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Inglis, R-S.C., a member of the Judiciary Committee,
says this distinction should not matter. ``It's all with the
coverup,'' he said. ``Same as with Richard Nixon.''
</P>
<P>
   But to decide such fundamental questions as whether Clinton did
commit perjury in his grand jury deposition, lawmakers may very
well have to ponder the president's attitudes toward sex and
re-examine in graphic detail what transpired between him and Ms.
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Picking his words carefully, Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., a
member of the Judiciary Committee, said, ``There are very sensitive
matters involved in this episode that no one wants to discuss in
public. It's very awkward. And I think we have to show dignity in
the way we conduct these proceeding.''
</P>
<P>
   But who can even imagine public hearings on these matters? Who
would ask the questions? Who would want to question Ms. Lewinsky?
Could anyone emerge as a hero? And what kind of dignity and privacy
would any member of Congress retain if this inquiry establishes the
rule that any politician's sex life is fair game?
</P>
<P>
   No wonder that the only area of agreement between House
Republicans and Democrats Thursday was the announcement by the two
re-election committee chairmen that thay would not finance
candidates this fall who make purely personal attacks on their
opponents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
