</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-RELEASE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLL FINDS MOST FAULT HOUSE FOR ISSUING ALL OF THE REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga, Minn., Pa., Texas)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(See also: CLINTON-DAY, CLINTON-CONGRESS-SLEAZE,
CLINTON-CONGRESS-ASSESS, CLINTON-EDITORIALS, CLINTON-BOSTON,
CLINTON-GINGRICH, CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-MINISTER,
CLINTON-CONGRESS-TV, CLINTON-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN) 
(js) 
 By MARJORIE CONNELLY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While most Americans approve of the way Congress is doing its
job over all, they disagree with the decision of last week to
release all of the independent counsel's main report, according to
the latest New York Times/CBS News poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually it was pretty annoying that they released it,'' said
Colette Tanner, a 22-year-old office manager from Seguin, Tex.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tanner, a respondent who was re-interviewed after the poll
had been completed, commends the work of Congress in general, but
on this she thinks the lawmakers went too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report has a lot of graphic details I didn't care to
hear,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The sexual details in the report of the independent counsel,
Kenneth Starr, are seen by most of the public as ``inappropriate''
information intended to embarrass President Clinton. The national
telephone poll was conducted with 1,813 adults from Saturday
through Monday, after the report had been posted on the Internet
and printed in newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-nine percent of the respondents said they disagreed with
Congress' releasing the report in full. There is even less support
for the release of videotape of Clinton's grand jury testimony: 70
percent of all Americans polled on Tuesday night by CBS News said
they would disagree with that step.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Congress does release the tapes, I will probably have a
little less respect for them,'' said Alison Lehman, 29, who also
disapproved of the scope of Starr's report.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to know about the alleged lies, but not about the
intimate details,'' said Mrs. Lehman, a day-care worker from
Rockledge, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Democrats and independents, most Republicans support
Congress' decision to release the report. But the Republicans join
the majority on the issue of the videotape. The release of the tape
in addition to the report is seen as unnecessary by 58 percent of
Republicans, 80 percent of Democrats and 72 percent of
independents.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of those polled said it was ``inappropriate'' for the
Starr report to have included graphic sexual details of Clinton's
relationship with Monica Lewinsky. In addition, 59 percent said
Starr's including such details was an effort to hurt and embarrass
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that detail is like mudslinging or name-calling,'' said
Vickie Prophitt, a 46-year-old insulation installer from Mount
Zion, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even among those who disagree with the decision to release
all the details, half approve of the overall job performance of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Those who saw Starr's report as fair and balanced _ they made up
one-third of all respondents _ were very positive in their
assessment of Congress, with 70 percent approving of the job it was
doing and 20 percent disapproving. People who considered the report
a ``one-sided look at only some of the facts'' _ half of all
respondents _ were divided in their view of Congress: 47 percent
approved, and 43 percent disapproved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress may be doing its job, but it is very upsetting and
not necessary to put out explicit sexual material,'' said Anson
Beaulieu of Bemidji, Minn., who considered the report one-sided.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I wouldn't think too much of Congress if they release the
videotapes,'' said Beaulieu, a 43-year-old self-employed auto
mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   The Times/CBS News poll had a margin of sampling error of plus
or minus two percentage points. The CBS News poll was conducted
with 429 adults and had a margin of sampling error of plus or minus
five percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
