<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMSEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JonBenet exhumation is just a rumor
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Rumors that JonBenet Ramsey's body might be exhumed
from her Marietta grave ignited when a local television news
station, citing unnamed sources, said Colorado officials had
inquired about the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   The reporter made clear that the calls to local officials were
preliminary and procedural, just in case the Colorado grand jury
decided another autopsy was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Since then Cobb County officials have been flooded with media
calls. Denials from the Boulder, Colo., police and prosecutors have
done little to slow the interest. Fuel was added to the fire when
Cobb County Medical Examiner Joseph Burton was seen on television
confirming that Cobb officials had received some calls.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Burton declined to discuss the matter. People in his
office said the story had been blown out of proportion. They said
they didn't know who made the calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now all we've heard is a lot of rumors,'' said Cobb
County Superior Court Judge Conley Ingram, stressing that his
office has received no calls or requests for a Ramsey exhumation.
</P>
<P>
   While several media outlets have run follow-up stories, some
newspapers, such as the Rocky Mountain News in Colorado, have
declined to run anything on the so-called story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically we're trying not to run rumors on this story,'' said
Deborah Goeken, assistant managing editor for news. ``We would want
to confirm it to the best of our ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Media expert Alan Caruba said conditions were perfect to create
a whirlwind of rumor. The Ramsey grand jury was meeting for the
first day, so the pressure was on for news stories, but the meeting
was secret so there was little to report.
</P>
<P>
   Though the initial story was filled with qualifiers, subsequent
reports added weight to the rumor and made the possibility of
exhumation sound more and more real, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a dubious story,'' said Caruba, a former editor for a
directory of media contacts and writer whose work has appeared in
The New York Times. ``But the pressure is on for journalists to
find new angles on an ongoing story. But there may not be a new
angle for days.''
</P>
<P>
   The public's interest in this story is heating up again. News
crews have been seen photographing JonBenet's grave in St. James'
Episcopal Church Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Eastep, 56, came from Maryland to visit the grave on
Thursday. It was his third trip. He said JonBenet reminded him of a
girl he used to baby-sit, who helped lift his spirits after he
suffered a bad car accident. ``She's my little guardian angel,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For an exhumation to occur, Boulder prosecutors must request
permission from a Cobb County Superior Court judge, and must make a
compelling case that additional evidence could be obtained. In such
a scenario, Ingram said he would allow the Ramseys to have their
say, though the judge could rule against their wishes.
</P>
<P>
   Exhumations are rare in Georgia, with only about three a year,
said Dr. Kris Sperry, the state's chief medical examiner. Having
read the girl's autopsy, he does not see any value in exhuming the
body.
</P>
<P>
   ``To call it a media circus would be a gross understatement,''
he said. ``This would be insane.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
