</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROACHES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pest free: Delta won't let a roach fly in coach
 &HT;    By Joe Earle
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Can cockroaches fly?
</P>
<P>
   Not without tickets, apparently.
</P>
<P>
   At least not Thursday on a Delta Air Lines flight from Atlanta
to California.
</P>
<P>
   Delta officials delayed Flight 217 from Hartsfield International
Airport to San Francisco for more than three hours after crew
members and passengers discovered cockroaches on the plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're obviously not going to accept anything less than a
pest-free plane,'' said Delta spokeswoman Laura Gillig.
</P>
<P>
   The flight originated in Atlanta and was supposed to leave about
9:15 a.m. But shortly after the crew and passengers boarded the
Lockheed L-1011, they spotted ``a handful'' of roaches near the
food service area, Gillig said.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot then refused to fly the plane, Gillig said.
</P>
<P>
   Delta gave the passengers coupons for lunch at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   The airline called the infestation ``an isolated incident'' and
said the passengers flew out on a roach-free plane about 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   No other similar incidents were reported Thursday, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, exterminators spray passenger planes at night, during
layovers between flights, Gillig said, and finding roaches on a
plane was highly unusual. ``That's why it concerned everyone enough
to get another plane,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Delta officials did not know Thursday how the roaches got onto
the plane. They were discussing the situation with representatives
of Dobbs International Services, which provides meals for Delta
flights, and with representatives of the pest control company,
Gillig said, to try to determine the source of the bugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You thought the Year 2000 bug was bad?'' she said. ``Let me
tell you ...''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
