<HEADER>
A1384 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HYDE-DEFENSE-HNS &LR;      09-17 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HYDE-DEFENSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE REPUBLICANS ASK FBI TO INVESTIGATE ALLEGED SMEAR CAMPAIGN BY
WHITE HOUSE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republican leaders Thursday accused the White
House of orchestrating a smear campaign against GOP House members,
including Judiciary Committee chairman Rep. Henry Hyde, and urged
the FBI to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   The White House vehemently denied that it was behind recent
disclosures of House members' past sexual indiscretions, including
an Internet magazine story about Hyde's five-year extramarital
affair in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Hyde, R-Ill., whose panel is deciding whether to
hold impeachment hearings against President Clinton, White House
Chief of Staff Erskine Bowles said any staffers participating in
such gossip would be fired.
</P>
<P>
   However, the GOP leadership was not convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are deeply troubled by recent media reports indicating that
certain individuals may be engaged in a systematic attempt to
intimidate Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde and other
elected members of the House from doing their constitutional duty
by promoting prurient allegations about their personal lives to the
media,'' the Republicans wrote in a letter to FBI Director Louis
Freeh.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these reports are true, the actions of the individuals
responsible are pure and simple intimidation _ no different than
threatening jurors to change their verdicts in organized crime
trails,'' they said. ``Therefore, we urge you to investigate these
reports in an effort to determine whether any individuals _ inside
or outside of the White House _ have made efforts to undermine the
lawful and constitutional work of the Judiciary Committee.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI issued a statement saying it will review the House
leadership's allegations. ``Appropriate steps will be taken to
determine whether a violation of federal law has occurred,'' the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas and the third ranking Republican in the
House, said it was no coincidence that the story of Hyde's
30-year-old affair broke on Wednesday, the day before the Judiciary
Committee began debate on whether to release Clinton's videotaped
grand-jury testimony about this affair with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky. ``This is not politics as usual,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay joined seven GOP colleagues in signing the letter to
Freeh. DeLay said Hyde's private life has ``nothing to do with him
carrying out his job as chairman.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay initiated a daylong attack on the White House with a
speech on the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I urge the president of the United States to stop his allies
from engaging in this disgusting conduct,'' DeLay said. ``This is a
very sad day for democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellow Republican Rep. Dana Rohrbacher of California said, ``We
will not be intimidated; we will not be blackmailed.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the GOP attacks, Rep. Martin Frost, D-Texas, said his party
would not support any candidate who exploits an opponent's
checkered personal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our candidates will win in November if they engage in a debate
on issues like HMO reform, Social Security and education,'' said
Frost, who chairs the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee.
``Attacks of an intimate personal nature only make the electorate
more cynical about the democratic process.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Linder, of Georgia, who chairs the Republican House
campaign committee, made a similar pledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initiating a personal attack on anybody running for office is
simply off limits,'' Linder said. ``We are soon going to have no
one of any stature willing to put themselves through this wringer,
and it is sad for America.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican attacks on the White House followed a report in
the Internet magazine Salon that Hyde, then an Illinois state
legislator, had an extramarital affair with Cherie Snodgrass, who
was also married at the time, from 1965 to 1969. Hyde confirmed the
report but vowed his committee would continue the review of
independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report alleging that Clinton
committed 11 impeachable offenses in trying to cover up his
relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statute of limitations has long since passed on my
youthful indiscretions,'' said Hyde, who was in his 40s at the time
of the affair.
</P>
<P>
   A retired Florida salesman, Norm Sommer, claimed credit Thursday
for giving the magazine the story about Hyde's affair. He said the
White House wouldn't call him back when he sought to tell his story
and many newspapers also declined to use his information. Salon was
the ``last on my list,'' he told the Associated Press. He said he
learned of the affair during a tennis match with Snodgrass' former
husband about six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The revelations about Hyde's past followed similar disclosures
about other Republicans this month.
</P>
<P>
   House Government Reform and Oversight Committee Chairman Dan
Burton, R-Ind., whose panel is investigating alleged campaign
finance abuses by Clinton, admitted to fathering a child during an
extramarital affair in the 1980s. Rep. Helen Chenoweth, R-Idaho,
acknowledged that after her divorce she had an affair with a
married man in the 1980s. Both confessions came after newspapers
began investigating their pasts.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spokesman Mike McCurry has denied GOP accusations that
the White House was behind those disclosures. ``If someone from the
White House was engaged in any such activity they would no longer
be on staff,'' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay and other Republicans pointed a finger at White House aide
Sidney Blumenthal, who had been named in television news reports as
trying to shop the Hyde story.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to DeLay, House GOP leaders who signed the letter to
Freeh included Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga.; Majority Leader Dick
Armey, R-Irving; Deputy Whip J. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill.; Conference
Chairman John Boehner, R-Ohio; Conference Vice Chairman Jennifer
Dunn, R-Wash.; Linder; and Policy Chairman Christopher Cox,
R-Calif. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
