<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1392 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-EDITORIALS-2T     09-17 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EDITORIALS-2TAKES-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO STAY OR NOT TO STAY? A QUESTION THAT WEIGHS ON EDITORIAL
WRITERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-DAY, CLINTON-CONGRESS-SLEAZE,
CLINTON-CONGRESS-ASSESS, CLINTON-BOSTON, CLINTON-RELEASE,
CLINTON-GINGRICH, CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-MINISTER,
CLINTON-CONGRESS-TV, CLINTON-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN) 
(sw) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jane Eisner, the editorial page editor of The Philadelphia
Inquirer, knew the jagged contours of the debate before it started.
Long before the release of the independent counsel Kenneth Starr's
report, it was clear that some colleagues believed, passionately,
that President Clinton's deceit made him unfit to remain in office.
An equal number felt just as passionately that his resignation now
would weaken the nation's most cherished institutions.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Eisner said she was not expecting the feelings of
profound exhaustion and ``nausea'' she experienced when finally,
after two and a half hours of anguished arguments, Chris Sattulo,
the deputy editorial page editor, went to write the Sunday
editorial that began with the words ``Bill Clinton should resign.''
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday, The Inquirer, once a staunch supporter of the
president, was one of at least 115 daily newspapers in the country
_ out of more than 1,500 _ to make the same plea to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But the informal tally boards that list newspapers like The
Inquirer, The Chicago Tribune, The Daily Oklahoman and The San Jose
Mercury in a ``resign'' column cannot reflect the depth of debate
at these papers. Old friends and colleagues find themselves
bringing to the discussion, explicitly or implicitly, religious
convictions, attitudes about sex and adultery, and their sense of
the Constitution's mandates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is far weightier than most we deal with on a
day-to-day basis,'' said Don Wycliff, the editorial page editor of
The Tribune, which on Tuesday also called for the president's
resignation. ``It's one that everybody has an opinion on _ or
virtually everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back at the debate that led up to the resignation of
President Richard Nixon in 1974, Wycliff added: ``It's a debate
that, frankly, as I said in one of the early editorials, I had
hoped I wouldn't see having to repeat twice in a lifetime. Yet it's
come to that.''
</P>
<P>
   But he is not sure that newspaper editorials on such subjects
mean as much as they once did. ``This is like when you make a
presidential endorsement _ people don't any more look to newspapers
for guidance on that as they may have once in the past. You're
making more of a statement about yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   The editorial board of The Tribune _ which had endorsed
Clinton's opponents in both the 1992 and the 1996 elections _ was
also divided, but not as sharply as The Inquirer's. According to
Wycliffe and Steve Chapman, a board member who opposed the final
decision, the board was split about 2-to-1 in favor of the
resignation call.
</P>
<P>
   At The St. Louis Post-Dispatch, which has generally supported
the president and his policies, the ratio was different and the
paper declined to call for resignation. According to Christine
Bertelson, the editorial page editor, and William Freivogel, the
deputy editor, most of the 10-member board are still opposed or
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   ``My vote tends to go back and forth, Ms. Bertelson said. ``What
we're trying to do is balance our personal sense of moral revulsion
against the broader issue: what does this do to the presidency?''
</P>
<P>
   Saying that she and her colleagues were ``trying to step back
from the daily melodrama,'' she added, ``If he were my employer, my
employee, my colleague or my husband I'd say, `Pack your bags,
pal.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's my president,'' Ms. Bertelsen continued. ``Whatever
happens to his soul or to his marriage or to his sexual neurosis,
that's his problem. He's got to deal with that in another arena
where I don't have any business being, and the country doesn't have
any business being.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Bronson, the editorial page editor of The Cincinnati
Enquirer, said on Thursday that he and the six colleagues on his
editorial board had earlier urged readers to withhold judgment on
the Starr investigation until the report came out. ``As soon as we
saw the Starr report and got knee deep, we said, `This really
smells, we've seen enough, the evidence is compelling and
damning,''' Bronson said.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper, a longtime Clinton opponent, called for the
president's resignation in an editorial on Sunday. It reiterated
the call on Thursday because the president was in town. Commenting
on the public safety burdens of a presidential visit, the newspaper
said on Friday, ``We'd object to that any time, but today it is
especially odious _ one more insult added to the insufferable
injuries you have done to our nation and the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Editorial pages are perhaps the clearest expression of
publishers' viewpoints. In some of the recent deliberations,
publishers have taken direct part; at the Chicago Tribune, Mr.
Wycliff said, Monday's meeting was attended by the publisher, Scott
Smith, the editor, Howard Tyner and Jack Fuller, the president of
Tribune Publishing Co. the newspaper's parent.
</P>
<P>
   The Cincinnati Enquirer's editorials were signed off on by that
paper's president and publisher, Harry Whipple.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, publishers did not participate in the deliberations
of the The Post-Dispatch or The Philadelphia Inquirer. Among the
country's largest newspapers, USA Today has called for resignation;
The New York Times, The Los Angeles Times and The Washington Post
have not.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a general practice, we don't discuss the details of
Editorial Board deliberations,'' said Howell Raines, the editorial
page editor of The New York Times. ``But we have a position that
we've defined in a series of editorials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've said that the debates over impeachment and resignation
ought to reflect in large measure the judgment of the American
people, expressed through Congress, on whether President Clinton
should remain in office. We've acknowledged that this is a process
that may take some time to unfold and argued that it could be
resolved through a negotiated settlement built around a
congressional censure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said that an essential feature of any settlement would be
that it recognized the sanctity of the law by requiring the
president to acknowledge that he testified falsely under oath.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, The Philadelphia Inquirer had locked itself into a
decision back in January when it had editorialized, ``If,
sorrowfully, the President of the United States obstructed justice,
suborned perjury or committed perjury, he should resign.''
</P>
<P>
   The earlier, provisional call for resignation was on Ms.
Eisner's and Satullo's mind as the meeting convened at about 4 p.m.
Ms. Eisner laid out the board's options: calling for resignation,
calling for the president to stay in office or avoiding the issue.
</P>
<P>
   One of The Inquirer's columnists, Trudy Rubin, who has been
particularly critical of the independent counsel's investigation,
spoke first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trudy's first point, among many, was that one thing we could
say was that the release of this report was a grave constitutional
error,'' Sattulo recalled. ``Trudy also feels very strongly that
the investigation is improper and tainted.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rubin would not comment on the deliberations themselves, but
did say, ``The subject matter under discussion is possibly the most
important domestic issue in many of our careers. It involves
institutions, not just a man. There are very serious disagreements
on our editorial board and in the country about whether this
process is going to weaken those institutions and is going to
function in the proper fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Eisner said, ``There was a great deal of discussion saying,
`It's too soon, let's wait,''' ``I was not satisfied with that. So
I tried to lead them through a conversation: what would make the
difference?'' between calling for resignation or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would public opinion make a difference? Well, how do we judge
public opinion? Would his effectiveness in office make a
difference? How do we judge his effectiveness in office? I hoped I
was doing that to make people realize that we had come to a
conclusion,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   With two members absent, the colleagues were evenly split. It
was a difficult moment in a process that usually operates by
consensus, in which votes are rare. With consensus impossible,
hierarchyy took over, and Ms. Eisner and Satullo's position was
adopted.
</P>
<P>
   Readers responded in surprising numbers. According to Kevin
Ferris, who edits the letters to the editor and community voices
sections of the newspaper, about 500 readers faxed, E-mailed or
called the paper on Sunday and Monday. The E-mail response was
split 50-50 he said; but about 60 percent of the callers wanted the
president to remain in office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
