<HEADER>
A1397 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-TV-N     09-17 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-TV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NETWORKS SORT OUT PLANS FOR SHOWING VIDEOTAPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-DAY, CLINTON-CONGRESS-SLEAZE,
CLINTON-CONGRESS-ASSESS, CLINTON-EDITORIALS, CLINTON-BOSTON,
CLINTON-RELEASE, CLINTON-GINGRICH, CLINTON-CONGRESS,
CLINTON-MINISTER) 
(mk) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If and when the House releases President Clinton's grand jury
testimony on videotape, much of the nation will get to see all four
hours almost immediately. CNN, Fox News Channel, MSNBC and a
variety of websites will carry it in full and without commercial
breaks as soon as they receive the feed from the House of
Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   But the major news networks appear to be taking a wait-and-see
attitude, wrestling with what Sandy Genelius, a CBS News
spokeswoman, described as ``uncharted territory, because of
material that may offend many people.''
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday night, CBS had still not decided whether it would
show parts of the testimony soon after the tape became available,
and if so what parts and how much, or whether, Ms. Genelius said,
``to put it on the air as it comes in.'' But the network has
decided to put the complete testimony on its website immediately,
except for a 20-second delay in case it is deemed necessary to edit
any words considered objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   ABC and NBC both plan to broadcast portions of the testimony
when it is first released, on the assumption that anything
objectionable is not likely to appear until later in the tape, and
to incorporate additional portions into regularly scheduled
newscasts. But the testimony will be broadcast simultaneously and
without interruption on the websites of both networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason for the different standard between networks and
their websites,'' Ms. Eileen Murphy of ABC said, ``is that everyone
has access to our network, including lots of children. On the
website you have to deliberately seek it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Most networks said that their decisions were made after debate
and discussion that ranged from polite to spirited. John Moody,
vice president of news editorial for Fox, said there were four
executive meetings to discuss such concerns as ``the widely held
suspicion there might graphic words and anatomical discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox would repeat the broadcast overnight and again early
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   C-Span, not unexpectedly, plans to broadcast the video in its
entirety, but not until 8 p.m. ET if it is released Friday. ``We're
committed to provide gavel-to-gavel coverage of the House,'' said
Richard Fahle, C-Span's spokesman, ``and since we're not in a race
for ratings, we'll put it on at a time when most Americans turn
their TV sets on for the night.'' But it will immediately put the
video on its website and broadcast it on its local FM radio
station.
</P>
<P>
   `We'll also re-air the video over the weekend,'' Fahle said.
``But we're not going to overplay it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
