A1399 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPAIN-BASQUES-NYT &LR;      09-17 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-BASQUES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPAIN'S LEADERS WARY OF BASQUE REBELS' CEASE-FIRE DECLARATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain _ The conservative government and the opposition
Socialist Party both reacted cautiously Thursday to the first
``indefinite'' cease-fire announced by the Basque guerrilla group
ETA in its 30-year battle for an independent homeland.
</P>
<P>
   But three smaller Basque nationalist parties, including one
linked to the guerrillas, expressed optimism that the truce could
lead to a lasting peace, although the rebels vowed for now to
retain their weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar said from Lima, Peru, where he
is on an official visit: ``After 30 years of terrorist activity we
cannot give ETA the benefit of the doubt. If ETA really wants to
end its path of death, it should know that credibility comes with
deeds, not words.''
</P>
<P>
   Aznar survived a bomb attack by the ETA in 1995, when he was the
opposition leader.
</P>
<P>
   Since last year the rebel group _ whose initials in the Basque
language stand for Basque Homeland and Liberty _ has killed five
town councilors belonging to Aznar's Popular Party. As a result,
police guards are now assigned to more than 100 of the party's
local officials.
</P>
<P>
   Both the government and the Socialists have insisted that there
can be no talks until the rebels, who have been accused by the
authorities of causing 800 deaths, renounce violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not content with a truce,'' said Joaquin Almunia, the
Socialist Party's secretary general. ``We want peace, which means
the permanent abandonment of arms, and respect for the law and the
results of elections.''
</P>
<P>
   The cease-fire, announced in a communique late Wednesday and due
to take effect Friday, comes just before the Oct. 25 elections for
the Basque regional parliament, where the moderate Basque
Nationalist Party has governed in minority for 10 years with
support from the Socialists.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Minister Jaime Mayor Oreja warned earlier in the week
that the anticipated truce offer could be a ploy to gain votes for
the nationalist parties. Last Saturday they seemed to bury their
own political differences by making a united appeal for peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
   ETA has observed four limited truces since 1981. The new
unconditional cease-fire comes when 535 convicted ETA members or
suspects are in Spanish jails. Dozens more are imprisoned in
France.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish government and courts have also cracked down on
ETA's supporters. Last December the Supreme Court sentenced all of
the top 23 leaders of the leftist Herri Batasuna nationalist party
to seven years in jail for collaborating with the rebels. In July a
judge shut down the newspaper Egin, in which ETA published its
communiques.
</P>
<P>
   Another paper, Euskadi Informacion, soon opened to replace it,
and published ETA's latest cease-fire communique. The Herri
Batasuna party, which has about 12 percent of the vote in the
Basque region, selected new leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The cease-fire communique said there was a ``unique occasion''
to advance Basque sovereignty. It derided as inadequate the
home-rule powers that Madrid has already accorded the three main
Basque provinces, whose 2 million residents have their own
parliament, taxing powers and a regional police force.
</P>
<P>
   But Aznar indicated Thursday that further autonomy would not be
given easily. ``Our constitutional and legal framework,'' he said,
``have been the constant references in the search for peace and
they continue to be fully in force.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
