<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-DISSIDENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA DETAINS TWO APPLICANTS FOR NEW PARTY  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Just days after dissidents in several parts of China
met small but encouraging signals when they applied to register a
political party, their counterparts in Beijing this week
encountered a different fate.
</P>
<P>
   Two dissidents who were about to submit a similar application to
the Beijing government have been detained and questioned by the
local police in the last 24 hours, and told not to proceed with
their request.
</P>
<P>
   One longtime advocate of democracy, Ren Wanding, who has spent
more than 10 years in custody, was taken from his house Thursday
afternoon for questioning and returned Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The other applicant, Ma Shaohua, a student leader of the
protests in 1989 in Tiananmen Square, was detained for four hours
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several of us had decided to go tomorrow to apply to form a
party,'' Ren said in a telephone interview after his release
Thursday night. ``They told me I couldn't go.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last 10 days three groups of dissidents have applied to
form branches of what the dissidents plan to call the China
Democratic Party. Dissidents from different regions have written
party bylaws that stress democratic principles like the election of
officials and regard for human rights. But the principles also
stress cooperation with President Jiang Zemin and the governing
Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   No party has been permitted to form since the Communist state
was founded in 1949. Because China has no clear procedure for doing
so, the dissidents are trying to register their new party as a
social organization.
</P>
<P>
   Last week two groups, in Shandong and Hubei provinces, received
what they considered somewhat encouraging responses from local
officials who, rather than rejecting the applications outright,
outlined the conditions for registration, a moderate fee, a
specified headquarters and a list of the local party's leaders and
members. A group of dissidents from the three far northeastern
provinces mailed a similar application to the Civil Affairs
Ministry here.
</P>
<P>
   Three months earlier, in Zhejiang province, a similar request
resulted in weeks of imprisonment for the applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Dissidents and scholars have wondered whether the apparent
change represents a new central government policy, dissent within
the government over how to handle such requests or an effort to put
on a good face for Mary Robinson, the United Nations High
Commissioner for Human Rights, who completed a 10-day visit to
China on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The detentions Thursday suggest, at the very least, that China
has not relaxed the central policy.
</P>
<P>
   Yao Zhenxian, a dissident who was considering applying to form a
party in Shanghai, was also detained Thursday, said the Hong
Kong-based Information Center for Human Rights and Democracy in
China.
</P>
<P>
   Ren suggested that the applications had perhaps been received
more kindly in the provinces, because security in Beijing tends to
be particularly tight.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
