<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-MASSACRE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNMEN SLAY 19 IN MEXICAN MASSACRE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Gunmen dragged men, women and children from three
houses before dawn Thursday near the Pacific Coast port of
Ensenada, lined them against a wall and riddled them with bullets.
</P>
<P>
   At least 18 people _ including an infant and six other children
_ were killed on the spot. One person was reported to have died
later.
</P>
<P>
   Police offered no clear motives for the killings. But a Mexican
news agency said a man who has ties to a powerful drug-smuggling
organization, was critically wounded in the attack, and Mexico's
national media and political leaders speculated that the massacre
was linked to narcotics trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen swept into El Sauzal, a community about 60 miles
south of San Diego, Calif., about 4:30 a.m. Thursday. They entered
a compound where the three houses were located, forced the victims
into a courtyard and opened fire.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican television images from the scene showed the victims
laying in front of a low wall, all either dressed in pajamas or
partially or fully naked, as if given no time to dress by the
killers. Hundreds of spent bullet casings, from either AK-47
automatic rifles and 9 mm pistols, littered the ground near the
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Children's bikes and other toys stood mute in the yard and the
concrete porches of what appeared to be expensive houses set behind
an elaborate iron fence. El Sauzal sits about six miles north of
Ensenada on the main coastal highway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears they rounded them all up, lined them up and gunned
them down,'' said Jose Ramon Espinosa, a state police agent in
Ensenada.
</P>
<P>
   Notimex, the government's news agency, quoted Baja California
state prosecutor, Marco Antonio de la Fuente, as saying the
surviving victim, Fermin Castro, worked in the marijuana growing
operations of the powerful Arrellano Felix narcotics organization.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, however, he said that there was no clear
motive for the slayings.
</P>
<P>
   The gang, headed by four Arrellano Felix brothers, is based in
Tijuana and smuggles much of the Mexican marijuana and heroin and
Colombian cocaine into the United States. Authorities say the
Arrelano Felix brothers' gang now comprises Mexico's most powerful
and bloody cocaine and narcotics trafficking organization.
</P>
<P>
   A port and fisheries center about 60 miles south of the border
on the coast, Ensenada is a popular weekend destination for many
Southern California residents.
</P>
<P>
   Although the level of violence pointed to by the massacre has
been rare in Mexico, local reporters said Thursday that the
Ensenada area has recently been racked by gangland killings and
police busts linked to Mexico's narcotics trade.
</P>
<P>
   But the Arrellano Felix brothers' many feuds with rivals have
left hundreds of dead this year in Tijuana, the border city an
hour's drive north of the site of Thursday's massacre. The brothers
have been blamed for the attempted assassination last fall of Jesus
Blancornelas, a Tijuana newspaper publisher who has often
campaigned against the smugglers and their alleged protectors
inside the Mexican government.
</P>
<P>
   Members of a well-to-do Tijuana family, the Arrellano Felixes
are widely assumed to be Mexico's dominant narcotics smuggling
organization since the death last year of Amado Carrillo Fuentes,
whose own gang was based in Ciudad Juarez, across the border from
El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Another powerful Juarez drug traffickers, Rafael Munoz Talavera,
was murdered last week in Juarez. U.S. and Mexican police suggested
Munoz was killed in the ongoing struggle to replace Amado Carrillo
as the principal trafficker in that area of the border and
predicted more deaths.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Scores of Mexican army troops and state and federal police
agents swarmed into the compound where the massacre took place,
blocking access to reporters on the scene. Roadblocks reportedly
were thrown up in the area throughout the day in hopes of turning
up suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Massacres involving women and children are rare in the Mexican
underworld. But such killings occur occasionally in the
drug-producing mountains of southern Guerrero and Oaxaca states. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
