u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLYMPIC-HISTORY-COX     09-17 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPIC-HISTORY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Interviews remember '96 Games
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The Atlanta Olympics are destined to be the best
documented Games in history.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation is assembling an
Olympic oral history, which will contain hundreds of hours of
videotape and thousands of pages of transcripts recording
recollections of the 1996 Summer Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really adds the human interest to the whole Games
experience,'' said Linda Stephenson, executive director of the
foundation, the nonprofit organization responsible for maintaining
the archives of the Games. ``Everyody seems to have a story to
tell, and we want to hear them.''
</P>
<P>
   The oral history project will be launched with a two-day public
event this weekend at the Atlanta History Center. About 50
invitees, including Olympic staff, athletes, local businesspeople
and politicians, will give in-depth interviews. But regular folks,
be they Games spectators, volunteers or out-of-town visitors, also
will have the opportunity to share for posterity their defining
Olympic moment.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals will be videotaped on a first-come, first-served
basis with about two minutes allowed to tell their story. Officials
such as Olympic chief Billy Payne and ceremonies producer Don
Mischer will be recorded for 30 minutes each and the public can
watch the tapings. Longer follow-up interviews will be conducted
later with officials and volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Every interview from athletes, such as handball team captain
Matt Ryan and gymnast Kerri Strug, to the Atlantans off the streets
will be taped, transcribed and cataloged. The oral history will be
archived at the Atlanta History Center _ alongside the rest of the
story.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic Games Collection already contains about 1,500 boxes
of documents, 3,900 hours of video footage, 300,000 photographs and
5,000 objects including uniforms, ceremonies costumes, lapel pins
and assorted souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   Other histories of the Games have been captured in print and on
film. The ``Official Report'' of the Games published last year
required three volumes and 1,500 pages of very small type to tell
the behind-the-scenes story _ from the beginning of the bid process
in 1987 to the closing ceremony Aug. 4, 1996. And Olympic
cinematographer Bud Greenspan's official three-hour film of the
Games, ``Atlanta's Olympic Glory,'' is in re-runs on television.
Information: 404-814-4000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
