<HEADLINE>
JEWISH SETTLER HELD AFTER PALESTINIAN TEEN IS SLAIN, ANOTHER HURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ A Palestinian teen-ager was killed and another was
wounded Thursday in the West Bank when a Jewish settler fired at a
group of Palestinian youths.
</P>
<P>
   The settler later surrendered to police, saying stones had been
thrown at his car. A spokeswoman for the Israeli police said
details of the incident were being investigated.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting, in the village of Beitunia, occurred at a time of
rising tension in the West Bank, after Israeli troops killed two
brothers, fugitives from the militant Islamic group Hamas, last
week near Hebron.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths of the brothers, Imad and Adel Awadallah, inspired
pledges of revenge from Hamas and set off several days of
stone-throwing protests in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Youths who said they witnessed the shooting Thursday insisted
that it had been unprovoked, although they acknowledged that there
had been stone-throwing clashes with Israeli soldiers in the area
this week.
</P>
<P>
   The youths said two settlers fired from their car at a group of
teen-agers returning from the Beitunia high school, hitting two in
the stomach. Jewish settlers use a road through the village to
reach their communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no stone throwing and no need for shooting,'' said
Hassan al-Qadi, a high school student who said he had been at the
scene. ``They were shooting randomly.''
</P>
<P>
   One victim, Iyad Qarabseh, 17, died in a hospital in Ramallah
from what a doctor described as bullet wounds from an M-16 rifle, a
weapon that Israeli settlers and soldiers carry. Another pupil was
wounded by the same ammunition, the doctor said.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting added to the pessimism surrounding a mediation
effort by the U.S. Middle East envoy, Dennis Ross, who has
apparently made little progress this week in bridging gaps between
Israelis and Palestinians that have stalled peace negotiations for
18 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of settler violence that is contributing to
the demise of the peace process,'' Nabil Shaath, a member of the
Palestinian Cabinet and a senior negotiator, said. ``Without
serious Israeli action this is going to create such an explosive
situation that it is really very difficult to see how we can
contain it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross, who pressed on with his mission in Gaza, said, ``Anything
that makes it more difficult to reach an agreement is the last
thing we want to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross, who had been expected to leave the region Friday, has
extended his visit until Saturday, a U.S. official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
