<HEADER>
A1409 &Cx1f; tth-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LINDA-SMITH-CRITICIZE     09-17 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINDA-SMITH-CRITICIZE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINDA SMITH LASHES OUT AT OPPONENT PATTY MURRAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. Rep. Linda Smith, fresh off her decisive
victory in the GOP primary for U.S. Senate, Thursday attacked Sen.
Patty Murray's positions on education, defense, trade and sexual
misconduct by public officials.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith's accusation that Murray has ignored the needs of
Washington state apple and wheat growers was immediately
contradicted by leaders of both those industries.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference outside the U.S. Supreme Court with other
GOP lawmakers from Washington state, Smith alleged that Murray is
so compromised by her support of free trade that she has ignored
the needs of Washington's two biggest agricultural commodities:
apples and wheat. Despite U.S. trade deals with many countries,
producers of apples are suffering from trade disputes with China
and Mexico while wheat farmers narrowly escaped serious harm
earlier this year when the United States temporarily banned grain
exports to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patty Murray ... has been silent on trying to get apples into
China,'' Smith said. ``She was out when we tried to get apples into
Mexico _ she was just silent when it came to those. (And) when it
came to Pakistan, if it hadn't been for Senator (Slade) Gorton and
Representative (George) Nethercutt, we wouldn't be getting wheat
into Pakistan.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the apple and wheat industries contested those
descriptions. And even a cursory review of press clippings and
Murray office records indicates that Murray has over the years
introduced legislation, held meetings with U.S. and foreign
officials, issued news releases and given speeches about the
problems facing Washington apple and wheat growers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Murray has been very supportive of our industry,''
said Kraig Naasz, president and chief executive of the U.S. Apple
Association. (Naasz is no longtime Murray fan _ he was the press
secretary for the 1992 Senate campaign of Republican Rod Chandler,
who was defeated by Murray, and he has worked for a variety of
Washington state Republicans, including Gorton.)
</P>
<P>
   Naasz said Murray ``played a critical role'' in getting U.S.
Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky to pay attention to the
apple industry's problems with Mexico, which last year accused
Washington state apple growers of harming the Mexican apple
industry by exporting to Mexico apples priced below cost.
</P>
<P>
   And Naasz said Murray is in line with the apple industry's
position on trade with China, which imposes steep tariffs on apple
imports from the United States. Murray, whose position is opposite
that of Smith but in sync with that of the apple industry, supports
Most Favored Nation status for China and believes tariff disputes
would best be resolved through negotiations with China over
membership in the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   As in the apple situation, lawmakers from both parties can claim
credit for helping the wheat industry in Washington this year, when
sanctions imposed by President Clinton against Pakistan threatened
to cut off wheat exports to that nation. Republicans, who control
Congress, played a key role in passing legislation to exempt wheat.
But Murray was highly visible on the issue, introducing
legislation, speaking on the floor, communicating the importance of
the issue to the White House and then using top White House
officials to help persuade reluctant Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patty Murray has represented state and national wheat growers
effectively, and she has a staff that understands very well the
importance of agriculture in her district,'' said Bill Flory,
president of the National Association of Wheat Growers.
</P>
<P>
   Told of the apple and wheat groups' comments, Smith spokesman
Jim Troyer said the real work on behalf of Washington state wheat
farmers was done by Nethercutt, not Murray. And he said the
continuing problems facing U.S. apple growers in China show Murray
has been ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   International trade is one of numerous issues where Smith, a
two-term Republican congresswoman from Hazel Dell, differs from
Murray, a first-term Democratic senator from Seattle. Smith is a
critic of free trade, arguing that the United States has been to
quick to overlook human rights and specific trade concerns in its
eagerness to sell products, while Murray has supported free trade.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Smith also criticized Murray's positions on education,
national defense and sexual misconduct by public officials. Smith
supports allowing states to decide about education spending, while
Murray supports a stronger federal role in education; Smith
supports funding a new missile defense system, which Murray
opposes; and Smith has called for President Clinton to resign
because of his affair with Monica Lewinsky, while Murray has
expressed anger and hurt over his conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Murray's campaign spokesman, Rex Carney, criticized Smith's
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate that Congresswoman Smith is already resorting
to negative attacks and distorting Senator Murray's record, but
this is what we have seen before from her,'' Carney said. ``This is
how she operates, and the people of Washington deserve better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
