u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-TAX-NYT &LR;      09-17 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PANEL APPROVES $80 BILLION TAX CUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Ways and Means Committee passed an $80
billion Republican tax cut on Thursday, setting up a confrontation
with President Clinton over how the nation should take advantage of
its return to fiscal health.
</P>
<P>
   Defying Clinton's insistence that projected federal budget
surpluses be set aside until Congress and the administration have
settled on a plan to shore up Social Security, the committee voted
23 to 15, largely along party lines, to dip into the surplus to pay
for a package of tax reductions likely to have broad appeal to the
middle class.
</P>
<P>
   Amid a rancorous debate over how to use the surplus, Democrats
admitted that they were sorely tempted to support the tax cut, both
because it has many provisions they have pushed for and because it
is less than two months before a congressional election. But in the
end only one of the committee's 16 Democrats, Rep. Barbara Kennelly
of Connecticut, who is running for governor and lagging in the
polls, sided with the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a vow on Thursday by Clinton to veto it, the tax bill is
expected to pass the full House as soon as next week. It will then
go to the Senate, where its prospects are uncertain. The bill has
the support of most of the Senate's 55 Republicans, and could
attract some Democrats. But under the Senate's procedures, it will
need 60 votes to pass because it will require a waiver of budget
rules to permit use of the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's committee vote was an important test of Clinton's
ability to hold his party together on politically difficult issues
as he struggles to avoid impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   His call to preserve the surplus has been the centerpiece of
Clinton's domestic policy agenda this year, and any widespread
defections by party members on the issue would have signaled
concern among Democrats that the president could no longer provide
them the cover they need to vote against popular tax cuts in favor
of the more nebulous benefits of fiscal restraint.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was tailored by Republicans to have broad middle class
appeal, and its main provision is a break for married couples. It
would raise the standard deduction for couples filing jointly to
$8,600, from $7,200. The change is intended to address the
so-called marriage penalty, the quirk in the tax code that leads
many two-income couples to pay bigger tax bills than they would if
single.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would exclude from taxation the first $400 of interest
and dividend income for couples filing jointly, and $200 for single
filers. It would accelerate the timetable under which self-employed
people will be able to deduct their health insurance costs and
speed up a gradual increase in the amount of an estate exempted
from federal taxation.
</P>
<P>
   It would make changes intended to insulate moderate-income
families from the effects of the alternative minimum tax, which was
designed to apply to wealthy taxpayers but increasingly results in
a tax increase for working families. To appeal to farm state
legislators, the measure would provide tax breaks to farmers and
ranchers who have been hit by a downturn in agriculture. And to
address the concerns of lawmakers from poor districts, it would
create tax incentives for redevelopment programs.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, who heads the committee, said the
bill would preserve nearly 90 percent of the coming budget
surpluses _ projected by the Congressional Budget Office at $1.55
trillion over the next decade _ while trimming a tax burden that by
some measures is the highest since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sets money aside to save Social Security and it gives
middle-income Americans the tax relief they need and deserve,''
Archer said, adding that the tax cut might also give the economy a
boost at a time when the global financial crisis is threatening to
slow growth in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also said Clinton's demand to save the surplus for
Social Security was hollow since the administration had proposed
using the surplus to pay for emergency spending for the
peacekeeping mission in Bosnia, strengthening security around
American embassies and preparing for the year 2000 computer
problem.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats said it would be irresponsible to start spending
the surplus on tax cuts before the nation determines how to deal
with the coming financial shortfall in the Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, they said, nearly all of the surplus for the next 10
years will come from the payroll taxes that are supposed to be
earmarked for Social Security. Not until 2006 will the government
start to run a significant surplus without counting the excess
Social Security payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for the Social Security trust fund, we wouldn't
even be showing a budget surplus,'' said Rep. Charles Rangel of New
York, the committee's senior Democrat. ``The surplus belongs to
Social Security _ it's not a spare cookie in the bottom of the jar
there for the taking.''
</P>
<P>
   Several hours before the vote, Clinton, in a speech to a labor
union group, said using the surplus would send the wrong signal to
the world about the nation's fiscal and economic stability at a
time of increasing global financial turmoil. But mostly, he said,
it would make it more difficult to make up the looming shortfall in
Social Security, which although healthy now will run short of money
in about 30 years after the baby boom generation retires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our friends in the other party say that, well, we're
projecting a surplus and it's close to the election, so let's give
everybody a tax cut,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care how close it is to the election,'' he added, ``it
is wrong to do that until we have solved this problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
