<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MYANMAR-POLITICS-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURMESE OPPOSITION ISSUES RISKY CHALLENGE TO THE JUNTA 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand _ In their riskiest challenge yet to the
military rulers of Myanmar, a small group of opposition politicians
said Thursday that they would act as the country's legitimate
parliament and declared all laws and proclamations issued by the
ruling junta null and void.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 politicians, led by Daw Aung San Suu Kyi, are members of
the National League for Democracy, which won an election in 1990 in
the former Burma for a parliament that was never allowed to take
office.
</P>
<P>
   When Mrs. Aung San Suu Kyi announced last month that she planned
to convene parliament, the military responded with its biggest wave
of arrests since a crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators in 1988
that took thousands of lives. The league said Thursday that 843
members of the party had been arrested, including 195 of its
elected representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is the most volatile and unpredictable moment in
the last 10 years in Burma,'' said Josef Silverstein, an expert on
the country at Rutgers University.
</P>
<P>
   With the opposition taking a giant gamble and the military
refusing to compromise, a diplomat in Myanmar called the
confrontation ``an approaching train wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   In its statement Thursday, the opposition said, ``The Committee
Representing Elected Lawmakers formed by the National League for
Democracy on Sept. 16 decided it will perform the functions of the
parliament until a formal parliament session is called under the
1990 multi-party democratic election law.''
</P>
<P>
   Its first parliamentary act was to call for the release of all
political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate response by the government Thursday, but
the junta has warned that any attempt to convene parliament would
be illegal.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days the language of official statements has grown
more threatening, describing pro-democracy forces as traitors and
terrorists. Published commentaries have suggested that Mrs. Aung
San Suu Kyi might be deported. Some political analysts say the
junta could be preparing to try to stamp out the opposition party
once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is pretty serious stuff,'' a Western diplomat said in a
telephone interview from Myanmar, which has been closed to foreign
reporters for weeks. ``This is an existential moment. Time is
ticking away here. So we are all extremely worried and nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   In a country whose military leaders have demonstrated their
readiness to shoot their opponents, the heightened challenge by
Mrs. Aung San Suu Kyi is a dangerous one.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition challenge has won support from parts of the
country's powerful Buddhist hierarchy and from some much-respected
retired military men, who have issued statements supporting Mrs.
Aung San Suu Kyi's call for a dialogue with the leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the ethnic insurgencies that have reached cease-fires
with the government have also recently made statements in her
support.
</P>
<P>
   Recent weeks have also seen what may be the reawakening of an
active student movement, traditionally the foundation of protest in
Myanmar.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For more than a month small groups of students have reportedly
staged hit-and-run rallies in the capital, Yangon, formerly
Rangoon, sometimes distributing leaflets before quickly disbanding.
</P>
<P>
   The All Burma Students Democratic Front, an exile group based in
Thailand, said Thursday that four high school students arrested in
connection with a demonstration on Sept. 9 had been sentenced on
Wednesday in Myanmar to five years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``The students are the unknown quotient here,'' Silverstein
said. ``I don't know how well they are organized; nobody knows.
They demonstrated 10 years ago that they could organize secretly to
the point of being quite effective.''
</P>
<P>
   As a protective measure, the authorities have closed all
universities since the last student demonstrations in December
1996.
</P>
<P>
   As the country's economy has worsened, with inflation and
unemployment rising and food shortages emerging, diplomats and
other residents say, the patience of many people with their
military rulers may be wearing thin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rank and file as well as the leadership of the NLD has
simply reached the point where they are not prepared to see time
just continue to drag on, year after year, with the government
never delivering on its promise to step aside and create a
multi-party democracy,'' a diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   But the options of the pro-democracy movement are limited. As in
1988, when virtually the whole nation rose up against its
government, the men with the guns may again have the last word.
</P>
<P>
   Any possible tactical debate in the military leadership seems to
have been won, for now, by hardliners who appear determined not to
compromise with the opposition even if it means driving their
country further into international isolation, several analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
   There may be members of the ruling junta who see the benefits of
a more subtle approach, said Bertil Lintner, a journalist who is
the author of several books on Myanmar. ``But the hardliners think,
the hell with that. The moment they sit down and talk with Aung San
Suu Kyi it's almost like admitting defeat. Talking, discussion,
dialogue _ this is not part of their political vocabulary.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said, ``there could be another crackdown that would
crush the NLD.'' He added: ``These guys are fighters who don't know
anything about the outside world. They don't care. They are
prepared to do totally irrational things like shooting people in
the streets, as they did in 1988.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 2034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
