<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BOSTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CRITICISM EXTENDS TO DEMOCRATIC ENCLAVES OF BOSTON
</HEADLINE>
   (Also moved in `w' category; with: CLINTON-DAY,
CLINTON-CONGRESS-SLEAZE, CLINTON-CONGRESS-ASSESS,
CLINTON-EDITORIALS, CLINTON-RELEASE, CLINTON-GINGRICH,
CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-MINISTER, CLINTON-CONGRESS-TV,
CLINTON-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN) 
(JT) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Even here in one of the most Democratic states in the
country and one of the most liberal cities, President Clinton has
been unable to escape withering criticism for his sexual affair
with a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   As the House Judiciary Committee in Washington debated the
release of his taped grand jury testimony, Clinton arrived Thursday
afternoon for a fund-raising dinner Thursday night in the wake of
harsh comments by a leading Massachusetts Democrat who refused to
attend the dinner, which was expected to raise more than $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview that appeared Thursday in The Boston Herald,
Thomas Finneran, the speaker of the Massachusetts House and a
Democrat, referred to the Watergate scandal of 24 years ago and
said President Clinton ``almost makes Nixon look like a moral
giant, the way it is going.''
</P>
<P>
   Stopping short of calling for Clinton's resignation, Finneran
said of the scandal: ``It's not just a stain on Bill Clinton's
presidency. It's a stain on the office of the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Finneran could not be reached Thursday for further comment. His
chief of staff, William Kennedy, said the speaker left Wednesday
night for a weeklong business trip to Portugal. Kennedy said that
he did not hear the interview in which the remarks were made but
that their sentiment accurately reflected Finneran's views.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran's comments are among the strongest delivered by any
Democrat since Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel,
sent his report to Congress last week, accusing Clinton of perjury,
obstruction of justice and other violations. While the accusations
have left many Democrats ambivalent _ supportive of Clinton's
policies but chagrined over his personal behavior _ few have spoken
out so sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Harshbarger, who won the Democratic primary for governor
on Tuesday, also criticized Clinton in the article, calling his
behavior ``a terrible lapse in judgment.'' But Harshbarger tempered
his remarks with praise of administration policies and said he
planned to attend Thursday night's dinner.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
