<HEADER>
A1433 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARCHER-DANIELS-GUILTY     09-17 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHER-DANIELS-GUILTY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY SAYS 3 EX-EXECUTIVES OF ARCHER DANIELS FIXED PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KURT EICHENWALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three former executives with Archer Daniels Midland Corp. _
including the son of its powerful chairman, Dwayne Andreas _ were
found guilty Thursday of engaging in an international conspiracy to
fix the prices of a widely used additive for animal feed.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict by a federal jury in Chicago marked an important
victory for prosecutors, capping a six-year effort by the
government to crack an illegal corporate cartel and bring
participants to trial. The investigation and trial have already
been declared hallmarks by the government, which said it upended a
conspiracy that controlled the prices of $1 billion in commerce
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   But the case and Thursday's verdict also has had an enormous
impact as well on Archer Daniels _ a food giant that advertises
itself as the ``supermarket to the world'' because it is a leading
processor of corn, oilseeds and wheat. The Decatur, Ill.-based
company's influence extends to virtually every grocery store aisle.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, it has been run as a virtual family fief under the
iron-fisted control of Dwayne Andreas, one of the nation's most
politically powerful executives who is known by presidents and
prime ministers alike. Despite that influence, Dwayne Andreas was
unable to stop the weight of the judicial system from falling upon
his son and onetime heir apparent, Michael.
</P>
<P>
   Over the seven-week trial, prosecutors presented evidence unlike
any ever offered in court in a price-fixing case, including audio
and video recordings of the illegal price-fixing meetings between
the defendants and their international competitors who made the
additive, known as lysine.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence, including testimony from co-conspirators,
portrayed price-fixing as common in the industry. Evidence was
offered pointing to price-fixing in at least one other product, and
conspiracies among foreign competitors that dated back decades.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants were Michael Andreas, on paid leave from his
position of vice chairman with Archer Daniels; Terrance Wilson, a
former head of the company's corn-processing division, and Mark
Whitacre, a former head of its bioproducts division, which
manufactures lysine.
</P>
<P>
   Sentencing was set for Jan. 7. The men face a maximum penalty of
three years in jail and a $350,000 fine. But the defendants could
be forced to pay more, since under the law the government is
allowed to seek twice the amount gained in the crime or lost by the
victims _ in this case, the purchasers of lysine.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Andreas nor Wilson showed any emotion when the jury of
six men and six women announced their verdict. They left the
courtroom without comment. Whitacre, who waived his right to attend
the trial, was not in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Andreas and Wilson said that they would appeal the
verdict. ``We've been fighting this for three years, and we are
going to continue to fight it,'' said John Bray, a lawyer for
Andreas. ``We're not through.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Walker, Whitacre's lawyer, said that he believed that the
jury had reached a conclusion on his client's guilt based in part
on the recorded evidence against the other defendants. ``I hate to
use the words `guilt by association,' but that's the way it
seems,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The conviction of Whitacre for price-fixing is the latest turn
in a series that have bedeviled this case from the beginning. It
was Whitacre himself who first alerted the government to
price-fixing at Archer Daniels in 1992. For the next two and a half
years, he worked as a government informant, secretly recording
meetings with competitors and conversations at the highest reaches
of the politically powerful grain giant.
</P>
<P>
   But, soon after raids on Archer Daniels in 1995, Whitacre was
discredited as a witness and eventually lost his immunity from
prosecution when it was revealed that he had been secretly taking
millions of dollars from the company, even while working as a
government informant. Whitacre contended that the money was
provided as part of an under-the-table bonus plan at the company,
but government investigators concluded that was not true.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Whitacre pleaded guilty to fraud, and was sentenced
to more than nine years in prison. Any additional sentence in the
price-fixing case is likely to be concurrent, according to lawyers
in the case, meaning it will not increase the time Whitacre spends
in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the trial, attacking Whitacre's character was a
central strategy of lawyers for Andreas and Wilson. They contended
that no price-fixing had ever occurred, and that Whitacre was an
out-of-control informant who set up their clients. But almost all
of the defendants' arguments were presented during
cross-examination in the government's case; the defense rested
after little more than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the conviction, Walker said that Whitacre felt good
about part of the verdict. ``He feels vindicated that they did
prove there was price-fixing,'' he said. ``But he didn't prove out
the bonus plan. He is going to fight to prove out the bonus plan
for the rest of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors and agents with the FBI expressed delight and relief
at the verdict. ``It's been a very long time,'' said Brian Shepard,
the FBI agent who was most involved with Whitacre during the
investigation. Shepard added that the case had ``completely
dominated'' his life since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   James Griffin, head of the midwest office for the Justice
Department's antitrust division, portrayed the victory as one that
would help in the continued enforcement of antitrust laws. ``This
verdict provides momentum for the division,'' he said. ``It proves
juries will hold accountable business executives who engage in this
kind of business activity that in effect defrauds Americans of
millions of dollars a year.''
</P>
<P>
   At this time, Griffin said, the Justice Department has more than
30 grand juries looking into potential antitrust violations.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said that both sides brought an enormous amount of
resources to the case. ``This is one of the hardest-fought trials
that I have ever been involved in, in terms of the firepower
brought in by both sides,'' said Scott Lassar, the U.S. attorney in
Chicago. ``There was no stone left unturned by either the
government or the defense.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In part, the enormous legal firepower stemmed from the riches
and influence won by the Andreas family during their decades at
Archer Daniels. Since the time of Thomas Dewey _ the former New
York governor and Republican presidential candidate who served as
an adviser to Andreas when he was a lawyer in private practice _
Archer Daniels has been a strong political force. With an ease that
bred envy among other corporations, the $9.2 billion food industry
giant navigated the shores between the Republicans and Democrats
while helping to form this country's agricultural policies.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, prosecutors portrayed Wilson, 60 years old, as
the man with the daily responsibility for the conspiracy. Andreas,
49, was portrayed as providing approvals for strategy.
</P>
<P>
   But the prosecutors also said that Andreas was responsible for
getting the conspiracy back on track when suspicions and cheating
among the competitors led prices to collapse. The central piece of
evidence in support of that argument was a videotape, taken in
October 1993, of a meeting between Andreas, Whitacre and the senior
executives of Ajinomoto Co., a Japanese competitor. Whitacre was
acting as a government informant at the time.
</P>
<P>
   On the videotape, Andreas appeared to be directing an effort to
allocate shares of the lysine market in the coming year among
competitors, a critical element of a price-fixing conspiracy.
``They can each have 2,000 tons more in 1994,'' Andreas said of the
other lysine producers. ``And we get the rest between you and us.''
</P>
<P>
   That tape had impact not only on the jury, but on Archer Daniels
itself. Once considered the most likely successor to his father,
Michael Andreas has since taken a paid leave from the company. A
spokesman for Archer Daniels had no comment on the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   All told, the government's investigation of the food and feed
additive industries has resulted in eight criminal cases against
nine corporations and eleven executives, almost all of whom pleaded
guilty. Almost $200 million in fines have been imposed by courts or
recommended as part of plea agreements. Archer Daniels itself
pleaded guilty in 1996, and agreed to pay a $100 million fine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
