u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RACE-REPORT-NYT &LR;      09-17 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT'S ADVISORY BOARD ON RACE PRODUCES MODEST REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After more than 15 months of work, President
Clinton's Advisory Board on Race has produced an extraordinarily
modest report whose chief recommendation is the creation of a
permanent presidential council on race.
</P>
<P>
   The voluminous report breaks little new ground and is, in many
ways, simply a compilation of observations and recommendations that
the seven-member board made to Clinton as it went about its work.
While it is filled with policy suggestions on education,
affirmative action, health, the criminal justice system and
immigration, the report lists four major recommendations:
</P>
<P>
   _ Establishment of a permanent body, to be known as the
President's Council for One America, to promote harmony and
dialogue between the country's racial and ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   _ Formation of a public education program to keep the public
informed about race in America.
</P>
<P>
   _ Promulgation of a presidential ``call to arms'' to government
and private-sector leaders across the country to ``make racial
reconciliation a reality.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Engaging youth leaders to build bridges between races.
</P>
<P>
   A number of scholars and civil rights advocates say the board
squandered an opportunity to make a bold contribution to
stimulating an informed discussion of race that moved beyond the
familiar positions of both liberals and conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those sound like a list of platitudes,'' said Randall Kennedy,
a Harvard Law School professor after hearing the panel's main
recommendations. ``My goodness, there is nothing substantive there.
It's not like I'm searching for a fight. But that's not exactly
giving people direction. Talk about lowest common denominator.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is to receive the report at the board's final meeting on
Friday. White House officials said he would incorporate some of its
recommendations and suggestions in a larger report on race and
ethnicity that he will issue by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The report marks the final chapter in the troubled history of
the advisory board, which was headed by John Hope Franklin, the
noted black historian. Almost from its inception in June 1997, the
board was troubled by a lack of organization, a youthful staff with
few policy experts in areas it studied, a lack of political
experience and continued interference by White House officials who
feared the political consequences of its work.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is timidity on this question,'' said Thomas Kean, the
former Republican governor New Jersey who is a board member. ``Race
is very divisive. As the year wore on, people became _ not the
board _ but, people in the administration became concerned. We were
not encouraged to be bold. My recommendations were much bolder than
anything contained in this report.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, with attention being diverted by the investigation of
the president's affair with Monica Lewinsky, the board was
hamstrung in efforts to stimulate a dialogue on race throughout the
country, one of its major goals.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Judith Winston, the board's executive director, said the
panel was able to achieve a measure of success. ``We have done what
the president asked us to do this initial year,'' she said in an
interview. ``Certainly the advisory board has carried out its
mandate.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Winston and White House officials say the board was never
expected to be an independent body like the Kerner Commission,
which investigated the country's racial climate after a series of
urban riots in the late 1960s and produced bold policy
pronouncements. Instead, the panel was to serve as Clinton's ``eyes
and ears,'' gathering information that would help him develop his
later report on race.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't want to create a commission that sort of went off
and did things independently and on its own,'' said one White House
official, who would speak only if not identified. But with
expectations having been raised by Clinton himself when he began
his initiative on race relations with a speech at the University of
California at San Diego, there was a palpable sense of
disappointment in the board's work by civil rights advocates and
those who study the country's racial climate.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond its main recommendations, the board's report did contain
many other suggestions, including some it had made before in
letters to the president. It recommended expanded enforcement of
the nation's civil rights laws. It called for an end to sentencing
disparities for crimes involving crack on one hand and powder
cocaine on the other. It recommended more money to be spent on
teacher training and school construction in minority areas, and
efforts to end income inequality.
</P>
<P>
   And, the board reaffirmed its support for race- and sex-based
affirmative action, declaring that ``for far too many minorities, a
level playing field remains a mirage.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the board ducked making any recommendations on many other
highly contentious issues that surround race and ethnicity, such as
busing to achieve school integration, the construction of
scatter-site public housing for poor minorities and the use of
school vouchers to allow poor children to attend private schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not able, in the short amount of time we had, and the
format we were working in, to cover the horizon,'' said Angela Oh,
a Los Angeles lawyer who was a board member.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
