<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Sept. 20,
1998. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category)
</P>
<P>
   FEATURE Stories
</P>
<P>
   TV-CENSORSHIP (subslug) (Undated) _ Last week, Fox ran an on-air
promotion for a pair of sitcoms, ``Living in Captivity'' and
``Getting Personal.'' To make the point that the shows were sassy
and sexy compared with tamer Friday night programming on other
channels, the commercial depicted a man being chased as a
voice-over announced, ``We ran the censors off, and boy, does it
show!'' It's easy to see the appeal of such a sales pitch to the
much-coveted youth audience, which has long felt a healthy
antipathy toward anyone trying to tone down the latest records,
music videos or sitcoms. But for more mature viewers who've been
battered in the last year by Jerry Springer's catfights, Howard
Stern's genitalia gags, ``South Park's'' scatological cartoon
children and ``Dawson Creek's'' libidinous teen-agers, the sight of
one more television guardian who has turned tail and run for cover
may not be particularly comforting. By Warren Berger. &UR;  &LR; (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   MONET-ART (Boston) _ The progress of Monet's reputation says
something, I suspect, not just about ``Monet in the 20th Century,''
which is the name of the show now at the Museum of Fine Arts, but
also about the public's relationship to 20th-century art generally.
Why is he so popular? Lots of great artists aren't. He didn't cut
off any ears or fail to sell his paintings before he died _ in fact
for much of his life he was immensely rich and successful _ so
there's no obvious biographical angle. Ultimately the answer must
be in the pictures, and I think it involves the essential soft core
of the art: the way works like the Water Lilies become passive
receptacles for nostalgia. Monet's popularity reveals our desire
for art as both refuge and spectacle. By Michael Kimmelman.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-MORALS (Los Angeles) _ The questions of how honest or
constrained the arts and entertainment are in these politically
charged times are exceptionally difficult to answer. Pressure
groups engaged in what are often called the culture wars have never
been more visible, commercial concerns have never been more
pressing, and, without a doubt, the arts have never been more
probing or explicit. By James Sterngold. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   FILM AND VIDEO
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA-FILMS (Tblisi, Georgia) _ This small nation nestled
under the towering Caucasus Mountains, which has a history
stretching back several millennia but which emerged from the debris
of the Soviet Union only seven years ago, has a rich creative
tradition based on the mixture of fantasy and reality. In the 20th
century that tradition has been expressed most vividly in film, and
today a hardy group of more than a dozen filmmakers is struggling
against severe economic constraints, trying to preserve, extend and
deepen it. By Stephen Kinzer. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   PECKER-FILM (Baltimore, Md.) _ ``Pecker,'' is filmed in John
Waters's hometown of Baltimore, where he has made all 13 of his
movies, most famously his 1972 cult classic, ``Pink Flamingos.''
``It's about a photographer called `Pecker,' '' the publicity agent
explained one day on the set in December. The movie which opens on
Friday is a comedy about a young fellow (Edward Furlong) who's a
short-order cook in a sub shop and takes pictures all the time, of
rats caught in flagrante delicto (Waters often employs rats for his
films), a woman shaving her thighs on a bus, his own sweetly
dysfunctional working-class family, that sort of thing. When he is
``discovered'' by a chic Manhattan art dealer (Lili Taylor) and
becomes the sensation of the New York art world, Pecker's everyday
Baltimore life, including the relationship with his girlfriend
(Christina Ricci) who runs _ well, rules _ the local laundromat, is
threatened. By Vicki Goldberg. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   THEATER
</P>
<P>
   DYING-GAUL-THEATER (New York) _ The return of ``The Dying Gaul''
to the Vineyard Theater, where it closed in June, conjures up
titles befitting a parody of a bad movie sequel _ ``The Gaul That
Would Not Die,'' perhaps, or ``The Dying Gaul: Resurrection.'' And
on one level, that's fine with the author, Craig Lucas. `` `The
Dying Gaul' (italics)is(end italics) a Hollywood satire,'' said
Lucas, who knows that world well as the adapter of several of his
own plays to film _ ``Prelude to a Kiss'' and ``Reckless'' _ and
the author of the screenplay for ``Longtime Companion.'' By Steven
Drukman. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   INFERNO-THEATER (New York) _ The award-winning version of the
``Inferno,'' translated from the Italian by Robert Pinsky, the
United States Poet Laureate, has found its way to the footlights.
Directed by Robert Scanlan and produced by the Unterberg Poetry
Center of the 92d Street Y, the play, following a brief run in
Boston, begins performances in New York on Saturday at Playhouse 91
and runs through Oct. 4. By Celia Wren. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   LOLITA-THEATER (New York) _ Jeremy Irons will play Humbert
Humbert on the big screen, starting on Friday, when Adrian Lyne's
long delayed, much persecuted film of Vladimir Nabokov's once long
delayed, much persecuted novel, ``Lolita'' opens. By Karen Durbin.
(Moved).
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DANCE
</P>
<P>
   KEERSMAEKER-DANCE (New York) _ The world of dance did not pause
in its erratic spin when a young Belgian dancer named Anne Teresa
De Keersmaeker presented what amounted to her first choreography in
1981 at a festival in Westchester County, near New York City. A
solo set to Steve Reich's ``Violin Phase,'' the dance was
uncompromisingly formal and repetitious. Though it was recognizably
influenced by the post-modernist dance minimalism of the time,
unexpected undercurrents of emotion set the solo apart. Ms. De
Keersmaeker, then a student at New York University, added a duet to
the solo and two more duets to the piece on her return to Belgium
the next year. The four-part dance, called ``Fase'' and set to four
pieces by Reich, established Ms. De Keersmaeker, who was to become
a major international dance talent over the next four years. She
will return to those roots on Tuesday at the Kitchen in five
performances of ``Fase,'' which will be accompanied by a symposium
and film screenings on Thursday and a video installation. By
Jennifer Dunning. (Moved). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRUITTE-DANCE (Undated) _ Cultural history is filled, of course,
with gifted individuals whose stories and contributions have become
lost in time. But Kevin Ward, the resident choreographer of the
Dayton Contemporary Dance Company, has not forgotten James Truitte,
an early and beloved mentor, who died in 1995 at age 72. Ward's new
``Offering,'' an homage to Truitte, will be performed by the Dayton
troupe starting Tuesday at the Joyce Theater, in a one-week season
that also includes revivals of dances by Asadata Dafora and Talley
Beatty and works by Donald Byrd and Sharon Leahy. By Jennifer
Dunning. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   CLASSICAL MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   STAGE-FRIGHT-MUSIC (New York) _ In music, stage fright may take
the form of icy fingers, shaky limbs, a racing heart or a blank
mind, and musicians report all manner of strategies to cope with
it. Teachers and psychologists offer strategies, too. In recent
years, schools have started addressing anxiety in courses dealing
with performance techniques or career preparation. By Eleanor Blau.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ANONYMOUS-4-ALBUM (Undated) _ Anonymous 4 has just released its
eighth recording, and it will not be surprising if this CD, ``A
Lammas Ladymass,'' sails to the top of the classical charts as most
of the group's earlier efforts have. But this new album of chant
and polyphony for the Roman Catholic feast of the Assumption, which
celebrates the Virgin Mary's passage into heaven, is itself a rite
of passage. By Cori Ellison. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   LP-IMAGES-MUSIC (Undated) _ Going back to the neighborhood of
one's youth and finding familiar objects smaller than remembered is
an experience shared by most of us. I had the same feeling, not
long ago, picking up a CD of Ravel's piano music and finding on its
cover the shrunken image of an LP record I knew some 45 years ago.
Sony Classical's Masterworks Heritage series, of which this two-CD
release is a part, represents a foolproof sales strategy, at least
where the middle-aged market is concerned. For this is our past,
perfectly reconstructed _ nostalgia we can touch in miniature By
Bernard Holland. (Moved).
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BARRAQUE-MUSIC (Undated) _ When the French composer Jean
Barraque died in 1973, at 45, he left behind a tiny body of work
and an enormous reputation. According to the version of
20th-century musical history put forward by Andre Hodeir in his
book ``Since Debussy,'' in 1961, Barraque, though he had written
just four works at the time, delivered the promises that had been
only partly fulfilled by Schoenberg, Stravinsky, Messiaen and
Pierre Boulez. This accolade brought him notoriety, and a paragraph
in Time magazine, but it probably caused him little embarrassment,
because it coincided pretty well with his own estimate of his
worth. In the few interviews he gave, he kept coming back to the
necessity of greatness. There was no room now, he felt, for minor
masters: the game of music had to be played for ultimate stakes.
And though he never quite said so directly, he strongly implied
that he judged himself _ and demanded to be judged _ at the level
of the few composers who for him were the absolute greats: Bach,
Beethoven, Schubert and Debussy. Whether he can be placed in their
ranks, only time _ not Time _ will tell. By Paul Griffiths.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   POP MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   ANATHEMAS-ALBUMS (Undated) _ Profanity? Check. Blasphemy? Check.
Threats and imprecations? Check. Drug references? Check. Sex talk?
Check. Distorted guitars? Check. Shouts, moans, growls? Check. With
those essentials and a little hysterical publicity, an ambitious
rock band can be on its way to becoming the anointed anathema: the
band that teen-agers flaunt as a symbol of alienation while their
parents worry enough to believe the worst. Just in time for
back-to-school, two leading anathemas have released their latest
albums: Marilyn Manson's ``Mechanical Animals'' and Korn's ``Follow
the Leader.'' By Jon Pareles. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   MIDLER-MUSIC (Undated) _ Bette Midler's up-and-down recording
career has always been about juggling personas to create a portrait
of an entertainer (and woman) of many (often contradictory) parts.
And ``Bathhouse Betty,'' her first album for Warner Brothers after
more than two decades on Atlantic, is arguably her most
multifaceted collection since her 1972 debut recording, ``The
Divine Miss M.'' By Stephen Holden. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   ROBERT-JOHNSON-MUSIC (Undated) _ Although the great blues singer
and guitarist Robert Johnson died 60 years ago, swallowed up at 27
by the rural Mississippi demiworld of juke joints and barrelhouses
that spawned him, he looms ever larger in Americas imagination.
Johnson had been dead for 23 years when an LP of his songs, ``King
of the Delta Blues Singers'' was released in 1961. It became a
sacred text to 60s folk and blues revivalists as well as to
rock-and-rollers curious about rock's origins. In 1990, after
protracted legal wrangling, came ``Robert Johnson: The Complete
Recordings'': two CDs, 29 songs and 12 outtakes. Improbably, it
became the record-business phenomenon of the winter of 1991,
briefly outselling Madonna, winning a Grammy and going on to sell
more than a million copies worldwide. Fifty-three years after his
death, Robert Johnson was a pop star. By Tony Scherman. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   ART
</P>
<P>
   MONUMENTS-VIDEO-ART (Chrlestown, Mass.) _ From Thursday through
Saturday, on three consecutive nights, the stories of bereaved
Charlestown mothers, whose sons were murdered, will be projected in
video onto the Bunker Hill Monument, Charlestown's most conspicuous
and famous public structure. Through the wizardry of Krzysztof
Wodiczko, a Polish-born conceptual artist, the 221-foot-tall
Egyptian-style obelisk will be transformed into a nighttime granite
goddess, its massive form first made to seem weightless through
animation, and then weighty with the gravity of these mothers'
tales. By Ken Shulman. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES
</P>
<P>
   CHINESE-FURNITURE-ANTIQUES (Minnepolis, Minn.) _ The Minneapolis
Institute of Art, will show 75 pieces of Ming and Ching furniture
that was given to the museum by a long-time trustee Bruce Dayton
and his wife, next Sunday. By Rita Reif. (Moved).
</P>
