<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MINISTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON MINISTER JOINS TWO COLLEAGUES IN COUNSELING CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-DAY, CLINTON-CONGRESS-SLEAZE,
CLINTON-CONGRESS-ASSESS, CLINTON-EDITORIALS, CLINTON-BOSTON,
CLINTON-RELEASE, CLINTON-GINGRICH, CLINTON-CONGRESS,
CLINTON-CONGRESS-TV, CLINTON-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN) 
(js) 
 By LAURIE GOODSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rev. J. Philip Wogaman, a Methodist pastor and Christian
ethicist from Washington, is the third minister who will privately
counsel President Clinton as part of a newly formed pastoral
``accountability group,'' said the Rev. Tony Campolo, one of the
other ministers in the group.
</P>
<P>
   Wogaman is the pastor of Foundry United Methodist Church, where
the president and his family have attended services for several
years. The other two ministers, who confirmed their roles early
this week, are the Rev. Gordon MacDonald, pastor of Grace Chapel in
Lexington, Mass., and Campolo of St. Davids, Pa., an evangelist who
runs ministries for the urban poor in the United States and Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will pray with him, study Scripture together and do our
best to help him as he searches his heart and soul,'' Campolo said
in a statement on Monday. ``We want him to understand what went
wrong with him personally that led to the tragic sins that have so
marred his life and the office of the presidency. We want to
provide all the help that we can to spiritually strengthen him
against yielding to the temptations that have conquered him in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   Campolo said in a brief interview that the three clergymen would
confer together, and then at least one of them would meet with the
president once a week.
</P>
<P>
   Campolo said that if the ministers sensed that the president
needed the kind of psychological counseling or treatment that the
three clergymen could not provide, they would advise him to seek
additional help.
</P>
</TEXT>
