<HEADER>
A1445 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-FBI-     09-17 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-FBI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE GOP CALLS ON FBI TO INVESTIGATE SOURCE OF REVELATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-CONGRESS-TV,
CLINTON-CONGRESS-SLEAZE, CLINTON-CONGRESS-ASSESS, CLINTON-DAY,
CLINTON-EDITORIALS, CLINTON-BOSTON, CLINTON-RELEASE,
CLINTON-GINGRICH, CLINTON-MINISTER, CLINTON-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN) 
(JT) 
 By DAVID STOUT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Republican leadership asked the FBI on
Thursday to investigate rumors that ``certain individuals'' have
been dredging up embarrassing personal information about some
members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these reports are true, the actions of the individuals
responsible are pure and simple intimidation,'' top Republicans
said in a letter to the bureau's director, Louis Freeh. The letter
was signed by Speaker Newt Gingrich, Reps. Dick Armey of Texas, the
majority leader, and Tom DeLay of Texas, the majority whip, and
several others.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department did not have an immediate comment,
although it is routine for such requests to be evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   The letter follows a rash of embarrassing disclosures about
Republican House members. The latest came on Wednesday, when an
Internet magazine told of an affair that Rep. Henry Hyde of
Illinois, the chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, had three
decades ago with a married woman.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde's committee is reviewing evidence compiled by the
Whitewater independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, to help determine
whether President Clinton should be impeached for conduct related
to his affair with a former White House intern, Monica Lewinsky.
Hyde's panel is also considering whether to release the videotape
of the president's grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has heatedly denied any role in finding such
information. In a letter to Hyde Thursday, Erskine Bowles, the
White House chief of staff, repeated the White House pledge of
``zero tolerance'' for smear tactics. And Sidney Blumenthal, a
special White House assistant who has been rumored to be the source
of some anti-Hyde leaks, Thursday dismissed those suggestions as
``completely false.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, both the Internet magazine Salon, which released
the information, and the person who provided the information to
Salon said there had been no contact with the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, DeLay called the timing of the Hyde article
``really interesting'' and accused the White House of ``lying, of
covering up, of stonewalling, of trying to destroy their enemies
for years.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
