A1453 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-WEIGHIN     09-17 0336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-WEIGHIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bean's 231 pounds his most ever
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Servicce
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Evander Holyfield's next heavyweight title defense
may be in Atlanta, but his opponent looks like he has been visiting
the famous Las Vegas buffets.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn Bean weighed in at an all-time high of 231 pounds
Thursday at the Westin Peachtree Plaza, then offered this
explanation for his seemingly bloated state: ``I feel good. I'm
still growing.''
</P>
<P>
   If this were sumo, Bean would have a 14-pound advantage over
Holyfield Saturday night at the Georgia Dome. Holyfield weighed in
at 217 pounds, which is consistent with his recent bouts.
</P>
<P>
   Bean, who is about three inches shorter than Holyfield, is eight
pounds heavier than he was for his last bout, a third-round TKO
over Lamont Burgin in April. He is a whopping 19 pounds heavier
thanfor his previous title shot against Michael Moorer in March
1997.
</P>
<P>
   His promoter, Butch Lewis, nonetheless said, ``What kind of
weight is that? It's the winning weight.''
</P>
<P>
   But Don Turner, Holyfield's trainer, said, ``He's too big, man.
That means he can't move.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield will conclude his workouts at 10:30 this morning at
the Holyfield Arena in West End. It is open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket giveaway
</P>
<P>
   Promoter Don King wants to give away 2,000 $25 tickets to
Atlanta-area kids. Any youth or church groups or other
organizations interested in receiving tickets to the fight should
contact the Don King Productions office at 404-589-7621. ... More
than 26,000 tickets had been sold by Thursday afternoon. ... What
do boxers do the day of a fight? Not usually this: Holyfield will
watch two of his sons play football games Saturday. ... Holyfield
is planning a postfight ``Homecoming Party'' at the Georgia World
Congress Center Saturday. Tickets, at $25 and $50, will benefit the
Holyfield Foundation. They are available at GWCC.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
