<HEADER>
A1454 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-HUMMER-COLUMN18-C     09-17 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HUMMER-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holyfield sure is making his rounds
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Before Evander Holyfield defends one of his
over-accessorized belts Saturday night at the Georgia Dome, he will
attend to some really important business. That same morning, he's
determined to spectate at two of his sons' football games. First, a
battle of pee-wees and one middle-school scrap. Then, he'll get
around to fighting for millions of dollars and a piece of the
heavyweight championship of the world. Sounds like a full day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just another day at the office,'' shrugged Holyfield, who
doesn't buy the notion that a man must spend the hours leading up
to a blood-letting in a deep, dark cave, with his feet elevated.
It's only a fight, after all, not an execution.
</P>
<P>
   Against this homey backdrop, today's challenge is to rank
Holyfield among Georgia's living, breathing sports personalities.
We're talking about athletes _ sorry, Ted Turner _ whose feats and
presence have made them local landmarks. Who is, or should be, most
important in the hearts of the hometown folk?
</P>
<P>
   The champeen is Henry Aaron. No debate. He's retired all the
belts. Here are my top-10 ranked contenders among the Georgia
sports heavyweights. They work just the same as boxing ratings,
meaning that for the right money, they can be changed:
</P>
<P>
   1. Holyfield
</P>
<P>
   2. Dale Murphy
</P>
<P>
   3. Herschel Walker
</P>
<P>
   4. Tom Glavine
</P>
<P>
   5. Bill Elliott
</P>
<P>
   6. Phil Niekro
</P>
<P>
   7. Gwen Torrence
</P>
<P>
   8. Dominique Wilkins
</P>
<P>
   9. Jeff Van Note
</P>
<P>
   10. Teresa Edwards
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield might be working out of the home, but he's still
covering a whole lot of ground. He has been out there _ really out
there _ in selling his fight with Vaughn Bean. Throwing out the
first pitch at a Braves game, dropping the flag at an Indy Car
race, training in the CNN Center or the westside gym that bears his
name. He was even spotted Wednesday night posing in a chef's hat
during a promotional barbeque at his home. There are no
indignities, only opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   So ubiquitous has Holyfield been around here, he should change
his first name to Peachtree.
</P>
<P>
   The profit motive behind all of that is strong, no doubt. He's
got 54,000 square feet in Fairburn to support. But there is a more
subtle undercurrent at work. In some ways, this fight is a
referendum on Holyfield's local popularity. The people will speak
with the tickets they buy. For the first time since Holyfield twice
disposed of Mike Tyson, there is a way to statistically measure his
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Where to put this supposedly undersized heavyweight who elevates
his sport and carries an Olympic torch in his spare time? I might
tend to rank Holyfield higher than some because of the fact that he
remains so connected to the community. Deep roots weigh heavily
with me; these characters should have done more than just change
planes here. He's my No. 1 ranked contender, based on
accomplishment and profile.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout most of his career, Holyfield has been an undervalued
Atlantan. Taken for granted in some aspects. Overlooked in others.
He's a couple laps down from perfect, but his intentions have been
as good as anyone who has ever earned a Midtown parade.
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to a lawyer to explain the finer points of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually everyone loves Evander, but a lot of people don't
like boxing,'' said Jim Thomas, Holyfield's point man. ``Many of
the same people like that more brutal, dangerous sport _ football.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can feel more comfortable loving a Dale Murphy than an
Evander Holyfield because it's easier to love baseball than it is
boxing. All things being equal, Evander is tops.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday _ the post-youth-football part of it, anyway _ is
scheduled to be a well-paying appreciation of Holyfield. Bean plays
the part of traditional homecoming opponent, trying to ruin a quite
sizable party.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield remembers what it was like to have sports figures who
were approachable and relevant. ``When I was growing up, different
athletes would come visit the (Warren) Boys Club,'' he said.
``Braves and Falcons, people who really inspired you. I remember
Claude Humphrey, Fulton Kuykendall, Tommy Nobis coming by. Even
Hank Aaron. And Chief Noc-A-Homa. They all talked about working
hard and setting goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he is among them, bettering the message.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
