<DOCNO> NYT19980917.0402 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1455 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-MOORE-COLUMN-COX     09-17 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-MOORE-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Frazier ready to bury hatchet with Ali
 &HT;    By Terrence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Imagine somebody shoving a boxing glove through the
eye of the world's smallest needle. That would be slightly less
incredible than what Joe Frazier just told us about Muhammad Ali.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier, squeezing our shoulder while sincerity ran through his
54-year-old eyes, said, ``What (Ali) and I need to do is get
together as soon as possible and kiss each other. We should
embrace. We should talk, and we should laugh together. Then we both
need to forget about all of those things that happened in the past.
It's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Hallelujah.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier is in town to help train Vaughn Bean for Saturday's
fight at the Georgia Dome against Evander Holyfield. Just so you
know, this would be a more competitive fight if Frazier were in the
ring instead of Bean. ``I'd beat up Evander, because I never let a
little guy take me out,'' said Frazier, laughing, still resembling
the human Army tank that he was as a former heavyweight champion of
the world.
</P>
<P>
   When we think of Frazier, we automatically think of the other
guy. We did just that while talking to Frazier about his popular
boxing gym back in his native Philadelphia. We also discussed his
healthy look, despite his fading hearing and eyesight and an
amputated toe.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, we thought about the last time we huddled with Frazier.
It was two years ago during the Atlanta Olympics. It wasn't pretty,
especially after we slipped, in Frazier's presence, by uttering his
old version of the worst profanity known to mankind _ Ali.
</P>
<P>
   As we told you then, it triggered the fourth Ali-Frazier brawl,
and that one was the bloodiest, even if it was verbal. For one,
Frazier threw all the punches. For another, Frazier just kept
throwing them. And with Frazier sticking and moving, Ali was
nowhere in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Among the many low blows, Ali was victimized by Parkinson's
disease because ``I don't think the Lord agrees with the things
he's done,'' Frazier said. ``I think it was the hand of the Lord
touching him and telling him that you can be (somebody), but you
can't be thee.''
</P>
<P>
   That was before Frazier was asked about that special look on the
faces of billions around the universe when Ali stood atop the
Olympic stadium to light the flame. Frazier, straight-faced, said,
``They probably were afraid he was going to fall in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Then it really got ugly. Just blame it on 25 years of
bitterness. In the latter 1960s, Frazier fought to help Ali get his
boxing license back after Ali's refusal to enter the armed forces
for religious reasons landed him out of the sport for 3 1/2 years.
Even so, Ali spent his subsequent holy wars with Frazier calling
his rough-looking opponent everything from a gorilla to the
white-man's fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier fumed. Until now. ``I haven't seen (Ali) since the
Olympics in Atlanta, and that was just briefly,'' said Frazier, his
words coming as gently now as they did as harshly then.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talk to his wife (Lonnie) all the time about how he's doing,
and she knows I've got no problem with him,'' Frazier said. ``Hell,
I'm 54 years old, man. We both have grandchildren running around.
This is something that has to stop, and that's why we have to get
together to end this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hallelujah and amen.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
