<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FLA-QBS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gators' QB Palmer out to prove himself
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ Jesse Palmer is a strong believer in the
adage: That which does not kill you only makes you stronger.
</P>
<P>
   It is why the sophomore from Ontario is still alive and kicking
and ready to start at quarterback for No. 2 Florida in Saturday
night's showdown with No. 6 Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer believes _ at least he hopes _ that he saw the worst side
of being a college quarterback last October when he got his first
career start against Auburn. Doug Johnson, the regular starter, had
been suspended for the game, giving Palmer his first real shot at
taking the job.
</P>
<P>
   But in front of a hostile crowd at Jordan-Hare Stadium, Palmer
threw two interceptions in the first half, and coach Steve Spurrier
pulled him in favor of senior Noah Brindise. The Gators went on to
win the game 24-10, but questions have remained about Palmer and
his ability to do the job in a big game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this is hard for people to believe, but I really
learned an awful lot in the game with Auburn,'' Palmer said. ``I
got a feel for the pressure, knowing that every throw you make,
every decision, could make or break the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer insists that he will take those lessons and put them to
good use before a larger and even more hostile house of 107,000 at
Tennessee's Neyland Stadium. Spurrier hopes he's right because
after two starts this season the jury is still out on Palmer as the
leader of the Gators' offense.
</P>
<P>
   In games with the Citadel and Northeast Louisiana, Palmer has
thrown for 593 yards and eight touchdowns. But he also has thrown
three interceptions and floated several other passes that could
have been intercepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesse will start because he's the best we've got right now,''
Spurrier said. ``He's thrown some beautiful passes. Hopefully, he
can learn from his mistakes, and, hopefully, we can put him in a
better position to make some plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee is preparing for Palmer, but Volunteer players and
coaches think Spurrier has a quarterback ace in the hole in
Johnson. Johnson, recovering from May 8 shoulder surgery, did not
see action against the Citadel and got only a handful of plays
against Northeast Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said earlier this week that his shoulder is close to 100
percent. But Spurrier is not convinced that Johnson, who threw for
2,023 yards and 21 touchdowns last season, is completely ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell that he's not throwing the ball the way he used
to,'' Spurrier said. ``If something happens, he'll be capable. But
you can tell his throwing motion is not what it was at this time
last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Given Johnson's performances in big games, including 261 yards
passing and three touchdowns in last year's win over Tennessee,
Volunteer coach Phillip Fulmer thinks Johnson will be a factor
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have to expect Doug Johnson,'' Fulmer said. ``He's
been big in the big games, and I would put this one in that
category.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier has not ruled out the possibility of using two
quarterbacks, as he did in Florida's 32-29 upset of No. 1 Florida
State last November.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's what it takes to get the job done, then that's what
we'll do,'' Spurrier said. ``We will always put the best players on
the field. The quarterback position is no different.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
