<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIPPLES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIAN CRISIS PINCHES SMALL COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By REBECCA ROLWING  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Times are grim at VSM Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sales have nose-dived,'' said Charles Vaughan, president of
the Tempe, Ariz., company that manufactures gas handling systems
and furnaces for the semiconductor industry.
</P>
<P>
   The business is among many small- and medium-sized companies
getting hammered as the effects of the Asian economic crisis
trickle down from the semiconductor's industry giants to its
suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's catching it,'' Vaughan said.
</P>
<P>
   Small companies sometimes bleed more because they have less cash
to endure a financial crisis and may rely on one or two large
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Layoffs, consolidations, hiring freezes, forced vacations and
shorter workweeks are occurring quietly as the Phoenix area's chip
suppliers tighten their belts to ride out the crunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the larger companies and the problems they're
having garner the most public attention. You don't hear much about
the small companies but certainly they're being impacted,'' said
Nancy Russell, president of the Arizona Association of Industries.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the state's mid-size high-tech companies, like
Three-Five Systems Inc., SpeedFam International Inc. and others
also are making adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   After laying off a third of its staff in June, VSM's 24
remaining workers have gone to a four-day work week. Sales this
year are half of what they were for 1997, a number Vaughan declined
to disclose.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the company will survive by marketing to other
industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're small enough that we can dodge the bullet,'' Vaughan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Around the world many semiconductor plants are shutting down,
making their equipment available to be refurbished and sold. The
availability of the used products cuts even further into the demand
for new equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a glut of equipment on the market,'' said Ken Rich,
who has a two-man operation that sells new and refurbished
equipment to semiconductor plants in Arizona and New Mexico. Three
years ago the company employed seven.
</P>
<P>
   Sales are off 80 percent from last year. The decline began
around January and has since ``fallen off a cliff,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ASM America, a 280-employee company in Phoenix, manufactures
equipment for the semiconductor industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are holding up fairly well but it's getting tougher and
tougher,'' President Daniel Queyssac said.
</P>
<P>
   The company has a hiring freeze in place and has instituted
forced vacation time.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Queyssac remains optimistic that the semiconductor
industry's troubles are turning around, noting that Intel Corp.
announced stronger sales for its third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Others are less hopeful. Motorola Inc. is the fourth major maker
to halt U.S. production of computer memory chips. It also announced
this week that it's shelving plans for a plant in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   SpeedFam International Inc., a Chandler, Ariz., semiconductor
equipment manufacturer, recently laid off at least 70 workers. It
was its second job reduction this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Management is now saying that they expect the industry
downturn to last until mid-1999,'' wrote Joe Blankenship, who
follows the company for the investment firm Peacock, Hislop, Staley
&AMP; Given Inc. ``This outlook is consistent with our recent revisions
of industry prospects for semiconductor equipment, in light of
continuing erosion of Asia economies.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the industry recovers, it will still take several months
before manufacturers begin to order new equipment again.
</P>
<P>
   Three-Five Systems felt sniffles of the Asian flu when Motorola
and some other customers demanded prices to meet the rates of Asian
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The Tempe manufacturer of displays for cellular phones and other
devices complied, dropping prices 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this action will result in gross margins being
reduced by nearly 66 percent,'' Blankenship wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Three-Five doesn't comment on analyst's forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to have an impact. The question is how much,'' CFO
Jeff Buchanan said. The company plans to ask its suppliers, most of
whom are Asian, to cut their rates as well.
</P>
<P>
   Three-Five also expects demand for cellular phones to pick up
and grow over the next several years. That means Three-Five can
spread its fixed costs over a greater number of products and make
its devices for less. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Rebecca Rolwing may be reached at rebecca.rolwing(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
