<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-MASSACRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNMEN SLAY 19 IN RAID ON 3 FAMILIES IN MEXICO  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By SAM DILLON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENSENADA, Mexico _ Gunmen dressed in black and carrying assault
rifles pulled three families from their homes early Thursday
morning and shot at least 20 men, women and children against a wall
in what the police described as a drug-related slaying.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, the authorities were still providing conflicting
versions of events that occurred in a suburb of this city, 60 miles
south of the California border.
</P>
<P>
   The executions took place in the concrete driveway of a
two-story stucco home on a hillside in Vista al Mar, a cluster of
houses a mile from the Pacific Ocean. Soldiers from the Ensenada
army garrison and Baja State judicial police officers refused to
let reporters enter the walled compound Thursday afternoon, as
detectives stood staring at a pool of blood in the driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Killed or wounded in the attack were Fermin Castro, 38, his wife
and 2-year-old son; his brother-in-law, Francisco Flores
Altamirano, 30, Flores' 52-year-old mother, his sister, his wife
and five children aged 4 through 13, and a family of seven
neighbors, including a pregnant teenager and a 1-year-old child. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The killing came hours after Castro produced a rodeo for an
independence day celebration near Ensenada, a relative said.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said at least 17 victims died immediately. Two
women and a man were left wounded, and one of the women has since
died, according to a bulletin issued by Baja California State
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's attorney general, Jorge Madrazo, said in an interview
that 19 people were killed in the attack by gunmen armed with AK-47
and 9-millimeter weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo said the head of one of the three families, Castro, had
been under federal investigation on suspicion of working with a top
lieutenant of the Arellano Felix drug smuggling gang, which is
based here in Baja California state.
</P>
<P>
   The government news agency Notimex Thursday quoted the state
attorney general, Marco Antonio de la Fuente Villarreal, as saying
Castro was a cultivator of marijuana for the Arellano Felix group,
which has been known as one of Mexico's most violent.
</P>
<P>
   Castro's fate was not clear. The state government bulletin
listed him as one of 19 dead in the attack. But the same bulletin
said that he had been taken to an Ensenada hospital and had
survived the attack.
</P>
<P>
   A relative of Castro, who asked not to be identified, said
Thursday night that Castro was alive.
</P>
<P>
   Castro's relative said she received a call at 8 a.m. from her
sister-in-law, who said, ```There had been a shootout in my
brother's house and that they had killed everybody, but they
weren't sure if anybody had been left alive or who had done it or
why,'' she recounted.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if she was sure her relative had not been involved in
illegal activities, the relative said, ``If he did things we didn't
know about, he must have had it all pretty hidden.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She said he is a former teacher who moved here 20 years ago from
another part of the state and has a rodeo company based in Tijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Castro interviewed outside his home Thursday said he
had grown wealthy in recent years as a successful cattleman, and he
is well known in Ensenada as an organizer of rodeo events. Eighteen
horses grazed in a fenced enclosure behind his home Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Armando Contreras, a contractor who said he had done
construction work for Castro, said, ``I think what caused this
killing was just the envy of people jealous because Fermin had so
many cattle.''
</P>
<P>
   People familiar with the case said that one teen-age girl
survived the attack by hiding in a closet.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Attorney General Madrazo said that Castro was
suspected of being an associate of Ismael Higuera Guerrero, a
lieutenant in the Arellano Felix organization said to have become
increasingly important as the brothers have been forced to operate
from hiding. Higuera has been using Ensenada as a trafficking base.
</P>
<P>
   In December, when federal authorities intensified efforts to
apprehend or suppress the Arellano Felix gang after several
high-profile slayings were attributed to them, prosecutors sought
to obtain a search warrant for Castro's property here, known as
``El Rancho del Rodeo,'' but were apparently denied the warrant by
a judge.
</P>
<P>
   The Baja State bulletin said that authorities in Ensenada
received a call at 5 a.m., reporting that ``it appeared that there
were from 10 to 12 persons dead, that it could be caused by
firearms, and that they were members of three families.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At 5:20, on arriving at the place, we realized that at one
side of the patio there were 18 bodies lying on the ground; 17
apparently dead, and one of them, of the feminine sex, still alive.
But once transported to the Hospital del Carmen by an ambulance,
she died at 7:50 a.m.,'' the bulletin said.
</P>
<P>
   One Mexican law enforcement official said Thursday that one
hypothesis is that the executions are related to the slaying of a
major trafficker, Rafael Munoz Talavera, on Sept. 11 in Ciudad
Juarez. He formed an alliance with the Arellano Felix brothers last
year during a violent attempt to take control of the cartel based
in Juarez.
</P>
<P>
   But the authorities acknowledged that they were still largely
baffled by the ferocity and ruthlessness of Thursday's killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really happened there?'' one Mexican official asked out
loud. ``At this point, who knows?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
