u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CITICORP-TRAVELERS-33     09-17 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITICORP-TRAVELERS-335&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDUSTRY TREND SEEN AS CITICORP, TRAVELERS PLAN MAJOR LAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER TRUELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the first of what is expected to be major layoffs
at financial companies, Citicorp and Travelers Group Inc. _ which
plan to merge into Citigroup Inc. _ confirmed Thursday that they
would eliminate several thousand jobs, many in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts, which the two companies declined to specify either by
number, percentage, or location of jobs, are expected to be spread
across the combined company, which currently employs more than
160,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Citicorp and Travelers executives who declined to be identified
by name said the cuts were likely to fall particularly hard on
businesses that have been hit by the recent decline in financial
markets, such as the issuing and trading of bonds and equities, and
in areas that overlap, such as foreign exchange trading, credit
card services, data processing, headquarters' staff and human
resources.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these businesses are based in and around New York City _
where the two companies now employ 28,000.
</P>
<P>
   Several New York companies, including Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. and
other big banks and brokerage houses, were also expected to
announce layoffs _ crimping, or even halting, a run of several
years of prosperity for New York, where financial services had
become an increasingly important part of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, 100,000 of the projected Citigroup work force is
based in the United States, so the brunt of the expected
retrenchment at the financial behemoth will probably fall on
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   And the cutbacks will not stop with Citibank and Travelers if
the global economic turmoil continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this environment continues I would expect all the companies
I follow _ the banks with big broker dealers _ to rethink their
staffing,'' said Diane Glossman, bank analyst at Lehman Inc.,
referring to the recent downturn in financial markets. ``J.P.
Morgan already announced a program earlier this year, Bankers Trust
is already revamping its business, Bank of Boston already
restructured in Europe and Asia.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The swoon in financial markets had led to frequent speculation
that Citibank and Travelers might even call off their pending
merger, which had yet to obtain the required approval from the
Federal Reserve Board. The company they are proposing to create
would offer banking, insurance, brokerage and other financial
services to companies and individuals in 100 different countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company is being very circumspect,'' said Judah Kraushaar,
an analyst at Merrill Lynch. ``They're saying it's up to the Fed.
He added, ``From my own point of view, there's a high probability
the deal will close in October.''
</P>
<P>
   Citibank and Travelers refused Thursday to confirm various
reports, first carried on CNBC television, that the two companies
would eliminate 5 percent of their combined work force, or about
8,000 jobs by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   But John M. Morris, a spokesman for Citibank who said he also
spoke for Travelers, admitted the cuts ``may be as much as that.''
He said that he could not confirm the 8,000 number, which he said
had been ``plucked out of the air,'' or the related report that 5
percent of the companies' combined work force would be cut by the
end of the year. But the spokesman said those numbers were
``directionally correct.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said such cuts were to be expected and that they might
well involve more than 8,000 jobs, or 5 percent of the combined
companies' work force. ``My own hunch is that this is a piece of
something that'll be broader,'' said Kraushaar, adding, ``I don't
find this surprising at all. There is a lot of bureaucracy in a
bank that you don't find in a company like Travelers.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Mandle, an analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co., the
brokerage firm, said, ``We thought the cost saves were going to be
greater than what the companies were talking about'' at the April
merger announcement. ``We thought it was more like $600 million,
rather than the $400 million they were talking about,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Glossman, the Lehman analyst, said, ``There are clear
opportunities to cut spending and cut right up front. I would not
be surprised to see more than 5 percent of the staff involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to play down Thursday's speculation of layoffs, Morris
said, ``There is no companywide goal. Each manager has been asked
to look for efficiencies, and to see that their costs are in line
with any revised business expectations they would have.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as specific numbers are concerned, Morris added, ``we are
not prepared to say that, because it's vague at the moment.'' He
also stressed that the cost-cutting was not a single program but a
host of different initiatives, some dating from before the
announcement of the merger. About a year ago, Morris said as an
example, Citicorp announced a program of 7,500 layoffs, which he
said is now ``about half done.''
</P>
<P>
   Travelers chairman Sanford Weill and Citicorp chairman John Reed
made no comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But Weill addressed a gathering of investors and analysts at the
St. Regis Hotel in Manhattan on Thursday. The famous financier _
who rose through the brokerage business to build up a huge
insurance, brokerage and financial services conglomerate _ made no
bones about the combined companies' intention to cut costs. ``We
all get spoiled in good times,'' he told the conference, according
to Morris. ``We probably say `yes' too many times. And we'll
probably be saying `no' too many times and that will be good. It's
time to plan for the worst and pray for the best instead of the
reverse.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's top executives seem to have been preparing its
employees and the markets for more austerity. ``We have to operate
a company in bad weather as well as in good weather,'' Travelers
president and chief operating officer James Dimon, a key lieutenant
of Weill's, told investors recently, according to Morris. ``A
company should be successful in adverse conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has had an opportunity to be ebullient for very long in
this environment,'' Morris said. ``Business conditions are not what
they were on April 6 when we announced our merger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
