<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PANEL WRANGLES OVER RELEASE OF VIDEOTAPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: 2nd take is scheduled to move by 9:30 p.m. ET) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(See also: CLINTON-DAY, CLINTON-CONGRESS-SLEAZE,
CLINTON-CONGRESS-ASSESS, CLINTON-EDITORIALS, CLINTON-BOSTON,
CLINTON-RELEASE, CLINTON-GINGRICH, CLINTON-MINISTER,
CLINTON-CONGRESS-TV) 
(mk) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Abandoning any pretense of bipartisanship, the
House Judiciary Committee spent the day Thursday wrangling over
whether to make public a videotape of President Clinton's grand
jury testimony in the Lewinsky case and discussing how to edit
reams of pages delivered by the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of 11 votes, Democrats on the panel pushed
unsuccessfully for a delay in releasing both the videotape and the
2,000-page appendix of supporting material attached to the
independent counsel's report, arguing that the material should not
be released at all or should be released all at once. They
expressed grave concern during the gathering about making the
information public piecemeal, calling the strategy politically
motivated.
</P>
<P>
   The panel is expected to approve release of the videotape of the
president's grand jury session without any redactions, as early as
Saturday. A videotape of the president's deposition in the Paula
Jones case in January, in which his testimony about Monica Lewinsky
has become the foundation for special prosecutor Kenneth Starr's
central charges of perjury, may also be released.
</P>
<P>
   David Kendall, Clinton's private lawyer, issued a statement
Thursday in which he said he had demanded that Starr destroy the
videotape of Clinton's grand jury testimony. Its continued
existence, he said, ``was to ensure its public release and
embarrass the president.''
</P>
<P>
   In a seething response Thursday night, Starr said the
independent counsel's office considered the videotaped testimony to
be ``evidence of a crime.'' The prosecutor is contending that
Clinton lied to the grand jury as well as in his Jones deposition.
The videotape does not cast Clinton in a flattering light,
depicting him as occasionally impatient, frustrated and quibbling
in his discussion of his affair with Ms. Lewinsky. Democrats said
an edited transcript of the testimony would have sufficed.
</P>
<P>
   While much attention has been focused on disputes over the
president's videotaped testimony, the panel spent much of the day
arguing about the supporting documents that Starr sent to Congress
to bolster his case that the president's actions may be cause for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The panel agreed on over 100 separate redactions of the report's
2,000-page appendix, which includes background information, maps of
the West Wing, a table of Ms. Lewinsky's White House visits and a
table of the contacts between the two of them. It also contains
lengthy footnotes and legal references.
</P>
<P>
   Their protracted debates mainly involved squabbles over eight
passages containing the most sexually explosive material, a person
familiar with the proceedings said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In their first meeting since Starr delivered his report to
Congress on Sept. 9, the panel's Republicans and Democrats bickered
about the merits of releasing the videotape and zeroed-in on the
most sensitive sexual material. They debated, among other things,
the relevance of mentioning sexual props. Both sides said they took
into consideration relevance and good taste.
</P>
<P>
   But, during a debate that boomeranged between collegiality and
partisanship, members accused each other of political motives and
questioned each other's sincerity in pursuing the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to let the public join in the decision-making
process,'' said Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., a member of the
committee, who argued that the committee is searching for a balance
between privacy and decency concerns and the public's right to
know. ``The very fact today is balance. It must be presented in a
balanced fashion so the American people can make their own
judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson's argument was echoed throughout the day by other
Republicans on the panel, who argued that the public should make
its own determination based on the same evidence handed to
Congress. And they accused Democrats of putting Clinton's concerns
ahead of the country's. The president's testimony, they said, is
vital to the case.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats insisted, as they have all week, that hasty disclosure
of the materials is a strategy that will humiliate Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Republicans are trying to do is get the bad stuff out
about the president, as much as they can, as fast as they can,''
said Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., a member of the panel. Frank
added, ``They're frustrated that the president's official standing
is as high as it is, and they're trying to tear it down.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
