<HEADER>
A1485 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MINORITIES-CO     09-17 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MINORITIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Staunchest allies stay faithful
 &HT;    By Scott Shepard
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- African-Americans, long suspicious of the nation's
law enforcement establishment, have become President Clinton's most
ardent defenders in his bid to withstand impeachment, while some
Latino leaders say there is growing uneasiness over investigating
the personal lives of politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Their defense of Clinton follows a yearlong White House effort
to promote a national conversation on race relations. The
President's Race Advisory Board, which has been responsible for
conducting this dialogue, meets Friday with Clinton. The
seven-member advisory board is expected to issue a report to
Clinton sometime this fall with a recommendation to create a
council to continue its work.
</P>
<P>
   During a news conference Wednesday with Czech Republic President
Vaclav Havel, Clinton said he will consider creating a permanent
body to continue the national dialogue he started last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect this to be a central part of the work I do for the
rest of my life,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   For many African-Americans, independent counsel Kenneth Starr's
investigation of Clinton's sexual affair with Monica Lewinsky is
not unlike J. Edgar Hoover's infamous investigation of the Rev.
Martin Luther King Jr.'s sex life in the early 1960s, said David
Bositis, a senior policy analyst at the Joint Center for Political
and Economic Studies, the nation's leading African-American think
tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word `prosecutor' has an entirely different meaning in the
African-American community than in the white community,'' said
Bositis. ``Hoover probably spent millions of dollars investigating
King, and Hoover didn't even have the excuse of an independent
counsel law.''
</P>
<P>
   A history of police brutality and persecution of black people by
the nation's law enforcement system has prompted many
African-American officials to rally behind the president, not in
approval of his conduct but to ensure that Clinton gets a fair
hearing as Congress proceeds on Starr's report, said Rep. Sheila
Jackson Lee (D-Texas).
</P>
<P>
   ``For those of us with a history in the civil rights movement,
this is an issue of fundamental fairness,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-nine of the 35 members of the House Congressional Black
Caucus voted last week against public release of Starr's report to
Congress. Rep. Maxine Waters (D-Calif.), who heads the caucus,
vowed that her organization intends to be ``the fairness cop'' as
Congress decides what to do about Starr's report of possible
impeachable offenses by the president.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the fairness issue, however, many African-Americans view
Clinton as their most important political ally since Lyndon
Johnson. They see Clinton as standing up to Republican-led efforts
to do away with affirmative action, programs designed in the late
1960s to correct past discrimination and ensure equal opportunity
for minorities, as well conducting a yearlong ``national
conversation'' to mend racial divisions in the country.
</P>
<P>
   A poll by the Pew Research Center for the People and the Press
just before Starr's report was released showed Clinton with an 88
percent job approval rating among African-Americans, considerably
higher than the 61 percent approval rating among white people.
</P>
<P>
   The poll did not provide such a breakdown among Latinos, but
Hispanic leaders at the grass-roots level suggested this week that
Latino support for Clinton mirrors the national trend, with roughly
2 out of 3 approving of the job he is doing but disapproving of his
personal conduct.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1996 election, Clinton received 88 percent of
African-Americans' votes and slightly more than 70 percent of
Latino votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latinos are pretty much mainstream,'' said Guillermo Galindo,
incoming chairman of the Hispanic Chamber of Commerce in Dallas.
``They don't like what the president did, but they think he's been
a pretty good president overall.''
</P>
<P>
   The political fall of former HUD Secretary Henry Cisneros,
accused of lying to the FBI about a mistress, has contributed to
Latino concerns about investigating the personal lives of public
officials, Galindo added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is whether we should be looking into such
matters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rosa Orenstein, a lawyer, said a meeting of Democratic and
Republican Latino leaders in Dallas on Saturday concluded with
``the overwhelming feeling'' that Starr's investigation had gone
too far into Clinton's personal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it really our business to be peeping into windows?'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Hispanic Caucus, however, in contrast to the
black caucus, has not asserted any caucus role if Congress proceeds
with impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that the Hispanic leadership is stuck in a political
fix,'' said Rodolpho de la Garza, a professor of government at the
University of Texas in Austin and vice president of the Thomas
Rivera Policy Institute, a Latino-oriented think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Latino leaders are promoting Energy Secretary Bill Richardson as
a possible vice presidential running mate for the Democratic
nominee in 2000, de la Garza noted: ``And if the nominee is (Vice
President Al) Gore, (Latinos) criticizing Clinton now could hurt
Richardson's chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
