<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1486 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TAPES-COX     09-17 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TAPES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Congress pushes the pause button on Clinton video
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman and Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- The House Judiciary Committee unexpectedly delayed
release of President Clinton's videotaped testimony Thursday, and
Republican leaders asked the FBI to investigate an alleged smear
campaign by the White House.
</P>
<P>
   In an atmosphere bereft of the cooperation promised by leaders
in both parties, Judiciary Committee members bickered all day over
release of additional material from independent counsel Kenneth
Starr's report to Congress, including Clinton's Aug. 17 testimony
to a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely that any of the material would be released before
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde (R-Ill.), the committee chairman, said his
panel's work bogged down over what to keep from the public out of
the 2,700 pages of supporting evidence that accompanied Starr's
445-page report on his investigation of the president's efforts to
conceal his relationship with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to agree on things that are extraneous and aren't
relevant to the central issues,'' Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   David Kendall, Clinton's private lawyer, issued a statement
saying that Starr had earlier refused a request to destroy the tape
of Clinton's testimony after it was viewed by an absent grand
juror. Kendall said the only purpose for preserving it ``was to
ensure its public release and embarrass the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Kendall's comments and the objections of some
congressional Democrats, the release of the videotape is virtually
certain. But Hyde said he would not make it available in advance of
printed documents, including the transcript of Clinton's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The public is likely to get more of the sexually explicit
details that characterized the release of the first part of Starr's
report a week ago, said Rep. Chris Cannon (R-Utah), a committee
member. ``We're talking about the Kenneth Starr report, and that's
a blusher,'' Cannon said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, fears of more disclosures about elected officials'
private lives prompted an extraordinary pledge from the chairmen of
the House Democratic and Republican campaign committees to cut off
campaign financing to candidates who make an issue of their
opponents' personal lives.
</P>
<P>
   The statements by Rep. John Linder of Georgia, the Republican
campaign committee chairman, and Rep. Martin Frost of Texas,
Linder's Democratic counterpart, came on the morning after Salon,
an on-line magazine, revealed that Hyde had an affair with a woman
30 years ago while both were married to other people.
</P>
<P>
   Frost said he would refuse to give committee money ``to any
Democratic candidate who initiates an attack on the personal
private life of an opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   Linder agreed, but later said candidates were free to make an
issue of their opponents' ``character.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's fine,'' Linder said. ``We've been doing it for 200
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Distinguishing between what is permissible and what is not will
be done on a case-by-case basis, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The story about Hyde's relationship drew expressions of anger
from Democrats and Republicans alike.
</P>
<P>
   But House Speaker Newt Gingrich and other GOP leaders went a
step further, sending FBI Director Louis Freeh a letter asking him
to investigate whether the White House was involved in planting the
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether or not that specific story originated with the White
House or its allies, clearly there is credible evidence that an
organized campaign of slander and intimidation may exist,'' the
letter said.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip Tom DeLay (R-Texas) offered no evidence of
White House involvement in the Hyde story other than a brief report
on ABC News based on anonymous sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hire a private investigator to go find the dirt, and they
give it to a reporter,'' DeLay said, with no substantiation.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Jim Kennedy denied that administration
officials gave Salon any information for its story.
</P>
<P>
   And the retired salesman Salon says tipped off the magazine
about the Hyde affair also denied that the White House was
involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me make very clear that nobody ... has been in contact
with me from the White House,'' Norm Sommer said. ``I tried to call
the White House to offer support but they never called me back.''
</P>
<P>
   White House Chief of Staff Erskine Bowles sent Hyde a letter
promising that ``any staff found to be engaging in such conduct
will be fired immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Members from both parties acknowledged little could be done to
stop the flow of stories of sexual liaisons.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few weeks, news organizations have reported on Rep.
Dan Burton's (R-Ind.) adulterous relationship with a woman that
produced a child and on Rep. Helen Chenoweth's (R-Idaho) six-year
affair with a married man in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   One House member was unfazed by the specter of disclosure of
still more lurid details. ``You think I'm worried about that?''
said Rep. Barney Frank (D-Mass.), once reprimanded by his
colleagues for a sex scandal. ``I gave at the office.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's edict banning indecorous references to Clinton on the
House floor remained in effect, but one Republican lawmaker used a
variation of the fable of the emperor's new clothes to make his
point without once mentioning the president's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day, however, the emperor was caught in deeds that brought
disgrace to his ability to lead and dishonor to his office,'' Rep.
Joseph Pitts of Pennsylvania said. ``He was caught with his clothes
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
