<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO PROMISES FULL INQUIRY INTO TAINTED ELITE DRUG UNIT  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By TIM GOLDEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Mexico's attorney general promised Thursday to
conduct a ``profound'' investigation into possible corruption of an
elite American-trained police unit and insisted that antidrug
cooperation with the United States should continue without
interruption.
</P>
<P>
   But Attorney General Jorge Madrazo Cuellar also bristled at the
statement by law-enforcement officials in Washington that problems
with the Mexican unit might have resulted in the betrayal of
important American information to powerful traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We share with the United States much, much more information
that we ourselves generate than we get from officials there,''
Madrazo said.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo spoke in an interview here after U.S. officials had
disclosed that three top investigators of an organized-crime unit
of the attorney general's office had failed lie-detector tests that
U.S. experts administered this month. The investigators were all
found to be lying when they were asked whether they had provided
information to traffickers, officials of both countries said.
</P>
<P>
   Several American officials described the test results as a
catastrophic sign that the integrity of the unit had been
compromised. Speaking privately, some of the officials also
questioned whether the Mexican authorities were really intent on
finding out what had occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in their position have access to every file in that
unit,'' one American official said. Referring to the United States
Drug Enforcement Administration and its informers in Mexico, the
official asked: ``Do they know who the DEA's sources are? No. But
they know who all the American targets are.''
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo insisted that he would get to the bottom of the case. To
insure an impartial investigation, he said, he had taken the
unusual step of assigning the inquiry not to his own
internal-affairs investigators, but to auditors in his office who
answer to the comptroller of the republic.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he had immediately removed the three senior
officials from the unit, along with two lower-ranking investigators
who also tested badly. Of eight tested, three senior officials
passed easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to follow this investigation wherever it goes,''
Madrazo said. ``We are not going to protect anyone. Somebody who
does not pass a polygraph has to go. Those are not American rules.
They are mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as a fuller picture emerged, however, Mexican and American
officials continued to contradict one another about its meaning.
</P>
<P>
   American officials had initially said that the lie-detector
tests were routine, part of the follow-up testing that is regularly
and randomly applied to carefully screened antidrug units that the
United States has helped establish in several countries.
</P>
<P>
   But in subsequent interviews officials acknowledged that members
of the Mexican unit became targets for testing after American
informers and other information had suggested that they might have
ties to powerful cocaine traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo said the only such information Mexico had came from
slips of paper captured in the raid of a drug gang's safe house
that were shared with U.S. investigators. The papers included what
appeared to be traffickers' notes about the federal police and
military officials who were pursuing them.
</P>
<P>
   Two notes shown to a reporter relate conversations or meetings
with what seem to be two of the three senior organized-crime
investigators in question.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials said they would not release the investigators'
names to assure their safety.
</P>
<P>
   The meaning of the notes is unclear. But they seem to indicate
that the officials said they could not help the traffickers, but
would not harm them, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't throw somebody in jail on the basis of something like
this,'' one Mexican investigator said, pointing to other notes that
appeared to indicate contacts between the traffickers' associates
and two well-known newspaper editors.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. officials said what appeared to be contacts between the
agents and the traffickers were indeed suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
