<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TRAIL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ACCUSES REPUBLICANS OF BEING OBSESSED WITH SCANDAL,
IGNORING ISSUES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Bristling with campaign rhetoric, President Clinton
accused Republicans Thursday of being obsessed with scandal and
doing little to address the issues critical to Americans.
</P>
<P>
   A newly assertive Clinton, striking a political tone belying his
own precarious situation, tried to regain the offensive before
Congress ponders whether to begin impeachment proceedings on
perjury and obstruction charges related to his affair with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In speeches to Democrats here and in Massachusetts, as well as
to union members in Washington, Clinton appeared to echo sentiments
found in public opinion polls and presented himself as a man at
work while Republicans were steeped in political machinations.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I would like for you to think about is not me. Hillary
and I, we're doing fine. We're working on what we need to be
working on and we're doing fine. What I'm concerned about is the
rest of the people in this country and one more time having
Washington obsessed with itself instead of America,'' Clinton told
a handful of wealthy contributors here.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to energize Democratic voters, Clinton seized on four
issues to mark his return to the political arena _ America's role
in the global economy, education spending, Social Security reform
before tax cuts and passage of a patient bill of rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember those four issues. Look at the (past) eight months.
We've got one appropriation bill, they killed campaign finance
reform and they killed tobacco legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``As near as I can tell that's the record of the last eight
months. That is what this is about. It is not about me. It is about
the people of this country. It is about their children, their
future and our common effort. I am going to do everything I can to
fight for these things and try to help people who believe in them
get elected,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Those were also the eight months that independent counsel
Kenneth Starr investigated allegations that Clinton committed
perjury and obstructed justice by covering up an affair with
Lewinsky. Clinton acknowledged on Aug. 17 that he misled Americans
about the relationship but continues to maintain that he testified
truthfully.
</P>
<P>
   The president's comments came as the Republican-led House
Judiciary Committee delayed a decision on whether to release the
president's videotaped testimony to a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The more combative statements Thursday stood in marked contrast
to the president's efforts last week to be contrite and seeking
forgiveness for his extramarital affair.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton received one of his harshest greetings here in
the heartland as Cincinnati's largest newspaper, the Enquirer,
demanded the president's resignation and published readers'
reactions over four full pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have disgraced yourself and the presidency,'' the
Enquirer's editorial said.
</P>
<P>
   The paper ran some of the 1,400 comments it had received about
Clinton's lies to Americans about his relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cincinnatians are angry and disappointed with the mess you're
in,'' the paper said in a front page story headlined: ``Mr.
President, we would like a word with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton came here for a $500,000 fund-raising luncheon for the
Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee, which provides
donations to House candidates, at the home of lawyer Stanley
Chesley.
</P>
<P>
   Chesley offered an emotional testimonial on Clinton's behalf,
bemoaning Starr's investigation which he said ``hounded and pursued
every move made'' by the president and first lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have now is rank partisan politics,'' Chesley said,
praising the first family for standing tall and doing their jobs.
He blasted the media for obscuring the good economic news of
Clinton's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton later raised $1 million for Democratic candidates at two
events in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But even on normally friendly Democratic turf, the president
faced stinging criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts House speaker Tom Finnerman refused to appear with
the president at a party unity rally, saying: ``Bill Clinton almost
makes Nixon look like a moral giant.''
</P>
<P>
   The president began his day with a politically laced speech to
the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers were he
received a warm welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make this a season of doing things for you _ not
idleness and not indulgence, but doing things for you,'' Clinton
told the IBEW in Washington. ``That is the choice _ partisanship
over progress, people over politics _ in every issue facing the
Congress and the country, that is the choice. And the people need
to make their voices heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton threatened to veto the Republicans $85 million tax cut
being proposed by Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, and suggested some
Republicans want to dismantle Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have asked some of our Republican friends, I've said, you
know, we've been waiting 29 years for this, couldn't we at least
see the ink turn from red to black and then watch it dry for a
minute or two before we get carried away?'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's election year and it's popular. But it isn't right,''
Clinton said, again calling for Congress to save the surplus for
overhauling Social Security. ``I have said over and over again that
if Congress sends me a bill that squanders the surplus on tax cuts
before we save Social Security I'll veto it.''
</P>
<P>
   He called on Congress to pass funding for the International
Monetary Fund to help stave off the international economic crisis,
to approve money for smaller class sizes and to pass restrictions
on health insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we ought to be talking about in Washington D.C. _
something that will affect the lives of the children in this
country,'' Clinton told the union. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
