<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1496 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOLITA-THEATER-2TAKES     09-17 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOLITA-THEATER-2TAKES-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HESITANT HUMBERT MAKES A STAND  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 Karen Durbin is the film critic for Mirabella magazine.  
 By KAREN DURBIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALAN DERSHOWITZ: ``You're a very strange man, Claus.''
</P>
<P>
   CLAUS VON BULOW: `'You have no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   _ From ``Reversal of Fortune'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This is perhaps the most memorable exchange in Barbet
Schroeder's stylish 1990 film about the infamous Danish socialite
accused of trying to kill his rich American wife.
</P>
<P>
   As played by Jeremy Irons _ elegantly, insinuatingly reptilian,
gray of skin as well as hair _ von Bulow appears to have something
chillier than blood running in his veins. And he delivers his
riposte to the actor Ron Silver's Dershowitzian blurt in the driest
of drawls.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Irons has made an excellent thing out of playing very
strange men. In 1988, he even played two at once _ the terminally
codependent twin gynecologists, Beverly and Elliott Mantle, in
David Cronenberg's mordant tragedy of manners ``Dead Ringers.''
</P>
<P>
   When Irons won an Academy Award three years later for ``Reversal
of Fortune,'' his acceptance speech included a prominent thank you
to Cronenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Now, audiences will finally be able to see Irons play Humbert
Humbert on the big screen, starting on Friday, when Adrian Lyne's
long delayed, much persecuted film of Vladimir Nabokov's once long
delayed, much persecuted novel, ``Lolita'' opens.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with Claus von Bulow and the woman-sharing,
morphine-addicted Mantle twins, Nabokov's notorious lover of
nymphets is a walk in the park. Nevertheless, it's a walk Irons at
first refused to take.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't much like him,'' the actor said recently over lunch
in his suite at the Lowell, a quietly smart hotel in the East 60s
favored by well-heeled Brits. ``I saw him as a sort of dirty old
man, as a raincoat man, you know. I thought I'd played enough of
these creepy people, so I said no.''
</P>
<P>
   Irons, of course, isn't the only one who said no to ``Lolita.''
After completing the film, Lyne spent two years being turned down
by one American distributor after another. They, too, reacted as if
Humbert Humbert was a raincoat man, and one of the great novels of
the 20th century a celebration of pedophilia.
</P>
<P>
   In a society eager to tell itself that child abuse is not
primarily a family crime but the province of depraved day care
teachers and suburban satanic cults, the distributors took one look
at Lyne's soulful, sophisticated movie and ran scared. The director
finally settled for a deal with Showtime, the cable network, to
broadcast it twice in August.
</P>
<P>
   The American rejection helped fuel the hysterical attacks on the
film (the conservative Daily Mail in London campaigned to have it
banned as perverted and obscene), and damaged its financial
prospects as well.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most galling to the filmmakers, the snub by the American
distributors appeared to stem not from artistic objections but from
a squeamish second-guessing of the marketplace. It was simply a
kind of pre-emptive self-censorship.
</P>
<P>
   Irons had come to town the night before the interview to join
Lyne at a gala screening of ``Lolita'' to benefit the Film Society
of Lincoln Center. The choice of the film was partly spurred by the
distributors' refusals.
</P>
<P>
   Joanne Koch, the Society's executive director, said the program
committee was reliably tipped that the movie was good. ``So, we
decided this was an ideal thing to show to our constituents because
they might not have another opportunity to see it on the screen.
Part of our mission is to show things that aren't available
elsewhere. My personal predilection is to show things that are
controversial.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lincoln Center screening was a crowd-pleaser. Better yet, it
was a seal of approval for ``Lolita'' from an unassailable source:
the Society's yearly New York Film Festival is one of the most
prestigious in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Better still, the deal with Showtime had broken the malignant
spell hanging over the film, and by the time of the benefit,
``Lolita'' had found a theatrical distributor, Samuel Goldwyn
Films, as well. For Irons and Lyne, celebration was in order.
</P>
<P>
   The next day found Irons hung over and as shamefaced as a
schoolboy about it. ``Margaritas,'' he said, looking a little
stunned. ``I'm no longer used to drinking like that. I fear it's
made me very dull.''
</P>
<P>
   Not likely. Even sandbagged by the aftereffects of tequila,
Irons is one of the most articulate actors in the business. And he
delivers his thoughts in his famously mellifluous voice _ a sort of
warm murmur, the aural equivalent of brown velvet. (Random House
has just issued ``Lolita'' on audiocassette with Irons narrating.)
</P>
<P>
   He hadn't planned on doing much publicity for ``Lolita.'' ``It
was difficult enough to play without having to justify it,'' he
said. ``But because people were talking such rubbish about it, I
felt I must plow in there.''
</P>
<P>
   He was also moved, he said, to ``put a bit of chat behind'' the
movie because for a time, at least, Lyne was so hurt by the attacks
on the film that ``he wasn't being the best ambassador for it.''
</P>
<P>
   At 47, Irons is lithe and handsome, looking every inch (all 73
of them) the soulful romantic hero that propelled him to fame in
``The French Lieutenant`s Woman'' almost two decades ago and that
he reprised recently as a doomed British journalist in ``Chinese
Box.''
</P>
<P>
   As that film proved, nobody dies better on camera. But for the
most part he has eschewed the predictable and glamorous career path
that beckoned early on in favor of more interesting work.
</P>
<P>
   He joked that he would do more romantic roles except that
``Richard Gere plays them all.'' Instead, he said, ``My career's
made up of roles that other actors have passed on,'' adding with a
certain glee that Lyne talked to Robert Redford, Warren Beatty and
Hugh Grant, among others, about playing Humbert.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Lyne had his eye on Irons from the start. He first
raised the possibility eight years ago at a screening of ``Reversal
of Fortune,'' adding that he had two projects in mind, one of which
turned out to be ``Indecent Proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave that role to Mr. Redford,'' Irons said mockingly. A
few years later, Lyne started going after Irons in earnest,
repeatedly pressing his case and showing him scripts until the
actor finally agreed. ``Many phone calls and much heart searching''
is the way the Irons summed it up. Friends and colleagues advised
against taking the role because ``they thought he was an unsavory
character'' (a stricture that would wipe out the best part of
Robert De Niro's career and make much of Shakespeare impossible to
cast).
</P>
<P>
   ``I read and reread the script,'' Irons said, ``and I was very
knocked out by Adrian's passion.'' Finally, the decision was made
when he talked it over with Glenn Close, who is a friend and who
played an infamously unsavory character _ the bunny-boiling Fury _
in Lyne's ``Fatal Attraction.'' ``Don't worry,'' she said. ``He'll
take care of you.''
</P>
<P>
   To explain why he wanted Irons, Lyne recited a passage from the
novel when the teen-age Humbert visits a young prostitute and is
unable to haggle because ``she saw the awful lone longing in my
lowered eyes.'' The phrase conjures up Irons's face on the screen.
His Humbert is, like Nabokov's, witty, erudite and a ruthless bully
in the pursuit of his compulsion _ a point the film drives home by
having him strike Lolita more than once.
</P>
<P>
   But he's also fully human, as he would have to be in order to
undergo the ultimate redemption of love and remorse that makes the
novel moving as well as brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   Irons said he found his way into the relationship between the
middle-aged man and the budding girl by making Humbert ``boyish,''
a case of arrested development. ``When he was with her,'' Irons
said, ``he felt terribly happy. He felt 14, and yet he knew he
wasn't. That's how I was able to play him without embarrassment.''
</P>
<P>
   By the film's end, Irons's Humbert knows very well who he is and
what he's done: his face has become a mask of sorrow and regret.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just want to see the history of the entire relationship in
his face,'' said Lyne. ``He's a man who's left with nothing.'' He's
a man who started with nothing as well, for what is compulsion but
``an awful lone longing,'' a fathomless emptiness screaming to be
filled?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps what makes ``Lolita'' so disturbing is not simply, as
Irons and Lyne suggested, the current prominence of the once
unmentionable subject of pedophilia. Perhaps the real problem is
that Irons and Lyne have done their work too well.
</P>
<P>
   Like Nabokov 40 years ago, they violate the real taboos that
surround the alarming, fascinating, tabloid-television-worthy
subject of sex with children. Instead of a drooling monster preying
on an ``innocent victim,'' they make their pedophile familiar,
engaging, even at times sympathetic. And the 12-year-old child he
desires feels desire as well; her sexuality may be different from
and incompatible with his, but it is real.
</P>
<P>
   Irons isn't a strange man at all; he just plays one in the
movies. He's been married for 20 years to the actress Sinead Cusack
and talks with obvious delight about their sons, Sam, 19, and Max,
12. He loves cars and vehicles of all kinds, particularly his
trusty BMW motorcycle.
</P>
<P>
   He relieved the stress of playing Humbert by going rollerblading
whenever he wasn't wanted on the set in North Carolina. The day of
the interview at his hotel, he was eager to fly back to Ireland,
where he and his family have a second home and where, just for fun,
he's rebuilding a 16th-century tower house castle that's on the
point of collapse. He doesn't feel the need to earn more money
because, he has said, ``I'm rich enough already,'' and he rejects
``the cardboard life'' of a superstar; he much prefers the real one
he has.
</P>
<P>
   Irons spent the morning after the Lincoln Center benefit touring
the Guggenheim Museum's motorcycle exhibit with Ulton Guilfoyle,
who helped organize the show. Time and again, as he and Guilfoyle
wound upward through the museum, women of all ages would notice
Irons and, with the consistency of whooping cranes, execute the
same little dance of desire: shock of recognition followed by a
backward step and a long, thorough look; then a slow move past the
object of attraction in a sort of polite arc; finally, having
achieved a suitably discreet distance, say, three feet, a half-turn
back for a last wordless look before moving on. Girls shriek at
Leo. Women silently drink in Irons.
</P>
<P>
   As for the object of all this libidinous kerfuffle, well, to
coin a phrase, Irons seemed to have no idea. His own fond gaze was
reserved for the motorcycles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 2129EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
