<HEADER>
A1498 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-COLUMN-ART-$AD     09-17 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-COLUMN-ART-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ISSUES DON'T MEAN EASY PICKINGS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 Mark Hulbert is editor of the Hulbert Financial Digest, a
newsletter based in Alexandria, Va. His column will appear every
other week.  
 By MARK HULBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Initial public offerings are viewed by many investors as the
ultimate no-brainer. Virtually no homework is required in order to
win. All you have to do is buy a company's stock on the day it goes
public and realize huge one-day profits.
</P>
<P>
   The coming IPO of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. is feeding into this
perception. Like schoolboys flipping through an issue of Playboy,
investors reading the preliminary prospectus are titillated by the
huge sums that the firm's partners stand to gain if, as expected,
the firm goes public this November. Investors wantpart of the
action.
</P>
<P>
   All but lost is a more important question: Should investors be
drawn to Goldman's IPO simply because it is a new issue?
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to understand why investors think they should.
Imprinted on their memories are IPO success stories like the saga
of Netscape Communications, which soared to more than $75 from $28
on its initial offering day in 1995. IPOs are just so much money in
the bank, they figure.
</P>
<P>
   A funny thing has happened, however, on the way to the bank.
Consider the performance of two newsletters that focus on IPOs: New
Issues, published by the Institute for Econometric Research in
Deerfield Beach, Fla., and Emerging and Special Situations, from
Standard &AMP; Poor's. If returns like Netscape's were readily
achievable, these newsletters should have easily beaten the market.
But I calculate that they lagged behind the return of the Wilshire
5000 by 5.2 and 7.3 percentage points a year, respectively, from
1983 through July 1998. The Wilshire, made up of about 7,600
companies, is used as a proxy for the entire stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the experience of these newsletters unique. Academic
studies have consistently found that the average IPO lags
significantly behind the market in the five years after going
public.
</P>
<P>
   How could the public's perception become so distorted? Memories,
it seems, are selective: Investors far more readily recall the
Netscapes than the laggards.
</P>
<P>
   If this were the end of the story, my advice would be to avoid
the Goldman offering. But it's not, thanks to a recently published
study by two professors, Alon Brav of the University of Chicago and
Paul Gompers of Harvard. They discovered a peculiarity of previous
studies that made the performance of IPOs appear to be worse than
it was.
</P>
<P>
   Here is why: Most companies that go public are of the ``small
cap growth'' variety; they have small market capitalizations and
relatively high price-to-book ratios. Historically, such companies
have underperformed the broad market. When previous studies found
that IPOs underperformed, all they were really reporting was the
pattern of small-cap growth stocks.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, such studies are not particularly relevant to the
IPO of a business like Goldman, which is certainly not a small-cap
company and may or may not qualify as a growth stock depending on
the price it brings. To correct for this, the professors studied
IPOs after adjusting for market capitalization and price-to-book
ratios. They found that the average IPO matched the market's
performance.
</P>
<P>
   The implication is that the investment value of a company going
public has nothing to do with the fact that it is a new issue.
While you shouldn't automatically avoid IPOs, neither should you
reflexively buy them.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one more cautionary note to the findings: More
companies go public near market tops than near bottoms. A company
typically doesn't go public when it thinks the market will
undervalue it.
</P>
<P>
   Where are we now? The Institute for Econometric Research
compares weekly IPO dollar volume with gross domestic product on an
annualized basis. Lower readings are more bullish. This ratio,
which normally fluctuates between zero and 0.5 percent, soared to
2.53 percent in mid-July, when volume was extremely high. Even
though volume has fallen, the current reading is a still-bearish
1.68 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that there is no reason to expect that the
Goldman offering will fare better or worse than the market over
all. But the recent pace of IPOs casts doubt on the health of the
market itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
