<SLUG> BC-WEATHERBOX-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE WEATHERBOX': KNACK FOR PLAYING GEORGE AND MARTHA, AND BAD
TIMING 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at the end of review.) 
(js) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK_ When Carol enters her childhood home, angry and having
broken a window to get in, you half expect her to declare ``What a
dump!'' When she and her brother Tom begin to trade insults in a
well-worn routine of sibling hatred, there's more than a little
George and Martha in them. ``The Weatherbox'' is no ``Who's Afraid
of Virginia Woolf?'' but there are echoes.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Albee was an adviser on Travis Baker's pointed,
entertaining one-act play, and it's a good match. Kim Levin, the
director, seems to have taken a no-holds-barred, dead-ahead
approach, and it works. Baker's characters may not have the brutal
eloquence of Albee's _ in fact, their taunts are deliberately
childish (``I have a life and you don't,'' ``You don't know
anything about anything'') _ but there's power in the directness
and simplicity of their longstanding fury.
</P>
<P>
   Carol (Geneva Carr) has come home to see her dying mother, whom
Tom (Rob Sedgwick) is taking care of. But this is no sentimental
farewell. Carol wants an apology from the woman who she feels
ruined her life. Tom just wants Carol to go away and lets her know
with the dialogue's typical subtlety: ``Please leave. We don't want
you here.'' Carol ignores him and begins to vent. Then Tom breaks
her nose. (George and Martha were always right on the edge of
physical violence, too.)
</P>
<P>
   While Carol and Tom are at the emergency room, their baby
brother, Dylan, arrives, sneaking into his mother's room with a
boyish giggle. ``I'm a little drunk, Mom _ sorry,'' he says to the
sleeping woman. Dylan (Ivan Martin) is the bad boy of the family,
the James Dean character, and his mother's favorite. He also has a
drug problem. When he sees his mother's pain-killing morphine
supply, he analyzes the situation aloud. ``We are not going to
steal our mother's drugs for our own recreational use,'' he says,
and promptly does just that, while reciting ``The Love Song of J.
Alfred Prufrock.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a dream sequence _ or maybe just a drug-induced altered
reality (signaled by Ed McCarthy's inventive lighting) _ Mother
(Johanna Leister) bounds out of bed, exuding youth, energy and
beauty, and talks about her own dreams and needs.
</P>
<P>
   The audience knows exactly how to feel about each of the
children: adore Dylan, dislike Tom, be a little annoyed by Carol.
But the play doesn't leave it at that. Tom and Carol are too
painfully human not to be sympathetic too. And it's clear that
Dylan has used his status as favorite to cop out on a lot of real
life. One physical symbol of the shifting perspective is a scene
change near the end: when the lights go up again, we are in the
same room but looking at it from an almost opposite angle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Weatherbox'' goes off track at times, and the explanation
of the title is a particularly tortured metaphor about hope and
answers, but over all it's a satisfying, involving drama.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `THE WEATHERBOX'
</P>
<P>
   By Travis Baker; directed by Kim Levin; sets by Catherine Chung;
lighting by Ed McCarthy; costumes by Elizabeth Roles; sound by
Aural Fixation; stage manager, Doretta Berry; assistant director,
Bill Augustin; assistant stage manager, Jere Williams; technical
director, Mike Hraban. Presented by Rattlestick Productions. The
play continues Wednesdays to Sundays through Oct. 11. at the
Theater Off Park, 224 Waverly Place.
</P>
<P>
   With: Geneva Carr (Carol), Johanna Leister (Mother), Ivan Martin
(Dylan) and Rob Sedgwick (Tom).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
