u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-ART-     09-17 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: it down.''  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   But some said the party-line friction in the panel was
predictable, members said. Last week, 11 of the Democrats on the
panel voted against a House-passed resolution to release Starr's
report and many of its accompanying documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe some Democrats would like to thwart the procedures
established under the resolution,'' said Rep. Charles Canaday,
R-Fla., a panel member.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign that the partisan battle threatened to intensify, the
panel's ranking Democrat, Rep. John Conyers of Michigan, filed a
letter of protest Thursday with Hyde over the chairman's request of
the Paula Jones tape without consulting Democrats. ``I have serious
concerns regarding the propriety of your seeking the release of a
videoptaped deposition in a private civil case that has now been
dismissed,'' Conyers wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's meeting also came at a time of ill-will between the
parties over the disclosure that Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., chairman
of the committee, had conducted a extramarital affair 30 years ago.
Meanwhile, House Republicans and Democrats continued to face
divisions within their own ranks. At the same time, Rep. Tom
Coburn, R-Okla., a conservative, expressed reservations about
making public Clinton's videotaped testimony, saying it will
``heighten partisan conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As we move toward the possibility of impeachment, Congress
will face extraordinary temptations to exploit the situation for
political gain,'' he said. ``I fear that, in this particular case,
this temptation will prove irresistible and we will fail an
important test.''
</P>
<P>
   An opening salvo in the Judiciary Committee meeting came when
Democrats requested that the gathering be held in public and not
under the cloak of secrecy. The motion was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans have decided that the appropriate way to fight for
openness is in total secrecy,'' Barney Frank said during one of the
committee's sporadic breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats complained that they had not had enough time to
sift through the material and the proposed redactions.
</P>
<P>
   But in an attempt to deflect charges of partisanship, Hyde
allowed members to speak on and on during the debate. After the
meeting, the chairman said: ``There's been lot's of debate. It's
been productive debate, not frivolous debate.'' He added, ``It gets
passionate at times, interesting at times.''
</P>
<P>
   One official familiar with the material and the proceedings said
Clinton's testimony shows him repeatedly relying on legalisms and a
narrow definition of sexual relations in his reponses. He also
refuses to answer a series of more prying questions about the
extent of the affair, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, many of the toughest questions are asked by grand
jurors and not lawyers in the proceeding, the person added.
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Committee aides have spent days poring over documents
in boxes delivered by Starr but Thursday's debate centered only on
the contents of one box, which indicates the process will be long
and slow.
</P>
</TEXT>
