<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS CONFIDENT DAVIS DISPLAY A FLUKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ They have reviewed film of how Terrell Davis
danced all over their defense. They have gone over their botched
on-field assignments with their coaches. They have studied their
playbooks with the same intensity that many of us have studied the
Starr report.
</P>
<P>
   And pointing to a schedule that features few remaining offensive
powerhouses, and a track record that has seen their defense rank no
worse than 10th in each of the past six seasons, Cowboys players
and coaches are confident that last week's meltdown in Denver will
not be an every-week occurrence. That confidence exists even though
Davis' 191-yard effort was the 10th time in the past 11
regular-season games that the Cowboys have yielded more than 100
yards rushing.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys (1-1) have nearly completed their defensive
preparations for the New York Giants (1-1) on Monday Night
Football. They have assured themselves that Giants running back
Tikki Barber, who has 69 yards rushing this year, does not pose the
same threat as Davis, who had 138 yards rushing in the first
quarter against the Cowboys last week.
</P>
<P>
   They intend to stick with their base 4-3 defense, eschewing the
multiple-set strategy that doomed them against the Broncos.
Linebacker Randall Godfrey said the Cowboys used four different
sets in the first quarter and at times were caught in their nickel
defense when the Broncos ran the ball and in their run defense when
the Broncos passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't plan on doing anything terribly different against the
Giants than we did against the Broncos,'' middle linebacker Fred
Strickland said. ``We overpursued some, lost some containment, and
then Terrell Davis just made some great runs. They spread us out
some. And we became more worried about the pass than the run. But
we've been able to correct things in practice. And now it's just
time to convert that to the next game.''
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jerry Jones never expected to have his rushing defense
ripped apart like wet toilet paper. In fact, Jones hired Chan
Gailey to fix the club's offensive problems. In turn, Gailey has
been so confident in his defensive staff that he basically allows
Dave Campo, the defensive coordinator since 1995, to run the
defense while he pays more attention to what the offense is doing.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey acknowledged that he was upset with the coaching and the
playing last week, but added that he was part of the problem. He
said he spent no more time with the defense this week than any
other week, and that his game-day duties will continue to include
an emphasis on the offense _ and the progress of quarterback Jason
Garrett.
</P>
<P>
   The defense, Gailey said, does not need him any more than it
ever has.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a great deal of confidence in our defense and our
staff,'' Gailey said. ``If you look back at the history of the
Cowboys' defense _ they were No. 2 in the league last year. The
defense played really well with this staff and this nucleus of
players for quite a few years. That's the confidence I have. That's
why I can say that last week was not the norm and that we will come
back and play well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, if (last week) was to happen three, four, or five times,
then you got a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   If you apply Gailey's logic to just this season, it would appear
that the Denver game was just a bump in the Cowboys' road back to
respectability. In Week 1, the Cowboys held the Arizona Cardinals
to 45 yards rushing.
</P>
<P>
   But questionable drafts, injury, and retirements have left the
Cowboys with no dependable pass rushers, and just one Pro Bowler
among its front seven, defensive tackle Leon Lett, who has but two
tackles and has been playing on a sore knee. Defensive end Kavika
Pittman (four tackles), Strickland (four tackles) and defensive
tackle Chad Hennings (three tackles) all have struggled this
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' defensive staff fully expects other teams to
attempt to copy the success that the Broncos had, which included
spreading the field to let Davis pick holes in the Cowboys'
defense, or letting quarterback John Elway find pass catching tight
ends open in the slot.
</P>
<P>
   But of the Cowboys remaining opponents, only the Warren
Moon-Ricky Watters-Joey Galloway-led Seattle Seahawks (Nov. 22) and
the Brad Johnson-Robert Smith-Cris Carter-Randy Moss-led Minnesota
Vikings (Nov. 26) have the same kind of offensive firepower as the
Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been around a long time and things like (the Broncos
game) just don't happen all the time _ and thank goodness,''
defensive line coach Jim Bates said. ``We're going to do our best
to make sure it doesn't happen again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
