<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TAPE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL DEFERS RELEASE OF VIDEOTAPE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With several Democrats waging a political trench
fight, the House Judiciary Committee abruptly postponed plans
Thursday to release the videotape and much of the sealed, sexually
explicit evidence in President Clinton's potential impeachment
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   But the delay was expected to defer additional public
humiliation for Clinton and the former White House intern, Monica
S. Lewinsky, for little more than a day or so.
</P>
<P>
   The panel cut off the intensely partisan talks Thursday night
after wrangling for nearly eight hours behind closed doors over
scores of proposed redactions in 2,700 pages of material, including
Lewinsky's grand jury testimony. The infighting grew so protracted
that the panel had yet to begin debating one of the most
potentially explosive pieces of evidence, a videotape of Clinton's
grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fighting page by page, item by item,'' said
Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Lowell Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is scheduled to resume talks Friday. But the
prolonged negotiations, which often focused on testimony so
salacious that several lawmakers later expressed discomfort at the
exercise, forced Republican leaders to drop plans to release the
material Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If the panel reaches a final agreement Friday, the material
could be released as early as tomorrow or as late as next Tuesday
or Wednesday because of weekend staff shortages and a Jewish
holiday on Monday, according to committee aides.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Republican-controlled committee, trying to play
down the panel's partisan infighting as they conduct the historic
inquiry, warned members that they face possible disciplinary action
if they publicly discuss specifics of the private meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a productive debate,'' said Representative Henry J. Hyde,
an Illinois Republican who is chairman of the committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a frivolous debate,'' Hyde said as he hurried out a
back door after the meeting, avoiding dozens of journalists. ``It
got passionate at times, but we are accomplishing a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The showdown unfolded amid fallout from a report on Wednesday
that Hyde engaged in an adulterous affair 30 years ago. Hyde issued
a statement attributing the relationship to a ``youthful
indiscretion.''
</P>
<P>
   But amid a swirl of charges and countercharges over the report,
committee members of both parties expessed confidence in Hyde's
ability to continue leading the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The committee, which is expected to recommend to the full House
by early October whether to impeach Clinton, tangled repeatedly as
some Democrats vigorously opposed releasing portions of grand jury
testimony, asserting it could unnecessarily harm innocent
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Several Democrats echoed concerns raised by Lewinksy's lawyers,
who had asked the panel to black out many sections of her testimony
that could offend people, including Lewinsky's scathing criticism
of Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``A wide range of people could be hurt,'' Meehan said, ``from
people whose names nobody knows to people who hold prestigious
positions in government and the private sector.''
</P>
<P>
   The material under debate includes a lengthy appendix to the
445-page report that the independent counsel, Kenneth W. Starr,
delivered last week to the committee. The appendix includes court
orders, discussions of legal issues, a diagram of the Oval Office,
and other reference material, including information about the
former sexual harassment lawsuit that Paula Corbin Jones filed
against Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 2142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980917.0433 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1527 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GREENSPAN-MARKETPLACE     09-17 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENSPAN-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: THE MAN WHO MOVES, AND SCARES, MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Alan Greenspan talks, the market listens. And
most of the time it doesn't like what it hears.
</P>
<P>
   During the last two years, on 31 occasions, the Federal Reserve
chairman has testified before Congress on a variety of matters. On
21 of those dates, almost 70 percent of the time, the market fell
immediately after his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Make that 22. Thursday, the Dow Jones industrial average dropped
by 216.01 points, a loss of 2.67 percent. It was the first full day
of trading after Greenspan's testimony Wednesday, in which he told
the House Banking Committee that there was no coordinated effort
among the world's central banks to cut interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were clearly disappointed that Greenspan presented no
solutions to the economic problems that have terrified many of the
world's markets. ``I was disturbed that the comments Mr. Greenspan
made about the changes that need to be made were all in the future
tense,'' said M. Cary Leahey, chief U.S. economist at High
Frequency Economics Ltd. in Valhalla, N.Y. ``He gave the impression
that he was no closer to solutions than he was in December.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's comments were just the latest in a long line of
disappointing utterances, at least where investors are concerned.
That the stock market falls fairly consistently when the Fed
chairman speaks is an indication that stock buyers think he's the
market's version of a wet blanket.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, investors have come to love Greenspan for his
ability to keep the economy on course. Until this summer, negative
reactions to his comments were temporary, usually lasting less than
a week. But his testimony before Congress on July 21 came only two
trading days after the broad stock market averages reached their
peaks. Since then, it's been rough sledding for shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Tracking what happens to stocks after the Fed chairman's
testimony _ what might be called the Greenspan effect _ comes
courtesy of Tom McClellan, of The McClellan Market Report, a
technical analysis investment advisory service based in Lakewood,
Wash. McClellan went back to 1996 for his research and included
only those occasions when Greenspan addressed Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to be his personality that he has been able to talk
down the market with words rather than actions,'' McClellan said.
``But it is funny how the market and investors hear what they want
to hear in the words that cross his lips.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's speech at the University of California at Berkeley
two weeks ago, which ignited the market Sept. 8, is a prime example
of investors' hearing in the Fed chairman's comments exactly what
they want to hear. Even though the speech gave only the hint that a
rate cut might be forthcoming, the market rallied by 380 points.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, though, Greenspan drives the market down with
his talks. For example, on July 18, 1996, he appeared at his
twice-yearly question-and-answer session with congressional
committees _ known as the Humphrey-Hawkins testimony, after a 1970s
law the requires the Fed chairman to make such congressional
appearances. He reminded the lawmakers that even if the nation was
indeed in a new economic era, as many were arguing, inflation could
still threaten economic stability and growth. For the next three
days, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 2.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 21, 1997, Greenspan addressed the Senate Budget
Committee. The only fretting he did in this talk was to worry about
a possible pickup in wage costs. The Dow lost 3.3 percent of its
value in the next five trading days.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the chairman has been especially talkative. He has
testified before Congress 15 times to date; in all of 1997, he
spoke on 14 occasions.
</P>
<P>
   So far in 1998, on nine occasions investors have reacted
negatively to Greenspan's testimony; on three occasions, they liked
what they heard. Twice, the market had no reaction at all.
</P>
<P>
   McClellan has limited his research to congressional testimony.
``When I looked at the dates of his speeches that were not
testimony,'' he said, ``there wasn't as good a correlation for what
the market did afterward. Routine speeches to the Rotary Club or
the University of California don't have the same effect on the
market.''
</P>
<P>
   The Greenspan effect could, of course, be a calculated one.
``He's been trying to let air gently out of the balloon for nearly
two years now,'' Leahey said, referring to inflated stock prices.
``The market has listened to him for a day and then has forgotten
what he said two days later.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
