<DOCNO> NYT19980917.0434 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1531 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-RABBI-MURDER-2TAKE     09-17 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-RABBI-MURDER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RABBI'S ARREST IN WIFE'S KILLING IS A TRIAL FOR THE FAITHFUL
</HEADLINE>
   (bl) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHERRY HILL, N.J. _ Nearly four years have passed since Rabbi
Fred Neulander returned from temple one autumn evening to find his
wife bludgeoned to death in their Colonial home here. Yet the more
time that passes, the more Neulander seems to embody a wrenching
test of faith for the 900 families who worship at the Congregation
M'Kor Shalom, the synagogue he founded more than 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   His family had barely finished sitting shiva for his wife, Carol
Neulander, when the whispers began about the couple's marital
problems. Then, an unusually talkative prosecutor publicly branded
Neulander as a possible suspect. The homicide investigation soon
revealed that Rabbi Neulander was involved in an affair with a
Philadelphia radio personality, forcing him to resign from the
temple and relinquish his status as one of southern New Jersey's
most prominent clerics.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the years of open speculation and a torrent of news
leaks, nothing prepared many Cherry Hill residents for the events
of the last week, when Neulander was arrested on charges that he
hired a hit man to kill his wife. He was led in front of television
and newspaper photographers wearing handcuffs and an orange prison
jumpsuit.
</P>
<P>
   To those who accept Neulander's apologies for his adultery, and
his steadfast denial of any involvement in the killing, the arrest
and impending trial are expected to pose strong challenges to their
faith in the rabbi.
</P>
<P>
   ``My faith in him as a person and my faith in his innocence
remain,'' said David Diamondstein, one of a handful of congregants
who still attend the wedding services and bar mitzvahs that
Neulander is asked to perform. ``But if evidence arises to change
that, I will be very disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   But the many congregants who believe that Neulander orchestrated
his wife's killing on Nov. 1, 1994, have been grappling with even
more profound questions, which cut to the core of their faith. How
does a believer reconcile the sins of a spiritual leader with the
message of peace he has so eloquently espoused?
</P>
<P>
   ``To us, he was God's voice, right here,'' said one member of
M'Kor Shalom, who insisted on anonymity. ``How could he deceive us
for all those years when he was disobeying God's law? How could he
let down so many people who looked to him for guidance? How can we
believe in anything he said all those years?''
</P>
<P>
   The arrest of any religious leader is startling, but Rabbi
Neulander's fall from grace is especially remarkable because of his
stature before the killing. He and his wife founded the temple in
an old warehouse in Mount Laurel in 1974 and, through his charisma,
expanded the congregation to become the largest Reform temple in
southern New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   M'Kor Shalom, which means ``A Source of Peace,'' was part of the
Reconstructionist movement, which sought to preserve traditional
Jewish rituals but adapt them to modern life and contemporary
social causes. It was one of the first temples in the area to grant
equal status to women, said Cherry Hill Mayor Susan Bass Levin, a
former congregant. Under Neulander's direction, its social action
committee financed a wide range of community projects, including
programs for the homeless and an AIDS ministry.
</P>
<P>
   M'Kor Shalom eventually joined the more mainstream Reform
movement, and before his departure, the rabbi gave personal
attention to the synagogue's Hebrew school. But he never abandoned
his flair for showmanship. He once commemorated the Exodus by
directing the schoolchildren onto the temple grounds, where they
were left to wander aimlessly, like their ancestors who were exiled
in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   During his sermons, he frequently prowled the aisles, posing
moral questions like a TV talk show host.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was incredibly respected,'' said the Rev. William Levering,
a minister at the First Presbyterian Church in nearby Haddonfield.
``Both a mover and shaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind that winning public image, however, Neulander, 57, also
led a tangled secret life. He has admitted to adultery with two
women in his congregation, including Elaine Soncini, a radio host
who had gone to him in 1992 seeking solace after her husband's
death. As their affair progressed, Ms. Soncini began pressuring
Neulander to end his marriage, according to her statements to
police, and threatened to break off their relationship if he did
not leave his wife by Christmas 1994.
</P>
<P>
   According to law enforcement officials familiar with Ms.
Soncini's testimony before a grand jury, she said that several
months before Carol Neulander was killed, the rabbi told her,
``Trust me, something will happen by the end of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   The officials said that Ms. Soncini also testified that after
Mrs. Neulander's death, the rabbi told her, ``See, I told you to
trust me.''
</P>
<P>
   Camden County Prosecutor Lee Solomon has argued in court that
Neulander hired a hit man to kill his wife because he feared a
divorce would reveal his adultery and cost him his position as head
rabbi. The authorities have been unable to locate the killer or the
blunt object they said was used to kill Mrs. Neulander, but they
plan to call at least two other witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Neulander, one of the couple's three children, was
talking on the telephone with Mrs. Neulander a few minutes before
she was killed. Ms. Neulander has testified that her mother told
her that there was a deliveryman at the door, and that he had been
sent by her father.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Neulander's former racquetball partner, Myron Levin, has
also told the authorities that the rabbi had talked openly about
ending his marriage. Several weeks before the killing, Levin
testified before the grand jury, the rabbi slammed his racquet to
the ground during a game and exclaimed, ``I wish I would come home
one day and find my wife dead on the floor,'' according to law
enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   Levin testified that Neulander then asked if he could help him
arrange her death.
</P>
<P>
   But Neulander's lawyers said the statements by Rebecca Neulander
and Ms. Soncini are hardly evidence of a murder plot and may not be
admissible in court. A defense lawyer, Jeffrey Zucker, also
ridiculed Levin, 72, as a ``feeble old man with a vivid
imagination'' and said he was not credible because he had a lengthy
criminal record.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``This case has no murder weapon and no murderer,'' said Dennis
Wixted, another lawyer for the rabbi. ``And so far, there's no
provable motive except the supposition that if you're having an
affair you are responsible for your spouse's death.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most striking things about the case, investigators
say, was the condition of Neulander's clothing the day of the
killing. The living room in which the rabbi found his wife slain
was spattered with blood. But when an ambulance responded to the
rabbi's emergency call, there wasn't a speck of blood on his hands,
face or clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't check for a pulse, didn't hold her, didn't kneel on
the floor, didn't get anywhere near her,'' said one investigator.
``Is that how you would react if you had nothing to do with it?''
</P>
<P>
   Wixted said he did not know what was on Neulander's clothes that
day because the prosecutor's office had not yet turned over
discovery material.
</P>
<P>
   With the trial looming, nearly everyone in the community is
bracing for a new round of media coverage, salacious details and
soul-searching, Mayor Bass Levin said. And nowhere is there more
anxious anticipation than at M'Kor Shalom.
</P>
<P>
   A few members quit M'Kor Shalom after Neulander was ousted in
1995 and never joined another synagogue, said a religious leader
who insisted on anonymity. Dozens of families quit and joined one
of Cherry Hill's five other temples.
</P>
<P>
   But most congregants have stayed, and the temple's leaders have
handled the crisis by saying that Neulander's infidelities were
wrong. Today M'Kor Shalom has more members than it did when Mrs.
Neulander was killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have new leadership now and we're in a new place,'' said
Linda Angstreich, a director and former board president. ``This
temple has come a long way in four years and we're doing
terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Angstreich said that she and other board members had
avoided discussions of the slaying case because ``it's not an issue
that we should comment on.''
</P>
<P>
   For individuals and family members, however, the court
proceedings are certain to rekindle questions over the character of
a man they used to rely on for moral guidance.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Karl is taking a more detached view. Karl said Neulander
performed his son's bar mitzvah a few months before the killing,
and when the accusations later arose at the dinner table, he urged
his children to remember the distinction between the frailties of
human beings and the power of God.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's odd,'' said Karl, a Cherry Hill judge. ``Our discussions
about him are a lot like the discussions we're having now about
President Clinton. You question these things because he's a role
model and he's supposed to behave in a certain way. But I tell my
kids, people are people. The reality is, you have to teach them not
to be in awe of anyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
