<HEADER>
A1536 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-BOEHNER-INVEST     09-17 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-BOEHNER-INVESTIGATION-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
 &HT;    
 &HT;      BOEHNER WANTS FBI TO PROBE SMEAR CAMPAIGN; 
 &HT;      WHITE HOUSE DENIES INVOLVEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Ronald F. Eckstein  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Sept. 17 -- The White House's alleged ``Scorched
Earth'' campaign against detractors of President Clinton is adding
fuel to the fire of House Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John A. Boehner, R-West Chester, and seven other House
Republican leaders have requested FBI Director Louis Freeh
investigate a ``systematic attempt (by Clinton allies) to
intimidate ... elected members of the House from doing their
constitutional duty by promoting prurient allegations about their
personal lives to the media.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans made their request in a letter to Freeh
Thursday, after reports surfaced of a 25-year-old adulterous affair
involving House Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill -- which Hyde
admitted. Hyde would preside over impeachment hearings if they are
held.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that this tactic has been employed by the White House
to attack opponents of the president during this entire
investigation,'' Boehner said.
</P>
<P>
   Two other Clinton critics -- Reps. Helen Chenoweth, R-Idaho, and
Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind. -- have recently had their past infidelity
reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sick,'' Boehner said of any effort to blackmail Clinton
enemies. Because the House of Representatives would hold hearings
and vote on whether the Senate should hold an impeachment trial,
Boehner added that ``outing'' congressmen would be comparable to
trying to intimidate potential jurors.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials heartily denied the
Republicans' allegations. In a letter to Hyde, White House Chief of
Staff Erskine Bowles promised to fire any staffers involved in
spreading gossip about lawmakers' private lives. White House Press
Secretary Mike McCurry also said any employee involved ``would no
longer be on staff.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a friend of the husband of Hyde's old mistress
claimed full credit for publicizing the story of that affair.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans are not convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly there is credible evidence that an organized campaign
of slander and intimidation may exist. If it does, any individuals
promoting such a campaign may be in violation of federal criminal
law,'' they wrote in the letter to Freeh.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans attached 11 examples of evidence from television and
newspaper reports pointing to a ``White House Smear Campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This goes to the core of the Constitution -- the separation of
powers. The executive branch is employing these tactics against the
legislative branch'' Boehner said. ``If this is coming from the
White House, I would recommend it be included in the impeachment
report.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 2150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980917.0438 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1537 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LINDBERGH-DAUGHTER-AR     09-17 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINDBERGH-DAUGHTER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REEVE LINDBERGH: A DAUGHTER'S LIFE OF REFLECTED GLORY AND PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By JOYCE WADLER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The mother of Charles Lindbergh, his biographers have
noted, was one of those omnipresent moms: Separated from
Lindbergh's father when Lindbergh was 2, she accompanied her son to
college, and hovered so close to him that at 25 the man who would
be the world's most famous aviator had never had a date.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, it seems reasonable to pose a question to Reeve Lindbergh,
the flier's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible Charles Lindbergh took to the air because it was
the only way he could get away from mom?
</P>
<P>
   A delighted howl from Ms. Lindbergh, in town from Vermont, in
comfortable clogs, a long, flowered skirt and a pink cotton
sweater, who, if her father was cool, mother reserved, reflects
neither of either.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think that, too?'' she says. ``That's always been my
theory. Single-engine plane, one seat. By golly, that would be the
way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   She assumes the role of the Lone Eagle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got to cross the Atlantic, Mom. Can't take you. It's a
one-seater. Monoplane. MONO _ get it, Mom? _ one.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two new books on Lindbergh, who became one of the
century's greatest heroes when he flew the Atlantic solo in 1927:
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Berg's ``Lindbergh'' (Putnam), an 800-page biography
done with the Lindbergh family's cooperation, portrays Lindbergh as
an emotionally remote man who insisted that his wife cry in private
after the death of their first son and who ignored his wife for
much of their marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is ``Under a Wing'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster), by Reeve
Lindbergh, 53, a novelist and children's book writer who is the
youngest of Lindbergh's six children. Ms. Lindbergh recalls a
father who made lists of his children's failings, but who was
playful and affectionate, too.
</P>
<P>
   It also depicts Ms. Lindbergh's attempts to deal with her
father's anti-Semitic remarks after his death _ of hearing him on
tape in a 1941 speech in Des Moines, saying that one of the
``greatest dangers'' to the United States is the influence of Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was transfixed and horrified, ablaze with shame and fury,''
she writes. `` `Not you!' I cried out silently to myself and to him
_ `No! You never said such things.'''
</P>
<P>
   Is it coincidence that the two books are out at the same time?
</P>
<P>
   Yes and no.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lindbergh's publisher made the decision to release her book
at the same time as Berg's. But her memoir was prompted not by
concern about the biography, but by the death of her sister, Anne,
five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a way to keep her voice alive,'' Ms. Lindbergh says.
``And in writing about her, I ended up writing about all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lindbergh likes Berg and, while she finds his portrait of
her father ``a little skewed,'' she likes his book. She sent Berg
chapters of her own book for comment as she was writing. She cannot
get too shook up about Berg's suggestion that her mother, the
writer Anne Morrow Lindbergh, had an affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think love is wonderful,'' says Ms. Lindbergh, who married
her second husband the day she divorced her first and has had an
unconventional domestic life herself. ``I graduated college in '68.
What can I say?''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ms. Lindbergh admits, there was a desire to protect her
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I write about the whole Des Moines thing twice, because the
first time I mentioned it, I didn't deal with it,'' Ms. Lindbergh
says. ``My editor pointed that out. The rage and the tears.
Originally, it wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   And why, as the analysts say, do we think that is?
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lindbergh laughs again.
</P>
<P>
   A famous name, Ms. Lindbergh says, is like ``another member of
the family, like your eccentric uncle.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lindbergh describes the uncle: ``Moody, sometimes horrific,
a real pain in the neck. He intrudes where he's not supposed to be,
he makes inappropriate jokes, but sometimes he comes home loaded
with presents. Every so often you wish someone would take him away
and lock him up. Uncle Lindy.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Lindbergh was a girl, if her father was recognized in a
restaurant, the family had to leave. At Radcliffe, friends told Ms.
Lindbergh that they were surprised they liked her, considering her
father was a fascist.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Ms. Lindbergh realized, it is inevitable that family
history becomes your own. Ms. Lindbergh has two grown daughters and
an 11-year- old son. Fourteen years ago she lost her first son,
Jonathan, to complications from encephalitis. Jonathan was 2, the
same age Ms. Lindbergh's brother had been when he was kidnapped and
killed. Ms. Lindbergh's mother insisted that her daughter sit with
her child's body.
</P>
<P>
   I never saw my son's body after he died,'' Anne Lindbergh said.
</P>
<P>
   Reeve Lindbergh talks again about fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Johnny died, we ordered this very simple little stone
that said, `Jonathan Lindbergh Brown, with love and light,''' Ms.
Lindbergh says.
</P>
<P>
   She averts her face, looking down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a very light, a kind of illuminating personality. Very
humorous. When the gravestone came back, the word Lindbergh was in
bigger letters than the others. I was so angry I made them take it
back and redo it. I never do things like that, never send food back
or make a fuss, but the idea that this little child should be
remembered as a Lindbergh rather than as himself.''
</P>
<P>
   She resents the fame?
</P>
<P>
   ``At times of loss I want things to be humane and real. Not be
inflated by me or anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
