<SLUG> BC-HKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ISLANDERS' FANS TAKING WILD RIDE  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINEOLA, N.Y. _ Just when you thought you had seen every
possible outrage for sports fans, along comes a new one: the
Islanders moved their offices off Long Island and into New York
City the other day, on the brink of the new training season.
Involved in a dispute that is either about the safety of Nassau
Coliseum or how much money can be wrung out of this faded
franchise, the new management is also threatening to seek other
sites in the three-state region for regular-season games.
</P>
<P>
   The owners of the Islanders have told fans that if they want to
see the first exhibition next Friday, they are going to have to
schlep to the upstate village of Lake Placid, five hours in each
direction. A thoughtful team official did arrange a free bus ride,
but will the owners subsidize travel to possible league games in
Connecticut, New Jersey and New York City? I am guessing they will
not.
</P>
<P>
   Here we are, looking forward to a classic 10 days of the
Once-Again Amazing Mets, Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire, but this
grubby Islander business is the true face of sports in America. The
Islander scenario is: Buy team. Wait for ink to dry. Get into feud
with stadium management. Threaten to move games.
</P>
<P>
   This is what has happened to the Islanders, a bad team playing
in a dismal barn, but with a great history and fans just aching to
be treated decently. Once upon a time, the Islanders won four
straight Stanley Cups, from 1980 through 1983, with charismatic
stars like Mike Bossy, Denis Potvin, Billy Smith and Bryan
Trottier. Then the ownership grew remote, and the team went
downhill. A prospective owner named John Spano lied himself into a
prison sentence. Needing somebody to run this historic franchise,
the league found Steven Gluckstern and Howard Milstein, developers
whose eyes just might be more on the wide-open spaces surrounding
the Coliseum than on finding players or pleasing fans.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting until the team was assembling at training camp upstate,
the new owners claimed the Coliseum was unsafe, which must have
been shocking news to Michelle Kwan and everybody else who skated
there in the recent Goodwill Games.
</P>
<P>
   When the ownership of the Islanders and SMG, which administers
the Coliseum, could not agree on safety, the new management
demanded an inspection, and moved out, the biggest pre-emptive
evacuation of a sports franchise since Robert Irsay sneaked the
Colts out of Baltimore one dark and stormy night.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, all sides discussed their ugly little grudge match at
the offices of the Nassau County executive, Thomas Gulotta. After
six and a half hours, the talks broke up. Gulotta, bristling with
real or feigned anger, likened the ownership to ``a pig at a
trough'' and said he would not tolerate a ``gun at the head'' of
Nassau County taxpayers. He said some of the same things to SMG
when Gluckstern and Milstein were trying to buy the team last
February. Gulotta also said the six and a half hours of discussion
had been 99 percent about money and 1 percent about safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``That just wasn't the case,'' said David Seldin, the president
of the Islanders, formerly with the Jacksonville Jaguars and once
on the board of governors of SMG while working for the Pritzker
company in Chicago. ``Safety was a significant issue in the
discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, a lawyer for the Islanders, John Zuccotti,
said the Islanders might be willing to let the NHL make the final
determination about whether the building was safe.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the meeting broke down, the owners discovered that
Nassau County had already secured a temporary restraining order to
be heard in court next Wednesday. Wednesday evening, Bill Daly, the
senior vice president of legal affairs for the NHL, said that an
inspection would be arranged by Tuesday or Wednesday and that there
was time to determine if the season could begin on Oct. 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bottom line is, this is a lease dispute,'' said Daly, who
added, ``We have to make sure the building is safe before we
require the team to play there.'' It seems rather seedy, but New
York fans have seen this stuff before. George Steinbrenner has been
blustering about needing a new stadium, but taxpayers in New Jersey
and New York just might resist building one for him. It takes
courage to stand up to owners because the grim potential is losing
a team. Brooklyn lost the Dodgers 40 years ago and in a few years
could welcome a minor league team in Coney Island to partly cover
up the gaping hole in its civic heart.
</P>
<P>
   Things go faster these days. These new Islander owners just
arrived, but already they are packing up and moving off Long
Island, the fans' loyalties being crushed under the wheels.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
