<SLUG> BC-MARKET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS PLUNGE WORLDWIDE AMID ECONOMIC JITTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (shortens 6th graf and corrects figure to $3.4 billion sted $3.5
billion.)  (bl) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices tumbled around the world Thursday after
overseas investors digested word that central banks are planning no
coordinated cut in interest rates to quell financial and economic
turmoil in Asia, Latin America and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of the release of President Clinton's videotaped
grand jury testimony in the Monica Lewinsky matter and Japanese
banking problems also weighed on stock markets, which skidded to a
12{-year low in Tokyo and finished nearly 5 percent lower in Brazil
after a plunge twice that much halted trading.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign turmoil quickly spread to the United States, where the
Dow Jones industrial average dropped 200 points in the first
half-hour before steadying for the rest of the day. It closed down
216.01 points, or 2.67 percent, to 7,873.77. The loss broke a
string of four straight gains, the first since late June, and
pushed the blue-chip indicator back into negative territory for the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Although Wall Street seemed only mildly disappointed when
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan told Congress on Wednesday
that there were no current efforts to coordinate an interest-rate
cut, overseas markets reacted by selling off sharply, and this
pressure spilled over into the U.S. markets.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts here said they thought Greenspan, along with
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, had sought to avoid comments that
could have reduced pressure on the House to approve $18 billion to
replenish depleted aid coffers at the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The House refused to consider the full amount anyway. Instead,
approved only $3.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, predicted Alfred Goldman, chief market
strategist at A.G. Edwards in St. Louis, ``The IMF will get their
funding. We have no choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Still another factor affecting trading was Friday's quarterly
``triple witching'' phenomenon, when options and futures contracts
expire.
</P>
<P>
   European markets slumped across the board, but the greatest fall
was in France, where the CAC 40 index fell 5.47 percent after the
communications giant Alcatel warned of lower profits, citing the
crises in Asia and Russia. Shares dived 12 1/16, to 19\, on the New
York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Leading indexes tumbled 4.99 percent in Germany and 3 percent in
London, also reflecting fears of lost business with economically
distressed countries.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, the Nikkei index fell 338.56 points, or 2.38 percent,
to 13,859.14, its lowest point since March 1986. Government leaders
worked deep into the night to find a way to reorganize the
debt-laden Japanese banking system. Stocks fell 3.61 percent in
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   After absorbing the early selling, U.S. markets fluctuated in a
relatively narrow range by recent standards, but almost nothing
escaped the downdraft. All 30 Dow stocks posted losses, as did 424
of the issues in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, which
dropped 2.55 percent for the day.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index, dominated by technology stocks,
slumped about the same amount, 2.58 percent, with Microsoft down
3\, to 104 15/16, and Cisco Systems down 3[, to 61{.
</P>
<P>
   Without minimizing the buffeting from overseas forces, many
analysts said they were not surprised by Thursday's retreat after
four sizable advances and said they remained upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pulling back into its recent bottoming pattern'' said
Richard McCabe, chief market analyst at Merrill Lynch. ``It was
probably entitled to give some back after the nice bounce off
7,500'' on the Dow. He said the index could reach the mid-8,000s
within a month.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks were pummeled once again, especially major
banks with big exposure to emerging markets. Citicorp slumped 6\,
to 96{, and J.P. Morgan was the biggest contributor to the Dow's
decline, falling 5{, to 89}. American Express lost 3 3/16, to 83~.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette, which on Wednesday warned of lower sales, saw its
stock skid 3 5/16 Thursday as Merrill Lynch trimmed its estimate of
the company's earnings to between $1.30 and $1.35 a share for this
year and $1.55 for 1999, 5 cents less than before. The shares
closed at 36~ after trading as high as 62 21/32 in early April.
</P>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble, another blue chip that warned recently of
weaker results, fell 3 Thursday, to 67. Other prominent decliners
were Lucent Technologies, which dropped 4 7/16, to 72[, and
Northern Telecom, which fell 6 1/16, to 39{.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues on the New York Stock Exchange swamped gainers
by nearly 5 to 1 as 255 made new lows compared with only 21 new
highs.
</P>
<P>
   Volume was moderate at 692.56 million shares, well below that of
most recent sessions. Traders said they spotted no surge of
activity related to the unwinding of positions in advance of
Friday's triple-witching expiration of futures and options.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 2154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
