u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SOSA-NYT &LR;      09-17 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SOSA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBS SLUGGER FLIES OUT THREE TIMES  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By ED GUZMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Millimeters. Fractions of millimeters. That's how
close Sammy Sosa came to taking sole possession of the major league
home run lead.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, one night removed from driving in six runs and hitting his
63d home run, failed to connect Thursday afternoon, going 0-4 with
an eighth-inning walk. He just got under pitches to fly out three
times while grounding out and breaking his bat in the fourth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was a home run by his teammate Gary Gaetti leading
off the 10th inning that gave the Chicago Cubs a 4-3 victory at
Qualcomm Stadium. Gaetti's 18th home run, off Padres relief ace
Trevor Hoffman, was the Cubs' fifth home run of the series, in
which each of the four games was decided by a late inning homer.
</P>
<P>
   The victory extended the Cubs' lead in the National League
wild-card race to one game over the idle Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Rod Beck recorded his career-high 49th save of the season, but
only after shortstop Jose Hernandez fielded a hard grounder off
Beck's body and threw out Carlos Hernandez, with the tying run at
third.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres argued the out call, and television replays showed
that Hernandez was safe. But the Cubs still took their third
straight victory and fifth in six games.
</P>
<P>
   The Sosa phenomenon, meanwhile, continued to take hold of the
San Diego crowd, as another standing ovation greeted his his first
at-bat Thursday afternoon. The cheering for Sosa had been the
subject of discontent among Padres players, and the fireworks
Wednesday night after Sosa's homer only made them more furious.
Several Padre pitchers, including Joey Hamilton, Trevor Hoffman and
Sterling Hitchcock, continued to voice their displeasure after
Wednesday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players were upset not so much because the fans cheered
Sammy but because the organization saw fit to shoot off fireworks
and other stuff on our scoreboard after he hit the home run,''
right fielder Tony Gwynn said. ``We thought we were in a race here.
The fans cheering was expected, but they don't need to shoot off
fireworks. It's kicking us in the gut. But hey, today we just go
about our business and win some ball games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres pitching staff, usually seen milling around the
batting cage in the previous games of this series, was nowhere to
be found before Thursday afternoon's contest. They were reportedly
still fuming over Wednesday night's festivities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you read what the Padres players said in the newspaper
today?,'' said Cubs outfielder Glenallen Hill. ``Well, I think
that's kind of selfish not to be involved in such a great part of
history. Someday, each one of them will reflect back on this time
and they will say, `I was there, I saw it, it was a great thing.'
We know they're fighting for who gets home-field advantage. I
wouldn't let winning and losing sidetrack you from being a part of
history.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Cubs first baseman Mark Grace: ``I can understand their
feelings, but all of America is rooting for Sammy. The fans last
night cheered every time their pitcher struck Sammy out. They
wanted the Padres to win. Sometimes guys have to back away from the
competition and realize what's going on and see that in their
lifetime, they may never be a part of this again.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about this issue, Sosa seemed almost puzzled by all
the commotion. ``They know that it's the first time in history that
two people hit 63 in the same year,'' said Sosa in a pre-game news
conference on the field. ``I think that everyone should be happy,
even the Padres. Everybody likes baseball and I just want to keep
bringing people to the ball park and make this game a little bit
more exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   One fan who feels Sosa has brought excitement to baseball is the
Hall of Famer Reggie Jackson, who was here Thursday afternoon to
congratulate Sosa. Before the top of the fourth inning, the video
screen at Qualcomm Stadium showed Jackson's three-home run
performance in Game 6 of the 1977 World Series. When the screen
faded to a shot of him in the stands, he was received with a
standing ovation from the crowd. But Jackson has also been
impressed by the way Sosa has handled the media attention and the
pressure of the home run chase.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
