<HEADER>
A1552 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-BOEHNER-INVEST     09-17 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-BOEHNER-INVESTIGATION-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
 &HT;    
 &HT;      BOEHNER WANTS FBI TO PROBE SMEAR CAMPAIGN; 
 &HT;      WHITE HOUSE DENIES INVOLVEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Ronald F. Eckstein  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Sept. 17 -- The White House's alleged ``Scorched
Earth'' campaign against detractors of President Clinton is adding
fuel to the fire of House Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John A. Boehner, R-West Chester, and seven other House
Republican leaders have requested FBI Director Louis Freeh
investigate a ``systematic attempt (by Clinton allies) to
intimidate ... elected members of the House from doing their
constitutional duty by promoting prurient allegations about their
personal lives to the media.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans made their request in a letter to Freeh
Thursday, after reports surfaced of a 25-year-old adulterous affair
involving House Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill -- which Hyde
admitted. Hyde would preside over impeachment hearings if they are
held.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that this tactic has been employed by the White House
to attack opponents of the president during this entire
investigation,'' Boehner said.
</P>
<P>
   Two other Clinton critics -- Reps. Helen Chenoweth, R-Idaho, and
Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind. -- have recently had their past infidelity
reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sick,'' Boehner said of any effort to blackmail Clinton
enemies. Because the House of Representatives would hold hearings
and vote on whether the Senate should hold an impeachment trial,
Boehner added that ``outing'' congressmen would be comparable to
trying to intimidate potential jurors.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials heartily denied the
Republicans' allegations. In a letter to Hyde, White House Chief of
Staff Erskine Bowles promised to fire any staffers involved in
spreading gossip about lawmakers' private lives. White House Press
Secretary Mike McCurry also said any employee involved ``would no
longer be on staff.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a friend of the husband of Hyde's old mistress
claimed full credit for publicizing the story of that affair.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans are not convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly there is credible evidence that an organized campaign
of slander and intimidation may exist. If it does, any individuals
promoting such a campaign may be in violation of federal criminal
law,'' they wrote in the letter to Freeh.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans attached 11 examples of evidence from television and
newspaper reports pointing to a ``White House Smear Campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This goes to the core of the Constitution -- the separation of
powers. The executive branch is employing these tactics against the
legislative branch'' Boehner said. ``If this is coming from the
White House, I would recommend it be included in the impeachment
report.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
