<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1553 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HARLEM-1STLD-WRITE     09-17 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HARLEM-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFFLUENT BLACKS DRAWN TO HARLEM BY PROPERTY BARGAINS AND HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (subs 2nd graf to add `and their daughter, Samantha...')  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By LISA W. FODERARO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Howard Sanders had garnered the trappings of American
success: a degree from Harvard Business School, a position with a
high-powered Manhattan investment firm and an apartment on Central
Park West.
</P>
<P>
   But Sanders, who is black, felt so strongly about one day owning
a home in Harlem, where he had grown up, that it became a condition
of his marriage proposal. Today, he and his wife, Karen, and their
daughter, Samantha, live in a five-bedroom brownstone with a
Japanese garden on West 147th Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to live next to a white family,'' Sanders, 32,
said. ``I effectively have integrated. I've gone to predominantly
white schools. I work in a white firm, and I can live anywhere I
want. It really is psychologically soothing for me to be in
Harlem.''
</P>
<P>
   What started in the early 1990s as a trickle of young
African-American lawyers, doctors, professors and bankers moving
back to Harlem and other historically black neighborhoods seems now
to have reached the flood stage.
</P>
<P>
   Black professionals are snatching up 5,000-square-foot
brownstones off avenues named for black leaders. And their
financial commitments extend beyond new boilers and restoring
woodwork; they are also looking to bring the amenities they had
found in Soho and the Upper West Side to neighborhoods that, while
on the upswing, are still marked by abandonment and a dearth of
shops and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Falling crime rates, relatively low housing prices, striking
residential architecture and signs of economic renewal are all
factors in the influx of affluent young black people to
historically black neighborhoods. But certain intangibles _
Harlem's storied place in the black consciousness, a new
generation's changing sensibility about integration, simple
idealism _ have played a role as well, scholars and new arrivals
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an economic incentive because you can basically get
housing for 30 to 40 percent of what you'd pay 25 blocks away,''
said Darren Walker, who gave up a doorman building in midtown
Manhattan and a career in the bond department of a Swiss bank to
move to Harlem and become a vice president of the nonprofit
Abyssinian Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I have always had a fascination with the Harlem of legend
and folklore,'' he said. ``Reading the writers of the Harlem
Renaissance created a lot of mythologies in our heads. I just feel
this visceral kind of connection that I don't know how to
describe.''
</P>
<P>
   Real estate brokers say there has also been a parallel increase
over the last five years in buyers without those connections _
white families and a small number of Asian-Americans _ who are
simply attracted by the amount of space and bygone splendor their
money can buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got houses up there with Honduran mahogany and 24-karat
gold leaf molding in the dining rooms,'' said Willie Kathryn Suggs,
a broker who estimates that buyers who are not black now account
for about 30 percent of her clients for row houses and
condominiums. ``To be able to have that kind of house in the city
is attractive to all kinds of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Other brokers say that the percentage of new buyers who are not
black is probably lower, between 10 and 15 percent, but that the
number is increasing more rapidly than the number of black buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Suggs cited as one example a white couple _ the husband is a
lawyer and the wife is a business consultant _ who closed last
month on a row house in the Hamilton Heights neighborhood, and who
told her they were interested in attracting theater companies to
the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Brokers say they have seen the effects of Harlem's pull. Housing
prices in West Harlem have risen 20 percent in five years,
according to R. Kenyatta Punter, a broker with the Harlem-based
Myers, Smith &AMP; Granady realty agency. Hard to market in the early
1990s, brownstones are now selling briskly, at prices ranging from
$80,000 for an abandoned shell to $450,000 for a house in perfect
condition.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the homes predate the Harlem Renaissance of the 1920s,
which is when many black people moving to New York chose to live in
Harlem, in part because it had a surplus of rental apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in the 1930s and accelerating through the '40s and
'50s, large numbers of black professionals left Harlem, although a
small middle-class presence remained through the decades, said
Winston James, an assistant professor of history at Columbia
University who specializes in the Harlem Renaissance. Their
departure followed the decay of apartment buildings during the
Depression and new opportunities for integration in places like
Brooklyn and Queens.
</P>
<P>
   James said the recent return of well-to-do blacks began in the
early 1990s and now seems ``to be expanding tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a sense of idealism among a large number of black
professional young people,'' he said. ``There is a terrible
frustration about the condition of black people in the society
despite the progress of many members of the professional class. I
suppose one of the ways people attempt to make some kind of
contribution is by their physical presence.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That is certainly true of Dr. Michael Jones. A 29-year-old ear,
nose and throat resident at Mount Sinai Medical Center, Jones said
he decided to move to Harlem after receiving both his undergraduate
and medical degrees from Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important for me to be in Harlem because I needed a
sense of purpose,'' he said. ``Being in Chelsea or Tribeca or the
Upper East Side, I wouldn't feel that my presence could make a
difference. Children on my block say, `Hey, Doc.' They see me
working hard. And because they can see it and touch it, they may
feel it's something they can attain.''
</P>
<P>
   His home, on West 147th Street between Convent and St. Nicholas
Avenues, is a handsome 6,000-square-foot brownstone in the leafy
section known both as Sugar Hill and Hamilton Heights.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With Jones' BMW parked out front and his carefully tended pink
and white impatiens in back, the house has become a beacon for
young people tempted to give Harlem a try. ``I started having
networking parties and became a funnel for a lot of young black
professionals who wanted to find brownstones here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One drawback is the lack of stores and services. Although ground
was recently broken for Harlem USA, an ambitious retail and
entertainment complex on 125th Street that is to include the area's
first Gap and Disney stores, commercial development farther north
has been spotty.
</P>
<P>
   ``When friends come to visit or when I'm tired and want to grab
a quick cup of gourmet coffee, I absolutely wish those amenities
were here,'' Jones said. ``But it's my dream to make them happen.
It's up to us to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Having already carved out a busy sideline in real estate
development by buying, renovating and selling old brownstones and
boardinghouses, mostly in Hamilton Heights, Jones is now determined
to fill the void of stylish restaurants with his latest venture,
the Sugar Hill Cafe. The plan calls for a combination coffeehouse,
restaurant and jazz club on three floors of a brownstone at 458 W.
145th St.
</P>
<P>
   Jones bought the building in June for $300,000 with two partners
who are also Harlem residents: Dineo Khabele, a fellow in
gynecology-oncology at Montefiore Medical Center, and her husband,
James Hunter, an engineer. The three plan to spend $450,000 to
renovate the tattered turn-of-the-century building, where the
original oak floors and elaborately carved mantelpieces are still
intact. They are now seeking financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the most affluent neighborhood in Harlem,'' Jones
said, ``without any quality dining establishments within walking
distance.''
</P>
<P>
   Other black professionals are considering buying franchises to
open businesses like florists and copy centers. The franchise
chains are expanding into Harlem and four other city neighborhoods
through a new program sponsored by the Local Initiatives Support
Corp., a nonprofit group in Manhattan, and Bankers Trust Co.
</P>
<P>
   The sponsors are recruiting entrepreneurs to team up with local
community development groups to buy the franchises, benefiting from
below-market financing and looser equity requirements. The first
such franchise, a Sterling Optical store, opened in Harlem on Sept.
2 on the corner of 125th Street and Lenox Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   While no hard numbers exist to document the movement of black
professionals to Harlem, the higher real estate prices speak
volumes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last five years, it has really gained momentum,'' said
Sherman Edmiston, a Harlem real estate agent whose wife, Essie
Green Edmiston, owns an art gallery there. ``We are getting more of
the younger people coming here with the idea that they want to be
part of the rebuilding of Harlem. They've got fresh ideas and a
considerable amount of money.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the Edmistons were pioneers in deciding 10 years
ago to move their home and art gallery from Park Slope in Brooklyn
to Harlem. Like many parts of the city, Harlem was then still in
the violent throes of the crack epidemic, and art meccas like SoHo
or 57th Street would have seemed a more likely choice for their
gallery, which sells the art of such black masters as Jacob
Lawrence and Romare Bearden.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we felt that our concentration is really on developing the
collections of black collectors, and there's a poetry to our being
in Harlem as opposed to being downtown,'' said Edmiston, who also
works in the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   The couple might have also considered Bedford-Stuyvesant, a
historically black community in Brooklyn that has plenty of scruffy
bodegas and garish beauty parlors but is known for its beautiful
brownstones. It, too, is drawing black professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis A. Watkins, district manager of Community Board 3, which
covers Bedford-Stuyvesant, attributes the trend to rising housing
prices in more gentrified Brooklyn neighborhoods like Park Slope
and Brooklyn Heights. ``You can buy the same town house in Bed-Stuy
for $250,000 that would sell for a half-million dollars in Park
Slope,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But for Monique Greenwood, the executive editor of Essence
magazine, and her husband, Glenn Pogue, a broadcast engineer for
WNBC-TV, money was not the only motivator. ``We could easily go to
the suburbs,'' she said, ``but we're about rebuilding our
communities and living in them.''
</P>
<P>
   One concern the couple had was the public schools. Ms. Greenwood
said that while she wanted her 6-year-old daughter, Glynn, to
attend a public school, ``I wasn't convinced that I wanted my child
to suffer because of my political beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   After checking out several private schools in Brooklyn, as well
as the public elementary schools, the couple decided that Glynn
could receive as good an education in the gifted program in their
neighborhood school as in private school. But they knew it would
mean more involvement on their part.
</P>
<P>
   During the last school year, the couple met weekly with other
parents, teachers and administrators as part of the school-based
management team to discuss issues, from the curriculum to grant
money. In the spring, they sat on the selection committee
responsible for hiring the new principal.
</P>
<P>
   Like Dr. Jones in Harlem, Ms. Greenwood also missed the
smorgasbord of services in wealthier New York neighborhoods. So
she, too, took matters into her own hands. Three years ago, she and
her husband opened Akwaaba Mansion, a lavish bed-and-breakfast in
the 18-room house that is also their home. (Akwaaba means welcome
in Akan, a language spoken in Ghana.)
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, they opened Akwaaba Cafe, a restaurant with
burgundy banquettes and light fixtures of copper wire, parchment
paper and colored glass beads. ``I realized I had to be involved in
economic development,'' Ms. Greenwood said, ``because the amenities
I would want in a neighborhood just weren't there.''
</P>
<P>
   While the commercial life of Harlem may never be as abundant or
luxurious as points south in Manhattan, that's fine with Sanders,
the investment banker. (It's easy enough, he said, to drive five
minutes south for Sunday brunch on Amsterdam Avenue.) Harlem, he
says, feeds his soul in a way that other Manhattan neighborhoods
never could.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be quite honest, there are cultural differences, and when
you live in your own community, there's not that pressure to
assimilate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm basking in my own culture when I go to the Schomberg
Center,'' he said, referring to the New York Public Library's
Schomberg Center for Research in Black Culture. ``If I lived in the
West Village I couldn't do that. I'd have to seek out activities
that brought me into contact with black professionals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
