</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-5-QUESTIONS-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM CLAY FORD JR.: A DIFFERENT SORT OF SCION  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   William Clay Ford Jr., soon to be chairman of Ford Motor Co., is
not exactly a car man from central casting.
</P>
<P>
   The auto industry has been feuding with environmentalists ever
since air quality became an issue in the 1960s, but Ford has long
been active in environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   He is a great-grandson of a famously autocratic industrial titan
and leads an extended family that still controls 40 percent of
Ford's voting stock, but he is happy to share power and the
spotlight with Jacques A. Nasser, who will become Ford's president
and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   After the company announced on Sept. 11 that Ford, 41, and
Nasser, 50, would succeed Alexander Trotman, 65, at the end of the
year, Ford talked about driving down roads less traveled. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. You've said Ford will seek environmental leadership in your
tenure. Is there a tension between that and maximizing profits?
</P>
<P>
   A. In the short term, there probably is a tension. But I think
in the long term, if we are the leading corporate citizen, it will
do several things for us. It will create an image for Ford in the
marketplace that is different from others, and in a cluttered and
crowded marketplace in which differentiation is hard to obtain,
particularly in image. If we achieve this, we will attract better
employees and the highest caliber of people out of universities.
They're going to want to come work for a company like Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is it true that when you joined the Ford board, you were
asked to distance yourself from the environmental movement?
</P>
<P>
   A. Somebody close to the board thought it would be a good idea
if I stopped associating with crazies, and I assured them that not
only was I not doing so, but that the group I was involved with,
which was very benign _ the Nature Conservancy _ was made up of a
cross-section of our customers. At the time, I was in Switzerland,
where business and environmentalists actually had a dialogue. In
this country, all they did was snipe at each other. I felt that
somebody needed to start building bridges, so I really chose to
stay involved.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are you going to have formal meetings with Nasser to
coordinate your division of responsibilities?
</P>
<P>
   A. We're going to have to set aside some formal time so that we
can both make sure we actually do it. And then there's going to be
a lot of just wandering into each other's offices and picking up
the phone. The less formal that we can make this, and the more of a
true partnership in making it easy, I think, the better it's going
to be for the company. That's something that both he and I want to
do. We really have a running start on this because we've known each
other a long time. We get on very well; we think the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Splitting the jobs of chairman and chief executive is
unusual. You're busy now with running the Detroit Lions football
team and other activities. Might you someday want to add the job of
chief executive at Ford?
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't believe so. I really believe this is a great setup.
One of the nice things about this arrangement is that it does use
the strength of two capable people. Having watched how large this
company has become, and how tough it is to manage, I think
separating these jobs makes a lot of sense. And internationally, as
you know, that is quite common _ less so in this country. Jac and I
both concluded this is the way to go. We're both relatively young,
and I think we'll hopefully be at this a long time together. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. After Princeton, why did you choose to study management at
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology rather than at the more
famous Harvard Business School?
</P>
<P>
   A. As a liberal arts major as an undergrad, I felt I would be
best served by going to the most quantitative program that I could
find. I felt that would give me the best rounding-out experience,
and, in fact, I think that was true.
</P>
<P>
   I was one of only two non-engineers in my class at MIT, and it
was a great experience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
