<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lockhart looking iffy for playoffs
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phoenix _ Has Keith Lockhart's gimpy right hamstring knocked the
second baseman out of the playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart won't go that far but he is second-guessing how he has
treated the injury, first sustained Aug. 22. He has made four
starts since then but felt the hamstring twinge so strongly in his
last game last Saturday that he hasn't been able to play since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess maybe I should have gone on the DL when I first did
it,'' Lockhart said Thursday. ``But everyone I talked to said it
wasn't bleeding. Usually if it's black and blue, it's done pretty
good and this wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's at the point now if it does anything else, then they'll
have to shut it down. I'm still going to have to play a few games.
It's getting to playoff time. That's why every day is pretty
crucial. I'm just trying to be real crucial. But I also have to
play a few games to keep sharp.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Cox would not rule out the possibility that rookie Marty
Malloy could take Lockhart's place in the first round, but also
made it sound that a less-than-100 percent Lockhart would still be
his preference.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very good defensive player,'' Cox said. ``Even if he's
85 (percent), he gets to everything. And if he can play that way
... ''
</P>
<P>
   Cox was also waiting for a more definitive reading of Walt
Weiss. Though the shortstop thought he was over a problem with his
left quadriceps, Weiss scored from first base Wednesday on a Curtis
Pride double and felt the quad act up. He was replaced by rookie
call-up Mark DeRosa three innings later and was in discomfort
Thursday. Ozzie Guillen started in his spot Thursday after
left-hander Omar Daal.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore calling?
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are declining comment on interest the Baltimore
Orioles are reportedly showing Atlanta assistant GM Dean Taylor.
With O's GM Pat Gillick having given word he will step down after
this year and his assistant, Kevin Malone, freshly hired in Los
Angeles, the Orioles are conducting a low-profile serach for a new
front-office head.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor was interviewed by the Dodgers for their vacancy but did
not make a short list of finalists. Braves GM John Schuerholz would
not verify that the team had given permission to Baltimore to talk
with Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I can say right now,'' said Taylor, ``is any
comment on this needs to come from them.'' And the O's aren't
talking.
</P>
<P>
   Bautista ready
</P>
<P>
   The Braves were planning to activate outfielder Danny Bautista
from the DL before Thursday's game, 24 days after he sustained a
slight tear in the medial colateral ligament in his right knee
during a collision with Los Angeles catcher Tom Prince. Cox said he
would probably hold Bautista out until Saturday's game against
Arizona lefty Brian Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
