<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1562 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-DISCLOSURES-B     09-17 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DISCLOSURES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP SEEKS FBI PROBE OF EMBARRASSING DISCLOSURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican leaders, livid over the disclosure of a
30-year-old affair involving House Judiciary Committee chairman
Henry Hyde, Thursday asked the FBI to investigate whether the White
House is involved in a conspiracy to embarrass GOP members by
exposing their private lives.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Hyde led the Republican move to release videotape of
President Clinton's secret grand jury testimony, GOP leaders said
one or more White House aides have orchestrated an investigation of
private lives that is designed to scare Republicans who are
investigating the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have reason to believe that top aides that have access to
the Oval Office have been orchestrating a conspiracy to intimidate
members of Congress by using their past lives,'' House Majority
Whip Thomas DeLay said, while declining to name a suspect at the
White House. The FBI said it would investigate.
</P>
<P>
   A letter signed by Republican leaders did not directly accuse a
specific White House official of peddling the Hyde story. But an
accompanying document noted that media reports have focused on the
tactics of White House aide Sidney Blumenthal and adviser James
Carville.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman James E. Kennedy said last night that the
publication of the Hyde story was ``tragic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a zero tolerance policy for any White House staff
found engaging in such conduct,'' Kennedy said. ``However, the
Republican members who sent the letter have taken this tragic case
and used it for their own partisan purposes. We have no intention
of responding further to such a politically motivated event.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican document quoted conservative commentator George
Will as saying on September 6 that Blumenthal was trying to ``smear
Henry Hyde.'' Earlier this year, independent counsel Kenneth W.
Starr called Blumenthal to testify about whether he was leaking
personal material on Starr and his assistants.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican document also quoted Carville as saying in June
that, ``I happen to like Henry Hyde. But people do research and
hand me stuff. Some of it I use, some it I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal and Carville did not return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Salon, the Internet magazine that published the article, said it
learned about the affair from a friend of the man whose wife had an
affair with Hyde, not from a White House official.
</P>
<P>
   Both political parties, and many campaigns, have ``opposition
research'' offices that conduct investigations into the actions and
lives of opponents. A few months ago, the White House accused
Republicans of spreading rumors about the president, with Hillary
Rodham Clinton saying that a ``vast right-wing conspiracy'' was
afoot.
</P>
<P>
   Salon editor David Talbot, who wrote the Hyde story, denied that
it came from a White House tip. He said in a television interview
that the original tipster contacted 50 media organizations before
reaching Salon. The magazine said it decided to publish the article
to draw attention to what it called the unfair focus on Clinton's
private life. ``It's time to put an end to the confusion of the
personal and the political,'' the magazine said in a letter to
readers. The letter said the Hyde story deserved to be published
because ``ugly times call for ugly tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans weren't buying Salon's explanation. DeLay and
other Republicans said the White House has hired a detective
company to dig into the private lives of GOP members and then pass
it along to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   As evidence, DeLay cited an ABC-TV news report that said two
unnamed reporters had been contacted by White House officials about
the Hyde story. Republicans also noted that the president's
brother, Roger Clinton, issued an ominous warning about the
exposure of private lives.
</P>
<P>
   If an issue is made of the president's actions, Roger Clinton
said on CNN's Larry King Live last month, ``some of the political
people...had best watch themselves because of the old glass house
story. Be very careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Roger Clinton's statement _ by coincidence or not _ three
House Republicans have been compelled by media investigations to
acknowledge sexual affairs:
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, of Illinois, acknowledged Wednesday that as a married man
he had an affair from 1965 to 1969. House Government Reform and
Oversight Committee chairman Dan Burton, one of the president's
toughest antagonists, admitted he had an affair and had a child out
of wedlock. The third Republican to admit having an affair was
Representative Helen Chenoweth of Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Last February, former White House aide George Stephanopoulos
broadly hinted that ``White House allies'' were investigating
Republicans with a ``deterrent strategy'' in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has said he would never resign, and I think some
around him are willing to take everybody down with him,''
Stephanopoulos, a commentator for ABC, said on the network's ``This
Week'' program.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said there is no comparison between what happened
between the president and Monica S. Lewinsky and the affairs of the
three Republicans that have been exposed in the last few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abuse of power is far more serious than having an affair 30
years ago. I just urge the president to stop his allies from
engaging in this kind of disgusting conduct,'' DeLay told reporters
Thursday. Starr said in his report that Clinton abused the power of
his office by trying to prevent the testimony of Secret Service
agents and others during the investigation into whether the
president lied about his relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   There are numerous cases in which people affiliated with
campaigns mention possible infidelity to reporters covering an
opponent. Clinton's 1992 presidential campaign was considered
nearly dead after Gennifer Flowers alleged she had an affair with
him when he was Arkansas governor.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Democrats voiced suspicions that Star magazine,
which published the Flowers story, got the information from the
Republican Party. But Star magazine and the GOP denied that
Republicans had anything to do with the story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
