<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MANNING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HOST A NATIONAL FIGURE IN AFFORDABLE HOUSING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ While not well known in his home city, John P. Manning,
who with his wife, Lyle, opened up his Beacon Street townhouse for
a $25,000-per-person fund-raiser for President Clinton Thursday
night, is a national name in affordable housing.
</P>
<P>
   His company, Boston Capital Corp., owns 88,000 units of
affordable housing, located in every state but Alaska and Hawaii,
making the firm the fourth-largest in its field in the country.
Company spokesman David Gasson said the properties collectively are
worth about $6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly called Boston Capital Partners, the firm was founded in
1974 to arrange financing of affordable housing through syndication
of partnerships and other investment units that incorporated tax
shelters then available to investors.
</P>
<P>
   Following changes in federal tax laws in 1986, the only
significant shelters that remain are Low Income Housing Tax
Credits, which Boston Capital uses to create investment units that
it sells to Fortune 500 companies as well as individuals.
</P>
<P>
   As Congress and successive administrations have renewed these
programs, Manning, president and chief executive of Boston Capital,
and Herbert F. Collins of Gloucester, chairman, also have become
major political contributors. According to the nonprofit Center for
Responsive Politics, the two men in the past four years alone have
given more than $600,000 to Democratic and Republican causes and
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Manning, 50, is listed as giving $$391,238 to Democrats between
1994 and 1998, including $205,000 in ``soft money'' to the
Democratic National Committee, and nearly $92,000 to the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, 68, gave $232,000 during that period, mostly to
Republicans, according to the Center for Responsive Politics. His
largest single contribution was $100,000, given last April, to the
Republican National Committee. Collins also gave $1,000 each to
several Democrats, including Senator Bob Kerrey of Nebraska and
former Senator George Mitchell of Maine.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are the masters of playing both sides of the
table,'' said one Boston real estate investment veteran who has
worked alongside Manning and Collins for more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Along with running Boston Capital, Manning is a member of the
President's Export Council, which advises on trade issues. Gasson,
the Boston Capital spokesman, said Manning has also served on
Federal National Mortgage Association committees and on the US
Conference of Mayors Task Force on Housing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
