Workers at one of the 450 oil wells at the Teapot Dome field, where
the average production has dribbled to a little over a barrel a day
per well. For much of the 1920s, Teapot Dome - a classic tale of
oil tycoons, $100 bills and a jailed Cabinet member - was the talk
of the nation. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Sept. 17, 1998 -- KENYA-BOMB, 9-17 -- A
poster of Haroun Fazil, suspected of orchestrating the Kenya
embassy bombing, is shown Thursday at a news conference in New York
by Lewis Schiliro of the FBI and a United States attorney, Mary Jo
White. (J. Emilio Flores/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Sept. 17, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 20 --
BIZ-5-QUESTIONS, 9-17 -- William Clay Ford Jr., who will be Ford's
chairman at year-end, is not exactly a car man from central
casting. The auto industry has been feuding with environmentalists
ever since air quality became an issue in the 1960s, but Ford has
long been active in environmental groups. (Chang W. Lee/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- Sept. 17, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 20 --
INVEST-VENTURE-FUNDS, 9-17 -- As an ``entrepreneur in residence''
at a venture capital firm, Chris Risley looked at many proposals
before becoming chief of a software start-up. He says the most
common mistake entrepeneurs make is to send in a business plan in
the hopes that someone will get excited and call them. (Peter
DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) LOS ANGELES -- Sept. 17, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 20
-- INVEST-WITH-GIPSON, 9-17 -- James Gipson, founder and lead
manager of the Clipper Fund. ``I think you will find that we did an
exceptionally good job of capital preservation during a difficult
period,'' says Gibson, and he's right. From July 17, when the
market peaked, through Sept. 11, the S&AMP;P 500 stock index slumped by
17.2 percent. Gipson's fund, with $960.1 million in assets, lost
just 7.2 percent. (Marissa Roth/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- Sept. 17, 1998 -- MASERATI-RETURN-2, 9-17 --
The interior of the new Maserati coupe which, along with a
convertible version to be shown later, will be the main weapons in
Maserati's assault on the United States market. The cars, which
will be priced from $75,000 to $125,000, are likely to be sold by
Ferrari dealers now that the two old rivals are part of the same
industrial group. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) UNDATED -- Sept. 17, 1998 -- MASERATI-RETURN-1, 9-17 --
Maserati's new coupe is leading its return to the United States. An
important milepost in Maserati's long, turbulent history will come
at the end of this month, when the Italian auto maker's new coupe
makes its debut at the Paris Auto Show. The coupe, whose name has
not been announced, will be the first truly new Maserati model
since Fiat bought the company five years ago. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) CANTON, Mass.-- Sept. 17, 1998 -- GLF-NELSON-BOS, 9-17
-- Byron Nelson stands at the second tee with his stepson, John
Tangeman. ``I love the game, love to be around it,'' says Nelson,
86. ``Always have, ever since I first played when I was 13.''
Between March 8 and August 4 or 1945, the man affectionately called
Lord Byron, won every tournament he entered - 11 straight. (Frank
O'Brien/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WEST BARNSTABLE, Mass. -- Sept. 17, 1998 --
AUTHOR-THEROUX-BOS, 9-17 -- Besides his half-dozen or so novels,
Alexander Theroux, 59, has written essays, poems, short stories,
and plays, and he has taught at Harvard, Yale, MIT, and Phillips
Academy in Andover. Next year he expects to publish a new novel,
``Laura Warholic, or The Sexual Intellectual.'' (Tom Herde/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) SAN DIEGO -- Sept. 16, 1998 -- APPLES-SANDIEGO-2, 9-16 --
A coastline drive from San Diego along the coast could include a
stop at Torrey Pines State Reserve, with its sandstone cliffs. For
a long time, people looked on San Diego as vanilla pudding, urban
white bread, more Midwest than the Midwest. But this is still a
young city, still somehow tentative, still in the process of
becoming. (Robert Burroughs/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) SAN DIEGO -- Sept. 16, 1998 -- APPLES-SANDIEGO-1, 9-16 --
The Spanish Colonial Revival style atof Balboa Park in San Diego.
This is a hard city to squeeze into a sentence. It has been a Navy
and Marine Corps base since 1846. It is a tourist town, with a
neo-Victorian Gaslamp District, beloved of convention-goers and
families on vacation, and an equally tourist-saturated Old Town,
full of adobe buildings, old and new. (Robert Burroughs/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Sept. 17, 1998 -- THEATER-NOTES, 9-17 --
Robert Sella, newly blond, is now the MC in the revival of
``Cabaret.'' Sella, 36, says the thought of replacing Alan Cumming,
who won a Tony in the role and is taking a two-month leave, was
daunting. But when he saw the understudy, Vance Avery, play the
role Tuesday, he was reassured. ``They lapped him up like cream,''
Sella says. ``They didn't want their money back.'' (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Sept. 17, 1998 -- WIT-THEATER-REVIEW, 9-17 --
Kathleen Chalfant as a dying literature professor in the Long Wharf
Theater production of ``Wit'' at the MCC Theater. The production,
directed with care and clarity by Derek Anson Jones, is an eggheady
piece, continually drawing our attention to parallels in the worlds
of words and wards. By the moment of the stunning, final fadeout,
you feel both enlightened and strangely comforted. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Sept. 17, 1998 -- NET-GENERATION-BOS,
9-17 -- John Connolly, an entrepreneur and former publishing
executive with Reading-based Addison-Wesley, is now the CEO of
Mainspring Communications. ``We're seeing the American business
executive in significant pain when it comes to 'What should I do
with the Internet?''' he explains from the company's office. (Tom
Landers/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) MASON, N.H. -- Sept. 17, 1998 -- AUTHOR-JONES-BOS, 9-17
-- Writer, illustrator, and local celebrity Elizabeth Orton Jones
walks through the trees toward the brook behind her home,
Rock-a-Bye. Ms. Jones has two houses in Mason, Rock-a-Bye where she
receives her steady stream of visitors and Misty Meadow, where she
keeps her papers and books and where she prefers to sleep at night.
Ms. Jones has written or illustrated, or both, more than 20 books,
most of them children's books, and she is fiercely proud of all of
them. (Joanne Rathe/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BOSTON -- Sept. 17, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 20 --
MONUMENTS-VIDEO, 9-17 -- Krzysztof Wodiczko, a Polish-born
conceptual artist, was recently awarded the Hiroshima Art Prize for
his achievement in contemporary art and his contribution to world
peace. Since 1994, Wodiczko, who is best known for his socially and
politically charged public projections, has been on the faculty of
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. (Ed Quinn/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BOSTON -- Sept. 17, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 20 --
INFERNO-THEATER-2, 9-17 -- The award-winning version of Dante's
``Inferno,'' translated from the Italian by Robert Pinsky, the U.S.
poet laureate is making its way, in the form of a play, to New
York. The production has been in the making since shortly after the
translation was published, in 1994. ``Poetry by its nature is
vocal,'' he says between rehearsals in Boston. (Evan Richman/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BOSTON -- Sept. 17, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 20 --
INFERNO-THEATER-1, 9-17 -- Rehearsing Dante's ``The Inferno in
Boston are Reg Cathey, left, and Bill Camp. The play, following a
brief run in Boston, begins performances in New York on Saturday at
Playhouse 91 and runs through Oct. 4. (Evan Richman/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
