<SLUG> BC-MIT-FRATERNITIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEWER STUDENTS SEEK FRATERNITIES AT MIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Fraternities at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology attracted fewer pledges this fall, after a year of bad
publicity that started with Scott Krueger's death from an alcohol
overdose following a fraternity rush party.
</P>
<P>
   The number of pledges dropped about 7 percent, from 366 last
year to 316, MIT officials said Thursday. And some fraternities
said students were more hesitant in pledging, largely because they
had heard horror stories about binge drinking in the houses, which
have historically played a key role in housing MIT students.
</P>
<P>
   But the school says it's unclear whether the smaller number
actually reflects a shrinking interest in fraternity life.
</P>
<P>
   Each fraternity had to give a bed to a resident adviser, meaning
they had room to house 36 fewer pledges overall. And two
fraternities were forbidden from taking pledges because of drinking
violations last year. Normally, those fraternities would have
absorbed between 15 and 25 students. Those two factors alone may
account for the 50 fewer pledges.
</P>
<P>
   The school had been expecting even more of a decline,
anticipating that 100 fewer students would choose to live in
fraternities, and had cleared space in graduate housing for those
students.
</P>
<P>
   MIT and the fraternities say they can't quantify how many more
pledges might have tried to live in the houses, or if interest
dropped off because of the Krueger death and other
nationally-publicized incidents last year.
</P>
<P>
   Krueger's fraternity was indicted Thursday on manslaughter
charges. Five other fraternities were sanctioned last year,
including the two forbidden from rushing students. Last years's
incidents prompted the institute to announce this summer that all
freshmen will have to live on campus beginning in 2001, when new
dorms are built.
</P>
<P>
   At other schools, freshmen often rush fraternities or sororities
in their first year but do not live in Greek houses until at least
their second year. But a dearth of residence halls on the MIT
campus, and more recently a tight housing market in Cambridge and
Boston, have made the Greek housing the residences of necessity for
even freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   The school had 21 fraternities before it built its first dorm.
Today it has 36 fraternities, sororities, and so-called independent
living groups, and 10 residence halls.
</P>
<P>
   At Sigma Phi Epsilon, students said Thursday they had signed up
about ten fewer pledges this year, down from about 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are several parents I talked to who were very nervous
about sending their son into a fraternity,'' said Jesse Davis, an
18-year old freshman from Castine, Maine. ``It's not that they
don't trust their kids, it's that they don't trust the
fraternities. They know the administration has cracked down, but
they don't believe we've changed. They all saw ``Animal House,''
where the administration cracked down and the fraternity didn't
care. In our case, it really has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, others said while concern was up, the number of pledges
didn't drop. One fraternity had 19 students vying for 12 beds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very nervous going into rush,'' said Michael Bonnet,
20, the rush director at Zeta Psi. ``There's been a big backlash;
everybody was making dire predictions that we'd get only half the
freshman who'd pledged before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freshman were a little more cautious shopping around,'' he
said. ``But a lot of them found they liked what they saw.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
