u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS &LR;      09-17 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE JUDICIARY COMMITTEE ADJOURNS WITHOUT DECISION ON CLINTON
VIDEOTAPED TESTIMONY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Judiciary Committee members waged a fiercely
partisan battle Thursday over whether to release President
Clinton's videotaped testimony in the Monica Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   The panel of 21 Republicans and 16 Democrats met behind closed
doors through the day, but adjourned in the evening after 11 votes
without announcing a decision.
</P>
<P>
   The videotape was turned over to Congress by independent counsel
Kenneth Starr as a basis for possible impeachment proceedings
against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., acknowledged, however,
that the decision to release the tape and other Starr information
was all but made and the panel is now trying to decide just what
and how much to make public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to release as much of it as we can,'' he said. But
he said the committee is sifting through ``17 boxes'' of supporting
material supplied by Starr, a process that will continue today.
</P>
<P>
   Several committee members said they hope to act on a formal
motion authorizing the release by early afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on the panel spent most the day fighting
tooth-and-nail to delay the release of the tape, which House
Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., had hoped to make available Friday.
But a spokesman for the committee said even if the committee does
wrap up its work Friday it may be several days before the
videotape, in which Clinton first admitted to having an improper
relationship with Lewinsky, is actually made public.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats lost on 11 attempts to keep the tapes from going
public and to limit disclosure of other materials.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bitter fighting inside the committee room, Hyde said
both sides managed to keep things ``civil.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're partisan, sure. We're all strongly partisan, but it's
been civil,'' he said. He said the delay in making a final decision
was the result of both sides trying to air their differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strong views strongly held are entitled to be heard,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the Democrats made sure they were heard,
beginning with a substitute motion offered by Reps. Sheila Jackson
Lee, of Texas, and Zoe Lofgren, of California, that would have
blocked the public release of any further Starr information.
Sources said that motion was defeated, however, with the vote
breaking down along party lines.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Lee declined to discuss the proceedings, noting that
members were bound to keep them secret even though they were
debating whether to make public more explicit details about
Clinton's sexual encounters with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   But she did describe committee Democrats as determined to keep
as much as possible of the Starr materials out of the public eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're trying to pursue constitutional rights, you can't
be anything but persistent,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, she said that her position on the issue ``is that no
documents should be released.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican committee member Lamar Smith, of Texas, conceded that
there was a strong partisan split on the committee about what to
release. ``Everybody has strong opinions, but it's still civil,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith declined as well to discuss any specific details of the
committee deliberations. But other committee sources confirmed that
the panel spent much of the afternoon discussing how to edit out
some of the sexually explicit material in the Starr records, which
could be embarrassing to people. One committee source said the
panel worked from a staff report that broke down nearly every sex
act or salacious reference in the materials.
</P>
<P>
   Further souring the committee's executive session Thursday,
Republican leaders called on FBI Director Louis Freeh to open an
investigation into whether someone connected to the president tried
to undermine the panel's work by planting a story in an Internet
magazine about an extramarital affair Hyde had 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde acknowledged the affair, but the White House joined with
Democrats and Republicans in condemning the story, saying that it
has no relevance to the chairman's qualifications to lead an
inquiry into whether Clinton lied and tried to cover up his own
indiscretions with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   However, Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., accused Hyde and other
Republicans of trying to further discredit Clinton by releasing
grand jury testimony that would be kept secret in any normal court
proceeding. He said GOP leaders were simply trying to build a
public relations case for impeachment against the president. Polls
show that many Americans are against Congress pursuing the matter
any further.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (videotape) wasn't made for sweeps week. It was made for
the purpose of informing grand jurors. This is a public relations
campaign for impeachment,'' Frank said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to get impeachment without public sentiment.
So I think they've decide that the thing to do is batter the
president,'' he said. ``They have decided that discrediting the
president is the main goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Conyers, the ranking Democrat on the committee, also
criticized Hyde for not consulting him about a request the chairman
made to Arkansas Judge Susan Webber Wright, seeking the release of
a videotaped deposition Clinton gave to lawyers in the Paula Jones
sexual harassment suit last January. In it he denied having any
sexual relations with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans hope to use the president's deposition to support
Starr's claim that Clinton committed perjury in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   Wright agreed to the request Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Hyde, Conyers questioned whether the deposition
could even be considered by the committee since it was not a part
of the report and other materials Starr submitted to Congress last
week. He also raised questions about the legality of the Hyde
request and the deposition itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have serious concerns regarding the propriety of your
seeking the release of a videotaped deposition in a private civil
case that has now been dismissed,'' Conyers said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Democratic committee member efforts to prevent
the release of the president's videotaped testimony to the public,
Clinton attorney David Kendall also tried to dissuade Republicans
from going ahead with it.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall issued a statement saying that Starr had refused a
request to destroy the tape made on Aug. 17, even though a
transcript of the president's testimony was also made at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only purpose of preserving this videotape after any absent
grand jurors viewed it was to ensure its public release and
embarrass the president,'' Kendall said.
</P>
<P>
   Starr responded by issuing a statement of his own, claiming that
federal law required him to keep the videotape and to turn it over
to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consistent with our legal and ethical obligations, we cannot
and will not destroy evidence of a crime,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
