<HEADLINE>
QUOTATION OF THE DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds.: This quotation refers to BC-NY-HARLEM-NYT, which moved in
``a'' news file.) 
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I don't have to live next to a white family. I effectively
have integrated. I've gone to predominantly white schools. I work
in a white firm, and I can live anywhere I want. It really is
psychologically soothing for me to be in Harlem.''
</P>
<P>
   _HOWARD SANDERS, an investment banker who grew up in Harlem and
has moved back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 2210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980917.0471 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1588 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  FRATERNITY-DEATH-BOS &LR;      09-17 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
DOCUMENTS DETAIL FRATERNITY DRINKING DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
 FRATERNITY-DEATH-BOS  
 (Attn.: N.Y.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLEMENT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It was ``Animal House Night'' at the Phi Gamma Delta
fraternity in the Fenway and Scott S. Krueger, an MIT freshman who
had been in Boston just five weeks, stood in a line with other
pledges as he had been instructed to do by a fraternity brother,
according to court papers.
</P>
<P>
   There was a ``prescribed amount of alcohol'' that the pledges
had to drink.
</P>
<P>
   A ``pledge trainer'' provided beer and Jack Daniels whiskey. The
pledges drank the alcohol and they sang a Phi Gamma Delta drinking
song that included the refrain ``drink her down, drink her down,
drink her down, down, down.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Krueger's ``big brother,'' a current fraternity member
who was to help guide Krueger through his years at the fraternity
and at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, gave him a gift _
a bottle of Bacardi spiced rum.
</P>
<P>
   Krueger, 18, joined in the drinking, became nauseated, and lay
down on a couch. Two fraternity brothers then carried him to his
room, put him on his stomach, placed a garbage can near his head _
and left him there. Ten minutes later, Krueger was covered with
vomit and unconscious. MIT police were called and then Boston
police and emergency medical technicians. Krueger was blue in the
face, his blood alcohol level was .401, and 40 hours later, he was
dead.
</P>
<P>
   That recounting of the final hours of Krueger's life was
contained in papers Suffolk District Attorney Ralph C. Martin 2d
filed Thursday in court after he announced his office indicted the
Phi Gamma Delta fraternity on one count of manslaughter and one
count of hazing for Krueger's death.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy M. Burke, the attorney for the ``pledge trainer,'' said
Thursday he disagreed with prosecutors' summary of Krueger's death.
``There was never any compulsion to drink a prescribed amount of
alcohol,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after Martin announced the indictment, Krueger's parents
angrily accused MIT of failing to take proper care of their son.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sent our son to MIT for five weeks and came down here and
picked him up in a box and took him back (home) in the back of a
station wagon,'' Krueger's mother, Darlene, said. ``We trusted MIT
with our son and they failed us miserably.''
</P>
<P>
   MIT has said it had little authority over what occurred in the
fraternity.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said it was the first time in the nation that a
fraternity _ instead of individuals _ was charged with manslaughter
for the hazing death of a pledge. None of the fraternity members
who purchased alcohol or provided it to Krueger were charged. Also
not charged were any officers of the Boston chapter of the
fraternity, or the alumni corporation that owns the fraternity
house in the Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a possibility the criminal charges will be ignored,
at least initially, by the fraternity. Martin is pushing the legal
envelope by charging an ``unincorporated association,'' lawyers
said, and attorneys for the fraternity may decide no one should
react to the criminal complaints. The Boston attorney who has
identified himself as Phi Gamma Delta lawyer in court papers,
Michael O'Malley, did not return telephone calls Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said his office considered charging the corporation that
runs MIT, but after reviewing the law, concluded that a judge would
throw it out.
</P>
<P>
   Krueger's parents and their attorney, Leo V. Boyle, met with
reporters after Martin's press conference. The Kruegers are
considering civil lawsuits against MIT, the fraternity, and
individuals involved in Krueger's death, Boyle said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kruegers said their goal was not to win money from MIT or
others involved, but to put parents, their children, and college
administrators on notice that alcohol kills. Krueger's father,
Robert, said he blames himself for his son's death because he did
not investigate how widespread alcohol use was at MIT _ and at Phi
Gamma Delta _ before his son joined the fraternity. The Kruegers
live in Orchard Park, N.Y., a Buffalo suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Darlene Krueger said she drove her son to Cambridge in the fall
of 1997 and that he had only two days to find a place to live. He
chose Phi Gamma Delta before she had ever seen it. She said she did
not know that it was in Boston, 28 minutes by foot from MIT's
Cambridge campus.
</P>
<P>
   The last time she saw her son, she said, was a week later when
she visited him at Phi Gamma Delta, which she described as a
``dive.'' Scott Krueger told her he was living in a basement room,
but would move in five weeks. He rushed off to a fraternity event.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 27, 1997, she was called by a nurse at Beth Israel
Deaconess Hospital and was told that her son was in the emergency
room.
</P>
<P>
   Boyle and the Kruegers broadly supported Martin's decision. A
corporation could be fined up to $1,000 on the manslaughter charge
and $3,000 for the hazing charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't put a value on my son's life,'' Darlene Krueger
said. ``But I think the fines should be greater.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyle said MIT should accept responsibility for Krueger's death
and should personally apologize to the Kruegers. ``This isn't
something MIT should feel good about,'' Boyle said.
</P>
<P>
   MIT has said it has no direct legal ties to Phi Gamma Delta and
that the problem of ``dangerous drinking'' is a nationwide one, not
limited to MIT. Ken Campbell, an MIT spokesman, declined to respond
directly to Boyle's assertion that the university has a significant
responsibility for Krueger's death.
</P>
<P>
   MIT is also moving to sever any ties it has to Phi Gamma Delta.
</P>
<P>
   Since Krueger's death, MIT's reaction has included ordering
freshmen to live in dormitories beginning in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, MIT Dean of Students Rosalind Williams said MIT
cooperated with Martin's investigation. ``The steps MIT has taken,
and will take, demonstrate our ongoing commitment to deal with this
national problem,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 2211EDT &QL; 
