<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1589 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-FUNDRAISER-BO     09-17 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FUNDRAISER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON FINDS CASH FOR DEMOCRATS   AMID BOSTON PROTESTERS  
 PROTESTER GREET CLINTON IN BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ President Clinton, looking to shed the pall of
Washington for the familiar exuberance of a fall election campaign,
stormed through Boston Thursday night on a round of big-ticket
fund-raisers, but found himself confronted along city streets by an
outpouring of anger.
</P>
<P>
   A few supporters on Beacon Street, standing outside a
closed-door fund-raising reception attended by wealthy donors, held
signs declaring, ``We're with you,'' and ``Impeach Ken Starr.''
</P>
<P>
   But their numbers were dwarfed by protesters who chanted ``Time
to resign'' and ``Gore 98'' and thrust placards into the air with
such sayings as ``Monica, you're grounded; Bill, you're fired.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Thursday night, Clinton basked in the applause of more
than 600 supporters in the chandeliered ballroom of the Park Plaza
Hotel, where Senator Edward M. Kennedy declared in a fevered voice,
``This was Clinton country in '92, it was Clinton country in 1996,
it is Clinton country tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator John F. Kerry, taking pains to separate his support for
Clinton's policy from his support for his personal actions, pointed
out that the battle was now over the ``heart and soul of the
Congress'' in the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, Washington sages believe the Clinton crisis may
cost Democrats 20 or more seats in the House of Representatives and
another four or five seats in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a time for Democrats anywhere in the country to be
faint of heart and to lose sight of what our battle is about,''
Kerry said.
</P>
<P>
   It was yet another day of political tumult for Clinton. As he
jetted from Washington to Cincinnati to Boston, the Judiciary
Committee huddled in private in an attempt to determine whether it
would release his videotaped testimony to the public. And at a
fund-raiser in Cincinnati, Clinton provided the most optimistic
view of of his marriage since he admitted his affair with Monica
Lewinsky exactly one month earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillary and I, we're doing fine,'' Clinton said. ``We're
working on what we need to be working on, and we're fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Clinton: ``It is not about me. It is about the people about
this country.''
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, Democratic officials said they were unbowed by the
protesters, and instead said that even in controversy and crisis,
Clinton had one of the most successful fund-raising nights of his
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The three fund-raisers _ a cocktail party for $25,000
contributors, a reception for those who gave or raised $10,000, and
a $1,000 a plate dinner _ brought in over $1 million, and caps a
nearly $5 million fund-raising week for the party, in a striking
juxtaposition to Clinton's problems in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The $25,000 contributors gave so-called soft money, which is
unregulated by the federal government and which Democratic
lawmakers have proposed banning. The $1,000 contributors donated
``hard'' money, which can be used by various candidates around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton touched down at Logan Airport at 6:30 p.m. He descended
the stairs of Air Force One with Vice President Al Gore a step
behind, and was greeted by a small group of Winthrop Police
officers and the family of a local Secret Service agent.
</P>
<P>
   He immediately sped off to Beacon Hill, where approximately 40
big-ticket contributors and elected officials gathered at the
Beacon Street condominium of longtime Democratic patron John P.
Manning, president of Boston Captial, and his wife, Lyle Howland.
Senators Kennedy and Kerry were also inside, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   After just under an hour chatting with the group, Clinton led
his motorcade several blocks to the Park Plaza Hotel for the
reception, followed by dinner. The president planned to return to
Washington late Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   All told, Democratic Party officials said they would exceed
their $1 million goal for the Boston events, which came just three
days after Clinton raised well over $3 million in a whirlwind tour
through Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The money was to be split between the Democratic National
Committee, the Democratic Senate Campaign Committee and the
Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee to aid candidates in
the November midterm elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one I know of has canceled,'' said Steven Grossman,
chairman of the Democratic National Committee. ``Boston has come
through again and again and again. It is and continues to be one of
the best places to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Grossman said that fund-raising replies have actually risen as
the controversy worsens over Clinton's longtime affair with former
White House intern Monica S. Lewinsky and his subsequent denials.
The party, Grossman said, has made more than 35,000 telephone calls
recently to small donors and has seen a 5 percent rise in responses
over similar solicitation campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very good about the unwavering support that we've had
from our strongest supporters,'' said Grossman. ``People have said
they believe this is a defining moment for the party and they want
to be there to make sure the interests are protected.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are saying they want us to talk about things that
matter,'' Grossman said. ``They hate this report. They hate this
tape about to come out. The GOP is risking overplaying their
hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not find such smooth waters throughout the day
Thursday. At a fund-raising event in Cincinnati, the Democratic
congressional challenger, Mayor Roxanne Qualls, declined a chance
to ride in Clinton's limousine from the airport to the fund-raising
event in her honor, and offered him words that were damning in
their modest praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is still the president,'' she told reporters.
``He's still the leader of the party. I will extend to him the
courtesy due his office.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Cincinnati Enquirer Thursday joined a
growing list of newspapers calling on Clinton to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, Clinton, trying to refocus attention away from
his travails, delivered a campaign-style speech to an auditorium
filled with cheering union loyalists supporting HMO overhaul and
opposing a Republican-backed tax cut. Time and again, Clinton
seemed to bask in the long rounds of applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the choice: partisanship over progress, people over
politics,'' Clinton said. ``In every issue facing the Congress and
the country, that is the choice and the people need to make their
voices heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton repeated his frequent call for any surplus funds to be
poured into Social Security reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make this a season of doing things for you, not
idleness and indulgence, but doing things for you,'' Clinton said
to the legislative convention of the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an election year and it's popular,'' Clinton said of the
tax-cut proposal. ``But it isn't right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 2213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
