u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLOCAUST-SILENCE-BOS     09-17 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-SILENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINAL DEFENDS CATHOLIC SILENCE ON HOLOCAUST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD HIGGINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ As Clark University dedicated its
first-in-the-nation doctoral program in Holocaust studies Thursday,
Cardinal John J. O'Connor of New York City defended the wartime
silence of Pope Pius XII as ``not only justified but necessary to
save lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal spoke to reporters shortly before giving the main
address inaugurating Clark's program at its Center for Holocaust
Studies.
</P>
<P>
   During the ceremonies, other speakers criticized the ``silent
complicity'' of Christians in the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, long an advocate of improved Catholic-Jewish
relations, said in response to a reporter's question that he was
``personally persuaded that the silence of Pius XII'' was the
wisest approach in the context of Nazi persecution, because it
``enabled him and others to save the greatest number of lives.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor also said that he favored the opening of the wartime
archives of the Vatican, which are scheduled to remain closed to
independent scholars for another 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Warning against the dangers of forgetting the Nazi crusade to
extinguish worldwide Jewry, Cardinal O'Connor and other speakers
praised Clark's initiative in creating the five-year doctoral
program in Holocaust studies. The center, which opened in 1996,
welcomed its first three doctoral students last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Holocaust is a defining, pivotal event in world history
and, therefore, should be part of the educational cannon,'' said
Clark's president, Richard Traina. He added that it would provide
an opportunity to study in depth ``humankind at its worst and its
best.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, serious study of the Holocaust has a permanent place in
academia,'' said Deborah Dwork, director of the center and one of
two full professors in the field at Clark. Dwork is working on
creating an undergraduate concentration in Holocaust studies.
</P>
<P>
   She said studying the Holocaust as an historical subject
separate from the broader field of Jewish studies would not, as
some critics have said, ``obscure the long and rich history of the
Jewish people.'' Nor, she said, can it be accepted as a definition
of Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to exploring the victims of the Holocaust, the
program will use history, sociology and psychology to study the
rescuers, perpetrators and silent bystanders of the Nazi's ``final
solution,'' which resulted in the deaths of more than six million
Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not remember the Holocaust?'' O'Connor asked rhetorically in
his remarks. ``The question is absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitler, he said, used the Holocaust to try to ``redefine and
destroy Judaism and Christiantiy, and its study is quite as
important for Christians as it is for Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, who heads the nation's third largest archdiocese, has
long been a champion of interfaith dialogue with Jews and strongly
backed the Vatican's establishment of formal ties with Israel in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor introduced Holocaust education programs into his
archdiocese, for which he received an award from Clark last year.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that he was making a ``shocking'' statement,
O'Connor compared the centrality and sacramentality of the
Holocaust in the Jewish psyche to the Christian belief in the
resurrection of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say to Jews, `Forget the Holocaust,' is to say to
Christians, `Forget the resurrection.' There is that much of a
sense of sacramentality about the subject for Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the Vatican archives, O'Connor said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I would like to see them open,'' he said, adding that the
fact that they remain closed is not unique and is due more to the
protective instincts and principles of archivists rather than an
effort to conceal alleged misbehavior.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
