<HEADER>
A1592 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-ARCA-TEX     09-17 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-ARCA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCA SERIES PROVIDES STEPPINGSTONE FOR DREAMERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Benny Parsons raced in the ARCA series. So
did Davey Allison, Alan Kulwicki, Tim Richmond, Ernie Irvan and
Jeremy Mayfield.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the names current Automobile Racing Club of America
drivers look to for inspiration. They are the drivers who made it
to the NASCAR Winston Cup, the pinnacle of the stock-car racing
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our series is designed to be a steppingstone to Winston Cup,
primarily,'' said Joe Walls, the competition director for the
series that races at Texas Motor Speedway tomorrow with the Z-MAX
250.
</P>
<P>
   However, the name that should be associated with the series is
perhaps Walter Mitty.
</P>
<P>
   ARCA is a series for dreamers, both those who dream of the big
time and those who simply dream of racing a stock car at a
superspeedway.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Gibson is one of the former. The 41-year-old driver has
raced in the series off and on since 1981. He was the rookie of the
year in 1986 and is second in the points this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to run Winston Cup next year, and I've been running
ARCA until the opportunity comes along,'' Gibson said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Burke is one of the latter. The 52-year-old driver from
Houston has an impressive resume in open-wheeled racing, but
yesterday morning's practice session was his first experience in a
stock car on a 1.5-mile oval.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's not so much a steppingstone as another goal
reached,'' he said. ``It is a very good goal to accomplish, to be
able to run in ARCA.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke's dream is on hold. He crashed his car in a practice
session yesterday, and it couldn't be repaired in time for
qualifying today.
</P>
<P>
   But at least he had the opportunity to try.
</P>
<P>
   The ARCA series consists of 23 races on tiny tracks in the
Midwest to superspeedways in Concord, N.C., Talladega, Ala.,
Hampton, Ga., and this year, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The drivers include a handful of full-time racers intent on
taking it to the next level, and part-timers with jobs in the
``real'' world, racing for the love of it.
</P>
<P>
   The series has more than 150 registered drivers, including a
political lobbyist from Alabama, a race instructor from England, a
real estate agent from Florida, and one of Joe Frazier's former
sparring partners.
</P>
<P>
   They are the dreamers who simply want to race a stock car. Most
of them compete in fewer than five races a year.
</P>
<P>
   ARCA also has a core group of racers who run for the
championship and dream of moving up to a major NASCAR series.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't go jump into a Winston Cup car or a Busch car
without any seat time in a big track,'' Walls said.
</P>
<P>
   The budgets are smaller in ARCA, about $750,000 for the full
series compared to the $1.5 million or so to finance a Busch ride,
but the cars are virtually the same as in Winston Cup. The only
major difference is a rear spoiler that's 11/2 inches larger.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there is another major difference. A Winston Cup field
consists of nothing but some of the best drivers in the world. An
ARCA field ranges from experienced racers like Gibson to rookies.
</P>
<P>
   Even without Burke, the Z-MAX 250 has four drivers in an ARCA
race for the first time. To earn the opportunity to qualify,
drivers had to have experience in another type of racing or compete
in a three-day course at a racing school, and take a few laps
around the track to prove to ARCA officials they can handle the
car.
</P>
<P>
   However, a lack of experience doesn't necessarily mean a lack of
talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's got to start somewhere,'' Gibson said. ``As long
as you use your head, and as long as they come and ask questions, I
don't have a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Why should he? He might have thousands of laps more experience
than some of his fellow competitors, but all the ARCA racers have
something in common.
</P>
<P>
   They are all dreamers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
