<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-MEDIA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ODD FIT, MAYBE, BUT ALLEN FIGHTS HIS WAY THROUGH ON CBS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Marcus Allen's up-and-over leap into your living
room as part of CBS' ``NFL Today'' show wasn't like one of those
plays he made during his Hall of Fame career.
</P>
<P>
   But at a time when many well-spoken and good-looking retired
pros sprint toward a TV career as a way to avoid the real life of
post-NFL stardom, Allen's decision to vault to the visual medium
rather than curl up and hibernate caught some by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   As an L.A. Raider, he'd be accessible to reporters, all right.
But this was no walking sound bite like a Todd Christensen, Howie
Long or Bob Golic, who you knew would head straight for the
camera's red light when it was time to quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd talk all the time (to reporters), I just felt not every
question deserved an answer,'' Allen said. ``Just because people
ask you a question, doesn't mean you have to volunteer information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought there was plenty of intrigue chatting with
me. I chose to be engaging when I wanted to be engaging. I was
always very loquacious when I wanted to be. I just choose to be
what I wanted to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the first two weeks, Allen has provided what little
spark has come flickering from the Jim Nantz-conducted CBS sunrise
service that includes the demure George Seifert and the erratic
Brent Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Allen isn't as demonstrative as a Terry Bradshaw, but he's
always been the kind of person to say something that means
something. You have the remote. Turn up the volume if you can't
hear it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone I talked to said just be yourself,'' Allen said about
advice he received from former teammates like Joe Montana and
Ronnie Lott. ``If you try to be someone else, everyone can see
through that.''
</P>
<P>
   So what kind of person is Allen?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a ham,'' he said. ``Anyone who knows me knows that I am. A
lot of you guys (in the media) may not have known that before, but
that was my choice. There's always a delicate balance between
public and private life. As an athlete, you find your balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen knows how to work within the media. He did the TV work
twice as an active player, once as a Fox analyst on a Detroit-Green
Bay regional game during a Chiefs bye week in '94, then working in
the ABC studio with Robin Roberts and Dave Wannstedt during the '95
wild-card playoffs a week prior to the Chiefs-Colts playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   Allen knows how to make the media work for him. It was that
Monday night game in 1992 when Allen agreed to sit down with Al
Michaels for a taped interview and get everything off his chest
about Al Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Allen also knows how the media can be relentless and
overbearing. For the first three years of his career in Kansas
City, he became caught in the swirl of the O.J. Simpson controversy
because of Allen's personal relationship with those involved in the
criminal and civil trial. Allen had to hide out from tabloid
journalists and was told by attorneys representing Simpson not to
even say ``no comment'' when harangued by reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``That period in my life didn't deter me in any way at all (from
getting into TV work),'' said Allen. ``When I was a kid, I used to
watch all the pregame shows and I wanted to do it then. This wasn't
an overnight decision.''
</P>
<P>
   KCBS Channel 2 anchor Jim Hill backs that up.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of athletes wait until the end of their career and think
about getting into this, but Marcus has always thought ahead,''
said Hill, who even had Allen work as an ``intern'' for him in the
offseason during his Raiders career. Allen counts Hill as one of
his closest friends in the business. Hill, after all, was one who
made broadcasting a post-NFL career move himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's also one of the most unassuming superstars I've ever
met,'' Hill said. ``He knows who he is and doesn't push it off on
anyone. We've talked a lot about broadcasting and our positions and
our place in life. He knows who he is and doesn't get caught up in
a lot of other stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of that stuff _ like the Allen vs. Davis episode _ doesn't
enter Allen's mind anymore unless someone else brings it up. But
don't be surprised if Allen comes up with something positive to say
about Davis down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only natural some assume that now I have a platform, I'm
going to use it (against Davis),'' Allen said Thursday morning,
driving from his Kansas City home to the airport to jet into New
York for this weekend's work that will include analysis on the
Oakland-Denver and San Diego-Kansas City games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that over time, I've lost any sense of vengeance. I'm
so far beyond that I can be critical and praising. There's complete
objectivity there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some may want you to slam other people, and maybe that's part
of today's climate, but you don't have to be a slave to it.
Actually, I think there's a lot of integrity surrounding the whole
(CBS) show. We'll be more entertaining as we become more settled.
But right now, we're just trying to figure out the logistics.''
</P>
<P>
   STATION BREAK:
</P>
<P>
   WHAT SMOKES
</P>
<P>
   -- ESPN has milked at least five more telecasts down the stretch
that include live action from the Mark McGwire-Sammy Sosa
swat-a-thon. Those games include Sunday (11 a.m.
Cincinnati-Chicago), Tuesday (5 p.m., Chicago-Milwaukee and/or
Houston-St. Louis) and Wednesday (5 p.m. and 7:30 p.m.
doubleheaders TBD) as well as games next Friday and Sunday. Fox
offers up the Giants-Dodgers on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   -- In celebration of the 25th anniversary of Billie Jean King's
tennis triumph over Bobby Riggs, ESPN Classic has a 90-minute
special with !racepay!Dick Schaap!off! Sunday at 6 p.m., while the
Lifetime Channel has its angle on ``Breaking Through'' with Maura
Driscoll on Monday at 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT CHOKES
</P>
<P>
   -- If you feel the need to pay $49.95 to see Oscar De La Hoya
hand another loss to former boxer Julio Cesar Chavez, God bless
you. Especially if they throw in a promotional oil change with the
deal. Why not just wait a few days and it'll be on HBO, OK?
</P>
<P>
   -- On the East Coast, Fox's ``Ally McBeal'' season premier had a
better overall rating (8.3) for adults 18-49 going head-to-head
with the San Francisco-Washington game on ``Monday Night Football''
(8.1) from 9-to-10 p.m. OK, so at that point, the 49ers already had
the Redskins whupped pretty good. But when has ``MNF'' ever lost to
anyone in the ratings?
</P>
<P>
   Staff Writer Tom Hoffarth's media column appears Fridays in the
Daily News. He can be reached at sptmedia(at)aol.com &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
