<HEADLINE>
BURTON SEEKS VOTE ON CONTEMPT RESOLUTION AGAINST RENO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The chairman of a House investigation committee
said Thursday that he was seeking a vote of the full House on a
contempt of Congress resolution against Attorney General Janet
Reno, escalating a bitter dispute over the appointment of an
independent prosecutor to examine possible campaign finance abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., chairman of the House Government Reform
and Oversight Committee, said he had discussed the vote with
Speaker Newt Gingrich after a breakdown in negotiations with Reno
over allowing lawmakers on his panel to read two confidential
reports urging her to seek an independent counsel to investigate
possible improprieties in President Clinton's 1996 re-election
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that the attorney general believes the president is
above the law,'' Burton said after discussions collapsed. He
apparently was referring to Reno's repeated refusals to refer
campaign finance issues to an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear when a contempt vote would be scheduled, with
lawmakers distracted by the furor over possible impeachment
proceedings against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Saying she was disappointed, Reno insisted she had tried to
comply with the subpoena for the documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This summer, in response to oversight requests, we have made
some of the most extraordinary accommodations in American law
enforcement history,'' Reno said. ``We briefed members of Congress
on a pending investigation, and we have allowed them to review
portions of sensitive law enforcement documents regarding that
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Thursday, Burton suggested that he might
take the issue a step further, by turning over information
uncovered in his committee's campaign finance investigation to Rep.
Henry Hyde, R-Ill., who is chairman of the Judiciary Committee that
is weighing impeachment proceedings against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Burton appeared to be referring to what Republicans viewed as
White House intransigence in responding to the panel's request for
documents, including legal challenges. Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr said in his report to the House that he found a similar
pattern in his investigation of Clinton's relationship with former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The contempt citation involves two reports, one written last
fall by FBI Director Louis Freeh and another sent to Reno in late
July by Charles La Bella. La Bella is the former head of the
Justice Department unit responsible for investigating possible
illegalities arising from the 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Both reports said that evidence compiled during the Justice
Department's investigation of campaign finance issues justified the
appointment of an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   After negotiations between the Justice Department and the
lawmakers, Burton and a few other senior lawmakers in the House and
Senate were permitted to read edited copies of the reports this
month. But Thursday, discussions that would have allowed other
lawmakers on Burton's panel to review the copies broke down.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Reno has said she would not allow all members of
Burton's committee to review the documents, congressional and
Justice Department officials said. Burton then proposed that six
lawmakers be allowed to view the material. Reno agreed, but only if
the committee agreed in advance to withdraw its subpoena for the
documents and drop the contempt resolution. Burton refused.
</P>
<P>
   The committee voted Aug. 6 to cite Reno for contempt. But before
the measure can be approved, it must be voted on by the full House.
</P>
<P>
   Although Reno has refused repeated demands by Republicans to ask
for the appointment of an independent counsel, she has, in recent
weeks, ordered 90-day inquiries into three campaign finance
accusations involving Clinton's re-election that could lead to an
independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   One of the inquiries centers on whether Clinton and White House
aides coordinated a Democratic advertising campaign, for what are
known as issue advertisements, in an effort to violate federal
spending limits that he agreed to when he accepted taxpayer
financing of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A second inquiry focuses on Vice President Al Gore's statements
about his telephone fund-raising calls from the White House, and
the third centers on possible perjury by former deputy White House
chief of staff Harold Ickes concerning his dealings with the
Teamsters union.
</P>
</TEXT>
