<SLUG> BC-U.S.-IRAQ-KURDS-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO KURD GROUPS UNITE AGAINST BAGHDAD IN PACT BROKERED BY U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The State Department announced Thursday that it had
brokered a settlement between two feuding factions of the Iraqi
Kurds, uniting them against the government of Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   The move by the United States to reunite the factions
underscores how few options remain for the Clinton administration
in trying to organize an opposition to Saddam.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago one of the faction leaders, Massoud Barzani, was
seen as a traitor by the administration, after he had betrayed the
CIA in its covert program against the Iraqi government.
</P>
<P>
   The accord was announced Thursday by Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright after meetings here between Barzani, leader of
the Kurdish Democratic Party, and the man once considered his
rival, Jalal Talibani of the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their joint meetings this week have opened a new and hopeful
chapter in their efforts to work together on behalf of their
people,'' Albright said. ``Without unity, the road ahead will
remain very difficult. With unity, there is every reason for the
Iraqi Kurds to look forward with hope.''
</P>
<P>
   The factions have set up a timetable to resolve their remaining
differences, through a power-sharing arrangement or through
elections.
</P>
<P>
   In its efforts to try to organize an opposition to topple
Saddam, the United States is compelled to work with Iraqi minority
groups, the Kurds of northern Iraq or the Shiite Muslims in the
south.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the Persian Gulf war in 1991 the United States
began a covert-action program that sought to unite Barzani and
Talibani under the umbrella of a CIA-backed organization, the Iraqi
National Congress. Both Kurdish leaders were on the CIA payroll.
</P>
<P>
   But in August 1996, Barzani was having one of his periodic
battles with Talibani, who was then backed by the Iranian military,
and invited the Iraqi army to move north in his territory to
counter Iranian support for his rival. As a result the Iraqi army
shattered what was left of the CIA presence in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his betrayal of the United States the administration has
decided that it cannot give up on Barzani, because his deal with
the Iraqis had turned him into the dominant Kurdish leader.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In recent months the principal deputy assistant secretary of
state for Near Eastern affairs, David Welch, has met both leaders
to try to mediate peace talks, and he led the negotiations in
Washington this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose for us is not only to help the Kurdish people, but
to reinforce our Iraq policy, which would benefit from containment
of Saddam from the north,'' said a senior administration official
who insisted on anonymity. ``We've been involved in a painstaking
effort to try to move them to understand that if they are united
they are less vulnerable to outside pressures. We've tried to prove
to them that their interests lie with us, not with Baghdad or
Tehran.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 2233EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980917.0479 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1626 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-JOHNSON-HN     09-17 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-JOHNSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
UPON joining the Astros, Randy Johnson shot down suggestions he was
the missing piece to the team's postseason puzzle, the long-awaited
answer in the club's journey to baseball's promised land.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And, no, he couldn't walk on water.
</P>
<P>
   Seven weeks later, his teammates aren't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   A case can be made that the Astros were a first-place team
before Johnson ever brought his 97-mph fastball to the Lone Star
State. The Astros were already 21 games over .500 when he arrived
from the Seattle Mariners on July 31 in arguably the biggest trade
in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the 6-10 lefthander is 8-1, two of those victories
coming against the Pittsburgh Pirates, whom Johnson will face in
the opener of a three-game series tonight at Three Rivers Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   He threw consecutive shutouts in his first four starts at the
Astrodome. His ERA since leaving the American League is 1.16.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was already an outstanding ballclub; all he did was take
us to another level,'' hitting instructor Tom McCraw said. ``He
puts us on equal footing with some of the other elite clubs in the
league. He solidifies us. They know it; we know it.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be the biggest difference between the pre-Johnson days
and now for the National League's Central Division champions.
</P>
<P>
   For a franchise that has not won a playoff series in 37 years of
existence, the bar has been raised this time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a guy now who can shut you out on any given day,''
pitcher Mike Hampton said. ``When he's on, you're not going to be
able to do anything against him. When you think someone might have
to face him three times in the postseason he's definitely an impact
player.''
</P>
<P>
   The excitement of the last-minute trade to acquire Johnson
triggered a seven-game winning streak and a revival of the starting
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros won 31 of their first 40 games after the deal and are
32-13 since July 31, the best record in the major leagues in that
span. They reached a club-record 43 games over .500 (96-53 on
Saturday) and are on pace to win 100 games for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere has the ``Johnson Factor'' had more of an impact than
the starting rotation. In the first four months of the season, the
starting five _ Shane Reynolds, Hampton, Jose Lima, Sean Bergman
and Pete Schourek _ combined to go 46-29 with a 3.76 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the results have been phenomenal. Reynolds and Lima
are 6-1 since the Johnson trade. Hampton, plagued by a lack of
support, is 3-1. Overall, the starters (including Johnson) are 25-8
with a 2.98 ERA over the last seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain players that have the ability, not only to
improve a ballclub but to really help everyone around them take
their game to another level, and I think Randy is one of those
people,'' general manager Gerry Hunsicker said. ``We're fortunate
to have three or four others like that on our team as well, but
Randy certainly is one of those special people that makes everyone
around him better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when you're dealing with an All-Star-caliber player
like Randy Johnson, he makes the whole team better for a number of
reasons. He makes the pitching staff better because he instills
confidence in them and challenges them to improve on their current
performance. He makes the position players better because he gives
them the confidence that they don't have to go out and score five
or six runs when he's pitching to win a ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just makes everybody feel better about themselves and the
ability of the team to win.''
</P>
<P>
   But is Johnson the reason?
</P>
<P>
   ``This team was in first place before I even got here,'' Johnson
said. ``To think I'm going to take them to the promised land is not
fair to me. It's going to take 24 other guys; it's not going to
take one guy. I'm not the missing part to the puzzle. I can only go
out and pitch once every five days.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Astros began the season, the organization freely
admitted it lacked a dominant, intimidating No. 1 starter to
complement one of the best offenses in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has Greg Maddux. Toronto has Roger Clemens. Boston has
Pedro Martinez. San Diego has Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   And now, the Astros have Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   All agree that even without Johnson, the Astros still would have
won the Central. But without him, a deep venture into the playoffs
seemed unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a pretty good team. We believed we had a good team, but
we just thought we were still kind of missing that one little
piece,'' second baseman Craig Biggio said. ``We have a lot of good
pitchers on our team, but we really didn't have that one main horse
like a Maddux-type guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now all of a sudden you have that kind of guy, somebody to
match up head-to-head with. He's been huge.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are 24-3 in series in which Johnson pitches. Three of
his victories have come after Astros losses. And when he doesn't
receive much support, one run can be enough.
</P>
<P>
   On Labor Day against Cincinnati, Johnson allowed a leadoff
eighth-inning double and let the runner advance to third on a wild
throw. He then got the next three hitters swinging, and the Astros
went on to win 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``The margin of error is slim. You'd better execute every chance
you've got because there won't be a lot of scoring,'' McCraw said
of facing Johnson. ``You'd better get the bunt down to get the man
over, better get a good pitch to get him (the runner) in.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to do all those little things to get that one run
because you know there's not going to be five runs scored in the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   While Johnson can dictate a game _ he holds the top four
strikeout performances by an Astros pitcher this season, including
a season-high 16 against the Pirates on Aug. 28 _ knowing he will
hold the opposition has taken some pressure off his own hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the psychological lift. We may not score six runs every
game. It's nice to win a ballgame when you're not hitting,'' McCraw
said. ``We have an outstanding offensive unit, and we're going to
score our runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, we're not going to hit every day. There lies the
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Johnson's coming will be the difference in the playoffs
remains to be seen. The Pirates already are believers. Johnson is
2-0 with 28 strikeouts in 16 innings against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear so much about him,'' Pittsburgh shortstop Kevin
Polcovich said, ``and then you face him and realize he really is as
good as everyone says he is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
