<HEADLINE>
FRANCE BLOCKS COKE'S BID FOR ORANGINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: This story has been added to the business front page).  
 (af)  
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Co.'s plan to take control of a leading French soft
drink brand was blocked Thursday after the French government
rejected the acquisition, saying it would hurt consumers and give
Coke too much dominance in the French market.
</P>
<P>
   Coke had announced the $840 million acquisition of the French
brand Orangina, a unit of Pernod-Ricard SA, in late December, and
highlighted it in its annual report. The deal was one of the first
major moves by M. Douglas Ivester, who became chief executive of
Coca-Cola in October.
</P>
<P>
   Orangina is the No. 2 soft drink in France, behind Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Pepsico Inc. filed an objection to the takeover
with the French government, contending that it would stifle
competition. Pepsi said that Orangina distributed Pepsi products to
many restaurants and other businesses in France and added that it
had been interested in buying the brand itself.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Coca-Cola, Randal Donaldson, said Thursday:
``We're disappointed with the government's initial decision.
However, the government had indicated there is an open door for
further consideration of undertakings. We will continue to evaluate
our options.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear Thursday whether Coke, which had been under
pressure from the French government to guarantee jobs and make
other concessions to win approval, would pursue the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Orangina workers had objected to the takeover, fearing they
would lose their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   A Pepsi-Cola spokesman, Brad Shaw, said: ``We're obviously very
pleased. This will send a signal around the world that France has
solid, well-defined rules enforcing open competition and is
prepared to enforce those rules.''
</P>
<P>
   But others seemed surprised by the ruling. ``What it shows is
that the competition and protectiveness between Coke and Pepsi is
at a high level and manifested not just in stores but in courts and
government tribunals,'' said John Sicher, the publisher of Beverage
Digest, an industry publication.
</P>
<P>
   ``The French government's action was partly based on Pepsi's
complaint,'' he added. ``This will further embitter the companies
toward each other and intensify the competitive environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Conway, an analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, said:
``I don't see it as a major issue affecting the direction of the
company. It's a disappointment because it had a high share in
France, and expectations were that this brand could be acquired.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Swanson, an analyst at A.G. Edwards, said, ``It's an
opportunity lost.''
</P>
<P>
   The rejection of the Orangina bid comes at a time when Coca-Cola
has seen its share price plummet by nearly a third. It closed at
$60.8125 Thursday, a 52-week low, falling from its high of $87.9375
on July 14. About 75 percent of Coca-Cola's profits come from its
international sales, which have been hurt by financial crises
abroad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
