<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1644 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON18-1STLEDE-COX     09-17 1402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON18-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WASHINGTON 'TOO OBSESSED WITH ITSELF,' CLINTON SAYS
 &HT;    800&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Amid a rising roar of public protest, President Clinton
tended to his Democratic base Thursday, deriding the political
culture of the capital as ''too obsessed with itself'' to address
the nation's business.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton wooed hundreds of supporters at the Park Plaza Hotel
after being introduced by the biggest names in Massachusetts
Democratic politics, Sens. Edward M. Kennedy and John F. Kerry.
</P>
<P>
   Also addressing the Democratic Party dinner, Vice President Al
Gore called Clinton ``the best thing we have going for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in Cincinnati, the president sought to portray the
impeachment fever gripping Washington as out of touch with the
concerns of mainstream America.
</P>
<P>
   ''Washington always thinks everything's about Washington,''
Clinton told an elite group of supporters in Cincinnati who donated
$10,000 per couple to have lunch with the president in the home of
a prominent attorney. ''It's not about Washington, it's about
America.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the coming election, ''It is not about me,'' Clinton
said. ''It is about the people of this country, it is about their
children, their future and our common efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   In both cities, the scandal inspired public protests on a scale
not seen for many years.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, scores of people lined Arlington Street near the site
of Clinton's fund-raiser, brandishing placards supporting and
opposing the president.
</P>
<P>
   Some read ``Scum'' and ``Impeach Clinton Now,'' while another
read ``Don't be a sucker for Ken (porno) Starr _ save the
presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Across from the Bull and Finch Pub on Beacon Street, the model
for the bar in the TV series ``Cheers,'' dozens of people waved
signs and chanted ``Gore in '98'' and ``Hey hey, ho ho, Clinton's
got to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the protesters, Raymond Ahrens, a 49-year-old real estate
developer, held a handmade sign reading ``America cares about
you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a political situation,'' Ahrens said. ``They're trying
to reverse two elections. They're trying to take away our future.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Walter Kane, 38, who said he was a Persian Gulf war
veteran and a lifelong Democrat, said Clinton should resign.
``Nixon had that much decency,'' said Kane.
</P>
<P>
   In Cincinnati, a crowd of protestors included dozens of people
who said Clinton's behavior infuriated them so much they came to
shout their outrage in public for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Their signs were blunt:
</P>
<P>
   ``Resign''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton is unfit for any public office''
</P>
<P>
   ``Adulterers end up in Hell.''
</P>
<P>
   As the president urged supporters to look beyond his personal
troubles to the policy issues affecting the nation's future, House
Republicans were preparing to release a videotape of Clinton's Aug.
17 grand jury testimony about his affair with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   With the House Judiciary Committee debating the issue, Clinton's
personal attorney, David Kendall, released a statement in
Washington criticizing Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr for
refusing to destroy the videotape and accusing Starr of
deliberately trying to ''embarrass the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Kendall said that he asked Starr before Clinton testified to
destroy the videotape after it was viewed by any grand jurors who
might have missed the president's actual testimony, which was
beamed live, via closed circuit television, from the White House
Map Room, where Clinton testified, to the grand jury room at the
U.S. Courthouse several blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   ''I asked the OIC (office of independent counsel) to agree to
discard the videotape after showing it to any grand jurors who
missed the testimony,'' Kendall said in a written statement. ''The
OIC refused to do so,'' Kendall added, even though a full
stenographic transcript of the testimony also was available.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only purpose of preserving this videotape after any absent
grand jurors viewed it was to ensure its public release and
embarrass the president,'' Kendall wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's appearance in Cincinnati was in support of two House
candidates, Mayor Roxanne Qualls of Cincinnai and former state
Attorney General Chris Gorman of Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Baring a bit of political tooth after weeks of absorbing
personal criticism from prominent figures in both parties, Clinton
lashed out at the Republican-led Congress that is reviewing
possible impeachment proceedings, accusing the Republicans of
waging ''a strategy of not doing anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Clinton, ''They've killed tobacco legislation and campaign
finance reform.''
</P>
<P>
   He then blasted a Republican plan to give back to taxpayers much
of an anticipated federal budget surplus through an $80-billion tax
cut, a proposal he earlier in the day in Washington pledged to
veto.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd just kind of like to watch the ink turn from red to black
and see it dry,'' Clinton explained, ''before we start shoveling it
out the door again.''
</P>
<P>
   Any available surplus money should be set aside, Clinton said,
until Congress and the White House can agree on a plan to shore up
the Social Security system, which is on track to go broke sometime
in the third decade of the next century.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he favored targeted tax cuts to help lower-income
Americans pay for child care and education, and to help encourage
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton drew praise from the luncheon's sponsor, attorney Stan
Chesley, who said Americans should ''thank our lucky stars,'' to
have Clinton and First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton in the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   m ''This president is here to stay,'' Chesley told about 40
wealthy Democrats. ''He's not going anywhere, and he's not going to
be goaded into resigning.''
</P>
<P>
   Near Chesley's home, however, several dozen protesters gathered
to demand that Clinton step down.
</P>
<P>
   ''Put America first and resign now,'' read the headline above a
blistering editorial in Thursday's Cincinnati Enquirer, one of 87
newspapers across the country whose editorial boards have called
upon the president to step aside.
</P>
<P>
   ''Your authority is crippled beyond repair,'' the Enquirer
intoned. ''Each day you remain makes it harder to remove the stains
you will leave on our White House.''
</P>
<P>
   As House Republicans prepared to release videotape of Clinton's
grand jury testimony, the White House rebuked the House Judiciary
Committee for considering the tape's fate behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they're going to have a debate about what the public has a
right to see, they ought to have a debate so the public can see
it,'' presidential spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters flying
with Clinton aboard Air Force One en route to Cincinnati from
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   White House Chief of Staff Erskine Bowles sent a letter Thursday
to House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., flatly
denying suggestions that the White House had urged on-line magazine
Salon to pursue a story that broke Wednesday disclosing that Hyde
had an affair three decades ago with a married woman. Hyde
acknowledged the affair, which took place over four years in the
1960s, after the Salon story appeared on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ''The White House has zero tolerance for staff who are found to
be prying or encouraging others to pry into the personal lives of
members (of Congress) or any other government official,'' Bowles
wrote. ''Let me reassure you: any staff who are found to be
engaging in such conduct will be fired immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowles took the additional step of saying journalists were free
to break confidentiality vows given to any White House source who
passed along rumors or information about stories meant to be
personally damaging to members of Congress or other public
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Bowles invited any journalist who might have received such
information in a confidential conversation with a White House
staffer to step forward and identify the staffer, writing, ''I am
committed to taking appropriate action based on any reliable
information.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If there is someone in our building who has so completely lost
their mind that they think this is helpful, they should be fired,''
Lockhart said. ''Everyone in our building says they're not the
source'' of the Hyde revelations.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
