<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1647 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SENATE-SCHUMER-CLI     09-17 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-SCHUMER-CLINTON-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CONTROVERSY ENCROACHES ON SCHUMER'S SENATE BID 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (budgeted earlier as NY-CAMPAIGN-RDP)   (bl)  
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ In Washington on Thursday, the House Judiciary
Committee debated whether to release to the public videotapes of
President Clinton's grand jury testimony in the Monica Lewinsky
case. Here in central New York, one of the committee's most
prominent Democrats, Rep. Charles Schumer, was touring a factory
that makes cat litter, soberly noting the economic distress of this
downtrodden region and proposing a series of measures to create
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after Schumer won the Democratic nomination to
challenge Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., the Judiciary Committee
deliberations served as a reminder of a major complication that
Schumer faces in his campaign to become New York's next junior
senator. And it goes beyond the man currently holding that job.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton's difficulties escalate, Schumer finds himself
balancing the conflicting demands of his campaign, which Democrats
consider one of the most promising in the nation, and his
obligations as one of 15 Democrats on a committee on the verge of
historic deliberations. The situation is potentially more
perplexing because Schumer has long been close to Clinton and has
viewed his association with the president as a political benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer said he had no regrets about missing Thursday's debate.
He noted that the Judiciary Committee was divided along party lines
over whether to disclose the tapes. Schumer also contended that the
debate in Washington did not involve great constitutional issues,
but rather partisan maneuvering by Republicans out to embarrass a
Democratic president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are a bunch of shenanigans down in Washington,'' Schumer
said, standing on the rooftop of an Arm &AMP; Hammer factory in
Syracuse with a sweeping view of industrial New York at his back.
He said he would oppose the release of the videotapes of Clinton's
grand jury testimony. ``We certainly should have the process go
forward,'' Schumer said. ``But releasing these tapes with these
salacious-type materials is not moving the process forward.
</P>
<P>
   ''You know what moving the process forward is?'' Schumer
continued. ``Talking about creating jobs in central New York.
Talking about fighting crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer declined to say what he would do if the Judiciary
Committee moved to bring impeachment proceedings. Asked if he might
step down from the committee so he could press on with his
campaign, he responded, ``I'll cross that bridge when I get to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Thursday's debate, though, happened at a less than
propitious time for Schumer, who is enjoying what is unquestionably
the best political week of his career. The 48 hours after a primary
victory _ especially for a victor who had faced long odds, as
Schumer did in defeating Geraldine Ferraro and Mark Green _ are
usually a guaranteed burst of free and almost invariably good
publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night Schumer introduced a series of strikingly harsh
television advertisements attacking D'Amato. They accuse the
senator of lying in asserting that Schumer was a proponent of big
tax increases. Each advertisement ends with this line: ``D'Amato:
too many lies for too long.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, D'Amato left little doubt that he would try to
make the most of Schumer's predicament with the Judiciary
Committee. Even as the panel began its deliberations, D'Amato, who
spent the day in an unsuccessful effort to push for passage of his
bill to restrict automated teller machine fees, issued a news
release saying that Schumer had missed 100 votes this year.
</P>
<P>
   Asked the senator's position on releasing the videotapes,
D'Amato's press secretary, Harvey Valentine, responded: ``This is a
matter properly before the Judiciary Committee, which has all the
facts. Chuck Schumer should do his job. If and when this matter
comes to the Senate, the senator will do his job.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's advisers are, by all indications, just starting to
assess how possible Judiciary Committee hearings could disrupt the
campaign. One associate, who spoke on the condition of anonymity,
suggested that Schumer might actually benefit from this, listing
members of Congress _ from former Rep. Elizabeth Holtzman to former
Sen. Howard Baker _ who became famous because of their televised
roles in the Watergate hearings.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Think about the potential to put a spotlight on him,'' this
associate said. ``These could be live, televised hearings.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Schumer's position on the Judiciary Committee could give
him valuable television exposure, it also threatens to keep him out
of New York for a good deal of time, and that could be a problem.
One of the first questions posed by a Syracuse reporter to Schumer
on Thursday was why he had campaigned so infrequently there.
</P>
<P>
   There are other ways hearings could complicate Schumer's
candidacy. More than most Democrats, Schumer has made clear that he
wants Clinton to campaign with him in this state. It is hard to
imagine that happening if Schumer is serving on the committee that
is considering whether to recommend impeachment proceedings against
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   And the prospect of hearings makes it likely that Schumer will
be pressed to answer more questions about Clinton and Ms. Lewinsky,
a situation that D'Amato's advisers said they welcomed.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, for example, Schumer spent an hour touring the Arm and
Hammer plant, which manufacturers cat litter and laundry detergent,
and then climbed to the roof to offer a detailed review of his
economic proposals. Those include using any money from a tobacco
industry settlement to finance a property tax cut and deregulating
the power industry to try to lower electricity costs here.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not what Brenda Tyler, a television reporter with
WTVH, the CBS affiliate in Syracuse, wanted to ask about after
Schumer finished his speech. ``You are on the Judiciary
Committee,'' Ms. Tyler said. ``Why are you hear instead of making
that important vote?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
