<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-TMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCA DRIVERS TRYING TO GRIP ONTO TMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ An unusually dusty racing surface and
rock-hard right-side tires combined to keep Automobile Racing Club
of America practice speeds in the ho-hum 170-mph range at Texas
Motor Speedway yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   But this is the ARCA Bondo/Mar-Hyde Series, where drivers race
on everything from superspeedways to dirt tracks.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the big deal about a little charcoal-gray dust?
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to hear us whine and complain about your
racetrack,'' series points leader Frank Kimmel said after posting
the day's top speed at 170.940 mph. ``We're not that type of
people. And I don't think the racetrack is all together at fault.''
</P>
<P>
   ARCA drivers preparing for tomorrow's Z-MAX 250 were greeted by
a dirty and slick surface when practice opened yesterday morning,
despite the efforts of speedway crews to clean the track with a jet
dryer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a combination of things,'' said Kimmel, driver of the No.
46 Advance Auto Parts/VisionAire Chevrolet Monte Carlo. Yesterday's
ARCA practice marked the first racing on the track since June 5-6,
when the NASCAR Craftsman Truck and Pep Boys Indy Racing League
series competed under the lights on a newly reconfigured and
repaved 1.5-mile trioval.
</P>
<P>
   Two months of intense Texas heat followed, with the rain that
plagued spring activity at the track returning only in the past
week. Whatever traction-enhancing rubber was put down in June is
long gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the track being green (free of rubber,) a blow dryer just
doesn't do what it needs to clean it,'' Kimmel said. ``Once we got
enough cars out there, it seemed like the track got better and the
speeds started picking up.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a reference to the afternoon session, at which 23 ARCA
drivers posted speeds. They ranged from Kimmel's hot lap at nearly
171 mph to the shakedown cruise by Norm Benning at 140.627 mph.
Speeds in the 160-plus-mph range were the norm, with the fastest 13
cars all cracking that barrier during ARCA's first appearance at
TMS.
</P>
<P>
   For comparison, the track's NASCAR Winston Cup qualifying record
was set by Jeremy Mayfield in April 1998 at 185.906 mph. Jeff Green
established the NASCAR Busch Grand National qualifying record at
180.054 mph in April 1997. And the Craftsman Truck qualifying mark
belongs to Jack Sprague at 178.642 mph, set in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The track is going to improve, and make our tires better come
race day,'' said Bill Baird, second-fastest at 169.907 mph in the
No. 52 Saturn Machine/Spee Dee Pop Chevy. ``When the IRL cars get
out there (this morning) it's going to be interesting to see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Kimmel said his recent experience with IRL cars at Atlanta Motor
Speedway indicate the open-wheelers will not only lay down fresh
rubber, but also pick up a lot of gray dust.
</P>
<P>
   But Kimmel also said he was not happy with the right-side tire
compound that Hoosier is providing ARCA teams this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Hoosier has missed a little bit on the tires _
again,'' said Kimmel, winner of a series-leading nine races. ``They
brought a hard tire here because Atlanta and Charlotte (similar
1.5-mile tracks) are so fast, and this place is going to be just as
fast. Look at our tires when they come in. They don't have any
rubber buildup _ nothing. That just shows you that (car) is sliding
across the racetrack. No grip.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we're here with what we've got. Now it's up to us to make
it a good race.''
</P>
<P>
   Baird said he expected the track to completely change by time
the ARCA cars qualify at 11 a.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The track's going to do what it's supposed to do _ the more
you run it the better it's going to get,'' said Baird, who was
among six drivers to either spin or brush a wall during the day.
Baird spun off the backstretch and through the grass but did not
damage his car.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still the surface everybody has to race on,'' Kimmel
said. ``I mean, we race on dirt. You can complain all you want to,
but that pothole's still there for everybody who goes through it.
We just have to get used to this place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
