<SLUG> BC-NY-JOBS-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY'S JOBLESS RATE SHRINKS TO 7.3 PERCENT, LOWEST SINCE 1990 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By LESLIE EATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the booming economy creating more jobs than at
any time since the 1950s, New York City's unemployment rate tumbled
to 7.3 percent in August from 9.3 percent a year ago, the State
Department of Labor said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The city unemployment rate, which edged down again last month,
is now at its lowest level since 1990. While the unemployment rate
in the city remained higher than the national average, its
2-percentage-point drop far outpaced the dip of 0.3 percent in the
national average in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, unemployment in August averaged 4.5 percent, down
from 4.8 percent in August 1997. Statewide, unemployment fell to
5.1 percent from 6.2 percent in the same period.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, the city has added more than 87,000 new public
and private sector jobs, an increase of 2.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``To find that, you'd have to go back to the '50s,'' said Jim
Brown, a labor market analyst for the state. The survey did not
include self-employed workers, agriculture workers or domestic
workers employed by private households.
</P>
<P>
   While commuters have accounted for some of the city's gain in
jobs, city residents have also increasingly found employment _ 54
percent of the adults who live in the city were working last month,
Brown said. The last time so many people were working, as a
percentage of the population, was in late 1989, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The new jobs came in almost every sector except manufacturing,
Brown said. Employment grew on Wall Street and in services like
accounting, and new jobs were also created at construction sites,
stores, hotels and airlines.
</P>
<P>
   City officials hailed the strength and breadth of the expansion.
``It's an explosion of jobs in New York,'' said Deputy Mayor Joseph
Lhota. And, he contended, the numbers show ``that we have a very
diversified economy _ this is not being fueled just by Wall
Street.''
</P>
<P>
   As the stock market continues to fluctuate, charges that the
city relies too much on Wall Street have become an increasingly
sore point for city officials, particularly since some securities
firms have recently announced big losses in overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the state comptroller's office issued a report
warning that the city had ``to an unprecedented extent'' become
dependent on Wall Street in the 1990s. While securities firms
employ only about 5 percent of the people who work in the city,
these workers account for more than 17 percent of total earnings.
</P>
<P>
   And some critics of city policies say that the surge in jobs is
leaving behind many people without college degrees, especially
women who have been forced off welfare.
</P>
<P>
   The current unemployment rate ``still leads other urban areas,
and it's a significant problem for us because this is the top of
the boom,'' said David R. Jones, president of the Community Service
Society of New York, which has just published a report on the
city's labor market.
</P>
<P>
   The society's report said that fewer people of working age had
jobs in New York than in other urban areas, although Jones conceded
that this had been the case for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merely saying, `That's the way it's always been' may not be a
sufficient guide for economic policy,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS &QC;  &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The fastest-growing areas of the state, in terms of jobs, were
Putnam and Rockland Counties, where the number of jobs surged 5.3
percent in the last 12 months, state data show. On Long Island,
24,000 jobs were added over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Rochester lost jobs, as did several rural areas,
including Greene and Sullivan Counties.
</P>
<P>
   The unemployment rate was lowest in upstate Tompkins County,
which includes Ithaca, at 2 percent. It was highest in the Bronx,
where unemployment was at 9.2 percent, down from more than 11
percent a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The other boroughs reported similar percentage drops over the
12-month period to August. The jobless rate dropped to 8.6 percent
from 10.6 percent in Brooklyn, to 6.2 percent from 7.7 percent in
Manhattan, to 6.3 percent from 8.3 percent in Queens and to 6.9
percent from 9.2 percent on Staten Island.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 2252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
