u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOTTI-BAIL-470&AMP;ADD-NY     09-17 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOTTI-BAIL-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRICT BAIL CONDITIONS SET FOR YOUNG GOTTI 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ Although he is expected to be released from
jail in a few days, John A. Gotti, the son of the imprisoned Mafia
boss, will be confined to virtual house arrest under bail
restrictions set Thursday. His phone calls will be monitored,
visitors will be screened and a 24-hour guard will be posted
outside his door.
</P>
<P>
   The set of strict bail conditions that will finally free Gotti,
who was arrested nine months ago on charges of extorting payments
from the Scores nightclub in Manhattan and other accusations, was
agreed upon by lawyers for Gotti and the federal prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I concede these are onerous conditions,'' said one of Gotti's
lawyers, Gerald Shargel, after the bail hearing in U.S. District
Court here. ``Our view is that having him out on bail is a
substantial advantage in terms of having him help prepare for his
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting near Shargel during the hearing was Gotti, a poised and
brawny man of 34 with close-cropped hair and gray glasses who was
dressed in chinos and a tan prison shirt. Behind him was his sister
Victoria, a writer of whodunits; her husband, Carmine Agnello, who
federal officials have described as a member of the Gambino crime
family; her uncle Peter Gotti; and two rows of casually dressed
friends notable for their muscular builds and immaculately white
sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gotti and a dozen or so of her brother's friends and
relatives are putting up $10 million worth of houses and other
property to assure that Gotti does not flee or violate conditions
of bail. The government wants to take a close look at those
properties, not just to validate their appraisals and titles but to
make sure they were not bought with the proceeds of organized
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Shargel and another Gotti lawyer, Bruce Cutler, said they
expected that process to be completed sometime next week, allowing
Gotti's prompt release from a federal wing of the Westchester
County Jail. The trial is being held in Westchester because the
investigation was started by law enforcement authorities here.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti's lawyers, relatives and friends said they were delighted
that he will now be reunited with his wife, Kim, and four young
children and will be free to help his lawyers prepare his defense
for a trial scheduled to begin Jan. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gotti, whose latest novel is titled ``I'll Be Watching
You,'' said her brother's family celebrated Wednesday night by
giving a pizza party rounded off with sweets from Dunkin' Donuts.
Ms. Gotti, who has offered her $4 million house in Old Westbury as
collateral for bail, praised Judge Barrington Parker, who ordered
the release Wednesday, for rejecting government arguments that
Gotti posed an imminent threat to society.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used his head and his heart and based his decision strictly
on the law,'' she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In contrast to the reticence of most family members embroiled in
organized crime cases, Ms. Gotti willingly repeated some of her
remarks for a bank of radio and television microphones. She was
then whisked away in a black stretch limousine.
</P>
<P>
   When Gotti is released, he will have to wear an electronic ankle
bracelet that will allow the authorities to trace his whereabouts.
He will only be able to leave his home in Oyster Bay for meetings
with lawyers. All telephone calls will be monitored except those
over a specially installed line that will be restricted to
confidential discussions with his lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The records of that line will be monitored to make sure that
only the lawyers are called. The government will limit Gotti's
visitors, insuring that business associates or those whom the
government suspects of criminal activities are barred. Gotti has
interests in an automobile-parts business and in real estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call these feel-good conditions because they make the
government feel good, but they don't mean anything,'' Shargel said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 2256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
