<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1675 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COLUMN-TRANSIT-NYT     09-17 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLUMN-TRANSIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: RAPID TRANSIT FAST BECOMING AN OXYMORON 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If you ride the subway every day, the following will
not come as a news flash: the trains move more slowly than they
used to.
</P>
<P>
   Don't confuse this with the fact that fewer trains run on many
lines, something else you already knew. The overcrowding got so bad
that transit officials finally announced plans Thursday to expand
both subway and bus service. It was a welcome development, even
though an uncharitable person might take it as a de facto
concession that the subwaymeisters were off track in previously
insisting that service reductions imposed in 1995 were marginal.
</P>
<P>
   Having more trains, however, does not mean having faster trains.
And whether you ride a creaking F train through Borough Park,
Brooklyn, or bump slowly along on the No. 6 line from Pelham Bay
Park in the Bronx, you have probably wondered if the phrase ``rapid
transit'' is inching closer toward an oxymoron.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of speed is not just in your imagination. New York City
Transit acknowledges having slowed down its trains after a couple
of fatal disasters earlier in the decade. Go-slow orders gained
urgency after a crash in 1995, when one train slammed into another
on the Williamsburg Bridge, killing a motorman and injuring dozens
of passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is all about safety,'' said Bob Slovak, a spokesman for New
York City Transit. ``Safety comes first.''
</P>
<P>
   Fair enough. Who wants to argue that safety should come second?
But some people with know-how, both inside and outside the subway
system, question whether the slowdown was absolutely needed. ``You
could have safety and higher speeds,'' insisted one subway official
who has studied the situation but who asked, for reasons that
should be obvious, to keep his name out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, express trains routinely reached speeds of 55 miles
per hour. Today, the top speed is about 40 mph, partly because
train motors have less power. Operators who comfortably took
stretches of track at 30 mph are now ordered to keep it to 25. As a
result, the journey on many subway lines takes several minutes
longer than it used to, though precisely how much longer is unclear
because transit officials would not provide hard figures.
</P>
<P>
   What, you may ask, is the big deal about a few minutes? Nothing,
really. But you may have noticed that this is not exactly a patient
city.
</P>
<P>
   When subway doors take an extra two seconds to close, passengers
act as though they are sitting on beds of needles. Some would bowl
over their grandmothers to make the switch from a local train to an
express. They gain what? A minute and a half? But to a New Yorker,
a lost minute can seem like an eternity.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no group of riders feels the slowdowns more than those
who must travel late at night. ``I feel sorry for people who work
at midnight,'' said the subway official mentioned earlier. ``If you
have to go at that hour from the Bronx to Brooklyn, you practically
have to pack a picnic box.''
</P>
<P>
   He, for one, is not convinced that safety is the only concern of
the subway brass. Cutting power to the motor happens to be a money
saver, he pointed out. Same with orders to motormen to increase
their ``braking distance,'' which is the number of feet recommended
to stop a train going at a specified speed. Higher braking
distances are time consuming and not always necessary, he said, but
they reduce costly wear and tear on brake shoes and other
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   One well-informed passenger who cannot understand the lower
speeds is Stan Fischler, a Brooklyn-born subway buff who has been
traveling underground for six decades. He has written several
loving books about the New York system, which, in general, he finds
to be in capable hands.
</P>
<P>
   Riding on several subway lines this week in his customary spot _
by the front window of the front car _ Fischler gave a companion a
running analysis of the tracks, the signals, the switching systems,
the skills of various motormen and so on. Nothing delighted him
more than a No. 2 express train reaching top speed on a tear from
72nd Street to Times Square. ``You feel that bounce?'' he said as
it took a curve at 59th Street. ``That's a New York bounce.''
</P>
<P>
   Fischler has trouble shaking a feeling that, in their admirable
concern for safety, transit officials have overreacted. ``It
doesn't make sense,'' he said. ``Say you have a crash on the BQE.
Do you lower the speed to 30 miles an hour because of it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
