<SLUG> BC-ATL-MLK18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-FBI man hands over Ray evidence
 &HT;    By Arthur Brice
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- A former FBI agent said he turned over evidence to a
top Justice Department official Thursday that he had removed from
James Earl Ray's abandoned car 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Former agent Donald Wilson had balked Wednesday at giving the
two slips of paper he took from Ray's car to Barry Kowalski, who is
heading the Justice Department's newly reopened investigation into
the assassination of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. Kowalski then
obtained a federal search warrant and vowed to take possession of
the material Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The documents were furnished to them voluntarily today,''
Wilson said late Thursday from his suburban Chicago home. ``It was
not subject to a search warrant.'' Justice Department spokesman
Myron Marlin declined to comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said in March that he had retrieved the two scraps of
paper from Ray's abandoned Ford Mustang when he was an FBI agent
stationed in Atlanta in April 1968. Both papers contain the word
``Raul.'' Ray, who died in prison in April while serving a 99-year
sentence for King's murder, insisted on his innocence and
maintained he had been set up by a smuggler he only knew as
``Raoul.''
</P>
<P>
   King was killed in Memphis on April 4, 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno authorized a limited investigation
last month into Wilson's allegations and into claims by former
Memphis restauarant owner Loyd Jowers that a mobster paid him
$100,000 to hire an assassin.
</P>
<P>
   Jowers, who is 71 and in ill health, does not want to talk with
Kowalski unless he receives immunity, said Lewis Garrison, Jowers'
attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
