<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MARYHARDIN-BAYLOR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOTBALL DROUGHT ENDS AT TEXAS' MARY HARDIN-BAYLOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELTON, Texas _ The campus of the University of Mary
Hardin-Baylor sits a scant two miles from the major north-south
traffic artery that cuts through Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The roar of the 18-wheelers on Interstate 35 is, however, no
more than a distant afterthought. Newer buildings pleasantly blend
with those that well could have been constructed when the campus
moved to its present site in 1886.
</P>
<P>
   A turn-of-the-century prairie colonial mansion sits to the right
of the main entrance, a restored relic of the days when cotton was
king of the Brazos River Valley. Ancient oaks abound, as do
numerous Texas Historical Markers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, we've been a quiet, laid-back institution,'' UMHB
President Jerry Bawcom admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Well, hello, millennium. Mary Hardin-Baylor _ are you ready to
rumble? Are you ready for some ``footbaaaaaall''?
</P>
<P>
   After 153 years, the answer appears to be a resounding yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response has been incredible,'' coach Pete Fredenburg
said.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA Division III fighting Crusaders play their first-ever
home football game against Belhaven (Miss.) College tomorrow night
just down Sixth Street at Belton Tiger Stadium. The Crusaders are a
bit bloodied but certainly unbowed after a 37-14 loss at Trinity
University, a Division III nationally ranked team, two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably had more fans (in San Antonio) than they did,''
proudly noted freshman offensive tackle Bryan Larned, from Plano
East Senior High School. ``Though we were getting beat 28-0 at the
time, when we scored a touchdown our fans just went crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   UHMB officials guess that close to 4,000 may show up for
tomorrow night's game against another first-year program. They also
estimate that more than 2,500 new Crusaders football fans made the
initial trek to the Trinity game. Bawcom _ formerly president of
Texas Wesleyan _ guesses that about that many showed up a few weeks
ago at Tiger Stadium for Football Funfest, the first meeting
between the team and its new constituents.
</P>
<P>
   ``They almost filled one side of the bleachers,'' Bawcom
boasted. ``And we only had our freshmen and a few upperclassmen on
campus at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when UMHB opened the doors Aug. 14 to its new
12,500-square-foot Andersen Athletic Fieldhouse, almost 200
prospective players showed up for two-a-day practices. The response
was so great that the university immediately added a junior
varsity, which will also play a 10-game schedule.
</P>
<P>
   UHMB has also added a 60-member marching band, a drill team and
has doubled its cheerleading squad to 22 members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was coming to school here anyway,'' said freshman
cheerleader Kerrie Chambers of Pflugerville. ``But when I found out
we were having football, it made it more attractive. Every
university has its own traditions. To me, it's exciting to be a
part of starting one of our own.''
</P>
<P>
   Final fall enrollment figures are not yet in. But as of midweek,
the student body had increased from 2,313 last fall to 2,479.
Freshman enrollment was up from 352 to 512. Bawcom said that
male-enrollment applications over the summer increased from 27
percent to 42 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
   UMHB officials first discussed adding a football program a
decade ago. The genesis of the idea was increasing male enrollment
in the traditionally female institution that became coed in 1971.
But that goal was only part of the overall picture when trustees
finally approved football in October 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made this decision strictly for philosophical reasons,''
said athletic director Ben Shipp, an alumnus and former baseball
coach. ``One, name recognition. Two, to provide a source of fun,
entertainment and camaraderie for our general student populace.
Three, to bring about greater involvement by the local community.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we're already seeing positive fallout on all three
fronts.''
</P>
<P>
   His players are not of Division I-A quality, admits Fredenburg,
a former defensive coordinator at Baylor (13 years), Louisiana
State and Louisiana Tech who said he sought a simpler, more stable
life for his family when he took the job July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Division III, but we're right here in the heart of the
best football players in America,'' Fredenburg said. ``And there
are so many kids who want to continue to play after high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those kinds of kids will run through a wall for you. They may
be an inch or two shorter than the kids we had at Baylor, but they
still have the same kind of heart to play the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
