u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-ISLES-COLISEUM-25     09-17 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-COLISEUM-250&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE TELLS ISLANDERS TO HONOR ARENA PACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINEOLA, N.Y. _ A state judge late Thursday afternoon told the
New York Islanders to honor their contract with Nassau County and
to play all their exhibition and home games at the Nassau County
Coliseum, despite a contention by the team's owners that the
Uniondale arena was unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   The court order was obtained in state Supreme Court here at the
direction of Nassau County Executive Thomas Gulotta, after the
failure of six-and-a-half hours of talks to resolve the dispute
between officials of the Islanders and SMG, a management group that
operates the 26-year-old arena for the county.
</P>
<P>
   John Zuccotti, a lawyer for the Islanders who took part in the
negotiations, said the team would abide by any ruling made by state
Supreme Court Justice Burton Joseph, even though the Islanders
still believed the arena to be unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a decision that will now have to be made by the
judge,'' Zuccotti said. The judge scheduled a hearing on the matter
for next Wednesday, two days before the Islanders' preseason
opener.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders have said that the 21-ton scoreboard hanging above
center ice is held aloft by an unsafe hoist. A week ago, the team's
owners went to court seeking $10 million in damages and saying that
because SMG had failed to correct the problem, their lease with the
county was no longer valid. They said they were looking at other
municipalities for a place to play and that the first preseason
exhibition game would be played in Lake Placid.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Both Gulotta and SMG president Wes Westley insisted after
Thursday's talks stalled that the hoist and the rest of the arena
were safe and that the Islanders were using the issue as a ruse to
obtain financial gains at the expense of Nassau County residents
and Islander fans.
</P>
<P>
   Gulotta said that 1 percent of Thursday's discussions with the
Islanders involved the safety issue and that 99 percent dealt with
ways the Islanders could ``obtain a bigger share of the financial
pie.''
</P>
<P>
   Gulotta said that those discussions included plans for a new
arena, the conversion of the old coliseum into a convention center
and the construction of a new hotel. The talks also covered the
hockey team's possible share of profits from concessions and
parking fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was on the table, but they were greedy,'' Gulotta
said. ``I am determined not to let the Islanders hold a gun to the
heads of Long Island taxpayers and fans for financial gain. They
have a contract and I plan to hold them to that contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Zuccotti said that the talks collapsed because the safety issue
was not resolved. He suggested that a way around the issue might be
an independent safety inspection by the National Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   The league has been monitoring the situation, but did not want
to get involved before Thursday's meeting. The league said Thursday
that it would step in at least to the extent of inspecting the
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last few days we were told by the county and SMG that
we could inspect the building,'' Bill Daly, the senior vice
president of legal affairs for the league, said in a statement.
``We are in the process of finalizing the hiring of the engineers
and we have advised SMG and the county that we will begin
inspecting next Tuesday or Wednesday.''
</P>
<P>
   Gulotta said that the Islanders, who have a 15-year contract
with the county, were seeking to reduce that to three years, with
the option to leave Long Island at the end of those three years if
the team is failing to make a profit. David Seldin, the president
of the Islanders, has said that the team is already losing $11
million a year because the coliseum is in such a state of bad
repair that it discourages fans from attending games.
</P>
<P>
   The New York state Legislature has already approved $40 million
for a new Nassau Coliseum that could cost more than $200 million,
and the owners of the Islanders are seeking more public funding.
</P>
<P>
   Gulotta said he remained available to continue efforts to
resolve the dispute, but he said it was now up the Islanders to
provide the county with a sign of good faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question they want a bigger piece of the pie, and
for that they claim they are willing to forfeit the season and hurt
the fans and the taxpayers of this county,'' Gulotta said.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Well, when it reaches the point where you are a pig
at the trough, it is just too much. At that point you draw the
line. And very frankly, Nassau County is not about to provide
welfare for the rich.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
