<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1804 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-BRACK-HNS &LR;      09-17 1466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-BRACK-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
A racing team on a winning streak can be a superstitious lot.
Keeping the proper chemistry is important to Kenny Brack, the
Swedish driver who is on the verge of winning the Indy Racing
League championship for the A.J. Foyt team.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brack, who lives in Houston so he can be close to his team owner
and mentor, has won an IRL-record three consecutive races.
</P>
<P>
   After his first victory at Charlotte, N.C., in July, Brack
treated the team to dinner at Miss Saigon Cafe, a Vietnamese
restaurant in Rice Village, near Brack's home.
</P>
<P>
   But Foyt was unable to attend the dinner. Brack took the team
back to the restaurant last week to celebrate win No. 3 at Atlanta,
but Foyt didn't go.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't invited,'' Brack said. ``Only the people who went to
the first one can go now.''
</P>
<P>
   Being the team owner and a racing legend didn't matter, and Foyt
understood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him no way I was going,'' Foyt said. ``We can't change
the routine now. That would be bad luck.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been all good luck for Foyt and Brack over the past two
months, when things started to jell and Brack became the man to
beat in the IRL. Brack, who will claim a $1 million bonus if he
wins the IRL title, can make it four victories in a row Sunday at
Texas Motor Speedway in the Lone Star 500.
</P>
<P>
   Few people would have thought that was possible nine months ago.
Foyt knew what people in auto racing would think when he decided he
wanted to end his relationship with Davey Hamilton and hire Brack,
32, to drive the Power Team Oldsmobile.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton was a steady performer who finished as the runner-up in
the Indy Racing League championship in 1997 _ a close battle with
Tony Stewart that came down to the final race of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Brack was from Europe and new to oval-track racing. He was
remembered mostly for being involved in the pace-lap crash at the
1997 Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew when I hired Kenny everybody would think I was an
idiot,'' Foyt said. ``They thought I was out of my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   No one questions Foyt's sanity now. Quite the contrary, the
Houston racing legend looks like a genius by hiring the man who is
the hottest driver on the circuit. Brack is just happy to be part
of a competitive team.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the first win, I told the team this was a special moment
for me and I wanted to make this a habit,'' Brack said. ``I didn't
know they were going to take me seriously. It has been fantastic.
Things look very encouraging (for the championship), but we have
two more races to go and we'll have to see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Brack's biggest challengers at TMS will be teammate Billy
Boat, who won there in June. At that time, it looked as if Boat was
the Foyt driver who was headed for a great season, but Boat
suffered a fractured pelvis in the next race at New Hampshire and
missed two races.
</P>
<P>
   When the Foyt team arrived in Charlotte, things looked grim.
Boat was recuperating, and Brack had not proved Foyt had made the
right decision to hire him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had to get our act together,'' Foyt said. ``We had a
meeting to talk about it, and all the guys pulled together.''
</P>
<P>
   Brack won an exciting race at Charlotte, but no one was ready to
call him a title contender. Then came a win at Pikes Peak, followed
by the win at Atlanta two weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the harder things got, the more we put into it,''
Brack said. ``Like the saying, `The going gets tough and the tough
get going.' That's what we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Brack had proved he could be the winning driver Foyt thought he
would be when he hired him before the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny has come on strong,'' Foyt said. ``Once he's out there
in a race, he runs hard and he stays with it all day. That's kind
of the way I was.''
</P>
<P>
   As a driver, Foyt was willing to take chances and aggressively
go for broke, which is one of the characteristics he saw in Brack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw things I liked in him last year, but I knew he needed
someone to settle him down a little,'' Foyt said. ``I like getting
young guys so I can teach them what they need to know. I felt he
just needed to be with someone who could help him understand what
it takes to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity to win is why Brack wanted to join the Foyt
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew if I signed with A.J. I would have the equipment I
needed to win races,'' Brack said. ``I didn't want better equipment
than everyone else. I just wanted equal equipment. I knew I could
win if I was on equal footing.''
</P>
<P>
   Having an even playing field is something Brack didn't see when
he was a test driver in Formula One.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, Formula One is the biggest thing in Europe, and
that's what I grew up wanting to do,'' Brack said. ``I was a test
driver for the Williams team in 1995 and Arrows in 1996. But I
didn't like what I saw in F1. Unless you are on one of the top
teams, you have no chance of winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to win races. I didn't want to be a back-marker my
whole career. It was a big controversy when I left. People thought
I was crazy, but I've always gone my own way in life and not
worried about what people thought. Finally, I said, `To hell with
this.' I packed my bag and didn't look back.''
</P>
<P>
   Brack's first big opportunity came when he made the field for
the 1997 Indy 500, but the chance to show his skills never made it
to the green flag. On a cold and wet day at the Brickyard, Brack
was involved in a crash on turn 4 of the parade lap.
</P>
<P>
   All three drivers on the fifth row _ Brack, Stephan Gregoire and
Alfonso Giaffone came together and mangled their cars, ending their
day in embarrassing fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``For sure, that was the low point of my career,'' Brack said.
``I think it took some time for people to give me a chance after
that. The worst thing about it was that I wasn't the one who
started the accident but I was the one blamed for it. I was just in
the wrong place at the wrong time.''
</P>
<P>
   Foyt said he had seen enough strange crashes over the years to
know not to blame a driver over one incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never paid any attention to it, especially since my cars
weren't involved,'' Foyt said. ``When something like that happens,
you can get 10 different answers about who did what.''
</P>
<P>
   Brack didn't let the disappointment affect his performance the
rest of the season. He finished fifth at Charlotte and New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``In racing, you have to expect some bad times and you have to
deal with it,'' Brack said. ``The Indy deal didn't make or break
me, but I knew I needed to show some people what I could do. I
always have believed that how you deal with hard times shows where
you are going to go in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Foyt liked what he saw in Brack during the 1997 season and began
thinking about putting Brack in the Power Team car. Hamilton had
done everything expected of him except win. So Foyt wanted a driver
who might be more aggressive on the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Power Team folks were against it at first,'' Foyt said.
``They liked Davey, and they wanted to keep him. But I told them I
was going to do it with or without them.''
</P>
<P>
   Power Team decided to stick with Foyt, who knew he had work to
do to make Brack a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny had to learn to bide his time in a race,'' Foyt said.
``What I've tried to teach him is to use that extra push when you
have to use it and not to burn up the engine. When it's time to let
it go, he has that little something extra to get it done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt Kenny could have won Indy this year if we hadn't messed
things up in the pits. My boys are young, and they're going to make
some mistakes, but I would rather have them young and hungry and
teach them how to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Foyt has taught Brack, it's working. With two races to
go in the 1998 season, Brack has a 23-point lead over Hamilton
(282-259) and a 25-point lead over Stewart. But 50 points are
available for each race, so the championship is a long way from
decided.
</P>
<P>
   Brack sees his situation as a dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider myself much of a points scorer,'' Brack said.
``I want to do everything possible to win, not just accumulate
points. If you win races, the points will take care of itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting in third in Atlanta after the last caution flag.
I was behind Stewart and (Scott) Sharp. I could have said, OK,
maybe I will just take it easy here and get the points, but I'm
just not that kind of driver. Winning is what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's why Foyt wanted Brack as one of his drivers. Brack
thinks he owes a lot to Foyt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a very good relationship with A.J.,'' Brack said.
``He's a perfectionist and wants all his people to do their best.
He's a winner. If you make a mistake, it's OK as long as he knows
you are doing your best.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
