<HEADLINE>
AGGIES LOOK TO REVIVE ANEMIC OFFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ The players doing the running, passing
and catching at Texas A&AMP;M have not changed since last season. But
the level of offensive production has slipped to depths uncharted
in 10 seasons under coach R.C. Slocum.
</P>
<P>
   With only two games under their belts, the 17th-ranked Aggies
(1-1) cite circumstances more than systemic failures to explain an
offense that has seen its statistics drop by more than two yards
per play and two touchdowns per game from 1997 averages.
</P>
<P>
   At their current pace of 3.5 yards per play, the Aggies would
finish as the first A&AMP;M team since 1987 to average fewer than 5
yards per snap. Although no one wearing maroon expects this power
outage to last, Slocum admitted he is anxious for a breakout game
from an offense that ranks last in the Big 12 and 102nd among 112
teams in Division I-A. He would love to see one tomorrow against
Southern Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were averaging 400 yards a game, I'd still be concerned
about our offense,'' said Slocum, whose unit falls well short of
that figure, at 241 yards per contest. ``But there are some reasons
it's like that. We've played one game in the rain and one against
Florida State. If you change those two things, we wouldn't be
having this conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably not. Opening the season with a 23-14 loss to the
11th-ranked Seminoles, who led the nation in total defense in 1997,
``will skew our rushing stats all year,'' in Slocum's estimation.
A&AMP;M followed with a rain-soaked, 28-7 win over Louisiana Tech that
saw the Aggies concentrate on ball control rather than big plays.
</P>
<P>
   Still, minor glitches continue to bother first-year offensive
coordinator Steve Kragthorpe. A&AMP;M has fumbled nine times, losing
three. Receivers dropped five passes against Louisiana Tech.
Quarterback Branndon Stewart has underthrown open receivers,
dropping his completion percentage to 51.1 after connecting at a
56.6 rate last season.
</P>
<P>
   Slowed by nagging injuries, tailbacks Dante Hall (back spasms)
and Sirr Parker (hamstring) have run tentatively while combining
for 126 yards on 40 carries (3.2 per attempt). Neither has found
the end zone. The duo combined for 1,773 yards and 19 touchdowns
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not executing plays that well right now,'' Kragthorpe
said. ``We've got three new offensive linemen and there's got to be
some jelling with those guys before we take off. That's starting to
happen, but we're not where we want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Among players, frustration is evident. Concern is not.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plays are there but we're not taking advantage of them.
That's what's frustrating,'' said tight end Dan Campbell. ``I
haven't lost any confidence in this offense. Pretty soon, we'll put
up some yards and we'll score some points.''
</P>
<P>
   An immediate turnaround may be difficult. Although 0-1, Southern
Mississippi is coming off a 9-3 season and employs a gambling,
unpredictable defensive scheme. The Golden Eagles rarely line up in
the same spot on consecutive plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question, this will be as big a challenge as we have all
year in terms of getting lined up right and executing our
offense,'' Slocum said. ``We're going to have some bad plays. But
we'll have some big plays, too.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Aggies' offense lacks, at this point, is consistency.
That won't happen, Slocum said, until the offensive line performs
better as a unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``With three new guys up front, it's not unreasonable to think
we wouldn't be polished this early,'' Slocum said.
</P>
<P>
   At this stage, Slocum sees no reason to reach for the panic
button. He simply hopes the offensive shine returns soon,
preferably against Southern Mississippi.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
