<HEADER>
A1822 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFING-NY     09-17 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S TROUBLES SCUTTLE STRAW POLL  
 NEW HAMPSHIRE: OTHER STRAW POLLS GO ON, AND ON  
 SOUTH CAROLINA: TRACK GETS SLIPPERY FOR SUPPOSED SHOO-IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When 3,000 members of the Christian Coalition gather this
weekend in Washington for their annual national conference, they
will find that one major event on the schedule _ an election 2000
presidential straw poll _ has been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Conference planners initially figured the poll would provide the
coalition with an opportunity to spark interest in the gathering
and provide a lift for pro-family White House wannabes,
particularly Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo., who has strong ties to
leaders of the coalition.
</P>
<P>
   But after Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's report was
published, according to coalition officials, members of the
coalition board had second thoughts and the beauty contest was
scrapped lest it detract from coalition's efforts to reap maximum
political hay from President Clinton's troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Was there also some concern, perhaps, that Ashcroft might lose
or show poorly?
</P>
<P>
   ``No way,'' one coalition insider insists. ``Heads would have
rolled if we'd had a poll and enough of John's supporters couldn't
be hauled in to guarantee he'd win. The problem was that the effort
to guarantee that result would have been distracting and gotten us
`off message,' especially since people who favor other candidates
wouldn't have taken it lying down.''
</P>
<P>
   The election 2000 straw poll will probably be scheduled for a
later date, the coalition insider said, adding:
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole focus now has to be election 1998 and the terrific
opportunity we've been handed to use the next six weeks to promote
the pro-family issue and pro-family candidates. Bill Clinton's
deplorably bad behavior has really put all that front and center
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Straw Polls Go On, and On
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of election 2000 polls . . .
</P>
<P>
   In the run-up to each presidential election, WMUR, the best
known of New Hampshire's television stations, periodically polls
Democratic and Republican voters to determine which White House
wannabes they would like to see nominated in the Granite State's
first-in-the-nation primaries. As polls go, these surveys tend to
cover fairly small samples of voters and thus have fairly large
margins of error.
</P>
<P>
   But given New Hampshire's prominence in the presidential picking
procedure, they nevertheless are followed closely by political
junkies, who understand and always keep in mind that this early in
the game, name recognition and the number of visits to New
Hampshire can often loom large in the results.
</P>
<P>
   Such caveats duly proffered, here are the results from the the
latest WMUR survey, which was conducted last Wednesday and
Thursday, covered 203 likely Democratic and 217 likely Republican
voters, and has a plus-or-minus margin of error of 6 percent for
Democrats and 6.9 percent for Republicans:
</P>
<P>
   Democrats (with percentage of support won): Vice President Al
Gore, 41; former former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, 14; Sen.
John Kerry of Massachusetts, 10; Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri,
10; Sen. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska, 7; Sen. Paul Wellstone of
Minnesota, 1; others, 2, and undecided, 15.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans: Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, 29; former Gov. Lamar
Alexander of Tennessee, 13; former Vice President Dan Quayle, 9;
Steve Forbes, the publisher, 9; Rep. John Kasich of Ohio, 6; Sen.
Robert Smith of New Hampshire, 5; Sen. John McCain of Arizona, 4;
Patrick J. Buchanan, the commentator, 4; House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, 3; Ashcroft, 2; Gary Bauer, head of the Family Research
Council, 2; others, 1, and undecided, 14.
</P>
<P>
   Any significant movement here from earlier polls?
</P>
<P>
   Not much, except that in the last WMUR poll, conducted in late
June, Bradley got less than 1 percent of the vote. Since then,
however, he has been moving around the country some and talking a
bit more about a possible run in 2000. And he is scheduled to visit
New Hampshire next week for a Democratic fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Track Gets Slippery For Supposed Shoo-In
</P>
<P>
   For months, the political presumption in South Carolina was that
Gov. David Beasley would easily be re-elected. All he had to do win
a second term, the reasoning went, was ride the strong
Christian-right Republican tide that has been sweeping across the
state throughout the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   But lately some voices of doubt have been raised about a Beasley
sweep.
</P>
<P>
   The doubt comes from a sense that the governor's Democratic
opponent, Jim Hodges, the former minority leader in the South
Carolina House, is picking up momentum.
</P>
<P>
   The governor still leads Hodges by 15 points or so in most
independent polls. But at least one Democratic polltaker now has
the race close to a toss-up after finding the governor well in the
lead in all earlier surveys. Perhaps more important, some leading
Republicans in the state have begun openly worrying about slippage
by the governor.
</P>
<P>
   The governor says there is no erosion in his campaign. ``Nothing
has changed,'' insisted his campaign manager, Tony Denny.
</P>
<P>
   But the other day when a fellow Republican, state Sen. David
Thomas of Greenville, called a news conference to criticize a
tax-cutting initiative proposed by Hodges, he expressed concern
about erosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you think I'm out here?'' he said. ``I know how serious
it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican legislator, state Rep. Dan Cooper of
Williamston, said he had been out talking to voters and ``not many
want to vote for Governor Beasley.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodges recently opened a major television attack on Beasley,
hammering him hard on what is probably the hottest issue in the
state: South Carolina's last-place ranking in education test
scores.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, Hodges contends, has done nothing to improve
schools. Further, Hodges argues that the governor has tried to rid
the state of one lucrative source of education financing, video
poker, and has refused to push for another source that would be
even more lucrative, the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   The Hodges ads are paid for in good part with money contributed
by gambling interests, particularly the video poker industry.
</P>
<P>
   Beasley senses political opportunity here in a state where the
Christian right is perhaps the most powerful political force. His
new ads, which have replaced defensive ads that boasted of his
education programs, aggressively assert that ``organized'' gambling
has Hodges in its pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Another hot issue is also dogging the governor. A couple of
years ago, he suggested that the Confederate flag should no longer
be flown over the South Carolina Capitol, a suggestion that
continues to rankle many residents of the state where the Civil War
started.
</P>
<P>
   But the governor still has some important things going for him,
not the least being incumbency. And Wednesday he began working the
Clinton-Lewinsky issue, demanding the president's resignation on
the grounds that he has lost ``moral authority'' and ``respect.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, say some worried Republicans, incumbency may be the
factor that sees the governor through.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a tough race,'' state Sen. Arthur Ravenel Jr. of
Charleston told The Greenville News the other day. ``But it's tough
to beat an incumbent governor. I can't remember that happening, and
I'm 71 years old.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
