<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: AGENCIES AND AGENCY COMPANIES ARE MAKING
ACQUISITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill, N.Y., Pa.)   (bl)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several agencies and agency companies are making acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Keroff &AMP; Rosenberg, an agency in Chicago with 68 employees and
billings estimated at $55 million, is being acquired by Marc USA in
Pittsburgh and will be renamed K&AMP;R/Marc. Terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   K&AMP;R/Marc will operate as an autonomous unit of Marc USA, which
also has units in Dallas; Indianapolis; Miami; Orlando, Fla., and
Tulsa, Okla. K&AMP;R/Marc clients include The Chicago Tribune, part of
The Tribune Co.; Lettuce Entertain You Enterprises, and Vita Food
Products.
</P>
<P>
   The principals of Keroff &AMP; Rosenberg will retain their duties at
K&AMP;R/Marc: Bill Keroff, 55, president and chief executive; Chas
Rosenberg, 54, partner and vice chairman, and Hank Hechtman, 54,
senior vice president and creative director.
</P>
<P>
   Marc also plans to expand to Boston, San Francisco and Seattle,
said chairman and chief executive Anthony Bucci and president and
chief operating officer Michele Fabrizi in an interview. The
acquisition brings Marc's billings to $280 million; clients include
PPG Industries Inc., Rite Aid Corp. and Truserve Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Tempus Group PLC in London, which owns and operates CIA
Medianetwork in Europe, is expanding to the United States by
acquiring VSM Media in New York for $14.7 million over three years.
</P>
<P>
   VSM, which is being renamed CIA VSM Media, has 55 employees
handling media accounts with billings estimated at $220 million for
clients like Barnes &AMP; Noble, Guinness, J.P. Morgan and Volvo.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Sassos, 46, chief executive at VSM Media, will retain that
post at CIA VSM and will join the board of a new CIA Medianetwork
holding company in the United States, CIA Medianetwork North
America. Joanne McGill, 39, president at VSM Media, will continue
in that post at CIA VSM. Chris Ingram, 55, chairman at Tempus, and
Ashley Martin, 38, finance director, have joined the board of CIA
VSM. CIA Medianetwork plans to make additional acquisitions in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Hadtke Associates, a marketing communications consulting company
in New York, acquired Augusta Annual Reports, a design consulting
company in New York. Terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, Hadtke Associates has been reorganized as a
holding company named Hadtke, a Creative Partnership, with two
operating units: Hadtke LLC and Hadtke Annual Reports LLC. The
combined company has billings estimated at $4.5 million from
clients like AT&AMP;T and NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Fox, 46, president of Augusta, becomes president of Hadtke
Annual Reports. The top executives at Hadtke Associates _ Fred
Hadtke, 58, president; Robert Churchill, 34, executive vice
president and managing director, and Richard Karsten, 35, executive
vice president and creative director _ continue in those roles at
Hadtke LLC and the combined company.
</P>
<P>
   Bozell Worldwide in New York, a unit of True North
Communications, acquired Borsch, Stengel &AMP; Partner in Frankfurt and
merged the agency with its Frankfurt office, Bozell Werbagentur
GmbH, to form Borsch, Stengel, Koerner, Bozell. Terms were not
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The combined shop has 167 employees handling accounts with
billings estimated at $175 million for clients including BASF
Coatings, Chrysler Corp. and Unisys. Rolf Koerner, 50, one of two
managing directors at Borsch, Stengel, was named to head the
combined shop as chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Nobert Borsch, 69, the other managing director at Borsch,
Stengel, is awaiting a new title at the combined agency, as are the
top executives at Bozell Werbagentur: Dietmar Steuer, 43, managing
director for client services, and Karsten Frick, 40, managing
partner and creative director.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Western International Media in Los Angeles, a unit of
Interpublic Group of Cos., acquired what was described as a
significant minority interest in Zentropy, an Internet development,
interactive communications and advertising services company based
in Hollywood. Terms were not disclosed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
