<HEADLINE>
7-UP PREVIEWS SUPER BOWL AD CAMPAIGN FOR ITS BOTTLERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLANO, Texas _ Seeking a fresher, younger image for the 7-Up
soft drink, Dr Pepper/Seven Up Inc. unveiled a series of new
television commercials Thursday that will begin during the Super
Bowl in January.
</P>
<P>
   The new commercials, which come as 7-Up continues to lose market
share to competitors like Sprite, ask ``Are u an un?'' and show
teen-agers in various situations where an entity called the ``Anti
Refreshment Syndicate'' is trying to stop them from drinking 7-Up.
People who are uns are ``unique, confident and self-assured,'' said
John Clarke, the chief advertising officer at Dr Pepper/Seven Up, a
unit of Cadbury Schweppes PLC.
</P>
<P>
   The commercials, prepared by Young &AMP; Rubicam, were screened
Thursday at the company's annual bottlers' meeting in Plano, and
drew a mixed response from the bottlers. Many seemed more enchanted
with three 15-second ``teaser'' spots that will be run in early
January. ``I liked the teasers better,'' said Fred Ester, a bottler
from Mason, Texas. In the spots, a man's face appears at the bottom
of a popcorn bucket, sending the bucket's owners shrieking from a
movie theater.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke said the commercials would run during the Super Bowl at
halftime and during two post-game shows. The teasers will be shown
on Fox, on the Fox MTV and UPN channels, as well as Comedy Central,
reflecting the company's desire to stimulate interest in 7-Up among
the 12-to-24-year-old demographic groups, who generally drink the
most soda.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
