<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KENDALL-TEXT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXT OF STATEMENT BY CLINTON LAWYER 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: CLINTON-DAY, CLINTON-CONGRESS-SLEAZE,
CLINTON-CONGRESS-ASSESS, CLINTON-EDITORIALS, CLINTON-BOSTON,
CLINTON-RELEASE, CLINTON-GINGRICH, CLINTON-CONGRESS,
CLINTON-MINISTER, CLINTON-CONGRESS-TV, CLINTON-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN)  
 (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Following is a statement from President Clinton's
personal lawyer, David Kendall, responding to efforts by the House
Judiciary Committee to release videotaped testimony by Clinton, as
provided Thursday by the White House:
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the president's grand jury deposition on Aug. 17, 1998,
the Office of Independent Counsel insisted that it had to videotape
his testimony because one or more grand jurors purportedly would
not be able to attend on that date. I offered to have the testimony
occur on Aug. 18 _ a date on which the grand jury was sitting _ but
the OIC stated that all the grand jurors could not be present on
that date either. I asked the OIC to agree to discard the videotape
after showing it to any grand jurors who missed the testimony. The
OIC refused to do so, despite the fact that a full and complete
stenographic transcript of the president's testimony (the normal
means of recording grand jury testimony) would remain available. I
do not know whether any grand jurors were in fact absent on Aug.
17. I do not know if the OIC videotaped the testimony of any other
witness to show to absent grand jurors.
</P>
<P>
   The only purpose of preserving this videotape after any absent
grand jurors viewed it was to insure its public release and
embarrass the president.
</P>
</TEXT>
