u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CENSUS-UNDERCOUNT-     09-17 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CENSUS-UNDERCOUNT-340&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORST CENSUS UNDERCOUNT FOUND IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A new study by a Democratic research group shows
that the three worst undercounts in the 1990 census occurred in
congressional districts in Manhattan, Brooklyn and the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis of estimates provided by the Census Bureau
indicates that the 1990 census failed to count an estimated 40,245
people _ the largest undercount of the country's 435 congressional
districts _ in the South Bronx district represented by Jose
Serrano.
</P>
<P>
   Serrano's district was followed by the Crown Heights, Brooklyn,
district represented by Major Owens, where an estimated 38,123
people were missed, and the district represented by Charles Rangel
in Harlem, where the Census Bureau failed to count an estimated
35,705 people, according to the study. Each congressional district
was drawn to have a population of about 550,000 people in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The total undercount for New York City, estimated to have been
about 245,000, would not be sufficient to gain the city another
seat in Congress. But the new data highlight the loss, to the
poorest congressional districts, of millions of dollars in federal
and state aid that is tied to population.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis was done by the National Committee for an Effective
Congress, a Democratic organization that provides demographic data
for Democratic candidates. The group's analysts used new estimates
provided by the Census Bureau, which estimated the number of people
missed and the number who were counted twice on all levels, as far
down as individual city blocks. In the past, the Census Bureau had
provided only estimates of overcounts and undercounts for states as
a whole and for cities with populations of more than 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   The new data underscored what had previously been surmised: that
the 1990 census tended to miss people living in low-income areas
populated by members of minority groups. ``It's more of the same,''
said Serrano when informed of the new analysis. ``We've known this
for a while _ known that a poor community like mine gets
undercounted in the census.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Owens echoed that, saying: ``It follows a correlation of
poverty, doesn't it? I think the large immigrant population is what
drives up the undercount in my district.''
</P>
<P>
   Conversely the analysis indicated that where double-counting
took place, it tended to occur in more affluent white areas. The
district where the largest number of people were counted twice was
that of Rep. Peter King, a Long Island Republican. According to
census data, an estimated 7,448 people were counted twice in King's
Nassau County district.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is a mirror of the problems of an unscientific
census,'' said Rep. Carolyn Maloney, a Manhattan Democrat whose
office distributed the study. ``If you own more than one home
you're more likely to be counted twice. If you don't own any home,
you're likely to be missed.''
</P>
<P>
   The data also indicate that much of the undercount was
concentrated in a few states. Aside from New York City, the 25
congressional districts with the largest numbers of missed people
were all in Arizona, California, Florida, New Jersey and Texas. All
but three of the districts were represented by Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The report should add fuel to the raging battle over the Census
Bureau's plans to use statistical sampling to supplement the 2000
Census. Proponents of sampling _ which is loosely similar to a
typical political poll but much more sophisticated _ say it would
help account for those people who are missed by traditional means
of conducting the census.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been saying all along the 1990 census was flawed,''
Engel said. ``I believe that statistical sample will go a long way
toward making the 2000 census more accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   The report may also stiffen Republican resolve against sampling
since it shows the extent to which the undercount is concentrated
in Democratic districts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
