<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOXNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOXER MIA ST. JOHN NOT JUST PRETTY FACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Mia St. John and boxing don't go together at first
glance.
</P>
<P>
   Modeling, maybe. Boxing, no.
</P>
<P>
   Which is a problem at the moment: The Calabasas resident's
colleagues have difficulty taking her fighting skills seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shouldn't worry about what anyone thinks,'' said St. John,
who fights B.J. Felter tonight on the undercard of the Oscar De La
Hoya-Julio Cesar Chavez fight. ``But I do. Everyone wants respect
from their peers.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, St. John, now 31 and the mother of two boys, was born
into fighting. Her father and older brother are accomplished
martial artists; she started when she was 6 and has been devoted to
it since. And she's good: She's won multiple amateur tournaments on
the state and national levels. She just happens to be beautiful,
which doesn't hurt when it comes to marketing oneself.
</P>
<P>
   Her looks helped the Cal State Northridge graduate (in
psychology) get through school. She modeled, including a five-year
stint with Playboy Modeling Agency. And it helped her when she made
the decision a year and a half ago to give professional boxing a
try.
</P>
<P>
   She mailed a letter detailing her qualifications and a photo of
herself to Don King and the promoter signed her immediately. She's
now promoted by Bob Arum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not stupid. I know he called me because of my picture,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's up to her to prove she's more than a pretty face.
</P>
<P>
   So far, she's 7-0 (with five knockouts) as a pro. Ultimately,
like any other fighter _ beautiful or not _ she wants to win a
world championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been my dream since I was a child,'' she said. ``When
(the film) Rocky came out, I remember I wanted to be Rocky.
Everyone thought I just had a crush on Sylvester Stallone but I
really wanted to be Rocky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm getting a chance to live out that dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny guys: St. John's presence in a sport dominated by men was
bound to result in quips. Said Arum at a press conference: ``This
is the first time in my six years introducing you (De La Hoya) that
you're not the best looking person on the dais.''
</P>
<P>
   At last: De La Hoya's next fight, assuming he beats Chavez, is
against Ike Quartey on Nov. 21 in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Which is good news to those who have been critical of De La
Hoya's opposition: Quartey, the former WBA welterweight champ, is
the first opponent given a decent chance of beating De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of fight that's going to make me somebody in
boxing,'' De La Hoya said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense, defense: De La Hoya's offensive skills are well
documented. Statistics provided by CompuBox Inc. indicate he's also
a superb defensive fighter.
</P>
<P>
   In the 13 De La Hoya fights CompuBox has tracked, De La Hoya has
connected on 45.5 percent of his punches, compared to his
opponents' 27.9 percent. The average welterweight connects at a
38.7 rate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-17-98 2355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980917.0511 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-17 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1854 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEMOCRATS-AZR &LR;      09-17 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS WANT CLINTON OUT, BUT WON'T SAY IT
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (Analysis) 
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
WASHINGTON _ It is a badly kept secret on Capitol Hill that many
Democratic lawmakers, especially those facing tough elections, want
President Clinton to resign. But they are afraid of the political
risk in saying so.
<TEXT>
<P>
   With new evidence soon to become public in the Clinton scandal,
Demo cratic House members increasingly fear that Clinton may drag
down the party's candidates by hanging onto his job past the Nov. 3
congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, Democrats want Clinton's fate resolved quickly.
Clinton's resig nation would accomplish that, while impeachment
hearings, even if the president emerged with his job in tact, would
not.
</P>
<P>
   The anxious Democrats are express ing their concerns to friends,
col leagues and campaign operatives, but apparently not to those
who matter most: The public and the president himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want him to leave,'' a top aide to a senior House
Democrat said this week. The aide said that members of the
president's own party lack the will to suggest he step down, in
part because his approval ratings remain high.
</P>
<P>
   Affecting an Arkansas drawl, the aide imagined Clinton's
reaction if a troupe of Democrats marched to the White House and
urged Clinton to step down: ``I'm at 60 (percent approval rating).
Where are you?''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are ``in a damned if you do, damned if you don't
situation,'' said Rep. Matt Salmon, R-Ariz. ``I've had Democrats
who are my friends tell me personally, the best thing that they
believe would happen to their party is that he would step down.
They could move on and remove him as an issue in the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They hope like heck he leaves on his own volition, but they
don't want to say anything, because they don't want to get tarred
and feathered by the party faithful,'' Salmon said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some Democrats have al ready paid a price for shunning
Clinton. Maryland Gov. Parris Glen denning, a Democrat, was
criticized within the party, especially by Afri can-Americans, for
canceling a pub lic appearance with Clinton last week.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all Democrats want Clinton to resign. But because
so many of the lawmakers remain cir cumspect, it is impossible to
tell just how much support Clinton does have on Capitol Hill.
Experienced political pundits think it's precious little.
</P>
<P>
   ``The silence on behalf of the presi dent from members of
Congress is deafening,'' said John Russonello, a Democratic public
opinion re searcher who worked on Interior Secretary Bruce
Babbitt's 1988 presi dential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats seem to be scared silent. But even silence can put
them at political risk.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, GOP congres sional candidate Tom Roberg is
using an ad that accuses Rep. David Price, his Democratic opponent,
of being ``silent,'' according to the Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now our president has admitted lying to us,'' the ad says.
``Now is not the time to be silent. Where do you stand, Mr.
Price?''
</P>
<P>
   All 435 House districts are up for election in November, as are
one-third of the Senate seats.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with other presidents, Clinton never enjoyed a close
rela tionship with members of Congress, not even the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Liberals felt he abandoned the par ty's core principals,
including defend ing minorities and the poor. And many of his
moderate brethren, the New Democrats, felt betrayed by Clinton's
actions in initially denying having had ``sexual relations'' with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky, then conceding that he
did have a relationship with her.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Clinton's base in the rank and file of the Democratic
Party was never as broad as the public may have assumed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for Democrats in Congress, it has come to this: The worse
the president looks, the worse the presi dent's party looks.
</P>
<P>
   That's why a battle Thursday by House Judiciary Committee Demo
crats to delay release of Clinton's videotaped grand jury testimony
may not have been so much about saving the president as it was
about saving the Democratic Party in the fall. &QL; 
